"A genus of New Zealand birds about the size of a hen  with only short rudiments of wings armed with a claw and without a tail; the kiwi. It is allied to the gigantic extinct moas of the same country. Five species are known."
"In an apt or suitable manner; fitly; properly; pertinently; appropriately; readily."
"Fitness; suitableness; appropriateness; as  the aptness of things to their end."
"A noun which has no distinction of cases; an indeclinable noun."
"Pertaining to  or characterized by aptotes; uninflected; as aptotic languages."
"A genus of fresh-water phyllopod crustaceans. See Phyllopod."
"Incombustible; capable of sustaining a strong heat without alteration of form or properties."
"Water; -- a word much used in pharmacy and the old chemistry  in various signification determined by the word or words annexed."
"Pertaining to water; growing in water; living in  swimming in or frequenting the margins of waters; as aquatic plants and fowls."
"Partaking of the nature of water  or abounding with it; watery."
"The Altar; a southern constellation  south of the tail of the Scorpion."
"One of a swarthy race occupying Arabia  and numerous in Syria Northern Africa etc."
"Of or pertaining to Arabia or its inhabitants."
"Of or pertaining to Arabia or the Arabians."
"A carbohydrate  isomeric with cane sugar contained in gum arabic from which it is extracted as a white amorphous substance."
"One well versed in the Arabic language or literature; also  formerly one who followed the Arabic system of surgery."
"Fit for plowing or tillage; -- hence  often applied to land which has been plowed or tilled."
"A South American bird  of the genus Pleroglossius allied to the toucans. There are several species."
"To tear up by the roots; to draw away."
"Of or pertaining to the Syrians and Chaldeans  or to their language; Aramaic."

"Pertaining to Aram  or to the territory inhabitants language or literature of Syria and Mesopotamia; Aramaean; -- specifically applied to the northern branch of the Semitic family of languages including Syriac and Chaldee."
"A bead of rough carnelian. Arangoes were formerly imported from Bombay for use in the African slave trade."
"The palm (or great black) cockatoo  of Australia (Microglossus aterrimus)."
"A person appointed  or chosen by parties to determine a controversy between them."
"A kind of latticework formed of  or covered with vines branches of trees or other plants for shade; a bower."
"Furnished with an arbor; lined with trees."
"The strawberry tree  a genus of evergreen shrubs of the Heath family. It has a berry externally resembling the strawberry; the arbute tree."
"A portion of a curved line; as  the arc of a circle or of an ellipse."

"A series of arches with the columns or piers which support them  the spandrels above and other necessary appurtenances; sometimes open serving as an entrance or to give light; sometimes closed at the back (as in the cut) and forming a decorative feature."
"A mountainous and picturesque district of Greece  in the heart of the Peloponnesus whose people were distinguished for contentment and rural happiness."
"Of or pertaining to Arcadia; pastoral; ideally rural; as  Arcadian simplicity or scenery."
"A secret; a mystery; -- generally used in the plural."
"Of or characterized by antiquity or archaism; antiquated; obsolescent."
"A bowman  one skilled in the use of the bow and arrow."
"The use of the bow and arrows in battle  hunting etc.; the art practice or skill of shooting with a bow and arrows."
"The vital principle or force which (according to the Paracelsians) presides over the growth and continuation of living beings; the anima mundi or plastic power of the old philosophers."
"A violet dye obtained from several species of lichen (Roccella tinctoria  etc.) which grow on maritime rocks in the Canary and Cape Verd Islands etc."
"The place in which public records or historic documents are kept."
"In an arch manner; with attractive slyness or roguishness; slyly; waggishly."
"One of the chief magistrates in ancient Athens  especially by preeminence the first of the nine chief magistrates."
"A way or passage under an arch."
"A suffix properly meaning a rule  ruling as in monarchy the rule of one only. Cf. -arch."
"Pertaining to  or situated under the northern constellation called the Bear; northern; frigid; as the arctic pole circle region ocean; an arctic expedition night temperature."
"Hot or burning; causing a sensation of burning; fiery; as  ardent spirits that is distilled liquors; an ardent fever."
"Heat  in a literal sense; as the ardor of the sun's rays."
"Steep and lofty  in a literal sense; hard to climb."
"The present indicative plural of the substantive verb to be; but etymologically a different word from be  or was. Am art are and is all come from the root as."
"Any plane surface  as of the floor of a room or church or of the ground within an inclosure; an open space in a building."
"To tell  declare explain or interpret; to divine; to guess; as to aread a riddle or a dream."
"Of or pertaining to an area; as  areal interstices (the areas or spaces inclosed by the reticulate vessels of leaves)."
"To raise; to set up; to stir up."
"A genus of palms  one species of which produces the areca nut or betel nut which is chewed in India with the leaf of the Piper Betle and lime."
"The area in the central part of an amphitheater  in which the gladiators fought and other shows were exhibited; -- so called because it was covered with sand."
"A palm tree (Saguerus saccharifer) which furnishes sago  wine and fibers for ropes; the gomuti palm."

"An interstice or small space  as between the cracks of the surface in certain crustaceous lichens; or as between the fibers composing organs or vessels that interlace; or as between the nervures of an insect's wing."
"Pertaining to  or like an areola; filled with interstices or areolae."
"A small inclosed area; esp. one of the small spaces on the wings of insects  circumscribed by the veins."
"A support for the spear when couched for the attack."
"A species of wild sheep (Ovis ammon  or O. argali) remarkable for its large horns. It inhabits the mountains of Siberia and central Asia."
"A genus of venomous ticks which attack men and animals. The famous Persian Argas  also called Miana bug is A. Persicus; that of Central America called talaje by the natives is A. Talaje."
"Pertaining to the ship Argo. See Argo."
"Clay  or potter's earth; sometimes pure clay or alumina. See Clay."
"Of or performance to Argos  the capital of Argolis in Greece."
"The name of the ship which carried Jason and his fifty-four companions to Colchis  in quest of the Golden Fleece."
"Crude tartar; an acidulous salt from which cream of tartar is prepared. It exists in the juice of grapes  and is deposited from wines on the sides of the casks."
"Pertaining to Argolis  a district in the Peloponnesus."
"A substance regarded as an element  contained in the atmosphere and remarkable for its chemical inertness."
"A large ship  esp. a merchant vessel of the largest size."
"A secret language or conventional slang peculiar to thieves  tramps and vagabonds; flash."
"To invent and offer reasons to support or overthrow a proposition  opinion or measure; to use arguments; to reason."
"One who argues; a reasoner; a disputant."
"A genus of copepod Crustacea  parasitic of fishes; a fish louse. See Branchiura."
"A fabulous being of antiquity  said to have had a hundred eyes who has placed by Juno to guard Io. His eyes were transplanted to the peacock's tail."
"An air or song; a melody; a tune."
"An alkaloid  first found in white cinchona bark."
"Exhausted of moisture; parched with heat; dry; barren."
"The state or quality of being arid or without moisture; dryness."
"The Ram; the first of the twelve signs in the zodiac  which the sun enters at the vernal equinox about the 21st of March."
"Rightly; correctly; in a right way or form; without mistake or crime; as  to worship God aright."
"A exterior covering  forming a false coat or appendage to a seed as the loose transparent bag inclosing the seed or the white water lily. The mace of the nutmeg is also an aril."
"Characterized by melody  as distinguished from harmony."
"In the smooth and melodious style of an air; ariose."

"To come up from a lower to a higher position; to come above the horizon; to come up from one's bed or place of repose; to mount; to ascend; to rise; as  to arise from a kneeling posture; a cloud arose; the sun ariseth; he arose early in the morning."
"3d sing. pres. of Arise  for ariseth."
"An earnest; earnest money; money paid to bind a bargain."
"The limb of the human body which extends from the shoulder to the hand; also  the corresponding limb of a monkey."
"A fleet of armed ships; a squadron. Specifically  the Spanish fleet which was sent to assail England a. d. 1558."
"A kind of helmet worn in the 14th  15th and 16th centuries."
"As much as the arm can hold."
"The cavity under the shoulder; the armpit."

"Formerly  an armor bearer as of a knight an esquire who bore his shield and rendered other services. In later use one next in degree to a knight and entitled to armorial bearings. The term is now superseded by esquire."
"A small arm; as  an armlet of the sea."
"Defensive arms for the body; any clothing or covering worn to protect one's person in battle."
"One who makes or repairs armor or arms."
"A place where arms and instruments of war are deposited for safe keeping."
"The hollow beneath the junction of the arm and shoulder; the axilla."
"A frame  generally vertical for holding small arms."
"Instruments or weapons of offense or defense."
"A collection or body of men armed for war  esp. one organized in companies battalions regiments brigades and divisions under proper officers."
"The wild buffalo of India (Bos  or Bubalus arni) larger than the domestic buffalo and having enormous horns."
"A genus of plants; also  the most important species (Arnica montana) native of the mountains of Europe used in medicine as a narcotic and stimulant."
"An active principle of Arnica montana. It is a bitter resin."
"The quality or principle of plants or other substances which constitutes their fragrance; agreeable odor; as  the aroma of coffee."
"A barbarous word used by the old chemists to designate various medical remedies."
"In a circle; circularly; on every side; round."
"The act of arousing  or the state of being aroused."
"To excite to action from a state of rest; to stir  or put in motion or exertion; to rouse; to excite; as to arouse one from sleep; to arouse the dormant faculties."
"In a row  line or rank; successively; in order."

"Formerly  a measure of land in France varying in different parts of the country. The arpent of Paris was 4 088 sq. yards or nearly five sixths of an English acre. The woodland arpent was about 1 acre 1 rood 1 perch English."

"A name in the East Indies and the Indian islands for all ardent spirits. Arrack is often distilled from a fermented mixture of rice  molasses and palm wine of the cocoanut tree or the date palm etc."
"To call or set as a prisoner at the bar of a court to answer to the matter charged in an indictment or complaint."
"To put in proper order; to dispose (persons  or parts) in the manner intended or best suited for the purpose; as troops arranged for battle."
"Notoriously or preeminently bad; thorough or downright  in a bad sense; shameless; unmitigated; as an arrant rogue or coward."
"Tapestry; a rich figured fabric; especially  a screen or hangings of heavy cloth with interwoven figures."
"Order; a regular and imposing arrangement; disposition in regular lines; hence  order of battle; as drawn up in battle array."
"One who arrays. In some early English statutes  applied to an officer who had care of the soldiers' armor and who saw them duly accoutered."
"To or in the rear; behind; backwards."
"To stop; to check or hinder the motion or action of; as  to arrest the current of a river; to arrest the senses."
"A judgment  decision or decree of a court or high tribunal; also a decree of a sovereign."
"""""That which is behind""""; the rear; -- chiefly used as an adjective in the sense of behind  rear subordinate."

"The sharp edge or salient angle formed by two surfaces meeting each other  whether plane or curved; -- applied particularly to the edges in moldings and to the raised edges which separate the flutings in a Doric column."
"The stubble of wheat or grass; a stubble field; eddish."
"The act of arriving  or coming; the act of reaching a place from a distance whether by water (as in its original sense) or by land."

"To come to the shore or bank. In present usage: To come in progress by water  or by traveling on land; to reach by water or by land; -- followed by at (formerly sometimes by to) also by in and from."
"A Spanish weight used in Mexico and South America = 25.36 lbs. avoir.; also  an old Portuguese weight used in Brazil = 32.38 lbs. avoir."
"A missile weapon of offense  slender pointed and usually feathered and barbed to be shot from a bow."
"The buttocks  or hind part of an animal; the posteriors; the fundament; the bottom."
"A public establishment for the storage  or for the manufacture and storage of arms and all military equipments whether for land or naval service."

"One of the elements  a solid substance resembling a metal in its physical properties but in its chemical relations ranking with the nonmetals. It is of a steel-gray color and brilliant luster though usually dull from tarnish. It is very brittle and sublimes at 356� Fahrenheit. It is sometimes found native but usually combined with silver cobalt nickel iron antimony or sulphur. Orpiment and realgar are two of its sulphur compounds the first of which is the true arsenicum of the ancients. The element and its compounds are active poisons. Specific gravity from 5.7 to 5.9. Atomic weight 75. Symbol As."
"A Russian measure of length = 2 ft. 4.246 inches."
"A compound of arsenic and hydrogen  AsH3 a colorless and exceedingly poisonous gas having an odor like garlic; arseniureted hydrogen."
"That part of a foot where the ictus is put  or which is distinguished from the rest (known as the thesis) of the foot by a greater stress of voice."
"The malicious burning of a dwelling house or outhouse of another man  which by the common law is felony; the malicious and voluntary firing of a building or ship."

"The second person singular  indicative mode present tense of the substantive verb Be; but formed after the analogy of the plural are with the ending -t as in thou shalt wilt orig. an ending of the second person sing. pret. Cf. Be. Now used only in solemn or poetical style."
"A genus of phyllopod Crustacea found in salt lakes and brines; the brine shrimp. See Brine shrimp."
"Performed with  or characterized by art or skill."
"Even; not odd; -- said of elementary substances and of radicals the valence of which is divisible by two without a remainder."

"A distinct portion of an instrument  discourse literary work or any other writing consisting of two or more particulars or treating of various topics; as an article in the Constitution. Hence: A clause in a contract system of regulations treaty or the like; a term condition or stipulation in a contract; a concise statement; as
"One who professes and practices some liberal art; an artist."
"One who practices some mechanic art or craft; an artisan."
"One peculiarly dexterous and tasteful in almost any employment  as an opera dancer a hairdresser a cook."
"Wanting art  knowledge or skill; ignorant; unskillful."
"A man skilled in an art or in arts."
"A genus of plants found in central Europe and about the Mediterranean  having flowers on a spadix inclosed in a spathe. The cuckoopint of the English is an example."
"One of the class of diviners among the Etruscans and Romans  who foretold events by the inspection of the entrails of victims offered on the altars of the gods."

"One of a primitive people supposed to have lived in prehistoric times  in Central Asia east of the Caspian Sea and north of the Hindoo Koosh and Paropamisan Mountains and to have been the stock from which sprang the Hindoo Persian Greek Latin Celtic Teutonic Slavonic and other races; one of that ethnological division of mankind called also Indo-European or Indo-Germanic."
"A genus of trilobites found in the Lower Silurian formation. See Illust. in Append."
"A crystallized substance  resembling camphor obtained from the Asarum Europaeum; -- called also camphor of asarum."
"A peculiar acrid and bitter oil  obtained from wood soot."

"A parasitic nematoid worm  espec. the roundworm Ascaris lumbricoides often occurring in the human intestine and allied species found in domestic animals; also commonly applied to the pinworm (Oxyuris) often troublesome to children and aged persons."
"To move upward; to mount; to go up; to rise; -- opposed to descend."
"The act of rising; motion upward; rise; a mounting upward; as  he made a tedious ascent; the ascent of vapors from the earth."
"Extremely rigid in self-denial and devotions; austere; severe."
"A sort of cupboard  or case to contain bows and other implements of archery."
"Persons who  at certain times of the year have no shadow at noon; -- applied to the inhabitants of the torrid zone who have twice a year a vertical sun."
"A collection of serous fluid in the cavity of the abdomen; dropsy of the peritoneum."
"To attribute  impute or refer as to a cause; as his death was ascribed to a poison; to ascribe an effect to the right cause; to ascribe such a book to such an author."
"A small membranous bladder or tube in which are inclosed the seedlike reproductive particles or sporules of lichens and certain fungi."
"Having no distinct sex; without sexual action; as  asexual reproduction. See Fission and Gemmation."
"A genus of trees of the Olive family  having opposite pinnate leaves many of the species furnishing valuable timber as the European ash (Fraxinus excelsior) and the white ash (F. Americana)."
"Affected by shame; abashed or confused by guilt  or a conviction or consciousness of some wrong action or impropriety."
"Of or pertaining to the ash tree."
"The earthy or mineral particles of combustible substances remaining after combustion  as of wood or coal."
"Hewn or squared stone; also  masonry made of squared or hewn stone."
"On shore or on land; on the land adjacent to water; to the shore; to the land; aground (when applied to a ship); -- sometimes opposed to aboard or afloat."
"Pertaining to  or composed of ashes; filled or strewed with ashes."
"One of the chiefs or pontiffs of the Roman province of Asia  who had the superintendence of the public games and religious rites."
"Of or pertaining to Asia or to its inhabitants."
"On  or to one side; out of a straight line course or direction; at a little distance from the rest; out of the way; apart."
"A genus of large and voracious two-winged flies  including the bee killer and robber fly."
"Of or belonging to  or having the qualities of the ass as stupidity and obstinacy."
"To request; to seek to obtain by words; to petition; to solicit; -- often with of  in the sense of from before the person addressed."
"Sideways; obliquely; with a side glance; with disdain  envy or suspicion."
"One who asks; a petitioner; an inquirer."
"Awry; askance; asquint; oblique or obliquely; -- sometimes indicating scorn  or contempt or entry."
"To mitigate; to moderate; to appease; to abate; to diminish."
"Toward one side; in a slanting direction; obliquely."
"In a state of sleep; in sleep; dormant."
"Slopingly; aslant; declining from an upright direction; sloping."
"The act of looking; vision; gaze; glance."
"To sprinkle  as water or dust upon anybody or anything or to besprinkle any one with a liquid or with dust."
"Apparent death  or suspended animation; the condition which results from interruption of respiration as in suffocation or drowning or the inhalation of irrespirable gases."
"To desire with eagerness; to seek to attain something high or great; to pant; to long; -- followed by to or after  and rarely by at; as to aspire to a crown; to aspire after immorality."
"With the eye directed to one side; not in the straight line of vision; obliquely; awry  so as to see distortedly; as to look asquint."

"A quadruped of the genus Equus (E. asinus)  smaller than the horse and having a peculiarly harsh bray and long ears. The tame or domestic ass is patient slow and sure-footed and has become the type of obstinacy and stupidity. There are several species of wild asses which are swift-footed."
"A spear used by tribes in South Africa as a missile and for stabbing  a kind of light javelin."
"A direction equivalent to very; as  adagio assai very slow."
"To attack with violence  or in a vehement and hostile manner; to assault; to molest; as to assail a man with blows; to assail a city with artillery."
"The peculiar bitter substance  soft or liquid and of a yellow color produced when meat bread gum sugar starch and the like are roasted till they turn brown."
"The act or offense of grubbing up trees and bushes  and thus destroying the thickets or coverts of a forest."
"A violent onset or attack with physical means  as blows weapons etc.; an onslaught; the rush or charge of an attacking force; onset; as to make assault upon a man a house or a town."
"One who assays. Specifically: One who examines metallic ores or compounds  for the purpose of determining the amount of any particular metal in the same especially of gold or silver."
"A small foxlike animal (Vulpes cama) of South Africa  valued for its fur."
"To admit a thing as true; to express one's agreement  acquiescence concurrence or concession."
"To affirm; to declare with assurance  or plainly and strongly; to state positively; to aver; to asseverate."
"To value; to make a valuation or official estimate of for the purpose of taxation."
"Any article or separable part of one's assets."

"Property of a deceased person  subject by law to the payment of his debts and legacies; -- called assets because sufficient to render the executor or administrator liable to the creditors and legatees so far as such goods or estate may extend."
"To appoint; to allot; to apportion; to make over."
"Resembling an ass; asinine; stupid or obstinate."
"To give support to in some undertaking or effort  or in time of distress; to help; to aid; to succor."
"An assembly of knights and other substantial men  with a bailiff or justice in a certain place and at a certain time for public business."
"An officer who has the care or inspection of weights and measures  etc."
"To separate and distribute into classes  as things of a like kind nature or quality or which are suited to a like purpose; to classify; as to assort goods. [Rarely applied to persons.]"
"To besot; to befool; to beguile; to infatuate."
"To soften  in a figurative sense; to allay mitigate ease or lessen as heat pain or grief; to appease or pacify as passion or tumult; to satisfy as appetite or desire."
"To take to or upon one's self; to take formally and demonstratively; sometimes  to appropriate or take unjustly."
"One who assumes  arrogates pretends or supposes."
"To take up; to elevate; to assume."
"To make sure or certain; to render confident by a promise  declaration or other evidence."
"One who assures. Specifically: One who insures against loss; an insurer or underwriter."
"A genus of crustaceans  containing the crawfish of fresh-water lobster of Europe and allied species of western North America. See Crawfish."
"A genus of bivalve mollusks  common on the coasts of America and Europe."
"Having little or no tendency to take a fixed or definite position or direction: thus  a suspended magnetic needle when rendered astatic loses its polarity or tendency to point in a given direction."
"An anchor is said to be astay  when in heaving it an acute angle is formed between the cable and the surface of the water."
"Genteel irony; a polite and ingenious manner of deriding another."
"An arch  or ceiling of boards placed over the men's heads in a mine."
"A genus of herbs with compound white or bluish flowers; starwort; Michaelmas daisy."
"In or at the hinder part of a ship; toward the hinder part  or stern; backward; as to go astern."
"To start up; to befall; to escape; to shun."
"Want or loss of strength; debility; diminution of the vital forces."

"A disease  characterized by difficulty of breathing (due to a spasmodic contraction of the bronchi) recurring at intervals accompanied with a wheezing sound a sense of constriction in the chest a cough and expectoration."
"Stirring; in a state of activity or motion; out of bed."
"To stun; to bewilder; to astonish; to dismay."
"Pertaining to  coming from or resembling the stars; starry; starlike."
"Out of the right  either in a literal or in a figurative sense; wandering; as to lead one astray."
"To bind up; to confine; to constrict; to contract."
"With one leg on each side  as a man when on horseback; with the legs stretched wide apart; astraddle."
"Sticking out  or puffed out; swelling; in a swelling manner."
"Apart; separate from each other; into parts; in two; separately; into or in different pieces or places."
"An enemy of the gods  esp. one of a race of demons and giants."
"A sanctuary or place of refuge and protection  where criminals and debtors found shelter and from which they could not be forcibly taken without sacrilege."
"A kettledrum; a kind of tabor  used by the Moors."
"A hetman  or chief of the Cossacks."
"Fully rigged  as a vessel; with all sails set; set on end or set right."
"Pertaining to a remote ancestor  or to atavism."
"The recurrence  or a tendency to a recurrence of the original type of a species in the progeny of its varieties; resemblance to remote rather than to near ancestors; reversion to the original form."
"Characterized by ataxy  that is (a) by great irregularity of functions or symptoms or (b) by a want of coordinating power in movements."
"The influence of a star upon other stars or upon men."
"A genus of American monkeys with prehensile tails  and having the thumb wanting or rudimentary. See Spider monkey and Coaita."
"Of or pertaining to Atella  in ancient Italy; as Atellan plays; farcical; ribald."
"A digesting furnace  formerly used by alchemists. It was so constructed as to maintain uniform and durable heat."
"The disbelief or denial of the existence of a God  or supreme intelligent Being."
"One who disbelieves or denies the existence of a God  or supreme intelligent Being."
"One who contended for a prize in the public games of ancient Greece or Rome."
"In the manner of a tilter; in the position  or with the action of one making a thrust."
"Public disgrace or stigma; infamy; loss of civil rights."
"A genus of small glassy heteropod mollusks found swimming at the surface in mid ocean. See Heteropod."

"The standard atmospheric pressure used in certain physical measurements calculations; conventionally  that pressure under which the barometer stands at 760 millimeters at a temperature of 0� Centigrade at the level of the sea and in the latitude of Paris."
"Producing only asexual individuals  as the eggs of certain annelids."
"A coral island or islands  consisting of a belt of coral reef partly submerged surrounding a central lagoon or depression; a lagoon island."
"The doctrine of atoms. See Atomic philosophy  under Atomic."
"One who holds to the atomic philosophy or theory."
"To reduce to atoms  or to fine spray."
"In concord or friendship; in agreement (with each other); as  to be bring make or set at one i. e. to be or bring in or to a state of agreement or reconciliation."
"To agree; to be in accordance; to accord."
"Characterized by atony  or want of vital energy; as an atonic disease."
"Want of tone; weakness of the system  or of any organ especially of such as are contractile."
"Absence or closure of a natural passage or channel of the body; imperforation."
"Just hove clear of the ground; -- said of the anchor."
"A square hall lighted from above  into which rooms open at one or more levels."
"A kind of chaetopod larva in which no circles of cilia are developed."
"A wasting away from want of nourishment; diminution in bulk or slow emaciation of the body or of any part."
"A extinct genus of Branchiopoda  very common in Silurian limestones."
"Attack at once; -- a direction at the end of a movement to show that the next is to follow immediately  without any pause."
"To bind  fasten tie or connect; to make fast or join; as to attach one thing to another by a string by glue or the like."
"One attached to another person or thing  as a part of a suite or staff. Specifically: One attached to an embassy."
"To fall upon with force; to assail  as with force and arms; to assault."
"A species of sand grouse (Syrrghaptes Pallasii) found in Asia and rarely in southern Europe."
"To achieve or accomplish  that is to reach by efforts; to gain; to compass; as to attain rest."
"To attain; to get act; to hit."
"A fragrant essential oil; esp.  a volatile and highly fragrant essential oil obtained from the petals of roses."
"To make trial or experiment of; to try; to endeavor to do or perform (some action); to assay; as  to attempt to sing; to attempt a bold flight."
"To direct the attention to; to fix the mind upon; to give heed to; to regard."
"Poison; venom; corrupt matter from a sore."
"To bear witness to; to certify; to affirm to be true or genuine; as  to attest the truth of a writing a copy of record."
"Of or pertaining to Attica  in Greece or to Athens its principal city; marked by such qualities as were characteristic of the Athenians; classical; refined."
"To dress; to array; to adorn; esp.  to clothe with elegant or splendid garments."
"Rubbish or refuse consisting of broken rock containing little or no ore."
"To turn  or transfer homage and service from one lord to another. This is the act of feudatories vassals or tenants upon the alienation of the estate."
"To draw to  or cause to tend to; esp. to cause to approach adhere or combine; or to cause to resist divulsion separation or decomposition."
"To tune or put in tune; to make melodious; to adjust  as one sound or musical instrument to another; as to attune the voice to a harp."
"To speak reproachfully of; to twit; to upbraid."
"An open air concert in the morning  as distinguished from an evening serenade; also a pianoforte composition suggestive of morning."
"Succession to the goods of a stranger not naturalized."
"A broken gait of a horse  between an amble and a gallop; -- commonly called a Canterbury gallop."
"A public sale of property to the highest bidder  esp. by a person licensed and authorized for the purpose; a vendue."
"Capable of being heard; loud enough to be heard; actually heard; as  an audible voice or whisper."
"A changeling or elf child  -- that is one left by fairies; a deformed or foolish child; a simpleton; an oaf."
"Of or pertaining to Augeus  king of Elis whose stable contained 3000 oxen and had not been cleaned for 30 years. Hercules cleansed it in a single day."

"A carpenter's tool for boring holes larger than those bored by a gimlet. It has a handle placed crosswise by which it is turned with both hands. A pod auger is one with a straight channel or groove  like the half of a bean pod. A screw auger has a twisted blade by the spiral groove of which the chips are discharge."
"A priming tube connecting the charge chamber with the gallery  or place where the slow match is applied."
"A variety of pyroxene  usually of a black or dark green color occurring in igneous rocks such as basalt; -- also used instead of the general term pyroxene."
"Pertaining to  or like augite; containing augite as a principal constituent; as augitic rocks."
"To enlarge or increase in size  amount or degree; to swell; to make bigger; as to augment an army by reeforcements; rain augments a stream; impatience augments an evil."

"An official diviner who foretold events by the singing  chattering flight and feeding of birds or by signs or omens derived from celestial phenomena certain appearances of quadrupeds or unusual occurrences."
"Of or pertaining to augurs or to augury; betokening; ominous; significant; as  an augural staff; augural books."
"The art or practice of foretelling events by observing the actions of birds  etc.; divination."
"Of a quality inspiring mingled admiration and reverence; having an aspect of solemn dignity or grandeur; sublime; majestic; having exalted birth  character state or authority."
"A name given to various species of arctic sea birds of the family Alcidae. The great auk  now extinct is Alca (/ Plautus) impennis. The razor-billed auk is A. torda. See Puffin Guillemot and Murre."
"Old; as  Auld Reekie (old smoky) i. e. Edinburgh."
"Of or pertaining to a pipe (flute) or piper."
"A form of Ambry  a closet; but confused with Almonry as if a place for alms."
"A rude balance for weighing  and a kind of weight formerly used in England."
"A French cloth measure  of different parts of the country (at Paris 0.95 of an English ell); -- now superseded by the meter."
"The sister of one's father or mother; -- correlative to nephew or niece. Also applied to an uncle's wife."
"A familiar name for an aunt. In the southern United States a familiar term applied to aged negro women."
"Any subtile  invisible emanation effluvium or exhalation from a substance as the aroma of flowers the odor of the blood a supposed fertilizing emanation from the pollen of flowers etc."
"Of or pertaining to the air  or to an aura."
"A combination of auric acid with a base; as  aurate or potassium."
"The chrysalis  or pupa of an insect esp. when reflecting a brilliant golden color as that of some of the butterflies."
"A celestial crown or accidental glory added to the bliss of heaven  as a reward to those (as virgins martyrs preachers etc.) who have overcome the world the flesh and the devil."
"The external ear  or that part of the ear which is prominent from the head."
"The Charioteer  or Wagoner a constellation in the northern hemisphere situated between Perseus and Gemini. It contains the bright star Capella."
"A red coloring matter derived from phenol; -- called also  in commerce yellow corallin."
"One skilled in treating and curing disorders of the ear."

"The European bison (Bison bonasus  / Europaeus) once widely distributed but now nearly extinct except where protected in the Lithuanian forests and perhaps in the Caucasus. It is distinct from the Urus of Caesar with which it has often been confused."
"The rising light of the morning; the dawn of day; the redness of the sky just before the sun rises."
"Belonging to  or resembling the aurora (the dawn or the northern lights); rosy."
"A divining or taking of omens by observing birds; an omen as to an undertaking  drawn from birds; an augury; an omen or sign in general; an indication as to the future."
"Sour and astringent; rough to the state; having acerbity; as  an austere crab apple; austere wine."
"Southern; lying or being in the south; as  austral land; austral ocean."
"The beginner  former or first mover of anything; hence the efficient cause of a thing; a creator; an originator."
"Personal observation or examination; seeing with one's own eyes; ocular view."

"The third season of the year  or the season between summer and winter often called """"the fall."""" Astronomically it begins in the northern temperate zone at the autumnal equinox about September 23 and ends at the winter solstice about December 23; but in popular language autumn in America comprises September October and November."
"A figure by which a grave and magnificent word is put for the proper word; amplification; hyperbole."
"To turn to the advantage of; to be of service to; to profit; to benefit; to help; as  artifices will not avail the sinner in the day of judgment."
"To cause to descend; to lower; to let fall; to doff."
"The front of an army. [Obs.] See Van."
"An excessive or inordinate desire of gain; greediness after wealth; covetousness; cupidity."
"The descent of a deity to earth  and his incarnation as a man or an animal; -- chiefly associated with the incarnations of Vishnu."
"Begone; depart; -- a word of contempt or abhorrence  equivalent to the phrase """"Get thee gone."
"A genus of grasses  including the common oat (Avena sativa); the oat grasses."
"A quantity of oats paid by a tenant to a landlord in lieu of rent."
"An officer of the king's stables whose duty it was to provide oats for the horses."
"To take vengeance for; to exact satisfaction for by punishing the injuring party; to vindicate by inflicting pain or evil on a wrongdoer."
"One who avenges or vindicates; as  an avenger of blood."
"A plant of the genus Geum  esp. Geum urbanum or herb bennet."
"To thrust forward (at a venture)  as a spear."
"A way or opening for entrance into a place; a passage by which a place may by reached; a way of approach or of exit."
"That service which a tenant owed his lord  to be done by the work beasts of the tenant as the carriage of wheat turf etc."
"To turn aside  or away; as to avert the eyes from an object; to ward off or prevent the occurrence or effects of; as how can the danger be averted? """"To avert his ire."
"The class of Vertebrata that includes the birds."
"A house  inclosure large cage or other place for keeping birds confined; a bird house."
"A genus of marine bivalves  having a pearly interior allied to the pearl oyster; -- so called from a supposed resemblance of the typical species to a bird."
"Greediness; strong appetite; eagerness; intenseness of desire; as  to eat with avidity."
"To abase or debase; to vilify; to depreciate."
"To look at; to view; to think of."
"The pulpy fruit of Persea gratissima  a tree of tropical America. It is about the size and shape of a large pear; -- called also avocado pear alligator pear midshipman's butter."
"To call off or away; to withdraw; to transfer to another tribunal."
"A grallatorial bird  of the genus Recurvirostra; the scooper. The bill is long and bend upward toward the tip. The American species is R. Americana."
"The person who carries anything away  or the vessel in which things are carried away."
"To fly away; to escape; to exhale."
"To appeal to; to cite or claim as authority."
"To declare openly  as something believed to be right; to own or acknowledge frankly; as a man avows his principles or his crimes."
"An open declaration; frank acknowledgment; as  an avowal of such principles."
"The defendant in replevin  who avows the distress of the goods and justifies the taking."
"The person who has a right to present to a benefice; the patron; an advowee. See Advowson."
"An advocate; a patron; a patron saint."
"A chief magistrate of a free imperial city or canton of Switzerland."
"To watch for; to look out for."
"To rouse from sleep; to wake; to awaken."
"To give by sentence or judicial determination; to assign or apportion  after careful regard to the nature of the case; to adjudge; as the arbitrators awarded damages to the complainant."
"One who awards  or assigns by sentence or judicial determination; a judge."
"Watchful; vigilant or on one's guard against danger or difficulty."
"Washed by the waves or tide; -- said of a rock or strip of shore  or (Naut.) of an anchor etc. when flush with the surface of the water so that the waves break over it."
"Just drawn out of the ground  and hanging perpendicularly; atrip; -- said of the anchor."
"Causing awe; appalling; awful; as  an awesome sight."
"Oppressing with fear or horror; appalling; terrible; as  an awful scene."
"In an awful manner; in a manner to fill with terror or awe; fearfully; reverently."
"For a while; for some time; for a short time."

"Wanting dexterity in the use of the hands  or of instruments; not dexterous; without skill; clumsy; wanting ease grace or effectiveness in movement; ungraceful; as he was awkward at a trick; an awkward boy."

"A pointed instrument for piercing small holes  as in leather or wood; used by shoemakers saddlers cabinetmakers etc. The blade is differently shaped and pointed for different uses as in the brad awl saddler's awl shoemaker's awl etc."
"The bristle or beard of barley  oats grasses etc. or any similar bristlelike appendage; arista."
"Furnished with an awn  or long bristle-shaped tip; bearded."
"A rooflike cover  usually of canvas extended over or before any place as a shelter from the sun rain or wind."
"Turned or twisted toward one side; not in a straight or true direction  or position; out of the right course; distorted; obliquely; asquint; with oblique vision; as to glance awry."

"A tool or instrument of steel  or of iron with a steel edge or blade for felling trees chopping and splitting wood hewing timber etc. It is wielded by a wooden helve or handle so fixed in a socket or eye as to be in the same plane with the blade. The broadax or carpenter's ax is an ax for hewing timber made heavier than the chopping ax and with a broader and thinner blade and a shorter handle."
"Of or pertaining to an axis; of the nature of  or resembling an axis; around an axis."
"In relation to  or in a line with an axis; in the axial (magnetic) line."
"The angle or point of divergence between the upper side of a branch  leaf or petiole and the stem or branch from which it springs."
"Situated in the axis of anything; as an embryo which lies in the axis of a seed."
"The armpit  or the cavity beneath the junction of the arm and shoulder."
"A borosilicate of alumina  iron and lime commonly found in glassy brown crystals with acute edges."

"A self-evident and necessary truth  or a proposition whose truth is so evident as first sight that no reasoning or demonstration can make it plainer; a proposition which it is necessary to take for granted; as """"The whole is greater than a part;"""" """"A thing can not at the same time be and not be."
"The spotted deer (Cervus axis or Axis maculata) of India  where it is called hog deer and parrah (Moorish name)."
"The pin or spindle on which a wheel revolves  or which revolves with a wheel."
"An amphibian of the salamander tribe found in the elevated lakes of Mexico; the siredon."
"A variety of jade. It is used by some savages  particularly the natives of the South Sea Islands for making axes or hatchets."
"Fat; grease; esp. the fat of pigs or geese; usually (Pharm.)  lard prepared for medical use."
"A native nurse for children; also  a lady's maid."
"The utterance of the ejaculation """"Ay me !"""" [Obs.] See Ay  interj."
"A genus of showy flowering shrubs  mostly natives of China or of North America; false honeysuckle. The genus is scarcely distinct from Rhododendron."
"The Neapolitan medlar (Crataegus azarolus)  a shrub of southern Europe; also its fruit."
"Destitute of any vestige of organic life  or at least of animal life; anterior to the existence of animal life; formed when there was no animal life on the globe; as the azoic. rocks."
"Pertaining to an acid produced by treating oleic with nitric acid."
"Confined to no zone or region; not local."
"The first principle of metals  i. e. mercury which was formerly supposed to exist in all metals and to be extractable from them."
"Pertaining to azote  or nitrogen; formed or consisting of azote; nitric; as azotic gas; azotic acid."
"A salt formed by the combination of azotous  or nitrous acid with a base; a nitrite."
"To impregnate with azote  or nitrogen; to nitrogenize."
"Of or relating to one of the early races in Mexico that inhabited the great plateau of that country at the time of the Spanish conquest in 1519."
"Sky-blue; resembling the clear blue color of the unclouded sky; cerulean; also  cloudless."
"Odd; having no fellow; not one of a pair; single; as  the azygous muscle of the uvula."
"One who administered the Eucharist with unleavened bread; -- a name of reproach given by those of the Greek church to the Latins."
"To cry baa  or bleat as a sheep."
"The supreme male divinity of the Phoenician and Canaanitish nations."
"A worshiper of Baal; a devotee of any false religion; an idolater."
"To utter words indistinctly or unintelligibly; to utter inarticulate sounds; as a child babbles."
"An idle talker; an irrational prater; a teller of secrets."
"An infant; a young child of either sex; a baby."
"The city and tower in the land of Shinar  where the confusion of languages took place."
"Finery of a kind to please a child."
"The doctrine of a modern religious sect  which originated in Persia in 1843 being a mixture of Mohammedan Christian Jewish and Parsee elements."
"The ring of the fruit of several East Indian species of acacia; neb-neb. It contains gallic acid and tannin  and is used for dyeing drab."
"A Hindoo gentleman; a native clerk who writes English; also  a Hindoo title answering to Mr. or Esquire."

"One of the Old World Quadrumana  of the genera Cynocephalus and Papio; the dog-faced ape. Baboons have dog-like muzzles and large canine teeth cheek pouches a short tail and naked callosities on the buttocks. They are mostly African. See Mandrill and Chacma and Drill an ape."
"An infant or young child of either sex; a babe."
"A broad  flatbottomed ferryboat usually worked by a rope."
"Stand back! give place! -- a cant word of the Elizabethan writers  probably in ridicule of some person who pretended to a knowledge of Latin which he did not possess."
"Pulpy throughout  like a berry; -- said of fruits."
"The god of wine  son of Jupiter and Semele."
"A large shallow vat; a cistern  tub or trough used by brewers distillers dyers picklers gluemakers and others for mixing or cooling wort holding water hot glue
"One who  or that which backs; especially one who backs a person or thing in a contest."
"A large stick of wood  forming the back of a fire on the hearth."
"Among leather dealers  the thickest and stoutest tanned hides."
"A saw (as a tenon saw) whose blade is stiffened by an added metallic back."
"A check; a relapse; a discouragement; a setback."
"The back and sides of a pig salted and smoked; formerly  the flesh of a pig salted or fresh."
"A form of the pat tense of Bid."
"A distinctive mark  token sign or cognizance worn on the person; as the badge of a society; the badge of a policeman."
"An itinerant licensed dealer in commodities used for food; a hawker; a huckster; -- formerly applied especially to one who bought grain in one place and sold it in another."
"A fresh-water sponge (Spongilla)  common in the north of Europe the powder of which is used to take away the livid marks of bruises."
"An evergreen Chinese shrub of the Magnolia family (Illicium anisatum)  and its aromatic seeds; Chinese anise; star anise."
"In a bad manner; poorly; not well; unskillfully; imperfectly; unfortunately; grievously; so as to cause harm; disagreeably; seriously."
"To cause to undergo a disgraceful punishment  as a recreant knight."
"A coarse stuff  usually of cotton originally made in India. Also an imitation of this fabric made for export."
"A sack or pouch  used for holding anything; as a bag of meal or of money."
"Sugar cane  as it comes crushed from the mill. It is then dried and used as fuel. Also extended to the refuse of beetroot sugar."
"The clothes  tents utensils and provisions of an army."
"A two-masted Arab or Indian trading vessel  used in Indian Ocean."
"Resembling a bag; loose or puffed out  or pendent like a bag; flabby; as baggy trousers; baggy cheeks."
"A commercial traveler; one employed to solicit orders for manufacturers and tradesmen."
"A house for bathing  sweating etc.; -- also in Turkey a prison for slaves."
"A musical wind instrument  now used chiefly in the Highlands of Scotland."
"The lower reef of fore and aft sails; also  the upper reef of topsails."
"The annular molding or group of moldings dividing a long shaft or clustered column into two or more parts."
"A wig  in use in the 18th century with the hair at the back of the head in a bag."

"One of several lepidopterous insects which construct  in the larval state a baglike case which they carry about for protection. One species (Platoeceticus Gloveri) feeds on the orange tree. See Basket worm."
"A weight used in certain parts of the East Indies  varying considerably in different localities the range being from 223 to 625 pounds."
"A bucket or scoop used in bailing water out of a boat."
"The person to whom goods are committed in trust  and who has a temporary possession and a qualified property in them for the purposes of the trust."
"The outer wall of a feudal castle."
"An officer in Scotland  whose office formerly corresponded to that of sheriff but now corresponds to that of an English alderman."
"Originally  a person put in charge of something especially a chief officer magistrate or keeper as of a county town hundred or castle; one to whom power/ of custody or care are intrusted."
"One who delivers goods or money to another in trust."
"The name of two Mohammedan festivals  of which one is held at the close of the fast called Ramadan and the other seventy days after the fast."
"Any substance  esp. food used in catching fish or other animals by alluring them to a hook snare inclosure or net."
"A coarse woolen stuff with a long nap; -- usually dyed in plain colors."
"A small copper coin formerly current in the Roman States  worth about a cent and a half."
"To prepare  as food by cooking in a dry heat either in an oven or under coals or on heated stone or metal; as to bake bread meat apples."
"One whose business it is to bake bread  biscuit etc."
"A paragraph describing something wonderful  used to fill out a newspaper column; -- an allusion to the miracle of Balaam's ass speaking."

"A platform projecting from the wall of a building  usually resting on brackets or consoles and inclosed by a parapet; as a balcony in front of a window. Also a projecting gallery in places of amusement; as the balcony in a theater."
"Destitute of the natural or common covering on the head or top  as of hair feathers foliage trees etc.; as a bald head; a bald oak."
"The most beautiful and beloved of the gods; the god of peace; the son of Odin and Freya."
"A piece of pork cut lower down than the sparerib  and destitute of fat."
"A broad belt  sometimes richly ornamented worn over one shoulder across the breast and under the opposite arm; less properly any belt."
"A kind of reddish  moderately acid winter apple."
"A bundle or package of goods in a cloth cover  and corded for storage or transportation; also a bundle of straw / hay etc. put up compactly for transportation."

"Plates or blades of """"whalebone " from two to twelve feet long and sometimes a foot wide which in certain whales (Balaenoidea) are attached side by side along the upper jaw and form a fringelike sieve by which the food is retained in the mouth."
"Full of deadly or pernicious influence; destructive."
"A pole or a frame raised as a sea beacon or a landmark."
"A ridge of land left unplowed between furrows  or at the end of a field; a piece missed by the plow slipping aside."
"Apt to balk; as  a balky horse."
"Any round or roundish body or mass; a sphere or globe; as  a ball of twine; a ball of snow."
"A popular kind of narrative poem  adapted for recitation or singing; as the ballad of Chevy Chase; esp. a sentimental or romantic poem in short stanzas."

"A form of French versification  sometimes imitated in English in which three or four rhymes recur through three stanzas of eight or ten lines each the stanzas concluding with a refrain and the whole poem with an envoy."
"Any heavy substance  as stone iron etc. put into the hold to sink a vessel in the water to such a depth as to prevent capsizing."
"An artistic dance performed as a theatrical entertainment  or an interlude by a number of persons usually women. Sometimes a scene accompanied by pantomime and dancing."
"A bag made of silk or other light material  and filled with hydrogen gas or heated air so as to rise and float in the atmosphere; especially one with a car attached for aerial navigation."
"Originally  a ball used for secret voting. Hence: Any printed or written ticket used in voting."
"An aromatic plant of the genus Melissa."
"Having the qualities of balm; odoriferous; aromatic; assuaging; soothing; refreshing; mild."
"A raft or float  used principally on the Pacific coast of South America."
"A resin containing more or less of an essential or volatile oil."
"Of or pertaining to the sea which separates Norway and Sweden from Jutland  Denmark and Germany; situated on the Baltic Sea."
"A child or baby; esp.  a representation in art of the infant Christ wrapped in swaddling clothes."
"A plant of the family of grasses  and genus Bambusa growing in tropical countries."
"A public proclamation or edict; a public order or notice  mandatory or prohibitory; a summons by public proclamation."
"A perennial herbaceous plant of almost treelike size (Musa sapientum); also  its edible fruit. See Musa."
"A bench; a high seat  or seat of distinction or judgment; a tribunal or court."
"A fillet  strap or any narrow ligament with which a thing is encircled or fastened or by which a number of things are tied bound together or confined; a fetter."
"A fillet or strip of woven material  used in dressing and binding up wounds etc."
"A fabric made in Manilla from the older leaf sheaths of the abaca (Musa textilis)."
"A species of silk or cotton handkerchief  having a uniformly dyed ground usually of red or blue with white or yellow figures of a circular lozenge or other simple form."
"A light box of pasteboard or thin wood  usually cylindrical for holding ruffs (the bands of the 17th century) collars caps bonnets etc."
"A narrow band or fillet; a part of a head-dress."
"A small band or fillet; any little band or flat molding  compassing a column like a ring."
"An Irish measure of two feet in length."
"A mastiff or other large and fierce dog  usually kept chained or tied up."
"A musical stringed instrument  similar in form to a guitar; a pandore."
"A carriage or cart used in India  esp. one drawn by bullocks."
"That which destroys life  esp. poison of a deadly quality."
"Having poisonous qualities; deadly; destructive; injurious; noxious; pernicious."
"To beat  as with a club or cudgel; to treat with violence; to handle roughly."
"To waste by little and little; to fritter away."
"A Hindoo trader  merchant cashier or money changer."
"To condemn to exile  or compel to leave one's country by authority of the ruling power."
"One who conducts the business of banking; one who  individually or as a member of a company keeps an establishment for the deposit or loan of money or for traffic in money bills of exchange etc."
"A kind of flag attached to a spear or pike by a crosspiece  and used by a chief as his standard in battle."
"A kind of cake or bread  in shape flat and roundish commonly made of oatmeal or barley meal and baked on an iron plate or griddle; -- used in Scotland and the northern counties of England."
"Notice of a proposed marriage  proclaimed in a church or other place prescribed by law in order that any person may object if he knows of just cause why the marriage should not take place."
"A feast; a sumptuous entertainment of eating and drinking; often  a complimentary or ceremonious feast followed by speeches."
"A supernatural being supposed by the Irish and Scotch peasantry to warn a family of the speedy death of one of its members  by wailing or singing in a mournful voice under the windows of the house."
"A variety of small barnyard fowl  with feathered legs probably brought from Bantam a district of Java."
"To address playful good-natured ridicule to  -- the person addressed or something pertaining to him being the subject of the jesting; to rally; as he bantered me about my credulity."

"A tree of the same genus as the common fig  and called the Indian fig (Ficus Indica) whose branches send shoots to the ground which take root and become additional trunks until it may be the tree covers some acres of ground and is able to shelter thousands of men."
"A gigantic African tree (Adansonia digitata)  also naturalized in India. See Adansonia."

"The act of baptizing; the application of water to a person  as a sacrament or religious ceremony by which he is initiated into the visible church of Christ. This is performed by immersion sprinkling or pouring."
"One who administers baptism; -- specifically applied to John  the forerunner of Christ."
"To administer the sacrament of baptism to."

"A piece of wood  metal or other material long in proportion to its breadth or thickness used as a lever and for various other purposes but especially for a hindrance obstruction or fastening; as the bars of a fence or gate; the bar of a door."
"Beard  or that which resembles it or grows in the place of it."
"The first word in certain mnemonic lines which represent the various forms of the syllogism. It indicates a syllogism whose three propositions are universal affirmatives."
"Of  or from barbarian nations; foreign; -- often with reference to barbarous nations of east."
"The countries on the north coast of Africa from Egypt to the Atlantic. Hence: A Barbary horse; a barb. [Obs.] Also  a kind of pigeon."
"Bearded; beset with long and weak hairs."
"A slender tactile organ on the lips of certain fished."
"One whose occupation it is to shave or trim the beard  and to cut and dress the hair of his patrons."
"A variety of small dog  having long curly hair."
"A vessel for freight; -- used in Mediterranean."
"A professional poet and singer  as among the ancient Celts whose occupation was to compose and sing verses in honor of the heroic achievements of princes and brave men."
"A piece of defensive (or  sometimes ornamental) armor for a horse's neck breast and flanks; a barb. [Often in the pl.]"
"Accoutered with defensive armor; -- said of a horse."
"Of or pertaining to bards  or their poetry."
"Pertaining to  or written by a bard or bards."
"The system of bards; the learning and maxims of bards."
"Without clothes or covering; stripped of the usual covering; naked; as  his body is bare; the trees are bare."
"A gauzelike fabric for ladies' dresses  veils etc. of worsted silk and worsted or cotton and worsted."

"An agreement between parties concerning the sale of property; or a contract by which one party binds himself to transfer the right to some property for a consideration  and the other party binds himself to receive the property and pay the consideration."
"A pleasure boat; a vessel or boat of state  elegantly furnished and decorated."
"Of or pertaining to barium; as  baric oxide."
"A name given to several species of Salsola from which soda is made  by burning the barilla in heaps and lixiviating the ashes."

"Native sulphate of barium  a mineral occurring in transparent colorless white to yellow crystals (generally tabular) also in granular form and in compact massive forms resembling marble. It has a high specific gravity and hence is often called heavy spar. It is a common mineral in metallic veins."

"One of the elements  belonging to the alkaline earth group; a metal having a silver-white color and melting at a very high temperature. It is difficult to obtain the pure metal from the facility with which it becomes oxidized in the air. Atomic weight 137. Symbol Ba. Its oxide called baryta."
"To strip the bark from; to peel."
"Formerly  any small sailing vessel as a pinnace fishing smack etc.; also a rowing boat; a barge. Now applied poetically to a sailing vessel or boat of any kind."
"An animal that barks; hence  any one who clamors unreasonably."
"A valuable grain  of the family of grasses genus Hordeum used for food and for making malt from which are prepared beer ale and whisky."
"Foam rising upon beer  or other malt liquors when fermenting and used as leaven in making bread and in brewing; yeast."
"A girl or woman who attends the customers of a bar  as in a tavern or beershop."
"A court held in Derbyshire  in England for deciding controversies between miners."
"A covered building used chiefly for storing grain  hay and other productions of a farm. In the United States a part of the barn is often used for stables."
"A form or mode of syllogism of which the first proposition is a universal affirmative  and the other two are particular negative."

"A title or degree of nobility; originally  the possessor of a fief who had feudal tenants under him; in modern times in France and Germany a nobleman next in rank below a count; in England a nobleman of the lowest grade in the House of Lords being next below a viscount."

"A dignity or degree of honor next below a baron and above a knight  having precedency of all orders of knights except those of the Garter. It is the lowest degree of honor that is hereditary. The baronets are commoners."
"The fee or domain of a baron; the lordship  dignity or rank of a baron."
"A post sunk in the ground to receive the bars closing a passage into a field."
"A building for soldiers  especially when in garrison. Commonly in the pl. originally meaning temporary huts but now usually applied to a permanent structure or set of buildings."
"An artificial bar or obstruction placed in a river or water course to increase the depth of water; as  the barrages of the Nile."
"A round vessel or cask  of greater length than breadth and bulging in the middle made of staves bound with hoops and having flat ends or heads."
"Incapable of producing offspring; producing no young; sterile; -- said of women and female animals."
"A kind of cap formerly worn by soldiers; -- called also barret cap. Also  the flat cap worn by Roman Catholic ecclesiastics."
"A carpentry obstruction  stockade or other obstacle made in a passage in order to stop an enemy."
"A room containing a bar or counter at which liquors are sold."
"A support having handles  and with or without a wheel on which heavy or bulky things can be transported by hand. See Handbarrow and Wheelbarrow."
"Traversed by barrulets or small bars; -- said of the field."
"Divided into bars; -- said of the field."
"To traffic or trade  by exchanging one commodity for another in distinction from a sale and purchase in which money is paid for the commodities transferred; to truck."
"The demesne lands of a manor; also  the manor itself."
"A passage into a field or yard  closed by bars made to take out of the posts."
"A red wood of a leguminous tree (Baphia nitida)  from Angola and the Gaboon in Africa. It is used as a dyewood and also for ramrods violin bows and turner's work."
"An oxide of barium (or barytum); a heavy earth with a specific gravity above 4."
"Barium sulphate  generally called heavy spar or barite. See Barite."
"A rock of igneous origin  consisting of augite and triclinic feldspar with grains of magnetic or titanic iron and also bottle-green particles of olivine frequently disseminated."
"In mechanics an apparatus on the principle of the seesaw  in which one end rises as the other falls."
"Of little  or less than the usual height; of low growth; as base shrubs."
"In a base manner; with despicable meanness; dishonorably; shamefully."
"To abash; to disconcert or be disconcerted or put out of countenance."
"A Turkish title of honor  now written pasha. See Pasha."
"Relating to a base; performing the office of a base in a salt."
"The slope or angle to which the cutting edge of a tool  as a plane is ground."
"A hollow vessel or dish  to hold water for washing and for various other uses."
"The middle of the anterior margin of the great foramen of the skull."
"The foundation of anything; that on which a thing rests."
"To lie in warmth; to be exposed to genial heat."
"A vessel made of osiers or other twigs  cane rushes splints or other flexible material interwoven."
"Pertaining to Biscay  its people or their language."
"A game at cards  resembling the modern faro said to have been invented at Venice."
"The bass or lowest part; as  to sing basso."
"A wind instrument of the double reed kind  furnished with holes which are stopped by the fingers and by keys as in flutes. It forms the natural bass to the oboe clarinet etc."
"The inner fibrous bark of various plants; esp. of the lime tree; hence  matting cordage etc. made therefrom."
"A """"natural"""" child; a child begotten and born out of wedlock; an illegitimate child; one born of an illicit union."
"To beat with a stick; to cudgel."

"A work projecting outward from the main inclosure of a fortification  consisting of two faces and two flanks and so constructed that it is able to defend by a flanking fire the adjacent curtain or wall which extends from one bastion to another. Two adjacent bastions are connected by the curtain which joins the flank of one with the adjacent flank of the other. The distance between the flanks of a bastion is called the gorge. A lunette is a detached bastion. See Ravelin."
"The ace of clubs in quadrille and omber."
"A positive or nonacid constituent of compound  either elementary or if compound performing the functions of an element."
"A large stick; a club; specifically  a piece of wood with one end thicker or broader than the other used in playing baseball cricket etc."
"An aboriginal American name for the sweet potato (Ipomaea batatas)."
"The quantity of bread baked at one time."
"A boat; esp. a flat-bottomed  clumsy boat used on the Canadian lakes and rivers."

"A name given to several species of fishes: (a) The Malthe vespertilio of the Atlantic coast. (b) The flying gurnard of the Atlantic (Cephalacanthus spinarella). (c) The California batfish or sting ray (Myliobatis Californicus.)"

"The act of exposing the body  or part of the body for purposes of cleanliness comfort health etc. to water vapor hot air or the like; as a cold or a hot bath; a medicated bath; a steam bath; a hip bath."
"To wash by immersion  as in a bath; to subject to a bath."
"A ludicrous descent from the elevated to the low  in writing or speech; anticlimax."
"Originally  cambric or lawn of fine linen; now applied also to cloth of similar texture made of cotton."
"A short bat for beating clothes in washing them; -- called also batler  batling staff batting staff."
"A weight used in the East  varying according to the locality; in Turkey the greater batman is about 157 pounds the lesser only a fourth of this; at Aleppo and Smyrna the batman is 17 pounds."
"A staff or truncheon  used for various purposes; as the baton of a field marshal; the baton of a conductor in musical performances."
"The one who wields the bat in cricket  baseball etc."
"Shaped like a bat's wing; as  a bat's-wing burner."
"Extra pay; esp. an extra allowance to an English officer serving in India."
"A single combat; as  trial by battel. See Wager of battel under Wager."
"A student at Oxford who is supplied with provisions from the buttery; formerly  one who paid for nothing but what he called for answering nearly to a sizar at Cambridge."
"To make fat by plenteous feeding; to fatten."
"To beat with successive blows; to beat repeatedly and with violence  so as to bruise shatter or demolish; as to batter a wall or rampart."
"The act of beating the woods  bushes etc. for game."
"An elevated river bed or sea bed."
"A springboard in a circus or gymnasium; -- called also batule board."
"A small copper coin  with a mixture of silver formerly current in some parts of Germany and Switzerland. It was worth about four cents."
"A trifling piece of finery; a gewgaw; that which is gay and showy without real value; a cheap  showy plaything."
"A fagot of brushwood  or other light combustible matter for kindling fires; refuse of brushwood."
"A fine fellow; -- a term of endearment."
"A person who keeps a house of prostitution  or procures women for a lewd purpose; a procurer or procuress; a lewd person; -- usually applied to a woman."
"The practice of procuring women for the gratification of lust."
"To cry out with a loud  full sound; to cry with vehemence as in calling or exultation; to shout; to vociferate."
"An inclosure with mud or stone walls  for keeping cattle; a fortified inclosure."
"Reddish brown; of the color of a chestnut; -- applied to the color of horses."
"A large  edible siluroid fish of the Nile of two species (Bagrina bayad and B. docmac)."
"Properly  a bay horse but often any horse. Commonly in the phrase blind bayard an old blind horse."
"A pointed instrument of the dagger kind fitted on the muzzle of a musket or rifle  so as to give the soldier increased means of offense and defense."
"An inlet from the Gulf of Mexico  from a lake or from a large river sometimes sluggish sometimes without perceptible movement except from tide and wind."
"A fragrant liquid  used for cosmetic and medicinal purposes."
"In the East  an exchange marketplace or assemblage of shops where goods are exposed for sale."
"Having a beach or beaches; formed by a beach or beaches; shingly."
"A signal fire to notify of the approach of an enemy  or to give any notice commonly of warning."
"A messenger or crier of a court; a servitor; one who cites or bids persons to appear and answer; -- called also an apparitor or summoner."
"A small hound  or hunting dog twelve to fifteen inches high used in hunting hares and other small game. See Illustration in Appendix."
"The bill or nib of a bird  consisting of a horny sheath covering the jaws. The form varied much according to the food and habits of the bird and is largely used in the classification of birds."
"Having a beak or a beaklike point; beak-shaped."
"A large drinking cup  with a wide mouth supported on a foot or standard."
"To gather matter; to swell and come to a head  as a pimple."
"Any large piece of timber or iron long in proportion to its thickness  and prepared for use."
"A name given to the seed of certain leguminous herbs  chiefly of the genera Faba Phaseolus and Dolichos; also to the herbs."
"To support or sustain; to hold up."
"Barley; the six-rowed barley or the four-rowed barley  commonly the former (Hord. vulgare)."
"The hair that grows on the chin  lips and adjacent parts of the human face chiefly of male adults."
"One who  or that which bears sustains or carries."
"Partaking of the qualities of a bear; resembling a bear in temper or manners."
"Any living creature; an animal; -- including man  insects etc."
"Pertaining to  or having the form nature or habits of a beast."
"To bathe; also  to dry or heat as unseasoned wood."
"To pronounce or regard as happy  or supremely blessed or as conferring happiness."
"A man who takes great care to dress in the latest fashion; a dandy."
"A niche  cupboard or sideboard for plate china glass etc.; a buffet."
"Like a beau; characteristic of a beau; foppish; fine."
"An assemblage or graces or properties pleasing to the eye  the ear the intellect the aesthetic faculty or the moral sense."
"An amphibious rodent  of the genus Castor."
"To make bloody; to stain with blood."
"To render calm or quiet; to calm; to still; to appease."
"A South American bird of the flycatcher family. (Tityra inquisetor)."
"By or for the cause that; on this account that; for the reason that."
"A European fish (Pagellus centrodontus); the sea bream or braise."
"A small grommet  or a ring or loop of rope / metal for holding things in position as spars ropes etc.; also a bracket a pocket or a handle made of rope."
"To make a significant sign to; hence  to summon as by a motion of the hand."
"To cause obscurity or dimness to; to dim; to cloud."
"A fish of the Mediterranean (Sphyraena spet). See Barracuda."

"An article of furniture to sleep or take rest in or on; a couch. Specifically: A sack or mattress  filled with some soft material in distinction from the bedstead on which it is placed (as a feather bed) or this with the bedclothes added. In a general sense any thing or place used for sleeping or reclining on or in as a quantity of hay straw leaves or twigs."
"To make a daff or fool of."
"The sacred books of the Buddhists in Burmah."
"To wet by dashing or throwing water or other liquid upon; to bespatter."
"To daub over; to besmear or soil with anything thick and dirty."
"A wingless  bloodsucking hemipterous insect (Cimex Lectularius) sometimes infesting houses and especially beds. See Illustration in Appendix."
"A cord or rope interwoven in a bedstead so as to support the bed."
"To pray; also  to offer; to proffer."
"To deck  ornament or adorn; to grace."
"A gall produced on rosebushes  esp. on the sweetbrier or eglantine by a puncture from the ovipositor of a gallfly (Rhodites rosae). It was once supposed to have medicinal properties."
"The Abyssinian or Arabian ibex (Capra Nubiana). It is probably the wild goat of the Bible."
"To throw into utter disorder and confusion  as if by the agency of evil spirits; to bring under diabolical influence; to torment."
"To moisten with dew  or as with dew."
"To make dim; to obscure or darken."
"To dress or adorn tawdrily or with false taste."
"An instrument for tightening the parts of a bedstead."
"A place appropriated to the confinement and care of the insane; a madhouse."
"One of the nomadic Arabs who live in tents  and are scattered over Arabia Syria and northern Africa esp. in the deserts."
"One of the four standards that support a bedstead or the canopy over a bedstead."
"A room or apartment intended or used for a bed; a lodging room."
"A recess in a room for a bed."
"A sore on the back or hips caused by lying for a long time in bed."
"A tick or bag made of cloth  used for inclosing the materials of a bed."
"To duck; to put the head under water; to immerse."
"To cover with dung  as for manuring; to bedaub or defile literally or figuratively."
"To sprinkle  soil or cover with dust."
"To make a dwarf of; to stunt or hinder the growth of; to dwarf."
"p. p. of Be; -- used for been."
"Consisting  or made of the wood or bark of the beech; belonging to the beech."
"An animal of the genus Bos  especially the common species B. taurus including the bull cow and ox in their full grown state; esp. an ox or cow fattened for food."
"Having much beef; of the nature of beef; resembling beef; fleshy."
"A hive for a swarm of bees. Also used figuratively."
"A fermented liquor made from any malted grain  but commonly from barley malt with hops or some other substance to impart a bitter flavor."
"Of or resembling beer; affected by beer; maudlin."
"The wax secreted by bees  and of which their cells are constructed."
"A biennial plant of the genus Beta  which produces an edible root the first year and seed the second year."
"A heavy mallet  used to drive wedges beat pavements etc."
"To be suitable to; to suit; to become."
"To involve in a fog; -- mostly as a participle or part. adj."
"To fool; to delude or lead into error; to infatuate; to deceive."
"In front of; preceding in space; ahead of; as  to stand before the fire; before the house."
"To furnish or deck with a frill."
"A title of honor in Turkey and in some other parts of the East; a bey."
"To adorn with gems  or as with gems."
"To procreate  as a father or sire; to generate; -- commonly said of the father."
"One who begs; one who asks or entreats earnestly  or with humility; a petitioner."
"The act of begging; the state of being a beggar; mendicancy; extreme poverty."

"One of an association of religious laymen living in imitation of the Beguines. They arose in the thirteenth century  were afterward subjected to much persecution and were suppressed by Innocent X. in 1650. Called also Beguins."
"To have or commence an independent or first existence; to take rise; to commence."
"To bind with a band or girdle; to gird."
"To gnaw; to eat away; to corrode."
"To exalt to the dignity of a god; to deify."
"A genus of plants  mostly of tropical America many species of which are grown as ornamental plants. The leaves are curiously one-sided and often exhibit brilliant colors."
"To soil with grime or dirt deeply impressed or rubbed in."
"To delude by guile  artifice or craft; to deceive or impose on as by a false statement; to lure."
"A woman belonging to one of the religious and charitable associations or communities in the Netherlands  and elsewhere whose members live in beguinages and are not bound by perpetual vows."
"In the East Indies  a princess or lady of high rank."
"Advantage; favor; stead; benefit; interest; profit; support; defense; vindication."
"To manage or govern in point of behavior; to discipline; to handle; to restrain."
"To sever the head from; to take off the head of."
"That which is willed or ordered; a command; a mandate; an injunction."
"On the side opposite the front or nearest part; on the back side of; at the back of; on the other side of; as  behind a door; behind a hill."
"To have in sight; to see clearly; to look at; to regard with the eyes."
"To be necessary for; to be fit for; to be meet for  with respect to necessity duty or convenience; -- mostly used impersonally."
"To jape; to laugh at; to deceive."
"To ornament with a jewel or with jewels; to spangle."
"The Babylonian name of the god known among the Hebrews as Baal. See Baal."
"To ply diligently; to work carefully upon."
"To fasten  as with a lace or cord."
"To lay on or cover; to adorn."
"To eject or throw up from the stomach with violence; to eruct."
"To place under the lee  or unfavorably to the wind."
"A movable tower erected by besiegers for purposes of attack and defense."
"Of or pertaining to the Belgae  a German tribe who anciently possessed the country between the Rhine the Seine and the ocean."
"An evil spirit; a wicked and unprincipled person; the personification of evil."
"To show to be false; to convict of  or charge with falsehood."

"Assent to a proposition or affirmation  or the acceptance of a fact opinion or assertion as real or true without immediate personal knowledge; reliance upon word or testimony; partial or full assurance without positive knowledge or absolute certainty; persuasion; conviction; confidence; as belief of a witness; the belief of our senses."

"To exercise belief in; to credit upon the authority or testimony of another; to be persuaded of the truth of  upon evidence furnished by reasons arguments and deductions of the mind or by circumstances other than personal knowledge; to regard or accept as true; to place confidence in; to think; to consider; as to believe a person a statement or a doctrine."
"A hollow metallic vessel  usually shaped somewhat like a cup with a flaring mouth containing a clapper or tongue and giving forth a ringing sound on being struck."
"A young lady of superior beauty and attractions; a handsome lady  or one who attracts notice in society; a fair lady."
"Having (such) a belly; puffed out; -- used in composition; as  pot-bellied; shad-bellied."
"A man who rings a bell  especially to give notice of anything in the streets. Formerly also a night watchman who called the hours."
"To make a hollow  loud noise as an enraged bull."

"An instrument  utensil or machine which by alternate expansion and contraction or by rise and fall of the top draws in air through a valve and expels it through a tube for various purposes as blowing fires ventilating mines or filling the pipes of an organ with wind."
"That part of the human body which extends downward from the breast to the thighs  and contains the bowels or intestines; the abdomen."
"To lock  or fasten as with a lock."
"To be the property of; as  Jamaica belongs to Great Britain."
"Under  or lower in place; beneath not so high; as below the moon; below the knee."
"To treat as a lout; to talk abusively to."
"That which engirdles a person or thing; a band or girdle; as  a lady's belt; a sword belt."
"A platform from which speakers addressed an assembly."
"To maul or beat severely; to bruise."
"To drag through  encumber with or fix in the mire; to soil by passing through mud or dirt."
"To express deep grief for by moaning; to express sorrow for; to lament; to bewail; to pity or sympathize with."
"To soil or encumber with mire and dirt."
