"The sign /; the same as B flat."
"To muddle  daze or partially stupefy as with liquor."
"The seed of one or more species of moringa; as  oil of ben. See Moringa."
"A long seat  differing from a stool in its greater length."
"One of the senior and governing members of an Inn of Court."
"To strain or move out of a straight line; to crook by straining; to make crooked; to curve; to make ready for use by drawing into a curve; as  to bend a bow; to bend the knee."
"A narrow bend  esp. one half the width of the bend."
"Divided into an even number of bends; -- said of a shield or its charge."
"Lower in place  with something directly over or on; under; underneath; hence at the foot of."
"An act of kindness; a favor conferred."
"To catch in a net; to insnare."
"A province in India  giving its name to various stuffs animals etc."
"To involve in darkness; to shroud with the shades of night; to obscure."
"Of a kind or gentle disposition; gracious; generous; favorable; benignant."

"The name of two plants (Sesamum orientale and S. indicum)  originally Asiatic; -- also called oil plant. From their seeds an oil is expressed called benne oil used mostly for making soap. In the southern United States the seeds are used in candy."
"The common yellow-flowered avens of Europe (Geum urbanum); herb bennet. The name is sometimes given to other plants  as the hemlock valerian etc."
"Relating to the deepest zone or region of the ocean."
"A bounding in bents  or the stalks of coarse stiff withered grass; as benty fields."
"To make torpid; to deprive of sensation or sensibility; to stupefy; as  a hand or foot benumbed by cold."
"A compound radical  C6H5.CH of the aromatic series related to benzyl and benzoyl; -- used adjectively or in combination."

"A volatile  very inflammable liquid C6H6 contained in the naphtha produced by the destructive distillation of coal from which it is separated by fractional distillation. The name is sometimes applied also to the impure commercial product or benzole and also but rarely to a similar mixed product of petroleum."
"A yellowish crystalline substance  C6H5.CO.CO.C6H5 formed from benzoin by the action of oxidizing agents and consisting of a doubled benzoyl radical."

"A liquid consisting mainly of the lighter and more volatile hydrocarbons of petroleum or kerosene oil  used as a solvent and for cleansing soiled fabrics; -- called also petroleum spirit petroleum benzine. Varieties or similar products are gasoline naphtha rhigolene ligroin etc."

"A resinous substance  dry and brittle obtained from the Styrax benzoin a tree of Sumatra Java etc. having a fragrant odor and slightly aromatic taste. It is used in the preparation of benzoic acid in medicine and as a perfume."
"An impure benzene  used in the arts as a solvent and for various other purposes. See Benzene."
"A compound radical  C6H5.CO; the base of benzoic acid of the oil of bitter almonds and of an extensive series of compounds."
"A compound radical  C6H5.CH2 related to toluene and benzoic acid; -- commonly used adjectively."
"To paint; to cover or color with  or as with paint."
"The act of bequeathing or leaving by will; as  a bequest of property by A. to B."
"To quote constantly or with great frequency."
"To rain upon; to wet with rain."
"To rate or chide vehemently; to scold."
"To make foul; to soil; to defile."

"A member of a race somewhat resembling the Arabs  but often classed as Hamitic who were formerly the inhabitants of the whole of North Africa from the Mediterranean southward into the Sahara and who still occupy a large part of that region; -- called also Kabyles. Also the language spoken by this people."
"To make destitute; to deprive; to strip; -- with of before the person or thing taken away."
"A large mass or hill  as of ice."
"To mention in rhyme or verse; to rhyme about."
"A four-wheeled carriage  having a sheltered seat behind the body and separate from it invented in the 17th century at Berlin."
"A narrow shelf or path between the bottom of a parapet and the ditch."
"Pertaining to the city or canton of Bern  in Switzerland or to its inhabitants."
"A small  oval transparent jellyfish belonging to the Ctenophora."
"Furnished with berries; consisting of a berry; baccate; as  a berried shrub."
"Any small fleshy fruit  as the strawberry mulberry huckleberry etc."
"A kind of collar or cape worn by ladies."

"A mineral of great hardness  and when transparent of much beauty. It occurs in hexagonal prisms commonly of a green or bluish green color but also yellow pink and white. It is a silicate of aluminium and glucinum (beryllium). The aquamarine is a transparent sea-green variety used as a gem. The emerald is another variety highly prized in jewelry and distinguished by its deep color which is probably due to the presence of a little oxide of chromium."
"To ask or entreat with urgency; to supplicate; to implore."
"Literally: To appear or seem (well  ill best etc.) for (one) to do or to have. Hence: To be fit suitable or proper for or worthy of; to become; to befit."
"A large food fish (Anoplopoma fimbria) of the north Pacific coast; -- called also candlefish."
"At the side of; on one side of."
"To beset or surround with armed forces  for the purpose of compelling to surrender; to lay siege to; to beleaguer; to beset."
"To smear with any viscous  glutinous matter; to bedaub; to soil."
"To blacken with smut; to foul with soot."
"To scatter like snow; to cover thick  as with snow flakes."
"A brush of twigs for sweeping; a broom; anything which sweeps away or destroys."
"To assort or be congruous with; to fit  or become."
"To make sottish; to make dull or stupid; to stupefy; to infatuate."
"To daub  soil or make foul with spawl or spittle."
"To speak or arrange for beforehand; to order or engage against a future time; as  to bespeak goods a right or a favor."
"To soil or daub with spew; to vomit on."
"To season with spice  or with some spicy drug."
"To mark with spots  or as with spots."
"To spurt on or over; to asperse."
"Having good qualities in the highest degree; most good  kind desirable suitable etc.; most excellent; as the best man; the best road; the best cloth; the best abilities."
"To sprinkle with  or as with stars; to decorate with or as with stars; to bestud."
"Belonging to a beast  or to the class of beasts."
"To stick over  as with sharp points pressed in; to mark by infixing points or spots here and there; to pierce."
"To put into brisk or vigorous action; to move with life and vigor; -- usually with the reciprocal pronoun."
"To lay up in store; to deposit for safe keeping; to stow; to place; to put."
"To strew or scatter over; to besprinkle."
"To set or adorn  as with studs or bosses; to set thickly; to stud; as to bestud with stars."
"That which is laid  staked or pledged as between two parties upon the event of a contest or any contingent issue; the act of giving such a pledge; a wager."

"A nitrogenous base  C5H11NO2 produced artificially and also occurring naturally in beet-root molasses and its residues from which it is extracted as a white crystalline substance; -- called also lycine and oxyneurine. It has a sweetish taste."
"An East India muslin  formerly used for cravats veils etc."
"To give ; to bestow; to grant; to accord; to consent."

"A species of pepper (Piper betle)  the leaves of which are chewed with the areca or betel nut and a little shell lime by the inhabitants of the East Indies. It is a woody climber with ovate many-nerved leaves."
"A place of worship; a hallowed spot."

"To call to mind; to recall or bring to recollection  reflection or consideration; to think; to consider; -- generally followed by a reflexive pronoun often with of or that before the subject of thought."
"To handle; to wear or soil by handling; as books."
"To happen to; to befall; to come to ; as  woe betide the wanderer."
"In good season or time; before it is late; seasonably; early."
"To furnish with a title or titles; to entitle."
"To signify by some visible object; to show by signs or tokens."
"The French name for concrete; hence  concrete made after the French fashion."
"To put in violent motion; to agitate; to disturb; to toss."
"To draw into  or catch in a trap; to insnare; to circumvent."
"To deliver into the hands of an enemy by treachery or fraud  in violation of trust; to give up treacherously or faithlessly; as an officer betrayed the city."
"To set in order; to adorn; to deck  to embellish; to trim."
"To contract to any one for a marriage; to engage or promise in order to marriage; to affiance; -- used esp. of a woman."
"Having good qualities in a greater degree than another; as  a better man; a better physician; a better house; a better air."
"A small  leaping Australian marsupial of the genus Bettongia; the jerboa kangaroo."
"A short bar used by thieves to wrench doors open."
"A substance of a resinous nature  obtained from the outer bark of the common European birch (Betula alba) or from the tar prepared therefrom; -- called also birch camphor."
"In the space which separates; betwixt; as  New York is between Boston and Philadelphia."
"A beurre (or buttery) pear  one with the meat soft and melting; -- used with a distinguishing word; as Beurre d'Anjou; Beurre Clairgeau."

"Any angle other than a right angle; the angle which one surface makes with another when they are not at right angles; the slant or inclination of such surface; as  to give a bevel to the edge of a table or a stone slab; the bevel of a piece of timber."
"A light repast between meals; a lunch."
"A chief broken or opening like a carpenter's bevel."
"A company; an assembly or collection of persons  especially of ladies."
"To express deep sorrow for  as by wailing; to lament; to wail over."
"To keep watch over; to keep awake."
"To be on one's guard; to be cautious; to take care; -- commonly followed by of or lest before the thing that is to be avoided."
"To weep over; to deplore; to bedew with tears."
"To corrupt with regard to chastity; to make a whore of."
"A double slip of leather by which bells are fastened to a hawk's legs."
"To gain an ascendency over by charms or incantations; to affect (esp. to injure) by witchcraft or sorcery."
"A governor of a province or district in the Turkish dominions; also  in some places a prince or nobleman; a beg; as the bey of Tunis."
"On the further side of; in the same direction as  and further on or away than."
"A gold coin of Byzantium or Constantinople  varying in weight and value usually (those current in England) between a sovereign and a half sovereign. There were also white or silver bezants."
"The rim which encompasses and fastens a jewel or other object  as the crystal of a watch in the cavity in which it is set."
"A game at cards in which various combinations of cards in the hand  when declared score points."

"A calculous concretion found in the intestines of certain ruminant animals (as the wild goat  the gazelle and the Peruvian llama) formerly regarded as an unfailing antidote for poison and a certain remedy for eruptive pestilential or putrid diseases. Hence: Any antidote or panacea."
"An astringent and narcotic drug made from the dried leaves and seed capsules of wild hemp (Cannabis Indica)  and chewed or smoked in the East as a means of intoxication. See Hasheesh."
"An Indian monkey (Macacus Rhesus)  protected by the Hindoos as sacred. See Rhesus."
"Having two hydrogen atoms which can be replaced by negative atoms or radicals to form salts; -- said of bases. See Diacid."
"A weight on the side of the ball used in the game of bowls  or a tendency imparted to the ball which turns it from a straight line."
"A small piece of cloth worn by children over the breast  to protect the clothes."
"Having to hydrogen atoms which can be replaced by positive or basic atoms or radicals to form salts; -- said of acids. See Dibasic."
"One given to drinking alcoholic beverages too freely; a tippler; -- chiefly used in composition; as  winebibber."
"Pieces of timber bolted to certain parts of a mast to support the trestletrees."
"A cock or faucet having a bent down nozzle."
"One who makes the Bible the sole rule of faith."
"A pale blue pigment  prepared from the native blue carbonate of copper or from smalt; -- called also blue bice."
"A muscle having two heads or origins; -- applied particularly to a flexor in the arm  and to another in the thigh."
"A remarkable ganoid fish (Polypterus bichir) found in the Nile and other African rivers. See Brachioganoidei."
"A small wooden vessel made of staves and hoops  like a tub."
"An anvil ending in a beak or point (orig. in two beaks); also  the beak or horn itself."
"A light vehicle having two wheels one behind the other. It has a saddle seat and is propelled by the rider's feet acting on cranks or levers."
"An invitation of friends to drink ale at some poor man's house  and there to contribute in charity for his relief."
"One who bids or offers a price."
"A name used in calling a hen or chicken."
"To dwell; to inhabit; to abide; to stay."
"An instrument or weapon with two prongs."
"A small horse formerly allowed to each trooper or dragoon for carrying his baggage."
"A handbarrow or portable frame on which a corpse is placed or borne to the grave."
"A sort of apple peculiar to Norfolk  Eng."
"Cleft to the middle or slightly beyond the middle; opening with a cleft; divided by a linear sinus  with straight margins."
"Two-threaded; involving the use of two threads; as  bifilar suspension; a bifilar balance."
"Twofold; double; of two kinds  degrees etc."
"Having largeness of size; of much bulk or magnitude; of great size; large."
"The offense of marrying one person when already legally married to another."
"A fish of the genus Priacanthus  remarkable for the large size of the eye."
"To make or become big; to enlarge."
"A child's cap; a hood  or something worn on the head."
"A measure of land in India  varying from a third of an acre to an acre."
"A corner  bend or angle; a hollow; as the bight of a horse's knee; the bight of an elbow."
"In a tumid  swelling blustering manner; haughtily; violently."
"The state or quality of being big; largeness; size; bulk."
"Obstinately and blindly attached to some creed  opinion practice or ritual; unreasonably devoted to a system or party and illiberal toward the opinions of others."
"The state of mind of a bigot; obstinate and unreasoning attachment of one's own belief and opinions  with narrow-minded intolerance of beliefs opposed to them."
"A person of consequence; as  the bigwigs of society."
"A trinket; a jewel; -- a word applied to anything small and of elegant workmanship."
"A nest of wild bees  wasps or ants; a swarm."
"The East Indian name of a virulent poison extracted from Aconitum ferox or other species of aconite: also  the plant itself."
"A two-masted passenger boat or small vessel  used in the bay of Manila."
"A rapier; a sword; so named from Bilbao  in Spain."

"A yellow  or greenish viscid fluid usually alkaline in reaction secreted by the liver. It passes into the intestines where it aids in the digestive process. Its characteristic constituents are the bile salts and coloring matters."
"The protuberant part of a cask  which is usually in the middle."
"Relating or belonging to bile; conveying bile; as  biliary acids; biliary ducts."
"A name applied to the amorphous or crystalline mass obtained from bile by the action of alcohol and ether. It is composed of a mixture of the sodium salts of the bile acids."
"To frustrate or disappoint; to deceive or defraud  by nonfulfillment of engagement; to leave in the lurch; to give the slip to; as to bilk a creditor."
"A beak  as of a bird or sometimes of a turtle or other animal."
"An English fish  allied to the cod; the coalfish."
"A weevil or curculio of various species  as the corn weevil. See Curculio."
"A small paper; a note; a short letter."
"According to the French and American method of numeration  a thousand millions or 1 0 0 000; according to the English method a million millions or 1 0 0 0 000. See Numeration."
"One who uses  or is armed with a bill or hooked ax."
"An alloy of gold and silver with a large proportion of copper or other base metal  used in coinage."
"A great wave or surge of the sea or other water  caused usually by violent wind."
"Of or pertaining to billows; swelling or swollen into large waves; full of billows or surges; resembling billows."
"Lean meat cut into strips and sun-dried."
"Animals having two hands; -- a term applied by Cuvier to man as a special order of Mammalia."
"A box  frame crib or inclosed place used as a receptacle for any commodity; as a corn bin; a wine bin; a coal bin."
"Compounded or consisting of two things or parts; characterized by two (things)."
"To tie  or confine with a cord band ligature chain etc.; to fetter; to make fast; as to bind grain in bundles; to bind a prisoner."
"One who binds; as  a binder of sheaves; one whose trade is to bind; as a binder of books."
"A place where books  or other articles are bound; a bookbinder's establishment."
"The winding or twining stem of a hop vine or other climbing plant."
"A heap or pile; as  a bing of wood."
"A large species of barbel (Barbus bynni)  found in the Nile and much esteemed for food."
"A dioptric telescope  fitted with two tubes joining so as to enable a person to view an object with both eyes at once; a double-barreled field glass or an opera glass."
"A doctrine that the genesis or production of living organisms can take place only through the agency of living germs or parents; -- opposed to abiogenesis."

"The science of life; that branch of knowledge which treats of living matter as distinct from matter which is not living; the study of living tissue. It has to do with the origin  structure development function and distribution of animals and plants."
"The physiological individual  characterized by definiteness and independence of function in distinction from the morphological individual or morphon."
"A physiological organ; a living organ; an organ endowed with function; -- distinguished from idorgan."
"The classification of living organisms according to their structural character; taxonomy."
"Relating to life; as  the biotic principle."
"Mica containing iron and magnesia  generally of a black or dark green color; -- a common constituent of crystalline rocks. See Mica."
"Doubly polar; having two poles; as  a bipolar cell or corpuscle."

"A tree of several species  constituting the genus Betula; as the white or common birch (B. alba) (also called silver birch and lady birch); the dwarf birch (B. glandulosa); the paper or canoe birch (B. papyracea); the yellow birch (B. lutea); the black or cherry birch (B. lenta)."
"Orig.  a chicken; the young of a fowl; a young eaglet; a nestling; and hence a feathered flying animal (see 2)."
"A pretty or dear little bird; -- a pet name."
"An ancient galley or vessel with two banks or tiers of oars."
"To whip with a birch or rod."
"To revolve or cause to revolve; to spin."
"A law made by husbandmen respecting rural affairs; a rustic or local law or by-law."
"To make  or move with a whirring noise as of wheels in motion."
"A coarse kind of thick woolen cloth  worn by the poor in the Middle Ages; also a woolen cap or hood worn over the shoulders or over the head."
"A fish of the turbot kind; the brill."
"The act or fact of coming into life  or of being born; -- generally applied to human beings; as the birth of a son."
"Twice; -- a word showing that something is  or is to be repeated; as a passage of music or an item in accounts."
"A kind of unraised bread  of many varieties plain sweet or fancy formed into flat cakes and bakes hard; as ship biscuit."
"To cut or divide into two parts."
"Soup or broth made by boiling several sorts of flesh together."

"One of the elements; a metal of a reddish white color  crystallizing in rhombohedrons. It is somewhat harder than lead and rather brittle; masses show broad cleavage surfaces when broken across. It melts at 507� Fahr. being easily fused in the flame of a candle. It is found in a native state and as a constituent of some minerals. Specific gravity 9.8. Atomic weight 207.5. Symbol Bi."
"A dark brown pigment extracted from the soot of wood."
"An herbaceous plant of the genus Polygonum  section Bistorta; snakeweed; adderwort. Its root is used in medicine as an astringent."
"The part of a bridle  usually of iron which is inserted in the mouth of a horse and having appendages to which the reins are fastened."
"The female of the canine kind  as of the dog wolf and fox."
"To seize with the teeth  so that they enter or nip the thing seized; to lacerate crush or wound with the teeth; as to bite an apple; to bite a crust; the dog bit a man."
"One who  or that which bites; that which bites often or is inclined to bite as a dog or fish."
"AA turn of the cable which is round the bitts."
"A wading bird of the genus Botaurus  allied to the herons of various species."
"A liquor  generally spirituous in which a bitter herb leaf or root is steeped."
"A small bit of anything  of indefinite size or quantity; a short distance."

"A frame of two strong timbers fixed perpendicularly in the fore part of a ship  on which to fasten the cables as the ship rides at anchor or in warping. Other bitts are used for belaying (belaying bitts) for sustaining the windlass (carrick bitts winch bitts or windlass bitts) to hold the pawls of the windlass (pawl bitts) etc."

"Mineral pitch; a black  tarry substance burning with a bright flame; Jew's pitch. It occurs as an abundant natural product in many places as on the shores of the Dead and Caspian Seas. It is used in cements in the construction of pavements etc. See Asphalt."
"A white  crystalline nitrogenous substance C2O2N3H5 formed by heating urea. It is intermediate between urea and cyanuric acid."

"A mollusk having a shell consisting of two lateral plates or valves joined together by an elastic ligament at the hinge  which is usually strengthened by prominences called teeth. The shell is closed by the contraction of two transverse muscles attached to the inner surface as in the clam -- or by one as in the oyster. See Mollusca."
"One side of an echinoderm  including a pair of ambulacra in distinction from the opposite side (trivium) which includes three ambulacra."
"The watch of a whole army by night  when in danger of surprise or attack."
"Odd in manner or appearance; fantastic; whimsical; extravagant; grotesque."
"The upper faceted portion of a brilliant-cut diamond  which projects from the setting and occupies the zone between the girdle and the table. See Brilliant n."
"To utter or tell unnecessarily  or in a thoughtless manner; to publish (secrets or trifles) without reserve or discretion."

"Destitute of light  or incapable of reflecting it; of the color of soot or coal; of the darkest or a very dark color the opposite of white; characterized by such a color; as black cloth; black hair or eyes."
"In a black manner; darkly  in color; gloomily; threateningly; atrociously."
"The name of a kind of in used in copperplate printing  prepared from the charred husks of the grape and residue of the wine press."

"A bag or sac in animals  which serves as the receptacle of some fluid; as the urinary bladder; the gall bladder; -- applied especially to the urinary bladder either within the animal or when taken out and inflated with air."
"Properly  the leaf or flat part of the leaf of any plant especially of gramineous plants. The term is sometimes applied to the spire of grasses."
"Having a blade or blades; as  a two-bladed knife."
"An inflammatory swelling or sore; a bulla  pustule or blister."
"To censure; to express disapprobation of; to find fault with; to reproach."
"To take the color out of  and make white; to bleach; as to blanch linen; age has blanched his hair."
"Mild; soft; gentle; smooth and soothing in manner; suave; as  a bland temper; bland persuasion; a bland sycophant."
"Of a white or pale color; without color."
"A heavy  loosely woven fabric usually of wool and having a nap used in bed clothing; also a similar fabric used as a robe; or any fabric used as a cover for a horse."
"In a blank manner; without expression; vacuously; as  to stare blankly."
"Having the sensibilities deadened by excess or frequency of enjoyment; sated or surfeited with pleasure; used up."
"One who  or that which blasts or destroys."
"To cry  as a calf or sheep; to bleat; to make a senseless noise; to talk inconsiderately."
"Bellowing  as a calf; bawling; brawling; clamoring; disagreeably clamorous; sounding loudly and harshly."
"To prate; to babble; to rail; to make a senseless noise; to patter."
"The blue buck. See Blue buck  under Blue."
"A stream of gas or vapor emitting light and heat in the process of combustion; a bright flame."
"One who spreads reports or blazes matters abroad."
"The part of a tree which lies immediately under the bark; the alburnum or sapwood."
"To make white  or whiter; to remove the color or stains from; to blanch; to whiten."
"Dim or sore with water or rheum; -- said of the eyes."
"To make the noise of  or one like that of a sheep; to cry like a sheep or calf."
"A large vesicle or bulla  usually containing a serous fluid; a blister; a bubble as in water glass etc."
"Containing blebs  or characterized by blebs; as blebby glass."
"To emit blood; to lose blood; to run with blood  by whatever means; as the arm bleeds; the wound bled freely; to bleed at the nose."
"One who  or that which draws blood."
"To mark with deformity; to injure or impair  as anything which is well formed or excellent; to mar or make defective either the body or mind."
"To shrink; to start back; to draw back  from lack of courage or resolution; to flinch; to quail."
"To mix or mingle together; esp. to mingle  combine or associate so that the separate things mixed or the line of demarcation can not be distinguished. Hence: To confuse; to confound."

"A mineral  called also sphalerite and by miners mock lead false galena and black-jack. It is a zinc sulphide but often contains some iron. Its color is usually yellow brown or black and its luster resinous."
"One who  or that which blends; an instrument as a brush used in blending."
"A marine fish of the genus Blennius or family Blenniidae; -- so called from its coating of mucus. The species are numerous."
"A South African antelope (Alcelaphus albifrons)  having a large white spot on the forehead."
"To make or pronounce holy; to consecrate"
"One who blesses; one who bestows or invokes a blessing."
"A form of decay in fruit which is overripe."
"An inflammation in the foot of a horse  between the sole and the bone."
"To affect with blight; to blast; to prevent the growth and fertility of."
"Destitute of the sense of seeing  either by natural defect or by deprivation; without sight."
"Without sight  discernment or understanding; without thought investigation knowledge or purpose of one's own."
"To wink; to twinkle with  or as with the eye."
"Orig.  blithesomeness; gladness; now the highest degree of happiness; blessedness; exalted felicity; heavenly joy."

"A vesicle of the skin  containing watery matter or serum whether occasioned by a burn or other injury or by a vesicatory; a collection of serous fluid causing a bladderlike elevation of the cuticle."
"A genus of herbs (Blitum) with a fleshy calyx. Blitum capitatum is the strawberry blite."
"Gay; merry; sprightly; joyous; glad; cheerful; as  a blithe spirit."
"To make turgid  as with water or air; to cause a swelling of the surface of from effusion of serum in the cellular tissue producing a morbid enlargement often accompanied with softness."
"The common herring  esp. when of large size smoked and half dried; -- called also bloat herring."
"Something blunt and round; a small drop or lump of something viscid or thick; a drop; a bubble; a blister."
"The roughest and cheapest sort of rubblework  in masonry."

"A piece of wood more or less bulky; a solid mass of wood  stone etc. usually with one or more plane or approximately plane faces; as a block on which a butcher chops his meat; a block by which to mount a horse; children's playing blocks etc."
"Of a fair color; light-colored; as  blond hair; a blond complexion."
"The fluid which circulates in the principal vascular system of animals  carrying nourishment to all parts of the body and bringing away waste products to be excreted. See under Arterial."
"Containing or resembling blood; of the nature of blood; as  bloody excretions; bloody sweat."
"A blossom; the flower of a plant; an expanded bud; flowers  collectively."
"A costume for women  consisting of a short dress with loose trousers gathered round ankles and (commonly) a broad-brimmed hat."
"Full of bloom; flowery; flourishing with the vigor of youth; as  a bloomy spray."
"The act of blowing; a roaring wind; a blast."

"The flower of a plant  or the essential organs of reproduction with their appendages; florescence; bloom; the flowers of a plant collectively; as the blossoms and fruit of a tree; an apple tree in blossom."
"To spot  stain or bespatter as with ink."
"A blot or spot  as of color or of ink; especially a large or irregular spot. Also Fig.; as a moral blotch."
"To cure  as herrings by salting and smoking them; to bloat."
"One who  or that which blots; esp. a device for absorbing superfluous ink."
"A light  loose over-garment like a smock frock worn especially by workingmen in France; also a loose coat of any material as the undress uniform coat of the United States army."
"Any species of fly of the genus Musca that deposits its eggs or young larvae (called flyblows and maggots) upon meat or other animal products."

"A tube  as of cane or reed sometimes twelve feet long through which an arrow or other projectile may be impelled by the force of the breath. It is a weapon much used by certain Indians of America and the West Indies; -- called also blowpipe and blowtube. See Sumpitan."
"Windy; as  blowy weather; a blowy upland."
"Having high color from exposure to the weather; ruddy-faced; blowzy; disordered."
"Coarse and ruddy-faced; fat and ruddy; high colored; frowzy."
"To swell; to puff out  as with weeping."
"A kind of half boot  named from the Prussian general Blucher."
"Having the color of the clear sky  or a hue resembling it whether lighter or darker; as the deep blue sea; as blue as a sapphire; blue violets."
"A species of whitefish (Coregonus nigripinnis) found in Lake Michigan."
"A name given to several different species of plants having blue flowers  as the Houstonia coerulea the Centaurea cyanus or bluebottle and the Vaccinium angustifolium."
"Having a broad  flattened front; as the bluff bows of a ship."
"To make a gross error or mistake; as  to blunder in writing or preparing a medical prescription."
"To amalgamate and blend; to beat up or mix in water  as clay."
"A wooden blade with a cross handle  used for mi/ing the clay in potteries; a plunger."
"Having a thick edge or point  as an instrument; dull; not sharp."
"In a blunt manner; coarsely; plainly; abruptly; without delicacy  or the usual forms of civility."

"To render obscure by making the form or outline of confused and uncertain  as by soiling; to smear; to make indistinct and confused; as to blur manuscript by handling it while damp; to blur the impression of a woodcut by an excess of ink."
"To utter suddenly and unadvisedly; to divulge inconsiderately; to ejaculate; -- commonly with out."
"To become suffused with red in the cheeks  as from a sense of shame modesty or confusion; to become red from such cause as the cheeks or face."
"Like a blush; having the color of a blush; rosy."
"To blow fitfully with violence and noise  as wind; to be windy and boisterous as the weather."
"A genus of large American serpents  including the boa constrictor the emperor boa of Mexico (B. imperator) and the chevalier boa of Peru (B. eques)."
"The uncastrated male of swine; specifically  the wild hog."
"A piece of timber sawed thin  and of considerable length and breadth as compared with the thickness -- used for building etc."
"One who has food statedly at another's table  or meals and lodgings in his house for pay or compensation of any kind."

"To vaunt one's self; to brag; to say or tell things which are intended to give others a high opinion of one's self or of things belonging to one's self; as  to boast of one's exploits courage descent wealth."
"A small open vessel  or water craft usually moved by cars or paddles but often by a sail."
"Conveyance by boat; also  a charge for such conveyance."
"The quantity or amount that fills a boat."
"A crying out; a roaring; a bellowing; reverberation."
"A man who manages a boat; a rower of a boat."
"Anything that hangs so as to play loosely  or with a short abrupt motion as at the end of a string; a pendant; as the bob at the end of a kite's tail."
"A squabble; a tumult; a noisy disturbance; as  to raise a bobbery."

"A small pin  or cylinder formerly of bone now most commonly of wood used in the making of pillow lace. Each thread is wound on a separate bobbin which hangs down holding the thread at a slight tension."
"A nickname for a policeman; -- from Sir Robert Peel  who remodeled the police force. See Peeler."
"The fly at the end of the leader; an end fly."
"A rope or chain to confine the bowsprit of a ship downward to the stem or cutwater; -- usually in the pl."
"An animal (as a horse or dog) with a short tail."
"A short wig with bobs or short curls; -- called also bobtail wig."
"A cylindrical glass vessel  with a large and short neck."
"A form of syllogism of which the first and third propositions are particular negatives  and the middle term a universal affirmative."
"The round hole in the furnace of a glass manufactory through which the fused glass is taken out."
"A European fish (Box vulgaris)  having a compressed body and bright colors; -- called also box and bogue."
"A bowl or vessel made from a gourd."
"A coarse woolen fabric  used for floor cloths to cover carpets etc.; -- so called from the town of Bocking in England where it was first made."
"To indicate by signs  as future events; to be the omen of; to portend to presage; to foreshow."
"A large food fish (Diagramma lineatum)  native of the East Indies."
"A kind of under waist stiffened with whalebone  etc. worn esp. by women; a corset; stays."
"Having a body; -- usually in composition; as  able-bodied."
"Having a body or material form; physical; corporeal; consisting of matter."
"A small Scotch coin worth about one sixth of an English penny."
"The material organized substance of an animal  whether living or dead as distinguished from the spirit or vital principle; the physical person."
"A colonist or farmer in South Africa of Dutch descent."
"A quagmire filled with decayed moss and other vegetable matter; wet spongy ground where a heavy body is apt to sink; a marsh; a morass."
"To stop or hesitate as if suddenly frightened  or in doubt or impeded by unforeseen difficulties; to take alarm; to exhibit hesitancy and indecision."
"Consisting of  or containing a bog or bogs; of the nature of a bog; swampy; as boggy land."
"A four-wheeled truck  having a certain amount of play around a vertical axis used to support in part a locomotive on a railway track."
"A goblin; a specter; a frightful phantom; a bogy; a bugbear."
"To fall off from the wind; to edge away to leeward; -- said only of inferior craft."
"Spurious; fictitious; sham; -- a cant term originally applied to counterfeit coin  and hence denoting anything counterfeit."
"The wood of trees  esp. of oaks dug up from peat bogs. It is of a shining black or ebony color and is largely used for making ornaments."
"Bohea tea  an inferior kind of black tea. See under Tea."

"To be agitated  or tumultuously moved as a liquid by the generation and rising of bubbles of steam (or vapor) or of currents produced by heating it to the boiling point; to be in a state of ebullition; as the water boils."
"A place and apparatus for boiling  as for evaporating brine in salt making."
"Of or pertaining to bole or clay; partaking of the nature and qualities of bole; clayey."

"A kind of missile weapon consisting of one  two or more balls of stone iron or other material attached to the ends of a leather cord; -- used by the Gauchos of South America and others for hurling at and entangling an animal."
"Forward to meet danger; venturesome; daring; not timorous or shrinking from risk; brave; courageous."
"To make bold; to encourage; to embolden."
"A fragrant evergreen shrub of Chili (Peumus Boldus). The bark is used in tanning  the wood for making charcoal the leaves in medicine and the drupes are eaten."
"The trunk or stem of a tree  or that which is like it."
"A Spanish dance  or the lively music which accompanies it."
"Pertaining to  or obtained from the Boletus."
"A genus of fungi having the under side of the pileus or cap composed of a multitude of fine separate tubes. A few are edible  and others very poisonous."
"A kind of bright meteor; a bolis."
"A meteor or brilliant shooting star  followed by a train of light or sparks; esp. one which explodes."
"The pod or capsule of a plant  as of flax or cotton; a pericarp of a globular form."
"An upright wooden or iron post in a boat or on a dock  used in veering or fastening ropes."
"A tree from which the branches have been cut; a pollard."
"A city of Italy which has given its name to various objects."
"A long pillow or cushion  used to support the head of a person lying on a bed; -- generally laid under the pillows."
"A shaft or missile intended to be shot from a crossbow or catapult  esp. a short stout blunt-headed arrow; a quarrel; an arrow or that which resembles an arrow; a dart."
"One who bolts; esp.: (a) A horse which starts suddenly aside. (b) A man who breaks away from his party."
"An edible fish of the Nile (genus Chromis)."
"A rounded mass of anything  esp. a large pill."
"A large American serpent  so called from the sound it makes."
"A piece of heavy ordnance formerly used for throwing stones and other ponderous missiles. It was the earliest kind of cannon."
"A genus of trees  called also the silkcotton tree; also a tree of the genus Bombax."
"Pertaining to  or obtained from the silkworm; as bombic acid."
"A thin spheroidal glass retort or flask  used in the sublimation of camphor."
"A genus of moths  which includes the silkworm moth. See Silkworm."
"In mining  a rich mine or vein of silver or gold; hence anything which is a mine of wealth or yields a large income."
"Sugar confectionery; a sugarplum; hence  any dainty."
"A boy's game played with large marbles."
"That which binds  ties fastens or confines or by which anything is fastened or bound as a cord chain etc.; a band; a ligament; a shackle or a manacle."
"The state of being bound; condition of being under restraint; restraint of personal liberty by compulsion; involuntary servitude; slavery; captivity."
"A small quadruped of Bengal (Paradoxurus bondar)  allied to the genet; -- called also musk cat."
"One who places goods under bond or in a bonded warehouse."
"A man slave  or one bound to service without wages."
"The hard  calcified tissue of the skeleton of vertebrate animals consisting very largely of calcic carbonate calcic phosphate and gelatine; as blood and bone."
"A medicinal plant  the thoroughwort (Eupatorium perfoliatum). Its properties are diaphoretic and tonic."
"A large fire built in the open air  as an expression of public joy and exultation or for amusement."
"A large tropical fish (Orcynus pelamys) allied to the tunny. It is about three feet long  blue above with four brown stripes on the sides. It is sometimes found on the American coast."
"A female servant charged with the care of a young child."
"A headdress for men and boys; a cap."
"Handsome; beautiful; pretty; attractively lively and graceful."
"The height of the fashion; fashionable society."
"A premium given for a loan  or for a charter or other privilege granted to a company; as the bank paid a bonus for its charter."
"Consisting of bone  or of bones; full of bones; pertaining to bones."
"A Buddhist or Fohist priest  monk or nun."
"A collection of sheets of paper  or similar material blank written or printed bound together; commonly many folded and bound sheets containing continuous printing or writing."
"One who enters accounts or names  etc. in a book; a bookkeeper."
"As much as will fill a book; a book full."
"Given to reading; fond of study; better acquainted with books than with men; learned from books."

"A company of Irish herdsmen  or a single herdsman wandering from place to place with flocks and herds and living on their milk like the Tartars; also a place in the mountain pastures inclosed for the shelter of cattle or their keepers."
"A long pole or spar  run out for the purpose of extending the bottom of a particular sail; as the jib boom the studding-sail boom etc."
"A small African hyracoid mammal (Dendrohyrax arboreus) resembling the daman."
"A husbandman; a peasant; a rustic; esp. a clownish or unrefined countryman."
"A stall or a crib for an ox  cow or other animal."
"To lift or push from behind (one who is endeavoring to climb); to push up; hence  to assist in overcoming obstacles or in making advancement."
"Remedy; relief; amends; reparation; hence  one who brings relief."
"A northern constellation  containing the bright star Arcturus."
"A house or shed built of boards  boughs or other slight materials for temporary occupation."
"A servant at a hotel or elsewhere  who cleans and blacks the boots and shoes."
"That which is seized by violence or obtained by robbery  especially collective spoil taken in war; plunder; pillage."
"To drink greedily or immoderately  esp. alcoholic liquor; to tipple."
"One who boozes; a toper; a guzzler of alcoholic liquors; a bouser."
"A little intoxicated; fuddled; stupid with liquor; bousy."
"The act of looking out suddenly  as from behind a screen so as to startle some one (as by children in play) or of looking out and drawing suddenly back as if frightened."
"Pertaining to  or produced from borax; containing boron; boric; as boracic acid."
"A mucilaginous plant of the genus Borago (B. officinalis)  which is used esp. in France as a demulcent and diaphoretic."
"A salt formed by the combination of boric acid with a base or positive radical."

"A white or gray crystalline salt  with a slight alkaline taste used as a flux in soldering metals making enamels fixing colors on porcelain and as a soap. It occurs native in certain mineral springs and is made from the boric acid of hot springs in Tuscany. It was originally obtained from a lake in Thibet and was sent to Europe under the name of tincal. Borax is a pyroborate or tetraborate of sodium Na2B4O7.10H2O."
"The base or servile tenure by which a bordar held his cottage."
"A villein who rendered menial service for his cottage; a cottier."
"The outer part or edge of anything  as of a garment a garden etc.; margin; verge; brink."
"A border one fifth the width of the shield  surrounding the field. It is usually plain but may be charged."
"Northern; pertaining to the north  or to the north wind; as a boreal bird; a boreal blast."
"The state of being bored  or pestered; a state of ennui."
"The smaller two-horned rhinoceros of South Africa (Atelodus bicornis)."
"One that bores; an instrument for boring."
"A binary compound of boron with a more positive or basic element or radical; -- formerly called boruret."

"A rare variety of camphor  C10H17.OH resembling ordinary camphor from which it can be produced by reduction. It is said to occur in the camphor tree of Borneo and Sumatra (Dryobalanops camphora) but the natural borneol is rarely found in European or American commerce being in great request by the Chinese. Called also Borneo camphor Malay camphor and camphol."
"A valuable ore of copper  containing copper iron and sulphur; -- also called purple copper ore (or erubescite) in allusion to the colors shown upon the slightly tarnished surface."

"A nonmetallic element occurring abundantly in borax. It is reduced with difficulty to the free state  when it can be obtained in several different forms; viz. as a substance of a deep olive color in a semimetallic form and in colorless quadratic crystals similar to the diamond in hardness and other properties. It occurs in nature also in boracite datolite tourmaline and some other minerals. Atomic weight 10.9. Symbol B."

"In England  an incorporated town that is not a city; also a town that sends members to parliament; in Scotland a body corporate consisting of the inhabitants of a certain district erected by the sovereign with a certain jurisdiction; in America an incorporated town or village as in Pennsylvania and Connecticut."
"Coarse woolen cloth; hence  coarse clothing; a garment."
"To receive from another as a loan  with the implied or expressed intention of returning the identical article or its equivalent in kind; -- the opposite of lend."
"Imperfectly crystallized or coarse diamonds  or fragments made in cutting good diamonds which are reduced to powder and used in lapidary work."
"A genus of ruminant quadrupeds  including the wild and domestic cattle distinguished by a stout body hollow horns and a large fold of skin hanging from the neck."
"A drink  used in the East. See Boza."
"A growth of trees or shrubs; underwood; a thicket; thick foliage; a wooded landscape."
"A kind of antelope. See Bush buck."
"A grove; a thicket; shrubbery; an inclosure formed by branches of trees  regularly or irregularly disposed."
"Woody or bushy; covered with boscage or thickets."
"The breast of a human being; the part  between the arms to which anything is pressed when embraced by them."
"Any protuberant part; a round  swelling part or body; a knoblike process; as a boss of wood."
"A stone in a building  left rough and projecting to be afterward carved into shape."
"A rudimental antler of a young male of the red deer."
"The rule or practices of bosses  esp. political bosses."

"A game at cards  played by four persons with two packs of fifty-two cards each; -- said to be so called from Boston Massachusetts and to have been invented by officers of the French army in America during the Revolutionary war."

"The science which treats of the structure of plants  the functions of their parts their places of growth their classification and the terms which are employed in their description and denomination. See Plant."
"A sort of cake or sausage  made of the salted roes of the mullet much used on the coast of the Mediterranean as an incentive to drink."
"A swelling on the skin; a large ulcerous affection; a boil; an eruptive disease."
"One who mends or patches  esp. a tailor or cobbler."
"Marked with botches; full of botches; poorly done."
"Compensation; amends; satisfaction; expiation; as  man bote a compensation or a man slain."

"A dipterous insect of the family (Estridae  of many different species some of which are particularly troublesome to domestic animals as the horse ox and sheep on which they deposit their eggs. A common species is one of the botflies of the horse (Gastrophilus equi) the larvae of which (bots) are taken into the stomach of the animal where they live several months and pass through their larval states. In tropical America one species sometimes lives under the human skin and another in the stomach. See Gadfly."
"The one and the other; the two; the pair  without exception of either."
"To annoy; to trouble; to worry; to perplex. See Pother."
"Of or pertaining to Bothnia  a country of northern Europe or to a gulf of the same name which forms the northern part of the Baltic sea."

"The peepul tree; esp.  the very ancient tree standing at Anurajahpoora in Ceylon grown from a slip of the tree under which Gautama is said to have received the heavenly light and so to have become Buddha."
"The larvae of several species of botfly  especially those larvae which infest the stomach throat or intestines of the horse and are supposed to be the cause of various ailments."
"A hollow vessel  usually of glass or earthenware (but formerly of leather) with a narrow neck or mouth for holding liquids."
"One who bottles wine  beer soda water etc."
"The lowest part of anything; the foot; as  the bottom of a tree or well; the bottom of a hill a lane or a page."
"Having a bud or button  or a kind of trefoil at the end; furnished with knobs or buttons."
"A weevil; a worm that breeds in malt  biscuit etc."
"A small room  esp. if pleasant or elegantly furnished to which a lady may retire to be alone or to receive intimate friends; a lady's (or sometimes a gentleman's) private room."
"A charge representing a leather vessel for carrying water; -- also called water bouget."
"An arm or branch of a tree  esp. a large arm or main branch."
"A flexure; a bend; a twist; a turn; a coil  as in a rope; as the boughts of a serpent."
"Boiled or stewed meat; beef boiled with vegetables in water from which its gravy is to be made; beef from which bouillon or soup has been made."
"A molding  the convexity of which is one fourth of a circle being a member just below the abacus in the Tuscan and Roman Doric capital; a torus; an ovolo."
"A long  stout fishing line to which many hooks are attached."
"To strike or thump  so as to rebound or to make a sudden noise; a knock loudly."
"One who bounces; a large  heavy person who makes much noise in moving."
"One who  or that which limits; a boundary."
"A member of a family which has occupied several European thrones  and whose descendants still claim the throne of France."
"A mullet (Mugil capito) found in the rivers of Southern Europe and in Africa."
"An old French dance tune in common time."
"An exchange  or place where merchants bankers etc. meet for business at certain hours; esp. the Stock Exchange of Paris."
"To drink immoderately; to carouse; to booze. See Booze."
"As much of an action as is performed at one time; a going and returning  as of workmen in reaping mowing etc.; a turn; a round."
"An oxgang  or as much land as an ox can plow in a year; an ancient measure of land of indefinite quantity but usually estimated at fifteen acres."
"Relating to that tribe of ruminant mammals of which the genus Bos is the type."
"Of or pertaining to the genus Bos; relating to  or resembling the ox or cow; oxlike; as the bovine genus; a bovine antelope."
"To cause to deviate from straightness; to bend; to inflect; to make crooked or curved."
"Capable of being bowed or bent; flexible; easily influenced; yielding."
"One born within hearing distance of Bow-bells; a cockney."
"One of the intestines of an animal; an entrail  especially of man; a gut; -- generally used in the plural."
"Shading  like a bower; full of bowers."
"A voracious ganoid fish (Amia calva) found in the fresh waters of the United States; the mudfish; -- called also Johnny Grindle  and dogfish."
"The great Arctic or Greenland whale. (Balaena mysticetus). See Baleen  and Whale."
"A knot in which a portion of the string is drawn through in the form of a loop or bow  so as to be readily untied."
"A concave vessel of various forms (often approximately hemispherical)  to hold liquids etc."
"One who plays at bowls  or who rolls the ball in cricket or any other game."

"A rope fastened near the middle of the leech or perpendicular edge of the square sails  by subordinate ropes called bridles and used to keep the weather edge of the sail tight forward when the ship is closehauled."
"A man who uses a bow; an archer."
"To make ready; to prepare; to dress."
"A trap for lobsters  being a wickerwork cylinder with a funnel-shaped entrance at one end."
"The distance traversed by an arrow shot from a bow."
"To drench; to soak; especially  to immerse (in water believed to have curative properties)."
"An onomatopoetic name for a dog or its bark."

"A tree or shrub  flourishing in different parts of the world. The common box (Buxus sempervirens) has two varieties one of which the dwarf box (B. suffruticosa) is much used for borders in gardens. The wood of the tree varieties being very hard and smooth is extensively used in the arts as by turners engravers mathematical instrument makers etc."
"Made of boxwood; pertaining to  or resembling the box (Buxus)."
"To put (a vessel) on the other tack by veering her short round on her heel; -- so called from the circumstance of bracing the head yards abox (i. e.  sharp aback on the wind)."
"A male child  from birth to the age of puberty; a lad; hence a son."
"A member of a Russian aristocratic order abolished by Peter the Great. Also  one of a privileged class in Roumania."
"A winding or zigzag trench forming a path or communication from one siegework to another  to a magazine etc."
"To combine against (a landlord  tradesman employer or other person) to withhold social or business relations from him and to deter others from holding such relations; to subject to a boycott."
"A Flemish sloop with a castle at each end."
"The state of being a boy; the time during which one is a boy."
"Resembling a boy in a manners or opinions; belonging to a boy; childish; trifling; puerile."
"An acidulated fermented drink of the Arabs and Egyptians  made from millet seed and various astringent substances; also an intoxicating beverage made from hemp seed darnel meal and water."
"That which holds anything tightly or supports it firmly; a bandage or a prop."
"That which braces  binds or makes firm; a band or bandage."
"An opening caused by the parting of any solid body; a crack or breach; a flaw."
"An architectural member  plain or ornamental projecting from a wall or pier to support weight falling outside of the same; also a decorative feature seeming to discharge such an office."
"A leaf  usually smaller than the true leaves of a plant from the axil of which a flower stalk arises."

"A thin nail  usually small with a slight projection at the top on one side instead of a head; also a small wire nail with a flat circular head; sometimes a small tapering square-bodied finishing nail with a countersunk head."
"A hillside; a slope; a bank; a hill."

"To talk about one's self  or things pertaining to one's self in a manner intended to excite admiration envy or wonder; to talk boastfully; to boast; -- often followed by of; as to brag of one's exploits courage or money or of the great things one intends to do."
"A liquor made of ale and honey fermented  with spices etc."
"In a manner to be bragged of; finely; proudly."
"The One First Cause; also  one of the triad of Hindoo gods. The triad consists of Brahma the Creator Vishnu the Preserver and Siva the Destroyer."
"A person of the highest or sacerdotal caste among the Hindoos."
"To weave  interlace or entwine together as three or more strands or threads; to form into a braid; to plait."
"A thong of soft leather to bind up a hawk's wing."

"The whitish mass of soft matter (the center of the nervous system  and the seat of consciousness and volition) which is inclosed in the cartilaginous or bony cranium of vertebrate animals. It is simply the anterior termination of the spinal cord and is developed from three embryonic vesicles whose cavities are connected with the central canal of the cord; the cavities of the vesicles become the central cavities or ventricles and the walls thicken unequally and become the three segments the fore- mid- and hind-brain."
"A European marine fish (Pagrus vulgaris) allied to the American scup; the becker. The name is sometimes applied to the related species."
"Full of brakes; abounding with brambles  shrubs or ferns; rough; thorny."
"Any plant of the genus Rubus  including the raspberry and blackberry. Hence: Any rough prickly shrub."
"Pertaining to  resembling or full of brambles."
"The broken coat of the seed of wheat  rye or other cereal grain separated from the flour or meal by sifting or bolting; the coarse chaffy part of ground grain."
"A shoot or secondary stem growing from the main stem  or from a principal limb or bough of a tree or other plant."
"Full of branches; having wide-spreading branches; consisting of branches."
"A burning piece of wood; or a stick or piece of wood partly burnt  whether burning or after the fire is extinct."
"One who  or that which brands; a branding iron."

"A strong alcoholic liquor distilled from wine. The name is also given to spirit distilled from other liquors  and in the United States to that distilled from cider and peaches. In northern Europe it is also applied to a spirit obtained from grain."
"A wrangle; a squabble; a noisy contest or dispute."
"A sort of bridle with wooden side pieces."
"A young salmon or parr  in the stage in which it has transverse black bands as if burned by a gridiron."
"Having the appearance of bran; consisting of or containing bran."
"A species of wild goose (Branta bernicla) -- called also brent and brand goose. The name is also applied to other related species."
"An alloy (usually yellow) of copper and zinc  in variable proportion but often containing two parts of copper to one part of zinc. It sometimes contains tin and rarely other metals."
"A spotted European fish of the genus Lucioperca  resembling a perch."
"Of or pertaining to brass; having the nature  appearance or hardness of brass."
"A coarse garment or cloak; also  coarse clothing in general."
"Boastful and threatening behavior; a boastful menace."
"Bold; courageous; daring; intrepid; -- opposed to cowardly; as  a brave man; a brave act."
"In a brave manner; courageously; gallantly; valiantly; splendidly; nobly."
"The quality of being brave; fearless; intrepidity."
"A daring villain; a bandit; one who sets law at defiance; a professional assassin or murderer."
"A florid  brilliant style of music written for effect to show the range and flexibility of a singer's voice or the technical force and skill of a performer; virtuoso music."
"Having large  strong muscles; muscular; fleshy; strong."
"A disease of sheep. The term is variously applied in different localities."
"To pound  beat rub or grind small or fine."
"An implement for braying and spreading ink in hand printing."
"To solder with hard solder  esp. with an alloy of copper and zinc; as to braze the seams of a copper pipe."
"Pertaining to  made of or resembling brass."
"The act of breaking  in a figurative sense."
"Apt to break fences or to break out of pasture; unruly; as  breachy cattle."
"Distance from side to side of any surface or thing; measure across  or at right angles to the length; width."
"To strain apart; to sever by fracture; to divide with violence; as  to break a rope or chain; to break a seal; to break an axle; to break rocks or coal; to break a lock."
"A European fresh-water cyprinoid fish of the genus Abramis  little valued as food. Several species are known."
"The fore part of the body  between the neck and the belly; the chest; as the breast of a man or of a horse."
"The air inhaled and exhaled in respiration; air which  in the process of respiration has parted with oxygen and has received carbonic acid aqueous vapor warmth etc."
"To respire; to inhale and exhale air; hence;  to live."
"A rock composed of angular fragments either of the same mineral or of different minerals  etc. united by a cement and commonly presenting a variety of colors."
"The lower part of the body behind; the buttocks."
"To produce as offspring; to bring forth; to bear; to procreate; to generate; to beget; to hatch."
"One who  or that which breeds produces brings up etc."
"The point of junction of the coronal and sagittal sutures of the skull."
"Of or relating to Brittany  or Bretagne in France."

"A note or character of time  equivalent to two semibreves or four minims. When dotted it is equal to three semibreves. It was formerly of a square figure (as thus: / ) but is now made oval with a line perpendicular to the staff on each of its sides; -- formerly much used for choir service."
"A warrant from the government  granting a privilege title or dignity. [French usage]."
"A size of type between bourgeois and minion."
"Shortness of duration; briefness of time; as  the brevity of human life."
"One who brews; one whose occupation is to prepare malt liquors."
"A brewhouse; the building and apparatus where brewing is carried on."
"A block or clay tempered with water  sand etc. molded into a regular form usually rectangular and sun-dried or burnt in a kiln or in a heap or stack called a clamp."
"Full of bricks; formed of bricks; resembling bricks or brick dust."
"A kind of traces with hooks and rings  with which men drag and maneuver guns where horses can not be used."
"Of or pertaining to a bride  or to wedding; nuptial; as bridal ornaments; a bridal outfit; a bridal chamber."
"A woman newly married  or about to be married."
"A structure  usually of wood stone brick or iron erected over a river or other water course or over a chasm railroad etc. to make a passageway from one bank to the other."
"The head gear with which a horse is governed and restrained  consisting of a headstall a bit and reins with other appendages."
"One who bridles; one who restrains and governs  as with a bridle."
"The snaffle and rein of a military bridle  which acts independently of the bit at the pleasure of the rider. It is used in connection with a curb bit which has its own rein."
"A body of troops  whether cavalry artillery infantry or mixed consisting of two or more regiments under the command of a brigadier general."
"A cabal  intrigue faction contention strife or quarrel."
"A fish allied to the turbot (Rhombus levis)  much esteemed in England for food; -- called also bret pearl prill. See Bret."
"The hair on the eyelids of a horse."
"The rim  border or upper edge of a cup dish or any hollow vessel used for holding anything."
"Full to the brim; completely full; ready to overflow."
"One of the radiating sticks of a fan. The outermost are larger and longer  and are called panaches."
"Of a gray or tawny color with streaks of darker hue; streaked; brindled."

"Water saturated or strongly impregnated with salt; pickle; hence  any strong saline solution; also the saline residue or strong mother liquor resulting from the evaporation of natural or artificial waters."
"To convey to the place where the speaker is or is to be; to bear from a more distant to a nearer place; to fetch."
"The edge  margin or border of a steep place as of a precipice; a bank or edge as of a river or pit; a verge; a border; as the brink of a chasm. Also Fig."
"Of or pertaining to brine  or to the sea; partaking of the nature of brine; salt; as a briny taste; the briny flood."
"Full of liveliness and activity; characterized by quickness of motion or action; lively; spirited; quick."
"That part of the breast of an animal which extends from the fore legs back beneath the ribs; also applied to the fore part of a horse  from the shoulders to the bottom of the chest."
"A short  stiff coarse hair as on the back of swine."
"Thick set with bristles  or with hairs resembling bristles; rough."
"A seaport city in the west of England."
"Any part of a rampart or parapet which deviates from the general direction."
"The young of the common herring; also  a small species of herring; the sprat."
"Of or pertaining to Great Britain or to its inhabitants; -- sometimes restricted to the original inhabitants."
"Easily broken; apt to break; fragile; not tough or tenacious."
"Wide; extend in breadth  or from side to side; -- opposed to narrow; as a broad street a broad table; an inch broad."
"To grow broad; to become broader or wider."
"A peculiar brad-shaped spike  to be driven alongside the end of an abutting timber to prevent its slipping."
"Silk stuff  woven with gold and silver threads or ornamented with raised flowers foliage etc.; -- also applied to other stuffs thus wrought and enriched."
"An elementary principle or maximum; a short  proverbial rule in law ethics or metaphysics."
"Woven with a figure; as  broche goods."
"A male red deer two years old; -- sometimes called brock."
"A pointed instrument  as a joiner's awl a brad awl a needle or a small sharp stick."
"To sniggle  or fish with a brog."
"A tumult; a noisy quarrel; a disturbance; a brawl; contention; discord  either between individuals or in the state."
"One who excites broils; one who engages in or promotes noisy quarrels."
"One who transacts business for another; an agent."
"Of or pertaining to a broker or brokers  or to brokerage."
"An oily  colorless fluid CBr3.COH related to bromoform as chloral is to chloroform and obtained by the action of bromine on alcohol."
"Of  pertaining to or containing bromine; -- said of those compounds of bromine in which this element has a valence of five or the next to its highest; as bromic acid."
"A compound of bromine with a positive radical."

"One of the elements  related in its chemical qualities to chlorine and iodine. Atomic weight 79.8. Symbol Br. It is a deep reddish brown liquid of a very disagreeable odor emitting a brownish vapor at the ordinary temperature. In combination it is found in minute quantities in sea water and in many saline springs. It occurs also in the mineral bromyrite."
"A diseased condition produced by the excessive use of bromine or one of its compounds. It is characterized by mental dullness and muscular weakness."
"To prepare or treat with bromine; as  to bromize a silvered plate."
"A native or a Mexican horse of small size."

"An alloy of copper and tin  to which small proportions of other metals especially zinc are sometimes added. It is hard and sonorous and is used for statues bells cannon etc. the proportions of the ingredients being varied to suit the particular purposes. The varieties containing the higher proportions of tin are brittle as in bell metal and speculum metal."
"An ornament  in various forms with a tongue pin or loop for attaching it to a garment; now worn at the breast by women; a breastpin. Formerly worn by men on the hat."
"The young birds hatched at one time; a hatch; as  a brood of chickens."
"A natural stream of water smaller than a river or creek."

"A plant having twigs suitable for making brooms to sweep with when bound together; esp.  the Cytisus scoparius of Western Europe which is a low shrub with long straight green angular branches minute leaves and large yellow flowers."
"Of or pertaining to broom; overgrowing with broom; resembling broom or a broom."
"Pottage made by pouring some boiling liquid on meal (esp. oatmeal)  and stirring it. It is called beef brose water brose etc. according to the name of the liquid (beef broth hot water etc.) used."
"Liquid in which flesh (and sometimes other substances  as barley or rice) has been boiled; thin or simple soup."
"A house of lewdness or ill fame; a house frequented by prostitutes; a bawdyhouse."
"A male person who has the same father and mother with another person  or who has one of them only. In the latter case he is more definitely called a half brother or brother of the half blood."
"The prominent ridge over the eye  with the hair that covers it forming an arch above the orbit."
"Having (such) a brow; -- used in composition; as  dark-browed stern-browed."
"Of a dark color  of various shades between black and red or yellow."
"An imaginary good-natured spirit  who was supposed often to perform important services around the house by night such as thrashing churning sweeping."
"The tender branches or twigs of trees and shrubs  fit for the food of cattle and other animals; green food."

"A powerful vegetable alkaloid  found associated with strychnine in the seeds of different species of Strychnos especially in the Nux vomica. It is less powerful than strychnine. Called also brucia and brucina."
"A white  pearly mineral occurring thin and foliated like talc and also fibrous; a native magnesium hydrate."
"A bear; -- so called in popular tales and fables."
"To injure  as by a blow or collision without laceration; to contuse; as to bruise one's finger with a hammer; to bruise the bark of a tree with a stone; to bruise an apple by letting it fall."
"The heat  or utmost violence of an onset; the strength or greatest fury of any contention; as the brunt of a battle."

"An instrument composed of bristles  or other like material set in a suitable back or handle as of wood bone or ivory and used for various purposes as in removing dust from clothes laying on colors etc. Brushes have different shapes and names according to their use; as clothes brush paint brush
"Rough and prompt in manner; blunt; abrupt; bluff; as  a brusque man; a brusque style."
"To crackle; to rustle  as a silk garment."
"Of or pertaining to a brute; as  brutal nature."
"Not having sensation; senseless; inanimate; unconscious; without intelligence or volition; as  the brute earth; the brute powers of nature."
"To make like a brute; to make senseless  stupid or unfeeling; to brutalize."
"Pertaining to  or resembling a brute or brutes; of a cruel gross and stupid nature; coarse; unfeeling; unintelligent."
"The nature or characteristic qualities or actions of a brute; extreme stupidity  or beastly vulgarity."
"A bitter principle obtained from the root of the bryony (Bryonia alba and B. dioica). It is a white  or slightly colored substance and is emetic and cathartic."
"The common name of several cucurbitaceous plants of the genus Bryonia. The root of B. alba (rough or white bryony) and of B. dioica is a strong  irritating cathartic."
"A class of Molluscoidea  including minute animals which by budding form compound colonies; -- called also Polyzoa."
"A large antelope (Alcelaphus bubalis) of Egypt and the Desert of Sahara  supposed by some to be the fallow deer of the Bible."
"A thin film of liquid inflated with air or gas; as  a soap bubble; bubbles on the surface of a river."
"An inflammation  with enlargement of a lymphatic gland esp. in the groin as in syphilis."
"Of or pertaining to a bubo or buboes; characterized by buboes."
"Of or pertaining to the mouth or cheeks."
"A genus of large perching birds; the hornbills."

"A South African shrub (Barosma) with small leaves that are dotted with oil glands; also  the leaves themselves which are used in medicine for diseases of the urinary organs etc. Several species furnish the leaves."
"Lye or suds in which cloth is soaked in the operation of bleaching  or in which clothes are washed."
"A vessel for drawing up water from a well  or for catching holding or carrying water sap or other liquids."
"Paste used by weavers to dress their webs."
"A name given to several American trees and shrubs of the same genus (Aesculus) as the horse chestnut."
"A large spiral marine shell  esp. the common whelk. See Buccinum."

"A device  usually of metal consisting of a frame with one more movable tongues or catches used for fastening things together as parts of dress or harness by means of a strap passing through the frame and pierced by the tongue."
"A kind of shield  of various shapes and sizes worn on one of the arms (usually the left) for protecting the front of the body."
"A white man; -- a term used by negroes of the African coast  West Indies etc."
"A coarse cloth of linen or hemp  stiffened with size or glue used in garments to keep them in the form intended and for wrappers to cover merchandise."
"Of or pertaining to the life and occupation of a shepherd; pastoral; rustic."
"A small protuberance on the stem or branches of a plant  containing the rudiments of future leaves flowers or stems; an undeveloped branch or flower."
"The title of an incarnation of self-abnegation  virtue and wisdom or a deified religious teacher of the Buddhists esp. Gautama Siddartha or Sakya Sinha (or Muni) the founder of Buddhism."
"An apparatus  especially an inclined trough or vat in which stamped ore is concentrated by subjecting it to the action of running water so as to wash out the lighter and less valuable portions."
"To move off; to stir; to walk away."
"A bag or sack with its contents; hence  a stock or store; an accumulation; as a budget of inventions."
"A little bud springing from a parent bud."
"A sort of leather  prepared from the skin of the buffalo dressed with oil like chamois; also the skins of oxen elks and other animals dressed in like manner."

"A species of the genus Bos or Bubalus (B. bubalus)  originally from India but now found in most of the warmer countries of the eastern continent. It is larger and less docile than the common ox and is fond of marshy places and rivers."
"An elastic apparatus or fender  for deadening the jar caused by the collision of bodies; as a buffer at the end of a railroad car."
"A cupboard or set of shelves  either movable or fixed at one side of a room for the display of plate china etc. a sideboard."
"A sort of coarse stuff; as  buffin gowns."
"A man who makes a practice of amusing others by low tricks  antic gestures etc.; a droll; a mimic; a harlequin; a clown; a merry-andrew."
"A genus of Amphibia including various species of toads."
"Something frightful  as a specter; anything imaginary that causes needless fright; something used to excite needless fear; also something really dangerous used to frighten children etc."
"A perennial white-flowered herb of the order Ranunculaceae and genus Cimiciguga; bugwort. There are several species."
"One guilty of buggery or unnatural vice; a sodomite."
"A sort of wild ox; a buffalo."
"A plant of the genus Anchusa  and especially the A. officinalis sometimes called alkanet; oxtongue."
"To erect or construct  as an edifice or fabric of any kind; to form by uniting materials into a regular structure; to fabricate; to make; to raise."
"One who builds; one whose occupation is to build  as a carpenter a shipwright or a mason."
"An East Indian insectivorous mammal (Gymnura Rafflesii)  somewhat like a rat in appearance but allied to the hedgehog."

"A spheroidal body growing from a plant either above or below the ground (usually below)  which is strictly a bud consisting of a cluster of partially developed leaves and producing as it grows a stem above and roots below as in the onion tulip etc. It differs from a corm in not being solid."
"Of or pertaining to bulb; especially  in medicine pertaining to the bulb of the spinal cord or medulla oblongata; as bulbar paralysis."
"A separable bulb formed on some flowering plants."
"A small bulb  either produced on a larger bulb or on some aerial part of a plant as in the axils of leaves in the tiger lily or replacing the flowers in some kinds of onion."
"Having or containing bulbs  or a bulb; growing from bulbs; bulblike in shape or structure."

"The Persian nightingale (Pycnonotus jocosus). The name is also applied to several other Asiatic singing birds  of the family Timaliidae. The green bulbuls belong to the Chloropsis and allied genera."
"The bilge or protuberant part of a cask."
"Bulged; bulging; bending  or tending to bend outward."
"A disease in which there is a perpetual and insatiable appetite for food; a diseased and voracious appetite."
"A genus of land snails having an elongated spiral shell  often of large size. The species are numerous and abundant in tropical America."
"Magnitude of material substance; dimensions; mass; size; as  an ox or ship of great bulk."
"A person employed to ascertain the bulk or size of goods  in order to fix the amount of freight or dues payable on them."
"Of great bulk or dimensions; of great size; large; thick; massive; as  bulky volumes."
"The male of any species of cattle (Bovidae); hence  the male of any large quadruped as the elephant; also the male of the whale."
"A bleb; a vesicle  or an elevation of the cuticle containing a transparent watery fluid."
"A small European plum (Prunus communis  var. insitita). See Plum."
"A variety of dog  of remarkable ferocity courage and tenacity of grip; -- so named probably from being formerly employed in baiting bulls."
"Any large fly troublesome to cattle  as the gadflies and breeze flies."
"Uncoined gold or silver in the mass."
"Partaking of the nature of a bull  or a blunder."
"A writer or drawer up of papal bulls."
"A young bull  or any male of the ox kind."
"A noisy  blustering fellow more insolent than courageous; one who is threatening and quarrelsome; an insolent tyrannical fellow."
"A kind of large rush  growing in wet land or in water."
"A purse or bag in which to carry or measure diamonds  etc."
"A bolter or bolting cloth; also  bran."
"A trawl; a boulter; the mode of fishing with a boulter or spiller."
"A rampart; a fortification; a bastion or outwork."
"A clumsy boat  used for conveying provisions fruit etc. for sale to vessels lying in port or off shore."

"A projecting beam or boom; as: (a) One projecting from each bow of a vessel  to haul the fore tack to called a tack bumpkin. (b) One from each quarter for the main-brace blocks and called brace bumpkin. (c) A small outrigger over the stern of a boat to extend the mizzen."
"A small marine Asiatic fish (Saurus ophidon) used in India as a relish; -- called also Bombay duck."
"An idle  worthless fellow who is without any visible means of support; a dissipated sponger."
"To strike  as with or against anything large or solid; to thump; as to bump the head against a wall."
"A cup or glass filled to the brim  or till the liquor runs over particularly in drinking a health or toast."
"An awkward  heavy country fellow; a clown; a country lout."
"A slightly sweetened raised cake or bisquit with a glazing of sugar and milk on the top crust."
"A protuberance; a hunch; a knob or lump; a hump."
"Speech-making for the gratification of constituents  or to gain public applause; flattering talk for a selfish purpose; anything said for mere show."
"League; confederacy; esp. the confederation of German states."
"A boat or raft used in the East Indies in the landing of passengers and goods."

"A number of things bound together  as by a cord or envelope into a mass or package convenient for handling or conveyance; a loose package; a roll; as a bundle of straw or of paper; a bundle of old clothes."
"The large stopper of the orifice in the bilge of a cask."
"To act or work in a clumsy  awkward manner."
"A clumsy  awkward workman; one who bungles."
"A kind of canoe used in Central and South America; also  a kind of boat used in the Southern United States."
"A wooden case or box  which serves for a seat in the daytime and for a bed at night."
"A sort of chest or box  as in a window the lid of which serves for a seat."
"A kind of swindling game or scheme  by means of cards or by a sham lottery."
"A great collection of ore without any vein coming into it or going out from it."
"A fungus (Ustilago foetida) which affects the ear of cereals  filling the grains with a fetid dust; -- also called pepperbrand."
"A woman who picks up rags in the streets; hence  a low vulgar woman."
"A bird of the genus Emberiza  or of an allied genus related to the finches and sparrows (family Fringillidae)."
"A thin woolen stuff  used chiefly for flags colors and ships' signals."
"A float; esp. a floating object moored to the bottom  to mark a channel or to point out the position of something beneath the water as an anchor shoal rock etc."
"Buoys  taken collectively; a series of buoys as for the guidance of vessels into or out of port; the providing of buoys."
"Having the quality of rising or floating in a fluid; tending to rise or float; as  iron is buoyant in mercury."
"Any rough or prickly envelope of the seeds of plants  whether a pericarp a persistent calyx or an involucre as of the chestnut and burdock. Also any weed which bears burs."
"A fresh-water fish of the genus Lota  having on the nose two very small barbels and a larger one on the chin."
"That which is borne or carried; a load."
"A genus of coarse biennial herbs (Lappa)  bearing small burs which adhere tenaciously to clothes or to the fur or wool of animals."
