"To call  as a hen her chickens; to cluck."
"A sedgelike plant (Cyperus esculentus) producing edible tubers  native about the Mediterranean now cultivated in many regions; the earth almond."
"Fat or puffed out in the cheeks."
"The fragrant flowers of the Chloranthus inconspicuus  used in China for perfuming tea."
"A roommate  especially in a college or university; an old and intimate friend."
"A short  thick heavy piece of wood."
"A building set apart for Christian worship."
"Relating to a church; unduly fond of church forms."
"A vessel in which milk or cream is stirred  beaten or otherwise agitated (as by a plunging or revolving dasher) in order to separate the oily globules from the other parts and obtain butter."
"A powerfully narcotic and intoxicating gum resin which exudes from the flower heads  seeds etc. of Indian hemp."
"A framework  trough or tube upon or through which objects are made to slide from a higher to a lower level or through which water passes to a wheel."
"A warm or spicy condiment or pickle made in India  compounded of various vegetable substances sweets acids etc."

"A milky fluid containing the fatty matter of the food in a state of emulsion  or fine mechanical division; formed from chyme by the action of the intestinal juices. It is absorbed by the lacteals and conveyed into the blood by the thoracic duct."
"To make chyle of; to be converted into chyle."
"The pulpy mass of semi-digested food in the small intestines just after its passage from the stomach. It is separated in the intestines into chyle and excrement. See Chyle."
"A perennial alliaceous plant (Allium fistulosum)  sometimes called Welsh onion. Its fistular leaves areused in cookery."

"Any species of the genus Cicada. They are large hemipterous insects  with nearly transparent wings. The male makes a shrill sound by peculiar organs in the under side of the abdomen consisting of a pair of stretched membranes acted upon by powerful muscles. A noted American species (C. septendecim) is called the seventeen year locust. Another common species is the dogday cicada."
"Any one of several umbelliferous plants  of the genera Myrrhis Osmorrhiza etc."
"Pica type; -- so called by French printers."
"a genus of poisonous umbelliferous plants  of which the water hemlock or cowbane is best known."
"Chief or commander; in Spanish literature  a title of Ruy Diaz Count of Bivar a champion of Christianity and of the old Spanish royalty in the 11th century."
"The expressed juice of apples. It is used as a beverage  for making vinegar and for other purposes."
"A wax candle used in religous rites."
"A small roll of tobacco  used for smoking."
"Pertaining to the cilia  or eyelashes. Also applied to special parts of the eye itself; as the ciliary processes of the choroid coat; the ciliary muscle etc."
"One of the orders of Infusoria  characterized by having cilia. In some species the cilia cover the body generally in others they form a band around the mouth."
"A fillet or band placed around the shaft of a column as if to strengthen it."
"Pertaining to the Cimbri  an ancient tribe inhabiting Northern Germany."
"A genus of hemipterous insects of which the bedbug is the best known example. See Bedbug."
"A strong saddle girth  as of canvas."
"Partly burned or vitrified coal  or other combustible in which fire is extinct."
"Resembling  or composed of cinders; full of cinders."
"Five; the number five in dice or cards."
"The group of Thysanura which includes Lepisma and allied forms; the bristletails. See Bristletail  and Lepisma."
"A character [0] which  standing by itself expresses nothing but when placed at the right hand of a whole number increases its value tenfold."
"A whitish marble  from Rome containiing pale greenish zones. It consists of calcium carbonate with zones and cloudings of talc."

"A small  low pillar square or round commonly having an inscription used by the ancients for various purposes as for indicating the distances of places for a landmark for sepulchral inscriptions etc."
"An amphitheatrical circle for sports; a circus."
"A district  or part of a province. See Sircar."

"Having the characteristics of Circe  daughter of Sol and Perseis a mythological enchantress who first charmed her victims and then changed them to the forms of beasts; pleasing but noxious; as a Circean draught."
"A plane figure  bounded by a single curve line called its circumference every part of which is equally distant from a point within it called the center."
"A mean or inferior poet  perhaps from his habit of wandering around as a stroller; an itinerant poet. Also a name given to the cyclic poets. See under Cyclic a."
"A little circle; esp.  an ornament for the person having the form of a circle; that which encircles as a ring a bracelet or a headband."
"The act of moving or revolving around  or as in a circle or orbit; a revolution; as the periodical circuit of the earth round the sun."

"A level oblong space surrounded on three sides by seats of wood  earth or stone rising in tiers one above another and divided lengthwise through the middle by a barrier around which the track or course was laid out. It was used for chariot races games and public shows."
"A circle; a circus; a circular erection or arrangement of objects."
"Having cirri along the margin of a part or organ."
"Bearing a tendril or tendrils; as  a cirrose leaf."
"The Lake herring (Coregonus Artedi)  valuable food fish of the Great Lakes of North America. The name is also applied to C. Hoyi a related species of Lake Michigan."

"A curve invented by Diocles  for the purpose of solving two celebrated problems of the higher geometry; viz. to trisect a plane angle and to construct two geometrical means between two given straight lines."

"A box or chest. Specifically: (a) A bronze receptacle  round or oval frequently decorated with engravings on the sides and cover and with feet handles etc. of decorative castings. (b) A cinerary urn. See Illustration in Appendix."
"An artificial reservoir or tank for holding water  beer or other liquids."
"A citizen; an inhabitant of a city; a pert townsman; -- used contemptuously."
"A fortress in or near a fortified city  commanding the city and fortifications and intended as a final point of defense."
"Summons to appear  as before a judge."
"To call upon officially or authoritatively to appear  as before a court; to summon."
"One who is born or bred in a city; a citizen."
"One who enjoys the freedom and privileges of a city; a freeman of a city  as distinguished from a foreigner or one not entitled to its franchises."
"A musical instrument; a kind of dulcimer."
"Of  pertaining to or derived from the citron or lemon; as citric acid."
"Like a citron or lemon; of a lemon color; greenish yellow."
"A fruit resembling a lemon  but larger and pleasantly aromatic. The thick rind when candied is the citron of commerce."
"A genus of trees including the orange  lemon citron etc. originally natives of southern Asia."
"An instrument shaped like a lute  but strung with wire and played with a quill or plectrum."

"A substance  of the consistence of butter or honey taken from glands in the anal pouch of the civet (Viverra civetta). It is of clear yellowish or brownish color of a strong musky odor offensive when undiluted but agreeable when a small portion is mixed with another substance. It is used as a perfume."
"Relating to  or derived from a city or citizen; relating to man as a member of society or to civil affairs."
"Pertaining to a city or state  or to a citizen in his relations to his fellow citizens or to the state; within the city or state."
"In a civil manner; as regards civil rights and privileges; politely; courteously; in a well bred manner."
"Milk curdled so as to become thick."
"To make a sudden  sharp noise or a succesion of such noises as by striking an object or by collision of parts; to rattle; to click."
"One who clacks; that which clacks; especially  the clapper of a mill."
"Adhesive; -- said of a roof in a mine to which coal clings."
"To ask for  or seek to obtain by virtue of authority right or supposed right; to challenge as a right; to demand as due."

"A bivalve mollusk of many kinds  especially those that are edible; as the long clam (Mya arenaria) the quahog or round clam (Venus mercenaria) the sea clam or hen clam (Spisula solidissima) and other species of the United States. The name is said to have been given originally to the Tridacna gigas a huge East Indian bivalve."
"To climb with difficulty  or with hands and feet; -- also used figuratively."
"Having the quality of being viscous or adhesive; soft and sticky; glutinous; damp and adhesive  as if covered with a cold perspiration."
"A great outcry or vociferation; loud and continued shouting or exclamation."
"Something rigid that holds fast or binds things together; a piece of wood or metal  used to hold two or more pieces together."
"An instrument of iron  with sharp prongs attached to a boot or shoe to enable the wearer to walk securely upon ice; a creeper."
"A tribe or collection of families  united under a chieftain regarded as having the same common ancestor and bearing the same surname; as the clan of Macdonald."
"To strike together so as to produce a ringing metallic sound."
"A sharp  brief ringing sound made by a collision of metallic or other sonorous bodies; -- usually expressing a duller or less resounding sound than clang and a deeper and stronger sound than clink."
"To strike; to slap; to strike  or strike together with a quick motion so as to make a sharp noise; as to clap one's hands; a clapping of wings."
"A collection of persons employed to applaud at a theatrical exhibition."
"A nun of the order of St. Clare."
"The name first given in England to the red wines of Medoc  in France and afterwards extended to all the red Bordeaux wines. The name is also given to similar wines made in the United States."
"To make clear or bright by freeing from feculent matter; to defecate; to fine; -- said of liquids  as wine or sirup."
"A kind of trumpet  whose note is clear and shrill."
"Wine with a mixture of honey and species."
"To daub  smear or spread as with mud etc."
"To make a loud or shrill noise."
"To make a noise by striking against something; to dash noisily together."
"To shut or fasten together with  or as with a clasp; to shut or fasten (a clasp or that which fastens with a clasp)."
"One who  or that which clasps as a tendril."
"A group of individuals ranked together as possessing common characteristics; as  the different classes of society; the educated class; the lower classes."
"Pertaining to what may be taken apart; as  clastic anatomy (of models)."
"To make a rattling sound by striking hard bodies together; to make a succession of abrupt  rattling sounds."
"A separate portion of a written paper  paragraph or sentence; an article stipulation or proviso in a legal document."
"The keyboard of an organ  pianoforte or harmonium."
"A callous growth  esp. one the foot; a corn."
"A sharp  hooked nail as of a beast or bird."

"A soft earth  which is plastic or may be molded with the hands consisting of hydrous silicate of aluminium. It is the result of the wearing down and decomposition in part of rocks containing aluminous minerals as granite. Lime magnesia oxide of iron and other ingredients are often present as impurities."
"Wattles  or hurdles made with stakes interwoven with osiers to cover lodgments."
"Consisting of clay; abounding with clay; partaking of clay; like clay."
"Partaking of the nature of clay  or containing particles of it."
"Free from dirt or filth; as  clean clothes."
"To render clean; to free from fith  pollution infection guilt etc.; to clean."
"Free from opaqueness; transparent; bright; light; luminous; unclouded."
"A strip of wood or iron fastened on transversely to something in order to give strength  prevent warping hold position etc."
"To adhere closely; to stick; to hold fast; to cling."
"One who cleaves  or that which cleaves; especially a butcher's instrument for cutting animal bodies into joints or pieces."

"Charged with another bearing of the same figure  and of the color of the field so large that only a narrow border of the first bearing remains visible; -- said of any heraldic bearing. Compare Voided."
"Stiff  stubborn clayey or tenacious; as a cledgy soil."
"A character used in musical notation to determine the position and pitch of the scale as represented on the staff."
"Mild in temper and disposition; merciful; compassionate."
"The body of men set apart  by due ordination to the service of God in the Christian church in distinction from the laity; in England usually restricted to the ministers of the Established Church."
"Possessing quickness of intellect  skill dexterity talent or adroitness; expert."

"A piece of metal bent in the form of an oxbow  with the two ends perforated to receive a pin used on the end of the tongue of a plow wagen etc. to attach it to a draft chain whiffletree etc.; -- called also clavel clevy."
"A ball of thread  yarn or cord; also The thread itself."
"A stereotype plate or any similar reproduction of ornament  or lettering in relief."
"To make a slight  sharp noise (or a succession of such noises) as by gentle striking; to tick."
"One who stands before a shop door to invite people to buy."
"A citizen who put himself under the protection of a man of distinction and influence  who was called his patron."

"One of thirty regions or zones  parallel to the equator into which the surface of the earth from the equator to the pole was divided according to the successive increase of the length of the midsummer day."
"To ascend or mount laboriously  esp. by use of the hands and feet."
"A climate; a tract or region of the earth. See Climate."
"To hold firmly; to hold fast by grasping or embracing tightly."
"To adhere closely; to stick; to hold fast  especially by twining round or embracing; as the tendril of a vine clings to its support; -- usually followed by to or together."
"One confined to the bed by sickness."
"To cause to give out a slight  sharp tinkling sound as by striking metallic or other sonorous bodies together."
"A mass composed of several bricks run together by the action of the fire in the kiln."
"Like a bed; -- applied to several processes on the inner side of the sphenoid bone."
"A genus of naked pteropods. One species (Clione papilonacea)  abundant in the Arctic Ocean constitutes a part of the food of the Greenland whale. It is sometimes incorrectly called Clio."
"One who clips; specifically  one who clips off the edges of coin."
"A narrow circle of persons associated by common interests or for the accomplishment of a common purpose; -- generally used in a bad sense."
"A sewer; as  the Cloaca Maxima of Rome."
"A loose outer garment  extending from the neck downwards and commonly without sleeves. It is longer than a cape and is worn both by men and by women."

"A machine for measuring time  indicating the hour and other divisions by means of hands moving on a dial plate. Its works are moved by a weight or a spring and it is often so constructed as to tell the hour by the stroke of a hammer on a bell. It is not adapted like the watch to be carried on the person."
"A lump or mass  especially of earth turf or clay."
"Formerly an allowance of two pounds in every three hundred weight after the tare and tret are subtracted; now used only in a general sense  of small deductions from the original weight."
"That which hinders or impedes motion; hence  an encumbrance restraint or impediment of any kind."
"The sound made when a cork is forcibly drawn from a bottle."
"To stop  or fill up as an opening; to shut; as to close the eyes; to close a door."
"One who  or that which closes; specifically a boot closer. See under Boot."
"A small room or apartment for retirement; a room for privacy."
"A disease in the feet of cattle; laminitis."
"The act of shutting; a closing; as  the closure of a chink."
"A concretion or coagulation; esp. a soft  slimy coagulated mass as of blood; a coagulum."

"A fabric made of fibrous material (or sometimes of wire  as in wire cloth); commonly a woven fabric of cotton woolen or linen adapted to be made into garments; specifically woolen fabrics as distinguished from all others."
"To put garments on; to cover with clothing; to dress."
"A collection of visible vapor  or watery particles suspended in the upper atmosphere."
"Overcast or obscured with clouds; clouded; as  a cloudy sky."
"A cleft in a hill; a ravine; a narrow valley."
"A cloth; a piece of cloth or leather; a patch; a rag."
"A plant of different species of the genus Trifolium; as the common red clover  T. pratense the white T. repens and the hare's foot T. arvense."
"A man of coarse nature and manners; an awkward fellow; an ill-bred person; a boor."
"To fill or choke up; to stop up; to clog."
"A heavy staff of wood  usually tapering and wielded the hand; a weapon; a cudgel."
"To make the noise  or utter the call of a brooding hen."
"A kind of field spaniel  with short legs and stout body which unlike other spaniels hunts silently."
"An unshaped piece or mass of wood or other substance."

"A game in which questions are asked for the purpose of enabling the questioners to discover a word or thing previously selected by two persons who answer the questions; -- so called because the players take sides in two """"clumps"""" or groups  the """"clump"""" which guesses the word winning the game."
"A monk of the reformed branch of the Benedictine Order  founded in 912 at Cluny (or Clugny) in France. -- Also used as a."
"A number of things of the same kind growing together; a bunch."
"A gripe or clinching with  or as with the fingers or claws; seizure; grasp."
"A confused collection; hence  confusion; disorder; as the room is in a clutter."
"The frontal plate of the head of an insect."
"A liquid injected into the lower intestines by means of a syringe; an injection; an enema."
"One of the peculiar stinging  cells found in Coelenterata; a nematocyst; a lasso cell."
"A large  closed four-wheeled carriage having doors in the sides and generally a front and back seat inside each for two persons and an elevated outside seat in front for the driver."
"An associate in an act; a coworker."
"The native name of certain South American monkeys of the genus Ateles  esp. A. paniscus. The black-faced coaita is Ateles ater. See Illustration in Appendix."
"A thoroughly charred  and extinguished or still ignited fragment from wood or other combustible substance; charcoal."
"Pertaining to  or resembling coal; containing coal; of the nature of coal."

"Large in bulk  or composed of large parts or particles; of inferior quality or appearance; not fine in material or close in texture; gross; thick; rough; -- opposed to fine; as coarse sand; coarse thread; coarse cloth; coarse bread."
"To make coarse or vulgar; as  to coarsen one's character."
"A vessel employed in sailing along a coast  or engaged in the coasting trade."
"An outer garment fitting the upper part of the body; especially  such a garment worn by men."
"A mammal of tropical America of the genus Nasua  allied to the raccoon but with a longer body tail and nose."
"To persuade by gentle  insinuating courtesy flattering or fondling; to wheedle; to soothe."
"A genus of climbing plants  native of Mexico and South America. C. scandens is a conservatory climber with large bell-shaped flowers."
"A tough  lustrous reddish white metal of the iron group not easily fusible and somewhat magnetic. Atomic weight 59.1. Symbol Co."
"An oceanic fish of large size (Elacate canada); the crabeater; -- called also bonito  cubbyyew coalfish and sergeant fish."
"An andiron with a knob at the top."
"A flat-floored fishing boat with a lug sail  and a drop rudder extending from two to four feet below the keel. It was originally used on the stormy coast of Yorkshire England."
"A large roundish variety of the cultivated hazelnut."
"A thin worsted fabric for women's dresses."
"A wall made of clay mixed with straw."
"The network spread by a spider to catch its prey."

"Built of logs  etc. laid horizontally with the ends dovetailed together at the corners as in a log house; in marine work often surrounding a central space filled with stones; as a cobwork dock or breakwater."
"The dried leaf of a South American shrub (Erythroxylon Coca). In med.  called Erythroxylon."
"An imaginary country of idleness and luxury."
"A powerful alkaloid  C17H21NO4 obtained from the leaves of coca. It is a bitter white crystalline substance and is remarkable for producing local insensibility to pain."
"One of the separable carpels of a dry fruit."
"The end of the vertebral column beyond the sacrum in man and tailless monkeys. It is composed of several vertebrae more or less consolidated."
"An appendage of the labyrinth of the internal ear  which is elongated and coiled into a spiral in mammals. See Ear."
"The male of birds  particularly of gallinaceous or domestic fowls."

"A badge  usually in the form of a rosette or knot and generally worn upon the hat; -- used as an indication of military or naval service or party allegiance and in England as a part of the livery to indicate that the wearer is the servant of a military or naval officer."
"A game played with sheep's bones instead of dice"
"To treat with too great tenderness; to fondle; to indulge; to pamper."
"A bivalve mollusk  with radiating ribs of the genus Cardium especially C. edule used in Europe for food; -- sometimes applied to similar shells of other genera."
"A pit  or inclosed area for cockfights."
"A game in which trinkets are set upon sticks  to be thrown at by the players; -- so called from an ancient popular sport which consisted in """"shying"""" or throwing cudgels at live cocks."
"A large  highly esteemed edible fish of India (Lates calcarifer); -- also called begti."
"An oblong case in which the silkworm lies in its chrysalis state. It is formed of threads of silk spun by the worm just before leaving the larval state. From these the silk of commerce is prepared."
"Made by baking  or exposing to heat as a brick."
"A husk; a pod; as  a peascod."
"A few measures added beyond the natural termination of a composition."
"A body of law  sanctioned by legislation in which the rules of law to be specifically applied by the courts are set forth in systematic form; a compilation of laws by public authority; a digest."
"One of the opium alkaloids; a white crystalline substance  C18H21NO3 similar to and regarded as a derivative of morphine but much feebler in its action; -- called also codeia."
"A short passage connecting two sections  but not forming part of either; a short coda."
"A kind of fish. Same as Cod."
"Relating to a codex  or a code."
"To reduce to a code  as laws."
"The coarse tow of flax and hemp."
"A term at omber  signifying that the game is won."
"An apple fit to stew or coddle."
"A small bronze mortar mounted on a wooden block with handles  and light enough to be carried short distances by two men."
"The Brazilian porcupine (Cercolades  / Sphingurus prehensiles) remarkable for its prehensile tail."
"Being on an equality in rank or power."
"To restrain by force  especially by law or authority; to repress; to curb."
"Of the same age; existing during the same period of time  especially time long and remote; -- usually followed by with."
"To exist at the same time; -- sometimes followed by with."

"The """"beans"""" or """"berries"""" (pyrenes) obtained from the drupes of a small evergreen tree of the genus Coffea  growing in Abyssinia Arabia Persia and other warm regions of Asia and Africa and also in tropical America."
"A casket  chest or trunk; especially one used for keeping money or other valuables."
"The case in which a dead human body is inclosed for burial."
"A gang of negro slaves being driven to market."
"To seduce  or draw away by adulation artifice or falsehood; to wheedle; to cozen; to cheat."
"The quality of being cogent; power of compelling conviction; conclusiveness; force."
"A dealer in cogware or coarse cloth."
"A kind of French brandy  so called from the town of Cognac."
"Allied by blood; kindred by birth; specifically (Law)  related on the mother's side."
"A coarse  narrow cloth like frieze used by the lower classes in the sixteenth century."
"To inhabit or reside in company  or in the same place or country."
"A joint heir; one of two or more heirs; one of several entitled to an inheritance."
"To stick together; to cleave; to be united; to hold fast  as parts of the same mass."
"A body of about five or six hundred soldiers; the tenth part of a legion."

"A perennial American herb (Caulophyllum thalictroides)  whose rootstock is used in medicine; -- also called pappoose root. The name is sometimes also given to the Cimicifuga racemosa and to two species of Actaea plants of the Crowfoot family."
"The practice of quartering one's self as landlord on a tenant; a quartering of one's self on anybody."
"To wind cylindrically or spirally; as  to coil a rope when not in use; the snake coiled itself before springing."
"A quoin; a corner or external angle; a wedge. See Coigne  and Quoin."
"The act or process of converting metal into money."
"One who makes or stamps coin; a maker of money; -- usually  a maker of counterfeit money."
"A material for cordage  matting etc. consisting of the prepared fiber of the outer husk of the cocoanut."

"Mineral coal charred  or depriver of its bitumen sulphur or other volatile matter by roasting in a kiln or oven or by distillation as in gas works. It is lagerly used where / smokeless fire is required."
"A short ridge connecting two higher elevations or mountains; the pass over such a ridge."
"Deprived of heat  or having a low temperature; not warm or hot; gelid; frigid."
"In a cold manner; without warmth  animation or feeling; with indifference; calmly."
"A plant of the Brassica or Cabbage genus; esp. that form of B. oleracea called rape and coleseed."
"A small European titmouse (Parus ater)  so named from its black color; -- called also coalmouse and colemouse."
"A plant of several species of the Mint family  cultivated for its bright-colored or variegated leaves."
"A severe paroxysmal pain in the abdomen  due to spasm obstruction or distention of some one of the hollow viscera."
"Of  pertaining to or of the nature of colic."
"Pertaining to  or troubled with colic; as a colicky disorder."
"The American quail or bobwhite. The name is also applied to other related species. See Bobwhite."
"An inflammation of the large intestine  esp. of its mucous membrane; colonitis."
"Something worn round the neck  whether for use ornament restraint or identification; as the collar of a coat; a lady's collar; the collar of a dog."
"To compare critically  as books or manuscripts in order to note the points of agreement or disagreement."
"To gather into one body or place; to assemble or bring together; to obtain by gathering."

"A collection  body or society of persons engaged in common pursuits or having common duties and interests and sometimes by charter peculiar rights and privileges; as a college of heralds; a college of electors; a college of bishops."
"To strike or dash against each other; to come into collision; to clash; as  the vessels collided; their interests collided."
"The Scotch shepherd dog. There are two breeds  the rough-haired and smooth-haired. It is remarkable for its intelligence displayed especially in caring for flocks."
"One engaged in the business of digging mineral coal or making charcoal  or in transporting or dealing in coal."
"A tool to polish the edge of a sole."
"Resembling glue or jelly; characterized by a jellylike appearance; gelatinous; as  colloid tumors."
"A small slice of meat; a piece of flesh."
"To have secretly a joint part or share in an action; to play into each other's hands; to conspire; to act in concert."
"The black grime or soot of coal."
"A perfumed liquid  composed of alcohol and certain aromatic oils used in the toilet; -- called also cologne water and eau de cologne."
"That part of the large intestines which extends from the caecum to the rectum. [See Illust of Digestion.]"
"The chief officer of a regiment; an officer ranking next above a lieutenant colonel and next below a brigadier general."
"A company of people transplanted from their mother country to a remote province or country  and remaining subject to the jurisdiction of the parent state; as the British colonies in America."
"A property depending on the relations of light to the eye  by which individual and specific differences in the hues and tints of objects are apprehended in vision; as gay colors; sad colors etc."
"The young of the equine genus or horse kind of animals; -- sometimes distinctively applied to the male  filly being the female. Cf. Foal."
"A knife or cutter  attached to the beam of a plow to cut the sward in advance of the plowshare and moldboard."

"A peculiar East Indian mammal (Galleopithecus volans)  having along the sides connecting the fore and hind limbs a parachutelike membrane by means of which it is able to make long leaps like the flying squirrel; -- called also flying lemur."
"A kind of pillar; a cylindrical or polygonal support for a roof  ceiling statue etc. somewhat ornamented and usually composed of base shaft and capital. See Order."

"One of two great circles intersecting at right angles in the poles of the equator. One of them passes through the equinoctial points  and hence is denominated the equinoctial colure; the other intersects the equator at the distance of 90� from the former and is called the solstitial colure."
"Any bird of the genus Colius and allied genera. They inhabit Africa."
"A variety of cabbage (Brassica oleracea)  cultivated for its seeds which yield an oil valued for illuminating and lubricating purposes; summer rape."
"A state of profound insensibility from which it is difficult or impossible to rouse a person. See Carus."
"Encompassed with a coma  or bushy appearance like hair; hairy."
"An instrument with teeth  for straightening cleansing and adjusting the hair or for keeping it in place."
"That unwatered portion of a valley which forms its continuation beyond and above the most elevated spring that issues into it."
"To struggle or contend  as with an opposing force; to fight."
"One who combs; one whose occupation it is to comb wool  flax etc. Also a machine for combing wool flax etc."
"To unite or join; to link closely together; to bring into harmonious union; to cause or unite so as to form a homogeneous substance  as by chemical union."
"A small nodule or cystic tumor  common on the nose etc. which on pressure allows the escape of a yellow wormlike mass of retained oily secretion with a black head (dirt)."

"A dramatic composition  or representation of a bright and amusing character based upon the foibles of individuals the manners of society or the ludicrous events or accidents of life; a play in which mirth predominates and the termination of the plot is happy; -- opposed to tragedy."
"Pleasing or agreeable to the sight; well-proportioned; good-looking; handsome."
"One who comes  or who has come; one who has arrived and is present."
"The answer to the theme (dux) in a fugue."

"A member of the solar system which usually moves in an elongated orbit  approaching very near to the sun in its perihelion and receding to a very great distance from it at its aphelion. A comet commonly consists of three parts: the nucleus the envelope or coma and the tail; but one or more of these parts is frequently wanting. See Illustration in Appendix."
"A dry sweetmeat; any kind of fruit  root or seed preserved with sugar and dried; a confection."
"To make strong; to invigorate; to fortify; to corroborate."
"A rough  hairy perennial plant of several species of the genus Symphytum."
"Relating to comedy  as distinct from tragedy."
"A public assembly of the Roman people for electing officers or passing laws."
"Mildness and suavity of manners; courtesy between equals; friendly civility; as  comity of manners; the comity of States."
"A character or point [ ] marking the smallest divisions of a sentence written or printed."
"To order with authority; to lay injunction upon; to direct; to bid; to charge."
"To commit  intrust or give in charge for care or preservation."

"To make remarks  observations or criticism; especially to write notes on the works of an author with a view to illustrate his meaning or to explain particular passages; to write annotations; -- often followed by on or upon."
"To give in trust; to put into charge or keeping; to intrust; to consign; -- used with to  unto."
"To mix or mingle together; to blend."
"A kind of headdress formerly worn by ladies  raising the hair and fore part of the cap to a great height."
"Belonging or relating equally  or similarly to more than one; as you and I have a common interest in the property."
"The mass of the people  as distinguished from the titled classes or nobility; the commonalty; the common people."
"To commove; to disturb; to stir up."
"To converse together with sympathy and confidence; to interchange sentiments or feelings; to take counsel."

"To exchange; to put or substitute something else in place of  as a smaller penalty obligation or payment for a greater or a single thing for an aggregate; hence to lessen; to diminish; as to commute a sentence of death to one of imprisonment for life; to commute tithes; to commute charges for fares."
"Bearing a tuft of soft hairs or down  as the seeds of milkweed."
"The state of being a companion or companions; the act of accompanying; fellowship; companionship; society; friendly intercourse."

"To examine the character or qualities of  as of two or more persons or things for the purpose of discovering their resemblances or differences; to bring into comparison; to regard with discriminating attention."
"To divide; to mark out into parts or subdivisions."
"An equal  as in rank age prowess etc.; a companion; a comrade; a mate."
"To drive or urge with force  or irresistibly; to force; to constrain; to oblige; to necessitate either by physical or moral force."

"To contend emulously; to seek or strive for the same thing  position or reward for which another is striving; to contend in rivalry as for a prize or in business; as tradesmen compete with one another."
"To put together; to construct; to build."
"Composed of two or more parts; composite; not simple; as  a complex being; a complex idea."
"The last division of the Roman Catholic breviary; the seventh and last of the canonical hours of the Western church; the last prayer of the day  to be said after sunset."
"A plotting together; a confederacy in some evil design; a conspiracy."
"To yield assent; to accord; agree  or acquiesce; to adapt one's self; to consent or conform; -- usually followed by with."
"To bear or endure; to put up (with); as  to comport with an injury."
"To form by putting together two or more things or parts; to put together; to make up; to fashion."
"A preparation of fruit in sirup in such a manner as to preserve its form  either whole halved or quartered; as a compote of pears."
"To determine calculation; to reckon; to count."
"Against the affirmative side; in opposition; on the negative side; -- The antithesis of pro  and usually in connection with it. See Pro."
"To underlet a portion of  for a single crop; -- said of a farm."
"A natural tendency inherent in a body to develop itself; an attempt; an effort."

"Hollow and curved or rounded; vaulted; -- said of the interior of a curved surface or line  as of the curve of the of the inner surface of an eggshell in opposition to convex; as a concave mirror; the concave arch of the sky."
"To hide or withdraw from observation; to cover; to cover or keep from sight; to prevent the discovery of; to withhold knowledge of."
"To yield or suffer; to surrender; to grant; as  to concede the point in question."
"That which is conceived  imagined or formed in the mind; idea; thought; image; conception."
"Concert of voices; concord of sounds; harmony; as  a concent of notes."
"An abstract general conception; a notion; a universal."
"To relate or belong to; to have reference to or connection with; to affect the interest of; to be of importance to."
"To plan together; to settle or adjust by conference  agreement or consultation."

"A name applied to various marine univalve shells; esp. to those of the genus Strombus  which are of large size. S. gigas is the large pink West Indian conch. The large king queen and cameo conchs are of the genus Cassis. See Cameo."
"The plain semidome of an apse; sometimes used for the entire apse."
"Pertaining to the concha  or external ear; as the conchal cartilage."
"Expressing much in a few words; condensed; brief and compacted; -- used of style in writing or speaking."
"To digest; to convert into nourishment by the organs of nutrition."
"To pronounce to be wrong; to disapprove of; to censure."
"One who watches shoals of fish; a balker. See Balker."
"To express sympathetic sorrow; to grieve in sympathy; -- followed by with."
"A very large bird of the Vulture family (Sarcorhamphus gryphus)  found in the most elevated parts of the Andes."
"To lead or tend  esp. with reference to a favorable or desirable result; to contribute; -- usually followed by to or toward."
"The act or method of conducting; guidance; management."
"A pipe  canal channel or passage for conveying water or fluid."
"A bony prominence; particularly  an eminence at the end of a bone bearing a rounded articular surface; -- sometimes applied also to a concave articular surface."

"A solid of the form described by the revolution of a right-angled triangle about one of the sides adjacent to the right angle; -- called also a right cone. More generally  any solid having a vertical point and bounded by a surface which is described by a straight line always passing through that vertical point; a solid having a circle for its base and tapering to a point or vertex."
"To prepare  as sweetmeats; to make a confection of."
"To bring together for comparison; to compare."
"To make acknowledgment or avowal in a matter pertaining to one's self; to acknowledge  own or admit as a crime a fault a debt."
"To put faith (in); to repose confidence; to trust; -- usually followed by in; as  the prince confides in his ministers."
"To restrain within limits; to restrict; to limit; to bound; to shut up; to inclose; to keep close."
"To make firm or firmer; to add strength to; to establish; as  health is confirmed by exercise."
"A flowing together; a meeting of currents."
"Of the same form; similar in import; conformable."
"To overwhelm by argument; to refute conclusively; to prove or show to be false or defective; to overcome; to silence."
"The act of taking leave; parting ceremony; farewell; also  dismissal."
"To change from a fluid to a solid state by cold; to freeze."
"To collect or gather into a mass or aggregate; to bring together; to accumulate."
"A liquid measure containing about three quarts."
"Black tea  of higher grade (finer leaf and less dusty) than the present bohea. See Tea."
"Having the form of  or resembling a geometrical cone; round and tapering to a point or gradually lessening in circumference; as a conic or conical figure; a conical vessel."
"That branch of geometry which treats of the cone and the curves which arise from its sections."
"A tree or shrub bearing cones; one of the order Coniferae  which includes the pine cypress and (according to some) the yew."

"A powerful and very poisonous vegetable alkaloid found in the hemlock (Conium maculatum) and extracted as a colorless oil  C8H17N of strong repulsive odor and acrid taste. It is regarded as a derivative of piperidine and likewise of one of the collidines. It occasions a gradual paralysis of the motor nerves. Called also coniine coneine conia etc. See Conium 2."
"A genus of biennial  poisonous white-flowered umbelliferous plants bearing ribbed fruit (""""seeds"""") and decompound leaves."
"To call on or summon by a sacred name or in solemn manner; to implore earnestly; to adjure."
"Born with another; being of the same birth."
"To join  or fasten together as by something intervening; to associate; to combine; to unite or link together; to establish a bond or relation between."
"A marine European fish (Crenilabrus melops); also  the related American cunner. See Cunner."
"To open and close the eyes rapidly; to wink."
"To mark along with; to suggest or indicate as additional; to designate by implication; to include in the meaning; to imply."
"Anything that has a form resembling that of a cone."
"To gain or acquire by force; to take possession of by violent means; to gain dominion over; to subdue by physical means; to reduce; to overcome by force of arms; to cause to yield; to vanquish."
"To agree in opinion or sentiment; to be of the same mind; to accord; to concur."

"To give  transfer or deliver in a formal manner as if by signing over into the possession of another or into a different state with the sense of fixedness in that state or permanence of possession; as to consign the body to the grave."
"To stand firm; to be in a fixed or permanent state  as a body composed of parts in union or connection; to hold together; to be; to exist; to subsist; to be supported and maintained."
"To cheer in distress or depression; to alleviate the grief and raise the spirits of; to relieve; to comfort; to soothe."
"One who shares the lot of another; a companion; a partner; especially  a wife or husband."
"A certificate showing what appears upon record touching a matter in question."
"One of the two chief magistrates of the republic."
"To seek the opinion or advice of another; to take counsel; to deliberate together; to confer."
"To destroy  as by decomposition dissipation waste or fire; to use up; to expend; to waste; to burn up; to eat up; to devour."
"A close union or junction of bodies; a touching or meeting."
"To hold within fixed limits; to comprise; to include; to inclose; to hold."
"To view or treat with contempt  as mean and despicable; to reject with disdain; to despise; to scorn."
"To strive in opposition; to contest; to dispute; to vie; to quarrel; to fight."
"Contained within limits; hence  having the desires limited by that which one has; not disposed to repine or grumble; satisfied; contented; at rest."
"To make a subject of dispute  contention litigation or emulation; to contend for; to call in question; to controvert; to oppose; to dispute."
"To twist  or twist together; to turn awry; to bend; to distort; to wrest."
"The outline of a figure or body  or the line or lines representing such an outline; the line that bounds; periphery."
"A Latin adverb and preposition  signifying against contrary in opposition etc. entering as a prefix into the composition of many English words. Cf. Counter adv. & pref."
"A duplicate book  register or account kept to correct or check another account or register; a counter register."
"An American parrakeet of the genus Conurus. Many species are known. See Parrakeet."
"To come together; to meet; to unite."
"Rising or swelling into a spherical or rounded form; regularly protuberant or bulging; -- said of a spherical surface or curved line when viewed from without  in opposition to concave."
"To carry from one place to another; to bear or transport."
"To call together; to summon to meet; to assemble by summons."
"To accompany for protection  either by sea or land; to attend for protection; to escort; as a frigate convoys a merchantman."
"A rabbit  esp. the European rabbit (Lepus cuniculus)"
"To make a low repeated cry or sound  like the characteristic note of pigeons or doves."
"A peculiar whistling sound made by the Australian aborigenes as a call or signal."
"To make the noise of the cuckoo."
"The art or process of preparing food for the table  by dressing compounding and the application of heat."
"A small  flat sweetened cake of various kinds."
"Moderately cold; between warm and cold; lacking in warmth; producing or promoting coolness."
"That which cools  or abates heat or excitement."
"The great gray crane of India (Grus cinerea)."
"Soot; coal dust; refuse matter  as the dirty grease which comes from axle boxes or the refuse at the mouth of an oven."
"A dry measure of four bushels  or half a quarter."
"A hollow in a hillside. [Prov. Eng.] See Comb  Combe."
"A cycadaceous plant of Florida and the West Indies  the Zamia integrifolia from the stems of which a kind of sago is prepared."
"One who makes barrels  hogsheads casks etc."
"To choose or elect in concert with another."
"A wading bird with lobate toes  of the genus Fulica."
"The top of a thing; the head; a crest."

"A more or less viscid  yellowish liquid the bitter oleoresin of several species of Copaifera a genus of trees growing in South America and the West Indies. It is stimulant and diuretic and is much used in affections of the mucous membranes; -- called also balsam of copaiba."

"A resinous substance flowing spontaneously from trees of Zanzibar  Madagascar and South America (Trachylobium Hornemannianum T. verrucosum and Hymenaea Courbaril) and dug from earth where forests have stood in Africa; -- used chiefly in making varnishes."
"One who copies; one who writes or transcribes from an original; a transcriber."
"Large in quantity or amount; plentiful; abundant; fruitful."
"A piece of ground terminating in a point or acute angle."
"Rising to a point or head; conical; pointed; crested."

"A common metal of a reddish color  both ductile and malleable and very tenacious. It is one of the best conductors of heat and electricity. Symbol Cu. Atomic weight 63.3. It is one of the most useful metals in itself and also in its alloys brass and bronze."
"Mixed with copper; containing copper  or made of copper; like copper."
"A grove of small growth; a thicket of brushwood; a wood cut at certain times for fuel or other purposes. See Copse."
"Something rising in a conical shape; specifically  a hill rising to a point."
"The dried meat of the cocoanut  from which cocoanut oil is expressed."
"A wood of small growth; a thicket of brushwood. See Coppice."
"An Egyptian race thought to be descendants of the ancient Egyptians."
"The word which unites the subject and predicate."
"A copier; a transcriber; an imitator; a plagiarist."
"To attempt to attract the notice  admiration or love of; to treat with a show of tenderness or regard with a view to deceive and disappoint."
"A soft  whitish coral-like stone formed of broken shells and corals found in the southern United States and used for roadbeds and for building material as in the fort at St. Augustine Florida."
"A Hebrew measure of capacity; a homer."
"The Arabian gazelle (Gazella Arabica)  found from persia to North Africa."

"A boat made by covering a wicker frame with leather or oilcloth. It was used by the ancient Britons  and is still used by fisherman in Wales and some parts of Ireland. Also a similar boat used in Thibet and in Egypt."
"The hard parts or skeleton of various Anthozoa  and of a few Hydrozoa. Similar structures are also formed by some Bryozoa."
"A sprightly but somewhat stately dance  now out of fashion."
"A basket used in coal mines  etc. see Corf."
"An offering of any kind  devoted to God and therefore not to be appropriated to any other use; esp. an offering in fulfillment of a vow."
"A sculptured basket of flowers; a corbel."
"A bracket supporting a superincumbent object  or receiving the spring of an arch. Corbels were employed largely in Gothic architecture."
"The heart of the seed; the embryo or germ."
"A string  or small rope composed of several strands twisted together."
"Ropes or cords  collectively; hence anything made of rope or cord as those parts of the rigging of a ship which consist of ropes."
"A cord or ribbon bestowed or borne as a badge of honor; a broad ribbon  usually worn after the manner of a baldric constituting a mark of a very high grade in an honorary order. Cf. Grand cordon."
"That which cores; an instrument for coring fruit; as  an apple corer."
"A native or inhabitant of Corfu  an island in the Mediterranean Sea."
"A city of Greece  famed for its luxury and extravagance."
"Armor made of leather  particularly that used by the Romans; used also by Enlish soldiers till the reign of Edward I."
"The outer layer of the bark of the cork tree (Quercus Suber)  of which stoppers for bottles and casks are made. See Cutose."
"The charge made by innkeepers for drawing the cork and taking care of bottles of wine bought elsewhere by a guest."
"Consisting of  or like cork; dry shriveled up."
"A solid bulb-shaped root  as of the crocus. See Bulb."
"A thickening of the epidermis at some point  esp. on the toes by friction or pressure. It is usually painful and troublesome."
"Anancient tenure of land  which obliged the tenant to give notice of an invasion by blowing a horn."
"The cob or axis on which the kernels of Indian corn grow."
"The transparent part of the coat of the eyeball which covers the iris and pupil and admits light to the interior. See Eye."
"The cornelian cherry (Cornus Mas)  a European shrub with clusters of small greenish flowers followed by very acid but edible drupes resembling cherries."
"The point where two converging lines meet; an angle  either external or internal."
"An obsolete rude reed instrument (Ger. Zinken)  of the oboe family."
"Pertaining to  derived from or resembling the dogwood (Cornus florida)."
"Any horizontal  molded or otherwise decorated projection which crowns or finishes the part to which it is affixed; as the cornice of an order pedestal door window or house."
"A bitter principle obtained from dogwood (Cornus florida)  as a white crystalline substance; -- called also cornic acid."
"Of or pertaining to Cornwall  in England."
"A performer on the cornet or horn."
"A horn  or anything shaped like or resembling a horn."
"A man that wears the horns; a cuckold."
"Strong  stiff or hard like a horn; resembling horn."
"An allowance of meat  drink or clothing due from an abbey or other religious house for the sustenance of such of the king's servants as he may designate to receive it."

"The inner envelope of a flower; the part which surrounds the organs of fructification  consisting of one or more leaves called petals. It is usually distinguished from the calyx by the fineness of its texture and the gayness of its colors. See the Note under Blossom."
"A crown or garland bestowed among the Romans as a reward for distinguished services."
"Of or pertaining to a corona (in any of the senses)."

"An officer of the peace whose principal duty is to inquire  with the help of a jury into the cause of any violent sudden or mysterious death or death in prison usually on sight of the body and at the place where the death occurred."

"An ornamental or honorary headdress  having the shape and character of a crown; particularly a crown worn as the mark of high rank lower than sovereignty. The word is used by Shakespeare to denote also a kingly crown."
"In Greek grammar  a sign ['] sometimes placed over a contracted syllable."
"The name in Central America for the seed of a true palm; also  a commercial name for the true ivory nut. See Ivory nut."
"The human body  whether living or dead."
"A human body in general  whether living or dead; -- sometimes contemptuously."
"A body  living or dead; the corporeal substance of a thing."
"To gnaw into; to wear away; to fret; to consume."
"A pen for animals; esp.  an inclosure made with wagons by emigrants in the vicinity of hostile Indians as a place of security for horses cattle etc."
"Set right  or made straight; hence conformable to truth rectitude or propriety or to a just standard; not faulty or imperfect; free from error; as correct behavior; correct views."
"A hollow in the side of a hill  where game usually lies."
"To eat away by degrees; to wear away or diminish by gradually separating or destroying small particles of  as by action of a strong acid or a caustic alkali."
"Changed from a sound to a putrid state; spoiled; tainted; vitiated; unsound."
"The waist or bodice of a lady's dress; as  a low corsage."
"A pirate; one who cruises about without authorization from any government  to seize booty on sea or land."
"A small foxlike mammal (Cynalopex corsac)  found in Central Asia."
"In the Middle Ages  a gown or basque of which the body was close fitting worn by both men and women."

"The morsel of execration; a species of ordeal consisting in the eating of a piece of bread consecrated by imprecation. If the suspected person ate it freely  he was pronounced innocent; but if it stuck in his throat it was considered as a proof of his guilt."
"The legislative assembly  composed of nobility clergy and representatives of cities which in Spain and in Portugal answers in some measure to the Parliament of Great Britain."
"Bark  as of a tree; hence an outer covering."
"An open internal courtyard inclosed by the walls of a large dwelling house or other large and stately building."
"An obligation to perform certain services  as the repair of roads for the lord or sovereign."
"Of or pertaining to the crow; crowlike."
"A flat-topped or convex cluster of flowers  each on its own footstalk and arising from different points of a common axis the outermost blossoms expanding first as in the hawthorn."
"To levy certain exactions or tribute upon; to lodge and eat at the expense of. See Coshering."
"The sine of the complement of an arc or angle. See Illust. of Functions."
"The universe or universality of created things; -- so called from the order and harmony displayed in it."
"A Hindoo measure of distance  varying from one and a half to two English miles."

"One of a warlike  pastoral people skillful as horsemen inhabiting different parts of the Russian empire and furnishing valuable contingents of irregular cavalry to its armies those of Little Russia and those of the Don forming the principal divisions."
"Plain India muslin  of various qualities and widths."
"A lamb reared without the aid of the dam. Hence: A pet  in general."
"A rib; a side; a region or coast."
"A rib of an animal or a human being."
"Pertaining to the ribs or the sides of the body; as  costal nerves."
"An apple  large and round like the head."
"One who hawks about fruit  green vegetables fish etc."
"Retaining fecal matter in the bowels; having too slow a motion of the bowels; constipated."
"A bottle of leather  earthenware or wood having ears by which it was suspended at the side."
"Dress in general; esp.  the distinctive style of dress of a people class or period."
"A small house; a cottage or hut."
"A set or circle of persons who meet familiarly  as for social literary or other purposes; a clique."
"A buskin anciently used by tragic actors on the stage; hence  tragedy in general."
"Marking an equality in the tides; having high tide at the same time."
"A bird of the family Cotingidae  including numerous bright-colored South American species; -- called also chatterers."
"Land appendant to a cot or cottage  or held by a cottager or cotter."
"A small house; a cot; a hut."
"In Great Britain and Ireland  a person who hires a small cottage with or without a plot of land. Cottiers commonly aid in the work of the landlord's farm."
"A diminutive of the bendlet  containing one half its area or one quarter the area of the bend. When a single cottise is used alone it is often called a cost. See also Couple-close."
"Like a fish of the genus Cottus."

"A soft  downy substance resembling fine wool consisting of the unicellular twisted hairs which grow on the seeds of the cotton plant. Long-staple cotton has a fiber sometimes almost two inches long; short-staple from two thirds of an inch to an inch and a half."
"Covered with hairs or pubescence  like cotton; downy; nappy; woolly."
"A trammel  or hook to support a pot over a fire."
"A cuplike cavity or organ. Same as Acetabulum."
"A large  Old World ground cuckoo of the genus Centropus of several species."
"To lay upon a bed or other resting place."
"Not erect; inclined; -- said of anything that is usually erect  as an escutcheon."
"A reception held at the time of going to bed  as by a sovereign or great prince."
"A measure of length; the distance from the elbow to the end of the middle finger; a cubit."

"An American feline quadruped (Felis concolor)  resembling the African panther in size and habits. Its color is tawny without spots; hence writers often called it the American lion. Called also puma panther mountain lion and catamount. See Puma."
"To expel air  or obstructing or irritating matter from the lungs or air passages in a noisy and violent manner."

"The standard unit of quantity in electrical measurements. It is the quantity of electricity conveyed in one second by the current produced by an electro-motive force of one volt acting in a circuit having a resistance of one ohm  or the quantity transferred by one ampere in one second. Formerly called weber."
"An assembly of men summoned or convened for consultation  deliberation or advice; as a council of physicians for consultation in a critical case."
"To tell or name one by one  or by groups for the purpose of ascertaining the whole number of units in a collection; to number; to enumerate; to compute; to reckon."
"A prefix meaning contrary  opposite in opposition; as counteract counterbalance countercheck. See Counter adv. & a."
"An advocate or professional pleader; one who counted for his client  that is orally pleaded his cause."

"A tract of land; a region; the territory of an independent nation; (as distinguished from any other region  and with a personal pronoun) the region of one's birth permanent residence or citizenship."
"An earldom; the domain of a count or earl."
"A sudden stroke; an unexpected device or stratagem; -- a term used in various ways to convey the idea of promptness and force."
"The front compartment of a French diligence; also  the front compartment (usually for three persons) of a car or carriage on British railways."
"Cut off smoothly  as distinguished from erased; -- used especially for the head or limb of an animal. See Erased."
"A motion in dancing  when one leg is a little bent and raised from the floor and with the other a forward motion is made."
"That which joins or links two things together; a bond or tie; a coupler."
"One who couples; that which couples  as a link ring or shackle to connect cars."
"Two taken together; a pair or couple; especially two lines of verse that rhyme with each other."

"A certificate of interest due  printed at the bottom of transferable bonds (state railroad etc.) given for a term of years designed to be cut off and presented for payment when the interest is due; an interest warrant."
"A passage cut through the glacis to facilitate sallies by the besieged."
"Represented as running; -- said of a beast borne in a coat of arms."
"A skin disease  common in India in which there is perpetual itching and eruption esp. of the groin breast armpits and face."
"A square piece of linen used formerly by women instead of a cap; a kerchief."
"A messenger sent with haste to convey letters or dispatches  usually on public business."
"A South American bird  of the genus Aramus allied to the rails."
"The act of moving from one point to another; progress; passage."
"A space in the galley; a part of the hatches."
"An inclosed space; a courtyard; an uncovered area shut in by the walls of a building  or by different building; also a space opening from a street and nearly surrounded by houses; a blind alley."
"One who courts; one who plays the lover  or who solicits in marriage; one who flatters and cajoles."
"One collaterally related more remotely than a brother or sister; especially  the son or daughter of an uncle or aunt."
"Could; was able; knew or known; understood."
"A custom  among certain barbarous tribes that when a woman gives birth to a child her husband takes to his bed as if ill."
"A retired nook; especially  a small sheltered inlet creek or bay; a recess in the shore."
"To overspread the surface of (one thing) with another; as  to cover wood with paint or lacquer; to cover a table with a cloth."
"To wish for with eagerness; to desire possession of; -- used in a good sense."
"A brood or hatch of birds; an old bird with her brood of young; hence  a small flock or number of birds together; -- said of game; as a covey of partridges."
"A collusive agreement between two or more persons to prejudice a third."
"One who works as a mason without having served a regular apprenticeship."
"Borne in the escutcheon with his tail doubled between his legs; -- said of a lion."
"A poisonous umbelliferous plant; in England  the Cicuta virosa; in the United States the Cicuta maculata and the Archemora rigida. See Water hemlock."

"The cow blackbird (Molothrus ater)  an American starling. Like the European cuckoo it builds no nest but lays its eggs in the nests of other birds; -- so called because frequently associated with cattle."
"A cattle herder; a drover; specifically  one of an adventurous class of herders and drovers on the plains of the Western and Southwestern United States."
"To stoop by bending the knees; to crouch; to squat; hence  to quail; to sink through fear."

"A leguminous climbing plant of the genus Mucuna  having crooked pods covered with sharp hairs which stick to the fingers causing intolerable itching. The spiculae are sometimes used in medicine as a mechanical vermifuge."
"One whose occupation is to tend cows."
"A monk's hood; -- usually attached to the gown. The name was also applied to the hood and garment together."
"Wearing a cowl; hooded; as  a cowled monk."
"A tuft of hair turned up or awry (usually over the forehead)  as if licked by a cow."
"The seed of one or more leguminous plants of the genus Dolichos; also  the plant itself. Many varieties are cultivated in the southern part of the United States."
"A pustular eruptive disease of the cow  which when communicated to the human system as by vaccination protects from the smallpox; vaccinia; -- called also kinepox cowpock and kinepock."
"A marine shell of the genus Cypraea."
"A common flower in England (Primula veris) having yellow blossoms and appearing in early spring. It is often cultivated in the United States."
"The first joint of the leg of an insect or crustacean."
"A strip of red cloth notched like the comb of a cock  which licensed jesters formerly wore in their caps."
"The quality of being coy; feigned o/ bashful unwillingness to become familiar; reserve."
"A carnivorous animal (Canis latrans)  allied to the dog found in the western part of North America; -- called also prairie wolf. Its voice is a snapping bark followed by a prolonged shrill howl."
"A South American rodent (Myopotamus coypus)  allied to the beaver. It produces a valuable fur called nutria."
"To cheat; to defraud; to beguile; to deceive  usually by small arts or in a pitiful way."
"One of the brachyuran Crustacea. They are mostly marine  and usually have a broad short body covered with a strong shell or carapace. The abdomen is small and curled up beneath the body."
"Characterized by or manifesting  sourness peevishness or moroseness; harsh; cross; cynical; -- applied to feelings disposition or manners."
"To break or burst  with or without entire separation of the parts; as to crack glass; to crack nuts."
"To make slight cracks; to make small  sharp sudden noises rapidly or frequently repeated; to crepitate; as burning thorns crackle."

"A bed or cot for a baby  oscillating on rockers or swinging on pivots; hence the place of origin or in which anything is nurtured or protected in the earlier period of existence; as a cradle of crime; the cradle of liberty."
"Relating to  or characterized by craft or skill; dexterous."
"A steep  rugged rock; a rough broken cliff or point of a rock on a ledge."
"Full of crags  or steep broken //cks; abounding with prominences points and inequalities; rough; rugged."
"Full of crags; rugged with projecting points of rocks; as  the craggy side of a mountain."
"To cry out harshly and loudly  like the bird called crake."
"To press  force or drive particularly in filling or in thrusting one thing into another; to stuff; to crowd; to fill to superfluity; as to cram anything into a basket; to cram a room with people."
"A game in which one person gives a word  to which another finds a rhyme."
"One who crams; esp.  one who prepares a pupil hastily for an examination or a pupil who is thus prepared."
"That which confines or contracts; a restraint; a shackle; a hindrance."
"A cramp iron or cramp ring; a chape  as of a scabbard."
"An a/rial rootlet for support in climbing  as of ivy."
"A measure for fresh herrings  -- as many as will fill a barrel."
"The liberty of using a crane  as for loading and unloading vessels."
"A genus of living Brachiopoda; -- so called from its fancied resemblance to the cranium or skull."
"The skull of an animal; especially  that part of the skull either cartilaginous or bony which immediately incloses the brain; the brain case or brainpan. See Skull."

"A bent portion of an axle  or shaft or an arm keyed at right angles to the end of a shaft by which motion is imparted to or received from it; also used to change circular into reciprocating motion or reciprocating into circular motion. See Bell crank."
"Formed with  or having a bend or crank; as a cranked axle."
"To break into bends  turns or angles; to crinkle."
"A small  narrow opening fissure crevice or chink as in a wall or other substance."
"A garland carried before the bier of a maiden."
"A thin  crimped stuff made of raw silk gummed and twisted on the mill. Black crape is much used for mourning garments also for the dress of some clergymen."
"A kind of fresh-water bass of the genus Pomoxys  found in the rivers of the Southern United States and Mississippi valley. There are several species."
"To break in pieces violently; to dash together with noise and violence."
"A mixture of constituents  as of the blood; constitution; temperament."
"Gross; thick; dense; coarse; not elaborated or refined."
"A manger or open frame for hay; a crib; a rack."
"A large basket or hamper of wickerwork  used for the transportation of china crockery and similar wares."
"The basinlike opening or mouth of a volcano  through which the chief eruption comes; similarly the mouth of a geyser about which a cone of silica is often built up."
"To crush with the teeth; to chew with violence and noise; to crunch."
"A neckcloth; a piece of silk  fine muslin or other cloth worn by men about the neck."
"To ask with earnestness or importunity; to ask with submission or humility; to beg; to entreat; to beseech; to implore."
"To move slowly by drawing the body along the ground  as a worm; to move slowly on hands and knees; to creep."
"One who  or that which crawls; a creeper; a reptile."
"An implement for drawing  made of clay and plumbago or of some preparation of chalk usually sold in small prisms or cylinders."
"To break into pieces; to crush; to grind to powder. See Crase."
"Characterized by weakness or feebleness; decrepit; broken; falling to decay; shaky; unsafe."
"To make a prolonged sharp grating or squeaking sound  as by the friction of hard substances; as shoes creak."
"The rich  oily and yellowish part of milk which when the milk stands unagitated rises and collects on the surface. It is the part of milk from which butter is obtained."
"Full of  or containing cream; resembling cream in nature appearance or taste; creamlike; unctuous."
"A tool  or a sewing-machine attachment for making lines or creases on leather or cloth as guides to sew by."
"Relating to  or produced by flesh or animal food; as creatic nausea."
"A white  crystalline nitrogenous substance found abundantly in muscle tissue."
"One who creates  produces or constitutes. Specifically the Supreme Being."
"The tin ore which collects in the central part of the washing pit or buddle."
"A public nursery  where the young children of poor women are cared for during the day while their mothers are at work."
"Reliance on the truth of something said or done; belief; faith; trust; confidence."
"The creed  as sung or read in the Roman Catholic church."
"A definite summary of what is believed; esp.  a summary of the articles of Christian faith; a confession of faith for public use; esp. one which is brief and comprehensive."
"A small inlet or bay  narrower and extending further into the land than a cove; a recess in the shore of the sea or of a river."
"A tribe or confederacy of North American Indians  including the Muskogees Seminoles Uchees and other subordinate tribes. They formerly inhabited Georgia Florida and Alabama."
"Containing  or abounding in creeks; characterized by creeks; like a creek; winding."
"An osier basket  such as anglers use."
"To move along the ground  or on any other surface on the belly as a worm or reptile; to move as a child on the hands and knees; to crawl."
"One who  or that which creeps; any creeping thing."
"Crawly; having or producing a sensation like that caused by insects creeping on the skin."
"An Algonquin tribe of Indians  inhabiting a large part of British America east of the Rocky Mountains and south of Hudson's Bay."
"A dagger or short sword used by the Malays  commonly having a serpentine blade."
"To burn; to reduce to ashes by the action of fire  either directly or in an oven or retort; to incremate or incinerate; as to cremate a corpse instead of burying it."
"A superior kind of violin  formerly made at Cremona in Italy."
"Cream; a substance resembling cream; yeast; scum."

"One born of European parents in the American colonies of France or Spain or in the States which were once such colonies  esp. a person of French or Spanish descent who is a native inhabitant of Louisiana or one of the States adjoining bordering on the Gulf of of Mexico."
"A colorless liquid resembling phenol or carbolic acid  homologous with pyrocatechin and obtained from beechwood tar and gum guaiacum."
"An injury in a horse's leg  caused by the shoe of one hind foot striking and cutting the other leg. It sometimes forms an ulcer."
"A thin stuff made of the finest wool or silk  or of wool and silk."

"Any one of three metameric substances  CH3.C6H4.OH homologous with and resembling phenol. They are obtained from coal tar and wood tar and are colorless oily liquids or solids. [Called also cresylic acid.]"
"A plant of various species  chiefly cruciferous. The leaves have a moderately pungent taste and are used as a salad and antiscorbutic."
"An open frame or basket of iron  filled with combustible material to be burned as a beacon; an open lamp or firrepan carried on a pole in nocturnal processions."
"A tuft  or other excrescence or natural ornament growing on an animal's head; the comb of a cock; the swelling on the head of a serpent; the lengthened feathers of the crown or nape of bird etc."
"A poetic foot  composed of one short syllable between two long ones (- / -)."
"Used in English only in the expression en creux. Thus  engraving en creux is engraving in intaglio or by sinking or hollowing out the design."
"A crucible or melting pot; a cruset."
"A narrow opening resulting from a split or crack or the separation of a junction; a cleft; a fissure; a rent."
"Worsted yarn slackly twisted used for embroidery."
"A manger or rack; a feeding place for animals."
"The ring which turns inward and condenses the flame of a lamp."
"The creaking of a door  or a noise resembling it."
"An orthopterous insect of the genus Gryllus  and allied genera. The males make chirping musical notes by rubbing together the basal parts of the veins of the front wings."
"Resembling a ring; -- said esp. of the cartilage at the larynx  and the adjoining parts."
"One who cries; one who makes proclamation."
"Any violation of law  either divine or human; an omission of a duty commanded or the commission of an act forbidden by law."
"To fold or plait in regular undulation in such a way that the material will retain the shape intended; to give a wavy appearance to; as  to crimp the border of a cap; to crimp a ruffle. Cf. Crisp."
"To cause to shrink or draw together; to contract; to curl."
"Having a crimped appearance; frizzly; as  the crimpy wool of the Saxony sheep."
"A deep red color tinged with blue; also  red color in general."
"A twist or bend; a turn; a whimsey."
"Having the hair of a different tincture from the rest of the body; as  a charge crined of a red tincture."
"To draw one's self together as in fear or servility; to bend or crouch with base humility; to wince; hence; to make court in a degrading manner; to fawn."
"Having the appearance of a tuft of hair; having a hairlike tail or train."
"To form with short turns  bends or wrinkles; to mold into inequalities or sinuosities; to cause to wrinkle or curl."
"A genus of bulbous plants  of the order Amaryllidace/ cultivated as greenhouse plants on account of their beauty."
"One who creeps  halts or limps; one who has lost or never had the use of a limb or limbs; a lame person; hence one who is partially disabled."
"The point of time when it is to be decided whether any affair or course of action must go on  or be modified or terminate; the decisive moment; the turning point."
"Curling in stiff curls or ringlets; as  crisp hair."
"One who  or that which crisps or curls; an instrument for making little curls in the nap of cloth as in chinchilla."
"A shoemaker; -- jocularly so called from the patron saint of the craft."
"Formed into short  close ringlets; frizzed; crisp; as crispy locks."
"Pertaining to the crissum; as  crissal feathers."
"That part of a bird  or the feathers surrounding the cloacal opening; the under tail coverts."

"The unit for estimating the weight of a/riform substances; -- the weight of a liter of hydrogen at 0/ centigrade  and with a tension of 76 centimeters of mercury. It is 0.0896 of a gram or 1.38274 grains."
"One skilled in judging of the merits of literary or artistic works; a connoisseur; an adept; hence  one who examines literary or artistic works etc. and passes judgment upon them; a reviewer."
"A kind of roughness on the surface of glass  which clouds its transparency."
"To make a low  hoarse noise in the throat as a frog a raven or a crow; hence to make any hoarse dismal sound."
"One who croaks  murmurs grumbles or complains unreasonably; one who habitually forebodes evil."
"A native of Croatia  in Austria; esp. one of the native Slavic race."
"A name given to any one of several yellow or scarlet dyestuffs of artificial production and complex structure. In general they are diazo and sulphonic acid derivatives of benzene and naphthol."
"A little bud or knob at the top of a deer's antler."
"A kind of knitting done by means of a hooked needle  with worsted silk or cotton; crochet work. Commonly used adjectively."
"The coloring matter of Chinese yellow pods  the fruit of Gardenia grandiflora."
"The loose black particles collected from combustion  as on pots and kettles or in a chimney; soot; smut; also coloring matter which rubs off from cloth."
"An ornament often resembling curved and bent foliage  projecting from the sloping edge of a gable spire etc."
"A white crystalline sugar  metameric with glucose obtained from the coloring matter of saffron."

"A genus of iridaceous plants  with pretty blossoms rising separately from the bulb or corm. C. vernus is one of the earliest of spring-blooming flowers; C. sativus produces the saffron and blossoms in the autumn."
"A king of Lydia who flourished in the 6th century b. c.  and was renowned for his vast wealth; hence a common appellation for a very rich man; as he is a veritable Croesus."
"A small  inclosed field adjoining a house; a small farm."
"One who rents and tills a small farm or helding; as  the crofters of Scotland."
"A pilgrim bearing or wearing a cross."
"A cultivator of saffron; a dealer in saffron."
"The iron head of a tilting spear."
"Saturnian; -- applied to the North Polar Sea."
"To cower or cuddle together  as from fear or cold; to lie close and snug together as pigs in straw."
"A bend  turn or curve; curvature; flexure."
"To make a continuous hollow moan  as cattle do when in pain."
"The pouchlike enlargement of the gullet of birds  serving as a receptacle for food; the craw."
"Having a full crop or belly; satiated."
"An open-air game in which two or more players endeavor to drive wooden balls  by means of mallets through a series of hoops or arches set in the ground according to some pattern."
"Ten millions; as  a crore of rupees (which is nearly $5 0 000)."
"The pastoral staff of a bishop (also of an archbishop  being the symbol of his office as a shepherd of the flock of God."

"A gibbet  consisting of two pieces of timber placed transversely upon one another in various forms as a T or + with the horizontal piece below the upper end of the upright or as an X. It was anciently used in the execution of criminals."
"Athwart; adversely; unfortunately; peevishly; fretfully; with ill humor."
"The angle formed by the parting of two legs or branches; a fork; the point where a trunk divides; as  the crotch of a tree."
"A genus of euphorbiaceous plants belonging to tropical countries."
"To bend down; to stoop low; to lie close to the ground with the logs bent  as an animal when waiting for prey or in fear."
"The hinder part or buttocks of certain quadrupeds  especially of a horse; hence the place behind the saddle."
"Of or pertaining to croup; resembling or indicating croup; as  a croupy cough."
"Bread cut in various forms  and fried lightly in butter or oil to garnish hashes etc."
"To make the shrill sound characteristic of a cock  either in joy gayety or defiance."
"A bar of iron sharpened at one end  and used as a lever."
"One who plays on a crowd; a fiddler."
"A thick gruel of oatmeal and milk or water; food of the porridge kind."
"A tribe of Indians of the Dakota stock  living in Montana; -- also called Upsarokas."
"A cooper's tool for making the grooves for the heads of casks  etc.; also the groove itself."
"Having the form of a cross; appertaining to a cross; cruciform; intersecting; as  crucial ligaments; a crucial incision."
"To fasten to a cross; to put to death by nailing the hands and feet to a cross or gibbet."
"In its natural state; not cooked or prepared by fire or heat; undressed; not altered  refined or prepared for use by any artificial process; raw; as crude flesh."
"The attribute or quality of being cruel; a disposition to give unnecessary pain or suffering to others; inhumanity; barbarity."
"A bottle or vessel; esp.  a vial or small glass bottle for holding vinegar oil pepper or the like for the table; a caster."
"One who  or a vessel that cruises; -- usually an armed vessel."
"A kind of weir or dam for trapping salmon; also  a hovel."
"A kind of sweet cake cut in strips and curled or twisted  and fried crisp in boiling fat."
"A small fragment or piece; especially  a small piece of bread or other food broken or cut off."
"To break into small pieces; to cause to fall in pieces."
"A kind of large  thin muffin or cake light and spongy and cooked on a griddle or spider."
"To draw or press into wrinkles or folds; to crush together; to rumple; as  to crumple paper."
"To chew with force and noise; to craunch."
"A point where one branch of a curve crosses another branch. See Double point  under Double a."
"The coloring matter of the blood; the clotted portion of coagulated blood  containing the coloring matter; gore."
"The coloring matter of the blood in the living animal; haemoglobin."
"The buttocks or rump of a horse."
"Of or pertaining to the thigh or leg  or to any of the parts called crura; as the crural arteries; crural arch; crural canal; crural ring."
