"That part of the hind limb between the femur  or thigh and the ankle or tarsus; the shank."
"Any one of the military expeditions undertaken by Christian powers  in the 11th 12th and 13th centuries for the recovery of the Holy Land from the Mohammedans."
"An old Portuguese coin  worth about seventy cents."
"To press or bruise between two hard bodies; to squeeze  so as to destroy the natural shape or integrity of the parts or to force together into a mass; as to crush grapes."
"The hard external coat or covering of anything; the hard exterior surface or outer shell; an incrustation; as  a crust of snow."
"Having the nature of crust; pertaining to a hard covering; as  a crusty coat; a crusty surface or substance."
"The rough  shaggy part of oak bark."
"A staff with a crosspiece at the head  to be placed under the arm or shoulder to support the lame or infirm in walking."
"Anything that is very puzzling or difficult to explain."
"To make a loud call or cry; to call or exclaim vehemently or earnestly; to shout; to vociferate; to proclaim; to pray; to implore."
"The female of the hawk; a falcon-gentil."
"A vault wholly or partly under ground; especially  a vault under a church whether used for burial purposes or for a subterranean chapel or oratory."

"The regular form which a substance tends to assume in solidifying  through the inherent power of cohesive attraction. It is bounded by plane surfaces symmetrically arranged and each species of crystal has fixed axial ratios. See Crystallization."
"Having a comblike margin  as a ctenoid scale"
"A young animal  esp. the young of the bear."
"Of or pertaining to Cuba or its inhabitants."
"A regular solid body  with six equal square sides."

"The small  spicy berry of a species of pepper (Piper Cubeba; in med. Cubeba officinalis) native in Java and Borneo but now cultivated in various tropical countries. The dried unripe fruit is much used in medicine as a stimulant and purgative."
"Pertaining to  or derived from cubebs; as cubebic acid (a soft olive-green resin extracted from cubebs)."
"Having the form or properties of a cube; contained  or capable of being contained in a cube."
"A loding room; esp.  a sleeping place partitioned off from a large dormitory."
"The lowest course of stones in a building."
"The forearm; the ulna  a bone of the arm extending from elbow to wrist."
"Of or pertaining to the cubit or ulna; as  the cubital nerve; the cubital artery; the cubital muscle."
"Cube-shaped  or nearly so; as the cuboid bone of the foot."
"A man whose wife is unfaithful; the husband of an adulteress."
"A bird belonging to Cuculus  Coccyzus and several allied genera of many species."
"The fire beetle of Mexico and the West Indies."
"A genus of plants including the cucumber  melon and same kinds of gourds."
"That portion of food which is brought up into the mouth by ruminating animals from their first stomach  to be chewed a second time."
"A powder of a violet red color  difficult to moisten with water used for making violet or purple dye. It is prepared from certain species of lichen especially Lecanora tartarea."
"A clown; a low rustic; a dolt."
"To lie close or snug; to crouch; to nestle."
"An ass; esp.  one driven by a huckster or greengrocer."
"A staff used in cudgel play  shorter than the quarterstaff and wielded with one hand; hence any heavy stick used as a weapon."
"A small composite plant with cottony or silky stem and leaves  primarily a species of Gnaphalium but the name is now given to many plants of different genera as Filago Antennaria etc.; cottonweed."
"The tail; the end of a thing; especially  a tail-like twist of hair worn at the back of the head; a queue."
"To strike; esp.  to smite with the palm or flat of the hand; to slap."
"Of or pertaining to the older characters of the Arabic language."
"The stamping of pigs of tin  by the proper officer with the arms of the duchy of Cornwall."
"A piece of defensive armor  covering the body from the neck to the girdle"
"The lower faceted portion of a brilliant-cut diamond."
"One of a class of anchorites who lived in various parts of Scotland  Ireland and Wales."
"A genus of dipterous insects  including the gnat and mosquito."
"To separate  select or pick out; to choose and gather or collect; as to cull flowers."
"One who picks or chooses; esp.  an inspector who selects wares suitable for market."
"A mean wretch; a base fellow; a poltroon; a scullion."
"A strong broth of meat  strained and made clear for invalids; also a savory jelly."
"Refuse timber  from which the best part has been culled out."
"A person easily deceived  tricked or imposed on; a mean dupe; a gull."
"The stalk or stem of grain and grasses (including the bamboo)  jointed and usually hollow."
"Negligence or fault  as distinguishable from dolus (deceit fraud) which implies intent culpa being imputable to defect of intellect dolus to defect of heart."
"A shred; a fragment; a strip of wood."
"One accused of  or arraigned for a crime as before a judge."
"Empty oyster shells and other substances laid down on oyster grounds to furnish points for the attachment of the spawn of the oyster."
"The act or practice of cultivating  or of preparing the earth for seed and raising crops by tillage; as the culture of the soil."
"Established or accepted religious rites or usages of worship; state of religious development. Cf. Cult  2."
"A transverse drain or waterway of masonry under a road  railroad canal etc.; a small bridge."
"An order of marine Crustacea  mostly of small size."
"To rest upon as a troublesome or useless weight or load; to be burdensome or oppressive to; to hinder or embarrass in attaining an object  to obstruct or occupy uselessly; to embarrass; to trouble."
"A colorless oily hydrocarbon  C6H5.C3H7 obtained by the distillation of cuminic acid; -- called also cumol."

"A dwarf umbelliferous plant  somewhat resembling fennel (Cuminum Cyminum) cultivated for its seeds which have a bitterish warm taste with an aromatic flavor and are used like those of anise and caraway."
"Pertaining to  or derived from cumin or from oil of caraway; as cuminic acid."
"A substance  analogous to benzil obtained from oil of caraway."
"A liquid  C3H7.C6H4.CHO obtained from oil of caraway; -- called also cuminic aldehyde."
"A present or bonus; -- originally applied to that paid on ships which entered the port of Canton."
"One of the four principal forms of clouds. SeeCloud."
"A drain trench  in a ditch or moat; -- called also cuvette."
"A small edible fish of the Atlantic coast (Ctenolabrus adspersus); -- called also chogset  burgall blue perch and bait stealer."

"A small vessel  used commonly to drink from; as a tin cup a silver cup a wine cup; especially in modern times the pottery or porcelain vessel commonly with a handle used with a saucer in drinking tea coffee and the like."
"A shallow porous cup  used in refining precious metals commonly made of bone ashes (phosphate of lime)."
"As much as a cup will hold."
"The god of love  son of Venus; usually represented as a naked winged boy with bow and arrow."
"A roof having a rounded form  hemispherical or nearly so; also a ceiling having the same form. When on a large scale it is usually called dome."
"One who performs the operation of cupping."
"Of  pertaining to or derived from copper; containing copper; -- said of those compounds of copper in which this element is present in its lowest proportion."
"The red oxide of copper; red copper; an important ore of copper  occurring massive and in isometric crystals."
"A solid related to a tetrahedron  and contained under twelve equal triangles."
"Of  pertaining to or derived from copper; containing copper; -- said of those compounds of copper in which this element is present in its highest proportion."
"A cuplet or little cup  as of the acorn; the husk or bur of the filbert chestnut etc."
"A liqueur  or cordial flavored with orange peel cinnamon and mace; -- first made at the island of Curaccao."
"The office or employment of a curate."

"A black resinoid extract prepared by the South American Indians from the bark of several species of Strychnos (S. toxifera  etc.). It sometimes has little effect when taken internally but is quickly fatal when introduced into the blood and used by the Indians as an arrow poison."
"One who has the cure of souls; originally  any clergyman but now usually limited to one who assists a rector or vicar."
"One who has the care and superintendence of anything  as of a museum; a custodian; a keeper."
"A genus of plants of the order Scitamineae  including the turmeric plant (Curcuma longa)."
"The coagulated or thickened part of milk  as distinguished from the whey or watery part. It is eaten as food especially when made into cheese."
"To change into curd; to coagulate; as  rennet causes milk to curdle."
"A remedy for all diseases  or for all ills; a panacea."
"One who cures; a healer; a physician."
"A scoop or ring with either a blunt or a cutting edge  for removing substances from the walls of a cavity as from the eye ear or womb."
"The ringing of an evening bell  originally a signal to the inhabitants to cover fires extinguish lights and retire to rest -- instituted by William the Conqueror; also the bell itself."
"One of the thirty parts into which the Roman people were divided by Romulus."
"Difficult to please or satisfy; solicitous to be correct; careful; scrupulous; nice; exact."
"To twist or form into ringlets; to crisp  as the hair."
"A wading bird of the genus Numenius  remarkable for its long slender curved bill."
"Curling or tending to curl; having curls; full of ripples; crinkled."
"A small kind of seedless raisin  imported from the Levant chiefly from Zante and Cephalonia; -- used in cookery."
"One who curries and dresses leather  after it is tanned."
"Having the qualities  or exhibiting the characteristics of a cur; snarling; quarrelsome; snappish; churlish; hence also malicious; malignant; brutal."
"To dress or prepare for use by a process of scraping  cleansing beating smoothing and coloring; -- said of leather."
"To call upon divine or supernatural power to send injury upon; to imprecate evil upon; to execrate."
"The state of being a cur; one who is currish."
"Any part of a mathematical instrument that moves or slides backward and forward upon another part."
"Characterized by excessive brevity; short; rudely concise; as  curt limits; a curt answer."
"To cut off the end or tail  or any part of; to shorten; to abridge; to diminish; to reduce."

"A hanging screen intended to darken or conceal  and admitting of being drawn back or up and reclosed at pleasure; esp. drapery of cloth or lace hanging round a bed or at a window; in theaters and like places a movable screen for concealing the stage."
"The pointless sword carried before English monarchs at their coronation  and emblematically considered as the sword of mercy; -- also called the sword of Edward the Confessor."

"Shortened or reduced; -- said of the distance of a planet from the sun or earth  as measured in the plane of the ecliptic or the distance from the sun or earth to that point where a perpendicular let fall from the planet upon the plane of the ecliptic meets the ecliptic."
"the life estate which a husband has in the lands of his deceased wife  which by the common law takes effect where he has had issue by her born alive and capable of inheriting the lands."
"Same as Courtesy  an act of respect."
"A Chilian burrowing rodent of the genus Spalacopus."
"Bent without angles; crooked; curved; as  a curve line; a curve surface."
"A particular leap of a horse  when he raises both his fore legs at once equally advanced and as his fore legs are falling raises his hind legs so that all his legs are in the air at once."
"The state of being curved; a bending in a regular form; crookedness."
"A case or bag stuffed with some soft and elastic material  and used to sit or recline upon; a soft pillow or pad."
"A descendant of Cush  the son of Ham and grandson of Noah."
"A large  edible marine fish (Brosmius brosme) allied to the cod common on the northern coasts of Europe and America; -- called also tusk and torsk."
"A triangular protection from the intrados of an arch  or from an inner curve of tracery."
"One of the canine teeth; -- so called from having but one point or cusp on the crown. See Tooth."
"A mixture of milk and eggs  sweetened and baked or boiled."
"A keeping or guarding; care  watch inspection for keeping preservation or security."
"Frequent repetition of the same act; way of acting common to many; ordinary manner; habitual practice; usage; method of doing or living."
"Having a part cut off or away; having the corners rounded or cut away."
"The substance which  added to the material of a cell wall makes it waterproof as in cork."
"A short  heavy curving sword used in the navy. See Curtal ax."
"One who makes or deals in cutlery  or knives and other cutting instruments."
"A piece of meat  especially of veal or mutton cut for broiling."
"The art of making edged tools or cutlery."
"A variety of cellulose  occuring as a fine transparent membrane covering the aerial organs of plants and forming an essential ingredient of cork; by oxidation it passes to suberic acid."
"One who cuts; as  a stone cutter; a die cutter; esp. one who cuts out garments."
"Short; as  a cutty knife; a cutty sark."
"The chief police officer of a large city."
"An ancient term for embroidery  esp. applied to the earliest form of lace or to that early embroidery on linen and the like from which the manufacture of lace was developed."

"A caterpillar which at night eats off young plants of cabbage  corn etc. usually at the ground. Some kinds ascend fruit trees and eat off the flower buds. During the day they conceal themselves in the earth. The common cutworms are the larvae of various species of Agrotis and related genera of noctuid moths."
"A pot  bucket or basin in which molten plate glass is carried from the melting pot to the casting table."
"A compound formed by the union of cyanogen with an element or radical."
"The blue coloring matter of flowers; -- called also anthokyan and anthocyanin."
"One of a series of artificial blue or red dyes obtained from quinoline and lepidine and used in calico printing."
"A mineral occuring in thin-bladed crystals and crystalline aggregates  of a sky-blue color. It is a silicate of aluminium."
"Any plant of the natural order Cycadaceae  as the sago palm etc."
"A genus of trees  intermediate in character between the palms and the pines. The pith of the trunk of some species furnishes a valuable kind of sago."
"A long gown or surcoat (cut off in front)  worn in the Middle Ages. It was sometimes embroidered or interwoven with gold. Also a rich stuff from which the gown was made."
"An imaginary circle or orbit in the heavens; one of the celestial spheres."
"A surface of the fourth degree  having certain special relations to spherical surfaces. The tore or anchor ring is one of the cyclides."
"A curve generated by a point in the plane of a circle when the circle is rolled along a straight line  keeping always in the same plane."

"A violent storm  often of vast extent characterized by high winds rotating about a calm center of low atmospheric pressure. This center moves onward often with a velocity of twenty or thirty miles an hour."

"One of a race of giants  sons of Neptune and Amphitrite having but one eye and that in the middle of the forehead. They were fabled to inhabit Sicily and to assist in the workshops of Vulcan under Mt. Etna."
"A peculiar mucilaginous substance extracted from the seeds of the quince (Cydonia vulgaris)  and regarded as a variety of amylose."
"A constellation of the northern hemisphere east of  or following Lyra; the Swan."
"A member or molding of the cornice  the profile of which is wavelike in form."
"A slight covering; a scarf. See Simar."
"A musical instrument used by the ancients. It is supposed to have been similar to the modern kettle drum  though perhaps smaller."
"A genus of marine univalve shells; the gondola."
"A flattish or convex flower cluster  of the centrifugal or determinate type differing from a corymb chiefly in the order of the opening of the blossoms."
"A colorless  liquid combustible hydrocarbon CH3.C6H4.C3H7 of pleasant odor obtained from oil of cumin oil of caraway carvacrol camphor etc.; -- called also paracymene and formerly camphogen."
"Having the nature of a cyme  or derived from a cyme; bearing or pertaining to a cyme or cymes."
"A collective term for the Welsh race; -- so called by themselves ."
"A small cyme  or one of very few flowers."
"Having the qualities of a surly dog; snarling; captious; currish."
"A large genus of plants belonging to the Sedge family  and including the species called galingale several bulrushes and the Egyptian papyrus."
"A genus of mollusks  including the cowries. See Cowrie."
"A rule for construing written instruments so as to conform as nearly to the intention of the parties as is consistent with law."
"A coniferous tree of the genus Cupressus. The species are mostly evergreen  and have wood remarkable for its durability."
"A genus of small  bivalve fresh-water Crustacea belonging to the Ostracoda; also a member of this genus."
"A thin  transparent stuff the same as or corresponding to crape. It was either white or black the latter being most common and used for mourning."
"A one-seeded  one-celled indehiscent fruit; an achene with the calyx tube adherent."
"A pouch or sac without opening  usually membranous and containing morbid matter which is accidentally developed in one of the natural cavities or in the substance of an organ."
"Having the form of  or living in a cyst; as the cystic entozoa."
"A white crystalline substance  C3H7NSO2 containing sulphur occuring as a constituent of certain rare urinary calculi and occasionally found as a sediment in urine."
"Containing  or resembling a cyst or cysts; cystic; bladdery."
"A nonnucleated mass of protoplasm  the supposed simplest form of independent life differing from the amoeba in which nuclei are present."
"Cell-like; -- applied to the corpuscles of lymph  blood chyle etc."
"The fertilized egg cell or parent cell  from the development of which the child or other organism is formed."
"A king; a chief; the title of the emperor of Russia."
"The title of the empress of Russia."
"The most westerly branch of the great Slavic family of nations  numbering now more than 6 0 0 and found principally in Bohemia and Moravia."
"A skillful hand; a dabster; an expert."
"A large  spine-tailed lizard (Uromastix spinipes) found in Egypt Arabia and Palestine; -- called also dhobb and dhabb."
"That with which one dabs; hence  a pad or other device used by printers engravers etc. as for dabbing type or engraved plates with ink."
"To wet by little dips or strokes; to spatter; to sprinkle; to moisten; to wet."
"A large and highly venomous Asiatic viper (Daboia xanthica)."
"One who is skilled; a master of his business; a proficient; an adept."
"From the beginning; a direction to return to  and end with the first strain; -- indicated by the letters D. C. Also the strain so repeated."
"A small European cyprinoid fish (Squalius leuciscus or Leuciscus vulgaris); -- called also dare."
"Of or pertaining to Dacia or the Dacians."
"One of a class of robbers  in India who act in gangs."
"The practice of gang robbery in India; robbery committed by dacoits."

"A poetical foot of three sylables (-- ~ ~)  one long followed by two short or one accented followed by two unaccented; as L. tegm/n/ E. mer\b6ciful; -- so called from the similarity of its arrangement to that of the joints of a finger."
"Father; -- a word sometimes used by children."
"To toddle; to walk unsteadily  like a child or an old man; hence to do anything slowly or feebly."
"To hold up by leading strings or by the hand  as a child while he toddles."
"That part of a pedestal included between the base and the cornice (or surbase); the die. See Illust. of Column."
"To cast aside; to put off; to doff."
"Stupid; foolish; idiotic; also  delirious; insane; as he has gone daft."
"A short weapon used for stabbing. This is the general term: cf. Poniard  Stiletto Bowie knife Dirk Misericorde Anlace."
"An ornamental cutting of the edges of garments  introduced about a. d. 1346 according to the Chronicles of St Albans."
"To trail  so as to wet or befoul; to make wet and limp; to moisten."
"A dirty or clotted lock of wool on a sheep; a taglock."
"A nickname given to a person of Spanish (or  by extension Portuguese or Italian) descent."
"A dome-shaped structure built over relics of Buddha or some Buddhist saint."
"The national god of the Philistines  represented with the face and hands and upper part of a man and the tail of a fish."

"A genus of plants native to Mexico and Central America  of the order Compositae; also any plant or flower of the genus. The numerous varieties of cultivated dahlias bear conspicuous flowers which differ in color."
"A variety of starch extracted from the dahlia; -- called also inulin. See Inulin."
"Happening  or belonging to each successive day; diurnal; as daily labor; a daily bulletin."
"The title of the feudal nobles of Japan."
"Value; estimation; the gratification or pleasure taken in anything."
"The place  room or house where milk is kept and converted into butter or cheese."
"The high or principal table  at the end of a hall at which the chief guests were seated; also the chief seat at the high table."
"A genus of low herbs (Bellis)  belonging to the family Compositae. The common English and classical daisy is B. prennis which has a yellow disk and white or pinkish rays."
"Post; mail; also  the mail or postal arrangements; -- spelt also dawk and dauk."
"A measure of certain commodities by number  usually ten or twelve but sometimes twenty; as a daker of hides consisted of ten skins; a daker of gloves of ten pairs."
"An extensive race or stock of Indians  including many tribes mostly dwelling west of the Mississippi River; -- also in part called Sioux."
"A low place between hills; a vale or valley."
"One who fondles; a trifler; as  dalliers with pleasant words."
"To waste time in effeminate or voluptuous pleasures  or in idleness; to fool away time; to delay unnecessarily; to tarry; to trifle."
"A female parent; -- used of beasts  especially of quadrupeds; sometimes applied in contempt to a human mother."
"Injury or harm to person  property or reputation; an inflicted loss of value; detriment; hurt; mischief."

"A small herbivorous mammal of the genus Hyrax. The species found in Palestine and Syria is Hyrax Syriacus; that of Northern Africa is H. Brucei; -- called also ashkoko  dassy and rock rabbit. See Cony and Hyrax."
"Damask silk; silk woven with an elaborate pattern of flowers and the like."
"A crystalline variety of fruit sugar obtained from dambonite."
"A mistress of a family  who is a lady; a woman in authority; especially a lady."
"A Mexican drug  used as an aphrodisiac."
"An oleoresin used in making varnishes; dammar gum; dammara resin. It is obtained from certain resin trees indigenous to the East Indies  esp. Shorea robusta and the dammar pine."
"To condemn; to declare guilty; to doom; to adjudge to punishment; to sentence; to censure."
"To cause loss or damage to; to injure; to impair."
"Harm; detriment  either to character or property."
"To make damp or moist; to make slightly wet."

"That which damps or checks; as: (a) A valve or movable plate in the flue or other part of a stove  furnace etc. used to check or regulate the draught of air. (b) A contrivance as in a pianoforte to deaden vibrations; or as in other pieces of mechanism to check some action at a particular time."
"A young person  either male or female of noble or gentle extraction; as Damsel Pepin; Damsel Richard Prince of Wales."
"A small oval plum of a blue color  the fruit of a variety of the Prunus domestica; -- called also damask plum."
"A title of honor equivalent to master  or sir."
"A water wheel having a vertical axis  and an inner and outer tapering shell between which are vanes or floats attached usually to both shells but sometimes only to one."

"To move with measured steps  or to a musical accompaniment; to go through either alone or in company with others with a regulated succession of movements (commonly) to the sound of music; to trip or leap rhythmically."
"One who dances or who practices dancing."
"One of a breed of small terriers; -- called also Dandie Dinmont."
"To cause to resemble a dandy; to make dandyish."
"To move up and down on one's knee or in one's arms  in affectionate play as an infant."
"One who affects special finery or gives undue attention to dress; a fop; a coxcomb."
"A native  or a naturalized inhabitant of Denmark."
"To hang loosely  or with a swinging or jerking motion."
"One who dangles about or after others  especially after women; a trifler."
"A Hebrew prophet distinguished for sagacity and ripeness of judgment in youth; hence  a sagacious and upright judge."
"Belonging to the Danes  or to their language or country."
"A descendant of Dan; an Israelite of the tribe of Dan."
"Relating to  emanating from or resembling the poet Dante or his writings."
"To drop the bait gently on the surface of the water."
"A genus of diminutive Shrubs  mostly evergreen and with fragrant blossoms."
"A dark green bitter resin extracted from the mezereon (Daphne mezereum) and regarded as the essential principle of the plant."
"One who brings meat to the table; hence  in some countries the official title of the grand master or steward of the king's or a nobleman's household."
"Little and active; spruce; trim; smart; neat in dress or appearance; lively."
"One of the spots on a dappled animal."
"Marked with spots of different shades of color; spotted; variegated; as  a dapple horse."
"A plasterer's float  having two handles; -- used in smoothing ceilings etc."
"To have adequate or sufficient courage for any purpose; to be bold or venturesome; not to be afraid; to venture."
"Full of daring or of defiance; adventurous."
"A day's work; also  a fixed amount of work whether more or less than that of a day."
"A gold coin of ancient Persia  weighing usually a little more than 128 grains and bearing on one side the figure of an archer."

"Destitute  or partially destitute of light; not receiving reflecting or radiating light; wholly or partially black or of some deep shade of color; not light-colored; as a dark room; a dark day; dark cloth; dark paint; a dark complexion."
"To make dark or black; to deprive of light; to obscure; as  a darkened room."
"With imperfect light  clearness or knowledge; obscurely; dimly; blindly; uncertainly."
"To mend as a rent or hole  with interlacing stitches of yarn or thread by means of a needle; to sew together with yarn or thread."

"Any grass of the genus Lolium  esp. the Lolium temulentum (bearded darnel) the grains of which have been reputed poisonous. Other species as Lolium perenne (rye grass or ray grass) and its variety L. Italicum (Italian rye grass) are highly esteemed for pasture and for making hay."
"To make ready to fight; to array."
"Last; as  darrein continuance the last continuance."
"A pointed missile weapon  intended to be thrown by the hand; a short lance; a javelin; hence any sharp-pointed missile weapon as an arrow."
"A kind of scab or ulceration on the skin of lambs."
"One who darts  or who throw darts; that which darts."
"To pierce or shoot through; to dart repeatedly: -- frequentative of dart."
"Like the dartos; dartoic; as  dartoid tissue."
"A thin layer of peculiar contractile tissue directly beneath the skin of the scrotum."
"To become dim-sighted; to become dazed or dazzled."
"To throw with violence or haste; to cause to strike violently or hastily; -- often used with against."
"That which dashes or agitates; as  the dasher of a churn."
"The character of making ostentatious or blustering parade or show."
"A pneumatic or hydraulic cushion for a falling weight  as in the valve gear of a steam engine to prevent shock."
"Calculated to arrest attention; ostentatiously fashionable; showy."
"One who meanly shrinks from danger; an arrant coward; a poltroon."
"A carnivorous marsupial quadruped of Australia  belonging to the genus Dasyurus. There are several species."
"That may be dated; having a known or ascertainable date."

"Formerly  a part of the Roman chancery; now a separate office from which are sent graces or favors cognizable in foro externo such as appointments to benefices. The name is derived from the word datum given or dated (with the indications of the time and place of granting the gift or favor)."
"An officer in the pope's court  having charge of the Dataria."
"The fruit of the date palm; also  the date palm itself."
"Noting the case of a noun which expresses the remoter object  and is generally indicated in English by to or for with the objective."
"Something given or admitted; a fact or principle granted; that upon which an inference or an argument is based; -- used chiefly in the plural."
"A genus of solanaceous plants  with large funnel-shaped flowers and a four-celled capsular fruit."
"To smear with soft  adhesive matter as pitch slime mud etc.; to plaster; to bedaub; to besmear."
"One who  or that which daubs; especially a coarse unskillful painter."
"See Dawk  v. t. to cut or gush."
"A variant of Dan  a title of honor."
"The title of the eldest son of the king of France  and heir to the crown. Since the revolution of 1830 the title has been discontinued."
"The striped quagga  or Burchell's zebra of South Africa (Asinus Burchellii); -- called also peechi or peetsi."
"Of or pertaining to David  the king and psalmist of Israel or to his family."
"A spar formerly used on board of ships  as a crane to hoist the flukes of the anchor to the top of the bow without injuring the sides of the ship; -- called also the fish davit."
"A rare metallic element found in platinum ore. It is a white malleable substance. Symbol Da. Atomic weight 154."
"A European bird of the Crow family (Corvus monedula)  often nesting in church towers and ruins; a jackdaw."
"To waste time in trifling employment; to trifle; to saunter."
"One who wastes time in trifling employments; an idler; a trifler."
"To begin to grow light in the morning; to grow light; to break  or begin to appear; as the day dawns; the morning dawns."
"The time of light  or interval between one night and the next; the time between sunrise and sunset or from dawn to darkness; hence the light; sunshine."
"A journal of accounts; a primary record book in which are recorded the debts and credits  or accounts of the day in their order and from which they are transferred to the journal."

"A neuropterous insect of the genus Ephemera and related genera  of many species and inhabiting fresh water in the larval state; the ephemeral fly; -- so called because it commonly lives but one day in the winged or adult state. See Ephemeral fly under Ephemeral."
"A kind of incubus which occurs during wakefulness  attended by the peculiar pressure on the chest which characterizes nightmare."
"The time during which there is daylight  as distinguished from the night."
"To stupefy with excess of light; with a blow  with cold or with fear; to confuse; to benumb."
"To overpower with light; to confuse the sight of by brilliance of light."

"An officer in Christian churches appointed to perform certain subordinate duties varying in different communions. In the Roman Catholic and Episcopal churches  a person admitted to the lowest order in the ministry subordinate to the bishops and priests. In Presbyterian churches he is subordinate to the minister and elders and has charge of certain duties connected with the communion service and the care of the poor. In Congregational churches he is subordinate to the pastor and has duties as in the Presbyterian church."

"Deprived of life; -- opposed to alive and living; reduced to that state of a being in which the organs of motion and life have irrevocably ceased to perform their functions; as  a dead tree; a dead man."
"To make as dead; to impair in vigor  force activity or sensation; to lessen the force or acuteness of; to blunt; as to deaden the natural powers or feelings; to deaden a sound."
"Capable of causing death; mortal; fatal; destructive; certain or likely to cause death; as  a deadly blow or wound."
"The substances which inclose the ore on every side."
"Wanting the sense of hearing  either wholly or in part; unable to perceive sounds; hard of hearing; as a deaf man."
"To make deaf; to deprive of the power of hearing; to render incapable of perceiving sounds distinctly."
"A part or portion; a share; hence  an indefinite quantity degree or extent degree or extent; as a deal of time and trouble; a deal of cold."
"One who deals; one who has to do  or has concern with others; esp. a trader a trafficker a shopkeeper a broker or a merchant; as a dealer in dry goods; a dealer in stocks; a retail dealer."
"A dignitary or presiding officer in certain ecclesiastical and lay bodies; esp.  an ecclesiastical dignitary subordinate to a bishop."
"The office or the revenue of a dean. See the Note under Benefice  n. 3."
"Bearing a high price; high-priced; costly; expensive."
"In a dear manner; with affection; heartily; earnestly; as  to love one dearly."
"Scarcity which renders dear; want; lack; specifically  lack of food on account of failure of crops; famine."
"The cessation of all vital phenomena without capability of resuscitation  either in animals or plants."
"To stun or stupefy with noise; to deafen."
"A breaking or bursting forth; a violent rush or flood of waters which breaks down opposing barriers  and hurls forward and disperses blocks of stone and other debris."
"To cut off from entrance  as if by a bar or barrier; to preclude; to hinder from approach entry or enjoyment; to shut out or exclude; to deny or refuse; -- with from and sometimes with of."
"To go ashore from a ship or boat; to disembark; to put ashore."

"To reduce from a higher to a lower state or grade of worth  dignity purity station etc.; to degrade; to lower; to deteriorate; to abase; as to debase the character by crime; to debase the mind by frivolity; to debase style by vulgar words."
"To engage in combat for; to strive for."
"One who debates; one given to argument; a disputant; a controvertist."

"To lead away from purity or excellence; to corrupt in character or principles; to mar; to vitiate; to pollute; to seduce; as  to debauch one's self by intemperance; to debauch a woman; to debauch an army."
"A kind of woolen or mixed dress goods."
"A debt; an entry on the debtor (Dr.) side of an account; -- mostly used adjectively; as  the debit side of an account."
"The cavity from which the earth for parapets  etc. (remblai) is taken."
"To march out from a wood  defile or other confined spot into open ground; to issue."
"Broken and detached fragments  taken collectively; especially fragments detached from a rock or mountain and piled up at the base."
"That which is due from one person to another  whether money goods or services; that which one person is bound to pay to another or to perform for his benefit; thing owed; obligation; liability."
"One to whom a debt is due; creditor; -- correlative to debtor."
"One who owes a debt; one who is indebted; -- correlative to creditor."
"A beginning or first attempt; hence  a first appearance before the public as of an actor or public speaker."
"A group or division of ten; esp.  a period of ten years; a decennium; as a decade of years or days; a decade of soldiers; the second decade of Livy."
"A plane figure having ten sides and ten angles; any figure having ten angles. A regular decagon is one that has all its sides and angles equal."
"To break up a camp; to move away from a camping ground  usually by night or secretly."
"A liquid hydrocarbon  C10H22 of the paraffin series including several isomeric modifications."
"Used of the side of the choir on which the dean's stall is placed; decanal; -- correlative to cantoris; as  the decanal or decani side."
"To pour off gently  as liquor so as not to disturb the sediment; or to pour from one vessel into another; as to decant wine."
"A crustacean with ten feet or legs  as a crab; one of the Decapoda. Also used adjectively."

"To pass gradually from a sound  prosperous or perfect state to one of imperfection adversity or dissolution; to waste away; to decline; to fail; to become weak corrupt or disintegrated; to rot; to perish; as a tree decays; fortunes decay; hopes decay."
"Departure  especially departure from this life; death."

"An attempt or disposition to deceive or lead into error; any declaration  artifice or practice which misleads another or causes him to believe what is false; a contrivance to entrap; deception; a wily device; fraud."
"To lead into error; to cause to believe what is false  or disbelieve what is true; to impose upon; to mislead; to cheat; to disappoint; to delude; to insnare."

"The quality or state of being decent  suitable or becoming in words or behavior; propriety of form in social intercourse in actions or in discourse; proper formality; becoming ceremony; seemliness; hence freedom from obscenity or indecorum; modesty."
"One of the higher hydrocarbons  C10H20 of the ethylene series."
"Suitable in words  behavior dress or ceremony; becoming; fit; decorous; proper; seemly; as decent conduct; decent language."
"To pluck off; to crop; to gather."
"To free from a charm; to disenchant."
"The inner layer of the wall of the uterus  which envelops the embryo forms a part of the placenta and is discharged with it."
"An aspect or position of two planets  when they are distant from each other a tenth part of the zodiac or 36�."
"Of or pertaining to decimals; numbered or proceeding by tens; having a tenfold increase or decrease  each unit being ten times the unit next smaller; as decimal notation; a decimal coinage."
"A French coin  the tenth part of a franc equal to about two cents."
"One of the higher hydrocarbons  C10H15 of the acetylene series; -- called also decenylene."
"One who  or that which decks or adorns; a coverer; as a table decker."

"A separate thin wooden frame used to form the border of a hand mold  or a curb of India rubber or other material which rests on and forms the edge of the mold in a paper machine and determines the width of the paper."

"To speak rhetorically; to make a formal speech or oration; to harangue; specifically  to recite a speech poem etc. in public as a rhetorical exercise; to practice public speaking; as the students declaim twice a week."
"To make clear; to free from obscurity."
"To bend  or lean downward; to take a downward direction; to bend over or hang down as from weakness weariness despondency etc.; to condescend."
"To prepare by boiling; to digest in hot or boiling water; to extract the strength or flavor of by boiling; to make an infusion of."

"Propriety of manner or conduct; grace arising from suitableness of speech and behavior to one's own character  or to the place and occasion; decency of conduct; seemliness; that which is seemly or suitable."
"To lead into danger by artifice; to lure into a net or snare; to entrap; to insnare; to allure; to entice; as  to decoy troops into an ambush; to decoy ducks into a net."

"An order from one having authority  deciding what is to be done by a subordinate; also a determination by one having power deciding what is to be done or to take place; edict law; authoritative ru// decision."
"The final judgment of the Court of Session  or of an inferior court by which the question at issue is decided."
"A crying down; a clamorous censure; condemnation by censure."
"To deprive of a crown; to discrown."
"To cry down; to censure as faulty  mean or worthless; to clamor against; to blame clamorously; to discredit; to disparage."
"Large; chief; -- applied to an extraordinary billow  supposed by some to be every tenth in order. [R.] Also used substantively."
"A set or squad of ten men under a decurion."
"A hydrocarbon radical  C10H21 never existing alone but regarded as the characteristic constituent of a number of compounds of the paraffin series."
"Allied to  or containing the radical decyl."
"A division  at one end of a tennis court for spectators."
"A writ to commission private persons to do some act in place of a judge  as to examine a witness etc."
"Full of deeds or exploits; active; stirring."
"To decide; to judge; to sentence; to condemn."

"Extending far below the surface; of great perpendicular dimension (measured from the surface downward  and distinguished from high which is measured upward); far to the bottom; having a certain depth; as a deep sea."
"To make deep or deeper; to increase the depth of; to sink lower; as  to deepen a well or a channel."
"At or to a great depth; far below the surface; as  to sink deeply."
"An invocation of  or address to the Supreme Being."

"To destroy or mar the face or external appearance of; to disfigure; to injure  spoil or mar by effacing or obliterating important features or portions of; as to deface a monument; to deface an edifice; to deface writing; to deface a note deed or bond; to deface a record."
"One who  or that which defaces or disfigures."
"To harm or destroy the good fame or reputation of; to disgrace; especially  to speak evil of maliciously; to dishonor by slanderous reports; to calumniate; to asperse."
"One who defames; a slanderer; a detractor; a calumniator."
"A failing or failure; omission of that which ought to be done; neglect to do what duty or law requires; as  this evil has happened through the governor's default."
"Want or absence of something necessary for completeness or perfection; deficiency; -- opposed to superfluity."
"To ward or fend off; to drive back or away; to repel."
"To put off; to postpone to a future time; to delay the execution of; to delay; to withhold."
"Full of defiance; bold; insolent; as  a defiant spirit or act."
"Deficiency in amount or quality; a falling short; lack; as  a deficit in taxes revenue etc."
"One who dares and defies; a contemner; as  a defier of the laws."
"To march off in a line  file by file; to file off."
"One who defiles; one who corrupts or violates; that which pollutes."
"To fix the bounds of; to bring to a termination; to end."
"To cause to turn aside; to bend; as  rays of light are often deflected."
"To keep from the rightful owner; to withhold wrongfully the possession of  as of lands or a freehold."
"To spoil the form of; to mar in form; to misshape; to disfigure."

"To deprive of some right  interest or property by a deceitful device; to withhold from wrongfully; to injure by embezzlement; to cheat; to overreach; as to defraud a servant or a creditor or the state; -- with of before the thing taken or withheld."
"To pay or discharge; to serve in payment of; to provide for  as a charge debt expenses costs etc."
"Apt; fit; dexterous; clever; handy; spruce; neat."
"Having finished the course of life; dead; deceased."
"To renounce or dissolve all bonds of affiance  faith or obligation with; to reject refuse or renounce."
"To reduce from a higher to a lower rank or degree; to lower in rank; to deprive of office or dignity; to strip of honors; as  to degrade a nobleman or a general officer."
"A small South American rodent (Octodon Cumingii)  of the family Octodontidae."
"To deprive of horns; to prevent the growth of the horns of (cattle) by burning their ends soon after they start. See Dishorn."
"Out of; without; foreign to; out of the agreement  record will or other instrument."
"To urge to abstain or refrain; to dissuade."
"The act of killing a being of a divine nature; particularly  the putting to death of Jesus Christ."
"Direct; proving directly; -- applied to reasoning  and opposed to elenchtic or refutative."
"Honored or worshiped as a deity; treated with supreme regard; godlike."
"To make a god of; to exalt to the rank of a deity; to enroll among the deities; to apotheosize; as  Julius Caesar was deified."
"To esteem worthy; to consider worth notice; -- opposed to disdain."
"The doctrine or creed of a deist; the belief or system of those who acknowledge the existence of one God  but deny revelation."
"One who believes in the existence of a God  but denies revealed religion; a freethinker."
"The collection of attributes which make up the nature of a god; divinity; godhead; as  the deity of the Supreme Being is seen in his works."
"Excrements; as  the dejecta of the sick."
"By right; of right; by law; -- often opposed to de facto."
"A kind of fabric for women's dresses."
"To pass down by inheritance; to lapse."
"A putting off or deferring; procrastination; lingering inactivity; stop; detention; hindrance."
"Erase; remove; -- a direction to cancel something which has been put in type; usually expressed by a peculiar form of d  thus: /."
"Capable of being blotted out or erased."
"Things to be erased or blotted out."
"To blot out; to erase; to expunge; to dele; to omit."
"A mine; a quarry; a pit dug; a ditch."
"An offense or transgression against law; (Scots Law) an offense of a lesser degree; a misdemeanor."
"A high degree of gratification of mind; a high- wrought state of pleasurable feeling; lively pleasure; extreme satisfaction; joy."
"The mistress of Samson  who betrayed him (Judges xvi.); hence a harlot; a temptress."
"To fix the limits of; to demarcate; to bound."

"To set free from restraint; to set at liberty; to release; to liberate  as from control; to give up; to free; to save; to rescue from evil actual or feared; -- often with from or out of; as to deliver one from captivity or from fear of death."
"A special breed of the dromedary used for rapid traveling; the swift camel; -- called also herire  and maharik."
"Of or relating to Delphi  or to the famous oracle of that place."

"A tract of land shaped like the letter delta (/)  especially when the land is alluvial and inclosed between two or more mouths of a river; as the delta of the Ganges of the Nile or of the Mississippi."
"To lead from truth or into error; to mislead the mind or judgment of; to beguile; to impose on; to dupe; to make a fool of."
"One who deludes; a deceiver; an impostor."
"A washing away; an overflowing of the land by water; an inundation; a flood; specifically  The Deluge the great flood in the days of Noah (Gen. vii.)."
"To dig; to open (the ground) as with a spade."
"One who digs  as with a spade."
"To ask or call for with authority; to claim or seek from  as by authority or right; to claim as something due; to call for urgently or peremptorily; as to demand a debt; to demand obedience."
"A territorial subdivision of Attica (also of modern Greece)  corresponding to a township."
"Dementia; loss of mental powers. See Insanity."
"To deprive of reason; to make mad."
"To plunge down into; to sink; to immerse."
"That which one merits or deserves  either of good or ill; desert."
"A lord's chief manor place  with that part of the lands belonging thereto which has not been granted out in tenancy; a house and the land adjoining kept for the proprietor's own use."
"A half god  or an inferior deity; a fabulous hero the offspring of a deity and a mortal."
"A woman of doubtful reputation or suspected character; an adventuress."
"Transmission by formal act or conveyance to an heir or successor; transference; especially  the transfer or transmission of the crown or royal authority to a successor."
"A spirit  or immaterial being holding a middle place between men and deities in pagan mythology."
"Of or pertaining to a demon or to demons; demoniac."
"Of or pertaining to the people; popular; common."
"To soothe; to mollify; to pacify; to soften."
"Of sober or serious mien; composed and decorous in bearing; of modest look; staid; grave."
"A printing and a writing paper of particular sizes. See under Paper."
"A small cavern or hollow place in the side of a hill  or among rocks; esp. a cave used by a wild beast for shelter or concealment; as a lion's den; a den of robbers."
"Containing ten; tenfold; proceeding by tens; as  the denary or decimal scale."

"A specific epidemic disease attended with high fever  cutaneous eruption and severe pains in the head and limbs resembling those of rheumatism; -- called also breakbone fever. It occurs in India Egypt the West Indies etc. is of short duration and rarely fatal."
"The act of gainsaying  refusing or disowning; negation; -- the contrary of affirmation."
"One who denies; as  a denier of a fact or of the faith or of Christ."
"A coarse cotton drilling used for overalls  etc."
"To make a denizen; to confer the rights of citizenship upon; to naturalize."
"A light  open two-wheeled carriage for one horse; a kind of gig."
"To mark out plainly; to signify by a visible sign; to serve as the sign or name of; to indicate; to point out; as  the hands of the clock denote the hour."
"Having the constituent parts massed or crowded together; close; compact; thick; containing much matter in a small space; heavy; opaque; as  a dense crowd; a dense forest; a dense fog."
"The quality of being dense  close or thick; compactness; -- opposed to rarity."
"Of or pertaining to the teeth or to dentistry; as  dental surgery."
"An edible European marine fish (Sparus dentex  or Dentex vulgaris) of the family Percidae."
"A small square block or projection in cornices  a number of which are ranged in an ornamental band; -- used particularly in the Ionic Corinthian and Composite orders."
"A small tooth  like that of a saw."
"The dense calcified substance of which teeth are largely composed. It contains less animal matter than bone  and in the teeth of man is situated beneath the enamel."
"One whose business it is to clean  extract or repair natural teeth and to make and insert artificial ones; a dental surgeon."
"An artificial tooth  block or set of teeth."
"To divest of all covering; to make bare or naked; to strip; to divest; as  to denude one of clothing or lands."
"To declare not to be true; to gainsay; to contradict; -- opposed to affirm  allow or admit."

"A personal chattel which had caused the death of a person  and for that reason was given to God that is forfeited to the crown to be applied to pious uses and distributed in alms by the high almoner. Thus if a cart ran over a man and killed him it was forfeited as a deodand."
"A kind of cedar (Cedrus Deodara)  growing in India highly valued for its size and beauty as well as for its timber and also grown in England as an ornamental tree."
"To hang down; to be sustained by being fastened or attached to something above."
"To empty or unload  as the vessels of human system by bloodletting or by medicine."
"To feel or to express deep and poignant grief for; to bewail; to lament; to mourn; to sorrow over."

"To open out; to unfold; to spread out (a body of troops) in such a way that they shall display a wider front and less depth; -- the reverse of ploy; as  to deploy a column of troops into line of battle."
"To strip or pluck off the feather of; to deprive of of plumage."
"To lay  as a stake; to wager."
"To transport; to carry away; to exile; to send into banishment."
"The act of deposing from office; a removal from the throne."
"To lay down; to divest one's self of; to lay aside."
"One who deposes or degrades from office."
"To lay down; to place; to put; to let fall or throw down (as sediment); as  a crocodile deposits her eggs in the sand; the waters deposited a rich alluvium."
"A place of deposit for the storing of goods; a warehouse; a storehouse."
"To speak ill of; to depreciate; to malign; to revile."
"To press down; to cause to sink; to let fall; to lower; as  to depress the muzzle of a gun; to depress the eyes."
"To take away; to put an end; to destroy."
"The quality of being deep; deepness; perpendicular measurement downward from the surface  or horizontal measurement backward from the front; as the depth of a river; the depth of a body of troops."
"To appoint as deputy or agent; to commission to act in one's place; to delegate."

"One appointed as the substitute of another  and empowered to act for him in his name or his behalf; a substitute in office; a lieutenant; a representative; a delegate; a vicegerent; as the deputy of a prince of a sheriff of a township etc."
"To prove or to refute by proof; to clear (one's self)."
"To cause to run off from the rails of a railroad  as a locomotive."

"To put out of place  order or rank; to disturb the proper arrangement or order of; to throw into disorder confusion or embarrassment; to disorder; to disarrange; as to derange the plans of a commander or the affairs of a nation."
"A race for three-old horses  run annually at Epsom (near London) for the Derby stakes. It was instituted by the 12th Earl of Derby in 1780."
"To laugh at with contempt; to laugh to scorn; to turn to ridicule or make sport of; to mock; to scoff at."
"One who derides  or laughs at another in contempt; a mocker; a scoffer."
"To turn the course of  as water; to divert and distribute into subordinate channels; to diffuse; to communicate; to transmit; -- followed by to into on upon."
"Pertaining to the integument or skin of animals; dermic; as  the dermal secretions."
"The deep sensitive layer of the skin beneath the scarfskin or epidermis; -- called also true skin  derm derma corium cutis and enderon. See Skin and Illust. in Appendix."
"A mast  spar or tall frame supported at the top by stays or guys with suitable tackle for hoisting heavy weights as stones in building."
"A Turkish or Persian monk  especially one who professes extreme poverty and leads an austere life."
"Originally  a double song; a melody or counterpoint sung above the plain song of the tenor; a variation of an air; a variation by ornament of the main subject or plain song."
"To pass from a higher to a lower place; to move downwards; to come or go down in any way  as by falling flowing walking etc.; to plunge; to fall; to incline downward; -- the opposite of ascend."
"The act of descending  or passing downward; change of place from higher to lower."
"To spy out or discover by the eye  as objects distant or obscure; to espy; to recognize; to discern; to discover."
"That which is deserved; the reward or the punishment justly due; claim to recompense  usually in a good sense; right to reward; merit."
"To earn by service; to be worthy of (something due  either good or evil); to merit; to be entitled to; as the laborer deserves his wages; a work of value deserves praise."
"To draw preliminary outline or main features of; to sketch for a pattern or model; to delineate; to trace out; to draw."
"To long for; to wish for earnestly; to covet."
"To cease to proceed or act; to stop; to forbear; -- often with from."
"A table  frame or case usually with sloping top but often with flat top for the use writers and readers. It often has a drawer or repository underneath."
"An amphibious  insectivorous mammal found in Russia (Myogale moschata). It is allied to the moles but is called muskrat by some English writers."
"Same as Stilbite. It commonly occurs in bundles or tufts of crystals."
"Resembling  or having the characteristics of a ligament; ligamentous."
"To be hopeless; to have no hope; to give up all hope or expectation; -- often with of."
"To look down upon with disfavor or contempt; to contemn; to scorn; to disdain; to have a low opinion or contemptuous dislike of."
"Malice; malignity; spite; malicious anger; contemptuous hate."
"To strip  as of clothing; to divest or unclothe."
"To give up  the will courage or spirit; to be thoroughly disheartened; to lose all courage; to become dispirited or depressed; to take an unhopeful view."
"A master; a lord; especially  an absolute or irresponsible ruler or sovereign."
"A service of pastry  fruits or sweetmeats at the close of a feast or entertainment; pastry fruits etc. forming the last course at dinner."

"To determine the future condition or application of; to set apart by design for a future use or purpose; to fix  as by destiny or by an authoritative decree; to doom; to ordain or preordain; to appoint; -- often with the remoter object preceded by to or for."
"That to which any person or thing is destined; predetermined state; condition foreordained by the Divine or by human will; fate; lot; doom."
"To unbuild; to pull or tear down; to separate virulently into its constituent parts; to break up the structure and organic existence of; to demolish."
"To part; to separate or disunite; to disengage; -- the opposite of attach; as  to detach the coats of a bulbous root from each other; to detach a man from a leader or from a party."
"A minute portion; one of the small parts; a particular; an item; -- used chiefly in the plural; as  the details of a scheme or transaction."
"To keep back or from; to withhold."
"That which locks or unlocks a movement; a catch  pawl or dog; especially in clockwork the catch which locks and unlocks the wheelwork in striking."
"To prevent by fear; hence  to hinder or prevent from action by fear of consequences or difficulty risk etc."
"To cleanse; to purge away  as foul or offending matter from the body or from an ulcer."
"To witness against; to denounce; to condemn."
"To turn form the original or plain meaning; to pervert; to wrest."
"A turning; a circuitous route; a deviation from a direct course; as  the detours of the Mississippi."
"To alight  or to cause to alight from a railway train."
"To thrust down or out; to push down with force."
"A present of books given to a meritorious undergraduate student as a prize."
"Two; a card or a die with two spots; as  the deuce of hearts."
"A genus of shrubs with pretty white flowers  much cultivated."
"A god; a deity; a divine being; an idol; a king."
"A deity; a divine being; a good spirit; an idol."

"To free from that which infolds or envelops; to unfold; to lay open by degrees or in detail; to make visible or known; to disclose; to produce or give forth; as  to develop theories; a motor that develops 100 horse power."
"To go out of the way; to turn aside from a course or a method; to stray or go astray; to err; to digress; to diverge; to vary."
"That which is devised  or formed by design; a contrivance; an invention; a project; a scheme; often a scheme to deceive; a stratagem; an artifice."
"The Evil One; Satan  represented as the tempter and spiritual of mankind."
"Conduct suitable to the devil; extreme wickedness; deviltry."
"Out of a straight line; winding; varying from directness; as  a devious path or way."

"To form in the mind by new combinations of ideas  new applications of principles or new arrangement of parts; to formulate by thought; to contrive; to excogitate; to invent; to plan; to scheme; as to devise an engine a new mode of writing a plan of defense or an argument."
"One to whom a devise is made  or real estate given by will."
"One who devises  or gives real estate by will; a testator; -- correlative to devisee."
"Duty; service owed; hence  due act of civility or respect; -- now usually in the plural; as they paid their devoirs to the ladies."
"To roll onward or downward; to pass on."

"One of a breed of hardy cattle originating in the country of Devon  England. Those of pure blood have a deep red color. The small longhorned variety called North Devons is distinguished by the superiority of its working oxen."
"To appropriate by vow; to set apart or dedicate by a solemn act; to consecrate; also  to consign over; to doom; to evil; to devote one to destruction; the city was devoted to the flames."
"One who is wholly devoted; esp.  one given wholly to religion; one who is superstitiously given to religious duties and ceremonies; a bigot."
"To eat up with greediness; to consume ravenously; to feast upon like a wild beast or a glutton; to prey upon."
"Devoted to religion or to religious feelings and duties; absorbed in religious exercises; given to devotion; pious; reverent; religious."
"Moisture from the atmosphere condensed by cool bodies upon their surfaces  particularly at night."
"In any animal  esp. of the Herbivora a rudimentary claw or small hoof not reaching the ground."
"The falling of dew; the time when dew begins to fall."
"The pendulous skin under the neck of an ox  which laps or licks the dew in grazing."
"To ret or rot by the process called dewretting."
"To rot  as flax or hemp by exposure to rain dew and sun. See Dewretting."
"Pertaining to dew; resembling  consisting of or moist with dew."
"Pertaining to  or situated on the right hand; right as opposed to sinister or left."
"Right  as opposed to sinistral or left."

"A translucent  gummy amorphous substance nearly tasteless and odorless used as a substitute for gum for sizing etc. and obtained from starch by the action of heat acids or diastase. It is of somewhat variable composition containing several carbohydrates which change easily to their respective varieties of sugar. It is so named from its rotating the plane of polarization to the right; -- called also British gum Alsace gum
"A servant who has charge of the dairy; a dairymaid."
"A fierce  wild dog (Canis Dukhunensis) found in the mountains of India. It is remarkable for its propensity to hunt the tiger and other wild animals in packs."
"A coasting vessel of Arabia  East Africa and the Indian Ocean. It has generally but one mast and a lateen sail."

"A basic  dark-colored holocrystalline igneous rock consisting essentially of a triclinic feldspar and pyroxene with magnetic iron; -- often limited to rocks pretertiary in age. It includes part of what was early called greenstone."
"Devilry; sorcery or incantation; a diabolical deed; mischief."
"Divalent; -- said of a base or radical as capable of saturating two acid monad radicals or a dibasic acid. Cf. Dibasic  a. and Biacid."
"Originally  an ornamental head band or fillet worn by Eastern monarchs as a badge of royalty; hence (later) also a crown in general."
"A complete course or vibration; time of vibration  as of a pendulum."
"A figure or drawing made to illustrate a statement  or facilitate a demonstration; a plan."

"An instrument  formerly much used for showing the time of day from the shadow of a style or gnomon on a graduated arc or surface; esp. a sundial; but there are lunar and astral dials. The style or gnomon is usually parallel to the earth's axis but the dial plate may be either horizontal or vertical."
"Means or mode of expressing thoughts; language; tongue; form of speech."
"A maker of dials; one skilled in dialing."
"Meeting and intersecting  as lines; not parallel; -- opposed to parallel."
"A volatile  pungent liquid hydrocarbon C6H10 consisting of two allyl radicals and belonging to the acetylene series."
"To separate  prepare or obtain by dialysis or osmose; to pass through an animal membrane; to subject to dialysis."
"Any compound containing two amido groups united with one or more acid or negative radicals  -- as distinguished from a diamine. Cf. Amido acid under Amido and Acid amide under Amide."
"A compound containing two amido groups united with one or more basic or positive radicals  -- as contrasted with a diamide."
"A precious stone or gem excelling in brilliancy and beautiful play of prismatic colors  and remarkable for extreme hardness."
"The daughter of Jupiter and Latona; a virgin goddess who presided over hunting  chastity and marriage; -- identified with the Greek goddess Artemis."
"Powdered aromatic herbs  sometimes made into little balls and strung together."
"Any textile fabric (esp. linen or cotton toweling) woven in diaper pattern. See 2."
"A form of government in which the supreme power is vested in two persons."
"A register of daily events or transactions; a daily record; a journal; a blank book dated for the record of daily memoranda; as  a diary of the weather; a physician's diary."

"A double star; -- applied to the nucleus of a cell  when during cell division the loops of the nuclear network separate into two groups preparatory to the formation of two daughter nuclei. See Karyokinesis."

"One of the Diatomaceae  a family of minute unicellular Algae having a siliceous covering of great delicacy each individual multiplying by spontaneous division. By some authors diatoms are called Bacillariae but this word is not in general use."
"Having two acid hydrogen atoms capable of replacement by basic atoms or radicals  in forming salts; bibasic; -- said of acids as oxalic or sulphuric acids. Cf. Diacid Bibasic."
"A pointed implement used to make holes in the ground in which no set out plants or to plant seeds."
"One who  or that which dibbles or makes holes in the ground for seed."
"A sweet preparation or treacle of grape juice  much used in the East."
"A liquid hydrocarbon  C8H18 of the marsh-gas series being one of several octanes and consisting of two butyl radicals. Cf. Octane."
"A functionary in ancient Athens answering nearly to the modern juryman."
"Small cubes used in gaming or in determining by chance; also  the game played with dice. See Die n."
"A box from which dice are thrown in gaming."
"A player at dice; a dice player; a gamester."
"The number or quantity of ten  particularly ten hides or skins; a dakir; as a dicker of gloves."
"A seat behind a carriage  for a servant."
"To tell or utter so that another may write down; to inspire; to compose; as  to dictate a letter to an amanuensis."

"Choice of words for the expression of ideas; the construction  disposition and application of words in discourse with regard to clearness accuracy variety etc.; mode of expression; language; as the diction of Chaucer's poems."
"An authoritative statement; a dogmatic saying; an apothegm."
"To totter  as a child in walking."
"Like or pertaining to the genus Didus  or the dodo."
"A shrewd trick; an antic; a caper."
"The curve which on a given surface and with a given perimeter contains the greatest area."
"A small interval  less than any in actual practice but used in the mathematical calculation of intervals."
"Course of living or nourishment; what is eaten and drunk habitually; food; victuals; fare."
"Pertaining to diet  or to the rules of diet."
"One who diets; one who prescribes  or who partakes of food according to hygienic rules."
"A subordinate or local assembly; a diet of inferior rank."
"To be or stand apart; to disagree; to be unlike; to be distinguished; -- with from."
"Irregular in form; -- opposed to uniform; anomalous; hence  unlike; dissimilar; as to difform corolla the parts of which do not correspond in size or proportion; difform leaves."
"To pour out and cause to spread  as a fluid; to cause to flow on all sides; to send out or extend in all directions; to spread; to circulate; to disseminate; to scatter; as to diffuse information."
"To turn up  or delve in (earth) with a spade or a hoe; to open loosen or break up (the soil) with a spade or other sharp instrument; to pierce open or loosen as if with a spade."
"A letter (/  /) of the Greek alphabet which early fell into disuse."
"Act  or state of being twice married; deuterogamy."
"A division of Trematoda in which alternate generations occur  the immediate young not resembling their parents."
"To distribute or arrange methodically; to work over and classify; to reduce to portions for ready use or application; as  to digest the laws etc."
"A degraded tribe of California Indians; -- so called from their practice of digging roots for food."
"One of the terminal divisions of a limb appendage; a finger or toe."
"Of or performance to the fingers  or to digits; done with the fingers; as digital compression; digital examination."
"A projecting face like the triglyph  but having only two channels or grooves sunk in it."
"To invest with dignity or honor; to make illustrious; to give distinction to; to exalt in rank; to honor."
"The state of being worthy or honorable; elevation of mind or character; true worth; excellence."
"Two signs or characters combined to express a single articulated sound; as ea in head  or th in bath."
"To step or turn aside; to deviate; to swerve; especially  to turn aside from the main subject of attention or course of argument in writing or speaking."
"A Linnaean order of plants having two styles."
"A kind of food  made from the almondlike seeds of the Irvingia Barteri much used by natives of the west coast of Africa; -- called also dika bread."
"A ditch; a channel for water made by digging."
"To expand; to distend; to enlarge or extend in all directions; to swell; -- opposed to contract; as  the air dilates the lungs; air is dilated by increase of heat."
"One who  or that which dilates expands o r enlarges."
"One who  or that which widens or expands."
"An argument which presents an antagonist with two or more alternatives  but is equally conclusive against him whichever alternative he chooses."
"An herb (Peucedanum graveolens)  the seeds of which are moderately warming pungent and aromatic and were formerly used as a soothing medicine for children; -- called also dillseed."
"An ambiguous speech; a figure in which a word is used an equivocal sense."
"Diluting; making thinner or weaker by admixture  esp. of water."
"To make thinner or more liquid by admixture with something; to thin and dissolve by mixing."
"One who  or that which dilutes or makes thin more liquid or weaker."
"Not bright or distinct; wanting luminousness or clearness; obscure in luster or sound; dusky; darkish; obscure; indistinct; overcast; tarnished."
"A silver coin of the United States  of the value of ten cents; the tenth of a dollar."
"A division of Coleoptera  having two joints to the tarsi."
"A cotton fabric employed for hangings and furniture coverings  and formerly used for women's under-garments. It is of many patterns both plain and twilled and occasionally is printed in colors."
"In a dim or obscure manner; not brightly or clearly; with imperfect sight."
"The state or quality / being dim; lack of brightness  clearness or distinctness; dullness; obscurity."
"Either one of the two forms of a dimorphous substance; as  calcite and aragonite are dimorphs."
"A slight natural depression or indentation on the surface of some part of the body  esp. on the cheek or chin."
"Full of dimples  or small depressions; dimpled; as the dimply pool."
"Loud  confused harsh noise; a loud continuous rattling or clanging sound; clamor; roar."
"A petty money of accounts of Persia."
"To eat the principal regular meal of the day; to take dinner."
"A kind of boat used in the East Indies."
"A narrow dale; a small dell; a small  secluded and embowered valley."
"A wild dog found in Australia  but supposed to have introduced at a very early period. It has a wolflike face bushy tail and a reddish brown color."
"A wether sheep between one and two years old."
"The principal meal of the day  eaten by most people about midday but by many (especially in cities) at a later hour."
"The circuit or extent of a bishop's jurisdiction; the district in which a bishop exercises his ecclesiastical authority."

"A genus of spinose  plectognath fishes having the teeth of each jaw united into a single beaklike plate. They are able to inflate the body by taking in air or water and hence are called globefishes swellfishes etc. Called also porcupine fishes and sea hedgehogs."
"Like or pertaining to the genus Diodon."
"A Linnaean class of plants having the stamens and pistils on different plants."
"An optical instrument  invented by Hipparchus for taking altitudes leveling etc."
"A unit employed by oculists in numbering glasses according to the metric system; a refractive power equal to that of a glass whose principal focal distance is one meter."

"A mode of scenic representation  invented by Daguerre and Bouton in which a painting is seen from a distance through a large opening. By a combination of transparent and opaque painting and of transmitted and reflected light and by contrivances such as screens and shutters much diversity of scenic effect is produced."
"An igneous  crystalline in structure consisting essentially of a triclinic feldspar and hornblende. It includes part of what was called greenstone."
"A vase or drinking cup having two handles or ears."
"An oxide containing two atoms of oxygen in each molecule; binoxide."
"To plunge or immerse; especially  to put for a moment into a liquid; to insert into a fluid and withdraw again."
"The soft  spongy or cancellated substance between the plates of the skull."
"A solid bounded by twenty-four similar quadrilateral faces. It is a hemihedral form of the hexoctahedron."
"A letter or writing  usually under seal conferring some privilege honor or power; a document bearing record of a degree conferred by a literary society or educational institution."
"The act or state of seeing double."

"A group of ganoid fishes  including the living genera Ceratodus and Lepidosiren which present the closest approximation to the Amphibia. The air bladder acts as a lung and the nostrils open inside the mouth. See Ceratodus and Illustration in Appendix."
"Two metrical feet taken together  or included in one measure."
"Having two poles  as a magnetic bar."
"One who  or that which dips; especially a vessel used to dip water or other liquid; a ladle."
"A serpent whose bite was fabled to produce intense thirst."

"An extensive order of insects having only two functional wings and two balancers  as the house fly mosquito etc. They have a suctorial proboscis often including two pairs of sharp organs (mandibles and maxillae) with which they pierce the skin of animals. They undergo a complete metamorphosis their larvae (called maggots) being usually without feet."
"A noun which has only two cases."
"A mineral of the scapolite group; -- so called from the double effect of fire upon it  in fusing it and rendering it phosphorescent."
"Straight; not crooked  oblique or circuitous; leading by the short or shortest way to a point or end; as a direct line; direct means."
"Dire; dreadful; terrible; calamitous; woeful; as  a direful fiend; a direful day."
"A piece of music of a mournful character  to accompany funeral rites; a funeral hymn."
"A service for the dead  in the Roman Catholic Church being the first antiphon of Matins for the dead of which Dirige is the first word; a dirge."
"A kind of dagger or poniard; -- formerly much used by the Scottish Highlander."
"Any foul of filthy substance  as excrement mud dust etc.; whatever adhering to anything renders it foul or unclean; earth; as a wagonload of dirt."
"In a dirty manner; foully; nastily; filthily; meanly; sordidly."
"Defiled with dirt; foul; nasty; filthy; not clean or pure; serving to defile; as  dirty hands; dirty water; a dirty white."
"To part  as an alliance; to sunder."
"To deprive of arms; to take away the weapons of; to deprive of the means of attack or defense; to render defenseless."

"To refuse strongly and solemnly to own or acknowledge; to deny responsibility for  approbation of and the like; to disclaim; to disown; as he was charged with embezzlement but he disavows the crime."
"To loose the bands of; to set free; to disunite; to scatter; to disperse; to break up the organization of; especially  to dismiss from military service; as to disband an army."
"To expel from the bar  or the legal profession; to deprive (an attorney barrister or counselor) of his status and privileges as such."
"To deprive of buds or shoots  as for training or economizing the vital strength of a tree."
"Pertaining to  or resembling a disk; as discal cells."
"To throw out of one's hand  as superfluous cards; to lay aside (a card or cards)."
"To yield or give up; to depart."
"To see and identify by noting a difference or differences; to note the distinctive character of; to discriminate; to distinguish."
"A genus of Branchiopoda  having a disklike shell attached by one valve which is perforated by the peduncle."
"Having the form of a disk  as those univalve shells which have the whorls in one plane so as to form a disk as the pearly nautilus."

"Want of concord or agreement; absence of unity or harmony in sentiment or action; variance leading to contention and strife; disagreement; -- applied to persons or to things  and to thoughts feelings or purposes."
"A quoit; a circular plate of some heavy material intended to be pitched or hurled as a trial of strength and skill."
"A feeling of contempt and aversion; the regarding anything as unworthy of or beneath one; scorn."
"Lack of ease; uneasiness; trouble; vexation; disquiet."
"To deprive of an edge; to blunt; to dull."
"To free from a gage or pledge; to disengage."
"To provoke disgust or strong distaste in; to cause (any one) loathing  as of the stomach; to excite aversion in; to offend the moral taste of; -- often with at with or by."
"A vessel  as a platter a plate a bowl used for serving up food at the table."
"As much as a dish holds when full."
"To deprive of horns; as  to dishorn cattle."
"To part; to disunite; to separate; to sunder."
"To regard with dislike or aversion; to disapprove; to disrelish."
"To tear limb from limb; to dismember."
"To deprive of a mast of masts; to break and carry away the masts from; as  a storm dismasted the ship."
"To eject from the maw; to disgorge."
"To disable with alarm or apprehensions; to depress the spirits or courage of; to deprive or firmness and energy through fear; to daunt; to appall; to terrify."
"A tenth; a tenth part; a tithe."
"To send away; to give leave of departure; to cause or permit to go; to put away."

"Not to obey; to neglect or refuse to obey (a superior or his commands  the laws etc.); to transgress the commands of (one in authority); to violate as an order; as refractory children disobey their parents; men disobey their Maker and the laws."
"To throw out of the proper orbit; to unsphere."

"To refuse to own or acknowledge as belonging to one's self; to disavow or deny  as connected with one's self personally; as a parent can hardly disown his child; an author will sometimes disown his writings."
"To throw (a park or inclosure); to treat (a private park) as a common."
"To part asunder; to divide; to separate; to sever; to rend; to rive or split; as  disparted air; disparted towers."
"To send off with speed; to dispatch."
"To drive away by scattering  or so to cause to vanish; to clear away; to banish; to dissipate; as to dispel a cloud vapors cares doubts illusions."
"To spend; to lay out; to expend."
"To unfold; to spread wide; to expand; to stretch out; to spread."
"To refuse to consider as pope; to depose from the popedom."
"To distribute and put in place; to arrange; to set in order; as  to dispose the ships in the form of a crescent."
"To eject from a post; to displace."
"To contend in argument; to argue against something maintained  upheld or claimed by another; to discuss; to reason; to debate; to altercate; to wrangle."
"To reduce to a lower rating or rank; to degrade."
"To divest of a robe; to undress; figuratively  to strip of covering; to divest of that which clothes or decorates; as autumn disrobes the fields of verdure."
"To tear up the roots of  or by the roots; hence to tear from a foundation; to uproot."
"To divide into separate parts; to cut in pieces; to separate and expose the parts of  as an animal or a plant for examination and to show their structure and relations; to anatomize."
"To differ in opinion; to be of unlike or contrary sentiment; to disagree; -- followed by from."
"To dismiss from service on board ship."
"Toward a distal part; on the distal side of; distally."
"The staff for holding a bunch of flax  tow or wool from which the thread is drawn in spinning by hand."
"To tinge with a different color from the natural or proper one; to stain; to discolor; to sully; to tarnish; to defile; -- used chiefly in poetry."
"Remote from the point of attachment or origin; as  the distal end of a bone or muscle"
