"A vessel with a narrow mouth  used for holding and conveying liquors. It is generally larger than a bottle and of leather or stoneware rather than of glass."

"An instrument for threshing or beating grain from the ear by hand  consisting of a wooden staff or handle at the end of which a stouter and shorter pole or club called a swipe is so hung as to swing freely."
"Consisting of flakes or of small  loose masses; lying or cleaving off in flakes or layers; flakelike."
"A freak or whim; also  a falsehood; a lie; an illusory pretext; deception; delusion."
"A stream of burning vapor or gas  emitting light and heat; darting or streaming fire; a blaze; a fire."

"A priest devoted to the service of a particular god  from whom he received a distinguishing epithet. The most honored were those of Jupiter Mars and Quirinus called respectively Flamen Dialis Flamen Martialis and Flamen Quirinalis."
"Flaming; blazing; flamelike; flame-colored; composed of flame."
"One who strolls about aimlessly; a lounger; a loafer."

"An external or internal rib  or rim for strength as the flange of an iron beam; or for a guide as the flange of a car wheel (see Car wheel.); or for attachment to another object as the flange on the end of a pipe steam cylinder etc."
"The fleshy or muscular part of the side of an animal  between the ribs and the hip. See Illust. of Beef."
"One who  or that which flanks as a skirmisher or a body of troops sent out upon the flanks of an army toguard a line of march or a fort projecting so as to command the side of an assailing body."
"A soft  nappy woolen cloth of loose texture."
"Anything broad and limber that hangs loose  or that is attached by one side or end and is easily moved; as the flap of a garment."
"To burn with an unsteady or waving flame; as  the candle flares."
"To burst or break forth with a sudden and transient flood of flame and light; as  the lighting flashes vividly; the powder flashed."
"Dazzling for a moment; making a momentary show of brilliancy; transitorily bright."
"A small bottle-shaped vessel for holding fluids; as  a flask of oil or wine."
"A long  shallow basket with two handles."
"Having an even and horizontal surface  or nearly so without prominences or depressions; level without inclination; plane."
"With the flat side  as of a sword; flatlong; in a prostrate position."
"In a flat manner; evenly; horizontally; without spirit; dully; frigidly; peremptorily; positively  plainly."
"To reduce to an even surface or one approaching evenness; to make flat; to level; to make plane."
"One who  or that which makes flat or flattens."
"To throw or spread out; to flutter; to move ostentatiously; as  a flaunting show."
"A yellow  crystalline organic base C13H12N2O obtained artificially."
"A yellow  crystalline substance obtained from anthraquinone and regarded as a hydroxyl derivative of it."
"That quality of anything which affects the smell; odor; fragrances; as  the flavor of a rose."
"A crack or breach; a gap or fissure; a defect of continuity or cohesion; as  a flaw in a knife or a vase."
"A sort of flat custard or pie."
"To scrape o/ pare  as a skin."
"Full of flaws or cracks; broken; defective; faulty."

"A plant of the genus Linum  esp. the L. usitatissimum which has a single slender stalk about a foot and a half high with blue flowers. The fiber of the bark is used for making thread and cloth called linen cambric lawn lace etc. Linseed oil is expressed from the seed."
"Made of flax; resembling flax or its fibers; of the color of flax; of a light soft straw color; fair and flowing  like flax or tow; as flaxen thread; flaxen hair."
"To skin; to strip off the skin or surface of; as  to flay an ox; to flay the green earth."
"A sharp instrument used for opening veins  lancing gums etc.; a kind of lancet."
"A simple fieldwork  consisting of two faces forming a salient angle pointing outward and open at the gorge."
"A flake; also  a lock as of wool."
"Feathered; furnished with feathers or wings; able to fly."
"To run away  as from danger or evil; to avoid in an alarmed or cowardly manner; to hasten off; -- usually with from. This is sometimes omitted making the verb transitive."
"The entire coat of wood that covers a sheep or other similar animal; also  the quantity shorn from a sheep or animal at one time."
"One who fleeces or strips unjustly  especially by trickery or fraund."
"Covered with  made of or resembling a fleece."
"To banish; to drive out; to expel."
"One who  or that which banishes or expels."
"To strip the blubber or skin from  as from a whale seal etc."
"The aggregate of the muscles  fat and other tissues which cover the framework of bones in man and other animals; especially the muscles."
"Of or pertaining to the flesh; corporeal."
"Full of  or composed of flesh; plump; corpulent; fat; gross."
"Finished at the ends with fleurs-de-lis; -- said esp. of a cross so decorated."
"The pendulous or overhanging lateral parts of the upper lip of dogs  especially prominent in hounds; -- called also chaps. See Illust. of Bloodhound."
"To bend; as  to flex the arm."
"Flexible; pliant; pliable; easily bent; plastic; tractable."
"The act of flexing or bending; a turning."
"A muscle which bends or flexes any part; as  the flexors of the arm or the hand; -- opposed to extensor."
"The act of flexing or bending; a turning or curving; flexion; hence  obsequious bowing or bending."
"To whip lightly or with a quick jerk; to flap; as  to flick a horse; to flick the dirt from boots."
"To flutter; to flap the wings without flying."
"One who flies or flees; a runaway; a fugitive."
"The act or flying; a passing through the air by the help of wings; volitation; mode or style of flying."
"Weak; feeble; limp; slight; vain; without strength or solidity; of loose and unsubstantial structure; without reason or plausibility; as  a flimsy argument excuse objection."

"To withdraw from any suffering or undertaking  from pain or danger; to fail in doing or perserving; to show signs of yielding or of suffering; to shrink; to wince; as one of the parties flinched from the combat."
"To cast  send to throw from the hand; to hurl; to dart; to emit with violence as if thrown from the hand; as to fing a stone into the pond."
"A massive  somewhat impure variety of quartz in color usually of a gray to brown or nearly black breaking with a conchoidal fracture and sharp edge. It is very hard and strikes fire with steel."
"Consisting of  composed of abounding in or resembling flint; as a flinty rock; flinty ground; a flinty heart."
"A mixture of beer  spirit etc. stirred and heated by a hot iron."
"To turn inside out  or with the leg part back over the foot as a stocking in pulling off or for putting on."
"A broad flat limb used for swimming  as those of seals sea turtles whales etc."
"To throw with a jerk or quick effort; to fling suddenly; as  they flirt water in each other's faces; he flirted a glove or a handkerchief."
"To move with celerity through the air; to fly away with a rapid motion; to dart along; to fleet; as  a bird flits away; a cloud flits along."
"The side of a hog salted and cured; a side of bacon."
"Anything which floats or rests on the surface of a fluid  as to sustain weight or to indicate the height of the surface or mark the place of something."
"A small cartridge designed for target shooting; -- sometimes called ball cap."
"The tuft of hair terminating the tail of mammals."
"A company or collection of living creatures; -- especially applied to sheep and birds  rarely to persons or (except in the plural) to cattle and other large animals; as a flock of ravenous fowl."
"A low  flat mass of floating ice."
"To beat or strike with a rod or whip; to whip; to lash; to chastise with repeated blows."

"A great flow of water; a body of moving water; the flowing stream  as of a river; especially a body of water rising swelling and overflowing land not usually thus covered; a deluge; a freshet; an inundation."
"The bottom or lower part of any room; the part upon which we stand and upon which the movables in the room are supported."
"Anything that floors or upsets a person  as a blow that knocks him down; a conclusive answer or retort; a task that exceeds one's abilities."
"To clap or strike  as a bird its wings a fish its tail etc.; to flap."
"Having a tendency to flop or flap; as  a floppy hat brim."
"Pertaining to Flora  or to flowers; made of flowers; as floral games wreaths."
"Tin ore scarcely perceptible in the stone; tin ore stamped very fine."
"The eight month of the French republican calendar. It began April 20  and ended May 19. See Vendemiare."
"A little flower; one of the numerous little flowers which compose the head or anthodium in such flowers as the daisy  thistle and dandelion."
"Covered with flowers; abounding in flowers; flowery."

"A silver coin of Florence  first struck in the twelfth century and noted for its beauty. The name is given to different coins in different countries. The florin of England first minted in 1849 is worth two shillings or about 48 cents; the florin of the Netherlands about 40 cents; of Austria about 36 cents."
"A cultivator of  or dealer in flowers."
"A hopper-shaped box or /nortar in which ore is placed for the action of the stamps."
"The slender styles of the pistillate flowers of maize; also called silk."
"Pertaining to  made of or resembling floss; hence light; downy."
"A fleet; especially  a /eet of Spanish ships which formerly sailed every year from Cadiz to Vera Cruz in Mexico to transport to Spain the production of Spanish America."
"Represented as flying or streaming in the air; as  a banner flotant."
"Goods lost by shipwreck  and floating on the sea; -- in distinction from jetsam or jetson."

"To throw the limbs and body one way and the other; to spring  turn or twist with sudden effort or violence; to struggle as a horse in mire; to flounder; to throw one's self with a jerk or spasm often as in displeasure."
"The finely ground meal of wheat  or of any other grain; especially the finer part of meal separated by bolting; hence the fine and soft powder of any substance; as flour of emery; flour of mustard."
"Of or resembling flour; mealy; covered with flour."
"To mock or insult; to treat with contempt."
"An overflowing with water; also  the water which thus overflows."
"In the popular sense  the bloom or blossom of a plant; the showy portion usually of a different color shape and texture from the foliage."
"p. p. of Fly; -- often used with the auxiliary verb to be; as  the birds are flown."
"A hydrocarbon extracted from gutta-percha  as a yellow resinous substance; -- called also fluanil."
"Soft clayey matter in the vein  or surrounding it."
"An inclosed passage way for establishing and directing a current of air  gases etc.; an air passage"
"The quality of being fluent; smoothness; readiness of utterance; volubility."
"Flowing or capable of flowing; liquid; glodding; easily moving."
"Nap or down; flue; soft  downy feathers."
"Pertaining to  or resembling fluff or nap; soft and downy."
"A grand piano or a harpsichord  both being wing-shaped."
"Having particles which easily move and change their relative position without a separation of the mass  and which easily yield to pressure; capable of flowing; liquid or gaseous."
"Pertaining to a fluid  or to its flowing motion."

"A stream; especially  a passage channel or conduit for the water that drives a mill wheel; or an artifical channel of water for hydraulic or placer mining; also a chute for conveying logs or lumber down a declivity."
"To fail  as on a lesson; to back out as from an undertaking through fear."
"A contemptuous name for a liveried servant or a footman."
"Pertaining to  obtained from or containing fluorine."
"A sudden and brief blast or gust; a light  temporary breeze; as a flurry of wind."
"To flow and spread suddenly; to rush; as  blood flushes into the face."
"A workman employed in cleaning sewers by flushing them with water."
"To make hot and rosy  as with drinking; to heat; hence to throw into agitation and confusion; to confuse; to muddle."

"A musical wind instrument  consisting of a hollow cylinder or pipe with holes along its length stopped by the fingers or by keys which are opened by the fingers. The modern flute is closed at the upper end and blown with the mouth at a lateral hole."
"One who plays on the flute; a flutist or flautist."
"A performer on the flute; a flautist."
"To vibrate or move quickly; as  a bird flutters its wings."
"Soft and clear in tone  like a flute."
"Belonging to rivers; growing or living in streams or ponds; as  a fluvial plant."
"The act of flowing; a continuous moving on or passing by  as of a flowing stream; constant succession; change."
"To move in or pass thorugh the air with wings  as a bird."
"A kind of catchfly of the genus Silene; also  a poisonous mushroom (Agaricus muscarius); fly agaric."
"To deposit eggs upon  as a flesh fly does on meat; to cause to be maggoty; hence to taint or contaminate as if with flyblows."
"A California scorpaenoid fish (Sebastichthys rhodochloris)  having brilliant colors."
"The driver of a fly  or light public carriage."
"A name given to the series of sandstones and schists overlying the true nummulitic formation in the Alps  and included in the Eocene Tertiary."
"The young of any animal of the Horse family (Equidae); a colt; a filly."

"The white substance  consisting of an aggregation of bubbles which is formed on the surface of liquids or in the mouth of an animal by violent agitation or fermentation; froth; spume; scum; as the foam of the sea."
"Belonging to or concerning a focus; as a focal point."
"A point in which the rays of light meet  after being reflected or refrcted and at which the image is formed; as the focus of a lens or mirror."
"A weight by which lead and some other metals were formerly sold  in England varying from 19/ to 24 cwt.; a fother."
"One who entertains personal enmity  hatred grudge or malice against another; an enemy."
"The Cornish name for a forge used for smelting tin."
"Filled or abounding with fog  or watery exhalations; misty; as a foggy atmosphere; a foggy morning."
"A dull old fellow; a person behind the times  over-conservative or slow; -- usually preceded by old."
"The principles and conduct of a fogy."
"An exclamation of abhorrence or contempt; poh; fle."
"Thrusting with the foil; fencing with the point  as distinguished from broadsword play."
"One who foists something surreptitiously; a falsifier."
"To lap or lay in plaits or folds; to lay one part over another part of; to double; as  to fold cloth; to fold a letter."
"One who  or that which folds; esp. a flat knifelike instrument used for folding paper."
"Leaves  collectively as produced or arranged by nature; leafage; as a tree or forest of beautiful foliage."
"Consisting of  or pertaining to leaves; as foliar appendages."
"Furnished with leaves; leafy; as  a foliate stalk."
"A leaf of a book or manuscript."
"To put a serial number on each folio or page of (a book); to page."
"One of the distinct parts of a compound leaf; a leaflet."
"A leaf  esp. a thin leaf or plate."
"In Anglo-Saxon times  the people of a group of townships or villages; a community; a tribe."
"To go or come after; to move behind in the same path or direction; hence  to go with (a leader guide etc.); to accompany; to attend."
"The state of being foolish; want of good sense; levity  weakness or derangement of mind."
"To apply a warm lotion to; to bathe with a cloth or sponge wet with warm water or medicated liquid."
"Any substance supposed to be capable of absorbing  retaining and transporting contagious or infectious germs; as woolen clothes are said to be active fomites."
"To treat or handle with tenderness or in a loving manner; to caress; as  a nurse fondles a child."
"A large copper vessel used for hot amalgamation."
"A style of printing calico  paper hangings etc. in which the colors are in bands and graduated into each other."

"A complete assortment of printing type of one size  including a due proportion of all the letters in the alphabet large and small points accents and whatever else is necessary for printing with that variety of types; a fount."
"Pertaining to a font  fountain source or origin; original; primitive."

"What is fed upon; that which goes to support life by being received within  and assimilated by the organism of an animal or a plant; nutriment; aliment; especially what is eaten by animals for nourishment."
"Full of food; supplying food; fruitful; fertile."
"A compound of gooseberries scalded and crushed  with cream; -- commonly called gooseberry fool."
"The practice of folly; the behavior of a fool; absurdity."
"To make a fool of; to befool."
"Marked with  or exhibiting folly; void of understanding; weak in intellect; without judgment or discretion; silly; unwise."
"The terminal part of the leg of man or an animal; esp.  the part below the ankle or wrist; that part of an animal upon which it rests when standing or moves. See Manus and Pes."
"A page; an attendant in livery; a lackey."
"Hastily; immediately; instantly; on the spot; hotfloot."
"A soldier who marches and fights on foot; a foot soldier."
"The settlings of oil  molasses etc. at the bottom of a barrel or hogshead."
"Having foots  or settlings; as footy oil molasses etc."
"One whose ambition it is to gain admiration by showy dress; a coxcomb; an inferior dandy."
"The behavior  dress or other indication of a fop; coxcombry; affectation of show; showy folly."
"Foplike; characteristic of a top in dress or manners; making an ostentatious display of gay clothing; affected in manners."
"In the most general sense  indicating that in consideration of in view of or with reference to which anything is done or takes place."
"The act of foraging; search for provisions  etc."
"A small opening  perforation or orifice; a fenestra."
"A sudden or irregular incursion in border warfare; hence  any irregular incursion for war or spoils; a raid."
"One who makes or joins in a foray."
"An ancestor; a forefather; -- usually in the plural."

"A pair of pinchers  or tongs; an instrument for grasping holding firmly or exerting traction upon bodies which it would be inconvenient or impracticable to seize with the fingers especially one for delicate operations as those of watchmakers surgeons accoucheurs dentists etc."
"One who  or that which forces or drives."
"A place in a river  or other water where it may be passed by man or beast on foot by wading."
"To arm or prepare for attack or resistance before the time of need."
"Near; hard by; along; past. See Forby."
"The anterior part of the alimentary canal  from the mouth to the intestine o/ to the entrance of the bile duct."
"Outside; extraneous; separated; alien; as  a foreign country; a foreign government."
"A kind of parchment for book covers. See Forrill."
"To turn before; to precede; to be in advance of (something following)."
"To see beforehand; to have prescience of; to foreknow."
"An extensive wood; a large tract of land covered with trees; in the United States  a wood of native growth or a tract of woodland which has never been cultivated."
"The hair on the forepart of the head; esp.  a tuft or lock of hair which hangs over the forehead as of a horse."
"A leader  or would-be leader in matters of knowledge or taste."
"A place or establishment where iron or other metals are wrought by heating and hammering; especially  a furnace or a shop with its furnace etc. where iron is heated and wrought; a smithy."
"One who forges  makes of forms; a fabricator; a falsifier."
"The act of forging metal into shape."
"To lose the remembrance of; to let go from the memory; to cease to have in mind; not to think of; also  to lose the power of; to cease from doing."
"To give wholly; to make over without reservation; to resign."
"To pass by; to leave. See 1st Forego."

"An instrument consisting of a handle with a shank terminating in two or more prongs or tines  which are usually of metal parallel and slightly curved; -- used from piercing holding taking up or pitching anything."
"Opening into two or more parts or shoots; forked; furcated."
"To lie in wait for; to ambush."
"To give up; to leave; to abandon."
"A suffix used to denote in the form / shape of  resembling etc.; as valiform; oviform."

"The shape and structure of anything  as distinguished from the material of which it is composed; particular disposition or arrangement of matter giving it individuality or distinctive character; configuration; figure; external appearance."
"The female of a hawk or falcon."
"One who forms; a maker; a creator."
"Pertaining to  or derived from ants; as formic acid; in an extended sense pertaining to or derived from formic acid; as formic ether."
"A Linnaean genus of hymenopterous insects  including the common ants. See Ant."
"A prescribed or set form; an established rule; a fixed or conventional method in which anything is to be done  arranged or said."
"A set or prescribed model; a formula."
"A univalent radical  H.C:O regarded as the essential residue of formic acid and aldehyde."
"An arch or fold; as  the fornix or vault of the cranium; the fornix or reflection of the conjuctiva."
"To pass by or along; to pass over."
"To waste away completely by suffering or torment."
"To quit or leave entirely; to desert; to abandon; to depart or withdraw from; to leave; as  false friends and flatterers forsake us in adversity."
"To forbid; to renounce; to forsake; to deny."
"To delay; to hinder; to neglect; to put off."

"A strong or fortified place; usually  a small fortified place occupied only by troops surrounded with a ditch rampart and parapet or with palisades stockades or other means of defense; a fortification."
"The strong point; that in which one excels."
"Furnished with  or guarded by forts; strengthened or defended as by forts."
"Forward; onward in time  place or order; in advance from a given point; on to end; as from that day forth; one two three and so forth."
"To add strength to; to strengthen; to confirm; to furnish with power to resist attack."

"The arrival of something in a sudden or unexpected manner; chance; accident; luck; hap; also  the personified or deified power regarded as determining human success apportioning happiness and unhappiness and distributing arbitrarily or fortuitously the lots of life."
"Four times ten; thirty-nine and one more."
"A market place or public place in Rome  where causes were judicially tried and orations delivered to the people."
"A pit  groove cavity or depression of greater or less depth; as the temporal fossa on the side of the skull; the nasal fossae containing the nostrils in most birds."
"A species of civet (Viverra fossa) resembling the genet."
"Dug out of the earth; as  fossil coal; fossil salt."
"To feed; to nourish; to support; to bring up."
"A wagonload; a load of any sort."
"A thin  washable material of silk or silk and cotton originally imported from India but now also made elsewhere."
"To flash  as lightning; to lighten; to gleam; to thunder."
"In a foul manner; filthily; nastily; shamefully; unfairly; dishonorably."
"The European polecat; -- called also European ferret  and fitchew. See Polecat."
"One who founds  establishes and erects; one who lays a foundation; an author; one from whom anything originates; one who endows."
"The act  process or art of casting metals."
"Having the ends forked or branched  and the ends of the branches terminating abruptly as if cut off; -- said of an ordinary especially of a cross."
"Next in order after the third; the ordinal of four."
"A viverrine animal of Madagascar (Cryptoprocta ferox). It resembles a cat in size and form  and has retractile claws."
"A slight depression or pit; a fossa."
"A small depression or pit; a fovea."
"One of the fine granules contained in the protoplasm of a pollen grain."
"Any bird; esp.  any large edible bird."
"A sportsman who pursues wild fowl  or takes or kills for food."

"A carnivorous animal of the genus Vulpes  family Canidae of many species. The European fox (V. vulgaris or V. vulpes) the American red fox (V. fulvus) the American gray fox (V. Virginianus) and the arctic white or blue fox (V. lagopus) are well-known species."
"An uproar; a noisy quarrel; a disturbance; a brawl."
"A shallow iron pan to hold glass ware while being annealed."
"Having a part displaced  as if broken; -- said of an ordinary."
"Behavior like that of a fox; cunning."
"The fox shark; -- called also sea fox. See Thrasher shark  under Shark."
"Resembling a fox in his characteristic qualities; cunning; artful; foxy."
"The tail or brush of a fox."
"Like or pertaining to the fox; foxlike in disposition or looks; wily."
"A lobby in a theater; a greenroom."
"A connecting fold of membrane serving to support or restrain any part; as  the fraenum of the tongue."
"Easily broken; brittle; frail; delicate; easily destroyed."
"A loud and sudden sound; the report of anything bursting; a crash."
"A basket made of rushes  used chiefly for containing figs and raisins."
"The condition quality of being frail  physically mentally or morally frailness; infirmity; weakness of resolution; liableness to be deceived or seduced."
"A large and thick pancake  with slices of bacon in it."

"To construct by fitting and uniting the several parts of the skeleton of any structure; specifically  in woodwork to put together by cutting parts of one member to fit parts of another. See Dovetail Halve v. t. Miter Tenon Tooth Tusk Scarf and Splice."
"One who frames; as  the framer of a building; the framers of the Constitution."

"A silver coin of France  and since 1795 the unit of the French monetary system. It has been adopted by Belgium and Swizerland. It is equivalent to about nineteen cents or ten pence and is divided into 100 centimes."
"Pertaining to the Franks  or their language; Frankish."
"A paramour; a loose woman; also  a gay idle fellow."
"Mad; raving; furious; violent; wild and disorderly; distracted."
"To draw together; to bind with a view to secure and strengthen  as a vessel by passing cables around it; to tighten; as a tackle by drawing the lines together."
"Deception deliberately practiced with a view to gaining an unlawful or unfair advantage; artifice by which the right or interest of another is injured; injurious stratagem; deceit; trick."

"A colorless crystalline substance  regarded as a glucoside and found in the bark of the ash (Fraxinus) and along with esculin in the bark of the horse-chestnut. It shows a delicate fluorescence in alkaline solutions; -- called also paviin."
"A small yellowish or brownish spot in the skin  particularly on the face neck or hands."
"Full of or marked with freckles; sprinkled with spots; freckled."
"Peace; -- a word used in composition  especially in proper names; as Alfred; Frederic."

"Exempt from subjection to the will of others; not under restraint  control or compulsion; able to follow one's own impulses desires or inclinations; determining one's own course of action; not dependent; at liberty."
"The state of being free; exemption from the power and control of another; liberty; independence."
"In a free manner; without restraint or compulsion; abundantly; gratuitously."
"One who enjoys liberty  or who is not subject to the will of another; one not a slave or vassal."
"One who  or that which cools or freezes as a refrigerator or the tub and can used in the process of freezing ice cream."
"That with which anything in fraught or laden for transportation; lading; cargo  especially of a ship or a car on a railroad etc.; as a freight of cotton; a full freight."
"Of or pertaining to France or its inhabitants."
"Any violent agitation of the mind approaching to distraction; violent and temporary derangement of the mental faculties; madness; rage."
"A cool  refreshing state of the air; duskiness; coolness; shade."
"Possessed of original life and vigor; new and strong; unimpaired; sound."
"To make fresh; to separate  as water from saline ingredients; to make less salt; as to freshen water fish or flesh."
"In a fresh manner; vigorously; newly  recently; brightly; briskly; coolly; as freshly gathered; freshly painted; the wind blows freshly."
"Disposed to fret; ill-humored; peevish; angry; in a state of vexation; as  a fretful temper."
"The worn side of the bank of a river. See 4th Fret  n. 4."
"Rubbed; marked; as  pock-fretten marked with the smallpox."
"A strait  or arm of the sea."
"The daughter of Njord  and goddess of love and beauty; the Scandinavian Venus; -- in Teutonic myths confounded with Frigga but in Scandinavian distinct."
"Easily crumbled  pulverized or reduced to powder."

"A brother or member of any religious order  but especially of one of the four mendicant orders viz: (a) Minors Gray Friars or Franciscans. (b) Augustines. (c) Dominicans or Black Friars. (d) White Friars or Carmelites. See these names in the Vocabulary."
"Like a friar; pertaining to friars or to a convent."
"Meat sliced and dressed with strong sauce."
"The sixth day of the week  following Thursday and preceding Saturday."
"One who entertains for another such sentiments of esteem  respect and affection that he seeks his society aud welfare; a wellwisher; an intimate associate; sometimes an attendant."
"Of or pertaining to Friesland  a province in the northern part of the Netherlands."

"That part of the entablature of an order which is between the architrave and cornice. It is a flat member or face  either uniform or broken by triglyphs and often enriched with figures and other ornaments of sculpture."
"Gathered  or having the map gathered into little tufts knots or protuberances. Cf. Frieze v. t. and Friz v. t. 2."
"One who  or that which friezes or frizzes."

"Originally  a vessel of the Mediterranean propelled by sails and by oars. The French about 1650 transferred the name to larger vessels and by 1750 it had been appropriated for a class of war vessels intermediate between corvettes and ships of the line. Frigates from about 1750 to 1850 had one full battery deck and often a spar deck with a lighter battery. They carried sometimes as many as fifty guns. After the application of steam to navigation steam frigates of largely increased size and power were built and formed the main part of the navies of the world till about 1870 when the introduction of ironclads superseded them."
"The wife of Odin and mother of the gods; the supreme goddess; the Juno of the Valhalla. Cf. Freya."
"A state of terror excited by the sudden appearance of danger; sudden and violent fear  usually of short duration; a sudden alarm."
"Cold; wanting heat or warmth; of low temperature; as  a frigid climate."
"To shake or shiver as with cold; as  the hawk frills."
"Flourishing; thriving; fresh; in good case; vigorous."

"An ornamental appendage to the border of a piece of stuff  originally consisting of the ends of the warp projecting beyond the woven fabric; but more commonly made separate and sewed on consisting sometimes of projecting ends twisted or plaited together and sometimes of loose threads of wool silk or linen or narrow strips of leather or the like."
"One who deals in frippery or in old clothes."
"Of or pertaining to Friesland  a province of the Netherlands; Friesic."
"One who frisks; one who leaps of dances in gayety; a wanton; an inconstant or unsettled person."
"The light frame which holds the sheet of paper to the tympan in printing."
"The dressing of the hair by crisping or curling."
"The material of which glass is made  after having been calcined or partly fused in a furnace but before vitrification. It is a composition of silex and alkali occasionally with other ingredients."
"A narrow arm of the sea; an estuary; the opening of a river into the sea; as  the Frith of Forth."
"A small quantity of batter  fried in boiling lard or in a frying pan. Fritters are of various kinds named from the substance inclosed in the batter; as apple fritters clam fritters oyster fritters."
"To curl or form into small curls  as hair with a crisping pin; to crisp."
"A movable furrowed piece of steel struck by the flint  to throw sparks into the pan in an early form of flintlock."
"To curl or crisp  as hair; to friz; to crinkle."
"From; away; back or backward; -- now used only in opposition to the word to  in the phrase to and fro that is to and from. See To and fro under To."

"A loose outer garment; especially  a gown forming a part of European modern costume for women and children; also a coarse shirtlike garment worn by some workmen over their other clothes; a smock frock; as a marketman's frock."
"A dirty woman; a slattern; a frow."
"An amphibious animal of the genus Rana and related genera  of many species. Frogs swim rapidly and take long leaps on land. Many of the species utter loud notes in the springtime."
"A European plant (Hydrocharis Morsus-ranae)  floating on still water and propagating itself by runners. It has roundish leaves and small white flowers."
"Provided or ornamented with frogs; as  a frogged coat. See Frog n. 4."
"Full of levity; dancing  playing or frisking about; full of pranks; frolicsome; gay; merry."

"Out of the neighborhood of; lessening or losing proximity to; leaving behind; by reason of; out of; by aid of; -- used whenever departure  setting out commencement of action being state occurrence etc. or procedure emanation absence separation etc.

"The organ formed by the combination or union into one body of stem and leaf  and often bearing the fructification; as the frond of a fern or of a lichen or seaweed; also the peculiar leaf of a palm tree."
"A political party in France  during the minority of Louis XIV. who opposed the government and made war upon the court party."
"The forehead; the part of the cranium between the orbits and the vertex."
"The forehead or brow  the part of the face above the eyes; sometimes also the whole face."
"Belonging to the front part; being in front"
"The act of freezing; -- applied chiefly to the congelation of water; congelation of fluids."
"Covered with hoarfrost or anything resembling hoarfrost; ornamented with frosting; also  frost-bitten; as a frosted cake; frosted glass."
"Attended with  or producing frost; having power to congeal water; cold; freezing; as a frosty night."
"To rub or wear by rubbing; to chafe."
"The bubbles caused in fluids or liquors by fermentation or agitation; spume; foam; esp.  a spume of saliva caused by disease or nervous excitement."
"Full of foam or froth  or consisting of froth or light bubbles; spumous; foamy."
"To gather into or adorn with plaits  as a dress; to form wrinkles in or upon; to curl or frizzle as the hair."
"Fetid  musty; rank; disordered and offensive to the smell or sight; slovenly; dingy. See Frowzy."
"A woman; especially  a Dutch or German woman."
"Not willing to yield or compIy with what is required or is reasonable; perverse; disobedient; peevish; as  a froward child."
"Working smoothly  or without splitting; -- said of timber."
"To contract the brow in displeasure  severity or sternness; to scowl; to put on a stern grim or surly look."
"Bearing fruit; -- said of a tree or plant so represented upon an escutcheon."

"Economical in the use or appropriation of resources; not wasteful or lavish; wise in the expenditure or application of force  materials time etc.; characterized by frugality; sparing; economical; saving; as a frugal housekeeper; frugal of time."
"Whatever is produced for the nourishment or enjoyment of man or animals by the processes of vegetable growth  as corn grass cotton flax etc.; -- commonly used in the plural."
"Having the odor  taste or appearance of fruit; also fruitful."
"To insult; to flout; to mock; to snub."
"The part of a solid next the base  formed by cutting off the top; or the part of any solid as of a cone pyramid etc. between two planes which may be either parallel or inclined to each other."
"A picture of fruit; decoration by representation of fruit."
"A plant having a woody  durable stem but less than a tree; a shrub."
"To cook in a pan or on a griddle (esp. with the use of fat  butter or olive oil) by heating over a fire; to cook in boiling lard or fat; as to fry fish; to fry doughnuts."
"Plump; chubby; short and stuffy; as a fubsy sofa."
"Painted; disguised with paint  or with false show."

"A genus of flowering plants having elegant drooping flowers  with four sepals four petals eight stamens and a single pistil. They are natives of Mexico and South America. Double-flowered varieties are now common in cultivation."

"Properly  belonging to an order of alga: (Fucoideae) which are blackish in color and produce oospores which are not fertilized until they have escaped from the conceptacle. The common rockweeds and the gulfweed (Sargassum) are fucoid in character."
"A paint; a dye; also  false show."
"An oily liquid  resembling and possibly identical with furfurol and obtained from fucus and other seaweeds."
"The tail of a hare  coney etc."
"To make foolish by drink; to cause to become intoxicated."
"A made-up story; stuff; nonsense; humbug; -- often an exclamation of contempt."
"Of or pertaining to Terra del Fuego."
"Any matter used to produce heat by burning; that which feeds fire; combustible matter used for fires  as wood coal peat etc."
"One who  or that which supplies fuel."
"A code; a charter; a grant of privileges."
"in the gugue style  but not strictly like a fugue."
"To maneuver; to move hither and thither."

"A polyphonic composition  developed from a given theme or themes according to strict contrapuntal rules. The theme is first given out by one voice or part and then while that pursues its way it is repeated by another at the interval of a fifth or fourth and so on until all the parts have answered one by one continuing their several melodies and interweaving them in one complex progressive whole in which the theme is often lost and reappears."
"A musician who composes or performs fugues."
"To fill up; to make full or complete."

"Filled up  having within its limits all that it can contain; supplied; not empty or vacant; -- said primarily of hollow vessels and hence of anything else; as a cup full of water; a house full of people."
"The money or price paid for fulling or cleansing cloth."
"One whose occupation is to full cloth."
"The place or the works where the fulling of cloth is carried on."
"In a full manner or degree; completely; entirely; without lack or defect; adequately; satisfactorily; as  to be fully persuaded of the truth of a proposition."

"One of several species of sea birds  of the family procellariidae allied to the albatrosses and petrels. Among the well-known species are the arctic fulmar (Fulmarus glacialis) (called also fulmar petrel malduck and mollemock) and the giant fulmar (Ossifraga gigantea)."
"Tawny; dull yellow  with a mixture of gray and brown."
"A salted and smoked fish  as the pilchard."
"Pertaining to  or derived from fumitory (Fumaria officinalis)."
"To feel or grope about; to make awkward attempts to do or find something."
"Exhalation; volatile matter (esp. noxious vapor or smoke) ascending in a dense body; smoke; vapor; reek; as  the fumes of tobacco."
"The stench or high flavor of game or other meat when kept long."
"To subject to the action of smoke."
"An aggregation or deposit of resources from which supplies are or may be drawn for carrying on any work  or for maintaining existence."
"The bottom or base of any hollow organ; as  the fundus of the bladder; the fundus of the eye."

"The solemn rites used in the disposition of a dead human body  whether such disposition be by interment burning or otherwise; esp. the ceremony or solemnization of interment; obsequies; burial; -- formerly used in the plural."
"A genus of simple  stony corals; -- so called because they are usually flat and circular with radiating plates like the gills of a mushroom. Some of them are eighteen inches in diameter."
"Of or pertaining to the Fungidae  a family of stony corals."
"Pertaining to  or obtained from mushrooms; as fungic acid."
"A name formerly given to cellulose found in certain fungi and mushrooms."
"Any one of the Fungi  a large and very complex group of thallophytes of low organization -- the molds mildews rusts smuts mushrooms toadstools puff balls and the allies of each."
"A cord; specifically  the umbilical cord or navel string."
"Pertaining to  or characterized by great fear or funking."
"A vessel of the shape of an inverted hollow cone  terminating below in a pipe and used for conveying liquids into a close vessel; a tunnel."
"The short  fine soft hair of certain animals growing thick on the skin and distinguished from the hair which is longer and coarser."
"To rub or scour to brightness; to clean; to burnish; as  to furbish a sword or spear."
"A forked process; the wishbone or furculum."
"To draw up into a bundle; to roll up."
"A yellow  crystalline substance (C4H3O)2.C2O2 obtained by the oxidation of furoin."
"Pertaining to  or derived from furile; as furilic acid."
"Transported with passion or fury; raging; violent; as  a furious animal."
"To draw up or gather into close compass; to wrap or roll  as a sail close to the yard stay or mast or as a flag close to or around its staff securing it there by a gasket or line. Totten."
"A measure of length; the eighth part of a mile; forty rods; two hundred and twenty yards."

"An inclosed place in which heat is produced by the combustion of fuel  as for reducing ores or melting metals for warming a house for baking pottery etc.; as an iron furnace; a hot-air furnace; a glass furnace; a boiler furnace etc."

"To supply with anything necessary  useful or appropriate; to provide; to equip; to fit out or fit up; to adorn; as to furnish a family with provisions; to furnish one with arms for defense; to furnish a Cable; to furnish the mind with ideas; to furnish one with knowledge or principles; to furnish an expedition or enterprise a room or a house."
"A colorless  crystalline substance C10H8O4 from furfurol."
"A dealer in furs; one who makes or sells fur goods."
"A trench in the earth made by  or as by a plow."
"To a greater distance; in addition; moreover. See Farther."
"Stolen; obtained or characterized by stealth; sly; secret; stealthy; as  a furtive look."
"A thorny evergreen shrub (Ulex Europaeus)  with beautiful yellow flowers very common upon the plains and hills of Great Britain; -- called also gorse and whin. The dwarf furze is Ulex nanus."
"bounding in  or overgrown with furze; characterized by furze."
"Fine charcoal of willow wood  used as a drawing implement."
"A brown  nitrogenous pigment contained in the retinal epithelium; a variety of melanin."
"A dark-colored substance obtained from empyreumatic animal oil."
"To liquefy by heat; to render fiuid; to dissolve; to melt."
"Capable of being melted or rendered fluid by heat; fusible."
"The act or operation of melting or rendering fluid by heat; the act of melting together; as  the fusion of metals."
"A tumult; a bustle; unnecessary or annoying ado about trifles."
"Making a fuss; disposed to make an unnecessary ado about trifles; overnice; fidgety."
"The wood of the Rhus Cptinus or Venice sumach  a shrub of Southern Europe which yields a fine orange color which however is not durable without a mordant."
"A kind of coarse twilled cotton or cotton and linen stuff  including corduroy velveteen etc."
"The wood of the Maclura tinctoria  a tree growing in the West Indies used in dyeing yellow; -- called also old fustic."
"The jaws between which the hinder end of a carriage tongue is inserted."
"One of the crooked timbers which are scarfed together to form the lower part of the compound rib of a vessel; one of the crooked transverse timbers passing across and over the keel."
"That is to be or come hereafter; that will exist at any time after the present; as  the next moment is future to the present."
"A tube  filled with combustible matter for exploding a shell etc. See Fuse n."
"To make drunk; to intoxicate; to fuddle."
"A long bag net distended by hoops  into which fish can pass easily without being able to return; -- called also fyke net."
"A rebated cross  formerly used as a secret emblem and a common ornament. It is also called gammadion and swastika."
"The military force of the whole nation  consisting of all men able to bear arms."
"The hook on the end of an eccentric rod opposite the strap. See. Illust. of Eccentric."
"To talk fast  or to talk without meaning; to prate; to jabber."

"A name originally given by the Italians to a kind of serpentine  later to the rock called euphotide and now generally used for a coarsely crystalline igneous rock consisting of lamellar pyroxene (diallage) and labradorite with sometimes chrysolite (olivine gabbro)."
"A rent  service tribute custom tax impost or duty; an excise."
"A lighter  or vessel for inland navigation."
"A hollow cylinder of wickerwork  like a basket without a bottom. Gabions are made of various sizes and filled with earth in building fieldworks to shelter men from an enemy's fire."
"A small gable  or gable-shaped canopy formed over a tabernacle niche etc."
"A false spur or gaff  fitted on the heel of a gamecock."
"The point of a spear  or an arrowhead."
"One who roves about idly  a rambling gossip."
"A small British fish (Motella argenteola) of the Cod family."
"Any dipterous insect of the genus Oestrus  and allied genera of botflies."
"Pertaining to  or derived from the cod (Gadus); -- applied to an acid obtained from cod-liver oil viz. gadic acid."
"Of or pertaining to the family of fishes (Gadidae) which includes the cod  haddock and hake."
"One who uses a gad or goad in driving."
"A yellow or brown amorphous substance  of indifferent nature found in cod-liver oil."
"A large duck (Anas strepera)  valued as a game bird found in the northern parts of Europe and America; -- called also gray duck."
"A Celt or the Celts of the Scotch Highlands or of Ireland; now esp.  a Scotch Highlander of Celtic origin."
"Of or pertaining to the Gael  esp. to the Celtic Highlanders of Scotland; as the Gaelic language."
"A barbed spear or a hook with a handle  used by fishermen in securing heavy fish."
"An artificial spur or gaff for gamecocks."
"To stop the mouth of  by thrusting sometimes in so as to hinder speaking; hence to silence by authority or by violence; not to allow freedom of speech to."
"A pledge or pawn; something laid down or given as a security for the performance of some act by the person depositing it  and forfeited by nonperformance; security."
"To make a noise like a goose; to cackle."
"Pertaining to hypogeic acid; -- applied to an acid obtained from hypogeic acid."
"A square or beveled notch cut out of a girder  binding joist or other timber which supports a floor beam so as to receive the end of the floor beam."
"The horses  oxen plows wains or wagons and implements for carrying on tillage."
"To contradict; to deny; to controvert; to dispute; to forbid."
"A going; a walk; a march; a way."
"Having (such) a gait; -- used in composition; as  slow-gaited; heavy-gaited."
"A covering of cloth or leather for the ankle and instep  or for the whole leg from the knee to the instep fitting down upon the shoe."
"A genus of African lemurs  including numerous species."

"The Milky Way; that luminous tract  or belt which is seen at night stretching across the heavens and which is composed of innumerable stars so distant and blended as to be distinguishable only with the telescope. The term has recently been used for remote clusters of stars."
"A strong current of air; a wind between a stiff breeze and a hurricane. The most violent gales are called tempests."
"The upper lip or helmet-shaped part of a labiate flower."
"That division of elasmobranch fishes which includes the sharks."
"A remedy or antidose for poison; theriaca."

"A porch or waiting room  usually at the west end of an abbey church where the monks collected on returning from processions where bodies were laid previous to interment and where women were allowed to see the monks to whom they were related or to hear divine service. Also frequently applied to the porch of a church as at Ely and Durham cathedrals."
"A small galley  formerly used in the Mediterranean built mainly for speed. It was moved both by sails and oars having one mast and sixteen or twenty seats for rowers."
"An impure resin of turpentine  hardened on the outside of pine trees by the spontaneous evaporation of its essential oil. When purified it is called yellow pitch white pitch or Burgundy pitch."
"The bitter  alkaline viscid fluid found in the gall bladder beneath the liver. It consists of the secretion of the liver or bile mixed with that of the mucous membrane of the gall bladder."
"A native or inhabitant of Galicia  in Spain; a Galician."
"A red crystalline dyestuff  obtained by heating together pyrogallic and phthalic acids."
"A sailing vessel of the 15th and following centuries  often having three or four decks and used for war or commerce. The term is often rather indiscriminately applied to any large sailing vessel."
"A long and narrow corridor  or place for walking; a connecting passageway as between one room and another; also a long hole or passage excavated by a boring or burrowing animal."
"A vessel propelled by oars  whether having masts and sails or not"
"An insect that deposits its eggs in plants  and occasions galls esp. any small hymenopteran of the genus Cynips and allied genera. See Illust. of Gall."
"A substance obtained by the reduction of gallein."
"A rare metallic element  found in certain zinc ores. It is white hard and malleable resembling aluminium and remarcable for its low melting point (86/ F. 30/C). Symbol Ga. Atomic weight 69.9."
"A round gall produced on the leaves and shoots of various species of the oak tree. See Gall  and Nutgall."
"A measure of capacity  containing four quarts; -- used for the most part in liquid measure but sometimes in dry measure."
"A narrow tapelike fabric used for binding hats  shoes etc. -- sometimes made ornamental."
"To move or run in the mode called a gallop; as a horse; to go at a gallop; to run or move with speed."
"To fright or terrify. See Gally  v. t."
"A noisy  swaggering or worthless fellow; a rowdy."
"A kind of lively dance  in 2-4 time; also the music to the dance."
"Any bird of the genuis Totanus. See Tattler."

"The inspissated juice of a plant (Uncaria Gambir) growing in Malacca. It is a powerful astringent  and under the name of Terra Japonica is used for chewing with the Areca nut and is exported for tanning and dyeing."
"A performer upon the viola di gamba. See under Viola."
"A mode of opening the game  in which a pawn is sacrificed to gain an attacking position."
"To play or game for money or other stake."

"A concrete juice  or gum resin produced by several species of trees in Siam Ceylon and Malabar. It is brought in masses or cylindrical rolls from Cambodia or Cambogia -- whence its name. The best kind is of a dense compact texture and of a beatiful reddish yellow. Taking internally it is a strong and harsh cathartic and emetic."
"A skipping or leaping about in frolic; a hop; a sportive prank."
"Pertaining to  or resulting from sexual connection; formed by the union of the male and female elements."
"A neglected and untrained city boy; a young street Arab."
"The third letter (/  / = Eng. G) of the Greek alphabet."
"An old wife; an old woman; -- correlative of gaffer  an old man."
"The buttock or thigh of a hog  salted and smoked or dried; the lower end of a flitch."
"Having the flavor of game  esp. of game kept uncooked till near the condition of tainting; high-flavored."
"To drop from a high place upon sharp stakes or hooks  as the Turks dropped malefactors by way of punishment."
"The male of any species of goose."
"The Hindoo god of wisdom or prudence."
"One who oversees a gang of workmen."
"A short line attached to a trawl. See Trawl  n."
"The mineral or earthy substance associated with metallic ore."
"A passage or way into or out of any inclosed place; esp.  a temporary way of access formed of planks."
"The dried hemp plant  used in India for smoking. It is extremely narcotic and intoxicating."
"One of several species of sea birds of the genus Sula  allied to the pelicans."
"Of or pertaining to Ganoidei. -- n. One of the Ganoidei."
"A peculiar bony tissue beneath the enamel of a ganoid scale."
"A military punishment formerly in use  wherein the offender was made to run between two files of men facing one another who struck him as he passed."
"A kind of wild goose  by a flock of which a virtuoso was fabled to be carried to the lunar world."
"A place of confinement  especially for minor offenses or provisional imprisonment; a jail."
"The keeper of a jail. See Jailer."

"An opening in anything made by breaking or parting; as  a gap in a fence; an opening for a passage or entrance; an opening which implies a breach or defect; a vacant space or time; a hiatus; a mountain pass."
"Any slender marine fish of the genera Belone and Tylosurus. See Garfish."
"Offal  as the bowels of an animal or fish; refuse animal or vegetable matter from a kitchen; hence anything worthless disgusting or loathsome."
"To sift or bolt  to separate the fine or valuable parts of from the coarse and useless parts or from dros or dirt; as to garble spices."
"Turning the head towards the spectator  but not the body; -- said of a lion or other beast."
"A piece of ground appropriated to the cultivation of herbs  fruits flowers or vegetables."
"Coarse wool on the legs of sheep."
"A European marine fish (Belone vulgaris); -- called also gar  gerrick greenback greenbone gorebill hornfish longnose mackerel guide sea needle and sea pike."
"A distemper in geese  affecting the head."
"Showy; dazzling; ostentatious; attracting or exciting attention."

"A plant of the genus Allium (A. sativum is the cultivated variety)  having a bulbous root a very strong smell and an acrid pungent taste. Each root is composed of several lesser bulbs called cloves of garlic inclosed in a common membranous coat and easily separable."
"Any article of clothing  as a coat a gown etc."
"A granary; a building or place where grain is stored for preservation."

"A mineral having many varieties differing in color and in their constituents  but with the same crystallization (isometric) and conforming to the same general chemical formula. The commonest color is red the luster is vitreous and the hardness greater than that of quartz. The dodecahedron and trapezohedron are the common forms."
"To decorate with ornamental appendages; to set off; to adorn; to embellish."
"A stick or small wooden cylinder used for tightening a bandage  in order to compress the arteries of a limb."

"A Spanish mode of execution by strangulation  with an iron collar affixed to a post and tightened by a screw until life become extinct; also the instrument by means of which the punishment is inflicted."
"One of several species of California market fishes  of the genus Sebastichthys; -- called also rockfish. See Rockfish."
"A band used to prevent a stocking from slipping down on the leg."
"A close; a yard; a croft; a garden; as  a cloister garth."
"A sauce made of small fish. It was prized by the ancients."
"The sprat; -- called also garvie herring  and garvock."

"An aeriform fluid; -- a term used at first by chemists as synonymous with air  but since restricted to fluids supposed to be permanently elastic as oxygen hydrogen etc. in distinction from vapors as steam which become liquid on a reduction of temperature. In present usage since all of the supposed permanent gases have been liquified by cold and pressure the term has resumed nearly its original signification and is applied to any substance in the elastic or aeriform state."
"Of or pertaining to Gascony  in France or to the Gascons; also braggart; swaggering."
"In the form  or of the nature of gas or of an aeriform fluid."
"To make a gash  or long deep incision in; -- applied chiefly to incisions in flesh."
"To convert into gas  or an aeriform fluid as by the application of heat or by chemical processes."
"A line or band used to lash a furled sail securely. Sea gaskets are common lines; harbor gaskets are plaited and decorated lines or bands. Called also casket."
"An apparatus for the generation of gases  or for impregnating a liquid with a gas or a gas with a volatile liquid."
"To open the mouth wide in catching the breath  or in laborious respiration; to labor for breath; to respire convulsively; to pant violently."
"The process of passing cotton goods between two rollers and exposing them to numerous minute jets of gas to burn off the small fibers; any similar process of singeing."
"Full of gas; like gas. Hence: [Colloq.] Inflated; full of boastful or insincere talk."
"To make aghast; to frighten; to terrify. See Aghast."
"Of  pertaining to or situated near the stomach; as the gastric artery."
"A large door or passageway in the wall of a city  of an inclosed field or place or of a grand edifice etc.; also the movable structure of timber metal etc. by which the passage can be closed."
"A passage through a fence or wall; a gate; also  a frame arch etc. in which a gate in hung or a structure at an entrance or gate designed for ornament or defense."
"To bring together; to collect  as a number of separate things into one place or into one aggregate body; to assemble; to muster; to congregate."
"One of the native inhabitants of the pampas  of Spanish-American descent. They live mostly by rearing cattle."
"Ostentatiously fine; showy; gay  but tawdry or meretricious."
"To plait  crimp or flute; to goffer as lace. See Goffer."
"To measure or determine with a gauge."
"One who gauges; an officer whose business it is to ascertain the contents of casks."
"The Anglicized form of Gallia  which in the time of the Romans included France and Upper Italy (Transalpine and Cisalpine Gaul)."
"Pertaining to ancient France  or Gaul; Gallic."
"A series of beds of clay and marl in the South of England  between the upper and lower greensand of the Cretaceous period."
"Attenuated  as with fasting or suffering; lean; meager; pinched and grim."
"A frame for supporting barrels in a cellar or elsewhere."
"An East Indian species of wild cattle (Bibos gauris)  of large size and an untamable disposition."
"A very thin  slight transparent stuff generally of silk; also any fabric resembling silk gauze; as wire gauze; cotton gauze."
"Pertaining to  or resembling gauze; thin and slight as gauze."
"An ancient special kind of cessavit used in Kent and London for the recovery of rent."
"The division of birds which includes the gulls and terns."
"A large Asiatic crocodilian (Gavialis Gangeticus); -- called also nako  and Gangetic crocodile."
"A kind of difficult dance; a dance tune  the air of which has two brisk and lively yet dignified strains in common time each played twice over."
"Foolish and awkward; clumsy; clownish; as  gawky behavior. -- n. A fellow who is awkward from being overgrown or from stupidity a gawk."
"Excited with merriment; manifesting sportiveness or delight; inspiring delight; livery; merry."
"A Southern Asiatic species of wild cattle (Bibos frontalis)."
"The state of being gay; merriment; mirth; acts or entertainments prompted by  or inspiring merry delight; -- used often in the plural; as the gayeties of the season."
"With mirth and frolic; merrily; blithely; gleefully."
"To fixx the eyes in a steady and earnest look; to look with eagerness or curiosity  as in admiration astonishment or with studious attention."
"A summerhouse so situated as to command an extensive prospect."
"The black currant; also  the wild plum."

"One of several small  swift elegantly formed species of antelope of the genus Gazella esp. G. dorcas; -- called also algazel corinne korin and kevel. The gazelles are celebrated for the luster and soft expression of their eyes."
"A Venetian coin  worth about three English farthings or one and a half cents."
"A newspaper; a printed sheet published periodically; esp.  the official journal published by the British government and containing legal and state notices."
"One of the pieces of sod used to line or cover parapets and the faces of earthworks."
"A species of cherry tree common in Europe (Prunus avium); also  the fruit which is usually small and dark in color."
"The channel or spout through which molten metal runs into a mold in casting."

"Any lizard of the family Geckonidae. The geckoes are small  carnivorous mostly nocturnal animals with large eyes and vertical elliptical pupils. Their toes are generally expanded and furnished with adhesive disks by which they can run over walls and ceilings. They are numerous in warm countries and a few species are found in Europe and the United States. See Wall gecko Fanfoot."
"Alluvial matter on the surface of land  not of recent origin."
"The original native name for the ancient Ethiopic language or people. See Ethiopic."

"The valley of Hinnom  near Jerusalem where some of the Israelites sacrificed their children to Moloch which on this account was afterward regarded as a place of abomination and made a receptacle for all the refuse of the city perpetual fires being kept up in order to prevent pestilential effluvia. In the New Testament the name is transferred by an easy metaphor to Hell."
"Pertaining to  or derived from earthy or vegetable mold."
"Capable of being congealed; capable of being converted into jelly."
"A baboon (Gelada Ruppelli) of Abyssinia  remarkable for the length of the hair on the neck and shoulders of the adult male."
"An amorphous  gummy carbohydrate found in Gelidium agar-agar and other seaweeds."
"The second part of the Talmud  or the commentary on the Mishna (which forms the first part or text)."
"A constellation of the zodiac  containing the two bright stars Castor and Pollux; also the third sign of the zodiac which the sun enters about May 20th."
"A leaf bud  as distinguished from a flower bud."
"A little leaf bud  as the plumule between the cotyledons."
"Full of gems; bright; glittering like a gem."
"A meeting; -- used in combination  as Witenagemote an assembly of the wise men."
"A South African antelope (Oryx Capensis)  having long sharp nearly straight horns."
"A small South American deer (Furcifer Chilensis)  with simple forked horns."
"The cheek; the feathered side of the under mandible of a bird."
"A worsted yarn or cord of peculiar smoothness  used in the manufacture of braid fringe etc."
"Relating to a genus or kind; pertaining to a whole class or order; as  a general law of animal or vegetable economy."
"The act of producing  or giving birth or origin to anything; the process or mode of originating; production; formation; origination."
"One of several species of small Carnivora of the genus Genetta  allied to the civets but having the scent glands less developed and without a pouch."
"Of or pertaining to Geneva  in Switzerland; Genevese."
"Of or pertaining to the chin; mental; as  the genian prominence."
"A man of a particular turn of mind."
"The edible fruit of a West Indian tree (Genipa Americana) of the order Rubiaceae. It is oval in shape  as a large as a small orange of a pale greenish color and with dark purple juice."
"A genus of plants including the common broom of Western Europe."
"Pertaining to generation  or to the generative organs."
"One who begets; a generator; an originator."
"A good or evil spirit  or demon supposed by the ancients to preside over a man's destiny in life; a tutelary deity; a supernatural being; a spirit good or bad. Cf. Jinnee."
"Of or pertaining to Genoa  a city of Italy."
"A style of painting  sculpture or other imitative art which illustrates everyday life and manners."
"A clan or family connection  embracing several families of the same stock who had a common name and certain common religious rites; a subdivision of the Roman curia or tribe."

"Possessing or exhibiting the qualities popularly regarded as belonging to high birth and breeding; free from vulgarity  or lowness of taste or behavior; adapted to a refined or cultivated taste; polite; well-bred; as genteel company manners address."
"Nobility of birth or of character; gentility."
"Any one of a genus (Gentiana) of herbaceous plants with opposite leaves and a tubular four- or five-lobed corolla  usually blue but sometimes white yellow or red. See Illust. of Capsule."
"One of a non-Jewish nation; one neither a Jew nor a Christian; a worshiper of false gods; a heathen."
"Well-born; of a good family or respectable birth  though not noble."

"Belonging to  or proceeding from the original stock; native; hence not counterfeit spurious false or adulterated; authentic; real; natural; true; pure; as a genuine text; a genuine production; genuine materials."

"A class of objects divided into several subordinate species; a class more extensive than a species; a precisely defined and exactly divided class; one of the five predicable conceptions  or sorts of terms."
"A nodule of stone  containing a cavity lined with crystals or mineral matter."

"That branch of applied mathematics which determines  by means of observations and measurements the figures and areas of large portions of the earth's surface or the general figure and dimenshions of the earth; or that branch of surveying in which the curvature of the earth is taken into account as in the surveys of States or of long lines of coast."
"A gigantic clam (Glycimeris generosa) of the Pacific coast of North America  highly valued as an article of food."
"The branch of science which treats of the formation of the earth."

"The science which treats: (a) Of the structure and mineral constitution of the globe; structural geology. (b) Of its history as regards rocks  minerals rivers valleys mountains climates life etc.; historical geology. (c) Of the causes and methods by which its structure features changes and conditions have been produced; dynamical geology. See Chart of The Geological Series."
"A hollow globe on the inner surface of which a map of the world is depicted  to be examined by one standing inside."
"A name given by miners to George Stephenson's safety lamp."
"A figure of St. George (the patron saint of England) on horseback  appended to the collar of the Order of the Garter. See Garter."
"A rural poem; a poetical composition on husbandry  containing rules for cultivating lands etc.; as the Georgics of Virgil."
"A small coin and weight; 1-20th of a shekel."
"The manager or acting partner of a company  joint-stock association etc."
"A salmon returning from the sea the second time."
"That which is to develop a new individual; as  the germ of a fetus of a plant or flower and the like; the earliest form under which an organism appears."
"Literally  near akin; hence closely allied; appropriate or fitting; relevant."
"A kind of verbal noun  having only the four oblique cases of the singular number and governing cases like a participle."
"Pertaining to deeds or feats of arms; legendary."
"A reciter of gests or legendary tales; a story-teller."
"Manner of carrying the body; position of the body or limbs; posture."
"the original third pers. sing. pres. of Go."
"One who gets  gains obtains acquires begets or procreates."
"A showy trifle; a toy; a splendid plaything; a pretty but worthless bauble."
"A boiling spring which throws forth at frequent intervals jets of water  mud etc. driven up by the expansive power of steam."
"Like a ghost in appearance; deathlike; pale; pallid; dismal."
"Egyptian dancing girls  of a lower sort than the almeh."
"Butter clarified by boiling  and thus converted into a kind of oil."
"A kind of small  prickly cucumber much used for pickles."
"The Jews'quarter in an Italian town or city."
"Relating to the soul; not carnal or secular; spiritual; as  a ghostly confessor."
"An imaginary evil being among Eastern nations  which was supposed to feed upon human bodies."
"A ravine. See Gill a woody glen."
"A man of extraordinari bulk and stature."
"An infidel; -- a term applied by Turks to disbelievers in the Mohammedan religion  especially Christrians."
"A kind of gallows; an upright post with an arm projecting from the top  on which formerly malefactors were hanged in chains and their bodies allowed to remain asa warning."

"Any arboreal ape of the genus Hylobates  of which many species and varieties inhabit the East Indies and Southern Asia. They are tailless and without cheek pouches and have very long arms adapted for climbing."
"Humped; protuberant; -- said of a surface which presents one or more large elevations."
"Swelling by a regular curve or surface; protuberant; convex; as  the moon is gibbous between the half-moon and the full moon."
"To cast reproaches and sneering expressions; to rail; to utter taunting  sarcastic words; to flout; to fleer; to scoff."
"A kind of carp (Cyprinus gibelio); -- called also Prussian carp."
"Made of giblets; as  a giblet pie."
"The inmeats  or edible viscera (heart gizzard liver etc.) of poultry."
"A disease of sheep  characterized by vertigo; the staggers. It is caused by the presence of the C/nurus a larval tapeworm in the brain. See C/nurus."
"Having in the head a sensation of whirling or reeling about; having lost the power of preserving the balance of the body  and therefore wavering and inclined to fall; lightheaded; dizzy."
"Anything given; anything voluntarily transferred by one person to another without compensation; a present; an offering."
"The leather strap by which the shield of a knight was slung across the shoulder  or across the neck and shoulder."
"To laugh with short catches of the breath or voice; to laugh in a light  affected or silly manner; to titter with childish levity."
"The act of fastending the gige or leather strap to the shield."
"A wanton; a lascivious or light  giddy girl."
"To overlay with a thin covering of gold; to cover with a golden color; to cause to look like gold."
"A drinking bout in which every one pays an equal share."
"One who gilds; one whose occupation is to overlay with gold."
"An organ for aquatic respiration; a branchia."
"A girl; esp.  a wanton; a gill."

"A contrivance for permitting a body to incline freely in all directions  or for suspending anything as a barometer ship's compass chronometer etc. so that it will remain plumb or level when its support is tipped as by the rolling of a ship. It consists of a ring in which the body can turn on an axis through a diameter of the ring while the ring itself is so pivoted to its support that it can turn about a diameter at right angles to the first."
"A small tool for boring holes. It has a leading screw  a grooved body and a cross handle."
"Joined work whose parts move within each other; a pair or series of interlocked rings."
"Made or consisting of interlocked ring/ or links; as  gimmal mail."
"A piece of mechanism; mechanical device or contrivance; a gimcrack."
"Against; near by; towards; as  gin night."
"A plant of the genus Zingiber  of the East and West Indies. The species most known is Z. officinale."
"A kind of cotton or linen cloth  usually in stripes or checks the yarn of which is dyed before it is woven; -- distinguished from printed cotton or prints."
"The lining of a mine shaft with stones or bricks to prevent caving."

"A large ornamental tree (Ginkgo biloba) from China and Japan  belonging to the Yew suborder of Coniferae. Its leaves are so like those of some maidenhair ferns that it is also called the maidenhair tree."

"A plant of the genus Aralia  the root of which is highly valued as a medicine among the Chinese. The Chinese plant (Aralia Schinseng) has become so rare that the American (A. quinquefolia) has largely taken its place and its root is now an article of export from America to China. The root when dry is of a yellowish white color with a sweetness in the taste somewhat resembling that of licorice combined with a slight aromatic bitterness."
"A shop or barroom where gin is sold as a beverage."
"A kind of pouch formerly worn at the girdle."

"An African ruminant (Camelopardalis giraffa) related to the deers and antelopes  but placed in a family by itself; the camelopard. It is the tallest of animals being sometimes twenty feet from the hoofs to the top of the head. Its neck is very long and its fore legs are much longer than its hind legs."
"A stroke with a rod or switch; a severe spasm; a twinge; a pang."
"A young person of either sex; a child."
"Like  or characteristic of a girl; of or pertaining to girlhood; innocent; artless; immature; weak; as girlish ways; girlish grief."
"A band or strap which encircles the body; especially  one by which a saddle is fastened upon the back of a horse."
"A weapon with a scythe-shaped blade  and a separate long sharp point mounted on a long staff and carried by foot soldiers."
"The corn cockle; also anciently applied to the Nigella  or fennel flower."
"A musical instrument  of unknown character supposed by some to have been used by the people of Gath and thence obtained by David. It is mentioned in the title of Psalms viii. lxxxi. and lxxxiv."
"To bestow without receiving a return; to confer without compensation; to impart  as a possession; to grant as authority or permission; to yield up or allow."
"One who gives; a donor; a bestower; a grantor; one who imparts or distributes."
"The second  or true muscular stomach of birds in which the food is crushed and ground after being softened in the glandular stomach (crop) or lower part of the esophagus; the gigerium."
"Pertaining to ice or to its action; consisting of ice; frozen; icy; esp.  pertaining to glaciers; as glacial phenomena."
"An immense field or stream of ice  formed in the region of perpetual snow and moving slowly down a mountain slope or valley as in the Alps or over an extended area as in Greenland."
"A gentle slope  or a smooth gently sloping bank; especially (Fort.) that slope of earth which inclines from the covered way toward the exterior ground or country (see Illust. of Ravelin)."

"Pleased; joyous; happy; cheerful; gratified; -- opposed to sorry  sorrowful or unhappy; -- said of persons and often followed by of at that or by the infinitive and sometimes by with introducing the cause or reason."
"To make glad; to cheer; to please; to gratify; to rejoice; to exhilarate."
"An open passage through a wood; a grassy open or cleared space in a forest."
"Sword grass; any plant with sword-shaped leaves  esp. the European Iris foetidissima."
"The internal shell  or pen of cephalopods like the squids."
"The white of egg. It is used as a size or a glaze in bookbinding  for pastry etc."
"A glairy viscous substance  which forms on the surface of certain mineral waters or covers the sides of their inclosures; -- called also baregin."
"Like glair  or partaking of its qualities; covered with glair; viscous and transparent; slimy."
"A weapon formerly used  consisting of a large blade fixed on the end of a pole whose edge was on the outside curve; also a light lance with a long sharp-pointed head."
"A copious gummy secretion of the humor of the eyelids  in consequence of some disorder; blearedness; lippitude."
"A charm affecting the eye  making objects appear different from what they really are."
"A sudden flash of light or splendor."
"An organ for secreting something to be used in  or eliminated from the body; as the sebaceous glands of the skin; the salivary glands of the mouth."
"The vascular body which forms the apex of the penis  and the extremity of the clitoris."
"To shine with a bright  dazzling light."
"Of a dazzling luster; glaring; bright; shining; smooth."

"A hard  brittle translucent and commonly transparent substance white or colored having a conchoidal fracture and made by fusing together sand or silica with lime potash soda or lead oxide. It is used for window panes and mirrors for articles of table and culinary use for lenses
"Made of glass; vitreous; as  a glassy substance."
"Of or pertaining to the Glaucium or horned poppy; -- formerly applied to an acid derived from it  now known to be fumaric acid."
"A genus of nudibranchiate mollusks  found in the warmer latitudes swimming in the open sea. These mollusks are beautifully colored with blue and silvery white."
"To grope with the hands  as in the dark."
"To furnish (a window  a house a sash a ease etc.) with glass."
"One who applies glazing  as in pottery manufacture etc.; one who gives a glasslike or glossy surface to anything; a calenderer or smoother of cloth paper and the like."
"One whose business is to set glass."
"Having a glazed appearance; -- said of the fractured surface of some kinds of pin iron."
"Darting beams of light; casting light in rays; flashing; coruscating."
"To gather after a reaper; to collect in scattered or fragmentary parcels  as the grain left by a reaper or grapes left after the gathering."
"Pertaining to the glebe; turfy; cloddy; fertile; fruitful."
"The common European kite (Milvus ictinus). This name is also sometimes applied to the buzzard."
"A live or glowing coal; a glede."
"A jest or scoff; a trick or deception."
"A name anciently given to an itinerant minstrel or musician."
"A transparent mucous discharge from the membrane of the urethra  commonly an effect of gonorrhea."
"A secluded and narrow valley; a dale; a depression between hills."

"Having the form of a smooth and shallow depression; socketlike; -- applied to several articular surfaces of bone; as  the glenoid cavity or fossa of the scapula in which the head of the humerus articulates."
"To squint; to look obliquely; to overlook things."
"Vegetable glue or gelatin; glutin. It is one of the constituents of wheat gluten  and is a tough amorphous substance which resembles animal glue or gelatin."
"In a glib manner; as  to speak glibly."
"A transient glance; an unexpected view of something that startles one; a sudden fear."
"To give feeble or scattered rays of light; to shine faintly; to show a faint  unsteady light; as the glimmering dawn; a glimmering lamp."
"A tumor springing from the neuroglia or connective tissue of the brain  spinal cord or other portions of the nervous system."
"To sparkle or shine; especially  to shine with a mild subdued and fitful luster; to emit a soft scintillating light; to gleam; as the glistening stars."
"To be bright; to sparkle; to be brilliant; to shine; to glisten; to glitter."
"To sparkle with light; to shine with a brilliant and broken light or showy luster; to gleam; as  a glittering sword."
"To begin to grow dark; to grow dusky."
"To look steadfastly; to gaze earnestly; -- usually in a bad sense  to gaze with malignant satisfaction passionate desire lust or avarice."
"A round or spherical body  solid or hollow; a body whose surface is in every part equidistant from the center; a ball; a sphere."
"Having a rounded form resembling that of a globe; globular  or nearly so; spherical."
"A little globe; a small particle of matter  of a spherical form."
"Resembling  or pertaining to a globe; round; orbicular."
"To gloom; to look gloomy  morose or sullen."
"Partial or total darkness; thick shade; obscurity; as  the gloom of a forest or of midnight."
"Imperfectly illuminated; dismal through obscurity or darkness; dusky; dim; clouded; as  the cavern was gloomy."
"To surprise or astonish; to be startled or astonished."
"A doxology (beginning Gloria Patri  Glory be to the Father) sung or said at the end of the Psalms in the service of the Roman Catholic and other churches."
"To make glorious by bestowing glory upon; to confer honor and distinction upon; to elevate to power or happiness  or to celestial glory."
"Praise  honor admiration or distinction accorded by common consent to a person or thing; high reputation; honorable fame; renown."
"Brightness or luster of a body proceeding from a smooth surface; polish; as  the gloss of silk; cloth is calendered to give it a gloss."
