"To conceal  or withdraw from sight; to put out of view; to secrete."
"Frightful  shocking or offensive to the eyes; dreadful to behold; as a hideous monster; hideous looks."
"To hasten; to go in haste; -- also often with the reciprocal pronoun."
"In a high manner  or to a high degree; very much; as highly esteemed."
"Loaded dice so contrived as to turn up high numbers."
"A road or way open to the use of the public; a main road or thoroughfare."
"A natural elevation of land  or a mass of earth rising above the common level of the surrounding land; an eminence less than a mountain."
"Abounding with hills; uneven in surface; as  a hilly country."
"A handle; especially  the handle of a sword dagger or the like."
"Having a hilt; -- used in composition; as  basket-hilted cross-hilted."
"The eye of a bean or other seed; the mark or scar at the point of attachment of an ovule or seed to its base or support; -- called also hile."

"An emphasized form of the third person masculine pronoun; -- used as a subject usually with he; as  he himself will bear the blame; used alone in the predicate either in the nominative or objective case; as it is himself who saved himself."
"A Hebrew measure of liquids  containing three quarts one pint one gill English measure."
"The female of the red deer  of which the male is the stag."
"Of or belonging to that part or end which is in the rear  or which follows; as the hinder part of a wagon; the hinder parts of a horse."
"The posterior part of the alimentary canal  including the rectum and sometimes the large intestine also."
"The name given by Europeans to that form of the Hindustani language which is chiefly spoken by native Hindoos. In employs the Devanagari character  in which Sanskrit is written."
"A native inhabitant of Hindostan. As an ethnical term it is confined to the Dravidian and Aryan races; as a religious name it is restricted to followers of the Veda."
"A servant; a farm laborer; a peasant; a hind."
"The hook with its eye  or the joint on which a door gate lid etc. turns or swings; a flexible piece as a strip of leather which serves as a joint to turn on."
"To bring to mind by a slight mention or remote allusion; to suggest in an indirect manner; as  to hint a suspicion."
"The projecting region of the lateral parts of one side of the pelvis and the hip joint; the haunch; the huckle."
"A genus of marine decapod crustaceans  which burrow rapidly in the sand by pushing themselves backward; -- called also bait bug. See Illust. under Anomura."
"Having the hip dislocated; hence  having one hip lower than the other."

"Of  pertaining to or derived from mutton suet; -- applied by Chevreul to an oily acid which was obtained from mutton suet and to which he attributed the peculiar taste and smell of that substance. The substance has also been called hircin."
"Rough with hair; set with bristles; shaggy."
"A genus of leeches  including the common medicinal leech. See Leech."
"A genus of birds including the swallows and martins."
"Belonging or pertaining to him; -- used as a pronominal adjective or adjective pronoun; as  tell John his papers are ready; formerly used also for its but this use is now obsolete."

"To make with the mouth a prolonged sound like that of the letter s  by driving the breath between the tongue and the teeth; to make with the mouth a sound like that made by a goose or a snake when angered; esp. to make such a sound as an expression of hatred passion or disapproval."
"Hush; be silent; -- a signal for silence."
"Resembling the normal tissues; as  histoid tumors."

"A learning or knowing by inquiry; the knowledge of facts and events  so obtained; hence a formal statement of such information; a narrative; a description; a written record; as the history of a patient's case; the history of a legislative bill."
"having become very popular or acclaimed; -- said of entertainment performances; as  a hit record a hit movie."
"To become entangled or caught; to be linked or yoked; to unite; to cling."
"A port or small haven; -- used in composition; as  Lambhithe now Lambeth."
"To this place; -- used with verbs signifying motion  and implying motion toward the speaker; correlate of hence and thither; as to come or bring hither."
"One who hits or strikes; as  a hard hitter."
"A box  basket or other structure for the reception and habitation of a swarm of honeybees."
"One who collects bees into a hive."
"A stop; a halt; a moderation of pace."
"White  or grayish white; as hoar frost; hoar cliffs."
"Having a harsh  rough grating voice or sound as when affected with a cold; making a rough harsh cry or sound; as the hoarse raven."
"A deception for mockery or mischief; a deceptive trick or story; a practical joke."
"A remarkable South American bird (Opisthocomus cristatus); the crested touraco. By some zoologists it is made the type of a distinct order (Opisthocomi)."
"The hub of a wheel. See Hub."

"The philosophical system of Thomas Hobbes  an English materialist (1588-1679); esp. his political theory that the most perfect form of civil government is an absolute monarchy with despotic control over everything relating to law morals and religion."
"One who accepts the doctrines of Thomas Hobbes."
"To walk lame  bearing chiefly on one leg; to walk with a hitch or hop or with crutches."
"Rough; uneven; causing one to hobble; as a hobbly road."
"A small  strong-winged European falcon (Falco subbuteo) formerly trained for hawking."
"A small mortar on a gun carriage  in use before the howitzer."
"A short  sharp-pointed large-headed nail -- used in shoeing houses and for studding the soles of heavy shoes."
"Have or have not; -- a familiar invitation to reciprocal drinking."
"The crested curassow; -- called also royal pheasant. See Curassow."
"A Rhenish wine  of a light yellow color either sparkling or still. The name is also given indiscriminately to all Rhenish wines."
"The joint in the hind limb of quadrupeds between the leg and shank  or tibia and tarsus and corresponding to the ankle in man."
"A holiday commemorating the expulsion of the Danes  formerly observed on the second Tuesday after Easter; -- called also hocktide."
"A game in which two parties of players  armed with sticks curved or hooked at the end attempt to drive any small object (as a ball or a bit of wood) toward opposite goals."
"A kind of wooden tray with a handle  borne on the shoulder for carrying mortar brick etc."
"A man who carries a hod; a mason's tender."

"A tool chiefly for digging up weeds  and arranging the earth about plants in fields and gardens. It is made of a flat blade of iron or steel having an eye or tang by which it is attached to a wooden handle at an acute angle."
"A cake of Indian meal  water and salt baked before the fire or in the ashes; -- so called because often cooked on a hoe."

"A quadruped of the genus Sus  and allied genera of Suidae; esp. the domesticated varieties of S. scrofa kept for their fat and meat called respectively lard and pork; swine; porker; specifically a castrated boar; a barrow."
"An upward curve or very obtuse angle in the upper surface of any member  as of a timber laid horizontally; -- the opposite of camber."
"A large West Indian and Florida food fish (Lachnolaemus)."
"A stocking without a foot  worn by coal miners at work."
"Hoggish character or manners; selfishness; greed; beastliness."
"A young boar of the second year."
"Leather tanned from a hog's skin. Also used adjectively."
"A pen  house or inclosure for hogs."
"To raise; to lift; to elevate; esp.  to raise or lift to a desired elevation by means of tackle as a sail a flag a heavy package or weight."
"To leap; to caper; to romp noisily."
"A large ship of burden  in ancient Greece."
"The whole interior portion of a vessel below the lower deck  in which the cargo is stowed."
"One who is employed in the hold of a vessel."
"A consecrated day; religious anniversary; a day set apart in honor of some person  or in commemoration of some event. See Holyday."
"Piously; with sanctity; in a holy manner."
"Undercutting in a bed of coal  in order to bring down the upper mass."
"A kind of linen first manufactured in Holland; a linen fabric used for window shades  children's garments etc.; as brown or unbleached hollands."
"Ho there; stop; attend; hence  a loud cry or a call to attract attention; a halloo."
"Having an empty space or cavity  natural or artificial within a solid substance; not solid; excavated in the interior; as a hollow tree; a hollow sphere."
"A common evergreen oak  of Europe (Quercus Ilex); -- called also ilex and holly."
"A rare element said to be contained in gadolinite."
"A name given to a vase having a rounded body"
"A leather case for a pistol  carried by a horseman at the bow of his saddle."
"3d pers. sing. pres. of Hold  contr. from holdeth."
"Set apart to the service or worship of God; hallowed; sacred; reserved from profane or common use; holy vessels; a holy priesthood."

"A symbolical acknowledgment made by a feudal tenant to  and in the presence of his lord on receiving investiture of fee or coming to it by succession that he was his man or vassal; profession of fealty to a sovereign."
"One who does homage  or holds land of another by homage; a vassal."
"A genus of decapod Crustacea  including the common lobsters."
"Belonging to  or having the characteristics of home; domestic; familiar; intimate."
"The European sand ray (Raia maculata); -- called also home  mirror ray and rough ray."
"A carrier pigeon remarkable for its ability to return home from a distance."
"Of or pertaining to Homer  the most famous of Greek poets; resembling the poetry of Homer."
"A discourse or sermon read or pronounced to an audience; a serious discourse."
"Maize hulled and broken  and prepared for food by being boiled in water."
"Like a home or a home circle."
"A small eminence of a conical form  of land or of ice; a knoll; a hillock. See Hummock."
"A word having the same sound as another  but differing from it in meaning; as the noun bear and the verb bear."
"A sweet viscid fluid  esp. that collected by bees from flowers of plants and deposited in the cells of the honeycomb."
"A mercantile establishment or factory for foreign trade in China  as formerly at Canton; a succession of offices connected by a common passage and used for business or storage."
"Esteem due or paid to worth; high estimation; respect; consideration; reverence; veneration; manifestation of respect or reverence."
"A young rowdy; a rough  lawless fellow."
"The person blindfolded in the game called hoodman-blind."
"The hooded crow; also  in Scotland the hooded gull."
"The horny substance or case that covers or terminates the feet of certain animals  as horses oxen etc."

"A piece of metal  or other hard material formed or bent into a curve or at an angle for catching holding or sustaining anything; as a hook for catching fish; a hook for fastening a gate; a boat hook etc."
"A pipe with a long  flexible stem so arranged that the smoke is cooled by being made to pass through water."
"A small black gibbon (Hylobates hoolock)  found in the mountains of Assam."
"A pliant strip of wood or metal bent in a circular form  and united at the ends for holding together the staves of casks tubs etc."
"One who hoops casks or tubs; a cooper."

"A European bird of the genus Upupa (U. epops)  having a beautiful crest which it can erect or depress at pleasure. Called also hoop whoop. The name is also applied to several other species of the same genus and allied genera."
"A nickname given to an inhabitant of the State of Indiana."
"To cry out or shout in contempt."
"A disease in cattle consisting in inflammation of the stomach by gas  ordinarily caused by eating too much green food; tympany; bloating."
"To move by successive leaps  as toads do; to spring or jump on one foot; to skip as birds do."
"Full of hope  or agreeable expectation; inclined to hope; expectant."
"A hydrous phosphate of zinc in transparent prismatic crystals."
"A hand basket; also  a dish used by miners for measuring ore."
"To impede by a hopple; to tie the feet of (a horse or a cow) loosely together; to hamper; to hobble; as  to hopple an unruly or straying horse."
"A collector of customs  as at Canton; an overseer of commerce."
"Of or pertaining to an hour  or to hours."
"Of or pertaining to an hour; noting the hours."
"A wandering troop or gang; especially  a clan or tribe of a nomadic people migrating from place to place for the sake of pasturage plunder etc.; a predatory multitude."
"Pertaining to  or derived from barley; as hordeic acid an acid identical or isomeric with lauric acid."
"A peculiar starchy matter contained in barley. It is complex mixture."
"An unidentified plant mentioned by Shakespeare  perhaps equivalent to burdock."
"The circle which bounds that part of the earth's surface visible to a spectator from a given point; the apparent junction of the earth and sky."

"A hard  projecting and usually pointed organ growing upon the heads of certain animals esp. of the ruminants as cattle goats and the like. The hollow horns of the Ox family consist externally of true horn and are never shed."
"A large nocturnal beetle of the genus Lucanus (as L. capreolus  and L. dama) having long curved upper jaws resembling a sickle. The grubs are found in the trunks of old trees."
"Furnished with a horn or horns; furnished with a hornlike process or appendage; as  horned cattle; having some part shaped like a horn."
"One who works or deal in horn or horns."

"A large  strong wasp. The European species (Vespa crabro) is of a dark brown and yellow color. It is very pugnacious and its sting is very severe. Its nest is constructed of a paperlike material and the layers of comb are hung together by columns. The American white-faced hornet (V. maculata) is larger and has similar habits."
"Appearance of the moon when increasing  or in the form of a crescent."
"A low  oven-shaped mound common in volcanic regions and emitting smoke and vapors from its sides and summit."
"Standing erect  as bristles; covered with bristling points; bristled; bristling."
"To cause to feel horror; to strike or impress with horror; as  the sight horrified the beholders."
"A bristling up; a rising into roughness; tumultuous movement."

"A hoofed quadruped of the genus Equus; especially  the domestic horse (E. caballus) which was domesticated in Egypt and Asia at a very early period. It has six broad molars on each side of each jaw with six incisors and two canine teeth both above and below. The mares usually have the canine teeth rudimentary or wanting. The horse differs from the true asses in having a long flowing mane and the tail bushy to the base. Unlike the asses it has callosities or chestnuts on all its legs. The horse excels in strength
"Pertaining to  or suggestive of a horse or of horse racing; as horsy manners; garments of fantastically horsy fashions."
"A Hebrew exclamation of praise to the Lord  or an invocation of blessings."
"One who deals in hose or stocking  or in goods knit or woven like hose."
"A convent or monastery which is also a place of refuge or entertainment for travelers on some difficult road or pass  as in the Alps; as the Hospice of the Great St. Bernard."
"The consecrated wafer  believed to be the body of Christ which in the Mass is offered as a sacrifice; also the bread before consecration."
"A person given as a pledge or security for the performance of the conditions of a treaty or stipulations of any kind  on the performance of which the person is to be released."
"A female host; a woman who hospitably entertains guests at her house."

"Belonging or appropriate to an enemy; showing the disposition of an enemy; showing ill will and malevolence  or a desire to thwart and injure; occupied by an enemy or enemies; inimical; unfriendly; as a hostile force; hostile intentions; a hostile country; hostile to a sudden change."
"A hostelry; an inn or lodging house."
"A bed of earth heated by fermenting manure or other substances  and covered with glass intended for raising early plants or for nourishing exotics."
"A house for entertaining strangers or travelers; an inn or public house  of the better class."
"In a hot or fiery manner; ardently; vehemently; violently; hastily; as  a hotly pursued."
"The quality or state of being hot."
"A piece of woodland; a small wood. [Obs.] See Holt."

"A variety of the domestic dog  usually having large drooping ears esp. one which hunts game by scent as the foxhound bloodhound deerhound but also used for various breeds of fleet hunting dogs as the greyhound boarhound etc."
"The twenty-fourth part of a day; sixty minutes."
"A nymph of paradise; -- so called by the Mohammedans."
"Happening or done every hour; occurring hour by hour; frequent; often repeated; renewed hour by hour; continual."
"Goddess of the seasons  or of the hours of the day."
"A fee for keeping goods in a house."
"A structure intended or used as a habitation or shelter for animals of any kind; but especially  a building or edifice for the habitation of man; a dwelling place a mansion."
"A head covering of various kinds; a hood; a coif; a cap."
"An open shed for sheltering cattle  or protecting produce etc. from the weather."
"One who assists in saving life and property from a wreck; a coast boatman."
"A device in an incubator for protecting the young chickens and keeping them warm."
"In what manner or way; by what means or process."
"Be it as it may; nevertheless; notwithstanding; although; albeit; yet; but; however."
"A seat or pavilion  generally covered fastened on the back of an elephant for the rider or riders."
"A tool used by coopers for smoothing and chamfering rheir work  especially the inside of casks."
"The upper stage of a porcelian furnace."
"To utter a loud  protraced mournful sound or cry as dogs and wolves often do."
"A small coaster vessel  usually sloop-rigged used in conveying passengers and goods from place to place or as a tender to larger vessels in port."
"The central part  usually cylindrical of a wheel; the nave. See Illust. of Axle box."
"A loud noise of many confused voices; a tumult; uproar."
"Full of hubs or protuberances; as  a road that has been frozen while muddy is hubby."
"A mineral of brownish black color  occurring in columnar or foliated masses. It is native manganese tungstate."
"A large salmon (Salmo  / Salvelinus hucho) inhabiting the Danube; -- called also huso and bull trout."
"A huck or hull  as of a nut."
"To press together promiscuously  from confusion apprehension or the like; to crowd together confusedly; to press or hurry in disorder; to crowd."
"An iron bucket for hoisting coal or ore."
"Color or shade of color; tint; dye."
"Having color; -- usually in composition; as  bright-hued; many-hued."
"One who cries out or gives an alarm; specifically  a balker; a conder. See Balker."
"To swell; to enlarge; to puff up; as  huffed up with air."
"Disposed to be blustering or arrogant; petulant."
"To cower; to crouch; to curl up."
"Very large; enormous; immense; excessive; -- used esp. of material bulk  but often of qualities extent etc.; as a huge ox; a huge space; a huge difference."
"An outer garment worn in Europe in the Middle Ages."
"The body of a ship or decked vessel of any kind; esp.  the body of an old vessel laid by as unfit for service."
"The outer covering of anything  particularly of a nut or of grain; the outer skin of a kernel; the husk."
"One who  or that which hulls; especially an agricultural machine for removing the hulls from grain; a hulling machine."
"To make a low  prolonged sound like that of a bee in flight; to drone; to murmur; to buzz; as a top hums."
"Belonging to man or mankind; having the qualities or attributes of a man; of or pertaining to man or to the race of man; as  a human voice; human shape; human nature; human sacrifices."
"In a human manner; after the manner of men; according to the knowledge or wisdom of men; as  the present prospects humanly speaking promise a happy issue."
"Near the ground; not high or lofty; not pretentious or magnificent; unpretending; unassuming; as  a humble cottage."
"One who  or that which humbles some one."
"An imposition under fair pretenses; something contrived in order to deceive and mislead; a trick by cajolery; a hoax."
"Of or pertaining to the humerus  or upper part of the arm; brachial."
"The bone of the brachium  or upper part of the arm or fore limb."
"Pertaining to  or derived from vegetable mold; as humic acid. See Humin."
"Containing sensible moisture; damp; moist; as  a humidair or atmosphere; somewhat wet or watery; as humid earth; consisting of water or vapor."

"A bitter  brownish yellow amorphous substance extracted from vegetable mold and also produced by the action of acids on certain sugars and carbohydrates; -- called also humic acid ulmin gein ulmic or geic acid etc."
"A fragrant balsam obtained from Brazilian trees of the genus Humirium."
"A mineral of a transparent vitreous brown color  found in the ejected masses of Vesuvius. It is a silicate of iron and magnesia containing fluorine."
"To separate from the awns; -- said of barley."
"One who  or that which hums; one who applauds by humming."
"A rounded knoll or hillock; a rise of ground of no great extent  above a level surface."
"A sweating bath or place for sweating."
"Moisture  especially the moisture or fluid of animal bodies as the chyle lymph etc.; as the humors of the eye etc."
"Pertaining to  or proceeding from the humors; as a humoral fever."
"A protuberance; especially  the protuberance formed by a crooked back."
"An exclamation denoting surprise  or contempt doubt etc."
"Full of humps or bunches; covered with protuberances; humped."
"That portion of the soil formed by the decomposition of animal or vegetable matter. It is a valuable constituent of soils."
"One of a warlike nomadic people of Northern Asia who  in the 5th century under Atilla invaded and conquered a great part of Europe."

"The product of ten mulitplied by ten  or the number of ten times ten; a collection or sum consisting of ten times ten units or objects; five score. Also a symbol representing one hundred units as 100 or C."
"A country in Central Europe  now a part of the Austro-Hungarian Empire."
"An uneasy sensation occasioned normally by the want of food; a craving or desire for food."
"Feeling hunger; having a keen appetite; feeling uneasiness or distress from want of food; hence  having an eager desire."
"A large lump or piece; a hunch; as  a hunk of bread."
"Originally  a nickname for a member of the conservative section of the Democratic party in New York; hence one opposed to progress in general; a fogy."
"A covetous  sordid man; a miser; a niggard."
"To search for or follow after  as game or wild animals; to chase; to pursue for the purpose of catching or killing; to follow with dogs or guns for sport or exercise; as to hunt a deer."
"One who hunts wild animals either for sport or for food; a huntsman."
"A coarse kind of linen; -- called also harden."

"A movable frame of wattled twigs  osiers or withes and stakes or sometimes of iron used for inclosing land for folding sheep and cattle for gates etc.; also in fortification used as revetments and for other purposes."
"The coarse part of flax or hemp; hards."
"In India  a running footman; a messenger."
"To send whirling or whizzing through the air; to throw with violence; to drive with great force; as  to hurl a stone or lance."
"One who hurls  or plays at hurling."

"; sing. Huron. (Ethnol.) A powerful and warlike tribe of North American Indians of the Algonquin stock. They formerly occupied the country between Lakes Huron  Erie and Ontario but were nearly exterminated by the Five Nations about 1650."
"To make a rolling or burring sound."
"A word used as a shout of joy  triumph applause encouragement or welcome."
"Urged on; hastened; going or working at speed; as  a hurried writer; a hurried life."
"A staith or framework from which coal is discharged from cars into vessels."
"To hasten; to impel to greater speed; to urge on."
"A wood or grove; -- a word used in the composition of many names  as in Hazlehurst."
"A band on a trip-hammer helve  bearing the trunnions."
"A bodily injury causing pain; a wound  bruise or the like."
"Tending to impair or damage; injurious; mischievous; occasioning loss or injury; as  hurtful words or conduct."
"To meet with violence or shock; to clash; to jostle."
"The male head of a household; one who orders the economy of a family."
"To still; to silence; to calm; to make quiet; to repress the noise or clamor of."
"The external covering or envelope of certain fruits or seeds; glume; hull; rind; in the United States  especially applied to the covering of the ears of maize."

"A large European sturgeon (Acipenser huso)  inhabiting the region of the Black and Caspian Seas. It sometimes attains a length of more than twelve feet and a weight of two thousand pounds. Called also hausen."
"Originally  one of the national cavalry of Hungary and Croatia; now one of the light cavalry of European armies."
"A follower of John Huss  the Bohemian reformer who was adjudged a heretic and burnt alive in 1415."
"To shake together in confusion; to push  jostle or crowd rudely; to handle roughly; as to hustle a person out of a room."
"A female housekeeper; a woman who manages domestic affairs; a thirfty woman."
"A small house  hivel or cabin; a mean lodge or dwelling; a slightly built or temporary structure."
"To place in huts; to live in huts; as  to hut troops in winter quarters."
"A word used as a shout of joy  exultation approbation or encouragement."
"A cluster of five stars in the face of the constellation Taurus  supposed by the ancients to indicate the coming of rainy weather when they rose with the sun."
"A pteroid of the genus Cavolina. See Pteropoda  and Illustration in Appendix."
"Glassy; resembling glass; consisting of glass; transparent  like crystal."
"A pellucid variety of opal in globules looking like colorless gum or resin; -- called also Muller's glass."
"Resembling glass; vitriform; transparent; hyaline; as  the hyaloid membrane a very delicate membrane inclosing the vitreous humor of the eye."
"An extinct genus of sharks having conical  compressed teeth."
"The offspring of the union of two distinct species; an animal or plant produced from the mixture of two species. See Mongrel."

"A membranous sac or bladder filled with a pellucid fluid  found in various parts of the bodies of animals but unconnected with the tissues. It is usually formed by parasitic worms esp. by larval tapeworms as Echinococcus and Coenurus. See these words in the Vocabulary."

"A serpent or monster in the lake or marsh of Lerna  in the Peloponnesus represented as having many heads one of which when cut off was immediately succeeded by two others unless the wound was cauterized. It was slain by Hercules. Hence a terrible monster."
"A discharge pipe with a valve and spout at which water may be drawn from the mains of waterworks; a water plug."
"A compound formed by the union of water with some other substance  generally forming a neutral body as certain crystallized salts."
"A water jar; esp.  one with a large rounded body a small neck and three handles. Some of the most beautiful Greek vases are of this form."
"Pertaining to  or containing hydrogen; as hydric oxide."
"A compound of the binary type  in which hydrogen is united with some other element."
"The group of hydroids to which the fresh-water hydras belong."
"Related to  or resembling the hydra; of or pertaining to the Hydroidea."
"A constellation of the southern hemisphere  near the south pole."
"Any carnivorous mammal of the family Hyaenidae  of which three living species are known. They are large and strong but cowardly. They feed chiefly on carrion and are nocturnal in their habits."
"Of or pertaining to rain; descriptive of the distribution of rain  or of rainy regions."
"The goddess of health  daughter of Esculapius."
"Relating to Hygeia  the goddess of health; of or pertaining to health or its preservation."
"That department of sanitary science which treats of the preservation of health  esp. of households and communities; a system of principles or rules designated for the promotion of health."
"An alkaloid associated with cocaine in coca leaves (Erythroxylon coca)  and extracted as a thick yellow oil having a pungent taste and odor."
"Of or pertaining to matter; material; corporeal; as  hylic influences."
"A theory which regards matter as the original principle of evil."
"The piping frog (Hyla Pickeringii)  a small American tree frog which in early spring while breeding in swamps and ditches sings with high shrill but musical notes."
"A fold of muscous membrane often found at the orifice of the vagina; the vaginal membrane."
"An ode or song of praise or adoration; especially  a religious ode a sacred lyric; a song of praise or thankgiving intended to be used in religious service; as the Homeric hymns; Watts' hymns."
"A collection of hymns; a hymn book."
"Having the form of an arch  or of the Greek letter upsilon [/]."
"An abbreviation of hypochonaria; -- usually in plural."

"The long  branching filaments of which the mycelium (and the greater part of the plant) of a fungus is formed. They are also found enveloping the gonidia of lichens making up a large part of their structure."

"A mark or short dash  thus [-] placed at the end of a line which terminates with a syllable of a word the remainder of which is carried to the next line; or between the parts of many a compound word; as in fine-leaved clear-headed. It is also sometimes used to separate the syllables of words."
"The largest genus of true mosses; feather moss."
"Under the tail; -- applied to the bones which support the caudal fin rays in most fishes."

"Any animal of the genus Hyrax  of which about four species are known. They constitute the order Hyracoidea. The best known species are the daman (H. Syriacus) of Palestine and the klipdas (H. capensis) of South Africa. Other species are H. arboreus and H. Sylvestris the former from Southern and the latter from Western Africa. See Daman."
"Of or pertaining to Hyrcania  an ancient country or province of Asia southeast of the Caspian (which was also called the Hyrcanian) Sea."
"A plant (Hyssopus officinalis). The leaves have an aromatic smell  and a warm pungent taste."
"A genus of rodents  including the porcupine."
"Consisting of a short syllable followed by a long one  or of an unaccented syllable followed by an accented; as an iambic foot."
"A foot consisting of a short syllable followed by a long one  as in /mans or of an unaccented syllable followed by an accented one as invent; an iambic. See the Couplet under Iambic n."
"One of several species of wild goats having very large  recurved horns transversely ridged in front; -- called also steinbok."
"In the same place; -- abbreviated ibid. or ib."

"Any bird of the genus Ibis and several allied genera  of the family Ibidae inhabiting both the Old World and the New. Numerous species are known. They are large wading birds having a long curved beak and feed largely on reptiles."
"Soaring too high for safety  like Icarus; adventurous in flight."

"Water or other fluid frozen or reduced to the solid state by cold; frozen water. It is a white or transparent colorless substance  crystalline brittle and viscoidal. Its specific gravity (0.92 that of water at 4� C. being 1.0) being less than that of water ice floats."
"A large mass of ice  generally floating in the ocean."
"An Arctic sea bird  as the Arctic fulmar."
"A frozen waterfall  or mass of ice resembling a frozen waterfall."
"A man who is skilled in traveling upon ice  as among glaciers."
"A fossil footprint; as  the ichnites in the Triassic sandstone."
"An ethereal fluid that supplied the place of blood in the veins of the gods."
"A nitrogenous substance resembling vitellin  present in the egg yolk of cartilaginous fishes."
"In early Christian and eccesiastical art  an emblematic fish or the Greek word for fish which combined the initials of the Greek words / / / / / Jesus Christ Son of God Savior."
"A pendent  and usually conical mass of ice formed by freezing of dripping water; as the icicles on the eaves of a house."
"The state or quality of being icy or very cold; frigidity."
"An image or representation; a portrait or pretended portrait."
"The formation of a figure  representation or semblance; a delineation or description."
"To form an image or likeness of."
"Pertaining to  or caused by a blow; sudden; abrupt."
"The stress of voice laid upon accented syllable of a word. Cf. Arsis."
"Pertaining to  resembling or abounding in ice; cold; frosty."
"A contraction from I would or I had."
"Of or pertaining to Idalium  a mountain city in Cyprus or to Venus to whom it was sacred."
"The transcript  image or picture of a visible object that is formed by the mind; also a similar image of any object whatever whether sensible or spiritual."
"Existing in idea or thought; conceptional; intellectual; mental; as  ideal knowledge."
"In an ideal manner; by means of ideals; mentally."
"The actual existence supposed to correspond with an idea; the correlate in real existence to the idea as a thought or existence."
"The same; the same as above; -- often abbreviated id."
"The fifteenth day of March  May July and October and the thirteenth day of the other months."
"The condition or quality of being an idiot; absence  or marked deficiency of sense and intelligence."
"The syntactical or structural form peculiar to any language; the genius or cast of a language."
"A man in private station  as distinguished from one holding a public office."
"Of no account; useless; vain; trifling; unprofitable; thoughtless; silly; barren."
"One who idles; one who spends his time in inaction; a lazy person; a sluggard."
"In a idle manner; ineffectually; vainly; lazily; carelessly; (Obs.) foolishly."
"To make an idol of; to pay idolatrous worship to; as  to idolize the sacred bull in Egypt."
"A morphological unit  consisting of two or more plastids which does not possess the positive character of the person or stock in distinction from the physiological organ or biorgan. See Morphon."
"Of or pertaining to ancient Idumea  or Edom in Western Asia."

"A short poem; properly  a short pastoral poem; as the idyls of Theocritus; also any poem especially a narrative or descriptive poem written in an eleveted and highly finished style; also by extension any artless and easily flowing description either in poetry or prose of simple rustic life of pastoral scenes
"Abbreviation of Latin id est  that is."
"Pertaining to  having the nature of fire; containing fire; resembling fire; as an igneous appearance."
"To kindle or set on fire; as  to ignite paper or wood."
"One who  or that which produces ignition; especially a contrivance for igniting the powder in a torpedo or the like."
"Of low birth or family; not noble; not illustrious; plebeian; common; humble."
"To be ignorant of or not acquainted with."
"Any species of the genus Iguana  a genus of large American lizards of the family Iguanidae. They are arboreal in their habits usually green in color and feed chiefly upon fruits."
"The peculiar dress worn by pilgrims to Mecca."
"The last  and usually the longest division of the small intestine; the part between the jejunum and large intestine."

"A morbid condition due to intestinal obstruction. It is characterized by complete constipation  with griping pains in the abdomen which is greatly distended and in the later stages by vomiting of fecal matter. Called also ileac / iliac passion."
"A celebrated Greek epic poem  in twenty-four books on the destruction of Ilium the ancient Troy. The Iliad is ascribed to Homer."
"Pertaining to  or derived from the holly (Ilex) and allied plants; as ilicic acid."
"The dorsal one of the three principal bones comprising either lateral half of the pelvis; the dorsal or upper part of the hip bone. See Innominate bone  under Innominate."
"Contrary to good  in a physical sense; contrary or opposed to advantage happiness etc.; bad; evil; unfortunate; disagreeable; unfavorable."
"Contraction for I will or I shall."
"To fall or glide; to pass; -- usually followed by into."
"Not according to  or authorized by law; specif. contrary to or in violation of human law; unlawful; illicit; hence immoral; as an illegal act; illegal trade; illegal love."
"Not permitted or allowed; prohibited; unlawful; as  illicit trade; illicit intercourse; illicit pleasure."
"The condition of being ill  evil or bad; badness; unfavorableness."
"To play upon by artifice; to deceive; to mock; to excite and disappoint the hopes of."
"To throw or spread light upon; to make light or bright; to illuminate; to illumine."
"A silicate of iron and lime occurring in black prismatic crystals and columnar masses."

"An imitation  representation or similitude of any person thing or act sculptured drawn painted or otherwise made perceptible to the sight; a visible presentation; a copy; a likeness; an effigy; a picture; a semblance."
"One who images or forms likenesses; a sculptor."
"The work of one who makes images or visible representation of objects; imitation work; images in general  or in mass."
"To form in the mind a notion or idea of; to form a mental image of; to conceive; to produce by the imagination."
"Among the Mohammedans  a minister or priest who performs the regular service of the mosque."
"To form into a band or bands."
"To inclose or defend with a bank or banks. See Embank."
"To bathe; to wash freely; to immerce."
"To sink or lay  as in a bed; to deposit in a partly inclosing mass as of clay or mortar; to cover as with earth sand etc."
"To drink in; to absorb; to suck or take in; to receive as by drinking; as  a person imbibes drink or a sponge imbibes moisture."
"To become corporeal; to assume the qualities of a material body. See Embody."
"To conceal  as in bushes; to hide."
"To hold in the bosom; to cherish in the heart or affection; to embosom."
"To inclose in limits; to shut in."
"To make like a bow; to curve; to arch; to vault; to embow."
"To make brown; to obscure; to darken; to tan; as  features imbrowned by exposure."
"To wet or moisten; to soak; to drench  especially in blood."
"To degrade to the state of a brute; to make brutal."
"To tinge deeply; to dye; to cause to absorb; as  clothes thoroughly imbued with black."

"A compound with  or derivative of the imido group; specif. a compound of one or more acid radicals with the imido group or with a monamine; hence also a derivative of ammonia in which two atoms of hydrogen have been replaced by divalent basic or acid radicals; -- frequently used as a combining form; as succinimide."
"Pertaining to  containing or combined with the radical NH which is called the imido group."
"To follow as a pattern  model or example; to copy or strive to copy in acts manners etc."
"Very great; huge; vast; also  monstrous in character; inhuman; atrocious; fierce."
"To cover  as with a mask; to disguise or conceal."
"Immeasurable; unlimited. In commonest use: Very great; vast; huge."
"To plungel into  under or within anything especially a fuid; to dip; to immerse. See Immerse."
"To catch or entangle in  or as in the meshes of a net. or in a web; to insnare."
"To send in; to inject; to infuse; -- the correlative of emit."
"Not moral; inconsistent with rectitude  purity or good morals; contrary to conscience or the divine law; wicked; unjust; dishonest; vicious; licentious; as an immoral man; an immoral deed."
"To wall around; to surround with walls."
"A shoot; a scion; a bud; a slip; a graft."
"To drive close; to press firmly together: to wedge into a place."
"To make worse; to diminish in quantity  value excellence or strength; to deteriorate; as to impair health character the mind value."
"To pierce with a pale; to put to death by fixing on a sharp stake. See Empale."
"To grasp with or hold in the hand."
"To enter in a list  or on a piece of parchment called a panel; to form or enroll as a list of jurors in a court of justice."
"To inclose for a park; to sever from a common; hence  to inclose or shut up."
"To bestow a share or portion of; to give  grant or communicate; to allow another to partake in; as to impart food to the poor; the sun imparts warmth."
"To knead; to make into paste; to concrete."
"The thickness of the layer or body of pigment applied by the painter to his canvas with especial reference to the juxtaposition of different colors and tints in forming a harmonious whole."
"To form into pearls  or into that which resembles pearls."
"To hinder; to stop in progress; to obstruct; as  to impede the advance of troops."
"To drive or urge forward or on; to press on; to incite to action or motion in any way."
"To shut up or inclose  as in a pen."
"To affict with pestilence; to infect  as with plague."
"A property possessed by a moving body in virtue of its weight and its motion; the force with which any body is driven or impelled; momentum."
"The African sugar cane (Holcus saccharatus)  -- resembling the sorghum or Chinese sugar cane."
"The quality of being impious; want of piety; irreverence toward the Supreme Being; ungodliness; wickedness."
"To fall or dash against; to touch upon; to strike; to hit; to ciash with; -- with on or upon."
"Not pious; wanting piety; irreligious; irreverent; ungodly; profane; wanting in reverence for the Supreme Being; as  an impious deed; impious language."
"To plant  or infix for the purpose of growth; to fix deeply; to instill; to inculate; to introduce; as to implant the seeds of virtue or the principles of knowledge in the minds of youth."
"To cover with plates; to sheathe; as  to implate a ship with iron."
"To institute and prosecute a suit against  in court; to sue or prosecute at law; hence to accuse; to impeach."
"Virtually involved or included; involved in substance; inferential; tacitly conceded; -- the correlative of express  or expressed. See Imply."

"To call upon  or for in supplication; to beseech; to prey to or for earnestly; to petition with urency; to entreat; to beg; -- followed directly by the word expressing the thing sought or the person from whom it is sought."
"To infold or involve; to wrap up."

"To bring in from abroad; to introduce from without; especially  to bring (wares or merchandise) into a place or country from a foreign country in the transactions of commerce; -- opposed to export. We import teas from China coffee from Brasil etc."
"To lay on; to set or place; to put; to deposit."
"That which is imposed or levied; a tax  tribute or duty; especially a duty or tax laid by goverment on goods imported into a country."
"To shut up or place in an inclosure called a pound; hence  to hold in the custody of a court; as to impound stray cattle; to impound a document for safe keeping."
"A device on a shield or seal  or used as a bookplate or the like."
"To press  stamp or print something in or upon; to mark by pressure or as by pressure; to imprint (that which bears the impression)."
"To impress; to mark by pressure; to indent; to stamp."
"To disprove or make void; to refute."
"To attack by words or arguments; to contradict; to assail; to call in question; to make insinuations against; to gainsay; to oppose."
"The act of impelling  or driving onward with sudden force; impulsion; especially force so communicated as to produced motion suddenly or immediately."

"Not pure; not clean; dirty; foul; filthy; containing something which is unclean or unwholesome; mixed or impregnated extraneous substances; adulterated; as  impure water or air; impure drugs food etc."
"To charge; to ascribe; to attribute; to set to the account of; to charge to one as the author  responsible originator or possessor; -- generally in a bad sense."
"A peculiar strong soup or broth  made in Scotland."
"Without contents; empty; void of sense or intelligence; purposeless; pointless; characterless; useless."
"To graft by uniting  as a scion to a stock without separating either from its root before the union is complete; -- also called to graft by approach."
"To embark; to go or put into a barge."
"Inside the line of a vessel's bulwarks or hull; the opposite of outboard; as  an inboard cargo; haul the boom inboard."
"Born in or with; implanted by nature; innate; as  inborn passions."
"A Japanese measure of length equal to about two and one twelfth yards."
"An emperor or monarch of Peru before  or at the time of the Spanish conquest; any member of this royal dynasty reputed to have been descendants of the sun."
"To confine in  or as in a cage; to coop up."
"To inclose in a case; to inclose; to cover or surround with something solid."
"To cover with a casque or as with a casque."
"To set on fire; to inflame; to kindle; to burn."
"The crime of cohabitation or sexual commerce between persons related within the degrees wherein marriage is prohibited by law."
"An island; -- often used in the names of small islands off the coast of Scotland  as in Inchcolm Inchkeith etc."
"To cut; to separate and remove; to resolve or break up  as by medicines."
"To cut in or into with a sharp instrument; to carve; to engrave."
"One of the teeth in front of the canines in either jaw; an incisive tooth. See Tooth."
"To move to action; to stir up; to rouse; to spur or urge on."
"To clasp within; to hold fast to; to embrace or encircle."
"Resembling a series of dovetails; -- said of a line of division  such as the border of an ordinary."
"To deviate from a line  direction or course toward an object; to lean; to tend; as converging lines incline toward each other; a road inclines to the north or south."
"To surround; to shut in; to confine on all sides; to include; to shut up; to encompass; as  to inclose a fort or an army with troops; to inclose a town with walls."
"To envelop as in clouds; to darken; to obscure."
"To confine within; to hold; to contain; to shut up; to inclose; as  the shell of a nut includes the kernel; a pearl is included in a shell."
"A tribe of bivalve mollusks  characterized by the closed state of the mantle which envelops the body. The ship borer (Teredo navalis) is an example."
"A coming in; entrance; admittance; ingress; infusion."
"To cover or line with a crust  or hard coat; to form a crust on the surface of; as iron incrusted with rust; a vessel incrusted with salt; a sweetmeat incrusted with sugar."
"To fix firmly  as in cube; to secure or place firmly."
"A demon; a fiend; a lascivious spirit  supposed to have sexual intercourse with women by night."

"To meet or fall in with  as something inconvenient harmful or onerous; to put one's self in the way of; to expose one's self to; to become liable or subject to; to bring down upon one's self; to encounter; to contract; as to incur debt danger displeasure/ penalty responsibility etc."
"To bend; to curve; to make crooked."
"Cut or stamped in  or hollowed out by engraving."
"To form  or mold by striking or stamping as a coin or medal."
"A nitrogenous compound  C7H6N2 analogous to indol and produced from a diazo derivative or cinnamic acid."
"To bring into debt; to place under obligation; -- chiefly used in the participle indebted."

"In reality; in truth; in fact; verily; truly; -- used in a variety of sense. Esp.: (a) Denoting emphasis; as  indeed it is so. (b) Denoting concession or admission; as indeed you are right. (c) Denoting surprise; as indeed is it you? Its meaning is not intrinsic or fixed but depends largely on the form of expression which it accompanies."
"To notch; to jag; to cut into points like a row of teeth; as  to indent the edge of paper."
"That which points out; that which shows  indicates manifests or discloses."
"A country in Southern Asia; the two peninsulas of Hither and Farther India; in a restricted sense  Hither India or Hindostan."
"Of or pertaining to India proper; also to the East Indies  or sometimes to the West Indies."

"A glucoside obtained from woad (indigo plant) and other plants  as a yellow or light brown sirup. It has a nauseous bitter taste a decomposes or drying. By the action of acids ferments etc. it breaks down into sugar and indigo. It is the source of natural indigo."
"To write; to compose; to dictate; to indite."
"A name designating the East Indies  also the West Indies."
"A kind of deep blue  one of the seven prismatic colors."
"A dark red crystalline substance  isomeric with and resembling indigo blue and obtained from isatide and dioxindol."
"To bury in  or cast into a ditch."
"To compose; to write; to be author of; to dictate; to prompt."

"A rare metallic element  discovered in certain ores of zinc by means of its characteristic spectrum of two indigo blue lines; hence its name. In appearance it resembles zinc being white or lead gray soft malleable and easily fusible but in its chemical relation it resembles aluminium or gallium. Symbol In. Atomic weight 113.4."
"A complex  nitrogenous radical C8H5NO regarded as the essential nucleus of indigo."
"A substance resembling indigo blue  obtained artificially from certain isatogen compounds."

"A white  crystalline substance C8H7N obtained from blue indigo and almost all indigo derivatives by a process of reduction. It is also formed from albuminous matter together with skatol by putrefaction and by fusion with caustic potash and is present in human excrement as well as in the intestinal canal of some herbivora."
"A dark resinous substance  polymeric with indol and obtained by the reduction of indigo white."
"Done or being within doors; within a house or institution; domestic; as  indoor work."
"Within the house; -- usually separated  in doors."
"To cover the back of; to load or burden."
"A nitrogenous substance  C8H7NO isomeric with oxindol obtained as an oily liquid."
"Any lemurine animal of the genus Indris."
"One who  or that which induces or incites."
"To bring in; to introduce; to usher in."
"To put on  as clothes; to draw on."
"To be complacent toward; to give way to; not to oppose or restrain"
"A privilege or exemption; an indulgence; a dispensation granted by the pope."
"To dwell in; to abide within; to remain in possession."
"An arrow poison  made from an apocynaceous plant (Strophanthus hispidus) of the Gaboon country; -- called also onaye."
"Not apt or fit; unfit; unsuitable; improper; unbecoming."
"Unarmed; destitute of prickles or thorns  as a leaf."
"Destitute of the power of moving itself  or of active resistance to motion; as matter is inert."

"That property of matter by which it tends when at rest to remain so  and when in motion to continue in motion and in the same straight line or direction unless acted on by some external force; -- sometimes called vis inertiae."
"In being; actually existing; -- distinguished from in posse  or in potentia which denote that a thing is not but may be."
"Not exact; not precisely correct or true; inaccurate."
"To ingraft  as a tree or plant by the insertion of a bud or eye; to inoculate."
"Total loss of reputation; public disgrace; dishonor; ignominy; indignity."
"The state or period of being an infant; the first part of life; early childhood."
"A child in the first period of life  beginning at his birth; a young babe; sometimes a child several years of age."
"A title borne by every one of the daughters of the kings of Spain and Portugal  except the eldest."
"A title given to every one of sons of the kings of Spain and Portugal  except the eldest or heir apparent."
"A house-warming; especially  a reception party or entertainment given by a newly married couple or by the husband upon receiving the wife to his house."
"To bring on; to induce; to occasion."
"Not holding the faith; -- applied esp. to one who does not believe in the inspiration of the Scriptures  and the supernatural origin of Christianity."
"To arrange in a file or rank; to place in order."
"To cover with a film; to coat thinly; as  to infilm one metal with another in the process of gilding; to infilm the glass of a mirror."
"Not firm or sound; weak; feeble; as  an infirm body; an infirm constitution."
"To set; to fasten or fix by piercing or thrusting in; as  to infix a sting spear or dart."
"To set on fire; to kindle; to cause to burn  flame or glow."
"To turn from a direct line or course; to bend; to incline  to deflect; to curve; to bow."
"To bend; to cause to become curved; to make crooked; to deflect."

"To give  cause or produce by striking or as if by striking; to apply forcibly; to lay or impose; to send; to cause to bear feel or suffer; as to inflict blows; to inflict a wound with a dagger; to inflict severe pain by ingratitude; to inflict punishment on an offender; to inflict the penalty of death on a criminal."
"The act of flowing in; as  an influx of light."
"To wrap up or cover with folds; to envelop; to inwrap; to inclose; to involve."
"Below; beneath; under; after; -- often used as a prefix."
"A sort of fillet worn by dignitaries  priests and others among the ancient Romans. It was generally white."
"To pour in  as a liquid; to pour (into or upon); to shed."
"A pasture or meadow; generally one lying low  near a river."
"Natural gift or talent; ability; wit; ingenuity."
"To take into  or as into the stomach or alimentary canal."
"That which is introduced into the body by the stomach or alimentary canal; -- opposed to egesta."
"To infix  as in a globe; to fix or secure firmly."
"That in which metal is cast; a mold."

"To insert  as a scion of one tree shrub or plant in another for propagation; as to ingraft a peach scion on a plum tree; figuratively to insert or introduce in such a way as to make a part of something."
"To make great; to enlarge; to magnify."
"The act of entering; entrance; as  the ingress of air into the lungs."
"To swallow up or overwhelm in  or as in a gulf; to cast into a gulf. See Engulf."
"To live or dwell in; to occupy  as a place of settled residence; as wild beasts inhabit the forest; men inhabit cities and houses."
"To breathe or draw into the lungs; to inspire; as  to inhale air; -- opposed to exhale."
"To be inherent; to stick (in); to be fixed or permanently incorporated with something; to cleave (to); to belong  as attributes or qualities."

"To take by descent from an ancestor; to take by inheritance; to take as heir on the death of an ancestor or other person to whose estate one succeeds; to receive as a right or title descendible by law from an ancestor at his decease; as  the heir inherits the land or real estate of his father; the eldest son of a nobleman inherits his father's title; the eldest son of a king inherits the crown."
"To check; to hold back; to restrain; to hinder."
"To place in a hive; to hive."
"To have inherent; to contain in itself; to possess."
"To inclose in a hoop  or as in a hoop."
"Destitute of the kindness and tenderness that belong to a human being; cruel; barbarous; savage; unfeeling; as  an inhuman person or people."
"To deposit  as a dead body in the earth; to bury; to inter."
"A South American freshwater dolphin (Inia Boliviensis). It is ten or twelve feet long  and has a hairy snout."
"The external occipital protuberance of the skull."
"To form into an island; to surround."
"Of or pertaining to the beginning; marking the commencement; incipient; commencing; as  the initial symptoms of a disease."
"To throw in; to dart in; to force in; as  to inject cold water into a condenser; to inject a medicinal liquid into a cavity of the body; to inject morphine with a hypodermic syringe."

"To do harm to; to impair the excellence and value of; to hurt; to damage; -- used in a variety of senses; as: (a) To hurt or wound  as the person; to impair soundness as of health. (b) To damage or lessen the value of as goods or estate. (c) To slander tarnish or impair as reputation or character. (d) To impair or diminish as happiness or virtue. (e) To give pain to as the sensibilities or the feelings; to grieve; to annoy. (f) To impair as the intellect or mind."

"Any damage or violation of  the person character feelings rights property or interests of an individual; that which injures or occasions wrong loss damage or detriment; harm; hurt; loss; mischief; wrong; evil; as his health was impaired by a severe injury; slander is an injury to the character."
"The step  or socket in which the lower end of a millstone spindle runs."
"One who  or that which inks; especially in printing the pad or roller which inks the type."
"A small bottle of horn or other material formerly used for holding ink; an inkstand; a portable case for writing materials."
"To fasten or bind  as with a knot; to knot together."
"Consisting of  or resembling ink; soiled with ink; black."
"To work in  as lace; to embellish with work resembling lace; also to lace or enlace."
"Within the land; more or less remote from the ocean or from open water; interior; as  an inland town."
"To clear of outlawry or attainder; to place under the protection of the law."
"To lay within; hence  to insert as pieces of pearl iviry choice woods or the like in a groundwork of some other material; to form an ornamental surface; to diversify or adorn with insertions."
"One who inlays  or whose occupation it is to inlay."
"A passage by which an inclosed place may be entered; a place of ingress; entrance."
"In the place; in the proper or natural place."

"One who lives in the same house or apartment with another; a fellow lodger; esp. one of the occupants of an asylum hospital or prison; by extension one who occupies or lodges in any place or dwelling."
"The edible viscera of animals  as the heart liver etc."
"To bring within meshes  as of a net; to enmesh."
"To inclose  as in a mew or cage."
"Deepest within; farthest from the surface or external part; innermost."
"A place of shelter; hence  dwelling; habitation; residence; abode."
"Inborn; native; natural; as  innate vigor; innate eloquence."
"Further in; interior; internal; not outward; as  an spirit or its phenomena."
"To give nervous energy or power to; to give increased energy force or courage to; to invigorate; to stimulate."
"A complex nitrogenous substance  which by Hermann's hypothesis is continually decomposed and reproduced in the muscles during their life."

"A white crystalline substance with a sweet taste  found in certain animal tissues and fluids particularly in the muscles of the heart and lungs also in some plants as in unripe pease beans potato sprouts etc. Called also phaseomannite."
"To ask a question; to seek for truth or information by putting queries."
"The act of inquiring; a seeking for information by asking questions; interrogation; a question or questioning."
"To rail in; to inclose or surround  as with rails."
"The entrance of an enemy into a country with purposes of hostility; a sudden or desultory incursion or invasion; raid; encroachment."
"A rush inwards; as  the inrush of the tide."
"Exhibiting unsoundness or disorded of mind; not sane; mad; deranged in mind; delirious; distracted. See Insanity  2."
"To impress or mark with a seam or cicatrix."
"One of the Insecta; esp.  one of the Hexapoda. See Insecta."

"One of the classes of Arthropoda  including those that have one pair of antennae three pairs of mouth organs and breathe air by means of tracheae opening by spiracles along the sides of the body. In this sense it includes the Hexapoda or six-legged insects and the Myriapoda with numerous legs. See Insect n."

"To set within something; to put or thrust in; to introduce; to cause to enter  or be included or contained; as to insert a scion in a stock; to insert a letter word or passage in a composition; to insert an advertisement in a newspaper."
"To be of use to an end; to serve."
"A plane for shaving or dressing the concave or inside faces of barrel staves."
"Being near or moving towards the shore; as  inshore fisheries; inshore currents."
"Within the sides of; in the interior; contained within; as  inside a house book bottle etc."
"A sight or view of the interior of anything; a deep inspection or view; introspection; -- frequently used with into."
"To strengthen  as with sinews; to invigorate."
"Wanting in the qualities which affect the organs of taste; without taste or savor; vapid; tasteless; as  insipid drink or food."
"To stand or rest; to find support; -- with in  on or upon."
"In its natural position or place; -- said of a rock or fossil  when found in the situation in which it was originally formed or deposited."
"To catch in a snare; to entrap; to take by artificial means."
"To make into a snarl or knot; to entangle; to snarl."
"The inside sole of a boot or shoe; also  a loose thin strip of leather felt etc. placed inside the shoe for warmth or ease."
"To set a soul in; reflexively  to fix one's strongest affections on."
"To yoke or harness  as oxen to a vehicle."
"To look upon; to view closely and critically  esp. in order to ascertain quality or condition to detect errors etc. to examine; to scrutinize; to investigate; as to inspect conduct."
"To breathe into; to fill with the breath; to animate."
"To set in a seat; to give a place to; establish (one) in a place."
"To set  place or establish as in a rank office or condition; to install; to invest; as to instate a person in greatness or in favor."
"In the place or room; -- usually followed by of."
"The arched middle portion of the human foot next in front of the ankle joint."
"To drop in; to pour in drop by drop; hence  to impart gradually; to infuse slowly; to cause to be imbibed."
"To stop; to close; to make fast; as  to instop the seams."
"To store up; to inclose; to contain."
"Of or pertaining to an island; of the nature  or possessing the characteristics of an island; as an insular climate fauna etc."
"The act of leaping on; onset; attack."
"To make sure or secure; as  to insure safety to any one."
"One who  or that which insures; the person or company that contracts to indemnify losses for a premium; an underwriter."
"Untouched  especially by anything that harms defiles or the like; uninjured; undefiled; left complete or entire."
"The place where water or air is taken into a pipe or conduit; -- opposed to outlet."
"A complete entity; a whole number  in contradistinction to a fraction or a mixed number."
"Strained; tightly drawn; kept on the stretch; strict; very close or earnest; as  intense study or application; intense thought."
"Closely directed; strictly attentive; bent; -- said of the mind  thoughts etc.; as a mind intent on self-improvement."
"To deposit and cover in the earth; to bury; to inhume; as  to inter a dead body."
"The meantime; time intervening; interval between events  etc."
"A transparent  extensible membrane of extreme tenuity which forms the innermost coating of grains of pollen."
"To the inside of; within. It is used in a variety of applications."
"To place in a tomb; to bury; to entomb. See Entomb."
"To utter with a musical or prolonged note or tone; to chant; as  to intone the church service."
"To twist in and out; to twine; to wreathe; to wind; to wring."
"To thrust one's self in; to come or go in without invitation  permission or welcome; to encroach; to trespass; as to intrude on families at unseasonable hours; to intrude on the lands of another."
"To inclose as in a trunk; to incase."

"To deliver (something) to another in trust; to deliver to (another) something in trust; to commit or surrender (something) to another with a certain confidence regarding his care  use or disposal of it; as to intrust a servant with one's money or intrust money or goods to a servant."
"To twine or twist into  or together; to wreathe; as a wreath of flowers intwined."
"To twist into or together; to interweave."

"A substance of very wide occurrence. It is found dissolved in the sap of the roots and rhizomes of many composite and other plants  as Inula Helianthus Campanula etc. and is extracted by solution as a tasteless white semicrystalline substance resembling starch with which it is isomeric. It is intermediate in nature between starch and sugar. Called also dahlin helenin alantin
"A substance resembling inulin  found in the unripe bulbs of the dahila."
"To apply in use; to train; to discipline; to use or accustom till use gives little or no pain or inconvenience; to harden; to habituate; to practice habitually."
"To put in an urn  as the ashes of the dead; hence to bury; to intomb."
"To go into or upon; to pass within the confines of; to enter; -- used of forcible or rude ingress."
"One who invades; an assailant; an encroacher; an intruder."
"Of no force  weight or cogency; not valid; weak."

"To declaim or rail (against some person or thing); to utter censorious and bitter language; to attack with harsh criticism or reproach  either spoken or written; to use invectives; -- with against; as to inveigh against character conduct manners customs morals a law an abuse."
"To come or light upon; to meet; to find."
"Opposite in order  relation or effect; reversed; inverted; reciprocal; -- opposed to direct."
"To turn over; to put upside down; to upset; to place in a contrary order or direction; to reverse; as  to invert a cup the order of words rules of justice etc."
"To put garments on; to clothe; to dress; to array; -- opposed to divest. Usually followed by with  sometimes by in; as to invest one with a robe."

"To ask; to request; to bid; to summon; to ask to do some act  or go to some place; esp. to ask to an entertainment or visit; to request the company of; as to invite to dinner or a wedding or an excursion."
"A written account of the particulars of merchandise shipped or sent to a purchaser  consignee factor etc. with the value or prices and charges annexed."

"To call on for aid or protection; to invite earnestly or solemnly; to summon; to address in prayer; to solicit or demand by invocation; to implore; as  to invoke the Supreme Being or to invoke His and blessing."
"To roll or fold up; to wind round; to entwine."
"To inclose or fortify as with a wall."
"Being or placed within; inner; interior; -- opposed to outward."
"Toward the inside; toward the center or interior; as  to bend a thing inward."
"To weave in or together; to intermix or intertwine by weaving; to interlace."
"To cover by wrapping; to involve; to infold; as  to inwrap in a cloak in smoke etc."
"An oily liquid  Cl3.CHO analogous to chloral and bromal."
"to  or containing iodine; specif. denoting those compounds in which it has a relatively high valence; as iodic acid."
"A binary compound of iodine  or one which may be regarded as binary; as potassium iodide."

"A nonmetallic element  of the halogen group occurring always in combination as in the iodides. When isolated it is in the form of dark gray metallic scales resembling plumbago soft but brittle and emitting a chlorinelike odor. Symbol I. Atomic weight 126.5. If heated iodine volatilizes in beautiful violet vapors."
"A morbid state produced by the use of iodine and its compounds  and characterized by palpitation depression and general emaciation with a pustular eruption upon the skin."
"To treat or impregnate with iodine or its compounds; as  to iodize a plate for photography."
"Pertaining to  or containing iodine. See -ous (chemical suffix)."
"A silicate of alumina  iron and magnesia having a bright blue color and vitreous luster; cordierite. It is remarkable for its dichroism and is also called dichroite."

"A large and handsome American moth (Hyperchiria Io)  having a large bright-colored spot on each hind wing resembling the spots on the tail of a peacock. The larva is covered with prickly hairs which sting like nettles."
"One of the elements which appear at the respective poles when a body is subjected to electro-chemical decomposition. Cf. Anion  Cation."
"Of or pertaining to Ionia or the Ionians; Ionic."
"Of or pertaining to Ionia or the Ionians."
"The ninth letter of the Greek alphabet (/) corresponding with the English i."

"A paper having on it these letters  with a sum named and duly signed; -- in use in England as an acknowledgment of a debt and taken as evidence thereof but not amounting to a promissory note; a due bill."
"A tribe of Indians which formerly occupied the region now included in the State of Iowa."
"An abbreviation of Ipecacuanha  and in more frequent use."
"A genus of twining plants with showy monopetalous flowers  including the morning-glory the sweet potato and the cypress vine."
"That branch of Christian science which treats of the methods of securing unity among Christians or harmony and union among the churches; -- called also Irenical theology."
"Of or pertaining to the iris or rainbow; prismatic; as  the iridal colors."
"Of or pertaining to the iris or rainbow."
"Of or pertaining to the iris of the eye."

"A rare metallic element  of the same group as platinum which it much resembles being silver-white but harder and brittle and indifferent to most corrosive agents. With the exception of osmium it is the heaviest substance known its specific gravity being 22.4. Symbol Ir. Atomic weight 192.5."
"To point or tip with iridium  as a gold pen."
"The goddess of the rainbow  and swift-footed messenger of the gods."
"Having colors like those of the rainbow; iridescent."
"Of or pertaining to Ireland or to its inhabitants; produced in Ireland."
"An inflammation of the iris of the eye."
"To weary; to give pain; to annoy; -- used only impersonally at present."
"Wearisome; tedious; disagreeable or troublesome by reason of long continuance or repetition; as  irksome hours; irksome tasks."

"The most common and most useful metallic element  being of almost universal occurrence usually in the form of an oxide (as hematite magnetite etc.) or a hydrous oxide (as limonite turgite etc.). It is reduced on an enormous scale in three principal forms; viz. cast iron steel and wrought iron. Iron usually appears dark brown from oxidation or impurity
"Made or consisting of iron; partaking of iron; iron; as  irony chains; irony particles."
"A fantastic grimace or contortion of the body."
"One of two or more objects containing the same information."
"A figure or polygon whose angles are equal."
"A white crystalline substance obtained by the partial reduction of isatin."
"An orange-red crystalline substance  C8H5NO2 obtained by the oxidation of indigo blue. It is also produced from certain derivatives of benzoic acid and is one important source of artificial indigo."
"A genus of herbs  some species of which especially the Isatis tinctoria yield a blue dye similar to indigo; woad."
"Of or pertaining to the ischium or hip; ischiac; ischiadic; ischiatic."
"The ventral and posterior of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis; seat bone; the huckle bone."
"Pertaining to the goddess Isis; as  Isiac mysteries."

"The principal goddess worshiped by the Egyptians. She was regarded as the mother of Horus  and the sister and wife of Osiris. The Egyptians adored her as the goddess of fecundity and as the great benefactress of their country who instructed their ancestors in the art of agriculture."
"The religion of the Mohammedans; Mohammedanism; Islamism. Their formula of faith is: There is no God but Allah  and Mohammed is his prophet."
"A tract of land surrounded by water  and smaller than a continent. Cf. Continent."
"Of or pertaining to islands; full of islands."
"A doctrine or theory; especially  a wild or visionary theory."

"A line connecting or marking places upon the surface of the earth where height of the barometer reduced to sea level is the same either at a given time  or for a certain period (mean height) as for a year; an isopiestic line."
"To place in a detached situation; to place by itself or alone; to insulate; to separate from others."
"A body or compound which is isomeric with another body or compound; a member of an isomeric series."
"Equal law or right; equal distribution of rights and privileges; similarity."
"Having the legs similar in structure; belonging to the Isopoda."
"An order of sessile-eyed Crustacea  usually having seven pairs of legs which are all similar in structure."
"A crystalline hydrocarbon derivative  metameric with orcin but produced artificially; -- called also cresorcin."
"Pertaining to  or designating a complex nitrogenous acid isomeric with uric acid."
"Issuing or coming up; -- a term used to express a charge or bearing rising or coming out of another."
"The act of passing or flowing out; a moving out from any inclosed place; egress; as  the issue of water from a pipe of blood from a wound of air from a bellows of people from a house."
"A neck or narrow slip of land by which two continents are connected  or by which a peninsula is united to the mainland; as the Isthmus of Panama; the Isthmus of Suez etc."
"An artificial nitrogenous base  isomeric with urea and forming a white crystalline substance; -- called also isuretine."

"Pronunciation of / (eta) as the modern Greeks pronounce it  that is like e in the English word be. This was the pronunciation advocated by Reu/hlin and his followers in opposition to the etacism of Erasmus. See Etacism."
"One who is in favor of itacism."
"An early Latin version of the Scriptures (the Old Testament was translated from the Septuagint  and was also called the Italic version)."
"Of or pertaining to Italy  or to its people or language."
"Relating to Italy or to its people."
"To have an uneasy sensation in the skin  which inclines the person to scratch the part affected."
"Infected with the itch  or with an itching sensation."
"To state in items  or by particulars; as to itemize the cost of a railroad."
"A passage; esp.  the passage between the third and fourth ventricles in the brain; the aqueduct of Sylvius."
"Possessive form of the pronoun it. See It."
"The neuter reciprocal pronoun of It; as  the thing is good in itself; it stands by itself."
"A silver coin of Japan  worth about thirty-four cents."
"One of the Iulidae  a family of myriapods of which the genus Iulus is the type. See Iulus."

"A genus of chilognathous myriapods. The body is long and round  consisting of numerous smooth equal segments each of which bears two pairs of short legs. It includes the galleyworms. See Chilognatha."
"A composition resembling ivory in appearance and used as a substitute for it."

"The hard  white opaque fine-grained substance constituting the tusks of the elephant. It is a variety of dentine characterized by the minuteness and close arrangement of the tubes as also by their double flexure. It is used in manufacturing articles of ornament or utility."

"A plant of the genus Hedera (H. helix)  common in Europe. Its leaves are evergreen dark smooth shining and mostly five-pointed; the flowers yellowish and small; the berries black or yellow. The stem clings to walls and trees by rootlike fibers."
"A South African bulbous plant of the Iris family  remarkable for the brilliancy of its flowers."
"A genus of parasitic Acarina  which includes various species of ticks. See Tick the insect."
"A tick of the genus Ixodes  or the family Ixodidae."
"A Mexican name for a variety of Agave rigida  which furnishes a strong coarse fiber; also the fiber itself which is called also pita and Tampico fiber."
"A variety of the chamois found in the Pyrenees."
"One of an Oriental religious sect which worships Satan or the Devil."
"To thrust; to stab; to punch. See Job  v. t."
"To talk rapidly  indistinctly or unintelligibly; to utter gibberish or nonsense; to chatter."
"One of several large wading birds of the genera Mycteria and Xenorhynchus  allied to the storks in form and habits."
"Originally  a kind of ruffle worn by men on the bosom of the shirt."

"Any one of numerous species of tropical American birds of the genus Galbula and allied genera. They are allied to the kingfishers  but climb on tree trunks like nuthatches and feed upon insects. Their colors are often brilliant."

"Any of several wading birds belonging to the genus Jacana and several allied genera  all of which have spurs on the wings. They are able to run about over floating water weeds by means of their very long spreading toes. Called also surgeon bird."
"The common marmoset (Hapale vulgaris). Formerly  the name was also applied to other species of the same genus."
"Lying at length; as  the jacent posture."

"A large tree  the Artocarpus integrifolia common in the East Indies closely allied to the breadfruit from which it differs in having its leaves entire. The fruit is of great size weighing from thirty to forty pounds and through its soft fibrous matter are scattered the seeds which are roasted and eaten. The wood is of a yellow color fine grain and rather heavy and is much used in cabinetwork. It is also used for dyeing a brilliant yellow."

"Any one of several species of carnivorous animals inhabiting Africa and Asia  related to the dog and wolf. They are cowardly nocturnal and gregarious. They feed largely on carrion and are noted for their piercing and dismal howling."
"A short upper garment  extending downward to the hips; a short coat without skirts."
"One wearing a jack; a horse soldier; a retainer. See 3d Jack  n."
"A Hebrew patriarch (son of Isaac  and ancestor of the Jews) who in a vision saw a ladder reaching up to heaven (Gen. xxviii. 12); -- also called Israel."
"A Dominican friar; -- so named because  before the French Revolution that order had a convent in the Rue St. Jacques Paris."
"An English gold coin  of the value of twenty-five shillings sterling struck in the reign of James I."
"A thin cotton fabric  between and muslin used for dresses neckcloths etc."

"A stone  commonly of a pale to dark green color but sometimes whitish. It is very hard and compact capable of fine polish and is used for ornamental purposes and for implements esp. in Eastern countries and among many early peoples."
"Vicious; ill-tempered; resembling a jade; -- applied to a horse."
"A notch; a cleft; a barb; a ragged or sharp protuberance; a denticulation."
"One who carries about a small load; a peddler. See 2d Jag."
"Raw palm sugar  made in the East Indies by evaporating the fresh juice of several kinds of palm trees but specifically that of the palmyra (Borassus flabelliformis)."
"Having jags; set with teeth; notched; uneven; as  jaggy teeth."
"A village or district the government and revenues of which are assigned to some person  usually in consideration of some service to be rendered esp. the maintenance of troops."

"A large and powerful feline animal (Felis onca)  ranging from Texas and Mexico to Patagonia. It is usually brownish yellow with large dark somewhat angular rings each generally inclosing one or two dark spots. It is chiefly arboreal in its habits. Called also the American tiger."
"A kind of prison; a building for the confinement of persons held in lawful custody  especially for minor offenses or with reference to some future judicial proceeding."
"The keeper of a jail or prison."
"One of a numerous sect in British India  holding the tenets of Jainism."

"The heterodox Hindoo religion  of which the most striking features are the exaltation of saints or holy mortals called jins above the ordinary Hindoo gods and the denial of the divine origin and infallibility of the Vedas. It is intermediate between Brahmanism and Buddhism having some things in common with each."
"A South American striped frog (Pseudis paradoxa)  remarkable for having a tadpole larger than the adult and hence called also paradoxical frog."
"An African parrot (Psittacus erithacus)  very commonly kept as a cage bird; -- called also gray parrot."

"The tubers of the Mexican plant Ipomoea purga (or Exogonium purga)  a climber much like the morning-glory. The abstract extract and powder prepared from the tubers are well known purgative medicines. Other species of Ipomoea yield several inferior kinds of jalap as the I. Orizabensis and I. tuberosa."
