"The maiming of a person by depriving him of the use of any of his members which are necessary for defense or protection. See Maim."
"The chief magistrate of a city or borough; the chief officer of a municipal corporation. In some American cities there is a city court of which the major is chief judge."
"The conductir of a mule team; also  a head shepherd."
"A tall pole erected in an open place and wreathed with flowers  about which the rustic May-day sports were had."
"The edible fruit of a passion flower  especially that of the North American Passiflora incarnata an oval yellowish berry as large as a small apple."
"A composite plant (Anthemis Cotula)  having a strong odor; dog's fennel. It is a native of Europe now common by the roadsides in the United States."
"A goatlike antelope (Haplocerus montanus) which inhabits the Rocky Mountains  frequenting the highest parts; -- called also mountain goat."
"Of or pertaining to Ahura-Mazda  or Ormuzd the beneficent deity in the Zoroastrian dualistic system; hence Zoroastrian."
"A large drinking bowl; -- originally made of maple."
"A Polish dance  or the music which accompanies it usually in 3-4 or 3-8 measure with a strong accent on the second beat."
"Perplexed with turns and windings; winding; intricate; confusing; perplexing; embarrassing; as  mazy error."
"A fermented drink made of water and honey with malt  yeast etc.; metheglin; hydromel."
"A tract of low or level land producing grass which is mown for hay; any field on which grass is grown for hay."
"Of or pertaining to meadows; resembling  or consisting of meadow."
"Destitue of  or having little flesh; lean."
"The process of picking out the oakum from the seams of a vessel which is to be recalked."
"Maize or Indian corn; -- the common name in South Africa."
"Having the qualities of meal; resembling meal; soft  dry and friable; easily reduced to a condition resembling meal; as a mealy potato."
"To have in the mind  as a purpose intention etc.; to intend; to purpose; to design; as what do you mean to do ?"
"A winding  crooked or involved course; as the meanders of the veins and arteries."
"Five hundred; as  a mease of herrings."
"Infected or spotted with measles  as pork."

"A standard of dimension; a fixed unit of quantity or extent; an extent or quantity in the fractions or multiples of which anything is estimated and stated; hence  a rule by which anything is adjusted or judged."
"Food  in general; anything eaten for nourishment either by man or beast. Hence the edible part of anything; as the meat of a lobster a nut or an egg."
"Of or pertaining to a meatus; resembling a meatus."
"A natural passage or canal; as  the external auditory meatus. See Illust. of Ear."
"A rope of hair or of maguey fiber  for tying horses etc."
"A kind of lace made at  or originating in Mechlin in Belgium."
"Pertaining to  or obtained from the poppy or opium; specif. (Chem.) designating an acid related to aconitic acid found in opium and extracted as a white crystalline substance."

"A substance regarded as an anhydride of meconinic acid  existing in opium and extracted as a white crystalline substance. Also erroneously called meconina meconia etc. as though it were an alkaloid."
"A piece of metal in the form of a coin  struck with a device and intended to preserve the remembrance of a notable event or an illustrious person or to serve as a reward."
"One who meddles; one who interferes or busies himself with things in which he has no concern; an officious person; a busybody."
"A native or inhabitant of Media in Asia."
"The state or quality of being mediate."
"Of or pertaining to a mean or average; mean; as  medial alligation."
"Being in the middle; running through the middle; as  a median groove."
"The third above the keynote; -- so called because it divides the interval between the tonic and dominant into two thirds."
"Being between the two extremes; middle; interposed; intervening; intermediate."
"A leguminous plant of the genus Medicago. The black medic is the Medicago lupulina; the purple medic  or lucern is M. sativa."
"Of  pertaining to or having to do with the art of healing disease or the science of medicine; as the medical profession; medical services; a medical dictionary; medical jurisprudence."
"That which lies in the middle  or between other things; intervening body or quantity. Hence specifically: (a) Middle place or degree; mean."
"The third or middle finger; the third digit  or that which corresponds to it."

"A tree of the genus Mespilus (M. Germanica); also  the fruit of the tree. The fruit is something like a small apple but has a bony endocarp. When first gathered the flesh is hard and austere and it is not eaten until it has begun to decay."
"A mixture; a mingled and confused mass of ingredients  usually inharmonious; a jumble; a hodgepodge; -- often used contemptuously."
"A class of claret wines  including several varieties from the district of Medoc in the department of Gironde."
"The Gorgon; or one of the Gorgons whose hair was changed into serpents  after which all who looked upon her were turned into stone."
"That which is bestowed or rendered in consideration of merit; reward; recompense."
"Worthy of meed  reward or recompense; meritorious."
"Mild of temper; not easily provoked or orritated; patient under injuries; not vain  or haughty or resentful; forbearing; submissive."
"To make meek; to nurture in gentleness and humility."
"A South African carnivore (Cynictis penicillata)  allied to the ichneumons."

"To join  or come in contact with; esp. to come in contact with by approach from an opposite direction; to come upon or against front to front as distinguished from contact by following and overtaking."
"Belonging  or pertaining to Megara a city of ancient Greece."
"One of the larger measures of work  amounting to one million ergs; -- called also megalerg."
"A gelatinous compound of linseed oil and mastic varnish  used by artists as a vehicle for colors."
"One of the larger measures of electrical resistance  amounting to one million ohms."
"A kind of sick or nevrous headache  usually periodical and confined to one side of the head."
"A family  including servants etc.; household; retinue; train."
"Diminution; a species of hyperbole  representing a thing as being less than it really is."
"A mixture of sugar and molasses; crude sugar as it comes from the pans without being drained."
"A discharge from the bowels of black matter  consisting of altered blood."
"The dark coloring matter of the liquid of the cuttlefish."
"A white or buff-colored granular powder  C6H9N11 obtained by heating ammonium sulphocyanate."

"A black pigment found in the pigment-bearing cells of the skin (particularly in the skin of the negro)  in the epithelial cells of the external layer of the retina (then called fuscin) in the outer layer of the choroid and elsewhere. It is supposed to be derived from the decomposition of hemoglobin."
"A dark discoloration of the skin  usually local; as Addison's melasma or Addison's disease."
"A fight in which the combatants are mingled in one confused mass; a hand to hand conflict; an affray."
"An unsaturated hydrocarbon  C30H60 of the ethylene series obtained from beeswax as a white scaly crystalline wax; -- called also melissene and melissylene."
"Of or pertaining to song; lyric; tuneful."

"Any species of Melilotus  a genus of leguminous herbs having a vanillalike odor; sweet clover; hart's clover. The blue melilot (Melilotus caerulea) is used in Switzerland to give color and flavor to sapsago cheese."
"A piece of melody; a song or tune  -- as opposed to recitative or musical declamation."
"A genus of labiate herbs  including the balm or bee balm (Melissa officinalis)."
"A mineral of a honey color  found in brown coal and partly the result of vegetable decomposition; honeystone. It is a mellitate of alumina."
"A yellow powder  C6H3N9 obtained from certain sulphocyanates. It has acid properties and forms compounds called mellonides."
"Soft or tender by reason of ripeness; having a tender pulp; as  a mellow apple."
"A climbing plant (Ullucus officinalis) of the Andes  having tuberous roots which are used as a substitute for potatoes."
"Of the nature of melody; relating to  containing or made up of melody; melodious."
"A sweet or agreeable succession of sounds."
"A genus of beetles without wings  but having short oval elytra; the oil beetles. These beetles are sometimes used instead of cantharides for raising blisters. See Oil beetle under Oil."
"The juicy fruit of certain cucurbitaceous plants  as the muskmelon watermelon and citron melon; also the plant that produces the fruit."
"A kind of stout woolen cloth with unfinished face and without raised nap. A commoner variety has a cotton warp."
"To remember; to cause to remember; to mention."
"A hint  suggestion token or memorial to awaken memory; that which reminds or recalls to memory; a souvenir."
"A small deerlet  or chevrotain of India."
"A celebrated Egyptian statue near Thebes  said to have the property of emitting a harplike sound at sunrise."

"A memorial account; a history composed from personal experience and memory; an account of transactions or events (usually written in familiar style) as they are remembered by the writer. See History  2."
"The faculty of the mind by which it retains the knowledge of previous thoughts  impressions or events."
"The show of an intention to inflict evil; a threat or threatening; indication of a probable evil or catastrophe to come."
"A work of twelve volumes  each containing the offices in the Greek Church for a month; also each volume of the same."

"To repair  as anything that is torn broken defaced decayed or the like; to restore from partial decay injury or defacement; to patch up; to put in shape or order again; to re-create; as to mend a garment or a machine."
"A large stone set upright in olden times as a memorial or monument. Many  of unknown date are found in Brittany and throughout Northern Europe."
"Belonging to a retinue or train of servants; performing servile office; serving."
"Belonging to the table; transacted at table; as  mensal conversation."
"The catamenial or menstrual discharge  a periodic flow of blood or bloody fluid from the uterus or female generative organs."
"Of or pertaining to the chin; genian; as  the mental nerve; the mental region."
"A widely distributed genus of fragrant herbs  including the peppermint spearmint etc. The plants have small flowers usually arranged in dense axillary clusters."
"A white  crystalline aromatic substance resembling camphor extracted from oil of peppermint (Mentha); -- called also mint camphor or peppermint camphor."
"A compound radical forming the base of menthol."
"A speaking or notice of anything  -- usually in a brief or cursory manner. Used especially in the phrase to make mention of."
"A wise and faithful counselor or monitor."
"The front median plate of the labium in insects. See Labium."
"The details of a banquet; a bill of fare."
"To subject to fine or amercement; to mulct; to amerce."
"Originally  a dealer in any kind of goods or wares; now restricted to a dealer in textile fabrics as silks or woolens."
"The trade of mercers; the goods in which a mercer deals."
"A Latin god of commerce and gain; -- treated by the poets as identical with the Greek Hermes  messenger of the gods conductor of souls to the lower world and god of eloquence."
"Forbearance to inflict harm under circumstances of provocation  when one has the power to inflict it; compassionate treatment of an offender or adversary; clemency."
"To cause to be swallowed up; to immerse; to sink; to absorb."
"A permanent colony of cells or plastids which may remain isolated  like Rotifer or may multiply by gemmation to form higher aggregates termed zoides."
"A boy's play  called also fivepenny morris. See Morris."
"Of or pertaining to a variety of sheep with very fine wool  originally bred in Spain."
"The quality or state of deserving well or ill; desert."
"A play of children  in swinging on ropes or the like till they are dizzy."
"An old Scotch silver coin; a mark or marc."
"Originally  a wig; afterwards a mop for cleaning cannon."
"A small European falcon (Falco lithofalco  or F. aesalon)."
"One of the solid parts of a battlemented parapet; a battlement. See Illust. of Battlement."
"The European hake; -- called also herring hake and sea pike."
"A fabled marine creature  typically represented as having the upper part like that of a woman and the lower like a fish; a sea nymph sea woman or woman fish."
"The male corresponding to mermaid; a sea man  or man fish."
"The plain surface between the channels of a triglyph."
"In a merry manner; with mirth; with gayety and laughter; jovially. See Mirth  and Merry."
"Laughingly gay; overflowing with good humor and good spirits; jovial; inclined to laughter or play ; sportive."
"A high tableland; a plateau on a hill."
"A distilled liquor prepared in Mexico from a species of agave. See Agave."
"The opening or space inclosed by the threads of a net between knot and knot  or the threads inclosing such a space; network; a net."
"Toward  or on the side toward the mesial plane; mesially; -- opposed to laterad."
"Middle; median; in  or in the region of the mesial plane; internal; -- opposed to lateral."
"A hypothetical radical formerly supposed to exist in mesityl oxide."

"Middle; intervening; as  a mesne lord that is a lord who holds land of a superior but grants a part of it to another person in which case he is a tenant to the superior but lord or superior to the second grantee and hence is called the mesne lord."

"The mesial plane dividing the body of an animal into similar right and left halves. The line in which it meets the dorsal surface has been called the dorsimeson  and the corresponding ventral edge the ventrimeson."
"A group of very lowly organized  wormlike parasites including the Dicyemata. They are found in cephalopods. See Dicyemata."
"A name for two trees of the southwestern part of North America  the honey mesquite and screw-pod mesquite."
"Any notice  word or communication written or verbal sent from one person to another."
"A German epic poem on the Messiah  by Klopstock."
"The expected king and deliverer of the Hebrews; the Savior; Christ."
"The offspring of a white person and a quadroon; -- so called in the West Indies."
"The offspring of an Indian or a negro and a European or person of European stock."

"An elementary substance  as sodium calcium or copper whose oxide or hydroxide has basic rather than acid properties as contrasted with the nonmetals or metalloids. No sharp line can be drawn between the metals and nonmetals and certain elements partake of both acid and basic qualities as chromium manganese bismuth etc."
"Any one of several metameric forms of the same substance  or of different substances having the same composition; as xylene has three metamers viz. orthoxylene metaxylene and paraxylene."
"One who cultivates land for a share (usually one half) of its yield  receiving stock tools and seed from the landlord."

"Those animals in which the protoplasmic mass  constituting the egg is converted into a multitude of cells which are metamorphosed into the tissues of the body. A central cavity is commonly developed and the cells around it are at first arranged in two layers -- the ectoderm and endoderm. The group comprises nearly all animals except the Protozoa."
"According to measure or proportion; proportionable; proportionate."
"Any phenomenon or appearance in the atmosphere  as clouds rain hail snow etc."
"One who  or that which metes or measures. See Coal-meter."

"Rhythmical arrangement of syllables or words into verses  stanzas strophes etc.; poetical measure depending on number quantity and accent of syllables; rhythm; measure; verse; also any specific rhythmical arrangements; as the Horatian meters; a dactylic meter."
"A white waxy substance  found in small quantities in spermaceti as an ethereal salt of several fatty acids and regarded as an alcohol of the methane series."
"A light  colorless gaseous inflammable hydrocarbon CH4; marsh gas. See Marsh gas under Gas."
"A binary compound of methyl with some element; as  aluminium methide Al2(CH3)6."
"An orderly procedure or process; regular manner of doing anything; hence  manner; way; mode; as a method of teaching languages; a method of improving the mind."

"The technical name of methyl alcohol or wood spirit; also  by extension the class name of any of the series of alcohols of the methane series of which methol proper is the type. See Methyl alcohol under Methyl."
"A hydrocarbon radical  CH3 not existing alone but regarded as an essential residue of methane and appearing as a component part of many derivatives; as methyl alcohol methyl ether methyl amine etc."
"A sojourner; an immigrant; an alien resident in a Grecian city  but not a citizen."
"The offspring of a white person and an American Indian."
"Pertaining to  or discovered by Meton the Athenian."
"The space between two triglyphs of the Doric frieze  which among the ancients was often adorned with carved work. See Illust. of Entablature."
"Of or pertaining to the forehead or frontal bones; frontal; as  the metopic suture."
"Relating to measurement; involving  or proceeding by measurement."
"Substance or quality of temperament; spirit  esp. as regards honor courage fortitude ardor etc.; disposition; -- usually in a good sense."
"Having mettle; high-spirited; ardent; full of fire."
"A cage for hawks; a mew. See 4th Mew  1."
"A gull  esp. the common British species (Larus canus); called also sea mew maa mar mow and cobb."
"To cry  as a young child; to squall."
"An alley where there are stables; a narrow passage; a confined place."
"Of or pertaining to Mexico or its people."
"A tribe of Indians that formerly occupied the country between the Wabash and Maumee rivers."
"Infectious particles or germs floating in the air; air made noxious by the presence of such particles or germs; noxious effluvia; malaria."
"To cry as a cat; to mew; to caterwaul."

"The name of a group of minerals characterized by highly perfect cleavage  so that they readily separate into very thin leaves more or less elastic. They differ widely in composition and vary in color from pale brown or yellow to green or black. The transparent forms are used in lanterns the doors of stoves etc. being popularly called isinglass. Formerly called also cat-silver and glimmer."
"A theoretical aggregation of molecules constituting a structural particle of protoplasm  capable of increase or diminution without change in chemical nature."
"To lie hid; to skulk; to act  or carry one's self sneakingly."
"One who skulks  or keeps out of sight; hence a truant; an idler; a thief etc."
"A tribe of Indians inhabiting Nova Scotia and New Brunswick."
"A small South American monkey (Mico melanurus)  allied to the marmoset. The name was originally applied to an albino variety."
"A measure of length; the thousandth part of one millimeter; the millionth part of a meter."
"Denoting the middle part; as  in mid ocean."
"A genus of longeared South American monkeys  including numerous species of marmosets. See Marmoset."
"The middle part of the day; noon."
"Situated most nearly in the middle; middlemost; midmost."

"Equally distant from the extreme either of a number of things or of one thing; mean; medial; as  the middle house in a row; a middle rank or station in life; flowers of middle summer; men of middle age."
"One of a middle or intermediate class in some schools and seminaries."
"The middle space or region between heaven and hell; the abode of human beings; the earth."
"Any one of many small  delicate long-legged flies of the Chironomus and allied genera which do not bite. Their larvae are usually aquatic."
"The middle part of the alimentary canal from the stomach  or entrance of the bile duct to or including the large intestine."
"Being in the interior country; distant from the coast or seashore; as  midland towns or inhabitants."
"The middle part of the main or sea."
"A talmudic exposition of the Hebrew law  or of some part of it."
"A continuation of the petiole  extending from the base to the apex of the lamina of a leaf."
"Of or pertaining to  or being in the middle of a ship."
"The interior or central part or place; the middle; -- used chiefly in the objective case after in; as  in the midst of the forest."
"The middle of the way or distance; a middle way or course."
"The middle of the week. Also used adjectively."
"A woman who assists other women in childbirth; a female practitioner of the obstetric art."
"A petty falling out; a tiff; a quarrel; offense."
"Possessing might; having great power or authority."
"To remove from one country or region to another  with a view to residence; to change one's place of residence; to remove; as the Moors who migrated from Africa into Spain; to migrate to the West."
"The popular designation of the hereditary sovereign of Japan."
"Giving milk; -- now applied only to beasts."

"Gentle; pleasant; kind; soft; bland; clement; hence  moderate in degree or quality; -- the opposite of harsh severe irritating violent disagreeable etc.; -- applied to persons and things; as a mild disposition; a mild eye; a mild air; a mild medicine; a mild insanity."
"A growth of minute powdery or webby fungi  whitish or of different colors found on various diseased or decaying substances."
"A certain measure of distance  being equivalent in England and the United States to 320 poles or rods or 5 280 feet."
"An allowance for traveling expenses at a certain rate per mile."
"A common composite herb (Achillea Millefolium) with white flowers and finely dissected leaves; yarrow."
"Like millet seeds; as  a miliary eruption."
"A genus of Foraminifera  having a porcelanous shell with several longitudinal chambers."

"In the widest sense  the whole military force of a nation including both those engaged in military service as a business and those competent and available for such service; specifically the body of citizens enrolled for military instruction and discipline but not subject to be called into actual service except in emergencies."

"A white fluid secreted by the mammary glands of female mammals for the nourishment of their young  consisting of minute globules of fat suspended in a solution of casein albumin milk sugar and inorganic salts."
"One who milks; also  a mechanical apparatus for milking cows."
"A man who sells milk or delivers is to customers."
"A piece of bread sopped in milk; figuratively  an effeminate or weak-minded person."
"A money of account of the United States  having the value of the tenth of a cent or the thousandth of a dollar."
"A dam or mound to obstruct a water course  and raise the water to a height sufficient to turn a mill wheel."
"One who keeps or attends a flour mill or gristmill."
"The name of several cereal and forage grasses which bear an abundance of small roundish grains. The common millets of Germany and Southern Europe are Panicum miliaceum  and Setaria Italica."
"A weight of the metric system  being one million grams; a metric ton."
"The number of ten hundred thousand  or a thousand thousand -- written 1 0 000. See the Note under Hundred."
"A Portuguese money of account rated in the treasury department of the United States at one dollar and eight cents; also  a Brazilian money of account rated at fifty-four cents and six mills."
"Of or resembling birds of the kite kind."
"A genus of raptorial birds  including the European kite."
"A kind of drama in which real persons and events were generally represented in a ridiculous manner."
"The act or practice of one who mimics; ludicrous imitation for sport or ridicule."
"A genus of leguminous plants  containing many species and including the sensitive plants (Mimosa sensitiva and M. pudica)."
"An ancient weight or denomination of money  of varying value. The Attic mina was valued at a hundred drachmas."
"Such as can be mined; as  minable earth."
"A slender  lofty tower attached to a mosque and surrounded by one or more projecting balconies from which the summon to prayer is cried by the muezzin."
"To cut into very small pieces; to chop fine; to hash; as  to mince meat."
"That minces; characterized by primness or affected nicety."

"The intellectual or rational faculty in man; the understanding; the intellect; the power that conceives  judges or reasons; also the entire spiritual nature; the soul; -- often in distinction from the body."
"One who minds  tends or watches something as a child a machine or cattle; as a minder of a loom."
"Bearing in mind; regardful; attentive; heedful; observant."
"One who mines; a digger for metals  etc.; one engaged in the business of getting ore coal or precious stones out of the earth; one who digs military mines; as armies have sappers and miners."

"An inorganic species or substance occurring in nature  having a definite chemical composition and usually a distinct crystalline form. Rocks except certain glassy igneous forms are either simple minerals or aggregates of minerals."
"The goddess of wisdom  of war of the arts and sciences of poetry and of spinning and weaving; -- identified with the Grecian Pallas Athene."
"The smallest of regular sizes of portrait photographs."
"To mix; intermix; to combine or join  as an individual or part with other parts but commonly so as to be distinguishable in the product; to confuse; to confound."
"To paint or tinge with red lead or vermilion; also  to decorate with letters or the like painted red as the page of a manuscript."
"A kind of light passenger vehicle  carrying four persons."
"To make small  or smaller; to diminish the apparent dimensions of; to lessen."
"A little darling; a favorite; a minion."
"Anything very minute; as  the minims of existence; -- applied to animalcula; and the like."
"The least quantity assignable  admissible or possible in a given case; hence a thing of small consequence; -- opposed to maximum."
"Of the color of red or vermilion."

"A heavy  brilliant red pigment consisting of an oxide of lead Pb3O4 obtained by exposing lead or massicot to a gentle and continued heat in the air. It is used as a cement as a paint and in the manufacture of flint glass. Called also red lead."
"A fur esteemed in the Middle Ages as a part of costume. It is uncertain whether it was the fur of one animal only or of different animals."
"A singing bird of India of the family Campephagidae."

"A carnivorous mammal of the genus Putorius  allied to the weasel. The European mink is Putorius lutreola. The common American mink (P. vison) varies from yellowish brown to black. Its fur is highly valued. Called also minx nurik and vison."

"A small European fresh-water cyprinoid fish (Phoxinus laevis  formerly Leuciscus phoxinus); sometimes applied also to the young of larger kinds; -- called also minim and minny. The name is also applied to several allied American species of the genera Phoxinus Notropis or Minnilus and Rhinichthys."
"Inferior in bulk  degree importance etc.; less; smaller; of little account; as minor divisions of a body."
"A king and lawgiver of Crete  fabled to be the son of Jupiter and Europa. After death he was made a judge in the Lower Regions."

"A church of a monastery. The name is often retained and applied to the church after the monastery has ceased to exist (as Beverly Minster  Southwell Minster etc.) and is also improperly used for any large church."
"The name of several aromatic labiate plants  mostly of the genus Mentha yielding odoriferous essential oils by distillation. See Mentha."
"The coin  or other production made in a mint."
"One skilled in coining  or in coins; a coiner."
"The number from which another number is to be subtracted."
"A slow graceful dance consisting of a coupee  a high step and a balance."
"A small kind of printing type; minion."
"Less; requiring to be subtracted; negative; as  a minus quantity."
"The sixtieth part of an hour; sixty seconds. (Abbrev. m.; as  4 h. 30 m.)"
"A minute particular; a small or minor detail; -- used chiefly in the plural."
"Of or pertaining to the middle division of the Tertiary."
"A remarkable variable star in the constellation Cetus (/ Ceti)."

"An optical effect  sometimes seen on the ocean but more frequently in deserts due to total reflection of light at the surface common to two strata of air differently heated. The reflected image is seen commonly in an inverted position while the real object may or may not be in sight. When the surface is horizontal and below the eye the appearance is that of a sheet of water in which the object is seen reflected; when the reflecting surface is above the eye the image is seen projected against the sky. The fata Morgana and looming are species of mirage."
"A looking-glass or a speculum; any glass or polished substance that forms images by the reflection of rays of light."
"Abounding with deep mud; full of mire; muddy; as  a miry road."
"The common title of honor in Persia  prefixed to the surname of an individual. When appended to the surname it signifies Prince."
"To carry improperly; to carry (one's self) wrongly; to misbehave."
"To call by a wrong name; to name improperly."
"A false stroke with a billiard cue  the cue slipping from the ball struck without impelling it as desired."
"To deal or distribute wrongly  as cards; to make a wrong distribution."
"The issue in a writ of right."
"A wretched person; a person afflicted by any great misfortune."
"Like a miser; very covetous; sordid; niggardly."
"Great unhappiness; extreme pain of body or mind; wretchedness; distress; woe."
"To befall  as ill luck; to happen to unluckily."
"The act or the state of fitting badly; as  a misfit in making a coat; a ludicrous misfit."
"A collection or digest of Jewish traditions and explanations of Scripture  forming the text of the Talmud."
"To have a mistaken notion of or about."
"To lay in a wrong place; to ascribe to a wrong source."
"To rain in very fine drops  like a thick mist; to mizzle."
"To lead into a wrong way or path; to lead astray; to guide into error; to cause to mistake; to deceive."
"To dislike; to disapprove of; to have aversion to; as  to mislike a man."
"To make or form amiss; to spoil in making."
"To mate wrongly or unsuitably; as  to mismate gloves or shoes; a mismated couple."
"To call by the wrong name; to give a wrong or inappropriate name to."
"A title of courtesy prefixed to the name of a girl or a woman who has not been married. See Mistress  5."
"The service or sacrifice of the Mass."
"The book containing the service of the Mass for the entire year; a Mass book."
"Capable of being thrown; adapted for hurling or to be projected from the hand  or from any instrument or rngine so as to strike an object at a distance."
"The act of sending  or the state of being sent; a being sent or delegated by authority with certain powers for transacting business; comission."
"A mistress; a wife; -- so used by the illiterate."
"To sit badly or imperfectly upon; to misbecome."
"Specially sent; intended or prepared to be sent; as  a letter missive."
"A wrong step; an error of conduct."
"Visible watery vapor suspended in the atmosphere  at or near the surface of the earth; fog."
"A title of courtesy prefixed to the name of a man or youth. It is usually written in the abbreviated form Mr."
"To call by a wrong name; to miscall."
"A kind of small sailing vessel used in the Mediterranean. It is rigged partly like a xebec  and partly like a felucca."
"To happen or come to pass unfortunately; also  to suffer evil fortune."
"To time wrongly; not to adapt to the time."
"To fall in very fine drops  as rain."
"A violent and cold northwest wind experienced in the Mediterranean provinces of France  etc."
"A mingled compound in which different ingredients are contained in a liquid state; a mixture. See Mixture  n. 4."
"Accompained with mist; characterized by the presence of mist; obscured by  or overspread with mist; as misty weather; misty mountains; a misty atmosphere."
"To treat or use improperly; to use to a bad purpose; to misapply; as  to misuse one's talents."
"To ween amiss; to misjudge; to distrust; to be mistaken."
"To word wrongly; as  to misword a message or a sentence."
"An impure yellow sulphate of iron; yellow copperas or copiapite."
"A minute arachnid  of the order Acarina of which there are many species; as the cheese mite sugar mite harvest mite etc. See Acarina."
"A covering for the head  worn on solemn occasions by church dignitaries. It has been made in many forms the present form being a lofty cap with two points or peaks."
"A little one; -- used as a term of endearment."
"The denser part of the protoplasm of a cell."
"Pertaining to a miter; resembling a miter; as  the mitral valve between the left auricle and left ventricle of the heart."
"A mitten; also  a covering for the wrist and hand and not for the fingers."
"A covering for the hand  worn to defend it from cold or injury. It differs from a glove in not having a separate sheath for each finger."
"A South American curassow of the genus Mitua."

"To cause a promiscuous interpenetration of the parts of  as of two or more substances with each other or of one substance with others; to unite or blend into one mass or compound as by stirring together; to mingle; to blend; as to mix flour and salt; to mix wines."
"With mixture; in a mixed manner; mixedly."
"The act of mixing  or the state of being mixed; as made by a mixture of ingredients."
"Hindmost; nearest the stern; as  the mizzen shrouds sails etc."

"Any one of several very large extinct species of wingless birds belonging to Dinornis  and other related genera of the suborder Dinornithes found in New Zealand. They are allied to the apteryx and the ostrich. They were probably exterminated by the natives before New Zealand was discovered by Europeans. Some species were much larger than the ostrich."
"One of the posterity of Moab  the son of Lot. (Gen. xix. 37.) Also used adjectively."
"To make a low prolonged sound of grief or pain  whether articulate or not; to groan softly and continuously."
"A deep trench around the rampart of a castle or other fortified place  sometimes filled with water; a ditch."
"To void the excrement  as a bird; to mute."
"Like a mob; tumultuous; lawless; as  a mobbish act."
"A plain cap or headdress for women or girls; especially  one tying under the chin by a very broad band generally of the same material as the cap itself."
"Capable of being moved; not fixed in place or condition; movable."
"To wrap the head of in a hood."
"A seaport town of Arabia  on the Red Sea."
"A large leather flap which covers the saddletree."
"To imitate; to mimic; esp.  to mimic in sport contempt or derision; to deride by mimicry."
"A stuff made in imitation of velvet; -- probably the same as mock velvet."
"One who  or that which mocks; a scorner; a scoffer; a derider."
"The act of mocking  deriding and exposing to contempt by mimicry by insincere imitation or by a false show of earnestness; a counterfeit appearance."
"A South American rodent (Cavia rupestris)  allied to the Guinea pig but larger; -- called also rock cavy."
"Of or pertaining to a mode or mood; consisting in mode or form only; relating to form; having the form without the essence or reality."
"Manner of doing or being; method; form; fashion; custom; way; style; as  the mode of speaking; the mode of dressing."
"A miniature representation of a thing  with the several parts in due proportion; sometimes a facsimile of the same size."
"One who models; hence  a worker in plastic art."

"Of or pertaining to the present time  or time not long past; late; not ancient or remote in past time; of recent period; as modern days ages or time; modern authors; modern fashions; modern taste; modern practice."
"Restraining within due limits of propriety; not forward  bold boastful or presumptious; rather retiring than pushing one's self forward; not obstructive; as a modest youth; a modest man."

"The quality or state of being modest; that lowly temper which accompanies a moderate estimate of one's own worth and importance; absence of self-assertion  arrogance and presumption; humility respecting one's own merit."
"A little; a small quantity; a measured simply."
"To change somewhat the form or qualities of; to alter somewhat; as  to modify a contrivance adapted to some mechanical purpose; to modify the terms of a contract."
"According to the mode  or customary manner; conformed to the fashion; fashionable; hence conventional; as a modish dress; a modish feast."
"A female maker of  or dealer in articles of fashion especially of the fashionable dress of ladies; a woman who gives direction to the style or mode of dress."
"A dry measure  containing about a peck."
"A tribe of warlike Indians formerly inhabiting Northern California. They are nearly extinct."
"Of or pertaining to mode  modulation module or modius; as modular arrangement; modular accent; modular measure."
"A quantity or coefficient  or constant which expresses the measure of some specified force property or quality as of elasticity strength efficiency etc.; a parameter."
"The arrangement of  or mode of expressing the terms of a contract or conveyance."
"A wry face or mouth; a mow."
"Movables; furniture; -- also used in the singular (moeble)."
"A thin silk stuff made in Caucasia."
"A closely fitting knit sleeve; also  a legging of knitted material."
"A kind of millet (Setaria Italica); German millet."
"The long silky hair or wool of the Angora goat of Asia Minor; also  a fabric made from this material or an imitation of such fabric."
"One of a tribe of Indians who formed part of the Five Nations. They formerly inhabited the valley of the Mohawk River."
"A gallinule (Notornis Mantelli) formerly inhabiting New Zealand  but now supposed to be extinct. It was incapable of flight. See Notornis."
"A West African gazelle (Gazella mohr)  having horns on which are eleven or twelve very prominent rings. It is one of the species which produce bezoar."
"A British Indian gold coin  of the value of fifteen silver rupees or $7.21."
"A gold coin of Portugal  valued at about 27s. sterling."
"One of two equal parts; a half; as  a moiety of an estate of goods or of profits; the moiety of a jury or of a nation."
"To daub; to make dirty; to soil; to defile."
"A kind of high shoe anciently worn."
"A small flat bastion  raised in the middle of an overlong curtain."
"The deity who assigns to every man his lot."
"Originally  a fine textile fabric made of the hair of an Asiatic goat; afterwards any textile fabric to which a watered appearance is given in the process of calendering."
"Moderately wet; damp; humid; not dry; as  a moist atmosphere or air."
"To make damp; to wet in a small degree."
"Of or pertaining to a mass of matter; -- said of the properties or motions of masses  as distinguished from those of molecules or atoms."
"A soft Tertiary sandstone; -- applied to a rock occurring in Switzerland. See Chart of Geology."
"Crumbling  soft friable earth; esp. earth containing the remains or constituents of organic matter and suited to the growth of plants; soil."
"One who  or that which molds or forms into shape; specifically (Founding) one skilled in the art of making molds for castings."
"Overgrown with  or containing mold; as moldy cheese or bread."
"A spot; a stain; a mark which discolors or disfigures."
"The fire god of the Ammonites  to whom human sacrifices were offered; Moloch."
"To trouble; to disturb; to render uneasy; to interfere with; to vex."
"The crossed iron that supports the upper millstone by resting on the spindle; a millrind."
"Minor; in the minor mode; as  A moll that is A minor."
"One of the higher order of Turkish judges; also  a Turkish title of respect for a religious and learned man."
"Lower by a semitone; flat; as  E molle that is E flat."
"To soften; to make tender; to reduce the hardness  harshness or asperity of; to qualify; as to mollify the ground."
"The fire god of the Ammonites in Canaan  to whom human sacrifices were offered; Molech. Also applied figuratively."
"To shed or cast the hair  feathers skin horns or the like as an animal or a bird."
"Much; very; as  molto adagio very slow."
"A fabulous herb of occult power  having a black root and white blossoms said by Homer to have been given by Hermes to Ulysses to counteract the spells of Circe."
"A minute portion of time; a point of time; an instant; as  at thet very moment."
"A name given in contempt to strict Calvinists in Switzerland  France and some parts of Germany in the early part of the 19th century."
"A small  handsome long-tailed West American monkey (Cercopithecus mona). The body is dark olive with a spot of white on the haunches."
"Having one hydrogen atom replaceable by a negative or acid atom or radical; capable of neutralizing a monobasic acid; -- said of bases  and of certain metals."
"An ultimate atom  or simple unextended point; something ultimate and indivisible."
"Any Asiatic pheasant of the genus Lophophorus  as the Impeyan pheasant."
"A sole or supreme ruler; a sovereign; the highest ruler; an emperor  king queen prince or chief."
"A genus of minute flagellate Infusoria of which there are many species  both free and attached. See Illust. under Monad."
"The second day of the week; the day following Sunday."
"The world; a globe as an ensign of royalty."
"The lowest division of rhizopods  including those which resemble the amoebas but are destitute of a nucleus."

"The bark  or a vegetable extract brought in solid cakes from South America and believed to be derived from the bark of the tree Chrysophyllum glycyphloeum. It is used as an alterative and astringent."
"The acrid principle of Monesia  sometimes used as a medicine."

"A piece of metal  as gold silver copper etc. coined or stamped and issued by the sovereign authority as a medium of exchange in financial transactions between citizens and with government; also any number of such pieces; coin."
"Supplied with money; having money; wealthy; as  moneyey men."
"A person who deals in money; banker or broker."
"A trader; a dealer; -- now used chiefly in composition; as  fishmonger ironmonger newsmonger."
"A species of ichneumon (Herpestes griseus)  native of India. Applied also to other allied species as the African banded mongoose (Crossarchus fasciatus)."
"The progeny resulting from a cross between two breeds  as of domestic animals; anything of mixed breed."
"That doctrine which refers all phenomena to a single ultimate constituent or agent; -- the opposite of dualism."
"One who admonishes; one who warns of faults  informs of duty or gives advice and instruction by way of reproof or caution."

"A man who retires from the ordinary temporal concerns of the world  and devotes himself to religion; one of a religious community of men inhabiting a monastery and bound by vows to a life of chastity obedience and poverty."
"The life of monks; monastic life; monastic usage or customs; -- now usually applied by way of reproach."
"In the most general sense  any one of the Quadrumana including apes baboons and lemurs."
"Like a monk  or pertaining to monks; monastic; as monkish manners; monkish dress; monkish solitude."
"The black howler of Central America (Mycetes villosus)."
"A species of poem of a mournful character  in which a single mourner expresses lamentation; a song for one voice."
"A division of Radiolaria; -- called also Monocyttaria."

"A wind blowing part of the year from one direction  alternating with a wind from the opposite direction; -- a term applied particularly to periodical winds of the Indian Ocean which blow from the southwest from the latter part of May to the middle of September and from the northeast from about the middle of October to the middle of December."
"Something of unnatural size  shape or quality; a prodigy; an enormity; a marvel."
"A favorite gambling game among Spaniards  played with dice or cards."

"A custom  formerly practiced by the scholars at Eton school England of going every third year on Whittuesday to a hillock near the Bath road and exacting money from all passers-by to support at the university the senior scholar of the school."
"An ancient kind of cap worn by horsemen or huntsmen."

"One of the twelve portions into which the year is divided; the twelfth part of a year  corresponding nearly to the length of a synodic revolution of the moon -- whence the name. In popular use a period of four weeks is often called a month."
"Continued a month  or a performed in a month; as the monthly revolution of the moon."
"A stone used in mounting a horse; a horse block."
"A heap of ore; a mass undergoing the process of amalgamation."
"That on which anything is mounted; a setting; hence  a saddle horse."
"Manner; style; mode; logical form; musical style; manner of action or being. See Mode which is the preferable form)."
"The governor of a province in Egypt  etc."
"Subject to varying moods  especially to states of mind which are unamiable or depressed."

"The celestial orb which revolves round the earth; the satellite of the earth; a secondary planet  whose light borrowed from the sun is reflected to the earth and serves to dispel the darkness of night. The diameter of the moon is 2 160 miles its mean distance from the earth is 240 000 miles and its mass is one eightieth that of the earth. See Lunar month under Month."
"One who abstractedly wanders or gazes about  as if moonstruck."
"The descent of the moon below the horizon; also  the time when the moon sets."
"One of a mixed race inhabiting Morocco  Algeria Tunis and Tripoli chiefly along the coast and in towns."
"Having the characteristics of a moor or heath."
"A clayey layer or pan underlying some moors  etc."

"A species of cassowary (Casuarius Bennetti) found in New Britain  and noted for its agility in running and leaping. It is smaller and has stouter legs than the common cassowary. Its crest is biloted; the neck and breast are black; the back rufous mixed with black; and the naked skin of the neck blue."
"Of or pertaining to moors; marshy; fenny; boggy; moorish."

"A large cervine mammal (Alces machlis  or A. Americanus) native of the Northern United States and Canada. The adult male is about as large as a horse and has very large palmate antlers. It closely resembles the European elk and by many zoologists is considered the same species. See Elk."
"One who argued moot cases in the inns of court."
"One of a class of Mohammedans in Malabar."
"A rag baby; a puppet made of cloth; hence  also in fondness a little girl or a woman."
"A game of guessing the number of fingers extended in a quick movement of the hand  -- much played by Italians of the lower classes."
"An accumulation of earth and stones carried forward and deposited by a glacier."

"Relating to duty or obligation; pertaining to those intentions and actions of which right and wrong  virtue and vice are predicated or to the rules by which such intentions and actions ought to be directed; relating to the practice manners or conduct of men as social beings in relation to each other as respects right and wrong so far as they are properly subject to rules."

"The moral condition  or the condition in other respects so far as it is affected by or dependent upon moral considerations such as zeal spirit hope and confidence; mental state as of a body of men an army and the like."
"In a moral or ethical sense; according to the rules of morality."
"A tract of soft  wet ground; a marsh; a fen."
"Not sound and healthful; induced by a diseased or abnormal condition; diseased; sickly; as  morbid humors; a morbid constitution; a morbid state of the juices of a plant."
"A thick woolen fabric  watered or with embossed figures; -- used in upholstery for curtains etc."
"An edible fungus (Morchella esculenta)  the upper part of which is covered with a reticulated and pitted hymenium. It is used as food and for flavoring sauces."
"A kind of nearly black cherry with dark red flesh and juice  -- used chiefly for preserving."
"Dying; a gradual decrescendo at the end of a strain or cadence."
"The European small-spotted dogfish  or houndfish. See the Note under Houndfish."
"A place where the bodies of persons found dead are exposed  that they may be identified or claimed by their friends; a deadhouse."
"Pertaining to  or derived from fustic (see Morin); as moric acid."
"A yellow crystalline substance of acid properties extracted from fustic (Maclura tinctoria  formerly called Morus tinctoria); -- called also moric acid."
"A genus of rubiaceous trees and shrubs  mostly East Indian many species of which yield valuable red and yellow dyes. The wood is hard and beautiful and used for gunstocks."

"A genus of trees of Southern India and Northern Africa. One species (Moringa pterygosperma) is the horse-radish tree  and its seeds as well as those of M. aptera are known in commerce as ben or ben nuts and yield the oil called oil of ben."
"A kind of open helmet  without visor or beaver and somewhat resembling a hat."
"A beast that has died of disease or by mischance."
"A bad sore; a gangrene; a cancer."
"A genus of sea birds  having a large thick bill; the puffin."
"The first part of the day; the morning; -- used chiefly in poetry."
"Of or pertaining to the morn; morning."
"Pertaining to the first part or early part of the day; being in the early part of the day; as  morning dew; morning light; morning service."
"A small abscess or tumor having a resemblance to a mulberry."

"A fine kind of leather  prepared commonly from goatskin (though an inferior kind is made of sheepskin) and tanned with sumac and dyed of various colors; -- said to have been first made by the Moors."
"Maroon; the color of an unripe black mulberry."
"Of a sour temper; sullen and austere; ill-humored; severe."

"Any one of numerous species of large  handsome tropical American butterflies of the genus Morpho. They are noted for the very brilliant metallic luster and bright colors (often blue) of the upper surface of the wings. The lower surface is usually brown or gray with eyelike spots."
"A morphological individual  characterized by definiteness of form bion a physiological individual. See Tectology."
"A Moorish dance  usually performed by a single dancer who accompanies the dance with castanets."
"A little bite or bit of food."
"Subject to death; destined to die; as  man is mortal."
"A strong vessel  commonly in form of an inverted bell in which substances are pounded or rubbed with a pestle."
"To destroy the organic texture and vital functions of; to produce gangrene in."
"A cavity cut into a piece of timber  or other material to receive something (as the end of another piece) made to fit it and called a tenon."
"Dead pay; the crime of taking pay for the service of dead soldiers  or for services not actually rendered by soldiers."
"A dish of meats and other ingredients  cooked together; an ollapodrida."

"The sphere or globular mass of cells (blastomeres)  formed by the clevage of the ovum or egg in the first stages of its development; -- called also mulberry mass segmentation sphere and blastosphere. See Segmentation."
"A genus of trees  some species of which produce edible fruit; the mulberry. See Mulberry."
"A surface decoration made by inlaying in patterns small pieces of variously colored glass  stone or other material; -- called also mosaic work."
"Attachment to the system or doctrines of Moses; that which is peculiar to the Mosaic system or doctrines."
"A light wine  usually white produced in the vicinity of the river Moselle."
"A large flatboat  used in the West Indies for taking freight from shore to ship."
"A Mohammedan church or place of religious worship."

"A cryptogamous plant of a cellular structure  with distinct stem and simple leaves. The fruit is a small capsule usually opening by an apical lid and so discharging the spores. There are many species collectively termed Musci growing on the earth on rocks and trunks of trees etc. and a few in running water."
"Overgrown with moss; abounding with or edged with moss; as  mossy trees; mossy streams."
"Consisting of the greatest number or quantity; greater in number or quantity than all the rest; nearly all."
"For the greatest part; for the most part; chiefly; in the main."
"Any singing bird of the genus Motacilla; a wagtail."
"Filled with motes  or fine floating dust; as the air."
"A composition adapted to sacred words in the elaborate polyphonic church style; an anthem."
"A female parent; especially  one of the human race; a woman who has borne a child."
"Consisting of  containing or resembling mother (in vinegar)."
"Having powers of self-motion  though unconscious; as the motile spores of certain seaweeds."
"The act  process or state of changing place or position; movement; the passing of a body from one place or position to another whether voluntary or involuntary; -- opposed to rest."
"Variegated in color; consisting of different colors; dappled; party-colored; as  a motley coat."

"Any one of several species of long-tailed  passerine birds of the genus Momotus having a strong serrated beak. In most of the species the two long middle tail feathers are racket-shaped at the tip when mature. The bird itself is said by some writers to trim them into this shape. They feed on insects reptiles and fruit and are found from Mexico to Brazil. The name is derived from its note."

"Movement; manner of movement; particularly  movement with increased rapidity; -- used especially in the phrase con moto directing to a somewhat quicker movement; as andante con moto a little more rapidly than andante etc."
"A small plate covering the armpit in armor of the 14th century and later."
"One who  or that which imparts motion; a source of mechanical power."
"A clump of trees in a prairie."
"To mark with spots of different color  or shades of color as if stained; to spot; to maculate."
"A sentence  phrase or word forming part of an heraldic achievment."
"Bearing or having a motto; as  a mottoed coat or device."

"A wild sheep (Ovis musimon)  inhabiting the mountains of Sardinia Corsica etc. Its horns are very large with a triangular base and rounded angles. It is supposed by some to be the original of the domestic sheep. Called also musimon or musmon."

"Applied to certain consonants having a """"liquid"""" or softened sound; e.g.  in French l or ll and gn (like the lli in million and ni in minion); in Italian gl and gn; in Spanish ll and �; in Portuguese lh and nh."
"To contract mold; to grow moldy; to mold."
"A ball or globe forming part of the regalia of an emperor or other sovereign. It is encircled with bands  enriched with precious stones and surmounted with a cross; -- called also globe."

"A mass of earth  or earth and rock rising considerably above the common surface of the surrounding land; a mountain; a high hill; -- used always instead of mountain when put before a proper name; as Mount Washington; otherwise chiefly in poetry."
"The rise of a hawk after prey."
"To express or to feel grief or sorrow; to grieve; to be sorrowful; to lament; to be in a state of grief or sadness."
"The armed or feruled end of a staff; in a sheephook  the end of the staff to which the hook is attached."
"One who mourns or is grieved at any misfortune  as the death of a friend."

"Any one of numerous species of small rodents belonging to the genus Mus and various related genera of the family Muridae. The common house mouse (Mus musculus) is found in nearly all countries. The American white-footed  or deer mouse (Hesperomys leucopus) sometimes lives in houses. See Dormouse Meadow mouse under Meadow and Harvest mouse under Harvest."
"The Chinese tree peony (Paeonia Mountan)  a shrub with large flowers of various colors."

"The opening through which an animal receives food; the aperture between the jaws or between the lips; also  the cavity containing the tongue and teeth between the lips and the pharynx; the buccal cavity."
"Capable of being moved  lifted carried drawn turned or conveyed or in any way made to change place or posture; susceptible of motion; not fixed or stationary; as a movable steam engine."

"To cause to change place or posture in any manner; to set in motion; to carry  convey draw or push from one place to another; to impel; to stir; as the wind moves a vessel; the horse moves a carriage."
"A person or thing that moves  stirs or changes place."
"To heat and ferment in the mow  as hay when housed too green."
"One who  or that which mows; a mowing machine; as a lawn mower."

"A soft woolly mass prepared from the young leaves of Artemisia Chinensis  and used as a cautery by burning it on the skin; hence any substance used in a like manner as cotton impregnated with niter amadou."
"Mud poured out from volcanoes during eruptions; -- so called in South America."
"The customary abbreviation of Mister in writing and printing. See Master  4."
"The customary abbreviation of Mistress when used as a title of courtesy  in writing and printing."
"A yellowish white  amorphous nitrogenous substance found in wheat rye etc. and resembling gluten; -- formerly called also mucin."
but supplied by"  "Great in quantity; long in duration; as much rain has fallen; much time."

"Pertaining to  or derived from gums and micilaginous substances; specif. denoting an acid obtained by the oxidation of gums dulcite etc. as a white crystalline substance isomeric with saccharic acid."
"Inducing or stimulating the secretion of mucus; blennogenous."
"A substance which is formed in mucous epithelial cells  and gives rise to mucin."
"A term of reproach for a low or vulgar labor person."
"Somewhat mucky; soft  sticky and dirty; muxy."
"Filthy with muck; miry; as  a mucky road."
"Of  pertaining to or designating an organic acid obtained indirectly from mucic acid and somewhat resembling itaconic acid."
"A genus of minute fungi. The plants consist of slender threads with terminal globular sporangia; mold."
"Of  pertaining to or resembling mucus; slimy ropy or stringy and lubricous; as a mucous substance."
"A minute abrupt point  as of a leaf; any small sharp point or process terminating a larger part or organ."

"A viscid fluid secreted by mucous membranes  which it serves to moisten and protect. It covers the lining membranes of all the cavities which open externally such as those of the mouth nose lungs intestinal canal urinary passages etc."
"Earth and water mixed so as to be soft and adhesive."
"Either one of two asclepiadaceous shrubs (Calotropis gigantea  and C. procera) which furnish a strong and valuable fiber. The acrid milky juice is used medicinally."
"A brown  amorphous bitter substance having a strong emetic action extracted from the root of the mudar."
"In a muddy manner; turbidly; without mixture; cloudily; obscurely; confusedly."
"To make turbid  or muddy as water."
"Abounding in mud; besmeared or dashed with mud; as  a muddy road or path; muddy boots."
"A hole  or hollow place containing mud as in a road."
"The lowest sill of a structure  usually embedded in the soil; the lowest timber of a house; also that sill or timber of a bridge which is laid at the bottom of the water. See Sill."
"A small herbaceous plant growing on muddy shores (Limosella aquatica)."
"A Mohammedan crier of the hour of prayer."
"A soft cover of cylindrical form  usually of fur worn by women to shield the hands from cold."
"A light  spongy cylindrical cake used for breakfast and tea."
"The bare end of the nose between the nostrils; -- used esp. of ruminants."
"Anything used in muffling; esp.  a scarf for protecting the head and neck in cold weather; a tippet."
"A kind of earthen or metal drinking cup  with a handle -- usually cylindrical and without a lip."
"The small entrails of a calf or a hog."
"A genus of fishes including the gray mullets. See Mullet."
"A slender European weed (Galium Cruciata); -- called also crossweed."
"A somewhat aromatic composite weed (Artemisia vulgaris)  at one time used medicinally; -- called also motherwort."
"A bolter from the Republican party in the national election of 1884; an Independent."
"The offspring of a negress by a white man  or of a white woman by a negro -- usually of a brownish yellow complexion."
"Half-rotten straw  or any like substance strewn on the ground as over the roots of plants to protect from heat drought etc. and to preserve moisture."
"A fine or penalty  esp. a pecuniary punishment or penalty."
"A hybrid animal; specifically  one generated between an ass and a mare sometimes a horse and a she-ass. See Hinny."
"A stiff  long saw guided at the ends but not stretched in a gate."
"A die  cut in intaglio for stamping an ornament in relief as upon metal."
"Any plant of the genus Verbascum. They are tall herbs having coarse leaves  and large flowers in dense spikes. The common species with densely woolly leaves is Verbascum Thapsus."

"Any one of numerous fishes of the genus Mugil; -- called also gray mullets. They are found on the coasts of both continents  and are highly esteemed as food. Among the most valuable species are Mugil capito of Europe and M. cephalus which occurs both on the European and American coasts."
"A slender bar or pier which forms the division between the lights of windows  screens etc."
"Like or pertaining to the genus Mullus  which includes the surmullet or red mullet."
"An extract of quassia licorice  fraudulently used by brewers in order to economize malt and hops."
"To speak with the lips partly closed  so as to render the sounds inarticulate and imperfect; to utter words in a grumbling indistinct manner indicating discontent or displeasure; to mutter."
"To sport or make diversion in a mask or disguise; to mask."
"One who mumms  or makes diversion in disguise; a masker; a buffon."
"To embalm and dry as a mummy; to make into  or like a mummy."
"A dead body embalmed and dried after the manner of the ancient Egyptians; also  a body preserved by any means in a dry state from the process of putrefaction."
"To move the lips with the mouth closed; to mumble  as in sulkiness."
"To chew with a grinding  crunching sound as a beast chews provender; to chew deliberately or in large mouthfuls."
"Of or pertaining to the world; worldly; earthly; terrestrial; as  the mundane sphere."
"Iron pyrites  or arsenical pyrites; -- so called by the Cornish miners."
"A turban ornamented with an imitation of gold or silver embroidery."
"Green gram  a kind of pulse (Phaseolus Mungo) grown for food in British India."
"A fibrous material obtained by deviling rags or the remnants of woolen goods."
"Same as Mullion; -- especially used in joiner's work."
"Any one of several species of small Asiatic deer of the genus Cervulus  esp. C. muntjac which occurs both in India and on the East Indian Islands."

"A genus of large eels of the family Miraenidae. They differ from the common eel in lacking pectoral fins and in having the dorsal and anal fins continuous. The murry (Muraena Helenae) of Southern Europe was the muraena of the Romans. It is highly valued as a food fish."
"A tax or toll paid for building or repairing the walls of a fortified town."
"Of or pertaining to a wall; being on  or in a wall; growing on or against a wall; as a mural quadrant."
"The offense of killing a human being with malice prepense or aforethought  express or implied; intentional and unlawful homicide."
"A genus of marine gastropods  having rough and frequently spinose shells which are often highly colored inside; the rock shells. They abound in tropical seas."

"A complex nitrogenous substance obtained from murexide  alloxantin and other ureids as a white or yellowish crystalline which turns red on exposure to the air; -- called also uramil dialuramide and formerly purpuric acid."
"A salt of muriatic hydrochloric acid; a chloride; as  muriate of ammonia."
"Bromine; -- formerly so called from its being obtained from sea water."
"Pertaining to a family of rodents (Muridae)  of which the mouse is the type."
"A low  confused and indistinct sound like that of running water."
"An infectious and fatal disease among cattle."
"Any one of several species of sea birds of the genus Uria  or Catarractes; a guillemot."
"One of the hereditary nobility among the Tatars  esp. one of the second class."
"A genus of small rodents  including the common mouse and rat."

"A genus of perennial  herbaceous endogenous plants of great size including the banana (Musa sapientum) the plantain (M. paradisiaca of Linnaeus but probably not a distinct species) the Abyssinian (M. Ensete) the Philippine Island (M. textilis which yields Manila hemp) and about eighteen other species. See Illust. of Banana and Plantain."
"Of or pertaining to the Muses  or to Poetry."

"A small animal of Java (Paradoxirus fasciatus)  allied to the civets. It swallows but does not digest large quantities of ripe coffee berries thus serving to disseminate the coffee plant; hence it is called also coffee rat."
"An itinerant player on the musette  an instrument formerly common in Europe."
"A genus of dipterous insects  including the common house fly and numerous allied species."
"A name given to several varieties of Old World grapes  differing in color size etc. but all having a somewhat musky flavor. The muscat of Alexandria is a large oval grape of a pale amber color."
"An order or subclass of cryptogamous plants; the mosses. See Moss  and Cryptogamia."
"Any fly of the genus Musca  or family Muscidae."
"An organ which  by its contraction produces motion."
"Furnished with muscles; having muscles; as  things well muscled."
"A long movable shed used by besiegers in ancient times in attacking the walls of a fortified town."
"A gap or hole in a hedge  hence wall or the like through which a wild animal is accustomed to pass; a muset."
"A small hole or gap through which a wild animal passes; a muse."
"A small bagpipe formerly in use  having a soft and sweet tone."
"A repository or a collection of natural  scientific or literary curiosities or of works of art."
"Meal (esp. Indian meal) boiled in water; hasty pudding; supawn."
"Soft like mush; figuratively  good-naturedly weak and effusive; weakly sentimental."

"The science and the art of tones  or musical sounds i. e. sounds of higher or lower pitch begotten of uniform and synchronous vibrations as of a string at various degrees of tension; the science of harmonical tones which treats of the principles of harmony or the properties dependences and relations of tones to each other; the art of combining tones in a manner to please the ear."

"Of or pertaining to music; having the qualities of music; or the power of producing music; devoted to music; melodious; harmonious; as  musical proportion; a musical voice; musical instruments; a musical sentence; musical persons."

"A substance of a reddish brown color  and when fresh of the consistence of honey obtained from a bag being behind the navel of the male musk deer. It has a slightly bitter taste but is specially remarkable for its powerful and enduring odor. It is used in medicine as a stimulant antispasmodic. The term is also applied to secretions of various other animals having a similar odor."

"A North American aquatic fur-bearing rodent (Fiber zibethicus). It resembles a rat in color and having a long scaly tail  but the tail is compressed the bind feet are webbed and the ears are concealed in the fur. It has scent glands which secrete a substance having a strong odor of musk. Called also musquash musk beaver and ondatra."
"Having an odor of musk  or somewhat the like."
"A thin cotton  white dyed or printed. The name is also applied to coarser and heavier cotton goods; as shirting and sheeting muslins."
"The nose band of a horse's bridle."
"A scramble  as when small objects are thrown down to be taken by those who can seize them; a confused struggle."

"Any one of many species of marine bivalve shells of the genus Mytilus  and related genera of the family Mytidae. The common mussel (Mytilus edulis; see Illust. under Byssus) and the larger or horse mussel (Modiola modiolus) inhabiting the shores both of Europe and America are edible. The former is extensively used as food in Europe."
"A variety of pyroxene  from the Mussa Alp in Piedmont; diopside."
"To be obliged; to be necessitated; -- expressing either physical or moral necessity; as  a man must eat for nourishment; we must submit to the laws."
"The half-wild horse of the plains in Mexico  California etc. It is small hardy and easily sustained."
"The name of several cruciferous plants of the genus Brassica (formerly Sinapis)  as white mustard (B. alba) black mustard (B. Nigra) wild mustard or charlock (B. Sinapistrum)."
"Having the rank  pungent offencive odor and taste which substances of organic origin acquire during warm moist weather; foul or sour and fetid; moldy; as musty corn; musty books."
"Capable of alteration; subject to change; changeable in form  qualities or nature."
"A process for checking the fermentation of the must of grapes."
"The close linen or muslin cap of an old woman."
"A liquid measure equal to four gills  or an imperial pint."
"Without uttering words or sounds; in a mute manner; silently."

"Insurrection against constituted authority  particularly military or naval authority; concerted revolt against the rules of discipline or the lawful commands of a superior officer; hence generally forcible resistance to rightful authority; insubordination."
"The condition  state or habit of being mute or without speech."
"To utter words indistinctly or with a low voice and lips partly closed; esp.  to utter indistinct complaints or angry expressions; to grumble; to growl."
"Like mutton; having a flavor of mutton."
"Reciprocally acting or related; reciprocally receiving and giving; reciprocally given and received; reciprocal; interchanged; as  a mutual love advantage assistance aversion etc."
"One who borrows personal chattels which are to be consumed by him  and which he is to return or repay in kind."
"A projecting block worked under the corona of the Doric corice  in the same situation as the modillion of the Corinthian and Composite orders. See Illust. of Gutta."
"One of a denomination of Christians formerly living under the government of the Moors in Spain  and having a liturgy and ritual of their own."
"The projecting mouth and nose of a quadruped  as of a horse; a snout."
"A genus of bivalve mollusks  including the common long or soft-shelled clam."
"Pain in the muscles; muscular rheumatism or neuralgia."
"A division of bivalve mollusks of which the common clam (Mya) is the type."
"A genus of South American monkeys  including the howlers. See Howler 2 and Illust."
"A variety of sugar  isomeric with sucrose and obtained from certain lichens and fungi. Called also trehalose."
"A soft white substance constituting the medullary sheats of nerve fibers  and composed mainly of cholesterin lecithin cerebrin albumin and some fat."
"Resembling marrow in appearance or consistency; as  a myeloid tumor."

"A genus of very large hairy spiders having four lungs and only four spinnerets. They do not spin webs  but usually construct tubes in the earth which are often furnished with a trapdoor. The South American bird spider (Mygale avicularia) and the crab spider or matoutou (M. cancerides) are among the largest species. Some of the species are erroneously called tarantulas as the Texas tarantula (M. Hentzii)."
"An extinct genus of large slothlike American edentates  allied to Megatherium."

"Any one of numerous species of Asiatic starlings of the genera Acridotheres  Sturnopastor Sturnia Gracula and allied genera. In habits they resemble the European starlings and like them are often caged and taught to talk. See Hill myna under Hill and Mino bird."
"The Dutch equivalent of Mr. or Sir; hence  a Dutchman."
"That part of anatomy which treats of muscles."
"A contractile striated layer found in the bodies and stems of certain Infusoria."

"Nearsightedness; shortsightedness; a condition of the eye in which the rays from distant object are brought to a focus before they reach the retina  and hence form an indistinct image; while the rays from very near objects are normally converged so as to produce a distinct image. It is corrected by the use of a concave lens."
"Pertaining to  or affected with or characterized by myopia; nearsighted."
"The appearance of muscae volitantes. See Muscae volitantes  under Musca."

"An albuminous body present in dead muscle  being formed in the process of coagulation which takes place in rigor mortis; the clot formed in the coagulation of muscle plasma. See Muscle plasma under Plasma."
"Long-continued contraction of the pupil of the eye."
"Producing myosis  or contraction of the pupil of the eye as opium calabar bean etc."
"A muscular segment; one of the zones into which the muscles of the trunk  especially in fishes are divided; a myocomma."
"The dissection  or that part of anatomy which treats of the dissection of muscles."
"A large genus of tropical American trees and shrubs  nearly related to the true myrtles (Myrtus) from which they differ in having very few seeds in each berry."
"The number of ten thousand; ten thousand persons or things."
"A measure of surface in the metric system containing ten thousand ares  or one million square meters. It is equal to about 247.1 acres."
"A widely dispersed genus of shrubs and trees  usually with aromatic foliage. It includes the bayberry or wax myrtle the sweet gale and the North American sweet fern so called."
"A silky  crystalline waxy substance forming the less soluble part of beeswax and regarded as a palmitate of a higher alcohol of the paraffin series; -- called also myricyl alcohol."
"A hypothetical radical regarded as the essential residue of myricin; -- called also melissyl."
"Pertaining to  or obtained from mustard; -- used specifically to designate a glucoside called myronic acid found in mustard seed."
"A ferment  resembling diastase found in mustard seeds."

"A gum resin  usually of a yellowish brown or amber color of an aromatic odor and a bitter slightly pungent taste. It is valued for its odor and for its medicinal properties. It exudes from the bark of a shrub of Abyssinia and Arabia the Balsamodendron Myrrha. The myrrh of the Bible is supposed to have been partly the gum above named and partly the exudation of species of Cistus or rockrose."
"Of  pertaining to or obtained from myrrh."

"A species of the genus Myrtus  especially Myrtus communis. The common myrtle has a shrubby upright stem eight or ten feet high. Its branches form a close full head thickly covered with ovate or lanceolate evergreen leaves. It has solitary axillary white or rosy flowers followed by black several-seeded berries. The ancients considered it sacred to Venus. The flowers leaves and berries are used variously in perfumery and as a condiment and the beautifully mottled wood is used in turning."

"I or me in person; -- used for emphasis  my own self or person; as I myself will do it; I have done it myself; -- used also instead of me as the object of the first person of a reflexive verb without emphasis; as I will defend myself."

"A genus of small schizopod shrimps found both in fresh and salt water; the opossum shrimps. One species inhabits the Great Lakes of North America  and is largely eaten by the whitefish. The marine species form part of the food of right whales."

"A profound secret; something wholly unknown  or something kept cautiously concealed and therefore exciting curiosity or wonder; something which has not been or can not be explained; hence specifically that which is beyond human comprehension."
"To involve in mystery; to make obscure or difficult to understand; as  to mystify a passage of Scripture."

"A story of great but unknown age which originally embodied a belief regarding some fact or phenomenon of experience  and in which often the forces of nature and of the soul are personified; an ancient legend of a god a hero the origin of a race etc.; a wonder story of prehistoric origin; a popular fable which is or has been received as historical."
"A genus of marine bivalve shells  including the common mussel. See Illust. under Byssus."
"The distal end of the mandibles of a bird."
"A genus of marsipobranchs  including the hagfish. See Hag 4."
"A tumor made up of a gelatinous tissue resembling that found in the umbilical cord."
"A rhizopod or moneran. Also used adjectively; as  a myxopod state."
"The edible berries of the Zizyphys Lotus  a tree of Northern Africa and Southwestern Europe."
"A deputy or viceroy in India; a governor of a province of the ancient Mogul empire."
"A pale red color  with a cast of orange."
"A pearly substance which lines the interior of many shells  and is most perfect in the mother-of-pearl. [Written also nacker and naker.] See Pearl and Mother-of-pearl."
"That point of the heavens  or lower hemisphere directly opposite the zenith; the inferior pole of the horizon; the point of the celestial sphere directly under the place where we stand."
"Resembling a naevus or naevi; as  naevoid elephantiasis."
"A spot or mark on the skin of children when born; a birthmark; -- usually applied to vascular tumors  i. e. those consisting mainly of blood vessels as dilated arteries veins or capillaries."
"A small horse; a pony; hence  any horse."
"A water nymph; one of the lower female divinities  fabled to preside over some body of fresh water as a lake river brook or fountain."
"Any one of numerous species of small  fresh-water chaetopod annelids of the tribe Naidina. They belong to the Oligochaeta."
"Having a true natural luster without being cut; -- applied by jewelers to a precious stone."
"A chief; a leader; a Sepoy corporal."
"the horny scale of plate of epidermis at the end of the fingers and toes of man and many apes."
"One whose occupation is to make nails; a nail maker."
"Having native or unaffected simplicity; ingenuous; artless; frank; as  naive manners; a naive person; naive and unsophisticated remarks."
"Native simplicity; unaffected plainness or ingenuousness; artlessness."
"Having no clothes on; uncovered; nude; bare; as  a naked body; a naked limb; a naked sword."
"In a naked manner; without covering or disguise; manifestly; simply; barely."
"The title by which any person or thing is known or designated; a distinctive specific appellation  whether of an individual or a class."
"By name; by particular mention; specifically; especially; expressly."
"One who names  or calls by name."
"An African carnivore (Nandinia binotata)  allied to the civets. It is spotted with black."
"Any one of three species of South American ostriches of the genera Rhea and Pterocnemia. See Rhea."

"A species of cloth  of a firm texture originally brought from China made of a species of cotton (Gossypium religiosum) that is naturally of a brownish yellow color quite indestructible and permanent."
"A diminutive of Ann or Anne  the proper name."
"A term used by modern archaeologists instead of cella. See Cella."
"To have a short sleep; to be drowsy; to doze."
"Table linen; also  linen clothing or linen in general."

"The complex mixture of volatile  liquid inflammable hydrocarbons occurring naturally and usually called crude petroleum mineral oil or rock oil. Specifically: That portion of the distillate obtained in the refinement of petroleum which is intermediate between the lighter gasoline and the heavier benzine and has a specific gravity of about 0.7 -- used as a solvent for varnishes as a carburetant illuminant etc."
"A little towel  or small cloth esp. one for wiping the fingers and mouth at table."
