"Sheet; surface; all that portion of a surface that is continuous in such a way that it is possible to pass from any one point of the portion to any other point of the portion without leaving the surface. Thus  some hyperboloids have one nappe and some have two."
"Inclined to sleep; sleepy; as  to feel nappy."
"A very small chevrotain (Tragulus Javanicus)  native of Java. It is about the size of a hare and is noted for its agility in leaping. Called also Java musk deer pygmy musk deer and deerlet."
"An East Indian plant (Nardostachys Jatamansi) of the Valerian family  used from remote ages in Oriental perfumery."
"Of or pertaining to nard; having the qualities of nard."
"An Australian name for Marsilea Drummondii  a four-leaved cryptogamous plant sometimes used for food."
"The nostrils or nasal openings  -- the anterior nares being the external or proper nostrils and the posterior nares the openings of the nasal cavities into the mouth or pharynx."
"To tell  rehearse or recite as a story; to relate the particulars of; to go through with in detail as an incident or transaction; to give an account of."
"Of little breadth; not wide or broad; having little distance from side to side; as  a narrow board; a narrow street; a narrow hem."
"A tall umbelliferous plant (Ferula communis). See Giant fennel  under Fennel."

"An arctic cetacean (Monodon monocerous)  about twenty feet long. The male usually has one long twisted pointed canine tooth or tusk projecting forward from the upper jaw like a horn whence it is called also sea unicorn unicorn fish and unicorn whale. Sometimes two horns are developed side by side."
"In a nasal manner; by the nose."
"A kind of pessary of medicated wool or cotton  formerly used."
"Commencing  or in process of development; beginning to exist or to grow; coming into being; as a nascent germ."
"The middle point of the nasofrontal suture."
"Any species of marine gastropods  of the genera Nassa Tritia and other allied genera of the family Nassidae; a dog whelk. See Illust. under Gastropoda."
"Offensively filthy; very dirty  foul or defiled; disgusting; nauseous."
"Of or pertaining to one's birth; accompying or dating from one's birth; native."
"One's birth  or the circumstances attending it."
"Floating in water  as the leaves of water lilies or submersed as those of many aquatic plants."
"The rump of beef; esp.  the lower and back part of the rump."
"A tribe of Indians who formerly lived near the site of the city of Natchez  Mississippi. In 1729 they were subdued by the French; the survivors joined the Creek Confederacy."
"Any one of numerous species of marine gastropods belonging to Natica  Lunatia Neverita and other allied genera (family Naticidae.) They burrow beneath the sand or mud and drill other shells."
"A part  or division of the people of the earth distinguished from the rest by common descent language or institutions; a race; a stock."
"Arising by birth; having an origin; born."

"Fixed or determined by nature; pertaining to the constitution of a thing; belonging to native character; according to nature; essential; characteristic; not artifical  foreign assumed put on or acquired; as the natural growth of animals or plants; the natural motion of a gravitating body; natural strength or disposition; the natural heat of the body; natural color."
"The existing system of things; the world of matter  or of matter and mind; the creation; the universe."
"Having (such) a nature  temper or disposition; disposed; -- used in composition; as good-natured ill-natured etc."
"Seasickness; hence  any similar sickness of the stomach accompanied with a propensity to vomit; qualm; squeamishness of the stomach; loathing."
"An entertainment consisting chiefly of dancing by professional dancing (or Nautch) girls."
"Having to do with shipping; of or pertaining to ships or a navy; consisting of ships; as  naval forces successes stores etc."
"The block in the center of a wheel  from which the spokes radiate and through which the axle passes; -- called also hub or hob."
"A mark or depression in the middle of the abdomen; the umbilicus. See Umbilicus."
"A kind of small turnip  a variety of Brassica campestris. See Brassica."
"Originally  a laborer on canals for internal navigation; hence a laborer on other public works as in building railroads embankments etc."
"A fleet of ships; an assemblage of merchantmen  or so many as sail in company."
"A deputy ruler or viceroy in India; also  a title given by courtesy to other persons of high rank in the East."
"No; -- a negative answer to a question asked  or a request made now superseded by no. See Yes."
"A specied of wild sheep (Ovis Hodgsonii)  native of Nepaul and Thibet. It has a dorsal mane and a white ruff beneath the neck."
"A byword; a proverb; also  a watchword."
"The tongue or pole of a cart or other vehicle drawn by two animals."
"Left aground on the height of a spring tide  so that it will not float till the next spring tide; -- called also beneaped."
"At a little distance  in place time manner or degree; not remote; nigh."
"In a near manner; not remotely; closely; intimately; almost."
"Cattle of the genus Bos  as distinguished from horses sheep and goats; an animal of the genus Bos; as a neat's tongue; a neat's foot."
"The nose; the snout; the mouth; the beak of a bird; a nib  as of a pen."
"A genus of small marine Crustacea  considered the type of a distinct order (Nebaloidea or Phyllocarida.)"
"A faint  cloudlike self-luminous mass of matter situated beyond the solar system among the stars. True nebulae are gaseous; but very distant star clusters often appear like them in the telescope."
"Of or pertaining to nebulae; of the nature of  or resembling a nebula."
"Composed of successive short curves supposed to resemble a cloud; -- said of a heraldic line by which an ordinary or subordinary may be bounded."
"The part of an animal which connects the head and the trunk  and which in man and many other animals is more slender than the trunk."
"A scarf  band or kerchief of silk etc. passing around the neck or collar and tied in front; a bow of silk etc. fastened in front of the neck."
"To affect with necrosis; to unergo necrosis."
"The drink of the gods (as ambrosia was their food); hence  any delicious or inspiring beverage."

"That part of a blossom which secretes nectar  usually the base of the corolla or petals; also the spur of such flowers as the larkspur and columbine whether nectariferous or not. See the Illustration of Nasturtium."
fem."  "Born; -- a term sometimes used in introducing the name of the family to which a married woman belongs by birth; as Madame de Stael nee Necker."
"A state that requires supply or relief; pressing occasion for something; necessity; urgent want."
"Full of need; in need or want; needy; distressing."
"In a needy condition or manner; necessarily."
"A small instrument of steel  sharply pointed at one end with an eye to receive a thread -- used in sewing."
"One who makes or uses needles; also  a dealer in needles."
"Like a needle or needles; as  a needly horn; a needly beard."
"Of necessity; necessarily; indispensably; -- often with must  and equivalent to of need."
"Distressed by want of the means of living; very por; indigent; necessitous."
"Any fish of the genus Distichodus. Several large species inhabit the Nile."

"Not to attend to with due care or attention; to forbear one's duty in regard to; to suffer to pass unimproved  unheeded undone etc.; to omit; to disregard; to slight; as to neglect duty or business; to neglect to pay debts."
"A blackish fish (Hypoplectrus nigricans)  of the Sea-bass family. It is a native of the West Indies and Florida."

"A black man; especially  one of a race of black or very dark persons who inhabit the greater part of tropical Africa and are distinguished by crisped or curly hair flat noses and thick protruding lips; also any black person of unmixed African blood wherever found."
"A beverage made of wine  water sugar nutmeg and lemon juice; -- so called it is said from its first maker Colonel Negus."
"A woman born in the state of villeinage; a female serf."
"To utter the cry of the horse; to whinny."
"Not either; not the one or the other."
"A genus of great water lilies. The North American species is Nelumbo lutea  the Asiatic is the sacred lotus N. speciosa."
"Of or pertaining to Nemea  in Argolis where the ancient Greeks celebrated games and Hercules killed a lion."
"The goddess of retribution or vengeance; hence  retributive justice personified; divine vengeance."
"Of or pertaining to a wood or grove."
"More recent than the Eocene  that is including both the Miocene and Pliocene divisions of the Tertiary."
"An alloy resembling silver  and consisting chiefly of copper zinc and nickel with small proportions of tin aluminium and bismuth."
"The introduction of a new word  or of words or significations into a language; as the present nomenclature of chemistry is a remarkable instance of neology."
"A panorama of the interior of a building  seen from within."
"More recent than the Paleozoic  -- that is including the Mesozoic and Cenozoic."
"A genus of aquatic hemipterus insects. The species feed upon other insects and are noted for their voracity; -- called also scorpion bug and water scorpion."
"A genus of labiate plants  including the catnip and ground ivy."
"A grandson or grandchild  or remoter lineal descendant."
"The son of Saturn and Ops  the god of the waters especially of the sea. He is represented as bearing a trident for a scepter."
"A sea nymph  one of the daughters of Nereus who were attendants upon Neptune and were represented as riding on sea horses sometimes with the human form entire and sometimes with the tail of a fish."
"A genus of marine gastropods  mostly natives of warm climates."
"A Roman emperor notorius for debauchery and barbarous cruelty; hence  any profligate and cruel ruler or merciless tyrant."
"An essential oil obtained by distillation from the flowers of the orange. It has a strong odor  and is used in perfumery etc."
"One of the whitish and elastic bundles of fibers  with the accompanying tissues which transmit nervous impulses between nerve centers and various parts of the animal body."
"Having the quality of acting upon or affecting the nerves; quieting nervous excitement."
"The bed or receptacle prepared by a fowl for holding her eggs and for hatching and rearing her young."
"As much or many as will fill a nest."
"To make and occupy a nest; to nest."
"A genus of parrots with gray heads. of New Zeland and papua  allied to the cockatoos. See Kaka."
"A fabric of twine  thread or the like wrought or woven into meshes and used for catching fish birds butterflies etc."
"To make into a net; to make n the style of network; as  to net silk."
"Situated down or below; lying beneath  or in the lower part; having a lower position; belonging to the region below; lower; under; -- opposed to upper."
"To render neat; to clean; to put in order."

"A plant of the genus Urtica  covered with minute sharp hairs containing a poison that produces a stinging sensation. Urtica gracitis is common in the Northern and U. chamaedryoides in the Southern United States. the common European species U. urens and U. dioica are also found in the Eastern united States. U. pilulifera is the Roman nettle of England."
"The halves of yarns in the unlaid end of a rope twisted for pointing or grafting."
"A fabric of threads  cords or wires crossing each other at certain intervals and knotted or secured at the crossings thus leaving spaces or meshes between them."
"Toward the neural side; -- opposed to haemad."

"relating to the nerves or nervous system; taining to  situated in the region of or on the side with the neural or cerebro-spinal axis; -- opposed to hemal. As applied to vertebrates neural is the same as dorsal; as applied to invertebrates it is usually the same as ventral. Cf. Hemal."

"A poisonous organic base (a ptomaine) formed in the decomposition of protagon with boiling baryta water  and in the putrefraction of proteid matter. It was for a long time considered identical with choline a crystalline body originally obtained from bile. Chemically however choline is oxyethyl-trimethyl-ammonium hydroxide while neurine is vinyl-trimethyl-ammonium hydroxide."
"Nerve force. See Vital force  under Vital."
"A tumor developed on  or connected with a nerve esp. one consisting of new-formed nerve fibers."
"The brain and spinal cord; the cerebro-spinal axis; myelencephalon."
"An embryo or certain invertebrates in the stage when the primitive band is first developed."
"Neither the one thing nor the other; on neither side; impartial; neutral."
"Not engaged on either side; not taking part with or assisting either of two or more contending parties; neuter; indifferent."
"The upper part of a glacier  above the limit or perpetual snow. See Galcier."
"Not ever; not at any time; at no time  whether past present or future."

"Having existed  or having been made but a short time; having originated or occured lately; having recently come into existence or into one's possession; not early or long in being; of late origin; recent; fresh; modern; -- opposed to old as a new coat; a new house; a new book; a new fashion."
"The quality or state of being new; as  the newness of a system; the newness of a scene; newness of life."
"A report of recent occurences; information of something that has lately taken place  or of something before unknown; fresh tindings; recent intelligence."
"A boy who distributes or sells newspaper."
"Full of news; abounding in information as to current events."

"Any one of several species of small aquatic salamanders. The common British species are the crested newt (Triton cristatus) and the smooth newt (Lophinus punctatus). In America  Diemictylus viridescens is one of the most abundant species."
"Nearest in place; having no similar object intervening."
"A young hawk; an eyas; hence  an unsophisticated person."
"A small and pointed thing or part; a point; a prong."
"To bite by little at a time; to seize gently with the mouth; to eat slowly or in small bits."
"A kind of golf stick used to lift the ball out of holes  ruts etc."
"Foolish; silly; simple; ignorant; also  weak; effeminate."
"Of or pertaining to Nice  a town of Asia Minor or to the ecumenial council held there A. D. 325."
"The quality or state of being nice (in any of the senses of that word.)."
"A cavity  hollow or recess generally within the thickness of a wall for a statue bust or other erect ornament. hence any similar position literal or figurative."

"A bright silver-white metallic element. It is of the iron group  and is hard malleable and ductile. It occurs combined with sulphur in millerite with arsenic in the mineral niccolite and with arsenic and sulphur in nickel glance. Symbol Ni. Atomic weight 58.6."
"One of the night brawlers of London formerly noted for breaking windows with half-pence."
"The European woodpecker  or yaffle; -- called also nicker pecker."
"A nestful; a brood; as  a nide of pheasants."
"A coward; a dastard; -- a term of utmost opprobrium."
"Scent or savor of meat or food  cooked or cooking."
"A nest: a repository for the eggs of birds  insects etc.; a breeding place; esp. the place or substance where parasites or the germs of a disease effect lodgment or are developed."
"A relative  in general; especially a descendant whether male or female; a granddaughter or a grandson."
"A metallic alloy of a deep black color."
"A person meanly close and covetous; one who spends grudgingly; a stingy  parsimonous fellow; a miser."
"A negro; -- in vulgar derision or depreciation."
"To trifle with; to deceive; to mock."
"Not distant or remote in place or time; near."
"In a near relation in place  time degree etc.; within a little; almost."

"That part of the natural day when the sun is beneath the horizon  or the time from sunset to sunrise; esp. the time between dusk and dawn when there is no light of the sun but only moonlight starlight or artificial light."
"Of or pertaining to the night  or to every night; happening or done by night or every night; as nightly shades; he kept nightly vigils."
"Not to will; to refuse; to reject."
"Of or pertaining to the river Nile; as  the Nilotic crocodile."
"Light and quick in motion; moving with ease and celerity; lively; swift."
"In a nimble manner; with agility; with light  quick motion."
"A circle  or disk or any indication of radiant light around the heads of divinities saints and sovereigns upon medals pictures etc.; a halo. See Aureola and Glory n. 5."
"Eight and one more; one less than ten; as  nine miles."
"Nine times ten; eighty-nine and one more; as  ninety men."
"Following the eight and preceding the tenth; coming after eight others."
"The daughter of Tantalus  and wife of Amphion king of Thebes. Her pride in her children provoked Apollo and Diana who slew them all. Niobe herself was changed by the gods into stone."
"A later name of columbium. See Columbium."
"A kind of snuff prepared by the natives of Venezuela from the roasted seeds of a leguminous tree (Piptadenia peregrina)  thence called niopo tree."
"A sip or small draught; esp.  a draught of intoxicating liquor; a dram."
"Small pinchers for holding  breaking or cutting."
"The protuberance through which milk is drawn from the breast or mamma; the mammilla; a teat; a pap."

"In the Buddhist system of religion  the final emancipation of the soul from transmigration and consequently a beatific enfrachisement from the evils of wordly existence as by annihilation or absorption into the divine. See Buddhism."
"The first month of the jewish ecclesiastical year  formerly answering nearly to the month of April now to March of the Christian calendar. See Abib."
"The egg of a louse or other small insect."
"A white crystalline semitransparent salt; potassium nitrate; saltpeter. See Saltpeter."

"Of  pertaining to or containing nitrogen; specifically designating any one of those compounds in which as contrasted with nitrous compounds the element has a higher valence; as nitric oxide; nitric acid."
"A binary compound of nitrogen with a more metallic element or radical; as  boric nitride."
"To combine or impregnate with nitrogen; to convert  by oxidation into nitrous or nitric acid; to subject to or produce by nitrification."

"Any one of a series of cyanogen compounds; particularly  one of those cyanides of alcohol radicals which by boiling with acids or alkalies produce a carboxyl acid with the elimination of the nitrogen as ammonia."
"Any one of a series of hydrocarbons containing the nitro and the nitroso or isonitroso group united to the same carbon atom."
"Of  pertaining to or containing niter; of the quality of niter or resembling it."
"A name sometimes given to the nitro group or radical."
"The horselouse; an insect that deposits nits on horses."
"Snowy; resembling snow; partaking of the qualities of snow."
"The fourth month of the French republican calendar [1792-1806]. It commenced December 21  and ended January 19. See VendEmiaire."
"One of a class of water spirits  commonly described as of a mischievous disposition."
"The title of the native sovereigns of Hyderabad  in India since 1719."
"A patriarch of Biblical history  in the time of the Deluge."
"Possessing eminence  elevation dignity etc.; above whatever is low mean degrading or dishonorable; magnanimous; as a noble nature or action; a noble heart."
"Of noble extraction; as  nobly born or descended."
"Indian corn parched  and beaten to powder -- used for food by the Northern American Indians."
"Doing hurt  or having a tendency to hurt; hurtful; mischievous; noxious; as nocent qualities."
"Any one of numerous moths of the family Noctuidae  or Noctuaelitae as the cutworm moths and armyworm moths; -- so called because they fly at night."
"An office of devotion  or act of religious service by night."
"To bend or incline the upper part  with a quick motion; as nodding plumes."
"Of the nature of  or relating to a node; as a nodal point."
"A knot  a knob; a protuberance; a swelling."
"Of or pertaining to the nodes; from a node to the same node again; as  the nodical revolutions of the moon."
"Of  pertaining to or in the form of a nodule or knot."
"A rounded mass or irregular shape; a little knot or lump."
"The science of the understanding; intellectual science."
"One of the followers of Noetus  who lived in the third century. He denied the distinct personality of the Father Son and Holy Ghost."
"Made of hemp; hence  hard; rough; harsh."
"Rough brick masonry used to fill in the interstices of a wooden frame  in building."
"Waste and knots of wool removed by the comb; combings."
"Noxious to health; hurtful; mischievous; unwholesome; insalubrious; destructive; as  noisome effluvia."
"Making a noise  esp. a loud sound; clamorous; vociferous; turbulent; boisterous; as the noisy crowd."
"One of a race or tribe that has no fixed location  but wanders from place to place in search of pasture or game."
"Of or pertaining to nomads  or their way of life; wandering; moving from place to place for subsistence; as a nomadic tribe."
"The art or practice of divining the destiny of persons by the letters which form their names."
"The chief magistrate of a nome or nomarchy."
"The entrails of a deer; the umbles."
"A point halfway between the fess point and the middle base point of an escutcheon; -- called also navel point. See Escutcheon."
"Customary; ordinary; -- applied to the usual English spelling  in distinction from strictly phonetic methods."
"Of or pertaining to a name or names; having to do with the literal meaning of a word; verbal; as  a nominal definition."
"A person named  or designated by another to any office duty or position; one nominated or proposed by others for office or for election to office."
"Destitute of acid properties; hence  basic; metallic; positive; -- said of certain atoms and radicals."
"The ninth part of movable goods  formerly payable to the clergy on the death of persons in their parishes."
"Having the quality of nonage; being a minor; immature."
"A figure or polygon having nine sides and nine angles."

"One of a group of metameric hydrocarbons C9H20 of the paraffin series; -- so called because of the nine carbon atoms in the molecule. Normal nonane is a colorless volatile liquid  an ingredient of ordinary kerosene."
"The one or single occasion; the present call or purpose; -- chiefly used in the phrase for the nonce."
"The edible plumlike fruit of the Australian tree  Parinarium Nonda."
"A coarse umbelliferous plant (Ligusticum actaeifolium) with a large aromatic root. It is found chiefly in the Alleghany region. Also called Angelico."
"No one; not one; not anything; -- frequently used also partitively  or as a plural not any."
"The fifth day of the months January  February April June August September November and December and the seventh day of March May July and October. The nones were nine days before the ides
"A composition for nine instruments  rarely for nine voices."
"Pertaining to  derived from or resembling nonane; as nonoic acid which is also called pelargonic acid. Cf. Pelargonic."
"Any one of several metameric unsaturated hydrocarbons (C9H14) of the valylene series."
"A state or condition which daffles reason or confounds judgment; insuperable difficalty; inability to proceed or decide; puzzle; quandary."
"Unsound; not perfect; as  a person of nonsane memory."

"A neglect or failure by the plaintiff to follow up his suit; a stopping of the suit; a renunciation or withdrawal of the cause by the plaintiff  either because he is satisfied that he can not support it or upon the judge's expressing his opinion. A compulsory nonsuit is a nonsuit ordered by the court on the ground that the plaintiff on his own showing has not made out his case."
"A vacation between two terms of a court."
"The hydrocarbon radical  C9H19 derived from nonane and forming many compounds. Used also adjectively; as nonyl alcohol."
"Of  pertaining to or designating nonyl or its compounds; as nonylic acid."
"A simpleton; a blockhead; a stupid person; a ninny."
"A narrow place formed by an angle in bodies or between bodies; a corner; a recess; a secluded retreat."
"Midday; twelve o'clock in the day; noon."
"A rest at noon; a repast at noon."
"A running knot  or loop which binds the closer the more it is drawn."
"A cactaceous plant (Nopalea cochinellifera)  originally Mexican on which the cochineal insect feeds and from which it is collected. The name is sometimes given to other species of Cactaceae."
"A plantation of the nopal for raising the cochineal insect."

"A negative connective or particle  introducing the second member or clause of a negative proposition following neither or not in the first member or clause (as or in affirmative propositions follows either). Nor is also used sometimes in the first member for neither and sometimes the neither is omitted and implied by the use of nor."

"A large water wheel  turned by the action of a stream against its floats and carrying at its circumference buckets by which water is raised and discharged into a trough; used in Arabia China and elsewhere for irrigating land; a Persian wheel."
"Pertaining to the upper portion of the Laurentian rocks."
"A Japanese covered litter  carried by men."
"A granular crystalline rock consisting essentially of a triclinic feldspar (as labradorite) and hypersthene."
"A supposed metal alleged to have been discovered in zircon."
"A rule or authoritative standard; a model; a type."
"A norm; a principle or rule; a model; a standard."
"According to an established norm  rule or principle; conformed to a type standard or regular form; performing the proper functions; not abnormal; regular; natural; analogical."
"One of the three Fates  Past Present and Future. Their names were Urd Verdandi and Skuld."
"The most northern of the English Kings-at-arms. See King-at-arms  under King."
"Of or pertaining to ancient Scandinavia  or to the language spoken by its inhabitants."

"That one of the four cardinal points of the compass  at any place which lies in the direction of the true meridian and to the left hand of a person facing the east; the direction opposite to the south."
"A wind from the north; esp.  a strong and cold north wind in Texas and the vicinity of the Gulf of Mexico."
"The prominent part of the face or anterior extremity of the head containing the nostrils and olfactory cavities; the olfactory organ. See Nostril  and Olfactory organ under Olfactory."
"A bag in which feed for a horse  ox or the like may be fastened under the nose by a string passing over the head."
"A bunch of odorous and showy flowers; a bouquet; a posy."
"To nurse; to lead or teach; to foster; to nuzzle."
"A genus of algae. The plants are composed of moniliform cells imbedded in a gelatinous substance."
"One of the external openings of the nose  which give passage to the air breathed and to secretions from the nose and eyes; one of the anterior nares."
"A medicine  the ingredients of which are kept secret for the purpose of restricting the profits of sale to the inventor or proprietor; a quack medicine."
"Capable of being noted; noticeable; plan; evident."
"The back or upper surface  as of a bird."
"Of or pertaining to the back; dorsal."
"One who records in shorthand what is said or done; as  the notary of an ecclesiastical body."
"Marked with spots or lines  which are often colored."
"A hollow cut in anything; a nick; an indentation."
"To butt; to push with the horns."
"A little or short note; a billet."
"Not anything; no thing (in the widest sense of the word thing); -- opposed to anything and something."
"The act of noting  remarking or observing; observation by the senses or intellect; cognizance; note."
"To make known; to declare; to publish; as  to notify a fact to a person."
"Mental apprehension of whatever may be known or imagined; an idea; a conception; more properly  a general or universal conception as distinguishable or definable by marks or notae."
"A cake  sweetmeat or confection made with almonds or other nuts."
"The top of the head; the head or noll."
"A word used as the designation or appellation of a creature or thing  existing in fact or in thought; a substantive."
"To change (an adjective  verb etc.) into a noun."
"To feed and cause to grow; to supply with matter which increases bulk or supplies waste  and promotes health; to furnish with nutriment."
"To nurse; to rear; to bring up."
"Of recent origin or introduction; not ancient; new; hence  out of the ordinary course; unusual; strange; surprising."
"The quality or state of being novel; newness; freshness; recentness of origin or introduction."
"Relating to  or dependent on the number nine; novenary."
"One who is new in any business  profession or calling; one unacquainted or unskilled; one yet in the rudiments; a beginner; a tyro."
"A game at dice  properly called novem quinque (L. nine five) the two principal throws being nine and five."
"At the present time; at this moment; at the time of speaking; instantly; as  I will write now."
"In no manner or degree; not at all; nowise."
"Knotted; tied in a knot  as a serpent."
"Christmas; also  a shout of joy at Christmas for the birth of the Savior."
"Not anywhere; not in any place or state; as  the book is nowhere to be found."
"Not in any manner or degree; in no way; noways."
"Hurtful; harmful; baneful; pernicious; injurious; destructive; unwholesome; insalubrious; as  noxious air food or climate; pernicious; corrupting to morals; as noxious practices or examples."
"A cordial of brandy  etc. flavored with the kernel of the bitter almond or of the peach stone etc."
"The nose; the snout; hence  the projecting vent of anything; as the nozzle of a bellows."
"A shade of difference; a delicate gradation."
"To push; to nudge; also  to beckon."
"A small or imperfect ear of maize."
"To beat or bruise with the fist."
"A light fabric of wool  worn on the head by women; a cloud."
"Of or pertaining to Nubia in Eastern Africa."
"Of an age suitable for marriage; marriageable."
"The back or upper part of the neck; the nape."
"Of  pertaining to or in the region of the back or nape of the neck; -- applied especially to the anterior median plate in the carapace of turtles."
"Of or pertaining to a nucleus; as  the nuclear spindle (see Illust. of Karyokinesis) or the nuclear fibrils of a cell; the nuclear part of a comet etc."

"A constituent of the nuclei of all cells. It is a colorless amorphous substance  readily soluble in alkaline fluids and especially characterized by its comparatively large content of phosphorus. It also contains nitrogen and sulphur."
"A kernel; hence  a central mass or point about which matter is gathered or to which accretion is made; the central or material portion; -- used both literally and figuratively."
"A genus of small marine bivalve shells  having a pearly interior."
"To walk quickly with the head bent forward; -- often with along."
"Bare; naked; unclothed; undraped; as  a nude statue."
"To touch gently  as with the elbow in order to call attention or convey intimation."
"The quality or state of being nude; nakedness."
"A lump; a mass  esp. a native lump of a precious metal; as a nugget of gold."
"To render trifling or futile; to make silly."
"No; not any; as  nul disseizin; nul tort."
"Of no legal or binding force or validity; of no efficacy; invalid; void; nugatory; useless."
"To make void; to render invalid; to deprive of legal force or efficacy."
"The quality or state of being null; nothingness; want of efficacy or force."
"Enfeebled in  or destitute of the power of sensation and motion; rendered torpid; benumbed; insensible; as the fingers or limbs are numb with cold."

"That which admits of being counted or reckoned; a unit  or an aggregate of units; a numerable aggregate or collection of individuals; an assemblage made up of distinct things expressible by figures."
"pl. of Number. The fourth book of the Pentateuch  containing the census of the Hebrews."
"Of or pertaining to number; consisting of number or numerals."
"Of or relating to coins or money."
"A woman devoted to a religious life  who lives in a convent under the three vows of poverty chastity and obedience."
"A house in which nuns reside; a cloister or convent in which women reside for life  under religious vows. See Cloister and Convent."
"Of  pertaining to or resembling a nun; characteristic of a nun."
"A genus of plants found in the fresh-water ponds or lakes of Europe  Asia and North America; the yellow water lily. Cf. Nymphaea."
"Of or pertaining to marriage; done or used at a wedding; as  nuptial rites and ceremonies."
"A hard knot in wood; also  a hard knob of wood used by boys in playing hockey."
"To cut with reeding or fluting on the edge of  as coins the heads of screws etc.; to knurl."

"One who nourishes; a person who supplies food  tends or brings up; as: (a) A woman who has the care of young children; especially one who suckles an infant not her own. (b) A person especially a woman who has the care of the sick or infirm."
"One who nurses; a nurse; one who cherishes or encourages growth."
"The act of nourishing or nursing; thender care; education; training."
"The fruit of certain trees and shrubs (as of the almond  walnut hickory beech filbert etc.) consisting of a hard and indehiscent shell inclosing a kernel."
"A more or less round gall resembling a nut  esp. one of those produced on the oak and used in the arts. See Gall Gallnut."
"A hook at the end of a pole to pull down boughs for gathering the nuts."
"A small nut; also  the stone of a drupe."
"The kernel of the fruit of the nutmeg tree (Myristica fragrans)  a native of the Molucca Islands but cultivated elsewhere in the tropics."
"The fur of the coypu. See Coypu."
"To noursle or nurse; to foster; to bring up."
"A carnivorous mannual (Helictis moscatus  or H. orientalis) native of Eastern Asia and the Indies. It has a dorsal white stripe and another one across the shoulders. It has a strong musky odor."
"A large Asiatic antelope (Boselaphus  / Portax tragocamelus) found in Northern India. It has short horns a black mane and a bunch of long hair on the throat. The general color is grayish brown."
"A goddess of the mountains  forests meadows or waters."
"Of or pertaining to a nymph or nymphs; nymphean."
"A species of ichneumon (Herpestes nyula). Its fur is beautifully variegated by closely set zigzag markings."
"Originally  an elf's child; a changeling left by fairies or goblins; hence a deformed or foolish child; a simpleton; an idiot."

"Any tree or shrub of the genus Quercus. The oaks have alternate leaves  often variously lobed and staminate flowers in catkins. The fruit is a smooth nut called an acorn which is more or less inclosed in a scaly involucre called the cup or cupule. There are now recognized about three hundred species of which nearly fifty occur in the United States the rest in Europe Asia and the other parts of North America a very few barely reaching the northern parts of South America and Africa. Many of the oaks form forest trees of grand proportions and live many centuries. The wood is usually hard and tough and provided with conspicuous medullary rays forming the silver grain."
"Made or consisting of oaks or of the wood of oaks."
"The material obtained by untwisting and picking into loose fiber old hemp ropes; -- used for calking the seams of ships  stopping leaks etc."

"An implement for impelling a boat  being a slender piece of timber usually ash or spruce with a grip or handle at one end and a broad blade at the other. The part which rests in the rowlock is called the loom."
"The notch  fork or other device on the gunwale of a boat in which the oar rests in rowing. See Rowlock."
"One who uses  or is skilled in the use of an oar; a rower."
"Having the form or the use of an oar; as  the swan's oary feet."
"A fertile or green spot in a waste or desert  esp. in a sandy desert."
"A kiln to dry hops or malt; a cockle."
"A well-known cereal grass (Avena sativa)  and its edible grain; -- commonly used in the plural and in a collective sense."
"Consisting of an oat straw or stem; as  an oaten pipe."
"A solemn affirmation or declaration  made with a reverent appeal to God for the truth of what is affirmed."
"The region of the skull between the two parietal foramina where the closure of the sagittal suture usually begins."

"An upright  four-sided pillar gradually tapering as it rises and terminating in a pyramid called pyramidion. It is ordinarily monolithic. Egyptian obelisks are commonly covered with hieroglyphic writing from top to bottom."
"To designate with an obelus; to mark as doubtful or spirituous."
"A mark [thus /  or � ]; -- so called as resembling a needle. In old MSS. or editions of the classics it marks suspected passages or readings."
"The king of the fairies  and husband of Titania or Queen Mab."
"The state or quality of being obese; incumbrance of flesh."
"To give ear to; to execute the commands of; to yield submission to; to comply with the orders of."
"A species of sorcery  probably of African origin practiced among the negroes of the West Indies."
"Death; decease; the date of one's death."
"Of or pertaining to obits  or days when obits are celebrated; as obitual days."
"To set before or against; to bring into opposition; to oppose."
"Flattened or depressed at the poles; as  the earth is an oblate spheroid."
"Children dedicated in their early years to the monastic state."
"An oblate spheroid; a figure described by the revolution of an ellipse about its minor axis. Cf. Oblongum."
"The person to whom another is bound  or the person to whom a bond is given."
"The person who binds himself  or gives his bond to another."
"Not erect or perpendicular; neither parallel to  nor at right angles from the base; slanting; inclined."
"Having greater length than breadth  esp. when rectangular."
"Censorious speech; defamatory language; language that casts contempt on men or their actions; blame; reprehension."

"One of the higher wind instruments in the modern orchestra  yet of great antiquity having a penetrating pastoral quality of tone somewhat like the clarinet in form but more slender and sounded by means of a double reed; a hautboy."
"A weight of twelve grains; or  according to some of ten grains or half a scruple."
"A copper coin  used in the Ionian Islands about one cent in value."
"A small silver coin of Athens  the sixth part of a drachma about three cents in value."
"Inversely ovate; ovate with the narrow end downward; as  an obovate leaf."
"Offensive to chastity or modesty; expressing of presenting to the mind or view something which delicacy  purity and decency forbid to be exposed; impure; as obscene language; obscene pictures."
"Covered over  shaded or darkened; destitute of light; imperfectly illuminated; dusky; dim."
"The last duty or service to a person  rendered after his death; hence a rite or ceremony pertaining to burial; -- now used only in the plural."
"To take notice of by appropriate conduct; to conform one's action or practice to; to keep; to heed; to obey; to comply with; as  to observe rules or commands; to observe civility."
"To seal; to confirm  as by a seal or stamp."
"To oppose; to hold out in opposition."
"To call to witness; to invoke as a witness."
"To thrust impertinently; to present without warrant or solicitation; as  to obtrude one's self upon a company."
"To reduce the edge  pungency or violent action of; to dull; to blunt; to deaden; to quell; as to obtund the acrimony of the gall."
"Not pointed or acute; blunt; -- applied esp. to angles greater than a right angle  or containing more than ninety degrees."
"Having the base  or end next the attachment narrower than the top as a leaf."
"A Peruvian name for certain species of Oxalis (O. crenata  and O. tuberosa) which bear edible tubers."
"The back  or posterior part of the head or skull; the region of the occipital bone."
"Hidden from the eye or the understanding; inviable; secret; concealed; unknown."
"To take or hold possession of; to hold or keep for use; to possess."
"The whole body of salt water which covers more than three fifths of the surface of the globe; -- called also the sea  or great sea."
"Of or pertaining to the ocean; found or formed in or about  or produced by the ocean; frequenting the ocean especially mid-ocean."
"The god of the great outer sea  or the river which was believed to flow around the whole earth."
"A little eye; a minute simple eye found in many invertebrates."

"An American feline carnivore (Felis pardalis). It ranges from the Southwestern United States to Patagonia. It is covered with blackish ocellated spots and blotches  which are variously arranged. The ground color varies from reddish gray to tawny yellow."
"A impure earthy ore of iron or a ferruginous clay  usually red (hematite) or yellow (limonite) -- used as a pigment in making paints etc. The name is also applied to clays of other colors."
"An atom or radical which has a valence of eight  or is octavalent."
"A plane figure of eight sides and eight angles."

"Any one of a group of metametric hydrocarcons (C8H18) of the methane series. The most important is a colorless  volatile inflammable liquid found in petroleum and a constituent of benzene or ligroin."
"The eighth part of a circle; an arc of 45 degrees."
"A portion of the Old Testament prepared by Origen in the 3d century  containing the Hebrew text and seven Greek versions of it arranged in eight parallel columns."
"The eighth day after a church festival  the festival day being included; also the week following a church festival."
"A book composed of sheets each of which is folded into eight leaves; hence  indicating more or less definitely a size of book so made; -- usually written 8vo or 8�."
"A composition for eight parts  usually for eight solo instruments or voices."
"A salt of an octoic acid; a caprylate."
"The tenth month of the year  containing thirty-one days."
"Cleft or separated into eight segments  as a calyx."
"Pertaining to  derived from or resembling octane; -- used specifically to designate any one of a group of acids the most important of which is called caprylic acid."
"A hypothetical radical (C8H15O)  regarded as the essential residue of octoic acid."
"A privilege granted by the sovereign authority  as the exclusive right of trade granted to a guild or society; a concession."
"A hypothetical hydrocarbon radical regarded as an essential residue of octane  and as entering into its derivatives; as octyl alcohol."
"Pertaining to  derived from or containing octyl; as octylic ether."
"Depending on  or perceived by the eye; received by actual sight; personally seeing or having seen; as ocular proof."
"Of or pertaining to the eye; ocular; optic; as  oculary medicines."
"A genus of tropical corals  usually branched and having a very volid texture."
"One skilled in treating diseases of the eye."
"Not paired with another  or remaining over after a pairing; without a mate; unmatched; single; as an odd shoe; an odd glove."
"The quality or state of being odd; singularity; queerness; peculiarity; as  oddity of dress manners and the like."
"The state of being odd  or not even."
"Difference in favor of one and against another; excess of one of two things or numbers over the other; inequality; advantage; superiority; hence  excess of chances; probability."
"A short poetical composition proper to be set to music or sung; a lyric poem; esp.  now a poem characterized by sustained noble sentiment and appropriate dignity of style."

"A kind of theater in ancient Greece  smaller than the dramatic theater and roofed over in which poets and musicians submitted their works to the approval of the public and contended for prizes; -- hence in modern usage the name of a hall for musical or dramatic performances."
"Of or pertaining to od. See Od."
"The supreme deity of the Scandinavians; -- the same as Woden  of the German tribes."
"Hateful; deserving or receiving hatred; as  an odious name system vice."
"A writer of an ode or odes."
"Hatred; dislike; as  his conduct brought him into odium or brought odium upon him."
"A volatile liquid obtained by boiling sulphur with linseed oil. It has an unpleasant garlic odor."
"The division of insects that includes the dragon flies."
"Any smell  whether fragrant or offensive; scent; perfume."
"Having or emitting an odor or scent  esp. a sweet odor; fragrant; sweet-smelling."
"A corruption of God's; -- formerly used in oaths and ejaculatory phrases."
"Of or pertaining to odyle; odic; as  odylic force."
"An epic poem attributed to Homer  which describes the return of Ulysses to Ithaca after the siege of Troy."
"The colorless porous framework  or stroma of red blood corpuscles from which the zooid or hemoglobin and other substances of the corpuscles may be dissolved out."
"A swelling from effusion of watery fluid in the cellular tissue beneath the skin or mucous membrance; dropsy of the subcutaneous cellular tissue."
"An eye  bud or shoot as of a plant; an oilet."
"A genus of gadflies. The species which deposits its larvae in the nasal cavities of sheep is oestrus ovis."
"In a general sense  denoting from or away from; as:"
"The rejected or waste parts of a butchered animal."
"To strike against; to attack; to assail."
"To transgress the moral or divine law; to commit a crime; to stumble; to sin."
"To present  as an act of worship; to immolate; to sacrifice; to present in prayer or devotion; -- often with up."
"One who offers; esp.  one who offers something to God in worship."
"Instant; ready; extemporaneous; as  an offhand speech; offhand excuses."
"That which a person does  either voluntarily or by appointment for or with reference to others; customary duty or a duty that arises from the relations of man to man; as kind offices pious offices."
"One who holds an office; a person lawfully invested with an office  whether civil military or ecclesiastical; as a church officer; a police officer; a staff officer."

"That part of the sea at a good distance from the shore  or where there is deep water and no need of a pilot; also distance from the shore; as the ship had ten miles offing; we saw a ship in the offing."
"In general  that which is set off from before or against something"
"That part of a landscape which recedes from the spectator into distance."
"A thing made up of eight parts."
"A molding  the section of which is the form of the letter S with the convex part above; cyma reversa. See Illust. under Cyma."
"A particular kind of writing practiced by the ancient Irish  and found in inscriptions on stones metals etc."
"The arch or rib which crosses a Gothic vault diagonally."
"To view or look at with side glances  as in fondness or with a design to attract notice."
"An imaginary monster  or hideous giant of fairy tales who lived on human beings; hence any frightful giant; a cruel monster."
"Resembling an ogre; having the character or appearance of an ogre; suitable for an ogre."
"The character or manners of an ogre."
"Of or pertaining to Ogyges  a mythical king of ancient Attica or to a great deluge in Attica in his days; hence primeval; of obscure antiquity."

"The standard unit in the measure of electrical resistance  being the resistance of a circuit in which a potential difference of one volt produces a current of one ampere. As defined by the International Electrical Congress in 1893 and by United States Statute it is a resistance substantially equal to 109 units of resistance of the C.G.S. system of electro-magnetic units and is represented by the resistance offered to an unvarying electric current by a column of mercury at the temperature of melting ice 14.4521 grams in mass of a constant cross-sectional area and of the length of 106.3 centimeters. As thus defined it is called the international ohm."

"A genus of minute fungi which form a floccose mass of filaments on decaying fruit  etc. Many forms once referred to this genus are now believed to be temporary conditions of fungi of other genera among them the vine mildew (Oidium Tuckeri) which has caused much injury to grapes."

"Any one of a great variety of unctuous combustible substances  not miscible with water; as olive oil whale oil rock oil etc. They are of animal vegetable or mineral origin and of varied composition and they are variously used for food for solvents for anointing lubrication
"The business  the place of business or the goods of a maker of or dealer in oils."
"A small opening or loophole  sometimes circular used in mediaeval fortifications."
"One who deals in oils; formerly  one who dealt in oils and pickles."
"The buffalo nut. See Buffalo nut  under Buffalo."
"Seed from which oil is expressed  as the castor bean; also the plant yielding such seed. See Castor bean."
"Consisting of oil; containing oil; having the nature or qualities of oil; unctuous; oleaginous; as  oily matter or substance."
"A spring  surrounded by rushes or rank grass; an oasis."
"A Turkish and Egyptian weight  equal to about 2/ pounds."
"A massive and fibrous mineral of a whitish color  chiefly hydrous silicate of lime."
"An annual plant (Abelmoschus  / Hibiscus esculentus) whose green pods abounding in nutritious mucilage are much used for soups stews or pickles; gumbo."
"Palm leaves  prepared for being written upon with a style pointed with steel."
"The state or quality of being old; old age."
"A genus of trees including the olive."
"A salt of oleic acid. Some oleates  as the oleate of mercury are used in medicine by way of inunction."
"Olefiant gas  or ethylene; hence by extension any one of the series of unsaturated hydrocarbons of which ethylene is a type. See Ethylene."

"Pertaining to  derived from or contained in oil; as oleic acid an acid of the acrylic acid series found combined with glyceryl in the form of olein in certain animal and vegetable fats and oils such as sperm oil olive oil etc. At low temperatures the acid is crystalline but melts to an oily liquid above 14/ C."

"A fat  liquid at ordinary temperatures but solidifying at temperatures below 0� C. found abundantly in both the animal and vegetable kingdoms (see Palmitin). It dissolves solid fats especially at 30-40� C. Chemically olein is a glyceride of oleic acid; and as three molecules of the acid are united to one molecule of glyceryl to form the fat it is technically known as triolein. It is also called elain."
"An oily liquid  obtained by distillation of calcium oleate and probably consisting of the ketone of oleic acid."
"A colorless mobile liquid of a pleasant aromatic odor obtained by the distillation of olibanum  or frankincense and regarded as a terpene; -- called also conimene."
"Hematite or specular iron ore; -- prob. so called in allusion to its feeble magnetism  as compared with magnetite."
"A dish of stewed meat of different kinds."
"Of or pertaining to  or produced in a kitchen garden; used for kitchen purposes; as olitory seeds."
"A genus of polished marine gastropod shells  chiefly tropical and often beautifully colored."

"A tree (Olea Europaea) with small oblong or elliptical leaves  axillary clusters of flowers and oval one-seeded drupes. The tree has been cultivated for its fruit for thousands of years and its branches are the emblems of peace. The wood is yellowish brown and beautifully variegated."
"A white crystalline substance  obtained from an exudation from the olive and having a bitter-sweet taste and acid proporties."
"A complex bitter gum  found on the leaves of the olive tree; -- called also olivite."
"A common name of the yellowish green mineral chrysolite  esp. the variety found in eruptive rocks."
"A pot or jar having a wide mouth; a cinerary urn  especially one of baked clay."
"A colloquial or humorous name for any science or branch of knowledge."
"Originally  a leather flask or vessel for oils or liquids; afterward an earthenware vase or pitcher without a spout."
"Of or pertaining to Olympus  a mountain of Thessaly fabled as the seat of the gods or to Olympia a small plain in Elis."
"A tribe of Indians who inhabited the south side of the Missouri River. They are now partly civilized and occupy a reservation in Nebraska."
"The third division of the stomach of ruminants. See Manyplies  and Illust. under Ruminant."
"A game at cards  borrowed from the Spaniards and usually played by three persons."
"The last letter of the Greek alphabet. See Alpha."
"Having the form of the Greek capital letter Omega (/)."
"Eggs beaten up with a little flour  etc. and cooked in a frying pan; as a plain omelet."
"An occurrence supposed to portend  or show the character of some future event; any indication or action regarded as a foreshowing; a foreboding; a presage; an augury."
"Of or pertaining to an omentum or the omenta."
"A free fold of the peritoneum  or one serving to connect viscera support blood vessels etc.; an epiploon."
"A Hebrew measure  the tenth of an ephah. See Ephah."

"Of or pertaining to an omen or to omens; being or exhibiting an omen; significant; portentous; -- formerly used both in a favorable and unfavorable sense; now chiefly in the latter; foreboding or foreshowing evil; inauspicious; as  an ominous dread."
"To let go; to leave unmentioned; not to insert or name; to drop."
"A long four-wheeled carriage  having seats for many people; especially one with seats running lengthwise used in conveying passengers short distances."
"That which is all-pervading or all-comprehensive; hence  the Deity."
"The aggregate value of the different stocks in which a loan to government is now usually funded."
"A military engine acting like a sling  which threw stones from a bag or wooden bucket and was operated by machinery."
"A nocturnal South American monkey (Callithrix discolor)  noted for its agility; -- called also ventriloquist monkey."
"By limitation to the number one; for one time; not twice nor any number of times more than one."
"Being a single unit  or entire being or thing and no more; not multifold; single; individual."
"A tribe of Indians formerly inhabiting the region near Oneida Lake in the State of New York  and forming part of the Five Nations. Remnants of the tribe now live in New York Canada and Wisconsin."
"The state of being at one or reconciled."
"The state of being one; singleness in number; individuality; unity."
"A reflexive form of the indefinite pronoun one. Commonly writen as two words  one's self."
"The act of going forward; progress; (pl.) affairs; business; current events."

"A liliaceous plant of the genus Allium (A. cepa)  having a strong-flavored bulb and long hollow leaves; also its bulbous root much used as an article of food. The name is often extended to other species of the genus."
"One alone; single; as  the only man present; his only occupation."
"A rushing or setting upon; an attack; an assault; a storming; especially  the assault of an army."
"On the top of; upon; on. See On to  under On prep."
"Moving in a forward direction; tending toward a contemplated or desirable end; forward; as  an onward course progress etc."
"An ingredient of the Mosaic incense  probably the operculum of some kind of strombus."
"Chalcedony in parallel layers of different shades of color. It is used for making cameos  the figure being cut in one layer with the next as a ground."
"One of the special zooids  or cells of Bryozoa destined to receive and develop ova; an ovicell. See Bryozoa."
"A variety of limestone  consisting of small round grains resembling the roe of a fish. It sometimes constitutes extensive beds as in the European Jurassic. See the Chart of Geology."
"Of or pertaining to oolite; composed of  or resembling oolite."
"The science of eggs in relation to their coloring  size shape and number."
"A fragrant variety of black tea having somewhat the flavor of green tea."
"A long  broad boat used by the Eskimos."
"To bind with a thread or cord; to join; to unite."

"An alternately produced form of certain cryptogamous plants  as ferns mosses and the like which bears antheridia and archegonia and so has sexual fructification as contrasted with the sporophore which is nonsexual but produces spores in countless number. In ferns the oophore is a minute prothallus; in mosses it is the leafy plant."

"Any plant of a proposed class or grand division (collectively termed oophytes or Oophyta)  which have their sexual reproduction accomplished by motile antherozoids acting on oospheres either while included in their oogonia or after exclusion."
"A wild  bearded sheep inhabiting the Ladakh mountains. It is reddish brown with a dark beard from the chin to the chest."
"The ovum  after fusion with the spermatozoon in impregnation."
"An unfertilized  rounded mass of protoplasm produced in an oogonium."
"A special kind of spore resulting from the fertilization of an oosphere by antherozoids."
"An egg case  especially those of many kinds of mollusks and of some insects as the cockroach. Cf. Ooecium."
"The part of the oviduct of certain trematode worms in which the ova are completed and furnished with a shell."
"Soft mud or slime; earth so wet as to flow gently  or easily yield to pressure."
"Miry; containing soft mud; resembling ooze; as  the oozy bed of a river."
"The state of being opaque; the quality of a body which renders it impervious to the rays of light; want of transparency; opaqueness."

"A large oceanic fish (Lampris quttatus)  inhabiting the Atlantic Ocean. It is remarkable for its brilliant colors which are red green and blue with tints of purple and gold covered with round silvery spots. Called also king of the herrings."
"A mineral consisting  like quartz of silica but inferior to quartz in hardness and specific gravity."
"Of  pertaining to or like opal in appearance; having changeable colors like those of the opal."
"To convert into opal  or a substance like opal."
"Impervious to the rays of light; not transparent; as  an opaque substance."
"A bright-colored European actinian (Anemonia  / Anthea sulcata); -- so called because it does not retract its tentacles."

"Free of access; not shut up; not closed; affording unobstructed ingress or egress; not impeding or preventing passage; not locked up or covered over; -- applied to passageways; as  an open door window road etc.; also to inclosed structures or objects; as open houses boxes baskets bottles etc.; also to means of communication or approach by water or land; as
"In an open manner; publicly; not in private; without secrecy."

"A drama  either tragic or comic of which music forms an essential part; a drama wholly or mostly sung consisting of recitative arials choruses duets trios etc. with orchestral accompaniment preludes and interludes
"The symbol  quantity or thing upon which a mathematical operation is performed; -- called also faciend."
"To perform a work or labor; to exert power or strengh  physical or mechanical; to act."
"Any one of the bony plates which support the gill covers of fishes; an opercular bone."
"Wrought with labor; requiring labor; hence  tedious; wearisome."
"Of  pertaining to or designating a substance (called ophelic acid) extracted from a plant (Ophelia) of the Gentian family as a bitter yellowish sirup used in India as a febrifuge and tonic."
"The order of reptiles which includes the serpents."
"Of  pertaining to or designating an organic acid obtained by the oxidation of narcotine."
"Originally  a medicine of a thicker consistence than sirup prepared with opium."
"To have an opinion; to judge; to think; to suppose."

"That which is opined; a notion or conviction founded on probable evidence; belief stronger than impression  less strong than positive knowledge; settled judgment in regard to any point of knowledge or action."
"The inspissated juice of the Papaver somniferum  or white poppy."
"Any American marsupial of the genera Didelphys and Chironectes. The common species of the United States is Didelphys Virginiana."
"To place in front of  or over against; to set opposite; to exhibit."
"One who opposes; an opponent; an antagonist; an adversary."
"To impose excessive burdens upon; to overload; hence  to treat with unjust rigor or with cruelty."
"To fight against; to attack; to be in conflict with; to oppose; to resist."
"To choose; to wish for; to desire."
"Of or pertaining to vision or sight."
"That branch of physical science which treats of the nature and properties of light  the laws of its modification by opaque and transparent bodies and the phenomena of vision."
"One of those who stand in the second rank of honors  immediately after the wranglers in the University of Cambridge England. They are divided into senior and junior optimes."
"The power of choosing; the right of choice or election; an alternative."
"Having a large estate or property; wealthy; rich; affluent; as  an opulent city; an opulent citizen."
"A genus of cactaceous plants; the prickly pear  or Indian fig."
"A small  handsome trout (Salvelinus oquassa) found in some of the lakes in Maine; -- called also blueback trout."
"A money of account among the Anglo-Saxons  valued in the Domesday Book at twenty pence sterling."
"A genus (Atriplex) of herbs or low shrubs of the Goosefoot family  most of them with a mealy surface."
"The answer of a god  or some person reputed to be a god to an inquiry respecting some affair or future event as the success of an enterprise or battle."
"Uttered by the mouth  or in words; spoken not written; verbal; as oral traditions; oral testimony; oral law."

"The fruit of a tree of the genus Citrus (C. Aurantium). It is usually round  and consists of pulpy carpels commonly ten in number inclosed in a leathery rind which is easily separable and is reddish yellow when ripe."

"An elaborate discourse  delivered in public treating an important subject in a formal and dignified manner; especially a discourse having reference to some special occasion as a funeral an anniversary a celebration or the like; -- distinguished from an argument in court a popular harangue a sermon a lecture etc.; as
"A public speaker; one who delivers an oration; especially  one distinguished for his skill and power as a public speaker; one who is eloquent."
"A place of orisons  or prayer; especially a chapel or small room set apart for private devotions."
"A woman plaintiff  or complainant in equity pleading."
"The path described by a heavenly body in its periodical revolution around another body; as  the orbit of Jupiter of the earth of the moon."
"Orblike; having the course of an orb; revolving."
"A reddish brown amorphous dyestuff  / obtained from orcin and forming the essential coloring matter of cudbear and archil. It is closely related to litmus."
"Any plant of the order Orchidaceae. See Orchidaceous."

"A genus of endogenous plants growing in the North Temperate zone  and consisting of about eighty species. They are perennial herbs growing from a tuber (beside which is usually found the last year's tuber also) and are valued for their showy flowers. See Orchidaceous."

"A colorless crystalline substance  C6H3.CH3.(OH)2 which is obtained from certain lichens (Roccella Lecanora etc.) also from extract of aloes and artificially from certain derivatives of toluene. It changes readily into orcein."
"An edge or point; also  a beginning."
"To set in order; to arrange according to rule; to regulate; to set; to establish."
"An ancient form of test to determine guilt or innocence  by appealing to a supernatural decision -- once common in Europe and still practiced in the East and by savage tribes."
"Regular arrangement; any methodical or established succession or harmonious relation; method; system"
"One who puts in order  arranges methodizes or regulates."
"Conformed to order; in order; regular; as  an orderly course or plan."
"Indicating order or succession; as  the ordinal numbers first second third etc."
"Honor; grace; favor; mercy; clemency; happy augry."
"One of the nymphs of mountains and grottoes."
"A group of butterflies which includes the satyrs. See Satyr  2."
"Of or pertaining to the desires; hence  impelling to gratification; appetitive."
"A genus of extinct herbivorous mammals  abundant in the Tertiary formation of the Rocky Mountains. It is more or less related to the camel hog and deer."
"A bright-colored domesticated variety of the id. See Id."
"Restitution for cattle; a penalty for taking away cattle."
"An instrument or medium by which some important action is performed  or an important end accomplished; as legislatures courts armies taxgatherers etc. are organs of government."

"Of or pertaining to an organ or its functions  or to objects composed of organs; consisting of organs or containing them; as the organic structure of animals and plants; exhibiting characters peculiar to living organisms; as organic bodies organic life organic remains. Cf. Inorganic."

"An organ or instrument; hence  a method by which philosophical or scientific investigation may be conducted; -- a term adopted from the Aristotelian writers by Lord Bacon as the title (""""Novum Organon"""") of part of his treatise on philosophical method."
"Eager or immoderate excitement or action; the state of turgescence of any organ; erethism; esp.  the height of venereal excitement in sexual intercourse."
"A sirup in which  formerly a decoction of barley entered but which is now prepared with an emulsion of almonds -- used to flavor beverages or edibles."

"A sacrifice accompanied by certain ceremonies in honor of some pagan deity; especially  the ceremonies observed by the Greeks and Romans in the worship of Dionysus or Bacchus which were characterized by wild and dissolute revelry."
"Any one of a number of long  thick pieces of timber pointed and shod with iron and suspended each by a separate rope over a gateway to be let down in case of attack."
"A frantic revel; drunken revelry. See Orgies"
"A genus of bombycid moths whose caterpillars (esp. those of Orgyia leucostigma) are often very injurious to fruit trees and shade trees. The female is wingless. Called also vaporer moth."
"A mouth or aperture  as of a tube pipe etc.; an opening; as the orifice of an artery or vein; the orifice of a wound."
"The first existence or beginning of anything; the birth."
"A semicircular projection made at the shoulder of a bastion for the purpose of covering the retired flank  -- found in old fortresses."

"Any one of various species of Old World singing birds of the family Oriolidae. They are usually conspicuously colored with yellow and black. The European or golden oriole (Oriolus galbula  or O. oriolus) has a very musical flutelike note."
"A large and bright constellation on the equator  between the stars Aldebaran and Sirius. It contains a remarkable nebula visible to the naked eye."
"A bearing  in the form of a fillet round the shield within but at some distance from the border."
"A cloth made of worsted and cotton  -- used for wearing apparel."
"A wind instrument of music in use among the Spaniards."
"The lowest deck of a vessel  esp. of a ship of war consisting of a platform laid over the beams in the hold on which the cables are coiled."

"A variety of brass made to resemble gold by the use of less zinc and more copper in its composition than ordinary brass contains. Its golden color is often heightened by means of lacquer of some sort  or by use of acids. Called also mosaic gold."
"The good principle  or being of the ancient Persian religion. See Ahriman."
"An alloy  chiefly of copper and zinc or tin resembling gold in color and brilliancy."
"Characterized by fullness  clearness strength and smoothness; ringing and musical; -- said of the voice or manner of utterance."
"A child bereaved of both father and mother; sometimes  also a child who has but one parent living."
"Of or pertaining to Orpheus  the mythic poet and musician; as Orphean strains."
"The famous mythic Thracian poet  son of the Muse Calliope and husband of Eurydice. He is reputed to have had power to entrance beasts and inanimate objects by the music of his lyre."
"Pertaining to Orpheus; Orphean; as  Orphic hymns."
"A band of rich embroidery  wholly or in part of gold affixed to vestments especially those of ecclesiastics."
"A yellow pigment of various degrees of intensity  approaching also to red."

"A low plant with fleshy leaves (Sedum telephium)  having clusters of purple flowers. It is found on dry sandy places and on old walls in England and has become naturalized in America. Called also stonecrop and live-forever."
"An apparatus which illustrates  by the revolution of balls moved by wheelwork the relative size periodic motions positions orbits etc. of bodies in the solar system."
"A plant of the genus Iris (I. Florentina); a kind of flower-de-luce. Its rootstock has an odor resembling that of violets."
"Leaf metal of bronze; Dutch metal. See under Dutch."
"A morsel left at a meal; a fragment; refuse; -- commonly used in the plural."
"A brachiopod shell of the genus Orthis  and allied genera of the family Orthidae."
"An extinct genus of Brachiopoda  abundant in the Paleozoic rocks."
"A variety of allanite occurring in slender prismatic crystals."
"Of or relating to the time or act of rising; eastern; as  the ortive amplitude of a planet."
"A European singing bird (Emberiza hortulana)  about the size of the lark with black wings. It is esteemed delicious food when fattened. Called also bunting."
"One of several species of East Indian birds of the genera Ortygis and Hemipodius. They resemble quails  but lack the hind toe. See Turnix."
"A genus of African antelopes which includes the gemsbok  the leucoryx the bisa antelope (O. beisa) and the beatrix antelope (O. beatrix) of Arabia."
"A genus of grasses including the rice plant; rice."
"A tribe of southern Sioux Indians  now living in the Indian Territory."
"Of or pertaining to the Osci  a primitive people of Campania a province of ancient Italy."
"Singing birds; a group of the Passeres  having numerous syringeal muscles conferring musical ability."
"One of the excurrent apertures of sponges."

"A kind of willow (Salix viminalis) growing in wet places in Europe and Asia  and introduced into North America. It is considered the best of the willows for basket work. The name is sometimes given to any kind of willow."
"Covered or adorned with osiers; as  osiered banks."

"One of the principal divinities of Egypt  the brother and husband of Isis. He was figured as a mummy wearing the royal cap of Upper Egypt and was symbolized by the sacred bull called Apis. Cf. Serapis."
"A Turkish official; one of the dominant tribe of Turks; loosely  any Turk."
"Pertaining to  derived from or containing osmium; specifically designating those compounds in which it has a valence higher than in other lower compounds; as osmic oxide."
"Denoting those compounds of osmium in which the element has a valence relatively lower than in the osmic compounds; as  osmious chloride."

"A rare metallic element of the platinum group  found native as an alloy in platinum ore and in iridosmine. It is a hard infusible bluish or grayish white metal and the heaviest substance known. Its tetroxide is used in histological experiments to stain tissues. Symbol Os. Atomic weight 191.1. Specific gravity 22.477."

"The tendency in fluids to mix  or become equably diffused when in contact. It was first observed between fluids of differing densities and as taking place through a membrane or an intervening porous structure. The more rapid flow from the thinner to the thicker fluid was then called endosmose and the opposite slower current exosmose. Both are however results of the same force. Osmose may be regarded as a form of molecular attraction allied to that of adhesion."
"Pertaining to  or having the property of osmose; as osmotic force."

"A fern of the genus Osmunda  or flowering fern. The most remarkable species is the osmund royal or royal fern (Osmunda regalis) which grows in wet or boggy places and has large bipinnate fronds often with a panicle of capsules at the top. The rootstock contains much starch and has been used in stiffening linen."
"A fish having a bony skeleton; a teleost."

"The organic basis of bone tissue; the residue after removal of the mineral matters from bone by dilute acid; in embryonic tissue  the substance in which the mineral salts are deposited to form bone; -- called also ostein. Chemically it is the same as collagen."
"Composed of bone; resembling bone; capable of forming bone; bony; ossific."
"A little bone; as  the auditory ossicles in the tympanum of the ear."
"Capable of producing bone; having the power to change cartilage or other tissue into bone."
"To form into bone; to change from a soft animal substance into bone  as by the deposition of lime salts."
"A place where the bones of the dead are deposited; a charnel house."
"A tumor composed mainly of bone; a tumor of a bone."
"The mouth of a river; an estuary."
"Pertaining to  or applied to the language of the Tuscaroras Iroquois Wyandots Winnebagoes and a part of the Sioux Indians."
"The exterior opening of a stomate. See Stomate."
"East men; Danish settlers in Ireland  formerly so called."
"Bone formation; ossification. See Ectostosis  and Endostosis."
"A genus of bivalve Mollusca which includes the true oysters."

"A large bird of the genus Struthio  of which Struthio camelus of Africa is the best known species. It has long and very strong legs adapted for rapid running; only two toes; a long neck nearly bare of feathers; and short wings incapable of flight. The adult male is about eight feet high."
"Either; -- used with other or or for its correlative (as either . . . or are now used)."
"Of  pertaining to or in the region of the ear; auricular; auditory."
"Being at leisure or ease; unemployed; indolent; idle."
"A genus of birds including the bustards."

"An auditory cyst or vesicle; one of the simple auditory organs of many invertebrates  containing a fluid and otoliths; also the embryonic vesicle from which the parts of the internal ear of vertebrates are developed."

"One of the small bones or particles of calcareous or other hard substance in the internal ear of vertebrates  and in the auditory organs of many invertebrates; an ear stone. Collectively the otoliths are called ear sand and otoconite."
"The branch of science which treats of the ear and its diseases."
"An extinct genus of huge vertebrates  probably dinosaurs known only from four-toed tracks in Triassic sandstones."
"A tribe of Indians who  when first known lived on the Ottawa River. Most of them subsequently migrated to the southwestern shore of Lake Superior."

"Any carnivorous animal of the genus Lutra  and related genera. Several species are described. They have large flattish heads short ears and webbed toes. They are aquatic and feed on fish. Their fur is soft and valuable. The common otter of Europe is Lutra vulgaris; the American otter is L. Canadensis; other species inhabit South America and Asia."
"Of or pertaining to the Turks; as  the Ottoman power or empire."
"Any South American monkey of the genus Brachyurus  especially B. ouakari."
"A Brazilian monkey of the genus Mycetes."
"A socket or bezel holding a precious stone; hence  a jewel or ornament worn on the person."
"A weight  the sixteenth part of a pound avoirdupois and containing 437/ grains."
"A small  graceful and swift African antelope allied to the klipspringer."
"One of several species of European thrushes  especially the blackbird (Merula merula or Turdus merula) and the mountain or ring ousel (Turdus torquatus)."
"A putting out of possession; dispossession; ejection; disseizin."

"In its original and strict sense  out means from the interior of something; beyond the limits or boundary of somethings; in a position or relation which is exterior to something; -- opposed to in or into. The something may be expressed after of from etc. (see Out of below); or if not expressed it is implied; as he is out; or he is out of the house office business etc.; he came out; or
"To do or beyond; to exceed in acting."
"To surpass in bragging; hence  to make appear inferior."
"That which comes out of  or follows from something else; issue; result; consequence; upshot."
"The coming out of a stratum to the surface of the ground."
"A vehement or loud cry; a cry of distress  alarm opposition or detestation; clamor."
"To surpass in daring; to overcome by courage; to brave."
"To go beyond in performance; to excel; to surpass."
"Being  or done in the open air; being or done outside of certain buildings as poorhouses hospitals etc.; as outdoor exercise; outdoor relief; outdoor patients."

"Being on the outside; external; farthest or farther from the interior  from a given station or from any space or position regarded as a center or starting place; -- opposed to inner; as the outer wall; the outer court or gate; the outer stump in cricket; the outer world."
"To face or look (one) out of countenance; to resist or bear down by bold looks or effrontery; to brave."
"The mouth of a river; the lower end of a water course; the open end of a drain  culvert etc. where the discharge occurs."

"A fitting out  or equipment as of a ship for a voyage or of a person for an expedition in an unoccupied region or residence in a foreign land; things required for equipment; the expense of or allowance made for equipment as by the government of the United States to a diplomatic agent going abroad."
"To surpass in flying; to fly beyond or faster than."
"To gaze beyond; to exceed in sharpness or persistence of seeing or of looking; hence  to stare out of countenance."
"To go beyond; to exceed in swiftness; to surpass; to outdo."
"To surpass in growing; to grow more than."
"A rope used for hauling out a sail upon a spar; -- opposite of inhaul."
"The act of going out; an airing; an excursion; as  a summer outing."
"To surpass in jesting; to drive out  or away by jesting."
"That which jets out or projects from anything."
"To exceed in duration; to survive; to endure longer than."
"A person excluded from the benefit of the law  or deprived of its protection."
"To lay out; to spread out; to display."
"The place or opening by which anything is let out; a passage out; an exit; a vent."
"One who does not live where his office  or business or estate is."
"An extreme member or part of a thing; a limb."
"The line which marks the outer limits of an object or figure; the exterior line or edge; contour."
"To live beyond  or longer than; to survive."
"Farthest from the middle or interior; farthest outward; outermost."
"The state of being out or beyond; separateness."
"To outgo; to move faster than; to leave behind."
"To pass beyond; to exceed in progress."
"To excel or defeat in a game; to play better than; as  to be outplayed in tennis or ball."
"A harbor or port at some distance from the chief town or seat of trade."
"A post or station without the limits of a camp  or at a distance from the main body of an army for observation of the enemy."
"The amount of coal or ore put out from one or more mines  or the quantity of material produced by or turned out from one or more furnaces or mills in a given time."
"To exceed in rank; hence  to take precedence of."
"Being out of the common course or limits; extravagant; bizarre."
"To surpass in giving rede  or counsel."
"To surpass in speed of riding; to ride beyond or faster than."
"To excel in volume of ringing sound; to ring louder than."
"To rush out; to issue  or ru/ out forcibly."
"To excel  or to leave behind in sailing; to sail faster than."
"To see beyond; to excel in cer/ainty of seeing; to surpass in foresight."
"To exceed in amount of sales; to sell more than."
"The external part of a thing; the part  end or side which forms the surface; that which appears or is manifest; that which is superficial; the exterior."
