"Pertaining to  or derived from or designating a complex organic acid found in the products of different members of the Pepper family and extracted as a yellowish crystalline substance."
"A small glass tube  often with an enlargement or bulb in the middle and usually graduated -- used for transferring or delivering measured quantities."

"Any one of numerous species of small singing birds belonging to Anthus and allied genera  of the family Motacillidae. They strongly resemble the true larks in habits colors and the great length of the hind claw. They are therefore often called titlarks and pipit larks."
"An apple from a tree raised from the seed and not grafted; a seedling apple."

"Any one of numerous species of small clamatorial birds belonging to Pipra and allied genera  of the family Pipridae. The male is usually glossy black varied with scarlet yellow or sky blue. They chiefly inhabit South America."
"Of or pertaining to the pipras  or the family Pipridae."
"Stimulating to the taste; giving zest; tart; sharp; pungent; as  a piquant anecdote."
"A cotton fabric  figured in the loom -- used as a dress goods for women and children and for vestings etc."
"The act or crime of a pirate."

"A robber on the high seas; one who by open violence takes the property of another on the high seas; especially  one who makes it his business to cruise for robbery or plunder; a freebooter on the seas; also one who steals in a harbor."
"A large voracious fresh-water fish (Serrasalmo piraya) of South America  having lancet-shaped teeth."
"A quill or reed on which thread or yarn is wound; a bobbin; also  the wound yarn on a weaver's shuttle; also the reel of a fishing rod."
"A dugout canoe; by extension  any small boat."
"The right or privilege of fishing in another man's waters."
"The twelfth sign of the zodiac  marked / in almanacs."
"A niche near the altar in a church  containing a small basin for rinsing altar vessels."
"Of or pertaining to a fish or fishes; as  piscine remains."
"A species of wall made of stiff earth or clay rammed in between molds which are carried up as the wall rises; -- called also pise work."
"The track or tread a horseman makes upon the ground he goes over."
"The smallest firearm used  intended to be fired from one hand -- now of many patterns and bearing a great variety of names. See Illust. of Revolver."

"The name of certain gold coins of various values formerly coined in some countries of Europe. In Spain it was equivalent to a quarter doubloon  or about $3.90 and in Germany and Italy nearly the same. There was an old Italian pistole worth about $5.40."

"A sliding piece which either is moved by  or moves against fluid pressure. It usually consists of a short cylinder fitting within a cylindrical vessel along which it moves back and forth. It is used in steam engines to receive motion from the steam and in pumps to transmit motion to a fluid; also for other purposes."
"A large cavity or hole in the ground  either natural or artificial; a cavity in the surface of a body; an indentation"
"A fiber obtained from the Agave Americana and other related species  -- used for making cordage and paper. Called also pita fiber and pita thread."
"In a flutter; with palpitation or quick succession of beats."
"A thick  black lustrous and sticky substance obtained by boiling down tar. It is used in calking the seams of ships; also in coating rope canvas wood ironwork etc. to preserve them."
"One who pitches anything  as hay quoits a ball etc.; specifically (Baseball) the player who delivers the ball to the batsman."
"Partaking of the qualities of pitch; resembling pitch."
"A pit deceitfully covered to entrap wild beasts or men; a trap of any kind."
"The soft spongy substance in the center of the stems of many plants and trees  especially those of the dicotyledonous or exogenous classes. It consists of cellular tissue."
"A division of mammals including the apes and monkeys. Sometimes used in the sense of Primates."
"Consisting wholly  or in part of pith; abounding in pith; as a pithy stem; a pithy fruit."
"Full of pity; tender-hearted; compassionate; kind; merciful; sympathetic."
"One who works in a pit  as in mining in sawing timber etc."
"A long  flat-bottomed canoe used for the navigation of rivers and lagoons in Central America."

"Any one of a large group of bright-colored clamatorial birds belonging to Pitta  and allied genera of the family Pittidae. Most of the species are varied with three or more colors such as blue green crimson yellow purple and black. They are called also ground thrushes and Old World ant thrushes; but they are not related to the true thrushes."
"A contrivance for removing the pits from peaches  plums and other stone fruit."
"A little more; as  piu allegro a little more briskly."
"A fixed pin or short axis  on the end of which a wheel or other body turns."
"Of or pertaining to a pivot or turning point; belonging to  or constituting a pivot; of the nature of a pivot; as the pivotalopportunity of a career; the pivotal position in a battle."
"An old English name for a fairy; an elf."
"The penis; -- so called in some animals  as the bull."
"A public proclamation; a manifesto or edict issued by authority."
"Any portion of space regarded as measured off or distinct from all other space  or appropriated to some definite object or use; position; ground; site; spot; rarely unbounded space."
"The first antiphon of the vespers for the dead."
"A vote of assent  as of the governing body of a university of an ecclesiastical council etc."
"Pleased; contented; unruffied; undisturbed; serene; peaceful; tranquil; quiet; gentle."
"A small copper coin formerly current in Scotland  worth less than a cent."
"A petticoat  esp. an under petticoat; hence a cant term for a woman."
"Platelike; having irregular  platelike bony scales often bearing spines; pertaining to the placoids."
"Having a scale running from the dominant to its octave; -- said of certain old church modes or tunes  as opposed to those called authentic which ran from the tonic to its octave."
"Having plagae  or irregular enlongated color spots."
"Fond of flogging; as  a plagose master."
"That which smites  wounds or troubles; a blow; a calamity; any afflictive evil or torment; a great trail or vexation."
"Vexatious; troublesome; tormenting; as  a plaguy horse. [Colloq.] Also used adverbially; as """"He is so plaguy proud."
"A European food fish (Pleuronectes platessa)  allied to the flounder and growing to the weight of eight or ten pounds or more."
"A rectangular garment or piece of cloth  usually made of the checkered material called tartan but sometimes of plain gray or gray with black stripes. It is worn by both sexes in Scotland."
"Of the material of which plaids are made; tartan."
"Audible expression of sorrow; lamentation; complaint; hence  a mournful song; a lament."
"A flat fold; a doubling  as of cloth; a pleat; as a box plait."

"A draught or form; properly  a representation drawn on a plane as a map or a chart; especially a top view as of a machine or the representation or delineation of a horizontal section of anything as of a building; a graphic representation; a diagram."
"One who  or that which planes; a planing machine; esp. a machine for planing wood or metals."

"A celestial body which revolves about the sun in an orbit of a moderate degree of eccentricity. It is distinguished from a comet by the absence of a coma  and by having a less eccentric orbit. See Solar system."
"To make smooth or plane  as a metallic surface; to condense toughen and polish by light blows with a hammer."
"A broad piece of sawed timber  differing from a board only in being thicker. See Board."

"A vegetable; an organized living being  generally without feeling and voluntary motion and having when complete a root stem and leaves though consisting sometimes only of a single leafy expansion or a series of cellules or even a single cellule."
"Of or pertaining to the sole of the foot; as  the plantar arteries."
"One who  or that which plants or sows; as a planterof corn; a machine planter."

"In embryonic development  a vesicle filled with fluid formed from the morula by the divergence of its cells in such a manner as to give rise to a central space around which the cells arrange themselves as an envelope; an embryonic form intermediate between the morula and gastrula. Sometimes used as synonymous with gastrula."
"An Irish or Welsh melody for the harp  sometimes of a mournful character."
"Any flat  thin piece of metal clay ivory or the like used for ornament or for painting pictures upon as a slab plate dish or the like hung upon a wall; also
"A small pool of standing water; a puddle."
"A small pond or pool; a puddle."
"A mold or matrix in which anything is cast or formed to a particular shape."
"A variety of quartz  of a color between grass green and leek green which is found associated with common chalcedony. It was much esteemed by the ancients for making engraved ornaments."
"Of  pertaining to or connected with plasma; plasmatic."

"A piece of DNA  usually circular functioning as part of the genetic material of a cell not integrated with the chromosome and replicating independently of the chromosome but transferred like the chromosome to subsequent generations. In bacteria plasmids often carry the genes for antibiotic resistance; they are exploited in genetic engineering as the vehicles for introduction of extraneous DNA into cells to alter the genetic makeup of the cell. The cells thus altered may produce desirable proteins which are extracted and used; in the case of genetically altered plant cells the altered cells may grow into complete plants with changed properties as for example increased resistance to disease."
"A proteid body  separated by some physiologists from blood plasma. It is probably identical with fibrinogen."
"The albuminous material composing the body of a cytode."

"An external application of a consistency harder than ointment  prepared for use by spreading it on linen leather silk or other material. It is adhesive at the ordinary temperature of the body and is used according to its composition to produce a medicinal effect to bind parts together etc.; as a porous plaster; sticking plaster."
"Having the power to give form or fashion to a mass of matter; as  the plastic hand of the Creator."

"a substance composed predominantly of a synthetic organic high polymer capable of being cast or molded; many varieties of plastic are used to produce articles of commerce (after 1900). [MW10 gives origin of word as 1905]"
"A substance associated with nuclein in cell nuclei  and by some considered as the fundamental substance of the nucleus."
"To form by interlaying interweaving; to braid; to plait."
"A flat  or nearly flat piece of metal the thickness of which is small in comparison with the other dimensions; a thick sheet of metal; as a steel plate."
"A flat surface; especially  a broad level elevated area of land; a table-land."
"The part of a printing press which presses the paper against the type and by which the impression is made."
"One who plates or coats articles with gold or silver; as  a silver plater."
"Formerly  a body of men who fired together; also a small square body of soldiers to strengthen the angles of a hollow square."
"To flatten and make into sheets or plates; as  to platten cylinder glass."
"A mark or expression of applause; praise bestowed."
"To engage in sport or lively recreation; to exercise for the sake of amusement; to frolic; to spot."
"A beach; a strand; in the plains and deserts of Texas  New Mexico and Arizona a broad level spot on which subsequently becomes dry by evaporation."
"A day given to play or diversion; a holiday."
"One who plays  or amuses himself; one without serious aims; an idler; a trifler."
"Sportive; gamboling; frolicsome; indulging a sportive fancy; humorous; merry; as  a playful child; a playful writer."
"A public square in a city or town."

"That which is alleged by a party in support of his cause; in a stricter sense  an allegation of fact in a cause as distinguished from a demurrer; in a still more limited sense and in modern practice the defendant's answer to the plaintiff's declaration and demand. That which the plaintiff alleges in his declaration is answered and repelled or justified by the defendant's plea. In chancery practice a plea is a special answer showing or relying upon one or more things as a cause why the suit should be either dismissed delayed or barred. In criminal practice the plea is the defendant's formal answer to the indictment or information presented against him."
"To unite by interweaving  as branches of trees; to plash; to interlock."
"One who pleads; one who argues for or against; an advotate."
"To give pleasure to; to excite agreeable sensations or emotions in; to make glad; to gratify; to content; to satisfy."

"The transfer of possession of personal property from a debtor to a creditor as security for a debt or engagement; also  the contract created between the debtor and creditor by a thing being so delivered or deposited forming a species of bailment; also that which is so delivered or deposited; something put in pawn."
"The one to whom a pledge is given  or to whom property pledged is delivered."
"One who pledges  or delivers anything in pledge; a pledger; -- opposed to pledgee."
"Full; complete; as  a plenal view or act."
"Full; entire; complete; absolute; as  a plenary license; plenary authority."
"One who holds that all space is full of matter."
"Full or adequate supply; enough and to spare; sufficiency; specifically  abundant productiveness of the earth; ample supply for human wants; abundance; copiousness."
"That state in which every part of space is supposed to be full of matter; -- opposed to vacuum."
"One of the abdominal legs of a crustacean. See Illust. under Crustacea."
"The central column of parenchyma in a growing stem or root."
"Of or pertaining to the pleura or pleurae  or to the sides of the thorax."
"One of the sides of an animal."
"The act or process of weaving together  or interweaving; that which is woven together."
"An old term for a river boat."
"Capable of being plied  turned or bent; easy to be bent; flexible; pliant; supple; limber; yielding; as willow is a pliable plant."
"The quality or state of being pliant in sense; as  the pliancy of a rod."

"Capable of plying or bending; readily yielding to force or pressure without breaking; flexible; pliable; lithe; limber; plastic; as  a pliant thread; pliant wax. Also used figuratively: Easily influenced for good or evil; tractable; as a pliant heart."
"A disease of the hair (Plica polonica)  in which it becomes twisted and matted together. The disease is of Polish origin and is hence called also Polish plait."
"A kind of small pinchers with long jaws  -- used for bending or cutting metal rods or wire for handling small objects such as the parts of a watch etc."
"In the form of a ply  fold or doubling."
"imp. & p. p. of Plight  to pledge."
"To swell  as grain or wood with water."

"In classical architecture  a vertically faced member immediately below the circular base of a column; also the lowest member of a pedestal; hence in general the lowest member of a base; a sub-base; a block upon which the moldings of an architrave or trim are stopped at the bottom. See Illust. of Column."
"An instrument of punishment or torture resembling the knout  used in Russia."
"A mixture of hair and tar for covering the bottom of a ship."

"A figure in which a word is separated or repeated by way of emphasis  so as not only to signify the individual thing denoted by it but also its peculiar attribute or quality; as """"His wife's a wife indeed."
"To travel slowly but steadily; to trudge."
"To cleanse  as open drains which are entered by the tide by stirring up the sediment when the tide ebbs."
"A slope or sloping toward the front; as  the plongee of a parapet; the plongee of a shell in its course."
"A small extent of ground; a plat; as  a garden plot."
"One who plots or schemes; a contriver; a conspirator; a schemer."
"Any one of numerous species of limicoline birds belonging to the family Charadridae  and especially those belonging to the subfamily Charadrinsae. They are prized as game birds."
"Having pluck or courage; characterized by pluck; displaying pluck; courageous; spirited; as  a plucky race."
"To throw out  as smoke dust etc. in puffs."
"Any piece of wood  metal or other substance used to stop or fill a hole; a stopple."
"The edible drupaceous fruit of the Prunus domestica  and of several other species of Prunus; also the tree itself usually called plum tree."
"A little mass or weight of lead  or the like attached to a line and used by builders etc. to indicate a vertical direction; a plummet; a plumb bob. See Plumb line below."
"One who works in lead; esp.  one who furnishes fits and repairs lead iron or glass pipes and other apparatus for the conveyance of water gas or drainage in buildings."
"Of  pertaining to resembling or containing lead; -- used specifically to designate those compounds in which it has a higher valence as contrasted with plumbous compounds; as plumbic oxide."
"The technical name of lead. See Lead."
"A feather; esp.  a soft downy feather or a long conspicuous or handsome feather."
"A piece of lead attached to a line  used in sounding the depth of water."
"Of the nature of a plum; desirable; profitable; advantageous."
"Well rounded or filled out; full; fleshy; fat; as  a plump baby; plump cheeks."
"One who  or that which plumps or swells out something else; hence something carried in the mouth to distend the cheeks."
"Covered or adorned with plumes  or as with plumes; feathery."
"To take the goods of by force  or without right; to pillage; to spoil; to sack; to strip; to rob; as to plunder travelers."

"To thrust into water  or into any substance that is penetrable; to immerse; to cause to penetrate or enter quickly and forcibly; to thrust; as to plunge the body into water; to plunge a dagger into the breast. Also used figuratively; as to plunge a nation into war."
"One who  or that which plunges; a diver."
"A kind of blue color; also  anciently a kind of cloth generally blue."
"Relating to  or containing more than one; designating two or more; as a plural word."
"A writ issued in the third place  after two former writs have been disregarded."
"More  required to be added; positive as distinguished from negative; -- opposed to minus."
"A textile fabric with a nap or shag on one side  longer and softer than the nap of velvet."
"The free-swimming larva of sea urchins and ophiurans  having several long stiff processes inclosing calcareous rods."
"The son of Saturn and Rhea  brother of Jupiter and Neptune; the dark and gloomy god of the Lower World."
"The son of Jason and Ceres  and the god of wealth. He was represented as bearing a cornucopia and as blind because his gifts were bestowed without discrimination of merit."
"The place at Athens where the meetings of the people were held for making decrees  etc."
"A genus of grasses  including a great number of species as the kinds called meadow grass Kentucky blue grass June grass and spear grass (which see)."
"To cook  as eggs by breaking them into boiling water; also to cook with butter after breaking in a vessel."
"One who poaches; one who kills or catches game or fish contrary to law."
"Wet and soft; easily penetrated by the feet of cattle; -- said of land"
"Waste matter from the preparation of skins  consisting of hair lime oil etc."
"The poke (Phytolacca decandra); -- called also pocan bush."
"A pustule raised on the surface of the body in variolous and vaccine diseases."
"A bag or pouch; especially; a small bag inserted in a garment for carrying small articles  particularly money; hence figuratively money; wealth."
"Full of pocks; affected with smallpox or other eruptive disease."
"A little; -- used chiefly in phrases indicating the time or movement; as  poco piu allegro a little faster; poco largo rather slow."
"Low  wooded grounds or swamps in Eastern Maryland and Virginia."
"Gout in the joints of the foot; -- applied also to gout in other parts of body."
"One of the chief magistrates of the Italian republics in the Middle Ages."
"Anal; -- applied to certain organs of insects."
"A low wall  serving as a foundation a substructure or a terrace wall."
"A miscellaneous dish of meats. See Olla-podrida."
"Any small leaping thysanurous insect of the genus Podura and related genera; a springtail."
"Any species of Podura or allied genera."

"A metrical composition; a composition in verse written in certain measures  whether in blank verse or in rhyme and characterized by imagination and poetic diction; -- contradistinguished from prose; as the poems of Homer or of Milton."
"A variety of jade or nephrite  -- used in New Zealand for the manufacture of axes and weapons."
"The art of composing poems; poetical skill or faculty; as  the heavenly gift of poesy."
"One skilled in making poetry; one who has a particular genius for metrical composition; the author of a poem; an imaginative thinker or writer."
"The principles and rules of the art of poetry."
"To write as a poet; to compose verse; to idealize."
"The art of apprehending and interpreting ideas by the faculty of imagination; the art of idealizing in thought and in expression."
"An exclamation expressing contempt or disgust; bah !"
"A national food of the Hawaiians  made by baking and pounding the kalo (or taro) root and reducing it to a thin paste which is allowed to ferment."
"The keeper of a cattle pound; a pinder."
"Weight; gravity; that which causes a body to descend; heaviness."
"Any agent which  when introduced into the animal organism is capable of producing a morbid noxious or deadly effect upon it; as morphine is a deadly poison; the poison of pestilential diseases."
"The breastplate of the armor of a horse. See Peytrel."

"A large North American herb of the genus Phytolacca (P. decandra)  bearing dark purple juicy berries; -- called also garget pigeon berry pocan and pokeweed. The root and berries have emetic and purgative properties and are used in medicine. The young shoots are sometimes eaten as a substitute for asparagus and the berries are said to be used in Europe to color wine."
"The European long-tailed titmouse; -- called also poke-pudding."
"A vessel with two or three masts  used in the Mediterranean. The masts are usually of one piece and without tops caps or crosstrees."
"Of or pertaining to one of the poles of the earth  or of a sphere; situated near or proceeding from one of the poles; as polar regions; polar seas; polar winds."
"The polestar. See North star  under North."
"Tending to a pole; having a direction toward a pole."
"A tract of low land reclaimed from the sea by of high embankments."
"A kind of coarse bagging  -- used for coal sacks."
"A native or inhabitant of Poland; a Polander."
"Anciently  a kind of battle-ax with a long handle; later an ax or hatchet with a short handle and a head variously patterned; -- used by soldiers and also by sailors in boarding a vessel."
"A small European carnivore of the Weasel family (Putorius foetidus). Its scent glands secrete a substance of an exceedingly disagreeable odor. Called also fitchet  foulmart and European ferret."
"Of or pertaining to controversy; maintaining  or involving controversy; controversial; disputative; as a polemic discourse or essay; polemic theology."
"Pudding made of Indian meal; also  porridge made of chestnut meal."
"The European spotted goby (Gobius minutus); -- called also pollybait."

"A judicial and executive system  for the government of a city town or district for the preservation of rights order cleanliness health etc. and for the enforcement of the laws and prevention of crime; the administration of the laws and regulations of a city incorporated town or borough."
"Of or pertaining to Poland or its inhabitants."
"Of or pertaining to polity  or civil government; political; as the body politic. See under Body."
"The form or constitution of the civil government of a nation or state; the framework or organization by which the various departments of government are combined into a systematic whole."
"A dance of Polish origin  but now common everywhere. It is performed by two persons in common time."
"A marine gadoid food fish of Europe (Pollachius virens). Called also greenfish  greenling lait leet lob lythe and whiting pollack."
"A head or poll tax; hence  extortion."
"A lake whitefish (Coregonus pollan)  native of Ireland. In appearance it resembles a herring."
"A tree having its top cut off at some height above the ground  that may throw out branches."

"One who polls; specifically: (a) One who polls or lops trees. (b) One who polls or cuts hair; a barber. [R.] (c) One who extorts or plunders. [Obs.] Baex. (d) One who registplws votplws  or one who enters his name as a voter."
"The first  or preaxial digit of the fore limb corresponding to the hallux in the hind limb; the thumb. In birds the pollex is the joint which bears the bastard wing."

"A marine gadoid fish (Pollachius carbonarius)  native both of the European and American coasts. It is allied to the cod and like it is salted and dried. In England it is called coalfish lob podley podling pollack etc."
"To make foul  impure or unclean; to defile; to taint; to soil; to desecrate; -- used of physical or moral defilement."
"A fixed star of the second magnitude  in the constellation Gemini. Cf. 3d Castor."
"A woman's name; also  a popular name for a parrot."
"A game of ball of Eastern origin  resembling hockey with the players on horseback."
"A kind of sausage made of meat partly cooked."

"A whitish woolly plant (Teucrium Polium) of the order Labiatae  found throughout the Mediterranean region. The name with sundry prefixes is sometimes given to other related species of the same genus."
"A plane figure having many angles  and consequently many sides; esp. one whose perimeter consists of more than four sides; any figure having many angles."
"Any one of two or more substances related to each other by polymerism; specifically  a substance produced from another substance by chemical polymerization."
"The open sea supposed to surround the north pole."
"One of the feeding or nutritive zooids of a hydroid or coral."
"A persistently excessive flow of watery urine  with low specific gravity and without the presence of either albumin or sugar. It is generally accompanied with more or less thirst."
"Same as Bryozoa. See Illust. under Bryozoa  and Phylactolaemata."
"The substance of apples  or of similar fruit crushed by grinding."
"A perfumed unguent or composition  chiefly used in dressing the hair; pomade."
"A fruit composed of several cartilaginous or bony carpels inclosed in an adherent fleshy mass  which is partly receptacle and partly calyx as an apple quince or pear."
"A variety of shaddock  called also grape fruit."
"A figure supposed to resemble an apple; a roundel  -- always of a green color."
"One of two or more species of marine food fishes of the genus Stromateus (S. niger  S. argenteus) native of Southern Europe and Asia."
"Having the ends terminating in rounded protuberances or single balls; -- said of a cross."
"A knob or ball; an object resembling a ball in form"
"The goddess of fruits and fruit trees."
"A procession distinguished by ostentation and splendor; a pageant."
"Any one of several species of marine fishes of the genus Trachynotus  of which four species are found on the Atlantic coast of the United States; -- called also palometa."
"The ball formerly used to ink the type."
"Any trifling ornament for a woman's dress or bonnet."
"Displaying pomp; stately; showy with grandeur; magnificent; as  a pompous procession."

"A kind of cloak worn by the Spanish Americans  having the form of a blanket with a slit in the middle for the head to pass through. A kind of poncho made of rubber or painted cloth is used by the mounted troops in the United States service."
"A body of water  naturally or artificially confined and usually of less extent than a lake."
"A fabric of undyed silk from India and China."
"A Buddhist priest of the higher orders in Burmah."
"Any large ape; especially  the chimpanzee and the orang-outang."
"A kind of dagger  -- usually a slender one with a triangular or square blade."

"A bridge; -- applied to several parts which connect others  but especially to the pons Varolii a prominent band of nervous tissue situated on the ventral side of the medulla oblongata and connected at each side with the hemispheres of the cerebellum; the mesocephalon. See Brain."
"A duty or tax paid for repairing bridges."
"An iron rod used by glass makers for manipulating the hot glass; -- called also  puntil puntel punty and ponty. See Fascet."
"Of or pertaining to the Pontus  Euxine or Black Sea."
"Of or pertaining to the pons Varolii. See Pons."
"Of or pertaining to an extensive marshy district between Rome and Naples."
"A wooden flat-bottomed boat  a metallic cylinder or a frame covered with canvas India rubber etc. forming a portable float used in building bridges quickly for the passage of troops."
"A Russian weight  equal to forty Russian pounds or about thirty-six English pounds avoirdupois."
"A breed of dogs having curly hair  and often showing remarkable intelligence in the performance of tricks."
"Pshaw! pish! nonsense! -- an expression of scorn  dislike or contempt."
"A red African antelope (Kobus Vardoni) allied to the water buck."
"A small and rather deep collection of (usually) fresh water  as one supplied by a spring or occurring in the course of a stream; a reservoir for water; as the pools of Solomon."
"A stick for stirring a tan vat."
"A name for several East Indian  or their wood used for the masts and spars of vessels as Calophyllum angustifolium C. inophullum and Sterculia foetida; -- called also peon."
"A kind of oil cake prepared from the cocoanut. See Oil cake  under Cake."
"Destitute of property; wanting in material riches or goods; needy; indigent."
"A receptacle in which money given for the poor is placed."
"In a poor manner or condition; without plenty  or sufficiency or suitable provision for comfort; as to live poorly."
"A small  sharp quick explosive sound or report; as to go off with a pop."
"The place  office or dignity of the pope; papal dignity."
"The religion of the Roman Catholic Church  comprehending doctrines and practices; -- generally used in an opprobrious sense."
"A child's gun; a tube and rammer for shooting pellets  with a popping noise by compression of air."
"Of or pertaining to the pope; taught or ordained by the pope; hence  of or pertaining to the Roman Catholic Church; -- often used opprobriously."
"Any tree of the genus Populus; also  the timber which is soft and capable of many uses."
"A fabric of many varieties  usually made of silk and worsted -- used especially for women's dresses."
"A utensil for popping corn  usually a wire basket with a long handle."
"To move quickly up and down; to bob up and down  as a cork on rough water; also to bubble."

"Any plant or species of the genus Papaver  herbs with showy polypetalous flowers and a milky juice. From one species (Papaver somniferum) opium is obtained though all the species contain it to some extent; also a flower of the plant. See Illust. of Capsule."
"Of or pertaining to the common people  or to the whole body of the people as distinguished from a select portion; as the popular voice; popular elections."
"A glycoside  related to salicin found in the bark of certain species of the poplar (Populus) and extracted as a sweet white crystalline substance."
"Having grooves or furrows broader than the intervening ridges; furrowed."

"A covered and inclosed entrance to a building  whether taken from the interior and forming a sort of vestibule within the main wall or projecting without and with a separate roof. Sometimes the porch is large enough to serve as a covered walk. See also Carriage porch under Carriage and Loggia."
"Of or pertaining to swine; characteristic of the hog."
"One of the minute orifices in an animal or vegetable membrane  for transpiration absorption etc."
"A theorem or proposition so easy of demonstration as to be almost self-evident."
"A proposition affirming the possibility of finding such conditions as will render a certain determinate problem indeterminate or capable of innumerable solutions."
"Any coral of the genus Porites  or family Poritidae."
"An important genus of reef-building corals having small twelve-rayed calicles  and a very porous coral. Some species are branched others grow in large massive or globular forms."
"The flesh of swine  fresh or salted used for food."
"A medicine supposed to promote the formation of callus."
"Full of pores; having interstices in the skin or in the substance of the body; having spiracles or passages for fluids; permeable by liquids; as  a porous skin; porous wood."

"A genus of bright-colored Siphonophora found floating in the warmer parts of the ocean. The individuals are round and disk-shaped  with a large zooid in the center of the under side surrounded by smaller nutritive and reproductive zooids and by slender dactylozooids near the margin. The disk contains a central float or pneumatocyst."
"A scallion; a leek or small onion."
"A dark red or purple astringent wine made in Portugal. It contains a large percentage of alcohol."
"The part of the liver or other organ where its vessels and nerves enter; the hilus."
"A door or gate; hence  a way of entrance or exit especially one that is grand and imposing."
"Borne not erect  but diagonally athwart an escutcheon; as a cross portate."
"The Ottoman court; the government of the Turkish empire  officially called the Sublime Porte from the gate (port) of the sultan's palace at which justice was administered."
"To indicate (events  misfortunes etc.) as in future; to foreshow; to foretoken; to bode; -- now used esp. of unpropitious signs."
"That which portends  or foretoken; esp. that which portends evil; a sign of coming calamity; an omen; a sign."
"A man who has charge of a door or gate; a doorkeeper; one who waits at the door to receive messages."
"A colonnade or covered ambulatory  especially in classical styles of architecture; usually a colonnade at the entrance of a building."
"That which is divided off or separated  as a part from a whole; a separated part of anything."
"Having a dignified port or mien; of a noble appearance; imposing."
"An inhabitant or burgess of a port  esp. of one of the Cinque Ports."
"One who  or that which bears; hence one who or that which produces."
"To paint or draw the likeness of; as  to portray a king on horseback."
"Standing still  with all the feet on the ground; -- said of the attitude of a lion horse or other beast."
"One who  or that which puzzles; a difficult or inexplicable question or fact."
"To dispose or set firmly or fixedly; to place or dispose in relation to other objects."
"A little basin; a porringer; a skillet."
"To occupy in person; to hold or actually have in one's own keeping; to have and to hold."
"A beverage composed of hot milk curdled by some strong infusion  as by wine etc. -- much in favor formerly."
"Hired to do what is wrong; suborned."
"The price established by law to be paid for the conveyance of a letter or other mailable matter by a public post."
"Belonging to the post office or mail service; as  postal arrangements; postal authorities."
"One who rides post horses; a position; a courier."
"The return of the judge before whom a cause was tried  after a verdict of what was done in the cause which is indorsed on the nisi prius record."
"A large bill or placard intended to be posted in public places."
"Originally  a back door or gate; a private entrance; hence any small door or gate."
"- (/). A combining form meaning posterior  back; as postero-inferior situated back and below; postero-lateral situated back and at the side."
"A letter  syllable or word added to the end of another word; a suffix."
"Originally  an explanatory note in the margin of the Bible so called because written after the text; hence a marginal note; a comment."
"A post or courier; a letter carrier."

"The position of the body; the situation or disposition of the several parts of the body with respect to each other  or for a particular purpose; especially (Fine Arts) the position of a figure with regard to the several principal members by which action is expressed; attitude."
"A brief poetical sentiment; hence  any brief sentiment motto or legend; especially one inscribed on a ring."
"A metallic or earthen vessel  appropriated to any of a great variety of uses as for boiling meat or vegetables for holding liquids for plants etc.; as a quart pot; a flower pot; a bean pot."
"The refuse from a grain distillery  used to fatten swine."
"The stud in which the bearing for the lower pivot of the verge is made."
"The hydroxide of potassium hydrate  a hard white brittle substance KOH having strong caustic and alkaline properties; -- hence called also caustic potash."

"A plant (Solanum tuberosum) of the Nightshade family  and its esculent farinaceous tuber of which there are numerous varieties used for food. It is native of South America but a form of the species is found native as far north as New Mexico."
"A boy who carries pots of ale  beer etc.; a menial in a public house."
"Whisky; especially  whisky illicitly distilled by the Irish peasantry."
"The quality or state of being potent; physical or moral power; inherent strength; energy; ability to effect a purpose; capability; efficacy; influence."
"Producing great physical effects; forcible; powerful' efficacious; as  a potent medicine."
"A circular hole formed in the rocky beds of rivers by the grinding action of stones or gravel whirled round by the water in what was at first a natural depression of the rock."
"An S-shaped hook on which pots and kettles are hung over an open fire."
"A draught; a dose; usually  a draught or dose of a liquid medicine."
"The lid or cover of a pot."
"Whatever may chance to be in the pot  or may be provided for a meal."
"Any small kangaroo belonging to Hypsiprymnus  Bettongia and allied genera native of Australia and Tasmania. Called also kangaroo rat."
"A meat pie which is boiled instead of being baked."
"A size of paper. See under Paper."
"A kind of food made by boiling vegetables or meat  or both together in water until soft; a thick soup or porridge."
"One whose occupation is to make earthen vessels."
"The vessels or ware made by potters; earthenware  glazed and baked."
"A nocturnal mammal (Perodictius potto) of the Lemur family  found in West Africa. It has rudimentary forefingers. Called also aposoro and bush dog."
"A small bag; usually  a leathern bag; as a pouch for money; a shot pouch; a mail pouch etc."
"A young chicken  partridge grouse or the like."
"Domestic fowls reared for the table  or for their eggs or feathers such as cocks and hens capons turkeys ducks and geese."
"A fine powder  as of sandarac or cuttlefish bone -- formerly used to prevent ink from spreading on manuscript."
"Furnished with claws or talons; as  the pounced young of the eagle."
"To strike repeatedly with some heavy instrument; to beat."

"A unit of force based upon the pound  foot and second being the force which acting on a pound avoirdupois for one second causes it to acquire by the of that time a velocity of one foot per second. It is about equal to the weight of half an ounce and is 13 825 dynes."
"One who  or that which pounds as a stamp in an ore mill."
"The young of some birds  as grouse; a young fowl."
"The quality or state of being poor or indigent; want or scarcity of means of subsistence; indigence; need."
"A small British lake whitefish (Coregonus clupeoides  or C. ferus); -- called also gwyniad and lake herring."
"The fine particles to which any dry substance is reduced by pounding  grinding or triturating or into which it falls by decay; dust."
"Easily crumbling to pieces; friable; loose; as  a powdery spar."
"A priest  or conjurer among the North American Indians."
"To use conjuration  with noise and confusion for the cure of disease etc. as among the North American Indians."
"Strictly  a disease by pustules or eruptions of any kind but chiefly or wholly restricted to three or four diseases -- the smallpox the chicken pox and the vaccine and the venereal diseases."
"A support; -- used in composition; as  teapoy."
"Paving or flooring made of small squares or lozenges set diagonally."
"A South American armadillo (Dasypus sexcinctus). Called also sixbanded armadillo."
"A flat-bottomed boat or lighter  -- used in Holland and the Baltic and sometimes armed in case of war."

"An extensive tract of level or rolling land  destitute of trees covered with coarse grass and usually characterized by a deep fertile soil. They abound throughout the Mississippi valley between the Alleghanies and the Rocky mountains."
"To commend; to applaud; to express approbation of; to laud; -- applied to a person or his acts."

"Any one of the popular dialects descended from  or akin to Sanskrit; -- in distinction from the Sanskrit which was used as a literary and learned language when no longer spoken by the people. Pali is one of the Prakrit dialects."
"To spring or bound  as a horse in high mettle."

"A genus of umbelliferous plants  one species of which (P. pabularia) found in Thibet Cashmere Afghanistan etc. has been used as fodder for cattle. It has decompound leaves with very long narrow divisions and a highly fragrant smell resembling that of new clover hay."
"To adorn in a showy manner; to dress or equip ostentatiously; -- often followed by up; as  to prank up the body. See Prink."
"A variety of cryptocrystalline of a leek-green color."
"To talk much and to little purpose; to be loquacious; to speak foolishly; to babble."
"To talk much and idly; to prate; hence  to talk lightly and artlessly like a child; to utter child's talk."
"Deterioration; degeneracy; corruption; especially  moral crookedness; moral perversion; perverseness; depravity; as the pravity of human nature."

"Any one of numerous species of large shrimplike Crustacea having slender legs and long antennae. They mostly belong to the genera Pandalus  Palaemon Palaemonetes and Peneus and are much used as food. The common English prawn is Palaemon serratus."
"Use; practice; especially  exercise or discipline for a specific purpose or object."
"To proclaim or publish tidings; specifically  to proclaim the gospel; to discourse publicly on a religious subject or from a text of Scripture; to deliver a sermon."
"A payment or stipend; esp.  the stipend or maintenance granted to a prebendary out of the estate of a cathedral or collegiate church with which he is connected. See Note under Benefice."
"To go before in order of time; to occur first with relation to anything."
"Any commandment  instruction or order intended as an authoritative rule of action; esp. a command respecting moral conduct; an injunction; a rule."
"A concise or abridged statement or view; an abstract; a summary."
"Having determinate limitations; exactly or sharply defined or stated; definite; exact; nice; not vague or equivocal; as  precise rules of morality."
"Of or pertaining to prey; plundering; predatory."
"To date anticipation; to affix to (a document) an earlier than the actual date; to antedate; as  a predated deed or letter."
"Consisting of land or farms; landed; as  predial estate; that is real estate."
"To tell or declare beforehand; to foretell; to prophesy; to presage; as  to predict misfortune; to predict the return of a comet."
"Cleared and ready for engagement  as a ship."
"To settle upon (public land) with a right of preemption  as under the laws of the United States; to take by preemption."
"A forked tool used by clothiers in dressing cloth."
"Something spoken as introductory to a discourse  or written as introductory to a book or essay; a proem; an introduction or series of preliminary remarks."

"A Roman officer who controlled or superintended a particular command  charge department etc.; as the prefect of the aqueducts; the prefect of a camp of a fleet of the city guard of provisions; the pretorian prefect who was commander of the troops guarding the emperor's person."

"To carry or bring (something) forward  or before one; hence to bring for consideration acceptance judgment etc.; to offer; to present; to proffer; to address; -- said especially of a request prayer petition claim charge etc."
"To put or fix before  or at the beginning of another thing; as to prefix a syllable to a word or a condition to an agreement."
"To form beforehand  or for special ends."
"The office or dignity of a prelate; church government by prelates."
"A clergyman of a superior order  as an archbishop or a bishop having authority over the lower clergy; a dignitary of the church."
"To read publicly  as a lecture or discourse."

"An introductory performance  preceding and preparing for the principal matter; a preliminary part movement strain etc.; especially (Mus.) a strain introducing the theme or chief subject; a movement introductory to a fugue yet independent; -- with recent composers often synonymous with overture."
"First; chief; principal; as  the premier place; premier minister."
"A proposition antecedently supposed or proved; something previously stated or assumed as the basis of further argument; a condition; a supposition."

"A reward or recompense; a prize to be won by being before another  or others in a competition; reward or prize to be adjudged; a bounty; as a premium for good behavior or scholarship for discoveries etc."
"The power or right of taking a thing before it is offered."
"Situated in front of  or anterior to the mouth; as preoral bands."
"To fit  adapt or qualify for a particular purpose or condition; to make ready; to put into a state for use or application; as to prepare ground for seed; to prepare a lesson."
"To pay in advance  or beforehand; as to prepay postage."
"To place or set before; to prefix."
"Something which foreshows or portends a future event; a prognostic; an omen; an augury."
"Being at hand  within reach or call within certain contemplated limits; -- opposed to absent."

"To be set  or to sit in the place of authority; to occupy the place of president chairman moderator director etc.; to direct control and regulate as chief officer; as to preside at a public meeting; to preside over the senate."
"An East Indian insectivore (Tupaia ferruginea). It is arboreal in its habits  and has a bushy tail. The fur is soft and varies from rusty red to maroon and to brownish black."

"Causing  or giving rise to pressure or to an increase of pressure; as pressor nerve fibers stimulation of which excites the vasomotor center thus causing a stronger contraction of the arteries and consequently an increase of the arterial blood pressure; -- opposed to depressor."
"A meteor or exhalation formerly supposed to be thrown from the clouds with such violence that by collision it is set on fire."
"To assume or take beforehand; esp.  to do or undertake without leave or authority previously obtained."
"To lay a claim to; to allege a title to; to claim."
"To frame; to devise; to disguise or excuse; hence  to pretend; to declare falsely."
"Ostensible reason or motive assigned or assumed as a color or cover for the real reason or motive; pretense; disguise."
"A civil officer or magistrate among the ancient Romans."

"Pleasing by delicacy or grace; attracting  but not striking or impressing; of a pleasing and attractive form a color; having slight or diminutive beauty; neat or elegant without elevation or grandeur; pleasingly but not grandly conceived or expressed; as a pretty face; a pretty flower; a pretty poem."
"A kind of German biscuit or cake in the form of a twisted ring  salted on the outside."
"To overcome; to gain the victory or superiority; to gain the advantage; to have the upper hand  or the mastery; to succeed; -- sometimes with over or against."
"To come before; to anticipate; hence  to hinder; to prevent."
"To go before; to precede; hence  to go before as a guide; to direct."
"Anything  as goods etc. taken or got by violence; anything taken by force from an enemy in war; spoil; booty; plunder."
"One who  or that which preys; a plunderer; a waster; a devourer."
"A corruption of pair royal. See under Pair  n."
"A fine  white somewhat friable clay; also the ore contained in a mixture of clay and pebbles."

"The sum or amount of money at which a thing is valued  or the value which a seller sets on his goods in market; that for which something is bought or sold or offered for sale; equivalent in money or other means of exchange; current value or rate paid or demanded in market or in barter; cost."
"That which pricks  penetrates or punctures; a sharp and slender thing; a pointed instrument; a goad; a spur etc.; a point; a skewer."
"One who  or that which pricks; a pointed instrument; a sharp point; a prickle."
"A buck in his second year. See Note under 3d Buck."
"A little prick; a small  sharp point; a fine sharp process or projection as from the skin of an animal the bark of a plant etc.; a spine."
"Full of sharp points or prickles; armed or covered with prickles; as  a prickly shrub."
"A small European lamprey (Petromyzon branchialis); -- called also prid  and sandpiper."
"Of or pertaining to the day before  or yesterday."
"One who pries; one who inquires narrowly and searches  or is inquisitive."
"To haggle about the price of a commodity; to bargain hard."
"The state or condition of being prime or first  as in time place rank etc. hence excellency; supremacy."

"A charge in addition to the freight; originally  a gratuity to the captain for his particular care of the goods (sometimes called hat money) but now belonging to the owners or freighters of the vessel unless by special agreement the whole or part is assigned to the captain."
"First in order of time or development or in intention; primitive; fundamental; original."
"The chief ecclesiastic in a national church; one who presides over other bishops in a province; an archbishop."
"The outermost of the two integuments of an ovule."
"To be formal or affected in dress or manners; -- often with up."
"The genus of plants including the primrose (Primula vera)."
"One of the bishops of the Episcopal Church of Scotland  who presides at the meetings of the bishops and has certain privileges but no metropolitan authority."
"The one of highest rank; one holding the highest place and authority; a sovereign; a monarch; -- originally applied to either sex  but now rarely applied to a female."
"To dress or adjust one's self for show; to prank."
"To fix or impress  as a stamp mark character idea etc. into or upon something."
"One who prints; especially  one who prints books newspapers engravings etc. a compositor; a typesetter; a pressman."

"Preceding in the order of time; former; antecedent; anterior; previous; as  a prior discovery; prior obligation; -- used elliptically in cases like the following: he lived alone [in the time] prior to his marriage."
"A religious house presided over by a prior or prioress; -- sometimes an offshoot of  an subordinate to an abbey and called also cell and obedience. See Cell 2."

"A right belonging to the crown of England  of taking two tuns of wine from every ship importing twenty tuns or more -- one before and one behind the mast. By charter of Edward I. butlerage was substituted for this."
"A solid whose bases or ends are any similar  equal and parallel plane figures and whose sides are parallelograms."
"A place where persons are confined  or restrained of personal liberty; hence a place or state o/ confinement restraint or safe custody."
"A corruption of pray thee; as  I prithee; generally used without I."
"The state of being in retirement from the company or observation of others; seclusion."
"A private friend; a confidential friend; a confidant."

"Belonging to  or concerning an individual person company or interest; peculiar to one's self; unconnected with others; personal; one's own; not public; not general; separate; as a man's private opinion; private property; a private purse; private expenses or interests; a private secretary."
"An ornamental European shrub (Ligustrum vulgare)  much used in hedges; -- called also prim."
"Of or pertaining to some person exclusively; assigned to private uses; not public; private; as  the privy purse."
"That which is taken from another; something captured; a thing seized by force  stratagem or superior power."
"One who estimates or sets the value of a thing; an appraiser."
"A Latin preposition signifying for  before forth."

"A sailing canoe of the Ladrone Islands and Malay Archipelago  having its lee side flat and its weather side like that of an ordinary boat. The ends are alike. The canoe is long and narrow and is kept from overturning by a cigar-shaped log attached to a frame extending several feet to windward. It has been called the flying proa and is the swiftest sailing craft known."
"A slender elastic rod  as of whalebone with a sponge on the end for removing obstructions from the esophagus etc."
"To examine  as a wound an ulcer or some cavity of the body with a probe."
"Tried virtue or integrity; approved moral excellence; honesty; rectitude; uprightness."
"A question proposed for solution; a matter stated for examination or proof; hence  a matter difficult of solution or settlement; a doubtful case; a question involving doubt."
"To move  pass or go forward or onward; to advance; to continue or renew motion begun; as to proceed on a journey."
"The act of proceeding; continued forward movement; procedure; progress; advance."
"Any species of small moths of the genus Procris. The larvae of some species injure the grapevine by feeding in groups upon the leaves."
"One who is employed to manage to affairs of another."
"To bring into possession; to cause to accrue to  or to come into possession of; to acquire or provide for one's self or for another; to gain; to get; to obtain by any means as by purchase or loan."
"A star of the first magnitude in the constellation Canis Minor  or the Little Dog."
"A pointed instrument for pricking or puncturing  as a goad an awl a skewer etc."
"Something extraordinary  or out of the usual course of nature from which omens are drawn; a portent; as eclipses and meteors were anciently deemed prodigies."
"To bring forward; to lead forth; to offer to view or notice; to exhibit; to show; as  to produce a witness or evidence in court."

"Anything that is produced  whether as the result of generation growth labor or thought or by the operation of involuntary causes; as the products of the season or of the farm; the products of manufactures; the products of the brain."
"Much good may it do you! -- a familiar salutation or welcome."
"Not sacred or holy; not possessing peculiar sanctity; unconsecrated; hence  relating to matters other than sacred; secular; -- opposed to sacred religious or inspired; as a profane place."
"The exhibition or production of a record or paper in open court  or an allegation that it is in court."
"To make open declaration of  as of one's knowledge belief action etc.; to avow or acknowledge; to confess publicly; to own or admit freely."
"To offer for acceptance; to propose to give; to make a tender of; as  to proffer a gift; to proffer services; to proffer friendship."
"An outline  or contour; as the profile of an apple."

"Acquisition beyond expenditure; excess of value received for producing  keeping or selling over cost; hence pecuniary gain in any transaction or occupation; emolument; as a profit on the sale of goods."
"Pouring forth with fullness or exuberance; bountiful; exceedingly liberal; giving without stint; as  a profuse government; profuse hospitality."
"To wander about and beg; to seek food or other supplies by low arts; to seek for advantage by mean shift or tricks."
"Descendants of the human kind  or offspring of other animals; children; offspring; race lineage."
"To lop; to trim; to prune; to adorn."
"The place from which a thing projects  or starts forth."
"A plan proposed; a draft of a proposed measure; a project."
"Stretched out; extended; especially  elongated in the direction of a line joining the poles; as a prolate spheroid; -- opposed to oblate."

"One of the fleshy legs found on the abdominal segments of the larvae of Lepidoptera  sawflies and some other insects. Those of Lepidoptera have a circle of hooks. Called also proped propleg and falseleg."

"Extending to a great length; unnecessarily long; minute in narration or argument; excessively particular in detail; -- rarely used except with reference to discourse written or spoken; as  a prolix oration; a prolix poem; a prolix sermon."
"To search or prowl after; to rob; to plunder."
"To extend in space or length; as  to prolong a line."

"In general  a declaration written or verbal made by one person to another which binds the person who makes it to do or to forbear to do a specified act; a declaration which gives to the person to whom it is made a right to expect or to claim the performance or forbearance of a specified act."

"To contribute to the growth  enlargement or prosperity of (any process or thing that is in course); to forward; to further; to encourage; to advance; to excite; as to promote learning; to promote disorder; to promote a business venture."
"To move forward; to advance; to promote."

"Ready and quick to act as occasion demands; meeting requirements readily; not slow  dilatory or hesitating in decision or action; responding on the instant; immediate; as prompt in obedience or compliance; -- said of persons."
"A limit of time given for payment of an account for produce purchased  this limit varying with different goods. See Prompt-note."
"The porch or vestibule of a temple."
"Having prongs or projections like the tines of a fork; as  a three-pronged fork."
"A word used instead of a noun or name  to avoid the repetition of it. The personal pronouns in English are I thou or you he she it we ye and they."
"Any effort  process or operation designed to establish or discover a fact or truth; an act of testing; a test; a trial."
"In front of the auditory capsule; -- applied especially to a bone  or center of ossification in the periotic capsule."
"A shell  used as a die. See Props."
"A heavy gaseous hydrocarbon  C3H8 of the paraffin series occurring naturally dissolved in crude petroleum and also made artificially; -- called also propyl hydride."
"To drive forward; to urge or press onward by force; to move  or cause to move; as the wind or steam propels ships; balls are propelled by gunpowder."
"To lean toward a thing; to be favorably inclined or disposed; to incline; to tend."
"One who prophesies  or foretells events; a predicter; a foreteller."
"To pledge; to offer as a toast or a health in the manner of drinking  that is by drinking first and passing the cup."
"A game of chance  in which four sea shells each called a prop are used instead of dice."
"To contend for; to defend; to vindicate."
"The hypothetical radical C3H7  regarded as the essential residue of propane and related compounds."
"To divide or distribute proportionally; to assess pro rata."
"The prow or fore part of a ship."
"The ordinary language of men in speaking or writing; language not cast in poetical measure or rhythm; -- contradistinguished from verse  or metrical composition."
"That part of grammar which treats of the quantity of syllables  of accent and of the laws of versification or metrical composition."
"The anterior of the body of an animal  as of a cephalopod; the thorax of an arthropod."
"Of or pertaining to prose; like prose."
"Of or pertaining to Proteus; characteristic of Proteus."
"To cover or shield from danger or injury; to defend; to guard; to preserve in safety; as  a father protects his children."

"One of a class of amorphous nitrogenous principles  containing as a rule a small amount of sulphur; an albuminoid as blood fibrin casein of milk etc. Proteids are present in nearly all animal fluids and make up the greater part of animal tissues and organs. They are also important constituents of vegetable tissues. See 2d Note under Food."
"A body now known as alkali albumin  but originally considered to be the basis of all albuminous substances whence its name."
"To affirm in a public or formal manner; to bear witness; to declare solemnly; to avow."
"A sea god in the service of Neptune who assumed different shapes at will. Hence  one who easily changes his appearance or principles."
"The hypothetical homogeneous cosmic material of the original universe  supposed to have been differentiated into what are recognized as distinct chemical elements."
"Feeling or manifesting pride  in a good or bad sense"
"In a proud manner; with lofty airs or mien; haughtily; arrogantly; boastfully."
"To supply with provender or provisions; to provide for."
"To try or to ascertain by an experiment  or by a test or standard; to test; as to prove the strength of gunpowder or of ordnance; to prove the contents of a vessel by a standard measure."

"An old and common saying; a phrase which is often repeated; especially  a sentence which briefly and forcibly expresses some practical truth or the result of experience and observation; a maxim; a saw; an adage."
"To look out for in advance; to procure beforehand; to get  collect or make ready for future use; to prepare."
"To lay a stock or branch of a vine in the ground for propagation."

"An article or clause in any statute  agreement contract grant or other writing by which a condition is introduced usually beginning with the word provided; a conditional stipulation that affects an agreement contract law grant or the like; as the contract was impaired by its proviso."

"To call forth; to call into being or action; esp.  to incense to action a faculty or passion as love hate or ambition; hence commonly to incite as a person to action by a challenge by taunts or by defiance; to exasperate; to irritate; to offend intolerably; to cause to retaliate."

"A person who is appointed to superintend  or preside over something; the chief magistrate in some cities and towns; as the provost of Edinburgh or of Glasgow answering to the mayor of other cities; the provost of a college answering to president; the provost or head of certain collegiate churches."
"The fore part of a vessel; the bow; the stem; hence  the vessel itself."
"Distinguished bravery; valor; especially  military bravery and skill; gallantry; intrepidity; fearlessness."
"To rove over  through or about in a stealthy manner; esp. to search in as for prey or booty."
"""""The ticket or list of candidates at elections  presented to the people for their votes."
"An officer who had the charge of showing hospitality to those who came from a friendly city or state."
"In the next month after the present; -- often contracted to prox.; as  on the 3d proximo."
"The agency for another who acts through the agent; authority to act for another  esp. to vote in a legislative or corporate capacity."
"A woman of affected modesty  reserve or coyness; one who is overscrupulous or sensitive; one who affects extraordinary prudence in conduct and speech."

"Sagacious in adapting means to ends; circumspect in action  or in determining any line of conduct; practically wise; judicious; careful; discreet; sensible; -- opposed to rash; as a prudent man; dictated or directed by prudence or wise forethought; evincing prudence; as prudent behavior."
"The quality or state of being prudish; excessive or affected scrupulousness in speech or conduct; stiffness; coyness."
"Like a prude; very formal  precise or reserved; affectedly severe in virtue; as a prudish woman; prudish manners."
"To lop or cut off the superfluous parts  branches or shoots of; to clear of useless material; to shape or smooth by trimming; to trim: as to prune trees; to prune an essay."
"One who prunes  or removes what is superfluous."
"A genus of trees with perigynous rosaceous flowers  and a single two-ovuled carpel which usually becomes a drupe in ripening."
"A papular disease of the skin  of which intense itching is the chief symptom the eruption scarcely differing from the healthy cuticle in color."
"designating the acid now called hydrocyanic acid  but formerly called prussic acid because Prussian blue is derived from it or its compounds. See Hydrocyanic."
"The period during which the presidency of the senate belonged to the prytanes of the section."
"A sacred song; a poetical composition for use in the praise or worship of God."
"The Book of Psalms; -- often applied to a book containing the Psalms separately printed."
"Pish! pooch! -- an exclamation used as an expression of contempt  disdain dislike etc."
"An internal muscle arising from the lumbar vertebrae and inserted into the femur. In man there are usually two on each side  and the larger one or great psoas forms a part of the iliopsoas."
"Of or pertaining to the soul; psychical."
"A lovely maiden  daughter of a king and mistress of Eros or Cupid. She is regarded as the personification of the soul."
"Any leaping plant louse of the genus Psylla  or family Psyllidae."
"The region of the skull  in the temporal fossa back of the orbit where the great wing of the sphenoid the temporal the parietal and the frontal hones approach each other."
"One of the definite areas of the skin of a bird on which feathers grow; -- contrasted with apteria."
"A decoction of barley with other ingredients; a farinaceous drink."
"Drooping of the upper eyelid  produced by paralysis of its levator muscle."
"An unorganized amylolytic ferment  on enzyme present in human mixed saliva and in the saliva of some animals."
"The way in which a leaf is sometimes folded in the bud."
"The earliest age at which persons are capable of begetting or bearing children  usually considered in temperate climates to be about fourteen years in males and twelve in females."
"The hair which appears upon the lower part of the hypogastric region at the age of puberty."
"Of or pertaining to the pubes; in the region of the pubes; as  the pubic bone; the pubic region or the lower part of the hypogastric region. See Pubes."
"The ventral and anterior of the three principal bones composing either half of the pelvis; sharebone; pubic bone."
"Of or pertaining to the people; belonging to the people; relating to  or affecting a nation state or community; -- opposed to private; as the public treasury."
"To make public; to make known to mankind  or to people in general; to divulge as a private transaction; to promulgate or proclaim as a law or an edict."
"Any one of several plants yielding a red pigment which is used by the North American Indians  as the bloodroot and two species of Lithospermum (L. hirtum and L. canescens); also the pigment itself."
"Of a dark brown or brownish purple color."
"A celebrated fairy  """"the merry wanderer of the night;"""" -- called also Robin Goodfellow Friar Rush Pug etc."
"To gather into small folds or wrinkles; to contract into ridges and furrows; to corrugate; -- often with up; as  to pucker up the mouth."
"Producing  or tending to produce a pucker; as a puckery taste."
"To make a tumult or bustle; to splash; to make a pother or fuss; to potter; to meddle."
"A species of food of a soft or moderately hard consistence  variously made but often a compound of flour or meal with milk and eggs etc."
"A small quantity of dirty standing water; a muddy plash; a small pool."
"One who converts cast iron into wrought iron by the process of puddling."
"Consisting of  or resembling puddles; muddy; foul."
"Short and fat or sturdy; dumpy; podgy; as  a short pudgy little man; a pudgy little hand."
"Of or pertaining to the external organs of generation."
"A very small deer (Pudua humilis)  native of the Chilian Andes. It has simple spikelike antlers only two or three inches long."
"To make a low whistling sound; to chirp  as birds."

"A communistic building erected by certain Indian tribes of Arizona and New Mexico. It is often of large size and several stories high  and is usually built either of stone or adobe. The term is also applied to any Indian village in the same region."
"The dung of dogs  used as an alkaline steep in tanning."
"A sudden and single emission of breath from the mouth; hence  any sudden or short blast of wind; a slight gust; a whiff."
"One who puffs; one who praises with noisy or extravagant commendation."
"The act of puffing; bestowment of extravagant commendation."
"An arctic sea bird Fratercula arctica) allied to the auks  and having a short thick swollen beak whence the name; -- called also bottle nose cockandy coulterneb marrot mormon pope and sea parrot."
"Swelled with air  or any soft matter; tumid with a soft substance; bloated; fleshy; as a puffy tumor."
"To mix and stir when wet  as clay for bricks pottery etc."
"Pshaw! pish! -- a word used in contempt or disdain."
"As much as is taken up between the thumb and two first fingers."
"A well; a small stream; a fountain; a spring."
"To eject the contests of the stomach; to vomit; to spew."
"The East Indian leguminous tree Butea frondosa. See Gum Butea  under Gum."
"One who pules; one who whines or complains; a weak person."
"A genus of parasitic insects including the fleas. See Flea."
"To draw  or attempt to draw toward one; to draw forcibly."
"A young hen  or female of the domestic fowl."

"A wheel with a broad rim  or grooved rim for transmitting power from or imparting power to the different parts of machinery or for changing the direction of motion by means of a belt cord rope or chain."
"A chick; a young bird in the downy stage."
"A moist  slightly cohering mass consisting of soft undissolved animal or vegetable matter."
"An elevated place  or inclosed stage in a church in which the clergyman stands while preaching."
"Like pulp; consisting of pulp; soft; fleshy; succulent; as  the pulpy covering of a nut; the pulpy substance of a peach or a cherry."
"To throb  as a pulse; to beat as the heart."
"Leguminous plants  or their seeds as beans pease etc."
"The act of driving forward; propulsion; -- opposed to suction or traction."

"A vegetable substance consisting of soft  elastic yellowish brown chaff gathered in the Hawaiian Islands from the young fronds of free ferns of the genus Cibotium chiefly C. Menziesii; -- used for stuffing mattresses cushions etc. and as an absorbent."

"A large American carnivore (Felis concolor)  found from Canada to Patagonia especially among the mountains. Its color is tawny or brownish yellow without spots or stripes. Called also catamount cougar American lion mountain lion and panther or painter."

"A very light porous volcanic scoria  usually of a gray color the pores of which are capillary and parallel giving it a fibrous structure. It is supposed to be produced by the disengagement of watery vapor without liquid or plastic lava. It is much used esp. in the form of powder for smoothing and polishing. Called also pumice stone."
"Affected with a kind of chronic laminitis in which there is a growth of soft spongy horn between the coffin bone and the hoof wall. The disease is called pumiced foot  or pumice foot."
"A low shoe with a thin sole."
"That which is raised by pumps  or the work done by pumps."
"One who pumps; the instrument or machine used in pumping."
"A well-known trailing plant (Cucurbita pepo) and its fruit  -- used for cooking and for feeding stock; a pompion."

"A beverage composed of wine or distilled liquor  water (or milk) sugar and the juice of lemon with spice or mint; -- specifically named from the kind of spirit used; as rum punch claret punch champagne punch etc."
"A nice point of form or ceremony."
"A learned man; a teacher; esp.  a Brahman versed in the Sanskrit language and in the science laws and religion of the Hindoos; in Cashmere any clerk or native official."
"A short and fat woman; a squab."
"A kind of plain sleigh drawn by one horse; originally  a rude oblong box on runners."
"Causing a sharp sensation  as of the taste smell or feelings; pricking; biting; acrid; as a pungent spice."
"Shriveled or shrunken; -- said especially of grain which has lost its juices from the ravages of insects  such as the wheat midge or Trips (Thrips cerealium)."
"A small sloop or shallop  or a large boat with sails."
"Of or pertaining to the ancient Carthaginians."

"To impose a penalty upon; to afflict with pain  loss or suffering for a crime or fault either with or without a view to the offender's amendment; to cause to suffer in retribution; to chasten; as to punish traitors with death; a father punishes his child for willful disobedience."
"Wood so decayed as to be dry  crumbly and useful for tinder; touchwood."
"A machine for fanning a room  usually a movable fanlike frame covered with canvas and suspended from the ceiling. It is kept in motion by pulling a cord."
"A broad  shallow basket for displaying fruit or flowers."
"One who puns  or is skilled in or given to punning; a quibbler; a low wit."
"To play at basset  baccara faro. or omber; to gamble."
"One who punts; specifically  one who plays against the banker or dealer as in baccara and faro."
"Imperfectly developed in size or vigor; small and feeble; inferior; petty."
"Any insect in that stage of its metamorphosis which usually immediately precedes the adult  or imago stage."
"Of or pertaining to a pupa  or the condition of a pupa."
"The aperture in the iris; the sight  apple or black of the eye. See the Note under Eye and Iris."
"A small image in the human form; a doll."
"The young of a canine animal  esp. of the common dog; a whelp."
"To utter a low  murmuring continued sound as a cat does when pleased."

"One of a class of sacred Hindoo poetical works in the Sanskrit language which treat of the creation  destruction and renovation of worlds the genealogy and achievements of gods and heroes the reigns of the Manus and the transactions of their descendants. The principal Puranas are eighteen in number and there are the same number of supplementary books called Upa Puranas."
"A curtain or screen; also  a cotton fabric in blue and white stripes used for curtains."
"Separate from all heterogeneous or extraneous matter; free from mixture or combination; clean; mere; simple; unmixed; as  pure water; pure clay; pure air; pure compassion."
"A dish made by boiling any article of food to a pulp and rubbing it through a sieve; as  a puree of fish or of potatoes; especially a soup the thickening of which is so treated."
"In a pure manner (in any sense of the adjective)."
"A sort of ancient trimming of tinsel and thread for women's gowns; -- called also bobbinwork."
"To decorate with a wrought or flowered border; to embroider; to ornament with metallic threads; as  to purfle with blue and white."
"A hem  border. or trimming as of embroidered work."
"Ornamented; decorated; esp.  embroidered on the edges."
"To cleanse  clear or purify by separating and carrying off whatever is impure heterogeneous foreign or superfluous."
"One who  or that which purges or cleanses; especially a cathartic medicine."
"The part of a sugarhouse where the molasses is drained off from the sugar."
"To make pure or clear from material defilement  admixture or imperfection; to free from extraneous or noxious matter; as to purify liquors or metals; to purify the blood; to purify the air."
"A Jewish festival  called also the Feast of Lots instituted to commemorate the deliverance of the Jews from the machinations of Haman."
"Rigid purity; the quality of being affectedly pure or nice  especially in the choice of language; over-solicitude as to purity."
"One who aims at excessive purity or nicety  esp. in the choice of language."

"One who  in the time of Queen Elizabeth and the first two Stuarts opposed traditional and formal usages and advocated simpler forms of faith and worship than those established by law; -- originally a term of reproach. The Puritans formed the bulk of the early population of New England."
"Originally  the ground near a royal forest which having been unlawfully added to the forest was afterwards severed from it and disafforested so as to remit to the former owners their rights."
"In root construction  a horizontal member supported on the principals and supporting the common rafters."
"To take or carry away for one's self; hence  to steal; to take by theft; to filch."
"A color formed by  or resembling that formed by a combination of the primary colors red and blue."

"That which a person sets before himself as an object to be reached or accomplished; the end or aim to which the view is directed in any plan  measure or exertion; view; aim; design; intention; plan."
"A disease characterized by livid spots on the skin from extravasated blood  with loss of muscular strength pain in the limbs and mental dejection; the purples."
"Purple  -- represented in engraving by diagonal lines declining from the right top to the left base of the escutcheon (or from sinister chief to dexter base)."
"To murmur as a cat. See Pur."

"A small bag or pouch  the opening of which is made to draw together closely used to carry money in; by extension any receptacle for money carried on the person; a wallet; a pocketbook; a portemonnaie."
"A commissioned officer in the navy who had charge of the provisions  clothing and public moneys on shipboard; -- now called paymaster."
"To follow with a view to overtake; to follow eagerly  or with haste; to chase; as to pursue a hare."
"One who pursues or chases; one who follows in haste  with a view to overtake."
"The act of following or going after; esp.  a following with haste either for sport or in hostility; chase; prosecution; as the pursuit of game; the pursuit of an enemy."
"Fat and short-breathed; fat  short and thick; swelled with pampering; as pursy insolence."
"To furnish or provide  as with a convenience provisions or the like."
"The body of a statute  or that part which begins with """" Be it enacted """" as distinguished from the preamble."
"The yellowish white opaque creamy matter produced by the process of suppuration. It consists of innumerable white nucleated cells floating in a clear liquid."
"A piece of armor for the breast; often  an addition to or reenforcement of. the breastplate; -- called also pesane."
"A pet name for a cat; also  an endearing name for a girl."
"A vesicle or an elevation of the cuticle with an inflamed base  containing pus."
"Prostitution or fornication on the part of a woman."
"The shell of a nut; the stone of a drupe fruit. See Endocarp."
"An inclosure surrounding a well to prevent persons from falling into it; a well curb."
"Rotten; fetid; stinking; base; worthless. Jer. Taylor."

"One of the short pieces of timber on which the planks forming the floor of a scaffold are laid  -- one end resting on the ledger of the scaffold and the other in a hole left in the wall temporarily for the purpose."
"A keeper of a brothel; a procurer."
"To render putrid; to cause to decay offensively; to cause to be decomposed; to cause to rot."
"Tending to decomposition or decay; decomposed; rotten; -- said of animal or vegetable matter; as  putrid flesh. See Putrefaction."

"A kind of thick paste or cement compounded of whiting  or soft carbonate of lime and linseed oil when applied beaten or kneaded to the consistence of dough -- used in fastening glass in sashes stopping crevices and for similar purposes."
"Something which perplexes or embarrasses; especially  a toy or a problem contrived for testing ingenuity; also something exhibiting marvelous skill in making."
"One who  or that which puzzles or perplexes."
