"A form of blood poisoning produced by the absorption into the blood of morbid matters usually originating in a wound or local inflammation. It is characterized by the development of multiple abscesses throughout the body  and is attended with irregularly recurring chills fever profuse sweating and exhaustion."
"Of or pertaining to pyaemia; of the nature of pyaemia."
"Situated in the region of the rump  or posterior end of the backbone; -- applied especially to the posterior median plates in the carapace of chelonians."
"Of or pertaining to a pygmy; resembling a pygmy or dwarf; dwarfish; very small."
"An albuminoid constituent of pus  related to mucin possibly a mixture of substances rather than a single body."
"In India and Persia  thin loose trowsers or drawers; in Europe and America drawers worn at night or a kind of nightdress with legs."
"The passage between the iter and optocoele in the brain."
"A low tower  having a truncated pyramidal form and flanking an ancient Egyptian gateway."
"Of  pertaining to or in the region of the pylorus; as the pyloric end of the stomach."
"The opening from the stomach into the intestine."
"Of or pertaining to pus; of the nature of  or like pus."
"Any moth of the family Pyralidae. The species are numerous and mostly small  but some of them are very injurious as the bee moth meal moth hop moth and clover moth."
"A solid body standing on a triangular  square or polygonal base and terminating in a point at the top; especially a structure or edifice of this shape."
"A funeral pile; a combustible heap on which the dead are burned; hence  any pile to be burnt."
"A nutlet resembling a seed  or the kernel of a drupe."
"One of the less volatile hydrocarbons of coal tar  obtained as a white crystalline substance C16H10."
"A variety of pyroxene; -- called also fassaite."
"Related to  or formed from pyridin or its homologues; as the pyridic bases."
"A hypothetical radical  C5H4N regarded as the essential residue of pyridine and analogous to phenyl."
"A common mineral of a pale brass-yellow color and brilliant metallic luster  crystallizing in the isometric system; iron pyrites; iron disulphide."
"A variety of garnet  of a poppy or blood-red color frequently with a tinge of orange. It is used as a gem. See the Note under Garnet."
"Of or pertaining to an ancient Greek martial dance."

"A nitrogenous base found in coal tar  bone oil and other distillates of organic substances and also produced synthetically as a colorless liquid C4H5N having on odor like that of chloroform. It is the nucleus and origin of a large number of derivatives. So called because it colors a splinter of wood moistened with hydrochloric acid a deep red."
"A genus of large marine gastropods. having a pear-shaped shell. It includes the fig-shells. See Illust. in Appendix."
"A genus of rosaceous trees and shrubs having pomes for fruit. It includes the apple  crab apple pear chokeberry sorb and mountain ash."
"Pertaining to  or designating an acid (called also pyroracemic acid) obtained as a liquid having a pungent odor by the distillation of racemic acid."
"A complex nitrogenous compound obtained by heating together pyruvic acid and urea."
"The period intervening between one celebration of the Pythian games and the next."
"Of or pertaining to Delphi  to the temple of Apollo or to the priestess of Apollo who delivered oracles at Delphi."
"Any species of very large snakes of the genus Python  and allied genera of the family Pythonidae. They are nearly allied to the boas. Called also rock snake."
"A morbid condition in which pus is discharged in the urine."
"The box  case vase or tabernacle in which the host is reserved."
"In so far as; in the capacity or character of; as."
"An unfledged bird; hence  something immature or unfinished."
"To utter a sound like the cry of a duck."
"Evil; bad; baffling; as  a quade wind."
"The plinth  or lowest member of any pedestal podium water table or the like."
"A block of type metal lower than the letters  -- used in spacing and in blank lines."
"A square piece of turf or peat."
"Of or pertaining to the second degree."
"A small piece of money  in value about a farthing or a half cent."
"Inquire; question; see; -- used to signify doubt or to suggest investigation."
"To drink with relish; to drink copiously of; to swallow in large draughts."
"A South African wild ass (Equus  / Hippotigris quagga). The upper parts are reddish brown becoming paler behind and behind and beneath with dark stripes on the face neck and fore part of the body."
"Of the nature of a quagmire; yielding or trembling under the foot  as soft wet earth; spongy; boggy."
"An American market clam (Venus mercenaria). It is sold in large quantities  and is highly valued as food. Called also round clam and hard clam."
"A small shallow cup or drinking vessel."
"To die; to perish; hence  to wither; to fade."
"To be agitated with quick  short motions continually repeated; to shake with fear cold etc.; to shudder; to tremble."

"To make such as is required; to give added or requisite qualities to; to fit  as for a place office occupation or character; to furnish with the knowledge skill or other accomplishment necessary for a purpose; to make capable as of an employment or privilege; to supply with legal power or capacity."
"The condition of being of such and such a sort as distinguished from others; nature or character relatively considered  as of goods; character; sort; rank."
"A flat file having the handle at one side  so as to be used like a plane."
"A punting pole with a broad flange near the end to prevent it from sinking into the mud; a setting pole."

"A homogeneous algebraic function of two or more variables  in general containing only positive integral powers of the variables and called quadric cubic quartic etc. according as it is of the second third fourth fifth or a higher degree. These are further called binary ternary
"An arrow for a crossbow; -- so named because it commonly had a square head."
"The fourth part; a quarter; hence  a region of the earth."
"Of or pertaining to the fourth; occurring every fourth day  reckoning inclusively; as a quartan ague or fever."
"One of four equal parts into which anything is divided  or is regarded as divided; a fourth part or portion; as a quarter of a dollar of a pound of a yard of an hour etc."
"Having four leaves to the sheet; of the form or size of a quarto."

"A form of silica  or silicon dioxide (SiO2) occurring in hexagonal crystals which are commonly colorless and transparent but sometimes also yellow brown purple green and of other colors; also in cryptocrystalline massive forms varying in color and degree of transparency being sometimes opaque."
"A kind of beer. Same as Quass."

"As if; as though; as it were; in a manner sense or degree; having some resemblance to; qualified; -- used as an adjective  or a prefix with a noun or an adjective; as a quasi contract an implied contract an obligation which has arisen from some act as if from a contract; a quasi corporation a body that has some but not all of the peculiar attributes of a corporation; a quasi argument that which resembles or is used as an argument; quasi historical
"A thin  sour beer made by pouring warm water on rye or barley meal and letting it ferment -- much used by the Russians."

"The wood of several tropical American trees of the order Simarubeae  as Quassia amara Picraena excelsa and Simaruba amara. It is intensely bitter and is used in medicine and sometimes as a substitute for hops in making beer."
"The bitter principle of quassia  extracted as a white crystalline substance; -- formerly called quassite."
"A card  die. or domino having four spots or pips"
"A quartet; -- applied chiefly to instrumental compositions."
"A mole  bank or wharf formed toward the sea or at the side of a harbor river or other navigable water for convenience in loading and unloading vessels."
"Yielding or trembling under the feet  as moist or boggy ground; shaking; moving."
"A woman; a young or unmarried woman; a girl."
"Sick at the stomach; affected with nausea; inclined to vomit; qualmish."
"A word occurring in a corrupt passage of Bacon's Essays  and probably meaning to stir to move."
"Like  becoming or suitable to a queen."
"At variance with what is usual or normal; differing in some odd way from what is ordinary; odd; singular; strange; whimsical; as  a queer story or act."
"A killer; as  Jack the Giant Queller."

"To extinguish; to overwhelm; to make an end of; -- said of flame and fire  of things burning and figuratively of sensations and emotions; as to quench flame; to quench a candle; to quench thirst love hate etc."
"A genus of trees constituted by the oak. See Oak."
"A complaint to a court. See Audita Querela."
"To twirl; to turn or wind round; to coil; as  to querl a cord thread or rope."
"A mill for grinding grain  the upper stone of which was turned by hand; -- used before the invention of windmills and watermills."
"The inner or body garments taken together. See Cuerpo."
"A question; an inquiry to be answered or solved."
"The long-tailed  or resplendent trogon (Pharomachus mocinno formerly Trogon resplendens) native of Southern Mexico and Central America. Called also quetzal and golden trogon."
"The act of seeking  or looking after anything; attempt to find or obtain; search; pursuit; as to rove in quest of game of a lost child of property etc."
"An officer who had the management of the public treasure; a receiver of taxes  tribute etc.; treasurer of state."
"A tail-like appendage of hair; a pigtail."
"A shift or turn from the point in question; a trifling or evasive distinction; an evasion; a cavil."
"A small South American opossum (Didelphys quica)  native of Guiana and Brazil. It feeds upon insects small birds and fruit."
"Alive; living; animate; -- opposed to dead or inanimate."
"To make alive; to vivify; to revive or resuscitate  as from death or an inanimate state; hence to excite; to stimulate; to incite."
"Speedily; with haste or celerity; soon; without delay; quick."
"A portion suitable to be chewed; a cud; as  a quid of tobacco."
"To spend time in trifling employments  or to attend to useful subjects in an indifferent or superficial manner; to dawdle."
"To be silent  as a letter; to have no sound."
"In a state of rest or calm; without stir  motion or agitation; still; as a quiet sea; quiet air."
"In a quiet state or manner; without motion; in a state of rest; as  to lie or sit quietly."
"Final discharge or acquittance  as from debt or obligation; that which silences claims; (Fig.) rest; death."
"One of the large feathers of a bird's wing  or one of the rectrices of the tail; also the stock of such a feather."

"Anything that is quilted; esp.  a quilted bed cover or a skirt worn by women; any cover or garment made by putting wool cotton etc. between two cloths and stitching them together; also any outer bed cover."
"A European scallop (Pecten opercularis)  used as food."
"Growing in sets of five; -- said especially of leaves composed of five leaflets set at the end of a common petiole."

"The fruit of a shrub (Cydonia vulgaris) belonging to the same tribe as the apple. It somewhat resembles an apple  but differs in having many seeds in each carpel. It has hard flesh of high flavor but very acid and is largely used for marmalade jelly and preserves."

"Pertaining to  derived from or connected with quinine and related compounds; specifically designating a nonnitrogenous acid obtained from cinchona bark coffee beans etc. as a white crystalline substance."

"An alkaloid extracted from the bark of several species of cinchona (esp. Cinchona Calisaya) as a bitter white crystalline substance  C20H24N2O2. Hence by extension (Med.) any of the salts of this alkaloid as the acetate chloride sulphate etc. employed as a febrifuge or antiperiodic. Called also quinia quinina etc."
"The California salmon (Oncorhynchus choicha); -- called also chouicha  king salmon chinnook salmon and Sacramento salmon. It is of great commercial importance."
"The seeds of a kind of goosewort (Chenopodium Quinoa)  used in Chili and Peru for making porridge or cakes; also food thus made."

"A crystalline substance  C6H4O2 (called also benzoketone) first obtained by the oxidation of quinic acid and regarded as a double ketone; also by extension any one of the series of which quinone proper is the type."
"A radical of which quinone is the hydride  analogous to phenyl."

"An inflammation of the throat  or parts adjacent especially of the fauces or tonsils attended by considerable swelling painful and impeded deglutition and accompanied by inflammatory fever. It sometimes creates danger of suffocation; -- called also squinancy and squinzey."
"A set or sequence of five  as in piquet."
"A hundredweight  either 112 or 100 pounds according to the scale used. Cf. Cental."
"Occurring as the fifth  after four others also occurring every fifth day reckoning inclusively; as a quintan fever."
"A game at cards in which the object is to make fifteen points."
"A smart  sarcastic turn or jest; a taunt; a severe retort; a gibe."

"A contrivance employed by the ancient Peruvians  Mexicans etc. as a substitute for writing and figures consisting of a main cord from which hung at certain distances smaller cords of various colors each having a special meaning as silver gold corn soldiers. etc. Single double
"A sudden turn; a starting from the point or line; hence  an artful evasion or subterfuge; a shift; a quibble; as the quirks of a pettifogger."
"Having  or formed with a quirk or quirks."
"Full of quirks; tricky; as  a quirky lawyer."
"A rawhide whip plaited with two thongs of buffalo hide."
"Any one of numerous species of small passerine birds native of tropical America. See Banana quit  under Banana and Guitguit."
"A chronic abscess  or fistula of the coronet in a horse's foot resulting from inflammation of the tissues investing the coffin bone."
"A riddle or obscure question; an enigma; a ridiculous hoax."
"A quadrangle or court  as of a prison; hence a prison."
"Originally  a solid exterior angle as of a building; now commonly one of the selected pieces of material by which the corner is marked."
"A flattened ring-shaped piece of iron  to be pitched at a fixed object in play; hence any heavy flat missile used for the same purpose as a stone piece of iron etc."
"A marsupial of Australia (Dasyurus macrurus)  about the size of a cat."

"Such a number of the officers or members of any body as is competent by law or constitution to transact business; as  a quorum of the House of Representatives; a constitutional quorum was not present."
"A proportional part or share; the share or proportion assigned to each in a division."
"To cite  as a passage from some author; to name repeat or adduce as a passage from an author or speaker by way of authority or illustration; as to quote a passage from Homer."
"One who quotes the words of another."
"Said; spoke; uttered; -- used only in the first and third persons in the past tenses  and always followed by its nominative the word or words said being the object; as quoth I. quoth he."
"A rod or stick used by masons in mixing hair with mortar."
"A polishing material made of potter's clay that has failed in baking."
"To recover to the fist  as a hawk."
"A kind of ruff for the neck; a turned-down collar; a rebato."
"To cut a rabbet in; to furnish with a rabbet."
"Master; lord; teacher; -- a Jewish title of respect or honor for a teacher or doctor of the law."

"Any of the smaller species of the genus Lepus  especially the common European species (Lepus cuniculus) which is often kept as a pet and has been introduced into many countries. It is remarkably prolific and has become a pest in some parts of Australia and New Zealand."
"An iron bar  with the end bent used in stirring or skimming molten iron in the process of puddling."
"In a rabid manner; with extreme violence."
"A kind of small ordnance formerly in use."
"A rubber of hard wood used in smoothing marble to be polished."
"A term of reproach used by the Jews of our Savior's time  meaning """"worthless."

"A North American nocturnal carnivore (Procyon lotor) allied to the bears  but much smaller and having a long full tail banded with black and gray. Its body is gray varied with black and white. Called also coon and mapach."
"A flower cluster with an elongated axis and many one-flowered lateral pedicels  as in the currant and chokecherry."
"Arranged in a raceme  or in racemes."

"Pertaining to  or designating an acid found in many kinds of grapes. It is also obtained from tartaric acid with which it is isomeric and from sugar gum etc. by oxidation. It is a sour white crystalline substance consisting of a combination of dextrorotatory and levorotatory tartaric acids."
"One who  or that which races or contends in a race; esp. a race horse."
"A dog that pursued his prey by scent  as distinguished from the greyhound."
"Of or pertaining to a race or family of men; as  the racial complexion."

"A thin strip of wood  having the ends brought together forming a somewhat elliptical hoop across which a network of catgut or cord is stretched. It is furnished with a handle and is used for catching or striking a ball in tennis and similar games."
"An old wind instrument of the double bassoon kind  having ventages but not keys."
"Having a strong flavor indicating origin; of distinct characteristic taste; tasting of the soil; hence  fresh; rich."
"A long  flexible stick rod or branch which is interwoven with others between upright posts or stakes in making a kind of hedge or fence."
"Of or pertaining to a radius or ray; consisting of  or like radii or rays; radiated; as (Bot.) radial projections; (Zool.) radial vessels or canals; (Anat.) the radial artery."
"The bone or cartilage of the carpus which articulates with the radius and corresponds to the scaphoid bone in man."
"An arc of a circle which is equal to the radius  or the angle measured by such an arc."
"Emitting or proceeding as from a center; resembling rays; radiating; radiate."
"An extensive artificial group of invertebrates  having all the parts arranged radially around the vertical axis of the body and the various organs repeated symmetrically in each ray or spheromere."
"To emit rays; to be radiant; to shine."
"Of or pertaining to the root; proceeding directly from the root."
"A small branch of a root; a rootlet."
"The rudimentary stem of a plant which supports the cotyledons in the seed  and from which the root is developed downward; the stem of the embryo; the caulicle."
"The barbs of the radii of a feather; barbules."
"The pungent fleshy root of a well-known cruciferous plant (Raphanus sativus); also  the whole plant."
"A right line drawn or extending from the center of a circle to the periphery; the semidiameter of a circle or sphere."
"A primitive word  from which spring other words; a radical; a root; an etymon."
"The chitinous ribbon bearing the teeth of mollusks; -- called also lingual ribbon  and tongue. See Odontophore."
"To sweep  snatch draw or huddle together; to take by a promiscuous sweep."
"A fibrous material used for tying plants  said to come from the leaves of a palm tree of the genus Raphia."
"Resembling  or having the character of raff or a raff; worthless; low."

"A kind of lottery  in which several persons pay in shares the value of something put up as a stake and then determine by chance (as by casting dice) which one of them shall become the sole possessor."
"To scold or rail at; to rate; to tease; to torment; to banter."
"Violent excitement; eager passion; extreme vehemence of desire  emotion or suffering mastering the will."
"A loose overcoat with large sleeves; -- named from Lord Raglan  an English general."
"A man who collects  or deals in rags."
"A dish made of pieces of meat  stewed and highly seasoned; as a ragout of mutton."
"A common American composite weed (Ambrosia artemisiaefolia) with finely divided leaves; hogweed."
"A kind of rubblework. In the United States  any rubblework of thin and small stones."
"A name given to several species of the composite genus Senecio."
"A genus of rays which includes the skates. See Skate."
"The order of elasmobranch fishes which includes the sawfishes  skates and rays; -- called also Rajae and Rajii."
"A hostile or predatory incursion; an inroad or incursion of mounted men; a sudden and rapid invasion by a cavalry force; a foray."
"An outer cloak or covering; a neckerchief for women."
"One who rails; one who scoffs  insults censures or reproaches with opprobrious language."
"A road or way consisting of one or more parallel series of iron or steel rails  patterned and adjusted to be tracks for the wheels of vehicles and suitably supported on a bed or substructure."
"Clothing in general; vesture; garments; -- usually singular in form  with a collective sense."

"A bow or arch exhibiting  in concentric bands the several colors of the spectrum and formed in the part of the hemisphere opposite to the sun by the refraction and reflection of the sun's rays in drops of falling rain."
"Abounding with rain; wet; showery; as  rainy weather; a rainy day or season."
"A rope; also  a measure equal to a rod."
"To cause to rise; to bring from a lower to a higher place; to lift upward; to elevate; to heave; as  to raise a stone or weight."
"One who  or that which raises (in various senses of the verb)."
"A grape  or a bunch of grapes."
"A native prince or king; also  a landholder or person of importance in the agricultural districts."
"A Hindoo of the second  or royal and military caste; a Kshatriya; especially an inhabitant of the country of Rajpootana in northern central India."

"An implement consisting of a headpiece having teeth  and a long handle at right angles to it -- used for collecting hay or other light things which are spread over a large surface or for breaking and smoothing the earth."
"An adventitious sound  usually of morbid origin accompanying the normal respiratory sounds. See Rhonchus."
"To collect  and reduce to order as troops dispersed or thrown into confusion; to gather again; to reunite."
"A name sometimes given to the raven."
"The male of the sheep and allied animals. In some parts of England a ram is called a tup."
"Of or pertaining to a ramus  or branch; rameal."
"To walk  ride or sail from place to place without any determinate object in view; to roam carelessly or irregularly; to rove; to wander; as to ramble about the city; to ramble over the world."
"One who rambles; a rover; a wanderer."
"Having the frames  stem and sternpost adjusted; -- said of a ship on the stocks."
"Thin brownish chaffy scales upon the leaves or young shoots of some plants  especially upon the petioles and leaves of ferns."
"The grass-cloth plant (B/hmeria nivea); also  its fiber which is very fine and exceedingly strong; -- called also China grass and rhea. See Grass-cloth plant under Grass."
"To divide into branches or subdivisions; as  to ramify an art subject scheme."
"A follower of Pierre Rame  better known as Ramus a celebrated French scholar who was professor of rhetoric and philosophy at Paris in the reign of Henry II. and opposed the Aristotelians."
"A line used to get a straight middle line  as on a spar or from stem to stern in building a vessel."
"One who  or that which rams or drives."
"A small West Indian tree (Trophis Americana) of the Mulberry family  whose leaves and twigs are used as fodder for cattle."
"Branched  as the stem or root of a plant; having lateral divisions; consisting of or having branches; full of branches; ramifying; branching; branchy."
"To spring; to leap; to bound; to rear; to prance; to become rampant; hence  to frolic; to romp."
"Violent or riotous behavior; a state of excitement  passion or debauchery; as to be on the rampage."
"Ramping; leaping; springing; rearing upon the hind legs; hence  raging; furious."
"That which fortifies and defends from assault; that which secures safety; a defense or bulwark."
"A plant (Campanula Rapunculus) of the Bellflower family  with a tuberous esculent root; -- also called ramps."
"The rod used in ramming home the charge in a muzzle-loading firearm."
"A broad-leaved species of garlic (Allium ursinum)  common in European gardens; -- called also buckram."
"A yellow-flowered weed; -- so named from a Mr. Ramsted who introduced it into Pennsylvania. See Toad flax. Called also Ramsted weed."
"A small branch  or branchlet of corals hydroids and similar organisms."
"A branch; a projecting part or prominent process; a ramification."
"A genus of anurous batrachians  including the common frogs."
"Having a general affinity to ranunculaceous plants."
"To wrench; to tear; to sprain; to injure by violent straining or contortion."
"A rude hut  as of posts covered with branches or thatch where herdsmen or farm laborers may live or lodge at night."
"Having a rank smell or taste  from chemical change or decomposition; musty; as rancid oil or butter."
"The deepest malignity or spite; deep-seated enmity or malice; inveterate hatred."
"The product of a second sifting of meal; the finest part of the bran."
"The act or process of making and applying rands for shoes."
"To set in a row  or in rows; to place in a regular line or lines or in ranks; to dispose in the proper order; to rank; as to range soldiers in line."
"One who ranges; a rover; sometimes  one who ranges for plunder; a roving robber."
"To range about in an irregular manner."
"A queen or princess; the wife of a rajah."
"Of or pertaining to the frogs and toads."
"Luxuriant in growth; of vigorous growth; exuberant; grown to immoderate height; as  rank grass; rank weeds."
"One who ranks  or disposes in ranks; one who arranges."
"To become  or be rank; to grow rank or strong; to be inflamed; to fester; -- used literally and figuratively."
"With rank or vigorous growth; luxuriantly; hence  coarsely; grossly; as weeds grow rankly."
"To search thoroughly; to search every place or part of; as  to ransack a house."
"The release of a captive  or of captured property by payment of a consideration; redemption; as prisoners hopeless of ransom."
"To rave in violent  high-sounding or extravagant language without dignity of thought; to be noisy boisterous and bombastic in talk or declamation; as a ranting preacher."
"A cyst formed under the tongue by obstruction of the duct of the submaxillary gland."
"A lay or skein containing 120 yards of yarn."
"Fruit  as grapes plucked from the cluster."

"A convulsive disease  attended with ravenous hunger not uncommon in Sweden and Germany. It was so called because supposed to be caused by eating corn with which seeds of jointed charlock (Raphanus raphanistrum) had been mixed but the condition is now known to be a form of ergotism."
"A line  ridge furrow or band of fibers especially in the median line; as the raphe of the tongue."
"Very swift or quick; moving with celerity; fast; as  a rapid stream; a rapid flight; a rapid motion."
"A straight sword  with a narrow and finely pointed blade used only for thrusting."
"The act of plundering; the seizing and carrying away of things by force; spoliation; pillage; plunder."
"The enlargement of a mold caused by rapping the pattern."
"A pungent kind of snuff made from the darker and ranker kinds of tobacco leaves."
"The beat of the drum to call soldiers to arms."
"One who  or that which raps or knocks; specifically the knocker of a door."
"A seizing by violence; a hurrying along; rapidity with violence."
"A dainty morsel; a Welsh rabbit. See Welsh rabbit  under Rabbit."
"To make rare  thin porous or less dense; to expand or enlarge without adding any new portion of matter to; -- opposed to condense."
"In a rare manner or degree; seldom; not often; as  things rarely seen."
"The quality or state of being rare; rareness; thinness; as  the rarity (contrasted with the density) of gases."

"Sweeping; grazing; -- applied to a style of fortification in which the command of the works over each other  and over the country is kept very low in order that the shot may more effectually sweep or graze the ground before them."
"One of the rabble; a low  common sort of person or creature; collectively the rabble; the common herd; also a lean ill-conditioned beast esp. a deer."
"To rub along the surface of; to graze."
"To rub or file with a rasp; to rub or grate with a rough file; as  to rasp wood to make it smooth; to rasp bones to powder."
"One who  or that which rasps; a scraper."
"Like a rasp  or the sound made by a rasp; grating."

"A carnivore (Viverricula Mallaccensis) allied to the civet but smaller  native of China and the East Indies. It furnishes a perfume resembling that of the civet which is highly prized by the Javanese. Called also Malacca weasel and lesser civet."
"The act of rasing  scraping or erasing; erasure; obliteration."

"One of several species of small rodents of the genus Mus and allied genera  larger than mice that infest houses stores and ships especially the Norway or brown rat (M. decumanus) the black rat (M. rattus) and the roof rat (M. Alexandrinus). These were introduced into America from the Old World."
"A New Zealand forest tree (Metrosideros robusta)  also its hard dark red wood used by the Maoris for paddles and war clubs."
"Capable of being rated  or set at a certain value."
"A spirituous liquor flavored with the kernels of cherries  apricots peaches or other fruit spiced and sweetened with sugar; -- a term applied to the liqueurs called noyau cura/ao etc."
"A pawl  click or detent for holding or propelling a ratchet wheel or ratch etc."
"To chide with vehemence; to scold; to censure violently."
"Any carnivore of the genus Mellivora  allied to the weasels and the skunks; -- called also honey badger."
"Coming before others  or before the usual time; early."

"To approve and sanction; to make valid; to confirm; to establish; to settle; especially  to give sanction to as something done by an agent or servant; as to ratify an agreement treaty or contract; to ratify a nomination."

"The relation which one quantity or magnitude has to another of the same kind. It is expressed by the quotient of the division of the first by the second; thus  the ratio of 3 to 6 is expressed by / or /; of a to b by a/b; or (less commonly) the second term is made the dividend; as a:b = b/a."
"A fixed daily allowance of provisions assigned to a soldier in the army  or a sailor in the navy for his subsistence."
"An order of birds in which the wings are small  rudimentary or absent and the breastbone is destitute of a keel. The ostrich emu moa and apteryx are examples."
"The small transverse ropes attached to the shrouds and forming the steps of a rope ladder."

"One of the long slender flexible stems of several species of palms of the genus Calamus  mostly East Indian though some are African and Australian. They are exceedingly tough and are used for walking sticks wickerwork chairs and seats of chairs cords and cordage and many other purposes."
"A thick woolen stuff quilled or twilled."
"To deprive feloniously of the tools used in one's employment (as by breaking or stealing them)  for the purpose of annoying; as to ratten a mechanic who works during a strike."
"One who  or that which rats as one who deserts his party."
"To make a quick succession of sharp  inharmonious noises as by the collision of hard and not very sonorous bodies shaken together; to clatter."
"One of the stems or shoots of sugar cane of the second year's growth from the root  or later. See Plant-cane."
"Harshness of sound; rough utterance; hoarseness; as  the raucity of a trumpet or of the human voice."
"Hoarse; harsh; rough; as  a raucous thick tone."
"Desolation by violence; violent ruin or destruction; devastation; havoc; waste; as  the ravage of a lion; the ravages of fire or tempest; the ravages of an army or of time."
"One who  or that which ravages or lays waste; spoiler."
"To separate or undo the texture of; to take apart; to untwist; to unweave or unknit; -- often followed by out; as  to ravel a twist; to ravel out a stocking."
"A detached work with two embankments which make a salient angle. It is raised before the curtain on the counterscarp of the place. Formerly called demilune  and half-moon."
"A large black passerine bird (Corvus corax)  similar to the crow but larger. It is native of the northern parts of Europe Asia and America and is noted for its sagacity."
"One who  or that which ravens or plunders."
"Food obtained by violence; plunder; prey; raven."
"To seize and carry away by violence; to snatch by force."
"Not altered from its natural state; not prepared by the action of heat; as  raw sienna; specifically not cooked; not changed by heat to a state suitable for eating; not done; as raw meat."
"A specter mentioned to frighten children; as  rawhead and bloodybones."
"A cowhide  or coarse riding whip made of untanned (or raw) hide twisted."
"In a raw manner; unskillfully; without experience."
"The quality or state of being raw."
"A person not a Mohammedan  who pays the capitation tax."
"Destitute of rays; hence  dark; not illuminated; blind; as a rayless sky; rayless eyes."
"A Shakespearean word (used once) supposed to mean the same as race  a root."
"An armed ship having her upper deck cut away  and thus reduced to the next inferior rate as a seventy-four cut down to a frigate."
"A keen-edged knife of peculiar shape  used in shaving the hair from the face or the head."
"The act of erasing or effacing  or the state of being effaced; obliteration. See Rasure."
"A plundering and destructive incursion; a foray; a raid."
"To act or perform a second time; to do over again; as  to react a play; the same scenes were reacted at Rome."
"To admit again; to give entrance or access to again."

"Prepared for what one is about to do or experience; equipped or supplied with what is needed for some act or event; prepared for immediate movement or action; as  the troops are ready to march; ready for the journey."
"A substance capable of producing with another a reaction  especially when employed to detect the presence of other bodies; a test."
"A small Spanish silver coin; also  a denomination of money of account formerly the unit of the Spanish monetary system."
"Arsenic sulphide  a mineral of a brilliant red color; red orpiment. It is also an artificial product."

"As opposed to nominalism  the doctrine that genera and species are real things or entities existing independently of our conceptions. According to realism the Universal exists ante rem (Plato) or in re (Aristotle)."

"One who believes in realism; esp.  one who maintains that generals or the terms used to denote the genera and species of things represent real existences and are not mere names as maintained by the nominalists."
"The state or quality of being real; actual being or existence of anything  in distinction from mere appearance; fact."
"To make real; to convert from the imaginary or fictitious into the actual; to bring into concrete existence; to effectuate; to accomplish; as  to realize a scheme or project."
"A royal jurisdiction or domain; a region which is under the dominion of a king; a kingdom."
"Cream; also  the cream or froth on ale."
"One who  or that which reams; specifically an instrument with cutting or scraping edges used with a twisting motion for enlarging a round hole as the bore of a cannon etc."
"To annex again or anew; to reunite."
"To cut with a sickle  scythe or reaping machine as grain; to gather as a harvest by cutting."

"A thought or a consideration offered in support of a determination or an opinion; a just ground for a conclusion or an action; that which is offered or accepted as an explanation; the efficient cause of an occurrence or a phenomenon; a motive for an action or a determination; proof  more or less decisive for an opinion or a conclusion; principle; efficient cause; final cause; ground of argument."
"Rusty and rancid; -- applied to salt meat."
"Of or pertaining to Rene Antoine Ferchault de Reaumur; conformed to the scale adopted by Reaumur in graduating the thermometer he invented."
"To take away by violence or by stealth; to snatch away; to rob; to despoil; to bereave. [Archaic]"
"To beat to obtuseness; to deprive of keenness; to blunt; to turn back the point of  as a lance used for exercise."
"An instrument formerly used which somewhat resembled the violin  having three strings and being played with a bow."
"Pertaining to rebels or rebellion; acting in revolt; rebellious; as  rebel troops."
"To boil  or to cause to boil again."
"To spring back; to start back; to be sent back or reverberated by elastic force on collision with another body; as  a rebounding echo."
"Repercussion  or beating back; a quick and sudden resistance."
"To build again  as something which has been demolished; to construct anew; as to rebuild a house a wall a wharf or a city."
"To check  silence or put down with reproof; to restrain by expression of disapprobation; to reprehend sharply and summarily; to chide; to reprove; to admonish."

"A mode of expressing words and phrases by pictures of objects whose names resemble those words  or the syllables of which they are composed; enigmatical representation of words by figures; hence a peculiar form of riddle made up of such representations."
"To drive or beat back; to repulse."
"To call back; to summon to return; as  to recall troops; to recall an ambassador."
"To withdraw or repudiate formally and publicly (opinions formerly expressed); to contradict  as a former declaration; to take back openly; to retract; to recall."
"To move back; to retreat; to withdraw."
"To take  as something that is offered given committed sent paid or the like; to accept; as to receive money offered in payment of a debt; to receive a gift a message or a letter."
"The state or quality of being recent; newness; new state; late origin; lateness in time; freshness; as  the recency of a transaction of a wound etc."
"Of late origin  existence or occurrence; lately come; not of remote date antiquated style or the like; not already known familiar worn out trite etc.; fresh; novel; new; modern; as recent news."
"A withdrawing or retiring; a moving back; retreat; as  the recess of the tides."
"To chase again; to chase or drive back."
"A strain given on the horn to call back the hounds when they have lost track of the game."
"A formulary or prescription for making some combination  mixture or preparation of materials; a receipt; especially a prescription for medicine."
"The act of reciting; the repetition of the words of another  or of a document; rehearsal; as the recital of testimony."

"To repeat  as something already prepared written down committed to memory or the like; to deliver from a written or printed document or from recollection; to rehearse; as to recite the words of an author or of a deed or covenant."
"One who recites; also  a book of extracts for recitation."
"To make account of; to care for; to heed; to regard."
"To count; to enumerate; to number; also  to compute; to calculate."
"To claim back; to demand the return of as a right; to attempt to recover possession of."
"To cause or permit to lean  incline rest etc.; to place in a recumbent position; as to recline the head on the hand."
"Shut up; sequestered; retired from the world or from public notice; solitary; living apart; as  a recluse monk or hermit; a recluse life."
"To boil or cook again; hence  to make over; to vamp up; to reconstruct."
"To start  roll bound spring or fall back; to take a reverse motion; to be driven or forced backward; to return."
"To recall to mind; to recollect; to remember; to meditate."
"To retire again to a couch; to lie down again."

"To keep back rightfully (a part)  as if by cutting off so as to diminish a sum due; to take off (a part) from damages; to deduct; as where a landlord recouped the rent of premises from damages awarded to the plaintiff for eviction."
"To repair by fresh supplies  as anything wasted; to remedy lack or deficiency in; as food recruits the flesh; fresh air and exercise recruit the spirits."
"Of or pertaining to the rectum; in the region of the rectum."
"To make or set right; to correct from a wrong  erroneous or false state; to amend; as to rectify errors mistakes or abuses; to rectify the will the judgment opinions; to rectify disorders."
"The province of a rector; a parish church  parsonage or spiritual living with all its rights tithes and glebes."
"The terminal part of the large intestine; -- so named because supposed by the old anatomists to be straight. See Illust. under Digestive."
"A straight muscle; as  the recti of the eye."
"To come back; to return again or repeatedly; to come again to mind."
"To arrive at; to reach; to attain."
"To curve in an opposite or unusual direction; to bend back or down."
"To refuse or reject  as a judge; to challenge that the judge shall not try the cause."
"To reduce to form  as literary matter; to digest and put in shape (matter for publication); to edit."
"A work having two parapets whose faces unite so as to form a salient angle toward the enemy."
"A small ornamental leguminous tree of the American species of the genus Cercis. See Judas tree  under Judas."
"One who wears a red coat; specifically  a red-coated British soldier."
"To make red or somewhat red; to give a red color to."
"To purchase back; to regain possession of by payment of a stipulated price; to repurchase."

"A small North American dace (Minnilus cornutus  or Notropis megalops). The male in the breeding season has bright red fins. Called also red dace and shiner. Applied also to Notropis ardens of the Mississippi valley."
"The blueback salmon of the North Pacific; -- called also nerka. See Blueback (b)."
"Any species of a tribe of butterflies (Fugacia) including the common yellow species and the cabbage butterflies. The antennae are usually red."

"A kind of larva  or nurse which is prroduced within the sporocyst of certain trematodes by asexual generation. It in turn produces in the same way either another generation of rediae or else cercariae within its own body. Called also proscolex and nurse. See Illustration in Appendix."
"The quality or state of being red; red color."

"A small  and usually a roughly constructed fort or outwork of varying shape commonly erected for a temporary purpose and without flanking defenses -- used esp. in fortifying tops of hills and passes and positions in hostile territory."
"To roll back  as a wave or flood; to be sent or driven back; to flow back as a consequence or effect; to conduce; to contribute; to result."
"A Bohemian dance of two kinds  one in triple time like a waltz the other in two-four time like a polka. The former is most in use."

"Any one of several species of small northern finches of the genus Acanthis (formerly Aegiothus)  native of Europe and America. The adults have the crown red or rosy. The male of the most common species (A. linarius) has also the breast and rump rosy. Called also redpoll linnet. See Illust. under Linnet."
"To draw again; to make a second draft or copy of; to redraft."

"A name of several plants having red roots  as the New Jersey tea (see under Tea) the gromwell the bloodroot and the Lachnanthes tinctoria an endogenous plant found in sandy swamps from Rhode Island to Florida."
"To be brittle when red-hot; to be red-short."
"A common appellation for a North American Indian; -- so called from the color of the skin."

"A kind of grass (Agrostis vulgaris) highly valued in the United States for pasturage and hay for cattle; -- called also English grass  and in some localities herd's grass. See Illustration in Appendix. The tall redtop is Triodia seslerioides."
"To refit; to repair  or make reparation for; hence to repay or requite."
"To bring or lead back to any former place or condition."
"A central or retired work within any other work."
"Any hemipterous insect of the genus Redivius  or family Reduvidae. They live by sucking the blood of other insects and some species also attack man."

"A European thrush (Turdus iliacus). Its under wing coverts are orange red. Called also redwinged thrush. (b) A North American passerine bird (Agelarius ph/niceus) of the family Icteridae. The male is black  with a conspicuous patch of bright red bordered with orange on each wing. Called also redwinged blackbird red-winged troupial marsh blackbird and swamp blackbird."
"A gigantic coniferous tree (Sequoia sempervirens) of California  and its light and durable reddish timber. See Sequoia."
"To echo back; to reverberate again; as  the hills reecho the roar of cannon."
"To edify anew; to build again after destruction."
"A small convex molding; a reed (see Illust. (i) of Molding); one of several set close together to decorate a surface; also  decoration by means of reedings; -- the reverse of fluting."
"A chain or range of rocks lying at or near the surface of the water. See Coral reefs  under Coral."
"One who reefs; -- a name often given to midshipmen."
"Soiled with smoke or steam; smoky; foul."
"A lively dance of the Highlanders of Scotland; also  the music to the dance; -- often called Scotch reel."
"To elect again; as  to reelect the former governor."
"The Hebrew name of a horned wild animal  probably the Urus."
"A second or new entry; as  a reentry into public life."
"To restore after hunger or fatigue; to refresh."
"To refute; to disprove; as  to refel the tricks of a sophister."
"One to whom a thing is referred; a person to whom a matter in dispute has been referred  in order that he may settle it."
"To find again; to get or experience again."

"To reduce to a fine  unmixed or pure state; to free from impurities; to free from dross or alloy; to separate from extraneous matter; to purify; to defecate; as to refine gold or silver; to refine iron; to refine wine or sugar."
"To fit or prepare for use again; to repair; to restore after damage or decay; as  to refit a garment; to refit ships of war."
"To fix again or anew; to establish anew."
"To bend back; to give a backwa/d turn to; to throw back; especially  to cause to return after striking upon any surface; as a mirror reflects rays of light; polished metals reflect heat."
"Directed back; attended by reflection; retroactive; introspective."
"Returning  or flowing back; reflex; as reflux action."
"To forge again or anew; hence  to fashion or fabricate anew; to make over."

"To put into a new and improved form or condition; to restore to a former good state  or bring from bad to good; to change from worse to better; to amend; to correct; as to reform a profligate man; to reform corrupt manners or morals."
"To bend sharply and abruptly back; to break off."
"To hold back; to restrain; to keep within prescribed bounds; to curb; to govern."

"To make fresh again; to restore strength  spirit animation or the like to; to relieve from fatigue or depression; to reinvigorate; to enliven anew; to reanimate; as sleep refreshes the body and the mind."
"Shelter or protection from danger or distress."
"One who flees to a shelter  or place of safety."
"To fund again or anew; to replace (a fund or loan) by a new fund; as  to refund a railroad loan."
"The act of refusing; denial of anything demanded  solicited or offered for acceptance."
"To deny  as a request demand invitation or command; to decline to do or grant."

"To disprove and overthrow by argument  evidence or countervailing proof; to prove to be false or erroneous; to confute; as to refute arguments; to refute testimony; to refute opinions or theories; to refute a disputant."
"To gain anew; to get again; to recover  as what has escaped or been lost; to reach again."
"Of or pertaining to a king; kingly; royal; as  regal authority pomp or sway."
"That which belongs to royalty. Specifically: (a) The rights and prerogatives of a king. (b) Royal estates and revenues. (c) Ensings  symbols or paraphernalia of royalty."
"To keep in view; to behold; to look at; to view; to gaze upon."
"Originally  a gondola race in Venice; now a rowing or sailing race or a series of such races."
"The office of ruler; rule; authority; government."
"An upholder of kingly authority; a royalist."
"Mode or system of rule or management; character of government  or of the prevailing social system."

"One of the grand districts or quarters into which any space or surface  as of the earth or the heavens is conceived of as divided; hence in general a portion of space or territory of indefinite extent; country; province; district; tract."
"Of or pertaining to a king; royal."

"A flat  narrow molding used chiefly to separate the parts or members of compartments or panels from one another or doubled turned and interlaced so as to form knots frets or other ornaments. See Illust. (12) of Column."
"A kind of dry fruit  consisting of three or more cells each which at length breaks open at the inner angle."
"Of or pertaining to the reign of a monarch; as  regnal years."
"Exercising regal authority; reigning; as  a queen regnant."
"To vomit up; to eject from the stomach; to throw back."
"To grant back; to grant again or anew."
"To remove the outer surface of  as of an old hewn stone so as to give it a fresh appearance."
"To go back; to retrograde  as the apsis of a planet's orbit."
"To greet again; to resalute; to return a salutation to; to greet."
"The act of passing back; passage back; return; retrogression. """"The progress or regress of man""""."

"Pain of mind on account of something done or experienced in the past  with a wish that it had been different; a looking back with dissatisfaction or with longing; grief; sorrow; especially a mourning on account of the loss of some joy advantage or satisfaction."

"Conformed to a rule; agreeable to an established rule  law principle or type or to established customary forms; normal; symmetrical; as a regular verse in poetry; a regular piece of music; a regular verb; regular practice of law or medicine; a regular building."
"A petty king; a ruler of little power or consequence."
"To hash over again; to prepare or use again; as  to rehash old arguments."
"To hear again; to try a second time; as  to rehear a cause in Chancery."
"A portuguese money of account  in value about one tenth of a cent."
"A hollow cut or channel for quiding anything; as  the reigle of a side post for a flood gate."
"Royal authority; supreme power; sovereignty; rule; dominion."
"A strip of oxhide  deprived of hair and rendered pliable -- used for twisting into ropes etc."
"The strap of a bridle  fastened to the curb or snaffle on each side by which the rider or driver governs the horse."
"The kidneys; also  the region of the kidneys; the loins."
"A German cavalry soldier of the fourteenth and fifteenth centuries."
"To cast from one; to throw away; to discard."
"To feel joy; to experience gladness in a high degree; to have pleasurable satisfaction; to be delighted."
"To join again; to unite after separation."
"To reunite the joints of; to joint anew."
"A reacting jolt or shock; a rebound or recoil."
"To judge again; to reexamine; to review; to call to a new trial and decision."
"A narrow space between the foot of the rampart and the scarp of the ditch  serving to receive the earth that may crumble off or be washed down and prevent its falling into the ditch."
"To land again; to put on land  as that which had been shipped or embarked."
"To slip or slide back  in a literal sense; to turn back."
"To make lax or loose; to make less close  firm rigid tense or the like; to slacken; to loosen; to open; as to relax a rope or cord; to relax the muscles or sinews."
"To lay again; to lay a second time; as  to relay a pavement."
"The roots of the Chilian plant Calceolaria arachnoidea  -- used for dyeing crimson."
"To lease again; to grant a new lease of; to let back."
"To become less rigid or hard; to yield; to dissolve; to melt; to deliquesce."
"Having  or characterized by reliance; confident; trusting."
"That which remains; that which is left after loss or decay; a remaining portion; a remnant."
"A woman whose husband is dead; a widow."

"The act of relieving  or the state of being relieved; the removal or partial removal of any evil or of anything oppressive or burdensome by which some ease is obtained; succor; alleviation; comfort; ease; redress."
"To lift up; to raise again  as one who has fallen; to cause to rise."
"To taste or eat with pleasure; to like the flavor of; to partake of with gratification; hence  to enjoy; to be pleased with or gratified by; to experience pleasure from; as to relish food."
"A second lending of the same thing; a renewal of a loan."
"To strive or struggle against anything; to make resistance; to draw back; to feel or show repugnance or reluctance."

"To rest with confidence  as when fully satisfied of the veracity integrity or ability of persons or of the certainty of facts or of evidence; to have confidence; to trust; to depend; -- with on formerly also with in."

"To stay behind while others withdraw; to be left after others have been removed or destroyed; to be left after a number or quantity has been subtracted or cut off; to be left as not included or comprised."
"A case for trial which can not be tried during the term; a postponed case."
"To mark in a notable manner; to distinquish clearly; to make noticeable or conspicuous; to piont out."
"To furnish with a new mast or set of masts."
"Earth or materials made into a bank after having been excavated."
"To give meaning to; to explain the meaning of; to interpret."
"That which relieves or cures a disease; any medicine or application which puts an end to disease and restores health; -- with for; as  a remedy for the gout."
"The quill feathers of the wings of a bird."
"To put (one) in mind of something; to bring to the remembrance of; to bring to the notice or consideration of (a person)."
"Having feet or legs that are used as oars; -- said of certain crustaceans and insects."
"To send  give or grant back; to release a claim to; to resign or surrender by deed; to return."

"Not energetic or exact in duty or business; not careful or prompt in fulfilling engagements; negligent; careless; tardy; behindhand; lagging; slack; hence  lacking earnestness or activity; languid; slow."
"To send back; to give up; to surrender; to resign."
"To model or fashion anew; to change the form of."
"To mold or shape anew or again; to reshape."
"The anguish  like gnawing pain excited by a sense of guilt; compunction of conscience for a crime committed or for the sins of one's past life."
"Removed to a distance; not near; far away; distant; -- said in respect to time or to place; as  remote ages; remote lands."
"The act of removing  or the state of being removed."
"To move away from the position occupied; to cause to change place; to displace; as  to remove a building."
"One who removes; as  a remover of landmarks."
"Of or pertaining to the kidneys; in the region of the kidneys."
"A fox; -- so called in fables or familiar tales  and in poetry."
"To separate into parts with force or sudden violence; to tear asunder; to split; to burst; as  powder rends a rock in blasting; lightning rends an oak."
"To nerve again; to give new vigor to; to reinvigorate."
"To make new again; to restore to freshness  perfection or vigor; to give new life to; to rejuvenate; to re/stablish; to recreate; to rebuild."
"The act of renewing  or the state of being renewed; as the renewal of a treaty."
"To plunder; -- only in the phrase """"to rape and renne."""" See under Rap  v. t. to snatch."
"A name of many different kinds of apples. Cf. Reinette."
"A milk-clotting enzyme obtained from the true stomach (abomasum) of a suckling calf. Mol. wt. about 31 000. Also called chymosin rennase and abomasal enzyme."
"The state of being much known and talked of; exalted reputation derived from the extensive praise of great achievements or accomplishments; fame; celebrity; -- always in a good sense."
"A schedule  account or list of rents with the names of the tenants etc.; a rent roll."
"In France  interest payable by government on indebtedness; the bonds shares stocks etc. which represent government indebtedness."
"One who rents or leases an estate; -- usually said of a lessee or tenant."
"One who has a fixed income  as from lands stocks or the like."
"A fabric made of silk or wool  or of silk and wool and having a transversely corded or ribbed surface."
"To pace again; to walk over again in a contrary direction."
"To pack a second time or anew; as  to repack beef; to repack a trunk."
"To paint anew or again; as  to repaint a house; to repaint the ground of a picture."
"Having a slightly undulating margin; -- said of leaves."
"A change of apparel; a second or different suit."
"To pass again; to pass or travel over in the opposite direction; to pass a second time; as  to repass a bridge or a river; to repass the sea."
"To pay back; to refund; as  to repay money borrowed or advanced."
"To recall; to summon again  as persons."
"To go over again; to attempt  do make or utter again; to iterate; to recite; as to repeat an effort an order or a poem."
"To drive back; to force to return; to check the advance of; to repulse as  to repel an enemy or an assailant."
"To place again; to restore to a former place  position condition or the like."
"To plait or fold again; to fold  as one part over another again and again."
"Filled again; completely filled; full; charged; abounding."

"To take or get back  by a writ for that purpose (goods and chattels wrongfully taken or detained) upon giving security to try the right to them in a suit at law and if that should be determined against the plaintiff to return the property replevied."
"A copy of a work of art  as of a picture or statue made by the maker of the original."
"The framework of some pods  as the cress which remains after the valves drop off."
"To make a return in words or writing; to respond; to answer."
"The act or state of reposing; as  the reposal of a trust."
"To cause to stop or to rest after motion; hence  to deposit; to lay down; to lodge; to reposit."
"To cause to rest or stay; to lay away; to lodge  as for safety or preservation; to place; to store."
"To print again; to print a second or a new edition of."
"Creeping; moving on the belly  or by means of small and short legs."
"To fight against; to oppose; to resist."
"To repel; to beat or drive back; as  to repulse an assault; to repulse the enemy."
"To hold in thought; to account; to estimate; to hold; to think; to reckon."
"The act of asking for anything desired; expression of desire or demand; solicitation; prayer; petition; entreaty."
"A mass said or sung for the repose of a departed soul."
"The man-eater  or white shark (Carcharodon carcharias); -- so called on account of its causing requiems to be sung."
"To demand; to insist upon having; to claim as by right and authority; to exact; as  to require the surrender of property."
"To repay; in a good sense  to recompense; to return (an equivalent) in good; to reward; in a bad sense to retaliate; to return (evil) for evil; to punish."
"A screen or partition wall behind an altar."
"To sail again; also  to sail back as to a former port."
"A sale at second hand  or at retail; also a second sale."
"To saw again; specifically  to saw a balk or a timber which has already been squared into dimension lumber as joists boards etc."
"To cut off; to abrogate; to annul."

"To free or deliver from any confinement  violence danger or evil; to liberate from actual restraint; to remove or withdraw from a state of exposure to evil; as to rescue a prisoner from the enemy; to rescue seamen from destruction."
"To seat or set again  as on a chair throne etc."
"To cut or pare off; to remove by cutting."
"A genus of plants  the type of which is mignonette."
"To seize again  or a second time."
"To sell again; to sell what has been bought or sold; to retail."
"To send again; as  to resend a message."
"To keep back; to retain; not to deliver  make over or disclose."
"To set again; as  to reset type; to reset copy; to reset a diamond."
"To ship again; to put on board of a vessel a second time; to send on a second voyage; as  to reship bonded merchandise."
"To dwell permanently or for a considerable time; to have a settled abode for a time; to abide continuosly; to have one's domicile of home; to remain for a long time."
"That which remains after a part is taken  separated removed or designated; remnant; remainder."

"To sign back; to return by a formal act; to yield to another; to surrender; -- said especially of office or emolument. Hence  to give up; to yield; to submit; -- said of the wishes or will or of something valued; -- also often used reflexively."
"To start back; to recoil; to recede from a purpose."

"Any one of a class of yellowish brown solid inflammable substances  of vegetable origin which are nonconductors of electricity have a vitreous fracture and are soluble in ether alcohol and essential oils but not in water; specif. pine resin (see Rosin)."
"Pertaining to  or obtained from resin; as the resinic acids."
"To stand against; to withstand; to obstruct."
"To separate the component parts of; to reduce to the constituent elements; -- said of compound substances; hence  sometimes to melt or dissolve."
"To sound loudly; as  his voice resounded far."
"To take notice of; to regard with special attention; to regard as worthy of special consideration; hence  to care for; to heed."
"To take breath again; hence  to take rest or refreshment."
"A putting off of that which was appointed; a postponement or delay."
"To say somethin in return; to answer; to reply; as  to respond to a question or an argument."
"To force back against the current; as  to restem their backward course."
"Unwilling to go on; obstinate in refusing to move forward; stubborn; drawing back."
"To bring back to its former state; to bring back from a state of ruin  decay disease or the like; to repair; to renew; to recover."
"Disposed to rest; indisposed toexercton; sluggish; also  restive."
"A summing up; a condensed statement; an abridgment or brief recapitulation."
"A shelf behind the altar  for display of lights vases of wlowers etc."
"The sale of commodities in small quantities or parcels; -- opposed to wholesale; sometimes  the sale of commodities at second hand."
"To continue to hold; to keep in possession; not to lose  part with or dismiss; to retrain from departure escape or the like."
"One who takes again what has been taken; a recaptor."

"To keep delaying; to continue to hinder; to prevent from progress; to render more slow in progress; to impede; to hinder; as  to retard the march of an army; to retard the motion of a ship; -- opposed to accelerate."
"To make an effort to vomit; to strain  as in vomiting."
"A net or network; a plexus; particularly  a network of blood vessels or nerves or a part resembling a network."
"A white crystalline hydrocarbon  polymeric with benzene. It is extracted from pine tar and is also found in certain fossil resins."
"Any spider which spins webs to catch its prey."
"The delicate membrane by which the back part of the globe of the eye is lined  and in which the fibers of the optic nerve terminate. See Eye."
"Of or pertaining to resin; derived from resin; specifically  designating an acid found in certain fossil resins and hydrocarbons."
"A hydrocarbon oil obtained by the distillation of resin  -- used in printer's ink."
"The body of retainers who follow a prince or other distinguished person; a train of attendants; a suite."
"A bird having small polygonal scales covering the tarsi."
"To withdraw; to take away; -- sometimes used reflexively."
"To bend or curve back; as  a retorted line."
"To touch again  or rework in order to improve; to revise; as to retouch a picture or an essay."
"To draw back; to draw up or shorten; as  the cat can retract its claws; to retract a muscle."
"The act of retiring or withdrawing one's self  especially from what is dangerous or disagreeable."
"A secdond trial  experiment or test; a second judicial trial as of an accused person."
"To try (esp. judicially) a second time; as  to retry a case; to retry an accused person."
"A place or establishment where flax is retted. See Ret."
"The act or process of preparing flax for use by soaking  maceration and kindred processes; -- also called rotting. See Ret."
"To blunt; to turn  as an edge; figuratively to cause to be obtuse or dull; as to retund confidence."
"To turn back; to go or come again to the same place or condition."
"Having the end rounded and slightly indented; as  a retuse leaf."
"A second union; union formed anew after separation  secession or discord; as a reunion of parts or particles of matter; a reunion of parties or sects."
"To unite again; to join after separation or variance."
"To vamp again; hence  to patch up; to reconstruct."
"To make known (that which has been concealed or kept secret); to unveil; to disclose; to show."
"The act of engaging in a revel; noisy festivity; reveling."

"To inflict harm in return for  as an injury insult etc.; to exact satisfaction for under a sense of injury; to avenge; -- followed either by the wrong received or by the person or thing wronged as the object or by the reciprocal pronoun as direct object and a preposition before the wrong done or the wrongdoer."
"That which returns  or comes back from an investment; the annual rents profits interest or issues of any species of property real or personal; income."
"To regard with reverence  or profound respect and affection mingled with awe or fear; to venerate; to reverence; to honor in estimation."
"A loose or irregular train of thought occurring in musing or mediation; deep musing; daydream."
"Turned backward; having a contrary or opposite direction; hence; opposite or contrary in kind; as  the reverse order or method."
"To turn back  or to the contrary; to reverse."
"To clothe again; to cover  as with a robe; to robe."
"To face  as an embankment with masonry wood or other material."
"To vie with  or rival in return."
"To view or see again; to look back on."
"To address or abuse with opprobrious and contemptuous language; to reproach."
"The act of revising  or reviewing and reexamining for correction and improvement; revision; as the revisal of a manuscript; the revisal of a proof sheet; the revisal of a treaty."
"To look at again for the detection of errors; to reexamine; to review; to look over with care for correction; as  to revise a writing; to revise a translation."
"The act of reviving  or the state of being revived."
"To return to life; to recover life or strength; to live anew; to become reanimated or reinvigorated."
"Revival of a suit which is abated by the death or marriage of any of the parties  -- done by a bill of revivor."
"To refurnish with a voice; to refit  as an organ pipe so as to restore its tone."
"To call or bring back; to recall."
"To turn away; to abandon or reject something; specifically  to turn away or shrink with abhorrence."
"To turn or roll round on  or as on an axis like a wheel; to rotate -- which is the more specific word in this sense."
"To give in return  whether good or evil; -- commonly in a good sense; to requite; to recompense; to repay; to compensate."
"To repeat in the same words; to reecho."
"An appelation applied after the manner of a proper name to the fox. Same as Renard."
"One of numerous minute rodlike structures formed of two or more cells situated behind the retinulae in the compound eyes of insects  etc. See Illust. under Ommatidium."
"Pertaining to  or of the same horizon as certain Mesozoic strata of the Rhetian Alps. These strata are regarded as closing the Triassic period. See the Chart of Geology."
"A genus of shrubs and small trees; buckthorn. The California Rhamnus Purshianus and the European R. catharticus are used in medicine. The latter is used for hedges."
"The continuation of the seed stalk along the side of an anatropous ovule or seed  forming a ridge or seam."
"The ramie or grass-cloth plant. See Grass-cloth plant  under Grass."
"A suborder of struthious birds including the rheas."
"Pertaining to  or designating an acid (commonly called chrysophanic acid) found in rhubarb (Rheum)."
"Of or pertaining to Rheimis  or Reima in France."
"Of or pertaining to the river Rhine; as  Rhenish wine."
"Pertaining to the ancient Rhaeti  or Rhaetians or to Rhaetia their country; as the Rhetian Alps now the country of Tyrol and the Grisons."
"Of or pertaining to rheum; abounding in  or causing rheum; affected with rheum."
"Og or pertaining to the nose or olfactory organs."
"A rootlike filament or hair growing from the stems of mosses or on lichens; a rhizoid."
"Of or pertaining to Rhodes  an island of the Mediterranean."
"Of or pertaining to rhodium; containing rhodium."

"A rare element of the light platinum group. It is found in platinum ores  and obtained free as a white inert metal which it is very difficult to fuse. Symbol Rh. Atomic weight 104.1. Specific gravity 12."

"An equilateral parallelogram  or quadrilateral figure whose sides are equal and the opposite sides parallel. The angles may be unequal two being obtuse and two acute as in the cut or the angles may be equal in which case it is usually called a square."
"The name of several large perennial herbs of the genus Rheum and order Polygonaceae."
"A line which crosses successive meridians at a constant angle; -- called also rhumb line  and loxodromic curve. See Loxodromic."
"A genus of shrubs and small treets. See Sumac."
"A mixtire of caustic lime and orpiment  or tersulphide of arsenic -- used in the depilation of hides."
"An expression of thought in numbers  measure or verse; a composition in verse; a rhymed tale; poetry; harmony of language."
"One who makes rhymes; a versifier; -- generally in contempt; a poor poet; a poetaster."
"The art or habit of making rhymes; rhyming; -- in contempt."
"In the widest sense  a dividing into short portions by a regular succession of motions impulses sounds accents etc. producing an agreeable effect as in music poetry the dance or the like."
"Laughing; laughable; exciting gayety; gay; merry; delightful to the view  as a landscape."
"One of the curved bones attached to the vertebral column and supporting the lateral walls of the thorax."
"A low  vulgar brutal foul-mouthed wretch; a lewd fellow."
"A fillet or narrow woven fabric  commonly of silk used for trimming some part of a woman's attire for badges and other decorative purposes."
"A genus of shrubs including gooseberries and currants of many kinds."
"A sort of stringed instrument; a rebec."
"A species of plantain (Plantago lanceolata) with long  narrow ribbed leaves; -- called also rib grass ripple grass ribwort plantain."

"A well-known cereal grass (Oryza sativa) and its seed. This plant is extensively cultivated in warm climates  and the grain forms a large portion of the food of the inhabitants. In America it grows chiefly on low moist land which can be overflowed."
"Having an abundance of material possessions; possessed of a large amount of property; well supplied with land  goods or money; wealthy; opulent; affluent; -- opposed to poor."
"That which makes one rich; an abundance of land  goods money or other property; wealth; opulence; affluence."
"Pertaining to  or derived from castor oil; formerly designating an acid now called ricinoleic acid."

"A genus of plants of the Spurge family  containing but one species (R. communis) the castor-oil plant. The fruit is three-celled and contains three large seeds from which castor oil iss expressed. See Palma Christi."
"A stack or pile  as of grain straw or hay in the open air usually protected from wet with thatching."
"A stout pole for use in making a rick  or for a spar to a boat."

"A disease which affects children  and which is characterized by a bulky head crooked spine and limbs depressed ribs enlarged and spongy articular epiphyses tumid abdomen and short stature together with clear and often premature mental faculties. The essential cause of the disease appears to be the nondeposition of earthy salts in the osteoid tissues. Children afflicted with this malady stand and walk unsteadily. Called also rachitis."
"Of or pertaining to the rictus; as  rictal bristles."
"The gape of the mouth  as of birds; -- often resricted to the corners of the mouth."
"imp. & p. p. of Ride  v. i."
"Suitable for riding; as  a ridable horse; a ridable road."
"A sieve with coarse meshes  usually of wire for separating coarser materials from finer as chaff from grain cinders from ashes or gravel from sand."
"To be carried on the back of an animal  as a horse."
"A small mound of earth; ground slightly elevated; a small ridge."
"The back  or top of the back; a crest."
"Having a ridge or ridges; rising in a ridge."
"A favorite Italian public entertainment  consisting of music and dancing -- held generally on fast eves."

"The reedbuck  a South African antelope (Cervicapra arundinacea); -- so called from its frequenting dry places covered with high grass or reeds. Its color is yellowish brown. Called also inghalla and rietbok."

"A trough or sluice having cleats  grooves or steps across the bottom for holding quicksilver and catching particles of gold when auriferous earth is washed; also one of the cleats grooves or steps in such a trough. Also called ripple."
"A curved file used in carving wool and marble."
"To seize and bear away by force; to snatch away; to carry off."
"A fixed star of the first magnitude in the left foot of the constellation Orion."
"One who rigs or dresses; one whose occupation is to fit the rigging of a ship."
"Straight; direct; not crooked; as  a right line."
"One who sets right; one who does justice or redresses wrong."
"Firm; stiff; unyielding; not pliant; not flexible."
"A musical instrument formerly in use  consisting of several sticks bound together but separated by beads and played with a stick with a ball at its end."
"To render turbid or muddy; to stir up; to roil."
"One of certain narrow  crooked valleys seen by aid of the telescope on the surface of the moon."
"The border  edge or margin of a thing usually of something circular or curving; as the rim of a kettle or basin."
"A narrow and elongated aperture; a cleft; a fissure."
"A short cylinder connecting a trunnion with the body of a cannon. See Illust. of Cannon."
"A rent or long aperture; a chink; a fissure; a crack."
"An implement for cutting  trimming or ornamenting the rim of anything as the edges of pies etc.; also a reamer."
"The external covering or coat  as of flesh fruit trees etc.; skin; hide; bark; peel; shell."
"To cause to sound  especially by striking as a metallic body; as to ring a bell."
"Having the lips widely separated and gaping like an open mouth; as a ringent bilabiate corolla."
"One who  or that which rings; especially one who rings chimes on bells."
"A small ring; a small circle; specifically  a fairy ring."
"The smooth and level extent of ice marked off for the game of curling."
"To wash lightly; to cleanse with a second or repeated application of water after washing."
"One who riots; a reveler; a roisterer."
"Involving  or engaging in riot; wanton; unrestrained; luxurious."
"The act or practice of rioting; riot."
"To grow ripe; to become mature  as grain fruit flowers and the like; as grapes ripen in the sun."
"Filling up; supplementary; supernumerary; -- a term applied to those instruments which only swell the mass or tutti of an orchestra  but are not obbligato."
"One who brings fish from the seacoast to markets in inland towns."
"In fencing  a return thrust after a parry."
"An implement  with teeth like those of a comb for removing the seeds and seed vessels from flax broom corn etc."
"Having ripples; as  ripply water; hence resembling the sound of rippling water; as ripply laughter; a ripply cove."
"A foundation or sustaining wall of stones thrown together without order  as in deep water or on a soft bottom."
"A handsaw with coarse teeth which have but a slight set  used for cutting wood in the direction of the fiber; -- called also ripping saw."

"To move from a lower position to a higher; to ascend; to mount up. Specifically: -- (a) To go upward by walking  climbing flying or any other voluntary motion; as a bird rises in the air; a fish rises to the bait."
"One who rises; as  an early riser."
"Having the faculty or power of laughing; disposed to laugh."
"Hazard; danger; peril; exposure to loss  injury or destruction."
"Any one of very numerous species of small spiral gastropods of the genus Rissoa  or family Rissoidae found both in fresh and salt water."
"A small ball of rich minced meat or fish  covered with pastry and fried."
"3d pers. sing. pres. of Rise  contracted from riseth."
"3d pers. sing. pres. of Ride  contracted from rideth."
"The act of performing divine or solemn service  as established by law precept or custom; a formal act of religion or other solemn duty; a solemn observance; a ceremony; as the rites of freemasonry."
"Of or pertaining to rites or ritual; as  ritual service or sacrifices; the ritual law."
"A person having a common right or privilege with another; a partner."
"The act of rivaling  or the state of being a rival; a competition."
"To rend asunder by force; to split; to cleave; as  to rive timber for rails or shingles."
"To contract into wrinkles; to shrivel; to shrink; as  riveled fruit; riveled flowers."
"Supplied with rivers; as  a well rivered country."

"A metallic pin with a head  used for uniting two plates or pieces of material together by passing it through them and then beating or pressing down the point so that it shall spread out and form a second head; a pin or bolt headed or clinched at both ends."
"A small stream or brook; a streamlet."
"To dry in the sun; as  rizzared haddock."
"A journey  or stage of a journey."
"In railroads  the bed or foundation on which the superstructure (ties rails etc.) rests; in common roads the whole material laid in place and ready for travel."
"A road; especially  the part traveled by carriages."
"To go from place to place without any certain purpose or direction; to rove; to wander."
"Having a bay  chestnut brown or black color with gray or white thickly interspersed; -- said of a horse."
"To cry with a full  loud continued sound."
"To cook by exposure to radiant heat before a fire; as  to roast meat on a spit or in an oven open toward the fire and having reflecting surfaces within; also to cook in a close oven."
"The inspissated juice of ripe fruit  obtained by evaporation of the juice over a fire till it acquires the consistence of a sirup. It is sometimes mixed with honey or sugar."
"One who robs; in law  one who feloniously takes goods or money from the person of another by violence or by putting him in fear."
"The act or practice of robbing; theft."
"A kind of package in which pepper and other dry commodities are sometimes exported from the East Indies. The robbin of rice in Malabar weighs about 84 pounds."
"An outer garment; a dress of a rich  flowing and elegant style or make; hence a dress of state rank office or the like."
"A small European singing bird (Erythacus rubecula)  having a reddish breast; -- called also robin redbreast robinet and ruddock."
"A genus of leguminous trees including the common locust of North America (Robinia Pseudocacia)."
"Evincing strength; indicating vigorous health; strong; sinewy; muscular; vigorous; sound; as  a robust body; robust youth; robust health."
"A linen garment resembling the surplise  but with narrower sleeves also without sleeves worn by bishops and by some other ecclesiastical dignitaries in certain religious ceremonies."
"One who rocks; specifically  one who rocks a cradle."
"A mound formed of fragments of rock  earth etc. and set with plants."
"A cruciferous plant (Eruca sativa) sometimes eaten in Europe as a salad."
