"Full of  or abounding in rocks; consisting of rocks; as a rocky mountain; a rocky shore."
"The orange-colored pulp covering the seeds of the tropical plant Bixa Orellana  from which annotto is prepared. See Annoto."
"A florid style of ornamentation which prevailed in Europe in the latter part of the eighteenth century."
"A straight and slender stick; a wand; hence  any slender bar as of wood or metal (applied to various purposes)."
"Gnawing; biting; corroding; (Med.) applied to a destructive variety of cancer or ulcer."
"One who carries and holds a leveling staff  or rod in a surveying party."

"A small European and Asiatic deer (Capreolus capraea) having erect  cylindrical branched antlers forked at the summit. This the smallest European deer is very nimble and graceful. It always prefers a mountainous country or high grounds."
"A vagrant; an idle  sturdy beggar; a vagabond; a tramp."
"To render turbid by stirring up the dregs or sediment of; as  to roil wine cider etc. in casks or bottles; to roil a spring."
"To bluster; to swagger; to bully; to be bold  noisy vaunting or turbulent."
"Parched Indian corn  pounded up and mixed with sugar; -- called also yokeage."
"A part  or character performed by an actor in a drama; hence a part of function taken or assumed by any one; as he has now taken the role of philanthropist."
"To cause to revolve by turning over and over; to move by turning on an axis; to impel forward by causing to turn over and over on a supporting surface; as  to roll a wheel a ball or a barrel."
"One who  or that which rolls; especially a cylinder sometimes grooved of wood stone metal etc. used in husbandry and the arts."
"A small wagon used for the underground work of a mine."
"To move or play in a careless  swaggering manner with a frolicsome air; to frolic; to sport; commonly in the form rollicking."
"A place prepared for rolling logs into a stream."
"Of or relating to modern Greece  and especially to its language."
"Of or pertaining to Rome  or the Roman people; like or characteristic of Rome the Roman people or things done by Romans; as Roman fortitude; a Roman aqueduct; Roman art."

"A species of fictitious writing  originally composed in meter in the Romance dialects and afterward in prose such as the tales of the court of Arthur and of Amadis of Gaul; hence any fictitious and wonderful tale; a sort of novel especially one which treats of surprising adventures usually befalling a hero or a heroine; a tale of extravagant adventures of love and the like."
"Of or pertaining to Rome or its people."
"A romantic story in verse; as  the """"Romaunt of the Rose."
"A mineral of a hyacinth or honey-yellow color  occuring in square octahedrons. It is an antimonate of calcium."

"A method of notation for all spoken sounds  proposed by Mr. Sweet; -- so called because it is based on the common Roman-letter alphabet. It is like the palaeotype of Mr. Ellis in the general plan but simpler."
"Belonging or relating to Rome  or to the Roman Catholic Church; -- frequently used in a disparaging sense; as the Romish church; the Romish religion ritual or ceremonies."
"To play rudely and boisterously; to leap and frisk about in play."
"Given to rude play; inclined to romp."
"Broken  as an ordinary; cut off or broken at the top as a chevron a bend or the like."
"An American marine food fish (Bathymaster signatus) of the North Pacific coast  allied to the tilefish."
"A kind of script in which the heavy strokes are nearly upright  giving the characters when taken together a round look."
"A species of lyric poetry so composed as to contain a refrain or repetition which recurs according to a fixed law  and a limited number of rhymes recurring also by rule."
"A small round tower erected at the foot of a bastion."
"A composition  vocal or instrumental commonly of a lively cheerful character in which the first strain recurs after each of the other strains."
"An instrument for removing small rough portions of bone."
"obs. p. p. of Renne  to run."
"A representation in sculpture or in painting of the cross with Christ hanging on it."

"The cover of any building  including the roofing (see Roofing) and all the materials and construction necessary to carry and maintain the same upon the walls or other uprights. In the case of a building with vaulted ceilings protected by an outer roof some writers call the vault the roof and the outer protection the roof mask. It is better however to consider the vault as the ceiling only in cases where it has farther covering."
"The breeding place of a colony of rooks; also  the birds themselves."
"Unobstructed spase; space which may be occupied by or devoted to any object; compass; extent of place  great or small; as there is not room for a house; the table takes up too much room."
"Having ample room; spacious; large; as  a roomy mansion; a roomy deck."
"The male of the domestic fowl; a cock."
"To turn up the earth with the snout  as swine."
"A mass of parenchymatous cells which covers and protects the growing cells at the end of a root; a pileorhiza."
"One who  or that which roots; one that tears up by the roots."
"A pile of roots  set with plants mosses etc. and used as an ornamental object in gardening."
"A large  stout cord usually one not less than an inch in circumference made of strands twisted or braided together. It differs from cord line and string only in its size. See Cordage."
"In a ropy manner; in a viscous or glutinous manner."
"capable of being drawn into a thread  as a glutinous substance; stringy; viscous; tenacious; glutinous; as ropy sirup; ropy lees."
"To hit  as another's ball with one's own ball."
"Of or pertaining to dew; consisting of dew; dewy."
"Of or pertaining to dew; resembling dew; dewy."
"A very large North Atlantic whalebone whale (Physalus antiquorum  or Balaenoptera physalus). It has a dorsal fin and strong longitudinal folds on the throat and belly. Called also razorback."
"Pertaining to  or designating an acid (called also lithic acid) found in certain red precipitates of urine. See Uric."
"A form of melody in which a phrase or passage is successively repeated  each time a step or half step higher; a melodic sequence."
"A bed of roses  or place where roses grow."
"resembling a rose in smell or color."
"Full of roses; rosy; as  roseate bowers."
"The flower of a rose before it opens  or when but partially open."

"A beautiful Australian parrakeet (Platycercus eximius) often kept as a cage bird. The head and back of the neck are scarlet  the throat is white the back dark green varied with lighter green and the breast yellow."
"a malvaceous plant (Hibiscus Sabdariffa) cultivated in the east and West Indies for its fleshy calyxes  which are used for making tarts and jelly and an acid drink."

"A rose-colored efflorescence upon the skin  occurring in circumscribed patches of little or no elevation and often alternately fading and reviving; also an acute specific disease which is characterized by an eruption of this character; -- called also rose rash."
"A place where roses are cultivated; a nursery of roses. See Rosary  1."
"An imitation of a rose by means of ribbon or other material  -- used as an ornament or a badge."
"Decorated with roses  or with the color of roses."
"The hard  amber-colored resin left after distilling off the volatile oil of turpentine; colophony."
"heathy land; land full of heather; moorish or watery land."

"Pertaining to  or designating a complex red dyestuff (called rosolic acid) which is analogous to rosaniline and aurin. It is produced by oxidizing a mixture of phenol and cresol as a dark red amorphous mass C20H16O3 which forms weak salts with bases and stable ones with acids. Called also methyl aurin and formerly corallin."
"The rough  scaly matter on the surface of the bark of trees."
"A register or roll showing the order in which officers  enlisted men companies or regiments are called on to serve."
"Of or pertaining to the beak or snout of an animal  or the beak of a ship; resembling a rostrum esp. the rostra at Rome or their decorations."
"The beak or head of a ship."
"Resembling a rose in color  form or qualities; blooming; red; blushing; also adorned with roses."

"To undergo a process common to organic substances by which they lose the cohesion of their parts and pass through certain chemical changes  giving off usually in some stages of the process more or less offensive odors; to become decomposed by a natural process; to putrefy; to decay."
"An ecclesiastical court of Rome  called also Rota Romana that takes cognizance of suits by appeal. It consists of twelve members."
"Relating to wheels or to rotary motion; rotary."
"Turning  as a wheel on its axis; pertaining to or resembling the motion of a wheel on its axis; rotatory; as rotary motion."
"Having the parts spreading out like a wheel; wheel-shaped; as  a rotate spicule or scale; a rotate corolla i.e. a monopetalous corolla with a flattish border and no tube or a very short one."
"that which gives a rotary or rolling motion  as a muscle which partially rotates or turns some part on its axis."
"A very small arctic sea bird (Mergulus alle  or Alle alle) common on both coasts of the Atlantic in winter; -- called also little auk dovekie rotch rotchie and sea dove."
"Any one of numerous species of small  polished brightcolored gastropods of the genus Rotella native of tropical seas."
"One of the Rotifera. See Illust. in Appendix."
"Having rotted; putrid; decayed; as  a rotten apple; rotten meat."
"Of or pertaining to the rotula  or kneepan."

"A round building; especially  one that is round both on the outside and inside like the Pantheon at Rome. Less properly but very commonly used for a large round room; as the rotunda of the Capitol at Washington."
"One devoted to a life of sensual pleasure; a debauchee; a rake."
"A small wheel formerly fixed to the pan of firelocks for discharging them."
"Having inequalities  small ridges or points on the surface; not smooth or plain; as a rough board; a rough stone; rough cloth."
"In a rough manner; unevenly; harshly; rudely; severely; austerely."
"A smoothly running passage of short notes (as semiquavers  or sixteenths) uniformly grouped sung upon one long syllable as in Handel's oratorios."
"A little roll; a roll of coins put up in paper  or something resembling such a roll."

"The handle by which the bed of a hand press  holding the form of type etc. is run in under the platen and out again; -- sometimes applied to the whole apparatus by which the form is moved under the platen."
"One who rounds; one who comes about frequently or regularly."
"To cry or shout; hence  to sell by auction."
"Rising; -- applied to a bird in the attitude of rising; also  sometmes to a bird in profile with wings addorsed."
"To pull or haul strongly and all together  as upon a rope without the assistance of mechanical appliances."
"To rouse; to disturb; as  to roust one out."
"To roar; to bellow; to snort; to snore loudly."
"The course or way which is traveled or passed  or is to be passed; a passing; a course; a road or path; a march."
"A plane made like a spokeshave  for working the inside edges of circular sashes."
"A round of business  amusement or pleasure daily or frequently pursued; especially a course of business or offical duties regularly or frequently returning."
"A thickening  made of flour for soups and gravies."
"One who practices robbery on the seas; a pirate."
"That may be rowed  or rowed upon."
"A boat designed to be propelled by oars instead of sails."
"One who engages in rows  or noisy quarrels; a ruffianly fellow."
"The little wheel of a spur  with sharp points."
"A stubble field left unplowed till late in the autumn  that it may be cropped by cattle."

"A contrivance or arrangement serving as a fulcrum for an oar in rowing. It consists sometimes of a notch in the gunwale of a boat  sometimes of a pair of pins between which the oar rests on the edge of the gunwale sometimes of a single pin passing through the oar or of a metal fork or stirrup pivoted in the gunwale and suporting the oar."
"An opening in the side of small vessels of war  near the surface of the water to facilitate rowing in calm weather."
"Kingly; pertaining to the crown or the sovereign; suitable for a king or queen; regal; as  royal power or prerogative; royal domains; the royal family; royal state."
"In a royal or kingly manner; like a king; as becomes a king."
"The state of being royal; the condition or quality of a royal person; kingship; kingly office; sovereignty."

"To subject (a body) to the action of something moving over its surface with pressure and friction  especially to the action of something moving back and forth; as to rub the flesh with the hand; to rub wood with sandpaper."
"Waste or rejected matter; anything worthless; valueless stuff; trash; especially  fragments of building materials or fallen buildings; ruins; debris."
"Water-worn or rough broken stones; broken bricks  etc. used in coarse masonry or to fill up between the facing courses of walls."
"An acute specific disease with a dusky red cutaneous eruption resembling that of measles  but unattended by catarrhal symptoms; -- called also German measles."
"One of several color-producing glycosides found in madder root."
"Colored a prevailing red  bay or black with flecks of white or gray especially on the flanks; -- said of horses."
"A small river which separated Italy from Cisalpine Gaul  the province alloted to Julius Caesar."
"Of or pertaining to rubidium; containing rubidium."

"The unit of monetary value in Russia. It is divided into 100 copecks  and in the gold coin of the realm (as in the five and ten ruble pieces) is worth about 77 cents. The silver ruble is a coin worth about 60 cents."
"That part of any work in the early manuscripts and typography which was colored red  to distinguish it from other portions."
"A genus of rosaceous plants  including the raspberry and blackberry."
"A precious stone of a carmine red color  sometimes verging to violet or intermediate between carmine and hyacinth red. It is a red crystallized variety of corundum."
"A plaited  quilled or goffered strip of lace net ribbon or other material -- used in place of collars or cuffs and as a trimming for women's dresses and bonnets."
"An uproar; a quarrel; a noisy outbreak."

"A fresh-water European fish of the Carp family (Leuciscus erythrophthalmus). It is about the size and shape of the roach  but it has the dorsal fin farther back a stouter body and red irises. Called also redeye roud finscale and shallow. A blue variety is called azurine or blue roach."
"Of a red color; red  or reddish; as a ruddy sky; a ruddy flame."
"Characterized by roughness; umpolished; raw; lacking delicacy or refinement; coarse."
"A perennial suffrutescent plant (Ruta graveolens)  having a strong heavy odor and a bitter taste; herb of grace. It is used in medicine."
"Causing one to rue or lament; woeful; mournful; sorrowful."
"A private circle or assembly at a private house; a circle."
"A game similar to whist  and the predecessor of it."
"A small freshwater European perch (Acerina vulgaris); -- called also pope  blacktail and stone / striped perch."
"A pimp; a pander; also  a paramour."
"To make into a ruff; to draw or contract into puckers  plaits or folds; to wrinkle."
"One who ruffles; a swaggerer; a bully; a ruffian."
"A phenol derivative of anthracene obtained as a white crystalline substance  which on oxidation produces a red dyestuff related to anthraquinone."
"Reddish; of a yellowish red or brownish red color; tawny."
"A kind of coarse  heavy frieze formerly used for garments."
"A wrinkle; a fold; as  the rugae of the stomach."
"Full of asperities on the surface; broken into sharp or irregular points  or otherwise uneven; not smooth; rough; as a rugged mountain; a rugged road."
"A coarse kind of woolen cloth  used for wrapping blanketing etc."
"An instrument for scraping the periosteum from bones; a raspatory."

"An extinct tribe of fossil corals  including numerous species many of them of large size. They are characteristic of the Paleozoic formations. The radiating septs when present are usually in multiples of four. See Cyathophylloid."
"Wrinkled; full of wrinkles; specifically (Bot.)  having the veinlets sunken and the spaces between them elevated as the leaves of the sage and horehound."
"The act of falling or tumbling down; fall."
"To demolish; to subvert; to destroy; to reduce to poverty; to ruin."
"Causing  or tending to cause ruin; destructive; baneful; pernicious; as a ruinous project."
"That may be ruled; subject to rule; accordant or conformable to rule."

"That which is prescribed or laid down as a guide for conduct or action; a governing direction for a specific purpose; an authoritative enactment; a regulation; a prescription; a precept; as  the rules of various societies; the rules governing a school; a rule of etiquette or propriety; the rules of cricket."
"One who rules; one who exercises sway or authority; a governor."

"A kind of intoxicating liquor distilled from cane juice  or from the scummings of the boiled juice or from treacle or molasses or from the lees of former distillations. Also sometimes used colloquially as a generic or a collective name for intoxicating liquor."
"To make a low  heavy continued sound; as the thunder rumbles at a distance."
"The first stomach of ruminants; the paunch; the fardingbag. See Illust. below."
"A yellow crystalline substance found in the root of yellow dock (Rumex crispus) and identical with chrysophanic acid."
"A popular or jocular name for a drinking vessel."
"A place or room for the stowage of cargo in a ship; also  the act of stowing cargo; the pulling and moving about of packages incident to close stowage; -- formerly written romage."
"A large and tall glass  or drinking cup."
"Of or pertaining to rum; characteristic of rum; as a rummy flavor."
"A flying or popular report; the common talk; hence  public fame; notoriety."
"A teller of news; especially  one who spreads false reports."
"The end of the backbone of an animal  with the parts adjacent; the buttock or buttocks."
"A member or a supporter of the Rump Parliament."
"To make uneven; to form into irregular inequalities; to wrinkle; to crumple; as  to rumple an apron or a cravat."
"A disturbance; noise and confusion; a quarrel."
"One who  or that which flees from danger duty restraint etc.; a fugitive."
"A moat with water in it; also  a small stream; a runlet."
"A round; a step of a ladder; a rung."
"A small barrel of no certain dimensions. It may contain from 3 to 20 gallons  but it usually holds about 14/ gallons."
"A letter  or character belonging to the written language of the ancient Norsemen or Scandinavians; in a wider sense applied to the letters of the ancient nations of Northern Europe in general."
"A bard  or learned man among the ancient Goths."
"Of or pertaining to a rune  to runes or to the Norsemen; as runic verses; runic letters; runic names; runic rhyme."
"A little run or stream; a streamlet; a brook."
"One who  or that which runs; a racer."
"Any animal which is unusually small  as compared with others of its kind; -- applied particularly to domestic animals."
"A silver coin  and money of account in the East Indies."
"An eruption upon the skin  consisting of vesicles with inflamed base and filled with serous purulent or bloody fluid which dries up forming a blackish crust."
"A breaking or bursting open; breach; rupture."
"The act of breaking apart  or separating; the state of being broken asunder; as the rupture of the skin; the rupture of a vessel or fiber; the rupture of a lutestring."
"Of or pertaining to the country  as distinguished from a city or town; living in the country; suitable for or resembling the country; rustic; as rural scenes; a rural prospect."
"The gossamer-winged butterflies; a family of small butterflies  including the hairstreaks violets and theclas."
"In a rural manner; as in the country."
"An artifice; trick; stratagem; wile; fraud; deceit."
"A name given to many aquatic or marsh-growing endogenous plants with soft  slender stems as the species of Juncus and Scirpus."
"Of  like or pertaining to a deer of the genus Rusa which includes the sambur deer (Rusa Aristotelis) of India."
"A kind of light  soft bread made with yeast and eggs often toasted or crisped in an oven; or a kind of sweetened biscuit."
"A depilatory made of orpiment and quicklime  and used by the Turks. See Rhusma."

"Of a reddish brown color  or (by some called) a red gray; of the color composed of blue red and yellow in equal strength but unequal proportions namely two parts of red to one each of blue and yellow; also of a yellowish brown color."
"Of or pertaining to Russia  its inhabitants or language."
"To Russianize; as  to Russify conquered tribes."
"The reddish yellow coating formed on iron when exposed to moist air  consisting of ferric oxide or hydroxide; hence by extension any metallic film of corrosion."
"Full of rust; resembling rust; causing rust; rusty."
"Of or pertaining to the country; rural; as  the rustic gods of antiquity."
"To make a quick succession of small sounds  like the rubbing or moving of silk cloth or dry leaves."
"Covered or affected with rust; as  a rusty knife or sword; rusty wheat."
"Sexual desire or oestrus of deer  cattle and various other mammals; heat; also the period during which the oestrus exists."
"Sorrow for the misery of another; pity; tenderness."
"Pertaining to  or obtained from rue (Ruta); as rutic acid now commonly called capric acid."
"A mineral usually of a reddish brown color  and brilliant metallic adamantine luster occurring in tetragonal crystals. In composition it is titanium dioxide like octahedrite and brookite."

"A glucoside resembling  but distinct from quercitrin. Rutin is found in the leaves of the rue (Ruta graveolens) and other plants and obtained as a bitter yellow crystalline substance which yields quercitin on decomposition."
"A chart of a course  esp. at sea."
"A rattling sound in the throat arising from difficulty of breathing; a rattle."
"A clause added to a document; a rider. See Rider."
"A grain yielded by a hardy cereal grass (Secale cereale)  closely allied to wheat; also the plant itself. Rye constitutes a large portion of the breadstuff used by man."
"A piece of iron crossing the hole in the upper millstone by which the stone is supported on the spindle."
"A peasant or cultivator of the soil."
"A genus of large edentulous sirenians  allied to the dugong and manatee including but one species (R. Stelleri); -- called also Steller's sea cow."
"A genus of palm trees including the palmetto of the Southern United States."
"In mediaeval demonology  the nocturnal assembly in which demons and sorcerers were thought to celebrate their orgies."

"A season or day of rest; one day in seven appointed for rest or worship  the observance of which was enjoined upon the Jews in the Decalogue and has been continued by the Christian church with a transference of the day observed from the last to the first day of the week which is called also Lord's Day."
"A genus of tubicolous annelids having a circle of plumose gills around the head."
"A sword with a broad and heavy blade  thick at the back and usually more or less curved like a scimiter; a cavalry sword."
"Of or pertaining to Saba in Arabia  celebrated for producing aromatic plants."
"The very hard wood of a leguminous West Indian tree (Lysiloma Sabicu)  valued for shipbuilding."
"Of or pertaining to the ancient Sabines  a people of Italy."
"A carnivorous animal of the Weasel family (Mustela zibellina) native of the northern latitudes of Europe  Asia and America -- noted for its fine soft and valuable fur."
"A kind of wooden shoe worn by the peasantry in France  Belgium Sweden and some other European countries."
"A sudden  violent check of a horse by drawing or twitching the reins on a sudden and with one pull."
"Having the form of a sack or pouch; furnished with a sack or pouch  as a petal."
"A little sac; specifically  the sacculus of the ear."
"A chief of a tribe of the American Indians; a sagamore."
"A scent bag  or perfume cushion to be laid among handkerchiefs garments etc. to perfume them."
"A name formerly given to various dry Spanish wines."
"The act of taking by storm and pillaging; sack."
"A brass wind instrument  like a bass trumpet so contrived that it can be lengthened or shortened according to the tone required; -- said to be the same as the trombone."
"One who sacks; one who takes part in the storm and pillage of a town."
"As much as a sack will hold."
"Of or pertaining to the sacrum; in the region of the sacrum."
"Set apart by solemn religious ceremony; especially  in a good sense made holy; set apart to religious use; consecrated; not profane or common; as a sacred place; a sacred day; sacred service."
"A sacristan; also  a person retained in a cathedral to copy out music for the choir and take care of the books."
"That part of the vertebral column which is directly connected with  or forms a part of the pelvis."
"A tribe of Indians  which together with the Foxes formerly occupied the region about Green Bay Wisconsin."
"A work in the Persian tongue  being a summary of the Zend-Avesta or sacred books."

"A seat for a rider  -- usually made of leather padded to span comfortably a horse's back furnished with stirrups for the rider's feet to rest in and fastened in place with a girth; also a seat for the rider on a bicycle or tricycle."
"A member of a monotheistic sect of Hindoos. Sadhs resemble the Quakers in many respects."
"An iron for smoothing clothes; a flatiron."
"A plant of the genus Ziziphus (Z. lotus); -- so called by the Arabs of Barbary  who use its berries for food. See Lotus (b)."
"Free from harm  injury or risk; untouched or unthreatened by danger or injury; unharmed; unhurt; secure; whole; as safe from disease; safe from storms; safe from foes."
"In a safe manner; danger  injury loss or evil consequences."
"The condition or state of being safe; freedom from danger or hazard; exemption from hurt  injury or loss."
"A bulbous iridaceous plant (Crocus sativus) having blue flowers with large yellow stigmas. See Crocus."

"To sink  in the middle by its weight or under applied pressure below a horizontal line or plane; as a line or cable supported by its ends sags though tightly drawn; the floor of a room sags; hence to lean give way or settle from a vertical position; as a building may sag one way or another; a door sags on its hinges."
"A Scandinavian legend  or heroic or mythic tradition among the Norsemen and kindred people; a northern European popular historical or religious tale of olden time."
"A mixed woven fabric of silk and cotton  or silk and wool; sayette; also a light woolen fabric."

"A suffruticose labiate plant (Salvia officinalis) with grayish green foliage  much used in flavoring meats etc. The name is often extended to the whole genus of which many species are cultivated for ornament as the scarlet sage and Mexican red and blue sage."
"A Russian measure of length equal to about seven English feet."
"A pot or case of fire clay  in which fine stoneware is inclosed while baking in the kiln; a seggar."
"A small constellation north of Aquila; the Arrow."

"A dry granulated starch imported from the East Indies  much used for making puddings and as an article of diet for the sick; also as starch for stiffening textile fabrics. It is prepared from the stems of several East Indian and Malayan palm trees but chiefly from the Metroxylon Sagu; also from several cycadaceous plants (Cycas revoluta Zamia integrifolia etc.)."
"The military cloak of the Roman soldiers."
"A genus of palms from which sago is obtained."
"A respectful title or appellation given to Europeans of rank."
"A kind of ketch very common in the Levant  which has neither topgallant sail nor mizzen topsail."
"An antelope (Saiga Tartarica) native of the plains of Siberia and Eastern Russia. The male has erect annulated horns  and tufts of long hair beneath the eyes and ears."
"An extent of canvas or other fabric by means of which the wind is made serviceable as a power for propelling vessels through the water."
"One who follows the business of navigating ships or other vessels; one who understands the practical management of ships; one of the crew of a vessel; a mariner; a common seaman."
"A person sanctified; a holy or godly person; one eminent for piety and virtue; any true Christian  as being redeemed and consecrated to God."
"Like a saint; becoming a holy person."
"The pollock  or coalfish; -- called also sillock."
"One of an important religious sect in India which regards Siva with peculiar veneration."

"Final cause; end; purpose of obtaining; cause; motive; reason; interest; concern; account; regard or respect; -- used chiefly in such phrases as  for the sake of for his sake for man's sake for mercy's sake and the like; as to commit crime for the sake of gain; to go abroad for the sake of one's health."
"A falcon (Falco sacer) native of Southern Europe and Asia  closely resembling the lanner."
"Any one of several species of South American monkeys of the genus Pithecia. They have large ears  and a long hairy tail which is not prehensile."
"The divine energy  personified as the wife of a deity (Brahma Vishnu Siva etc.); the female principle."
"An East Indian timber tree (Shorea robusta)  much used for building purposes. It is of a light brown color close-grained heavy and durable."
"Capable of being sold; fit to be sold; finding a ready market."
"A preparation of vegetables  as lettuce celery water cress onions etc. usually dressed with salt vinegar oil and spice and eaten for giving a relish to other food; as lettuce salad; tomato salad
"A salutation or compliment of ceremony in the east by word or act; an obeisance  performed by bowing very low and placing the right palm on the forehead."
"The dried tubers of various species of Orchis  and Eulophia. It is used to make a nutritious beverage by treating the powdered preparation with hot water."
"Denoting a tribe of Franks who established themselves early in the fourth century on the river Sala [now Yssel]; Salic."
"Of or pertaining to the Salian Franks  or to the Salic law so called."
"A glucoside found in the bark and leaves of several species of willow (Salix) and poplar  and extracted as a bitter white crystalline substance."
"The hypothetical radical of salicylic acid and of certain related compounds."
"Moving by leaps or springs; leaping; bounding; jumping."
"To combine or impregnate with a salt."
"A salt marsh  or salt pond inclosed from the sea."
"Consisting of salt  or containing salt; as saline particles; saline substances; a saline cathartic."
"A genus of trees or shrubs including the willow  osier and the like growing usually in wet grounds."
"A light kind of helmet  with or without a visor introduced during the 15th century."
"To leap or rush out; to burst forth; to issue suddenly; as a body of troops from a fortified place to attack besiegers; to make a sally."
"A ragout of partly roasted game stewed with sauce  wine bread and condiments suited to provoke appetite."
"A white crystalline substance consisting of phenol salicylate."
"An apartment for the reception of company; hence  in the plural fashionable parties; circles of fashionable society."

"A spacious and elegant apartment for the reception of company or for works of art; a hall of reception  esp. a hall for public entertainments or amusements; a large room or parlor; as the saloon of a steamboat."
"An aromatic drink prepared from sassafras bark and other ingredients  at one time much used in London."
"Any species of Salpa  or of the family Salpidae."
"A genus of transparent  tubular free-swimming oceanic tunicates found abundantly in all the warmer latitudes. See Illustration in Appendix."
"The Eustachian tube  or the Fallopian tube."
"A mud volcano  the water of which is often impregnated with salts whence the name."
"A genus of plants including the glasswort. See Glasswort."

"The chloride of sodium  a substance used for seasoning food for the preservation of meat etc. It is found native in the earth and is also produced by evaporation and crystallization from sea water and other water impregnated with saline particles."
"A mixture of salt  coarse meal lime etc. attractive to pigeons."
"One who makes  sells or applies salt; one who salts meat or fish."
"A building or place where salt is made by boiling or by evaporation; salt works."
"A St. Andrew's cross  or cross in the form of an X -- one of the honorable ordinaries."
"With taste of salt; in a salt manner."
"To address  as with expressions of kind wishes and courtesy; to greet; to hail."
"The act of saving a vessel  goods or life from perils of the sea."
"One who salves  or uses salve as a remedy; hence a quacksalver or quack."
"A genus of plants including the sage. See Sage."
"One who assists in saving a ship or goods at sea  without being under special obligation to do so."
"A dry  indehiscent usually one-seeded winged fruit as that of the ash maple and elm; a key or key fruit."
"A colloquial or humorous appellation for a negro; sometimes  the offspring of a black person and a mulatto; a zambo."
"An ancient stringed instrument used by the Greeks  the particular construction of which is unknown."

"An East Indian deer (Rusa Aristotelis) having a mane on its neck. Its antlers have but three prongs. Called also gerow. The name is applied to other species of the genus Rusa  as the Bornean sambur (R. equina)."
"Not different or other; not another or others; identical; unchanged."
"Of or pertaining to the island of Samos."
"A hot and destructive wind that sometimes blows  in Turkey from the desert. It is identical with the simoom of Arabia and the kamsin of Syria."
"A species of silk stuff  or taffeta generally interwoven with gold."
"A machine for pressing the water from skins in tanning."
"Of or pertaining to the Samoan Islands (formerly called Navigators' Islands) in the South Pacific Ocean  or their inhabitants."
"A metal urn used in Russia for making tea. It is filled with water  which is heated by charcoal placed in a pipe with chimney attached which passes through the urn."
"An article of food consisting of maize broken or bruised  which is cooked by boiling and usually eaten with milk; coarse hominy."
"A Chinese boat from twelve to fifteen feet long  covered with a house and sometimes used as a permanent habitation on the inland waters."
"One who makes up samples for inspection; one who examines samples  or by samples; as a wool sampler."
"A spirituous liquor distilled by the Chinese from the yeasty liquor in which boiled rice has fermented under pressure."
"An Israelite of Bible record (see Judges xiii.)  distinguished for his great strength; hence a man of extraordinary physical strength."
"Capable of being healed or cured; susceptible of remedy."
"A sacred place; hence  a place of retreat; a room reserved for personal use; as an editor's sanctum."
"A part of the Mass  or in Protestant churches a part of the communion service of which the first words in Latin are Sanctus sanctus sanctus [Holy holy holy]; -- called also Tersanctus."
"Fine particles of stone  esp. of siliceous stone but not reduced to dust; comminuted stone in the form of loose grains which are not coherent when wet."
"An old name of sandalwood  now applied only to the red sandalwood. See under Sandalwood."
"Approaching the nature of sand; loose; not compact."
"A kind of minium  or red lead made by calcining carbonate of lead but inferior to true minium."
"A mythical person who makes children sleepy  so that they rub their eyes as if there were sand in them."
"A pit or excavation from which sand is or has been taken."
"A Russian fish (Lucioperca sandre) which yields a valuable oil  called sandre oil used in the preparation of caviare."
"Consisting of  abounding with or resembling sand; full of sand; covered or sprinkled with sand; as a sandy desert road or soil."
"Being in a healthy condition; not deranged; acting rationally; -- said of the mind."
"The Abyssinian ox (Bos / Bibos  Africanus) noted for the great length of its horns. It has a hump on its back."
"A collection of vedic hymns  songs or verses forming the first part of each Veda."
"Any plant of the umbelliferous genus Sanicula  reputed to have healing powers."
"A thin  serous fluid commonly discharged from ulcers or foul wounds."
"Pertaining to sanies  or partaking of its nature and appearance; thin and serous with a slight bloody tinge; as the sanious matter of an ulcer."
"The condition or quality of being sane; soundness of health of body or mind  especially of the mind; saneness."
"A district or a subvision of a vilayet."
"A chank shell (Turbinella pyrum); also  a shell bracelet or necklace made in India from the chank shell."
"A Hindoo system of philosophy which refers all things to soul and a rootless germ called prakriti  consisting of three elements goodness passion and darkness."
"A male Indian; a brave; -- correlative of squaw."
"Without; deprived or destitute of. Rarely used as an English word."
"A colorless crystalline substance  isomeric with piperonal but having weak acid properties. It is extracted from sandalwood."
"One of the seven confederated tribes of Indians belonging to the Sioux  or Dakotas."
"A Turkish saint; a kind of dervish  regarded by the people as a saint: also a hermit."
"Any marine annelid of the genus Hyalinaecia  especially H. tubicola of Europe which inhabits a transparent movable tube resembling a quill in color and texture."
"The juice of plants of any kind  especially the ascending and descending juices or circulating fluid essential to nutrition."

"Any one of several species of South American monkeys of the genus Cebus  having long and prehensile tails. Some of the species are called also capuchins. The bonnet sapajou (C. subcristatus) the golden-handed sapajou (C. chrysopus) and the white-throated sapajou (C. hypoleucus) are well known species. See Capuchin."
"Having the power of affecting the organs of taste; possessing savor  or flavor."
"Wise; sage; discerning; -- often in irony or contempt."

"A poisonous glucoside found in many plants  as in the root of soapwort (Saponaria) in the bark of soap bark (Quillaia) etc. It is extracted as a white amorphous powder which occasions a soapy lather in solution and produces a local anaesthesia. Formerly called also struthiin quillaiin senegin polygalic acid etc. By extension any one of a group of related bodies of which saponin proper is the type."
"A soapy mixture obtained by treating an essential oil with an alkali; hence  any similar compound of an essential oil."
"Power of affecting the organs of taste; savor; flavor; taste."
"One who saps; specifically (Mil.)  one who is employed in working at saps building and repairing fortifications and the like."
"Of or pertaining to Sappho  the Grecian poetess; as Sapphic odes; Sapphic verse."
"Any one of several species of brilliant South American humming birds of the genus Sappho  having very bright-colored and deeply forked tails; -- called also firetail."
"Abounding with sap; full of sap; juicy; succulent."
"A kind of Swiss cheese  of a greenish color flavored with melilot."
"The alburnum  or part of the wood of any exogenous tree next to the bark being that portion of the tree through which the sap flows most freely; -- distinguished from heartwood."
"Anciently  an Arab; later a Mussulman; in the Middle Ages the common term among Christians in Europe for a Mohammedan hostile to the crusaders."
"A keen  reproachful expression; a satirical remark uttered with some degree of scorn or contempt; a taunt; a gibe; a cutting jest."
"One of the outer pinions or feathers of the wing of a bird  esp. of a hawk."

"A genus of bacteria found in various organic fluids  especially in those those of the stomach associated with certain diseases. The individual organisms undergo division along two perpendicular partitions so that multiplication takes place in two directions giving groups of four cubical cells. Also used adjectively; as a sarcina micrococcus; a sarcina group."
"To weed  or clear of weeds with a hoe."
"A name applied by Dujardin in 1835 to the gelatinous material forming the bodies of the lowest animals; protoplasm."
"Resembling flesh  or muscle; composed of sarcode."

"A tumor of fleshy consistence; -- formerly applied to many varieties of tumor  now restricted to a variety of malignant growth made up of cells resembling those of fetal development without any proper intercellular substance."
"Fleshy; -- applied to the minute structural elements  called sarcous elements or sarcous disks of which striated muscular fiber is composed."
"A variety of carnelian  of a rich reddish yellow or brownish red color. See the Note under Chalcedony."

"Any one of several small species of herring which are commonly preserved in olive oil for food  especially the pilchard or European sardine (Clupea pilchardus). The California sardine (Clupea sagax) is similar. The American sardines of the Atlantic coast are mostly the young of the common herring and of the menhaden."
"A precious stone  probably a carnelian one of which was set in Aaron's breastplate."

"The principal garment of a Hindoo woman. It consists of a long piece of cloth  which is wrapped round the middle of the body a portion being arranged to hang down in front and the remainder passed across the bosom over the left shoulder."
"Any one of several species of sparoid fishes belonging to Sargus  Pomadasys and related genera; -- called also sar and saragu."
"A small South American opossum (Didelphys opossum)  having four white spots on the face."
"Thin boards for sheathing  as above the rafters and under the shingles or slates and for similar purposes."
"A prostrate filiform stem or runner  as of the strawberry. See Runner."
"A sort of petticoat worn by both sexes in Java and the Malay Archipelago."
"A Chaldean astronomical period or cycle  the length of which has been variously estimated from 3 600 years to 3 600 days or a little short of 10 years."
"A large bale or package of wool  containing eighty tods or 2 240 pounds in weight."
"A large toadfish of the Southern United States and the Gulf of Mexico (Batrachus tau  var. pardus)."
"One of the large sandstone blocks scattered over the English chalk downs; -- called also sarsen stone  and Druid stone."

"A scarf or band worn about the waist  over the shoulder or otherwise; a belt; a girdle -- worn by women and children as an ornament; also worn as a badge of distinction by military officers members of societies etc."
"A collection of sashes; ornamentation by means of sashes."
"A kind of pad worn on the leg under the boot."
"The Indian antelope (Antilope bezoartica  / cervicapra) noted for its beauty and swiftness. It has long spiral divergent horns."
"A sluice or lock  as in a river to make it more navigable."
"The grand adversary of man; the Devil  or Prince of darkness; the chief of the fallen angels; the archfiend."
"A little sack or bag for carrying papers  books or small articles of wearing apparel; a hand bag."
"To satisfy the desire or appetite of; to satiate; to glut; to surfeit."
"A kind of dress goods made of cotton or woolen  with a glossy surface resembling satin."
"Filled to satiety; glutted; sated; -- followed by with or of."

"The state of being satiated or glutted; fullness of gratification  either of the appetite or of any sensual desire; fullness beyond desire; an excess of gratification which excites wearisomeness or loathing; repletion; satiation."
"A silk cloth  of a thick close texture and overshot woof which has a glossy surface."
"Like or composed of satin; glossy; as  to have a satiny appearance; a satiny texture."

"A composition  generally poetical holding up vice or folly to reprobation; a keen or severe exposure of what in public or private morals deserves rebuke; an invective poem; as the Satires of Juvenal."

"In general  to fill up the measure of a want of (a person or a thing); hence to grafity fully the desire of; to make content; to supply to the full or so far as to give contentment with what is wished for."
"The governor of a province in ancient Persia; hence  a petty autocrat despot."
"The government or jurisdiction of a satrap; a principality."
"One of the elder and principal deities  the son of Coelus and Terra (Heaven and Earth) and the father of Jupiter. The corresponding Greek divinity was Kro`nos later CHro`nos Time."
"A sylvan deity or demigod  represented as part man and part goat and characterized by riotous merriment and lasciviousness."
"A composition of condiments and appetizing ingredients eaten with food as a relish; especially  a dressing for meat or fish or for puddings; as mint sauce; sweet sauce etc."
"A small pan or vessel in which sauce was set on a table."
"In a saucy manner; impudently; with impertinent boldness."
"Showing impertinent boldness or pertness; transgressing the rules of decorum; treating superiors with contempt; impudent; insolent; as  a saucy fellow."
"An American fresh-water food fish (Stizostedion Canadense); -- called also gray pike  blue pike hornfish land pike sand pike pickering and pickerel."
"A rapid in some rivers; as  the Sault Ste. Marie."
"To wander or walk about idly and in a leisurely or lazy manner; to lounge; to stroll; to loiter."
"Soil; dirt; dirty water; urine from a cowhouse."
"Any carangoid fish of the genus Trachurus  especially T. trachurus or T. saurus of Europe and America and T. picturatus of California. Called also skipjack and horse mackerel."
"A division of Reptilia formerly established to include the Lacertilia  Crocodilia Dinosauria and other groups. By some writers the name is restricted to the Lacertilia."
"Of or pertaining to  or of the nature of the Sauria."
"A slender marine fish (Scomberesox saurus) of Europe and America. It has long  thin beaklike jaws. Called also billfish gowdnook gawnook skipper skipjack skopster lizard fish and Egypt herring."
"An article of food consisting of meat (esp. pork) minced and highly seasoned  and inclosed in a cylindrical case or skin usually made of the prepared intestine of some animal."
"To fry lightly and quickly  as meat by turning or tossing it over frequently in a hot pan greased with a little fat."
"Capable of  or admitting of being saved."
"Of or pertaining to the forest; remote from human abodes and cultivation; in a state of nature; wild; as  a savage wilderness."
"A tract of level land covered with the vegetable growth usually found in a damp soil and warm climate  -- as grass or reeds -- but destitute of trees."
"A man of learning; one versed in literature or science; a person eminent for acquirements."

"A coniferous shrub (Juniperus Sabina) of Western Asia  occasionally found also in the northern parts of the United States and in British America. It is a compact bush with dark-colored foliage and produces small berries having a glaucous bloom. Its bitter acrid tops are sometimes used in medicine for gout amenorrhoea etc."
"One who saves  preserves or delivers from destruction or danger."
"That property of a thing which affects the organs of taste or smell; taste and odor; flavor; relish; scent; as  the savor of an orange or a rose; an ill savor."
"Pleasing to the organs of taste or smell."
"A variety of the common cabbage (Brassica oleracea major)  having curled leaves -- much cultivated for winter use."
"A corrupt spelling and pronunciation of solder."
"Dust or small fragments of wood (or of stone  etc.) made by the cutting of a saw."

"Any one of several species of elasmobranch fishes of the genus Pristis. They have a sharklike form  but are more nearly allied to the rays. The flattened and much elongated snout has a row of stout toothlike structures inserted along each edge forming a sawlike organ with which it mutilates or kills its prey."

"Any one of numerous species of hymenopterous insects belonging to the family Tenthredinidae. The female usually has an ovipositor containing a pair of sawlike organs with which she makes incisions in the leaves or stems of plants in which to lay the eggs. The larvae resemble those of Lepidoptera."
"A mill for sawing  especially one for sawing timber or lumber."
"One whose occupation is to saw timber into planks or boards  or to saw wood for fuel; a sawer."
"A kind of chopping instrument for trimming the edges of roofing slates."

"A name given to a numerous family of brass wind instruments with valves  invented by Antoine Joseph Adolphe Sax (known as Adolphe Sax) of Belgium and Paris and much used in military bands and in orchestras."
"One of a nation or people who formerly dwelt in the northern part of Germany  and who with other Teutonic tribes invaded and conquered England in the fifth and sixth centuries."
"Relating to the Saxons or Anglo- Saxons."
"A mixed stuff  called also sagathy. See Sagathy."
"An abbreviation of God's blood; -- used as an oath."
"An incrustation over a sore  wound vesicle or pustule formed by the drying up of the discharge from the diseased part."
"A small carangoid fish (Trachurus saurus) abundant on the European coast  and less common on the American. The name is applied also to several allied species."
"A machine formerly employed for reducing dislocations of the humerus."
"In the quaternion analysis  a quantity that has magnitude but not direction; -- distinguished from a vector which has both magnitude and direction."
"To burn with hot liquid or steam; to pain or injure by contact with  or immersion in any hot fluid; as to scald the hand."
"Of or pertaining to the scalds of the Norsemen; as  scaldic poetry."

"The dish of a balance; hence  the balance itself; an instrument or machine for weighing; as to turn the scale; -- chiefly used in the plural when applied to the whole instrument or apparatus for weighing. Also used figuratively."
"Having the sides and angles unequal; -- said of a triangle."
"One who  or that which scales; specifically a dentist's instrument for removing tartar from the teeth."
"A scurf or scabby disease  especially of the scalp."

"Any one of numerous species of marine bivalve mollusks of the genus Pecten and allied genera of the family Pectinidae. The shell is usually radially ribbed  and the edge is therefore often undulated in a characteristic manner. The large adductor muscle of some the species is much used as food. One species (Vola Jacobaeus) occurs on the coast of Palestine and its shell was formerly worn by pilgrims as a mark that they had been to the Holy Land. Called also fan shell. See Pecten 2."
"A small knife with a thin  keen blade -- used by surgeons and in dissecting."
"Covered or abounding with scales; as  a scaly fish."
"To move awkwardly; to be shuffling  irregular or unsteady; to sprawl; to shamble."
"To run with speed; to run or move in a quick  hurried manner; to hasten away."
"To mount by steps; to go through with step by step."
"Offense caused or experienced; reproach or reprobation called forth by what is regarded as wrong  criminal heinous or flagrant: opprobrium or disgrace."
"A chemical earth  the oxide of scandium."
"Of or pertaining to scandium; derived from  or containing scandium."

"Not full  large or plentiful; scarcely sufficient; less than is wanted for the purpose; scanty; meager; not enough; as a scant allowance of provisions or water; a scant pattern of cloth for a garment."
"In a scant manner; not fully or sufficiently; narrowly; penuriously."
"Wanting amplitude or extent; narrow; small; not abundant."
"A peduncle rising from the ground or from a subterranean stem  as in the stemless violets the bloodroot and the like."
"To work roughly  or shape without finishing as stone before leaving the quarry."
"The principal bone of the shoulder girdle in mammals; the shoulder blade."
"A mark in the skin or flesh of an animal  made by a wound or ulcer and remaining after the wound or ulcer is healed; a cicatrix; a mark left by a previous injury; a blemish; a disfigurement."
"Not plentiful or abundant; in small quantity in proportion to the demand; not easily to be procured; rare; uncommon."
"To frighten; to strike with sudden fear; to alarm."
"To scratch or cut the skin of; esp. (Med.)  to make small incisions in by means of a lancet or scarificator so as to draw blood from the smaller vessels without opening a large vein."
"A deep bright red tinged with orange or yellow  -- of many tints and shades; a vivid or bright red color."
"Of or pertaining to the Scaridae  a family of marine fishes including the parrot fishes."
"A band in the same position as the bend sinister  but only half as broad as the latter."
"A Mediterranean food fish (Sparisoma scarus) of excellent quality and highly valued by the Romans; -- called also parrot fish."
"Barren land having only a thin coat of grass."
"Go away; begone; away; -- chiefly used in driving off a cat."
"A kind of bit for the bridle of a horse; -- called also scatchmouth."
"To strew about; to sprinkle around; to throw down loosely; to deposit or place here and there  esp. in an open or sparse order."
"A bed or stratum of shellfish; scalp."
"A tool with a semicircular edge  -- used by engravers to clear away the spaces between the lines of an engraving."
"A precipitous bank or rock; a scar."
"A toll or duty formerly exacted of merchant strangers by mayors  sheriffs etc. for goods shown or offered for sale within their precincts."
"The structure on which a spectacle or play is exhibited; the part of a theater in which the acting is done  with its adjuncts and decorations; the stage."

"Assemblage of scenes; the paintings and hangings representing the scenes of a play; the disposition and arrangement of the scenes in which the action of a play  poem etc. is laid; representation of place of action or occurence."
"To perceive by the olfactory organs; to smell; as  to scent game as a hound does."
"A staff or baton borne by a sovereign  as a ceremonial badge or emblem of authority; a royal mace."

"An outline or image universally applicable to a general conception  under which it is likely to be presented to the mind; as five dots in a line are a schema of the number five; a preceding and succeeding event are a schema of cause and effect."
"A combination of things connected and adjusted by design; a system."
"One who forms schemes; a projector; esp.  a plotter; an intriguer."
"An Egyptian or Persian measure of length  varying from thirty-two to sixty stadia."
"A playful  humorous movement commonly in 3-4 measure which often takes the place of the old minuet and trio in a sonata or a symphony."
"General state or disposition of the body or mind  or of one thing with regard to other things; habitude."

"Division or separation; specifically (Eccl.)  permanent division or separation in the Christian church; breach of unity among people of the same religious faith; the offense of seeking to produce division in a church without justifiable cause."
"An interval equal to half a comma."

"Any crystalline rock having a foliated structure (see Foliation) and hence admitting of ready division into slabs or slates. The common kinds are mica schist  and hornblendic schist consisting chiefly of quartz with mica or hornblende and often feldspar."
"The finer portion of a crushed ore  as of gold lead or tin separated by the water in certain wet processes."
"One who attends a school; one who learns of a teacher; one under the tuition of a preceptor; a pupil; a disciple; a learner; a student."
"A shoal; a multitude; as  a school of fish."
"Pertaining to  or containing schorl; as schorly granite."
"Of or pertaining to the hip; in the region of  or affecting the hip; ischial; ischiatic; as the sciatic nerve sciatic pains."
"Knowledge; knowledge of principles and causes; ascertained truth of facts."
"Some kind of stinging or biting insect  as a flea a gnat a sandfly or the like."
"A shoot or sprout of a plant; a sucker."
"Of or pertaining to the island Scio (Chio or Chios)."
"The clippings of metals made in various mechanical operations."
"To cut with scissors or shears; to prepare with the aid of scissors."
"A genus of rodents comprising the common squirrels."
"Raspings of ivory  hartshorn metals or other hard substance."
"Derision; ridicule; mockery; derisive or mocking expression of scorn  contempt or reproach."
"To find fault or rail with rude clamor; to brawl; to utter harsh  rude boisterous rebuke; to chide sharply or coarsely; -- often with at; as to scold at a servant."
"The embryo produced directly from the egg in a metagenetic series  especially the larva of a tapeworm or other parasitic worm. See Illust. of Echinococcus."
"A genus of acanthopterygious fishes which includes the common mackerel."
"A fortification  or work for defense; a fort."
"A cake  thinner than a bannock made of wheat or barley or oat meal."
"A large ladle; a vessel with a long handle  used for dipping liquids; a utensil for bailing boats."
"To walk fast; to go quickly; to run hastily away."
"Having the surface closely covered with hairs  like a brush."
"That at which one aims; the thing or end to which the mind directs its view; that which is purposed to be reached or accomplished; hence  ultimate design aim or purpose; intention; drift; object."
"A peculiar brushlike organ found on the foot of spiders and used in the construction of the web."
"To burn superficially; to parch  or shrivel the surface of by heat; to subject to so much heat as changes color and texture without consuming; as to scorch linen."
"A notch or incision; especially  one that is made as a tally mark; hence a mark or line made for the purpose of account."
"The recrement of metals in fusion  or the slag rejected after the reduction of metallic ores; dross."

"To reduce to scoria or slag; specifically  in assaying to fuse so as to separate the gangue and earthy material with borax lead soda etc. thus leaving the gold and silver in a lead button; hence to separate from or by means of a slag."
"Extreme and lofty contempt; haughty disregard; that disdain which springs from the opinion of the utter meanness and unworthiness of an object."
"One who scorns; a despiser; a contemner; specifically  a scoffer at religion."
"The keeping of an alehouse by an officer of a forest  and drawing people to spend their money for liquor for fear of his displeasure."
"Of or pertaining to Scotland  its language or its inhabitants; Scottish."
"Any one of several species of northern sea ducks of the genus Oidemia."
"A concave molding used especially in classical architecture."

"A follower of (Joannes) Duns Scotus  the Franciscan scholastic (d. 1308) who maintained certain doctrines in philosophy and theology in opposition to the Thomists or followers of Thomas Aquinas the Dominican scholastic."
"Of or pertaining to the Scotch; Scotch; Scottish; as  Scots law; a pound Scots (1s. 8d.)."

"To rub hard with something rough  as sand or Bristol brick especially for the purpose of cleaning; to clean by friction; to make clean or bright; to cleanse from grease dirt etc. as articles of dress."
"A lash; a strap or cord; especially  a lash used to inflict pain or punishment; an instrument of punishment or discipline; a whip."
"A sailor's dish. Bread scouse contains no meat; lobscouse contains meat  etc. See Lobscouse."
"A mop for sweeping ovens; a malkin."
"A large flat-bottomed boat  having broad square ends."
"To wrinkle the brows  as in frowning or displeasure; to put on a frowning look; to look sour sullen severe or angry."
"Something thin  lean or rough; a bony piece; especially a bony neckpiece of meat; hence humorously or in contempt the neck."
"To grind with the teeth  and with a crackling sound; to craunch."
"Something scraped off; hence  a small piece; a bit; a fragment; a detached incomplete portion."

"To rub over the surface of (something) with a sharp or rough instrument; to rub over with something that roughens by removing portions of the surface; to grate harshly over; to abrade; to make even  or bring to a required condition or form by moving the sharp edge of an instrument breadthwise over the surface with pressure cutting away excesses and superfluous parts; to make smooth or clean; as to scrape a bone with a knife; to scrape a metal plate to an even surface."
"An instrument with which anything is scraped."
"Consisting of scraps; fragmentary; lacking unity or consistency; as  a scrappy lecture."
"To rub and tear or mark the surface of with something sharp or ragged; to scrape  roughen or wound slightly by drawing something pointed or rough across as the claws the nails a pin or the like."
"To utter suddenly a sharp  shrill sound; to screech; to creak as a door or wheel."
"To cry out with a shrill voice; to utter a sudden  sharp outcry or shrill loud cry as in fright or extreme pain; to shriek; to screech."
"A pebble; a stone; also  a heap of stones or rocky debris."
"To utter a harsh  shrill cry; to make a sharp outcry as in terror or acute pain; to scream; to shriek."
"A strip of plaster of the thickness proposed for the coat  applied to the wall at intervals of four or five feet as a guide."
"Anything that separates or cuts off inconvenience  injury or danger; that which shelters or conceals from view; a shield or protection; as a fire screen."

"A cylinder  or a cylindrical perforation having a continuous rib called the thread winding round it spirally at a constant inclination so as to leave a continuous spiral groove between one turn and the next -- used chiefly for producing when revolved motion or pressure in the direction of its axis by the sliding of the threads of the cylinder in the grooves between the threads of the perforation adapted to it the former being distinguished as the external or male screw
"One who writes; a draughtsman; a writer for another; especially  an offical or public writer; an amanuensis or secretary; a notary; a copyist."
"A sharp-pointed tool  used by joiners for drawing lines on stuff; a marking awl."
"A kind of light cotton or linen fabric  often woven in openwork patterns -- used for curtains etc ; -- called also India scrim."
"To make too small or short; to limit or straiten; to put on short allowance; to scant; to contract; to shorten; as  to scrimp the pattern of a coat."
"A chest  bookcase or other place where writings or curiosities are deposited; a shrine."
"A small bag; a wallet; a satchel."
"A young codfish  especially when cut open on the back and dressed."
"A roll of paper or parchment; a writing formed into a roll; a schedule; a list."
"Of or pertaining to the scrotum; as  scrotal hernia."
"The bag or pouch which contains the testicles; the cod."
"To rub hard; to wash with rubbing; usually  to rub with a wet brush or with something coarse or rough for the purpose of cleaning or brightening; as to scrub a floor a doorplate."
"Of the nature of scrub; small and mean; stunted in growth; as  a scrubby cur."
"A weight of twenty grains; the third part of a dram."
"To move swiftly; especially  to move as if driven forward by something."
"To run hastily; to hurry; to scuttle."
"A silver coin  and money of account used in Italy and Sicily varying in value in different parts but worth about 4 shillings sterling or about 96 cents; also a gold coin worth about the same."
"The back part of the neck; the scruff."
"To strive or struggle with a close grapple; to wrestle in a rough fashion."
"A boat rowed by one man with two sculls  or short oars."

"Any one of numerous species of marine cottoid fishes of the genus Cottus  or Acanthocottus having a large head armed with sharp spines and a broad mouth. They are generally mottled with yellow brown and black. Several species are found on the Atlantic coasts of Europe and America."
"The extraneous matter or impurities which rise to the surface of liquids in boiling or fermentation  or which form on the surface by other means; also the scoria of metals in a molten state; dross."

"To cover lighty  as a painting or a drawing with a thin wash of opaque color or with color-crayon dust rubbed on with the stump or to make any similar additions to the work so as to produce a softened effect."
"Covered with scum; of the nature of scum."
"To cause to loathe  or feel disgust at."
"An opening cut through the waterway and bulwarks of a ship  so that water falling on deck may flow overboard; -- called also scupper hole."
"Thin dry scales or scabs upon the body; especially  thin scales exfoliated from the cuticle particularly of the scalp; dandruff."
"Having or producing scurf; covered with scurf; resembling scurf."
"To hasten away or along; to move rapidly; to hurry; as  the rabbit scurried away."
"Covered or affected with scurf or scabs; scabby; scurfy; specifically  diseased with the scurvy."
"The tail of a hare  or of a deer or other animal whose tail is short sp. when carried erect; hence sometimes the animal itself."
"Shield money; commutation of service for a sum of money. See Escuage."
"An oblong shield made of boards or wickerwork covered with leather  with sometimes an iron rim; -- carried chiefly by the heavy-armed infantry."
"Arm scye  a cutter's term for the armhole or part of the armhole of the waist of a garnment."

"A dangerous rock on the Italian coast opposite the whirpool Charybdis on the coast of Sicily  -- both personified in classical literature as ravenous monsters. The passage between them was formerly considered perilous; hence the saying """"Between Scylla and Charybdis " signifying a great peril on either hand."
"A kind of large drinking cup  -- used by Greeks and Romans esp. by poor folk."
"An instrument for mowing grass  grain or the like by hand composed of a long curving blade with a sharp edge made fast to a long handle called a snath which is bent into a form convenient for use."
"An exclamation expressive of impatience or anger."

"One of the larger bodies of salt water  less than an ocean found on the earth's surface; a body of salt water of second rank generally forming part of or connecting with an ocean or a larger sea; as the Mediterranean Sea; the Sea of Marmora; the North Sea; the Carribean Sea."
"A boat or vessel adapted to the open sea; hence  a vessel considered with reference to her power of resisting a storm or maintaining herself in a heavy sea; as a good sea boat."
"Any gorgonian which branches in a fanlike form  especially Gorgonia flabellum of Florida and the West Indies."
"A sertularian hydroid  especially Sertularia abietina which branches like a miniature fir tree."
"Surrounded by the water of the sea or ocean; as  a seagirt isle."
"A marine deity; a fabulous being supposed to live in  or have dominion over the sea or some particular sea or part of the sea as Neptune."
"A Jewish dry measure containing one third of an an ephah."
"the common guillemot; -- applied also to various other sea birds."
"Soap prepared for use in milling cloth."
"Any aquatic carnivorous mammal of the families Phocidae and Otariidae."
"One who seals; especially  an officer whose duty it is to seal writs or instruments to stamp weights and measures or the like."
"A merman; the male of the mermaid."
"Any elevated object on land which serves as a guide to mariners; a beacon; a landmark visible from the sea  as a hill a tree a steeple or the like."
"Any bryozoan of the genus Flustra or allied genera which form frondlike corals."
"A rich slimy deposit in salt marshes and along the seashore  sometimes used as a manure; -- called also sea ooze."
"Having a seam; containing seams  or showing them."
"A session  as of some public body; especially a meeting of spiritualists to receive spirit communication so called."
"The oyster catcher  a limicoline bird of the genus Haematopus."
"A port on the seashore  or one accessible for seagoing vessels. Also used adjectively; as a seaport town."

"[OE. seer  AS. sear (assumed) fr. searian to wither; akin to D. zoor dry LG. soor OHG. sor/n to to wither Gr. a""""y`ein to parch to dry Skr. /ush (for sush) to dry to wither Zend hush to dry. �152. Cf. Austere Sorrel a.] Dry; withered; no longer green; -- applied to leaves."
"To look over or through  for the purpose of finding something; to examine; to explore; as to search the city."
"The land bordering on  or adjacent to the sea; the seashore. Also used adjectively."

"One of the divisions of the year  marked by alternations in the length of day and night or by distinct conditions of temperature moisture etc. caused mainly by the relative position of the earth with respect to the sun. In the north temperate zone four seasons namely spring summer autumn and winter
"The place or thing upon which one sits; hence; anything made to be sat in or upon  as a chair bench stool saddle or the like."
"The name used by the Algonquin Indians for the shell beads which passed among the Indians as money."
"Seaweed; esp.  coarse seaweed. See Ware and Sea girdles."
"Popularly  any plant or plants growing in the sea."

"Of or pertaining to fat; derived from  or resembling fat; specifically designating an acid (formerly called also sebic and pyroleic acid) obtained by the distillation or saponification of certain oils (as castor oil) as a white crystalline substance."
"The eleventh month of the ancient Hebrew year  approximately corresponding with February."
"A genus of cereal grasses including rye."
"A cutting; an intersection; as  the point of secancy of one line by another."
"Cutting; divivding into two parts; as  a secant line."
"To withdraw from fellowship  communion or association; to separate one's self by a solemn act; to draw off; to retire; especially to withdraw from a political or religious body."

"The edible fruit of a West Indian plant (Sechium edule) of the Gourd family. It is soft  pear-shaped and about four inches long and contains a single large seed. The root of the plant resembles a yam and is used for food."
"Barren; unprofitable. See Rent seck  under Rent."
"A small reddish brown sweet and juicy pear. It originated on a farm near Philadelphia  afterwards owned by a Mr. Seckel."
"To shut up apart from others; to withdraw into  or place in solitude; to separate from society or intercourse with others."
"Immediately following the first; next to the first in order of place or time; hence  occuring again; another; other."
"The second part in a concerted piece."
"The state or quality of being hidden; as  his movements were detected in spite of their secrecy."
"Hidden; concealed; as  secret treasure; secret plans; a secret vow."
"To deposit in a place of hiding; to hide; to conceal; as  to secrete stolen goods; to secrete one's self."
"One of the portions of space bounded by the three coordinate planes. Specif. (Crystallog.)  one of the parts of a crystal into which it is divided by the axial planes."
"A sectarian; a member or adherent of a sect; a follower or disciple of some particular teacher in philosophy or religion; one who separates from an established church; a dissenter."
"Capable of being cut; specifically (Min.)  capable of being severed by the knife with a smooth cut; -- said of minerals."
"The act of cutting  or separation by cutting; as the section of bodies."
"One devoted to a sect; a soetary."
"A part of a circle comprehended between two radii and the included arc."
"Coming or observed once in an age or a century."
"Arranged on one side only  as flowers or leaves on a stalk."
"Free from fear  care or anxiety; easy in mind; not feeling suspicion or distrust; confident."
"A portable chair or covered vehicle for carrying a single person  -- usually borne on poles by two men. Called also sedan chair."
"Undisturbed by passion or caprice; calm; tranquil; serene; not passionate or giddy; composed; staid; as  a sedate soul mind or temper."

"Any plant of the genus Carex  perennial endogenous herbs often growing in dense tufts in marshy places. They have triangular jointless stems a spiked inflorescence and long grasslike leaves which are usually rough on the margins and midrib. There are several hundred species."
"Seats in the chancel of a church near the altar for the officiating clergy during intervals of service."
"To draw aside from the path of rectitude and duty in any manner; to entice to evil; to lead astray; to tempt and lead to iniquity; to corrupt."
"One who  or that which seduces; specifically one who prevails over the chastity of a woman by enticements and persuasions."
"A genus of plants  mostly perennial having succulent leaves and cymose flowers; orpine; stonecrop."
"A seat; a site; a place where sovereign power is exercised."
"One who  or that which sows or plants seed."
"A vessel in which a sower carries the seed to be scattered."
"Abounding with seeds; bearing seeds; having run to seeds."
"One who seeks; that which is used in seeking or searching."
"To close the eyes of (a hawk or other bird) by drawing through the lids threads which were fastened over the head."
"To appear  or to appear to be; to have a show or semblance; to present an appearance; to look; to strike one's apprehension or fancy as being; to be taken as."
"One who seems; one who carries or assumes an appearance or semblance."
"Suited to the object  occasion purpose or character; suitable; fit; becoming; comely; decorous."
"To run or soak through fine pores and interstices; to ooze."
"Water that seeped or oozed through a porous soil."
"Oozy; -- applied to land under cultivation that is not well drained."
"A play among children in which they are seated upon the opposite ends of a plank which is balanced in the middle  and move alternately up and down."
"To decoct or prepare for food in hot liquid; to boil; as  to seethe flesh."
"A pot for boiling things; a boiler."
"A case or holder made of fire clay  in which fine pottery is inclosed while baking in the kin."
"One of the parts into which any body naturally separates or is divided; a part divided or cut off; a section; a portion; as  a segment of an orange; a segment of a compound or divided leaf."
"A sign. See Al segno  and Dal segno."
"A liliaceous plant (Calochortus Nuttallii) of Western North America  and its edible bulb; -- so called by the Ute Indians and the Mormons."
"Local oscillations in level observed in the case of some lakes  as Lake Geneva."
"A descendant of Mohammed through his daughter Fatima and nephew Ali."
"A large net  one edge of which is provided with sinkers and the other with floats. It hangs vertically in the water and when its ends are brought together or drawn ashore incloses the fish."
"Of or pertaining to an earthquake; caused by an earthquake."
"To fall or rush upon suddenly and lay hold of; to gripe or grasp suddenly; to reach and grasp."

"Possession; possession of an estate of froehold. It may be either in deed or in law; the former when there is actual possession  the latter when there is a right to such possession by construction of law. In some of the United States seizin means merely ownership."
"The act of seizing  or the state of being seized; sudden and violent grasp or gripe; a taking into possession; as the seizure of a thief a property a throne etc."
"Sitting  as a lion or other beast."
"A place in a pagan temple in which the images of the deities were inclosed."
"A word of doubtful meaning  occuring frequently in the Psalms; by some supposed to signify silence or a pause in the musical performance of the song."
"Taken from a number by preferance; picked out as more valuable or exellent than others; of special value or exellence; nicely chosen; selected; choice."
"Of or pertaining to selenium; derived from  or containing selenium; specifically designating those compounds in which the element has a higher valence as contrasted with selenious compounds."
"Caring supremely or unduly for one's self; regarding one's own comfort  advantage etc. in disregard or at the expense of those of others."
"Concentration of one's interests on one's self; self-love; selfishness."
"A short piece of land in arable ridges and furrows  of uncertain quantity; also a ridge of land lying between two furrows."
"To imitate; to make a representation or likeness."
"Sprinkled or sown; -- said of field  or a charge when strewed or covered with small charges."
"A daughter of Cadmus  and by Zeus mother of Bacchus."
"A yellowish alloy of copper and zinc. See Simplor."
"Pertaining to  containing or consisting of seed or semen; as the seminal fluid."
"Thickly covered or sown  as with seeds."
"A fasciole of a spatangoid sea urchin."
"One belonging to the Semitic race. Also used adjectively."
"Of or pertaining to Shem or his descendants; belonging to that division of the Caucasian race which includes the Arabs  Jews and related races."
"Always; throughout; as  sempre piano always soft."
"A Japanese coin  worth about one half of a cent."
"Of six; belonging to six; containing six."
"An assembly or council having the highest deliberative and legislative functions."
"To cause to go in any manner; to dispatch; to commission or direct to go; as  to send a messenger."
"A tribe of Indians who formerly inhabited a part of Western New York. This tribe was the most numerous and most warlike of the Five Nations."
"A very large genus of composite plants including the groundsel and the golden ragwort."
"A substance extracted from the rootstock of the Polygala Senega (Seneca root)  and probably identical with polygalic acid."
"Of or pertaining to old age; proceeding from  or characteristic of old age; affected with the infirmities of old age; as senile weakness."
"More advanced than another in age; prior in age; elder; hence  more advanced in dignity rank or office; superior; as senior member; senior counsel."
"The leaves of several leguminous plants of the genus Cassia. (C. acutifolia  C. angustifolia etc.). They constitute a valuable but nauseous cathartic medicine."
"A signal call on a trumpet or cornet for entrance or exit on the stage."
"A braided cord or fabric formed by plaiting together rope yarns or other small stuff."
"A Spanish title of courtesy corresponding to the English Mr. or Sir; also  a gentleman."
"A Spanish title of courtesy given to a lady; Mrs.; Madam; also  a lady."
"To feel or apprehend more or less distinctly through a sense  or the senses; as to sensate light or an odor."

"A faculty  possessed by animals of perceiving external objects by means of impressions made upon certain organs (sensory or sense organs) of the body or of perceiving changes in the condition of the body; as the senses of sight smell hearing taste and touch. See Muscular sense under Muscular and Temperature sense under Temperature."
"One who  in philosophy holds to sensism."

"Of or pertaining to the sensorium or sensation; as  sensory impulses; -- especially applied to those nerves and nerve fibers which convey to a nerve center impulses resulting in sensation; also sometimes loosely employed in the sense of afferent to indicate nerve fibers which convey impressions of any kind to a nerve center."
"Pertaining to  consisting in or affecting the sense or bodily organs of perception; relating to or concerning the body in distinction from the spirit."
"A place for dregs and dirt; a sink; a sewer."
"A soldier placed on guard; a sentinel."
"A leaf or division of the calyx."
"A large sting ray of the genus Trygon  especially T. sephen of the Indian Ocean and the Red Sea. The skin is an article of commerce."
"Of or pertaining to sepia; done in sepia; as  a sepic drawing."
"A native of India employed as a soldier in the service of a European power  esp. of Great Britain; an Oriental soldier disciplined in the European manner."
"A soluble poison (ptomaine) present in putrid blood. It is also formed in the putrefaction of proteid matter in general."
