"To splash or wet carelessly; as  to sozzle the feet in water."
"A spring or mineral water; -- so called from a place of this name in Belgium."
"A kind of spar; earth flax  or amianthus."
"Extension  considered independently of anything which it may contain; that which makes extended objects conceivable and possible."
"A hart or stag three years old."
"One who  or that which spades; specifically a digging machine."
"A fleshy spike of flowers  usually inclosed in a leaf called a spathe."
"A lath; a shaving or chip  as of wood or stone."
"A rope used for tying or hobbling the legs of a horse or cow."
"A small plate or boss of shining metal; something brilliant used as an ornament  especially when stitched on the dress."
"Resembling  or consisting of spangles; glittering; as spangly light."
"One of a breed of small dogs having long and thick hair and large drooping ears. The legs are usually strongly feathered  and the tail bushy. See Illust. under Clumber and Cocker."
"Of or pertaining to Spain or the Spaniards."
"To strike  as the breech with the open hand; to slap."
"One who spanks  or anything used as an instrument for spanking."

"An old name for a nonmetallic mineral  usually cleavable and somewhat lustrous; as calc spar or calcite fluor spar etc. It was especially used in the case of the gangue minerals of a metalliferous vein."
"A small California surf fish (Micrometrus aggregatus); -- called also shiner."
"To use frugally or stintingly  as that which is scarce or valuable; to retain or keep unused; to save."
"To sprinkle; to moisten by sprinkling; as  to sparge paper."
"A vessel with a perforated cover  for sprinkling with a liquid; a sprinkler."
"A small particle of fire or ignited substance which is emitted by a body in combustion."
"Of or pertaining to the Sparidae  a family of spinous-finned fishes which includes the scup sheepshead and sea bream."

"One of many species of small singing birds of the family Fringilligae  having conical bills and feeding chiefly on seeds. Many sparrows are called also finches and buntings. The common sparrow or house sparrow of Europe (Passer domesticus) is noted for its familiarity its voracity its attachment to its young and its fecundity. See House sparrow under House."
"Resembling spar  or consisting of spar; abounding with spar; having a confused crystalline structure; spathose."
"Thinly scattered; set or planted here and there; not being dense or close together; as  a sparse population."
"Of or pertaining to Sparta  especially to ancient Sparta; hence hardy; undaunted; as Spartan souls; Spartan bravey."
"An involuntary and unnatural contraction of one or more muscles or muscular fibers."
"Of or pertaining to spasm; spasmodic; especially  pertaining to tonic spasm; tetanic."
"A river flood; an overflow or inundation."
"Furnished with a spathe; as  spathal flowers."
"A special involucre formed of one leaf and inclosing a spadix  as in aroid plants and palms. See the Note under Bract and Illust. of Spadix."
"Having a spathe or calyx like a sheath."
"To sprinkle with a liquid or with any wet substance  as water mud or the like; to make wet of foul spots upon by sprinkling; as to spatter a coat; to spatter the floor; to spatter boots with mud."
"An implement shaped like a knife  flat thin and somewhat flexible used for spreading paints fine plasters drugs in compounding prescriptions etc. Cf. Palette knife under Palette."

"A disease of horses characterized by a bony swelling developed on the hock as the result of inflammation of the bones; also  the swelling itself. The resulting lameness is due to the inflammation and not the bony tumor as popularly supposed."
"A splinter or fragment  as of wood or stone. See Spall."
"To produce or deposit (eggs)  as fishes or frogs do."
"To remove or extirpate the ovaries of  as a sow or a bitch; to castrate (a female animal)."
"To utter words or articulate sounds  as human beings; to express thoughts by words; as the organs may be so obstructed that a man may not be able to speak."
"A long  pointed weapon used in war and hunting by thrusting or throwing; a weapon with a long shaft and a sharp head or blade; a lance."
"One who uses a spear; as  a spearer of fish."
"Of or pertaining to a species; constituting a species or sort."
"abl. of L. species sort  kind. Used in the phrase in specie that is in sort in kind in (its own) form."
"Visible or sensible presentation; appearance; a sensible percept received by the imagination; an image."
"To mention or name  as a particular thing; to designate in words so as to distinguish from other things; as to specify the uses of a plant; to specify articles purchased."
"The blubber of whales or other marine mammals; also  the fat of the hippopotamus."
"A little or spot in or anything  of a different substance or color from that of the thing itself."
"Something preternaturally visible; an apparition; a ghost; a phantom."
"The faculty of uttering articulate sounds or words; the faculty of expressing thoughts by words or articulate sounds; the power of speaking."
"Prosperity in an undertaking; favorable issue; success."
"Not dilatory or slow; quick; swift; nimble; hasty; rapid in motion or performance; as  a speedy flight; on speedy foot."
"A woodpecker; -- called also specht  spekt spight."
"A regulus consisting essentially of nickel  obtained as a residue in fusing cobalt and nickel ores with silica and sodium carbonate to make smalt."
"A small stick or rod used as a spike in thatching; a splinter."
"Zinc; -- especially so called in commerce and arts."
"A place where provisions are kept; a buttery; a larder; a pantry."
"One who has the care of the spence  or buttery."
"To weigh or lay out; to dispose of; to part with; as  to spend money for clothing."
"One who spends; esp.  one who spends lavishly; a prodigal; a spendthrift."
"To shut in; to support; to inclose; to fasten."
"Hoped for  or to be hoped for."
"To search; to pry; to ask; to inquire."
"A charge of wash for the still."
"The male fecundating fluid; semen. See Semen."
"Of or pertaining to sperm  or semen."
"To eject from the stomach; to vomit."
"A mineral found usually in thin  wedge-shaped crystals of a yellow or green to black color. It is a silicate of titanium and calcium; titanite."
"Of or pertaining to a sphere or the spheres."
"A body or space contained under a single surface  which in every part is equally distant from a point within called its center."
"Having the form of a sphere; like a sphere; globular; orbicular; as  a spherical body."
"Any one of numerous species of sand wasps of the genus Sphex and allied genera. These wasps have the abdomen attached to the thorax by a slender pedicel. See Illust. of Sand wasp  under Sand."
"In Egyptian art  an image of granite or porphyry having a human head or the head of a ram or of a hawk upon the wingless body of a lion."
"A kind of bandage passing  by successive turns and crosses from an extremity to the trunk; -- so called from its resemblance to a spike of a barley."
"Having spikes  or ears like corn spikes."
"Flavored with  or containing spice or spices; fragrant; aromatic; as spicy breezes."

"Any one of numerous species of arachnids comprising the order Araneina. Spiders have the mandibles converted into poison fangs  or falcers. The abdomen is large and not segmented with two or three pairs of spinnerets near the end by means of which they spin threads of silk to form cocoons or nests to protect their eggs and young. Many species spin also complex webs to entrap the insects upon which they prey. The eyes are usually eight in number (rarely six) and are situated on the back of the cephalothorax. See Illust. under Araneina."
"An aromatic plant of America. See Spikenard."
"A pin or peg used to stop the vent in a cask; also  the plug of a faucet or cock."
"A sort of very large nail; also  a piece of pointed iron set with points upward or outward."
"A small plug or wooden pin  used to stop a vent as in a cask."
"A bit of wood split off; a splinter."
"Any one of the small branches on a stag's head."
"Anything spilt  or freely poured out; slop; effusion."
"To draw out  and twist into threads either by the hand or machinery; as to spin wool cotton or flax; to spin goat's hair; to produce by drawing out and twisting a fibrous material."
"A common pot herb (Spinacia oleracea) belonging to the Goosefoot family."
"Of  pertaining to or in the region of the backbone or vertebral column; rachidian; vertebral."

"The long  round slender rod or pin in spinning wheels by which the thread is twisted and on which when twisted it is wound; also the pin on which the bobbin is held in a spinning machine or in the shuttle of a loom."
"A sharp appendage to any of a plant; a thorn."

"A keyed instrument of music resembling a harpsichord  but smaller with one string of brass or steel wire to each note sounded by means of leather or quill plectrums or jacks. It was formerly much used."
"One who  or that which spins one skilled in spinning; a spinning machine."
"A small thicket or grove with undergrowth; a clump of trees."
"Full of spines; armed with thorns; thorny."
"Full of spines; thorny; as  a spiny tree."

"An extensive division of marine Annelida  including those that are without oral tentacles or cirri and have the gills when present mostly arranged along the sides of the body. They generally live in burrows or tubes."
"A genus of shrubs or perennial herbs including the meadowsweet and the hardhack."
"Winding or circling round a center or pole and gradually receding from it; as  the spiral curve of a watch spring."

"A term used differently by different authorities; -- by some as equivalent to fricative  -- that is as including all the continuous consonants except the nasals m n ng; with the further exception by others of the liquids r l and the semivowels w y; by others limited to f v
"Air set in motion by breathing; breath; hence  sometimes life itself."
"A genus of cephalopods having a multilocular  internal siphunculated shell in the form of a flat spiral the coils of which are not in contact."
"Of a spiral form; wreathed; curled; serpentine."
"A long  slender pointed rod usually of iron for holding meat while roasting."
"Ill-will or hatred toward another  accompanied with the disposition to irritate annoy or thwart; petty malice; grudge; rancor; despite."
"One who ejects saliva from the mouth."
"To strike and dash about  as water mud etc.; to plash."
"Full of dirty water; wet and muddy  so as be easily splashed about; slushy."
"A peculiar glandlike but ductless organ found near the stomach or intestine of most vertebrates and connected with the vascular system; the milt. Its exact function in not known."
"A cloth dipped in a liquid for washing a sore."
"Of or pertaining to the spleen; lienal; as  the splenic vein."
"To unite  as two ropes or parts of a rope by a particular manner of interweaving the strands -- the union being between two ends or between an end and the body of a rope."

"A rectangular piece fitting grooves like key seats in a hub and a shaft  so that while the one may slide endwise on the other both must revolve together; a feather; also sometimes a groove to receive such a rectangular piece."
"A blustering demonstration  or great effort; a great display."
"To plunder; to strip by violence; to pillage; to rob; -- with of before the name of the thing taken; as  to spoil one of his goods or possession."
"One who spoils; a plunderer; a pillager; a robber; a despoiler."
"A poetic foot of two long syllables  as in the Latin word leges."
"An irregular  narrow projecting part of a field."
"Any one of numerous species of Spongiae  or Porifera. See Illust. and Note under Spongiae."
"One who sponges  or uses a sponge."
"The chemical basis of sponge tissue  a nitrogenous hornlike substance which on decomposition with sulphuric acid yields leucin and glycocoll."
"Soft  and full of cavities; of an open loose pliable texture; as a spongy excrescence; spongy earth; spongy cake; spongy bones."
"Relating to marriage  or to a spouse; spousal."
"One of the triangular platforms in front of  and abaft the paddle boxes of a steamboat."
"One who binds himself to answer for another  and is responsible for his default; a surety."
"A spirit; a ghost; an apparition; a hobgoblin."
"A piece of cane or red with a knot at each end  or a hollow cylinder of wood with a ridge at each end used to wind thread or yarn upon."
"To be driven steadily and swiftly  as before a strong wind; to be driven before the wind without any sail or with only a part of the sails spread; to scud under bare poles."
"The track or trail of any wild animal; as  the spoor of an elephant; -- used originally by travelers in South Africa."
"One of the minute grains in flowerless plants  which are analogous to seeds as serving to reproduce the species."
"A large purse or pouch made of skin with the hair or fur on  worn in front of the kilt by Highlanders when in full dress."
"That which diverts  and makes mirth; pastime; amusement."
"Of or pertaining to sports; used in sports."
"A mark on a substance or body made by foreign matter; a blot; a place discolored."
"Of or pertaining to a spouse or marriage; nuptial; matrimonial; conjugal; bridal; as  spousal rites; spousal ornaments."
"A man or woman engaged or joined in wedlock; a married person  husband or wife."
"To throw out forcibly and abudantly  as liquids through an office or a pipe; to eject in a jet; as an elephant spouts water from his trunk."
"To weaken  as a joint ligament or muscle by sudden and excessive exertion as by wrenching; to overstrain or stretch injuriously but without luxation; as to sprain one's ankle."
"A small European herring (Clupea sprattus) closely allied to the common herring and the pilchard; -- called also garvie. The name is also applied to small herring of different kinds."
"To spread and stretch the body or limbs carelessly in a horizontal position; to lie with the limbs stretched out ungracefully."
"Small branches of a tree; twigs; sprays."
"A small shoot or branch; a twig."
"A merry frolic; especially  a drinking frolic; a carousal."
"A small shoot or twig of a tree or other plant; a spray; as  a sprig of laurel or of parsley."
"Spirit; mind; soul; state of mind; mood."
"A noose fastened to an elastic body  and drawn close with a sudden spring whereby it catches a bird or other animal; a gin; a snare."
"Resembling  having the qualities of or pertaining to a spring; elastic; as springy steel; a springy step."
"To run very rapidly; to run at full speed."
"To throw out with force from a narrow orifice; to eject; to spurt out."
"A spirit; a soul; a shade; also  an apparition. See Spright."
"To shoot  as the seed of a plant; to germinate; to push out new shoots; hence to grow like shoots of plants."
"Any coniferous tree of the genus Picea  as the Norway spruce (P. excelsa) and the white and black spruces of America (P. alba and P. nigra) besides several others in the far Northwest. See Picea."
"Strictly  the hole through which melted metal is poured into the gate and thence into the mold."
"To spring up; to germinate; to spring forward or outward."
"Having great power of leaping or running; nimble; active."
"A sharp  narrow spade usually with a long handle used by farmers for digging up large-rooted weeds; a similarly shaped implement used for various purposes."
"One employed to inspect yarn  to see that it is well spun and fit for the loom."
"Frothy matter raised on liquids by boiling  effervescence or agitation; froth; foam; scum."
"Consisting of  containing or covered with froth scum or foam; frothy; foamy."
"Wood that readily takes fire; touchwood; also  a kind of tinder made from a species of fungus; punk; amadou."
"To emit foam; to froth; -- said of the emission of yeast from beer in course of fermentation."
"To drive back or away  as with the foot; to kick."
"An annual herb (Spergula arvensis) with whorled filiform leaves  sometimes grown in Europe for fodder."
"To gush or issue suddenly or violently out in a stream  as liquor from a cask; to rush from a confined place in a small stream or jet; to spirt."
"A sudden or violent ejection or gushing of a liquid  as of water from a tube orifice or other confined place or of blood from a wound; a jet; a spirt."
"To spurt or shoot in a scattering manner."
"An annular reenforce  to strengthen a place where a hole is made."
"To spit  or to emit saliva from the mouth in small scattered portions as in rapid speaking."
"That which is expectorated; a salival discharge; spittle; saliva."
"To gain sight of; to discover at a distance  or in a state of concealment; to espy; to see."
"A boat sent to make discoveries and bring intelligence."
"A heron (Ardea comata) found in Asia  Northern Africa and Southern Europe."
"A small party of men assembled for drill  inspection or other purposes."
"To throw sticls at cocks; to throw anything about awkwardly or irregularly."
"The suborder of elasmobranch fishes which comprises the sharks."
"Dirty through neglect; foul; filthy; extremely dirty."
"A sudden violent gust of wind often attended with rain or snow."
"Abounding with squalls; disturbed often with sudden and violent gusts of wind; gusty; as  squally weather."
"A scale cast off from the skin; a thin dry shred consisting of epithelium."
"The corner  or angle of a figure."
"An American animal allied to the weasel."
"A female; a woman; -- in the language of Indian tribes of the Algonquin family  correlative of sannup."
"To utter a shrill  abrupt scream; to squeak harshly."
"To utter a sharp  shrill cry usually of short duration; to cry with an acute tone as an animal; or to make a sharp disagreeable noise as a pipe or quill a wagon wheel a door; to creak."
"To cry with a sharp  shrill prolonged sound as certain animals do indicating want displeasure or pain."

"To press between two bodies; to press together closely; to compress; often  to compress so as to expel juice moisture etc.; as to squeeze an orange with the fingers; to squeeze the hand in friendship."
"To quell; to crush; to silence or put down."
"A little pipe  or hollow cylinder of paper filled with powder or combustible matter to be thrown into the air while burning so as to burst there with a crack."

"Any one of numerous species of ten-armed cephalopods having a long  tapered body and a caudal fin on each side; especially any species of Loligo Ommastrephes and related genera. See Calamary Decacerata Dibranchiata."
"A company of squires; the whole body of squires."
"A European bulbous liliaceous plant (Urginea  formerly Scilla maritima) of acrid expectorant diuretic and emetic properties used in medicine. Called also sea onion."
"Any one of numerous stomapod crustaceans of the genus Squilla and allied genera. They make burrows in mud or beneath stones on the seashore. Called also mantis shrimp. See Illust. under Stomapoda."
"A small arch thrown across the corner of a square room to support a superimposed mass  as where an octagonal spire or drum rests upon a square tower; -- called also sconce and sconcheon."
"Looking obliquely. Specifically (Med.)  not having the optic axes coincident; -- said of the eyes. See Squint n. 2."
"To throw with a jerk; to throw edge foremost."
"To twist about briskly with contor/ions like an eel or a worm; to wriggle; to writhe."
"To drive or eject in a stream out of a narrow pipe or orifice; as  to squirt water."
"The body of squires  collectively considered; squirarchy."
"To pierce with a pointed weapon; to wound or kill by the thrust of a pointed instrument; as  to stab a man with a dagger; also to thrust; as to stab a dagger into a person."
"One who  or that which stabs; a privy murderer."
"Firmly established; not easily moved  shaken or overthrown; fixed; as a stable government."
"In a stable manner; firmly; fixedly; steadily; as  a government stably settled."
"A large pile of hay  grain straw or the like usually of a nearly conical form but sometimes rectangular or oblong contracted at the top to a point or ridge and sometimes covered with thatch."
"One of the sweet spices used by the ancient Jews in the preparation of incense. It was perhaps an oil or other form of myrrh or cinnamon  or a kind of storax."
"Anything which serves for support; a staff; a prop; a crutch; a cane."

"A Greek measure of length  being the chief one used for itinerary distances also adopted by the Romans for nautical and astronomical measurements. It was equal to 600 Greek or 625 Roman feet or 125 Roman paces or to 606 feet 9 inches English. This was also called the Olympic stadium as being the exact length of the foot-race course at Olympia."
"A long piece of wood; a stick; the long handle of an instrument or weapon; a pole or srick  used for many purposes; as a surveyor's staff; the staff of a spear or pike."
"The adult male of the red deer (Cervus elaphus)  a large European species closely related to the American elk or wapiti."
"A floor or story of a house."
"Pertaining to a stage; becoming the theater; theatrical."
"To move to one side and the other  as if about to fall in standing or walking; not to stand or walk with steadiness; to sway; to reel or totter."
"A structure of posts and boards for supporting workmen  etc. as in building."
"Sober; grave; steady; sedate; composed; regular; not wild  volatile or fanciful."
"To discolor by the application of foreign matter; to make foul; to spot; as  to stain the hand with dye; armor stained with blood."
"One step of a series for ascending or descending to a different level; -- commonly applied to those within a building."
"A landing place; an elevated staging upon a wharf for discharging coal  etc. as from railway cars into vessels."
"A piece of wood  usually long and slender pointed at one end so as to be easily driven into the ground as a support or stay; as a stake to support vines fences hedges etc."
"A wooden frame to set casks on."
"The stock or handle of anything; as  the stale of a rake."
"The stem or main axis of a plant; as  a stalk of wheat rye or oats; the stalks of maize or hemp."
"Hard as a stalk; resembling a stalk."
"A stand; a station; a fixed spot; hence  the stand or place where a horse or an ox kept and fed; the division of a stable or the compartment for one horse ox or other animal."
"A slip from a plant; a scion; a cutting."
"To make involuntary stops in uttering syllables or words; to hesitate or falter in speaking; to speak with stops and diffivulty; to stutter."
"To strike beat  or press forcibly with the bottom of the foot or by thrusting the foot downward."
"To stop the flowing of  as blood; to check; also to stop the flowing of blood from; as to stanch a wound."
"To be at rest in an erect position; to be fixed in an upright or firm position"
"A young tree  especially one reserved when others are cut."
"The kestrel; -- called also standgale  standgall stanchel stand hawk stannel hawk steingale stonegall."
"Of or pertaining to tin; derived from or containing tin; specifically  designating those compounds in which the element has a higher valence as contrasted with stannous compounds."
"The technical name of tin. See Tin."

"A number of lines or verses forming a division of a song or poem  and agreeing in meter rhyme number of lines etc. with other divisions; a part of a poem ordinarily containing every variation of measure in that poem; a combination or arrangement of lines usually recurring; whether like or unlike in measure."
"The innermost of the ossicles of the ear; the stirrup  or stirrup bone; -- so called from its form. See Illust. of Ear."
"A settled mart; an emporium; a city or town to which merchants brought commodities for sale or exportation in bulk; a place for wholesale traffic."
"One of the innumerable luminous bodies seen in the heavens; any heavenly body other than the sun  moon comets and nebulae."
"Consisting of starch; resembling starch; stiff; precise."
"One who  or that which starts; as a starter on a journey; the starter of a race."
"To move suddenly  or be excited on feeling alarm; to start."

"A slackening or arrest of the blood current in the vessels  due not to a lessening of the heart's beat but presumably to some abnormal resistance of the capillary walls. It is one of the phenomena observed in the capillaries in inflammation."
"Of  pertaining to or existing with reference to a State of the American Union as distinguished from the general government."
"In a standing position; as  a lion statant."
"The circumstances or condition of a being or thing at any given time."
"Evincing state or dignity; lofty; majestic; grand; as  statelymanners; a stately gait."
"That branch of mechanics which treats of the equilibrium of forces  or relates to bodies as held at rest by the forces acting on them; -- distinguished from dynamics."
"The act of standing; also  attitude or pose in standing; posture."
"The art of governing a state; statecraft; policy."
"A statesman; a politician; one skilled in government."
"Of or pertaining to a fixed camp  or military posts or quarters."
"The likeness of a living being sculptured or modeled in some solid substance  as marble bronze or wax; an image; as a statue of Hercules or of a lion."
"The natural height of an animal body; -- generally used of the human body."

"An act of the legislature of a state or country  declaring commanding or prohibiting something; a positive law; the written will of the legislature expressed with all the requisite forms of legislation; -- used in distinction fraom common law. See Common law under Common a."

"One of a number of narrow strips of wood  or narrow iron plates placed edge to edge to form the sides covering or lining of a vessel or structure; esp. one of the strips which form the sides of a cask a pail etc."
"To be fixed or set; to stay."

"A large  strong rope employed to support a mast by being extended from the head of one mast down to some other or to some part of the vessel. Those which lead forward are called fore-and-aft stays; those which lead to the vessel's side are called backstays. See Illust. of Ship."
"One who upholds or supports that which props; one who  or that which stays stops or restrains; also colloquially a horse man etc. that has endurance an a race."
"Firm in standing or position; not tottering or shaking; fixed; firm."
"A slice of beef  broiled or cut for broiling; -- also extended to the meat of other large animals; as venison steak; bear steak; pork steak; turtle steak."
"The elastic  aeriform fluid into which water is converted when heated to the boiling points; water in the state of vapor."
"A vessel propelled by steam; a steamship or steamboat."
"Consisting of  or resembling steam; full of steam; vaporous; misty."
"Pertaining to  or obtained from stearin or tallow; resembling tallow."

"One of the constituents of animal fats and also of some vegetable fats  as the butter of cacao. It is especially characterized by its solidity so that when present in considerable quantity it materially increases the hardness or raises the melting point of the fat as in mutton tallow. Chemically it is a compound of glyceryl with three molecules of stearic acid and hence is technically called tristearin or glyceryl tristearate."
"The hypothetical radical characteristic of stearic acid."
"A horse  especially a spirited horse for state of war; -- used chiefly in poetry or stately prose."
"To pierce with a sharp instrument; hence  to stitch; to sew; also to fix; to fasten."

"A variety of iron intermediate in composition and properties between wrought iron and cast iron (containing between one half of one per cent and one and a half per cent of carbon)  and consisting of an alloy of iron with an iron carbide. Steel unlike wrought iron can be tempered and retains magnetism. Its malleability decreases and fusibility increases with an increase in carbon."
"One who points  edges or covers with steel."
"A vessel  vat or cistern in which things are steeped."
"A spire; also  the tower and spire taken together; the whole of a structure if the roof is of spire form. See Spire."
"In a steep manner; with steepness; with precipitous declivity."
"A young male of the ox kind; especially  a common ox; a castrated taurine male from two to four years old. See the Note under Ox."
"One who steers; as  a boat steerer."
"To project upward  or make an angle with the horizon or with the line of a vessel's keel; -- said of the bowsprit etc."
"A small column or pillar  used as a monument milestone etc."
"Resembling  or used as a stela; columnar."
"To place or fix firmly or permanently."
"One of the ocelli of an insect. See Ocellus."
"One who  or that which stems (in any of the senses of the verbs)."
"Abounding in stems  or mixed with stems; -- said of tea dried currants etc."
"A crossbar of wood in a shaft  serving as a step."
"A piece of curved timber bolted to the stem  keelson and apron in a ship's frame near the bow."

"A thin plate of metal  leather or other material used in painting marking etc. The pattern is cut out of the plate which is then laid flat on the surface to be marked and the color brushed over it. Called also stencil plate."
"A herald  in the Iliad who had a very loud voice; hence any person having a powerful voice."
"To move the foot in walking; to advance or recede by raising and moving one of the feet to another resting place  or by moving both feet in succession."
"One of the vast plains in Southeastern Europe and in Asia  generally elevated and free from wood analogous to many of the prairies in Western North America. See Savanna."
"One who  or that which steps; as a quick stepper."
"A son of one's husband or wife by a former marriage."
"A unit of cubic measure in the metric system  being a cubic meter or kiloliter and equal to 35.3 cubic feet or nearly 1/ cubic yards."
"Producing little or no crop; barren; unfruitful; unproductive; not fertile; as  sterile land; a sterile desert; a sterile year."
"A small sturgeon (Acipenser ruthenus) found in the Caspian Sea and its rivers  and highly esteemed for its flavor. The finest caviare is made from its roe."
"Of or pertaining to the sternum; in the region of the sternum."
"Having a stern of a particular shape; -- used in composition; as  square-sterned."
"A plate of cartilage  or a series of bony or cartilaginous plates or segments in the median line of the pectoral skeleton of most vertebrates above fishes; the breastbone."
"To die  or cause to die; to perish. See Starve."
"Let it stand; -- a word used by proof readers to signify that something once erased  or marked for omission is to remain."
"One of the higher alcohols of the methane series  homologous with ethal and found in small quantities as an ethereal salt of stearic acid in spermaceti."
"To pack or stow  as cargo in a ship's hold. See Steeve."
"A small pond or pool where fish are kept for the table; a vivarium."
"A man employed in a large family  or on a large estate to manage the domestic concerns supervise other servants collect the rents or income keep accounts and the like."

"Strong; active; -- said especially of morbid states attended with excessive action of the heart and blood vessels  and characterized by strength and activity of the muscular and nervous system; as a sthenic fever."
"A sty on the eye. See Styan."
"Like  or having the qualities of antimony; antimonial."
"Antimonic; -- used with reference to certain compounds of antimony."

"Antimony hydride  or hydrogen antimonide a colorless gas produced by the action of nascent hydrogen on antimony. It has a characteristic odor and burns with a characteristic greenish flame. Formerly called also antimoniureted hydrogen."
"A verse  of whatever measure or number of feet."
"Of or pertaining to stichs  or lines; consisting of stichs or lines."
"A small shoot  or branch separated as by a cutting from a tree or shrub; also any stem or branch of a tree of any size cut for fuel or timber."
"One who  or that which sticks; as a bill sticker."
"Having the quality of sticking to a surface; adhesive; gluey; viscous; viscid; glutinous; tenacious."
"An anvil; also  a smith shop. See Stithy."
"Not easily bent; not flexible or pliant; not limber or flaccid; rigid; firm; as  stiff wood paper joints."
"To make stiff; to make less pliant or flexible; as  to stiffen cloth with starch."
"The joint next above the hock  and near the flank in the hind leg of the horse and allied animals; the joint corresponding to the knee in man; -- called also stifle joint. See Illust. under Horse."
"A mark made with a burning iron; a brand."
"Of or pertaining to the style of a dial."
"A pin set on the face of a dial  to cast a shadow; a style. See Style."
"Motionless; at rest; quiet; as  to stand still; to lie or sit still."

"A pole  or piece of wood constructed with a step or loop to raise the foot above the ground in walking. It is sometimes lashed to the leg and sometimes prolonged upward so as to be steadied by the hand or arm."
"Unreasonably elevated; pompous; stilted; as  a stilty style."
"A slight gleam or glimmer; a glimpse."

"Any sharp organ of offense and defense  especially when connected with a poison gland and adapted to inflict a wound by piercing; as the caudal sting of a scorpion. The sting of a bee or wasp is a modified ovipositor. The caudal sting or spine of a sting ray is a modified dorsal fin ray. The term is sometimes applied to the fang of a serpent. See Illust. of Scorpion."
"To emit a strong  offensive smell; to send out a disgusting odor."
"Any one of several species of small sandpipers  as the sanderling of Europe and America the dunlin the little stint of India (Tringa minuta) etc. Called also pume."
"The stalk or petiole of a frond  as of a fern."
"Settled pay or compensation for services  whether paid daily monthly or annually."
"The second joint of a maxilla of an insect or a crustacean."
"To engrave by means of dots  in distinction from engraving in lines."
"An appendage at the base of petioles or leaves  usually somewhat resembling a small leaf in texture and appearance."
"To change the place of in any manner; to move."
"One who  or that which stirs something; also one who moves about especially after sleep; as an early stirrer."

"A kind of ring  or bent piece of metal wood leather or the like horizontal in one part for receiving the foot of a rider and attached by a strap to the saddle -- used to assist a person in mounting a horse and to enable him to sit steadily in riding as well as to relieve him by supporting a part of the weight of the body."
"A single pass of a needle in sewing; the loop or turn of the thread thus made."
"To stuff; to crowd; to fill full; hence  to make hot and close; to render stifling."
"A Dutch coin  and money of account of the value of two cents or about one penny sterling; hence figuratively anything of little worth."
"The ermine in its summer pelage  when it is reddish brown but with a black tip to the tail. The name is sometimes applied also to other brown weasels."
"The stem  or main body of a tree or plant; the fixed strong firm part; the trunk."
"One who makes or fits stocks  as of guns or gun carriages etc."
"Short and thick; thick rather than tall or corpulent."

"A disciple of the philosopher Zeno; one of a Greek sect which held that men should be free from passion  unmoved by joy or grief and should submit without complaint to unavoidable necessity by which all things are governed."
"Of or pertaining to the Stoics; resembling the Stoics or their doctrines."
"One who is employed to tend a furnace and supply it with fuel  especially the furnace of a locomotive or of a marine steam boiler; also a machine for feeding fuel to a fire."
"A long garment  descending to the ankles worn by Roman women."
"Hopelessly insensible or stupid; not easily aroused or excited; dull; impassive; foolish."
"A trailing branch which is disposed to take root at the end or at the joints; a stole."
"One of the minute apertures between the cells in many serous membranes."

"An enlargement  or series of enlargements in the anterior part of the alimentary canal in which food is digested; any cavity in which digestion takes place in an animal; a digestive cavity. See Digestion and Gastric juice under Gastric."
"Concreted earthy or mineral matter; also  any particular mass of such matter; as a house built of stone; the boy threw a stone; pebbles are rounded stones."
"One who stones; one who makes an assault with stones."
"Of or pertaining to stone  consisting of or abounding in stone or stones; resembling stone; hard; as a stony tower; a stony cave; stony ground; a stony crust."
"A small collection of sheaves set up in the field; a shock; in England  twelve sheaves."
"A plant from which layers are propagated by bending its branches into the soil."

"Originally  a covered porch with seats at a house door; the Dutch stoep as introduced by the Dutch into New York. Afterward an out-of-door flight of stairs of from seven to fourteen steps with platform and parapets leading to an entrance door some distance above the street; the French perron. Hence any porch platform entrance stairway or small veranda at a house door."
"To close  as an aperture by filling or by obstructing; as to stop the ears; hence to stanch as a wound."
"A horizontal working forming one of a series  the working faces of which present the appearance of a flight of steps."
"One who stops  closes shuts or hinders; that which stops or obstructs; that which closes or fills a vent or hole in a vessel."
"That which stops or closes the mouth of a vessel; a stopper; as  a glass stopple; a cork stopple."
"The act of depositing in a store or warehouse for safe keeping; also  the safe keeping of goods in a warehouse."

"Any one of a number of similar complex resins obtained from the bark of several trees and shrubs of the Styrax family. The most common of these is liquid storax  a brown or gray semifluid substance of an agreeable aromatic odor and balsamic taste sometimes used in perfumery and in medicine as an expectorant."
"That which is accumulated  or massed together; a source from which supplies may be drawn; hence an abundance; a great quantity or a great number."
"One who lays up or forms a store."
"Parental affection; the instinctive affection which animals have for their young."
"To form or tell stories of; to narrate or describe in a story."

"Any one of several species of large wading birds of the family Ciconidae  having long legs and a long pointed bill. They are found both in the Old World and in America and belong to Ciconia and several allied genera. The European white stork (Ciconia alba) is the best known. It commonly makes its nests on the top of a building a chimney a church spire or a pillar. The black stork (C. nigra) is native of Asia Africa and Europe."
"A violent disturbance of the atmosphere  attended by wind rain snow hail or thunder and lightning; hence often a heavy fall of rain snow or hail whether accompanied with wind or not."
"Characterized by  or proceeding from a storm; subject to storms; agitated with furious winds; biosterous; tempestous; as a stormy season; a stormy day or week."

"A set of rooms on the same floor or level; a floor  or the space between two floors. Also a horizontal division of a building's exterior considered architecturally which need not correspond exactly with the stories within."
"A flagon; a vessel or measure for liquids."
"A battle or tumult; encounter; combat; disturbance; passion."
"Strong; lusty; vigorous; robust; sinewy; muscular; hence  firm; resolute; dauntless."
"In a stout manner; lustily; boldly; obstinately; as  he stoutly defended himself."
"Fodder for cattle  especially straw or coarse hay."
"To place or arrange in a compact mass; to put in its proper place  or in a suitable place; to pack; as to stowbags bales or casks in a ship's hold; to stow hay in a mow; to stow sheaves."
"The act or method of stowing; as  the stowage of provisions in a vessel."
"One of the twists  or strings as of fibers wires etc. of which a rope is composed."
"A long  narrow pliable strip of leather cloth or the like; specifically a strip of thick leather used in flogging."
"A brilliant glass  used in the manufacture of artificial paste gems which consists essentially of a complex borosilicate of lead and potassium. Cf. Glass."
"A valley of considerable size  through which a river runs; a valley bottom; -- often used in composition with the name of the river; as Strath Spey Strathdon Strathmore."
"A bed of earth or rock of one kind  formed by natural causes and consisting usually of a series of layers which form a rock as it lies between beds of other kinds. Also used figuratively."
"A form of clouds in which they are arranged in a horizontal band or layer. See Cloud."
"To spread or scatter. See Strew  and Strow."
"Of or pertaining to straw; made of  or resembling straw."
"To wander  as from a direct course; to deviate or go out of the way."
"To stretch; to extend; hence  to lay out as a dead body."

"A current of water or other fluid; a liquid flowing continuously in a line or course  either on the earth as a river brook etc. or from a vessel reservoir or fountain; specifically any course of running water; as many streams are blended in the Mississippi; gas and steam came from the earth in streams; a stream of molten lead from a furnace; a stream of lava from a volcano."
"Abounding with streams  or with running water; streamful."
"To stretch; also  to lay out as a dead body. See Streak."
"To trail along; to saunter or be drawn along  carelessly swaying in a kind of zigzag motion."
"Originally  a paved way or road; a public highway; now commonly a thoroughfare in a city or village bordered by dwellings or business houses."
"To reach out; to extend; to put forth."
"The crowding of answer upon subject near the end of a fugue."

"To scatter; to spread by scattering; to cast or to throw loosely apart; -- used of solids  separated or separable into parts or particles; as to strew seed in beds; to strew sand on or over a floor; to strew flowers over a grave."

"A minute groove  or channel; a threadlike line as of color; a narrow structural band or line; a striation; as the striae or groovings produced on a rock by a glacier passing over it; the striae on the surface of a shell; a stria of nervous matter in the brain."
"A bunch of hackled flax prepared for drawing into slivers."
"Strained; drawn close; tight; as  a strict embrace; a strict ligature."
"A narrow passage between precipitous rocks or banks  which looks as if it might be crossed at a stride."
"To walk with long steps  especially in a measured or pompous manner."
"The tribe of birds which comprises the owls."
"An instrument of metal  ivory etc. used for scraping the skin at the bath."
"To touch or hit with some force  either with the hand or with an instrument; to smite; to give a blow to either with the hand or with any instrument or missile."
"One who  or that which strikes; specifically a blacksmith's helper who wields the sledge."

"A small cord  a line a twine or a slender strip of leather or other substance used for binding together fastening or tying things; a cord larger than a thread and smaller than a rope; as a shoe string; a bonnet string; a silken string."
"Consisting of strings  or small threads; fibrous; filamentous; as a stringy root."

"To deprive; to bereave; to make destitute; to plunder; especially  to deprive of a covering; to skin; to peel; as to strip a man of his possession his rights his privileges his reputation; to strip one of his clothes; to strip a beast of his skin; to strip a tree of its bark."

"A line  or long narrow division of anything of a different color or structure from the ground; hence any linear variation of color or structure; as a stripe or streak of red on a green ground; a raised stripe."
"To make efforts; to use exertions; to endeavor with earnestness; to labor hard."
"One of the flutings of a column."
"One who strokes; also  one who pretends to cure by stroking."
"To wander on foot; to ramble idly or leisurely; to rove."
"The connective tissue or supporting framework of an organ; as  the stroma of the kidney."
"Any marine univalve mollusk of the genus Strombus and allied genera. See Conch  and Strombus."
"Having active physical power  or great physical power to act; having a power of exerting great bodily force; vigorous."

"In Greek choruses and dances  the movement of the chorus while turning from the right to the left of the orchestra; hence the strain or part of the choral ode sung during this movement. Also sometimes used of a stanza of modern verse. See the Note under Antistrophe."
"A kind of coarse blanket or garment used by the North American Indians."
"To swell; to puff out; to project."
"A bar so placed as to resist weight."
"To play on an instrument of music  or as on an instrument in an unskillful or noisy way; to thrum; as to strum a piano."
"A Russian river craft used for transporting freight."
"The stump of a tree; that part of a tree or plant which remains fixed in the earth when the stem is cut down; -- applied especially to the stump of a small tree  or shrub."
"The stumps of wheat  rye barley oats or buckwheat left in the ground; the part of the stalk left by the scythe or sickle."
"Plaster of any kind used as a coating for walls  especially a fine plaster composed of lime or gypsum with sand and pounded marble used for internal decorations and fine work."
"A number of sheaves set together in the field; a stook."
"A collection of breeding horses and mares  or the place where they are kept; also a number of horses kept for a racing riding etc."

"A person engaged in study; one who is devoted to learning; a learner; a pupil; a scholar; especially  one who attends a school or who seeks knowledge from professional teachers or from books; as the students of an academy a college or a university; a medical student; a hard student."
"Closely examined; read with diligence and attention; made the subject of study; well considered; as  a studied lesson."
"A setting of the mind or thoughts upon a subject; hence  application of mind to books arts or science or to any subject for the purpose of acquiring knowledge."
"A jet of steam issuing from a fissure in the earth."
"Material which is to be worked up in any process of manufacture."
"A framework of timber covered with boards to support rubbish; also  a framework of boards to protect miners from falling stones."
"A shaft or gallery to drain a mine."
"A short  stout post used for any purpose a to mark a boundary."
"Unfermented grape juice or wine  often used to raise fermentation in dead or vapid wines; must."
"To trip in walking or in moving in any way with the legs; to strike the foot so as to fall  or to endanger a fall; to stagger because of a false step."
"The part of a tree or plant remaining in the earth after the stem or trunk is cut off; the stub."
"To make senseless or dizzy by violence; to render senseless by a blow  as on the head."
"To hinder from growing to the natural size; to prevent the growth of; to stint  to dwarf; as to stunt a child; to stunt a plant."
"A mound or monument commemorative of Buddha."
"Cloth or flax dipped in warm water or medicaments and applied to a hurt or sore."
"To make stupid; to make dull; to blunt the faculty of perception or understanding in; to deprive of sensibility; to make torpid."
"Very dull; insensible; senseless; wanting in understanding; heavy; sluggish; in a state of stupor; -- said of persons."
"Great diminution or suspension of sensibility; suppression of sense or feeling; lethargy."
"Composed of  or having tufted or matted filaments like tow; stupeous."
"Foolishly obstinate or resolute; stubborn; unrelenting; unfeeling; stern."
"To hesitate or stumble in uttering words; to speak with spasmodic repetition or pauses; to stammer."
"An anglo-Saxon copper coin of the lowest value  being worth half a farthing."
"Of or pertaining to the river Styx; hence  hellish; infernal. See Styx."

"An instrument used by the ancients in writing on tablets covered with wax  having one of its ends sharp and the other blunt and somewhat expanded for the purpose of making erasures by smoothing the wax."
"Having style or artistic quality; given to  or fond of the display of style; highly fashionable; modish; as a stylish dress house manner."
"One who is a master or a model of style  especially in writing or speaking; a critic of style."
"One of a sect of anchorites in the early church  who lived on the tops of pillars for the exercise of their patience; -- called also pillarist and pillar saint."

"A genus of minute insects parasitic  in their larval state on bees and wasps. It is the typical genus of the group Strepsiptera formerly considered a distinct order but now generally referred to the Coleoptera. See Strepsiptera."
"An instrument for writing. See Style  n. 1."
"Producing contraction; stopping bleeding; having the quality of restraining hemorrhage when applied to the bleeding part; astringent."
"A genus of shrubs and trees  mostly American or Asiatic abounding in resinous and aromatic substances. Styrax officinalis yields storax and S. Benzoin yields benzoin."
"A white crystalline substance having a sweet taste and a hyacinthlike odor  obtained by the decomposition of styracin; -- properly called cinnamic / styryl alcohol."
"A hypothetical radical found in certain derivatives of styrolene and cinnamic acid; -- called also cinnyl  or cinnamyl."
"The principal river of the lower world  which had to be crossed in passing to the regions of the dead."
"Capable of being sued; subject by law to be called to answer in court."
"Spread equally over the surface; uniform; even."
"The act of persuading; persuasion; as  moral suasion."
"Sweet; pleasant; delightful; gracious or agreeable in manner; bland."
"Moderately acid or sour; as  some plants have subacid juices."
"A province; a government  as of a viceroy; also a subahdar."
"To aid secretly; to assist in a private manner  or indirectly."
"A hypothetical component of a chemical atom  on the theory that the elements themselves are complex substances; -- called also atomicule."
"To understand or supply in an ellipsis."
"An under dean; the deputy or substitute of a dean."
"Of or pertaining to the open air; being under the open sky."
"To bring under; to conquer by force or the exertion of superior power  and bring into permanent subjection; to reduce under dominion; to vanquish."
"One who  or that which subdues; a conqueror."
"Of or pertaining to cork; specifically  designating an acid C6H12.(CO2H)2 homologous with oxalic acid and obtained from cork and certain fatty oils as a white crystalline substance."
"A material found in the cell walls of cork. It is a modification of lignin."
"Placed or situated under; lying below  or in a lower situation."
"To add after something else has been said or written; to ANNEX; as  to subjoin an argument or reason."
"To take or carry away; to remove."
"Lifted up; high in place; exalted aloft; uplifted; lofty."
"To tie or fasten beneath; to join beneath."
"To procure or cause to take a false oath amounting to perjury  such oath being actually taken."
"A basic salt. See the Note under Salt."
"To sink or fall to the bottom; to settle  as lees."
"Support; aid; cooperation; esp.  extraordinary aid in money rendered to the sovereign or to a friendly power."
"To be; to have existence; to inhere."
"The bed  or stratum of earth which lies immediately beneath the surface soil."

"To take up into or under  as individual under species species under genus or particular under universal; to place (any one cognition) under another as belonging to it; to include under something else."
"To extend under  or be opposed to; as the line of a triangle which subtends the right angle; the chord subtends an arc."
"Thin; not dense or gross; rare; as  subtile air; subtile vapor; a subtile medium."
"Sly in design; artful; cunning; insinuating; subtile; -- applied to persons; as  a subtle foe."
"In a subtle manner; slyly; artfully; cunningly."

"An outlying part of a city or town; a smaller place immediately adjacent to a city; in the plural  the region which is on the confines of any city or large town; as a house stands in the suburbs; a garden situated in the suburbs of Paris."
"To come under  as a support or stay; to happen."
"To overturn from the foundation; to overthrow; to ruin utterly."
"An underground way or gallery; especially  a passage under a street in which water mains gas mains telegraph wires etc. are conducted."
"To follow in order; to come next after; hence  to take the place of; as the king's eldest son succeeds his father on the throne; autumn succeeds summer."
"Appearing as if a part were cut off at the extremity."
"To run to  or run to support; hence to help or relieve when in difficulty want or distress; to assist and deliver from suffering; to relieve; as to succor a besieged city."
"A plant of the genus Cichorium. See Chicory."
"A female demon or fiend. See Succubus."
"A bare axis or cylinder with staves or levers in it to turn it round  but without any drum."
"To yield; to submit; to give up unresistingly; as  to succumb under calamities; to succumb to disease."
"The expressed juice of a plant  for medicinal use."

"Of that kind; of the like kind; like; resembling; similar; as  we never saw such a day; -- followed by that or as introducing the word or proposition which defines the similarity or the standard of comparison; as the books are not such that I can recommend them or not such as I can recommend; these apples are not such as those we saw yesterday; give your children such precepts as tend to make them better."
"To draw  as a liquid by the action of the mouth and tongue which tends to produce a vacuum and causes the liquid to rush in by atmospheric pressure; to draw or apply force to by exhausting the air."
"The jurisdiction of a mill  or that extent of ground astricted to it the tenants of which are bound to bring their grain thither to be ground."
"One who  or that which sucks; esp. one of the organs by which certain animals as the octopus and remora adhere to other bodies."
"An animal that suckles its young; a mammal."
"A compound of sucrose (or of some related carbohydrate) with some base  after the analogy of a salt; as sodium sucrate."
"A silver coin of Ecuador  worth 68 cents."

"A common variety of sugar found in the juices of many plants  as the sugar cane sorghum sugar maple beet root etc. It is extracted as a sweet white crystalline substance which is valuable as a food product and being antiputrescent is largely used in the preservation of fruit. Called also saccharose cane sugar etc. By extension
"The act or process of sucking; the act of drawing  as fluids by exhausting the air."
"Happening without previous notice or with very brief notice; coming unexpectedly  or without the common preparation; immediate; instant; speedy."
"Of or pertaining to sweat; as  sudoral eruptions."
"The lowest of the four great castes among the Hindoos. See Caste."
"Water impregnated with soap  esp. when worked up into bubbles and froth."
"To follow up; to chase; to seek after; to endeavor to win; to woo."
"Uniformly or evenly distributed or spread; even; smooth. See Suant."
"The fat and fatty tissues of an animal  especially the harder fat about the kidneys and loins in beef and mutton which when melted and freed from the membranes forms tallow."
"Consisting of  or resembling suet; as a suety substance."
"To feel  or endure with pain annoyance etc.; to submit to with distress or grief; to undergo; as to suffer pain of body or grief of mind."
"To be enough  or sufficient; to meet the need (of anything); to be equal to the end proposed; to be adequate."
"A letter  letters syllable or syllables added or appended to the end of a word or a root to modify the meaning; a postfix."
"To overspread  as with a fluid or tincture; to fill or cover as with something fluid; as eyes suffused with tears; cheeks suffused with blushes."
"A title or surname of the king of Persia."
"A refined mysticism among certain classes of Mohammedans  particularly in Persia who hold to a kind of pantheism and practice extreme asceticism in their lives."

"A sweet white (or brownish yellow) crystalline substance  of a sandy or granular consistency obtained by crystallizing the evaporated juice of certain plants as the sugar cane sorghum beet root sugar maple etc. It is used for seasoning and preserving many kinds of food and drink. Ordinary sugar is essentially sucrose. See the Note below."
"Resembling or containing sugar; tasting of sugar; sweet."
"To introduce indirectly to the thoughts; to cause to be thought of  usually by the agency of other objects."

"The act of taking one's own life voluntary and intentionally; self-murder; specifically (Law)  the felonious killing of one's self; the deliberate and intentional destruction of one's own life by a person of years of discretion and of sound mind."
"A mixture of oleomargarine with lard or other fatty ingredients. It is used as a substitute for butter. See Butterine."
"A peculiar substance obtained from the wool of sheep  consisting largely of potash mixed with fatty and earthy matters. It is used as a source of potash and also for the manufacture of gas."
"One who seeks for things which gratify merely himself; a selfish person; a selfist."
"The act of following or pursuing  as game; pursuit."
"A retinue or company of attendants  as of a distinguished personage; as the suite of an ambassador. See Suit n. 5."
"One who sues  petitions or entreats; a petitioner; an applicant."
"Indian wheat  granulated but not pulverized; a kind of semolina."
"A genus of sea birds including the booby and the common gannet."
"The condition of being sulky; a sulky mood or humor; as  to be in the sulks."
"Moodly silent; sullen; sour; obstinate; morose; splenetic."
"Drainage of filth; filth collected from the street or highway; sewage."
"To soil; to dirty; to spot; to tarnish; to stain; to darken; -- used literally and figuratively; as  to sully a sword; to sully a person's reputation."

"A nonmetallic element occurring naturally in large quantities  either combined as in the sulphides (as pyrites) and sulphates (as gypsum) or native in volcanic regions in vast beds mixed with gypsum and various earthy materials from which it is melted out. Symbol S. Atomic weight 32. The specific gravity of ordinary octohedral sulphur is 2.05; of prismatic sulphur 1.96."
"A ruler  or sovereign of a Mohammedan state; specifically the ruler of the Turks; the Padishah or Grand Seignior; -- officially so called."
"The wife of a sultan; a sultaness."
"Very hot  burning and oppressive; as Libya's sultry deserts."
"The aggregate of two or more numbers  magnitudes quantities or particulars; the amount or whole of any number of individuals or particulars added together; as the sum of 5 and 7 is 12."

"Any plant of the genus Rhus  shrubs or small trees with usually compound leaves and clusters of small flowers. Some of the species are used in tanning some in dyeing and some in medicine. One the Japanese Rhus vernicifera yields the celebrated Japan varnish or lacquer."
"The musky root of an Asiatic umbelliferous plant  Ferula Sumbul. It is used in medicine as a stimulant."
"Not to be summed up or computed; so great that the amount can not be ascertained; incalculable; inestimable."
"Formed into a sum; summed up; reduced into a narrow compass  or into few words; short; brief; concise; compendious; as a summary statement of facts."
"One who sums; one who casts up an account."
"Of or pertaining to summer; like summer; as  a summery day."
"One who sums up; one who forms an abridgment or summary."
"To call  bid or cite; to notify to come to appear; -- often with up."
"The act of summoning; a call by authority  or by the command of a superior to appear at a place named or to attend to some duty."
"A round pit of stone  lined with clay for receiving the metal on its first fusion."
"A beam or ray of the sun."

"Any one of numerous species of small brilliantly colored birds of the family Nectariniidae  native of Africa Southern Asia the East Indies and Australia. In external appearance and habits they somewhat resemble humming birds but they are true singing birds (Oscines)."
"To burn or discolor by the sun; to tan."
"The first day of the week  -- consecrated among Christians to rest from secular employments and to religious worship; the Christian Sabbath; the Lord's Day."
"To disunite in almost any manner  either by rending cutting or breaking; to part; to put or keep apart; to separate; to divide; to sever; as to sunder a rope; to sunder a limb; to sunder friends."

"Any plant of the genus Drosera  low bog plants whose leaves are beset with pediceled glands which secrete a viscid fluid that glitters like dewdrops and attracts and detains insects. After an insect is caught the glands curve inward like tentacles and the leaf digests it. Called also lustwort."
"An instrument to show the time of day by means of the shadow of a gnomon  or style on a plate."
"A luminous spot occasionally seen a few degrees from the sun  supposed to be formed by the intersection of two or more halos or in a manner similar to that of halos."
"Several; divers; more than one or two; various."
"A very large oceanic plectognath fish (Mola mola  Mola rotunda or Orthagoriscus mola) having a broad body and a truncated tail."
"A rosy flush in the sky seen after sunset."
"Destitute or deprived of the sun or its rays; shaded; shadowed."
"An East Indian leguminous plant (Crotalaria juncea) and its fiber  which is also called sunn hemp."
"A collection of traditions received by the orthodox Mohammedans as of equal authority with the Koran."
"One of the orthodox Mohammedans who receive the Sunna as of equal importance with the Koran."
"A charter or warrant; also  a deed of gift."
"Of or pertaining to the sun; proceeding from  or resembling the sun; hence shining; bright; brilliant; radiant."

"In the direction of the sun's apparent motion  or from the east southward and westward and so around the circle; also in the same direction as the movement of the hands of a watch lying face upward."
"To take into the mouth with the lips  as a liquid; to take or drink by a little at a time; to sip."
"Grand; magnificent; august; stately; as  a superb edifice; a superb colonnade."
"Lying on the back  or with the face upward; -- opposed to prone."
"A meal taken at the close of the day; the evening meal."
"Pliant; flexible; easily bent; as  supple joints; supple fingers."

"To fill up  or keep full; to furnish with what is wanted; to afford or furnish with a sufficiency; as rivers are supplied by smaller streams; an aqueduct supplies an artificial lake; -- often followed by with before the thing furnished; as to supply a furnace with fuel; to supply soldiers with ammunition."

"To bear by being under; to keep from falling; to uphold; to sustain  in a literal or physical sense; to prop up; to bear the weight of; as a pillar supports a structure; an abutment supports an arch; the trunk of a tree supports the branches."

"To represent to one's self  or state to another not as true or real but as if so and with a view to some consequence or application which the reality would involve or admit of; to imagine or admit to exist for the sake of argument or illustration; to assume to be true; as let us suppose the earth to be the center of the system what would be the result?"
"To reckon; to compute; to suppose; to impute."
"Over; above; before; also  beyond; besides; -- much used as a prefix."
"Highest in authority; holding the highest place in authority  government or power."
"One of the sections or chapters of the Koran  which are one hundred and fourteen in number."
"A soft twilled silk fabric much used for women's dresses; -- called also surah silk."
"Of or pertaining to the calf of the leg; as  the sural arteries."
"A cornice  or series of moldings on the top of the base of a pedestal podium etc. See Illust. of Column."
"To make sore or bruise  as the feet by travel."
"To set edgewise  as a stone; that is to set it in a position different from that which it had in the quarry."
"A little shoot; a twig; a sucker."
"A coat worn over the other garments; especially  the long and flowing garment of knights worn over the armor and frequently emblazoned with the arms of the wearer."
"Net having the sense of hearing; deaf."
"Certainly knowing and believing; confident beyond doubt; implicity trusting; unquestioning; positive."
"In a sure or certain manner; certainly; infallibly; undoubtedly; assuredly."
"One to be sure of  or to be relied on."
"The state of being sure; certainty; security."
"The swell of the sea which breaks upon the shore  esp. upon a sloping beach."

"The exterior part of anything that has length and breadth; one of the limits that bound a solid  esp. the upper face; superficies; the outside; as the surface of the earth; the surface of a diamond; the surface of the body."
"To wash  as the face with a cosmetic water said by some to be prepared from the sulphur."
"One who serves in a surfboat in the life-saving service."
"Tired or sore of foot from travel; lamed."
"Consisting of  abounding in or resembling surf; as a surfy shore."

"One whose profession or occupation is to cure diseases or injuries of the body by manual operation; one whose occupation is to cure local injuries or disorders (such as wounds  dislocations tumors etc.) whether by manual operation or by medication and constitutional treatment."

"The art of healing by manual operation; that branch of medical science which treats of manual operations for the healing of diseases or injuries of the body; that branch of medical science which has for its object the cure of local injuries or diseases  as wounds or fractures tumors etc. whether by manual operation or by medicines and constitutional treatment."
"Rising in surges or billows; full of surges; resembling surges in motion or appearance; swelling."
"A loin of beef  or the upper part of the loin. See Sirloin the more usual but not etymologically preferable orthography."
"A mark made on the molds of a ship  when building to show where the angles of the timbers are to be placed."
"A thought  imagination or conjecture which is based upon feeble or scanty evidence; suspicion; guess; as the surmisses of jealousy or of envy."
"A name or appellation which is added to  or over and above the baptismal or Christian name and becomes a family name."
"To go beyond in anything good or bad; to exceed; to excel."
"That which remains when use or need is satisfied  or when a limit is reached; excess; overplus."
"A four-wheeled pleasure carriage  (commonly two-seated) somewhat like a phaeton but having a straight bottom."
"A man's coat to be worn over his other garments; an overcoat  especially when long and fitting closely like a body coat."
"To supervene upon; to come as an addition to."
"To inspect  or take a view of; to view with attention as from a high place; to overlook; as to stand on a hill and survey the surrounding country."
"To survey; to make a survey of."
"To live beyond the life or existence of; to live longer than; to outlive; to outlast; as  to survive a person or an event."
"A ground squirrel (Spermophilus citillus) of Europe and Asia. It has large cheek pouches."
"To attach to something above; to hang; as  to suspend a ball by a thread; to suspend a needle by a loadstone."
"To fetch a long  deep breath; to sigh; to breathe."
"To keep from falling; to bear; to uphold; to support; as  a foundation sustains the superstructure; a beast sustains a load; a rope sustains a weight."
"A person who follows an army  and sells to the troops provisions liquors and the like."
"Belonging to sutlers; engaged in the occupation of a sutler."
"A kind of sirup made by the Indians of Arizona from the fruit of some cactaceous plant (probably the Cereus giganteus)."
"A precept; an aphorism; a brief rule."
"A Hindoo widow who immolates herself  or is immolated on the funeral pile of her husband; -- so called because this act of self-immolation is regarded as envincing excellence of wifely character."
"The weight when the tare has been deducted  and tret is yet to be allowed."
"Of or pertaining to a suture  or seam."
"The act of sewing; also  the line along which two things or parts are sewed together or are united so as to form a seam or that which resembles a seam."
"Having a suture or sutures; knit or united together."
"To clean with a mop or swab; to wipe when very wet  as after washing; as to swab the desk of a ship."
"A cod  or pod as of beans or pease."
"Anything used to swaddle with  as a cloth or band; a swaddling band."
"To hang or move  as something loose and heavy; to sway; to swing."
"To walk with a swaying motion; hence  to walk and act in a pompous consequential manner."
"Inclined to swag; sinking  hanging or leaning by its weight."
"A valley or low place; a tract of low  and usually wet land; a moor; a fen."
"Water breaking in upon the miners at their work; -- so called among tin miners."

"Any one of numerous species of passerine birds of the family Hirundinidae  especially one of those species in which the tail is deeply forked. They have long pointed wings and are noted for the swiftness and gracefulness of their flight."
"Wet  spongy land; soft low ground saturated with water but not usually covered with it; marshy ground away from the seashore."
"Consisting of swamp; like a swamp; low  wet and spongy; as swampy land."

"Any one of numerous species of large aquatic birds belonging to Cygnus  Olor and allied genera of the subfamily Cygninae. They have a large and strong beak and a long neck and are noted for their graceful movements when swimming. Most of the northern species are white. In literature the swan was fabled to sing a melodious song especially at the time of its death."
"Swanlike; as  a swanny glossiness of the neck."
"To climb a tree  pole or the like by embracing it with the arms and legs alternately. See Shin."
"Being of a dark hue or dusky complexion; tawny; swart; as  swarthy faces."
"An oval figure  whose moldings are oblique to the axis of the work."
"One who makes a blustering show of valor or force of arms."
"Soft  like fruit that is too ripe; quashy; swash."
"A line of grass or grain cut and thrown together by the scythe in mowing or cradling."
"To bind with a swathe  band bandage or rollers."
"A device attached to a mowing machine for raising the uncut fallen grain and marking the limit of the swath."
"To move or wield with the hand; to swing; to wield; as  to sway the scepter."
"To melt and run down  as the tallow of a candle; to waste away without feeding the flame."

"To affirm or utter a solemn declaration  with an appeal to God for the truth of what is affirmed; to make a promise threat or resolve on oath; also to affirm solemnly by some sacred object or one regarded as sacred as the Bible the Koran etc."
"One who swears; one who calls God to witness for the truth of his declaration."
"Moist with sweat; as  a sweaty skin; a sweaty garment."
"Of or pertaining to Sweden or its inhabitants."
"An atrophy of the muscles of the shoulder in horses; also  atrophy of any muscle in horses."

"To pass a broom across (a surface) so as to remove loose dirt  dust etc.; to brush or rub over with a broom for the purpose of cleaning; as to sweep a floor the street or a chimney. Used also figuratively."
"One who  or that which sweeps or cleans by sweeping; a sweep; as a carpet sweeper."
"Having an agreeable taste or flavor such as that of sugar; saccharine; -- opposed to sour and bitter; as  a sweet beverage; sweet fruits; sweet oranges."
"To make sweet to the taste; as  to sweeten tea."

"To grow larger; to dilate or extend the exterior surface or dimensions  by matter added within or by expansion of the inclosed substance; as the legs swell in dropsy; a bruised part swells; a bladder swells by inflation."
"To be overcome and faint with heat; to be ready to perish with heat."
"A vision seen in sleep; a dream."
"Moving a great distance in a short time; moving with celerity or velocity; fleet; rapid; quick; speedy; prompt."
"A rope used to retain the bars of the capstan in their sockets while men are turning it."
"In a swift manner; with quick motion or velocity; fleetly."
"To drink in long draughts; to gulp; as  to swig cider."
"To be supported by water or other fluid; not to sink; to float; as  any substance will swim whose specific gravity is less than that of the fluid in which it is immersed."
"A moaning or sighing sound or noise; a sough."
"To cheat defraud grossly  or with deliberate artifice; as to swindle a man out of his property."

"Any animal of the hog kind  especially one of the domestical species. Swine secrete a large amount of subcutaneous fat which when extracted is known as lard. The male is specifically called boar the female sow and the young pig. See Hog."
"To move to and fro  as a body suspended in the air; to wave; to vibrate; to oscillate."
"The swinging part of a flail which falls on the grain in thrashing; the swiple."
"Of or pertaining to swine; befitting swine; like swine; hoggish; gross; beasty; as  a swinish drunkard or sot."
"That part of a flail which strikes the grain in thrashing; a swingel."
"To whirl  or cause to whirl as in an eddy."
"To flourish  so as to make the sound swish."
"A native or inhabitant of Switzerland; a Switzer; the people of Switzerland."
"A native or inhabitant of Switzerland; a Swiss."
"A piece  as a ring or hook attached to another piece by a pin in such a manner as to permit rotation about the pin as an axis."
"To sink into a fainting fit  in which there is an apparent suspension of the vital functions and mental powers; to faint; -- often with away."
"To fall on at once and seize; to catch while on the wing; as  a hawk swoops a chicken."
"An offensive weapon  having a long and usually sharp/pointed blade with a cutting edge or edges. It is the general term including the small sword rapier saber scimiter and many other varieties."
"One who uses  or fights with a sword; a swordsman; a soldier; a cutthroat."
"A sound; a groan; a moan; a sough."
"Silver  pounded into ingots of the shape of a shoe and used as currency. The most common weight is about one pound troy."
"A nodule of flint  or a pebble which resembles a fig."
"A collective fleshy fruit  in which the ovaries are hidden within a hollow receptacle as in the fig."
"A pustular eruption upon the scalp  or the beared part of the face whether due to ringworm acne or impetigo."
"Orig.  a rock composed of quartz hornblende and feldspar anciently quarried at Syene in Upper Egypt and now called granite."
"An imaginary being inhabiting the air; a fairy."
"A little sylph; a young or diminutive sylph."
"Of or pertaining to a sylva; forestlike; hence  rural; rustic."

"Of  pertaining to or resembling pine or its products; specifically designating an acid called also abeitic acid which is the chief ingredient of common resin (obtained from Pinus sylvestris and other species)."

"A visible sign or representation of an idea; anything which suggests an idea or quality  or another thing as by resemblance or by convention; an emblem; a representation; a type; a figure; as the lion is the symbol of courage; the lamb is the symbol of meekness or patience."

"Any affection which accompanies disease; a perceptible change in the body or its functions  which indicates disease or the kind or phases of disease; as the causes of disease often lie beyond our sight but we learn their nature by the symptoms exhibited."
"A genus of slender  transparent holothurians which have delicate calcareous anchors attached to the dermal plates. See Illustration in Appendix."
"A congregation; also  formerly the Lord's Supper."
"A kind of aggregate fruit in which the ovaries cohere in a solid mass  with a slender receptacle as in the magnolia; also a similar multiple fruit as a mulberry."
"An elision or retrenchment of one or more letters or syllables from the middle of a word; as  ne'er for never ev'ry for every."
"An officer of government  invested with different powers in different countries; a magistrate."
"The interjunction  or joining of words in uttering the clauses of sentences."
"A sense organ found in certain sponges. It consists of several filaments  each of which arises from a single cell."
"An ecclesiastic council or meeting to consult on church matters."

"One of two or more words (commonly words of the same language) which are equivalents of each other; one of two or more words which have very nearly the same signification  and therefore may often be used interchangeably. See under Synonymous."
"A transparent  viscid lubricating fluid which contains mucin and secreted by synovial membranes; synovial fluid."
"Connected system or order; union of things; a number of things jointed together; organism."
"Of or pertaining to Syria  or its language; as the Syriac version of the Pentateuch."
"A Syrian idiom; a Syrianism; a Syriacism."

"A kind of small hand-pump for throwing a stream of liquid  or for purposes of aspiration. It consists of a small cylindrical barrel and piston or a bulb of soft elastic material with or without valves and with a nozzle which is sometimes at the end of a flexible tube; -- used for injecting animal bodies cleansing wounds etc."
"A wind instrument made of reeds tied together; -- called also pandean pipes."
"A long dress  trailing on the floor worn by tragic actors in Greek and Roman theaters."
"Of or pertaining to a syrt; resembling syrt  or quicksand."

"An assemblage of objects arranged in regular subordination  or after some distinct method usually logical or scientific; a complete whole of objects related by some common law principle or end; a complete exhibition of essential principles or facts arranged in a rational dependence or connection; a regular union of principles or parts forming one entire thing; as a system of philosophy; a system of government; a system of divinity; a system of botany or chemistry; a military system; the solar system."
"Having a space equal to two diameters or four modules between two columns; -- said of a portico or building. See Intercolumniation."
"The point of an orbit  as of the moon or a planet at which it is in conjunction or opposition; -- commonly used in the plural."
"The flap or latchet of a shoe fastened with a string or a buckle."
"A genus of blood sucking flies  including the horseflies."

"A sort of tunic or mantle formerly worn for protection from the weather. When worn over the armor it was commonly emblazoned with the arms of the wearer  and from this the name was given to the garment adopted for heralds."
"A stout silk having satin stripes  -- used for furniture."
"A kind of waved silk  usually called watered silk manufactured like taffeta but thicker and stronger. The watering is given to it by calendering."
"To cause to waste gradually  to emaciate."
"Progressive emaciation of the body  accompained with hectic fever with no well-marked logical symptoms."
"Of or pertaining to tabes; of the nature of tabes; affected with tabes; tabid."
"A smooth  flat surface like the side of a board; a thin flat smooth piece of anything; a slab."
"A striking and vivid representation; a picture."
"A forming into tables; a setting down in order."

"A total prohibition of intercourse with  use of or approach to a given person or thing under pain of death -- an interdict of religious origin and authority formerly common in the islands of Polynesia; interdiction."
"A small drum used as an accompaniment to a pipe or fife  both being played by the same person."
