"Having lost motion  or the power of exertion and feeling; numb; benumbed; as a torpid limb."
"To make torpid; to numb  or benumb."
"Loss of motion  or of the motion; a state of inactivity with partial or total insensibility; numbness."
"A collar or neck chain  usually twisted especially as worn by ancient barbaric nations as the Gauls Germans and Britons."
"A cervical ring of hair or feathers  distinguished by its color or structure; a collar."
"A violent stream  as of water lava or the like; a stream suddenly raised and running rapidly as down a precipice."
"Parched; dried with heat; as  a torrid plain or desert."
"A worthless woman; also  a worthless horse."
"A plate of timber for the end of a beam or joist to rest on."

"The act of turning or twisting  or the state of being twisted; the twisting or wrenching of a body by the exertion of a lateral force tending to turn one end or part of it about a longitudinal axis while the other is held fast or turned in the opposite direction."
"The human body  as distinguished from the head and limbs; in sculpture the trunk of a statue mutilated of head and limbs; as the torso of Hercules."
"a flat heap of moist  crushed silver ore prepared for the patio process."
"Any one of numerous species of small moths of the family Tortricidae  the larvae of which usually roll up the leaves of plants on which they live; -- also called leaf roller."
"Extreme pain; anguish of body or mind; pang; agony; torment; as  torture of mind."
"A chain of special bacteria. (b) A genus of budding fungi. Same as Saccharomyces. Also used adjectively."
"A lage molding used in the bases of columns. Its profile is semicircular. See Illust. of Molding."
"Sour of aspect; of a severe countenance; stern; grim."

"A member of the conservative party  as opposed to the progressive party which was formerly called the Whig and is now called the Liberal party; an earnest supporter of exsisting royal and ecclesiastical authority."
"To throw with the hand; especially  to throw with the palm of the hand upward or to throw upward; as to toss a ball."
"A toper; one habitually given to strong drink; a drunkard."
"Tossing the head  as in scorn or pride; hence proud; contemptuous; scornful; affectedly indifferent; as a tossy commonplace."
"Anything small; -- frequently applied as a term of endearment to a little child."
"Whole; not divided; entire; full; complete; absolute; as  a total departure from the evidence; a total loss."
"To carry or bear; as  to tote a child over a stream; -- a colloquial word of the Southern States and used esp. by negroes."
"A rude picture  as of a bird beast or the like used by the North American Indians as a symbolic designation as of a family or a clan."
"Of or pertaining to a totem  or totemism."
"The stone roller. See Stone roller (a)  under Stone."
"A colloquial contraction of the other  and formerly a contraction for that other. See the Note under That 2."
"To shake so as to threaten a fall; to vacillate; to be unsteady; to stagger; as an old man totters with age."
"Trembling or vaccilating  as if about to fall; unsteady; shaking."
"To walk in a wavering  unsteady manner; to toddle; to topple."

"Any one of numerous species of fruit-eating birds of tropical America belonging to Ramphastos  Pteroglossus and allied genera of the family Ramphastidae. They have a very large but light and thin beak often nearly as long as the body itself. Most of the species are brilliantly colored with red yellow white and black in striking contrast."
"To come in contact with; to hit or strike lightly against; to extend the hand  foot or the like so as to reach or rest on."
"Peevish; irritable; irascible; techy; apt to take fire."
"Having the quality of flexibility without brittleness; yielding to force without breaking; capable of resisting great strain; as  the ligaments of animals are remarkably tough."
"To grow or make tough  or tougher."
"A little tuft; a curl or artificial lock of hair."
"One who makes a tour  or performs a journey in a circuit."
"To pull; to haul; to tear; to worry."
"To put into disorder; to tumble; to touse."
"To act as a tout. See 2d Tout."
"One who seeks customers  as for an inn a public conveyance shops and the like: hence an obtrusive candidate for office."
"The coarse and broken part of flax or hemp  separated from the finer part by the hatchel or swingle."
"A vessel constructed for being towed  as a canal boat."
"A cloth used for wiping  especially one used for drying anything wet as the person after a bath."
"A mass of building standing alone and insulated  usually higher than its diameter but when of great size not always of that proportion."
"Having towers; adorned or defended by towers."
"The sanderling; -- so called from its cry."
"A line used to tow vessels; a towrope."

"Formerly: (a) An inclosure which surrounded the mere homestead or dwelling of the lord of the manor. [Obs.] (b) The whole of the land which constituted the domain. [Obs.] (c) A collection of houses inclosed by fences or walls."
"Of or pertaining to the inhabitants of a town; like the town."
"A path traveled by men or animals in towing boats; -- called also towing path."
"Of or pertaining to poison; poisonous; as  toxic medicines."
"A poisonous product formed by pathogenic bacteria  as a toxic proteid or poisonous ptomaine."
"A gigantic extinct herbivorous mammal from South America  having teeth bent like a bow. It is the type of the order Toxodonta."
"A genus of fishes comprising the archer fishes. See Archer fish."
"One who toys; one who is full of trifling tricks; a trifler."
"Soft  like wool that has been teased."
"A toga of purple  or ornamented with purple horizontal stripes. -- worn by kings consuls and augurs."
"One of two straps  chains or ropes of a harness extending from the collar or breastplate to a whiffletree attached to a vehicle or thing to be drawn; a tug."
"The act of one who traces; especially  the act of copying by marking on thin paper or other transparent substance the lines of a pattern placed beneath; also the copy thus producted."
"A mark left by something that has passed along; as  the track or wake of a ship; the track of a meteor; the track of a sled or a wheel."
"One who  or that which tracks or pursues as a man or dog that follows game."
"A written discourse or dissertation  generally of short extent; a short treatise especially on practical religion."
"That which draws  or is used for drawing."
"A track; a trail; a way; a path; also  passage; travel; resort."
"One engaged in trade or commerce; one who makes a business of buying and selling or of barter; a merchant; a trafficker; as  a trader to the East Indies; a country trader."
"To transfer; to transmit; to hand down; as  to traduce mental qualities to one's descendants."
"To derive or deduce; also  to transmit; to transfer."
"To pass goods and commodities from one person to another for an equivalent in goods or money; to buy or sell goods; to barter; to trade."

"A dramatic poem  composed in elevated style representing a signal action performed by some person or persons and having a fatal issue; that species of drama which represents the sad or terrible phases of character and life."
"The prominence in front of the external opening of the ear. See Illust. under Ear."
"To hunt by the track; to track."
"To draw along; to trail; to drag."
"One who trains; an instructor; especially  one who trains or prepares men horses etc. for exercises requiring physical agility and strength."
"To walk or run about in a slatternly  careless or thoughtless manner."

"One who violates his allegiance and betrays his country; one guilty of treason; one who  in breach of trust delivers his country to an enemy or yields up any fort or place intrusted to his defense or surrenders an army or body of troops to the enemy unless when vanquished; also one who takes arms and levies war against his country; or one who aids an enemy in conquering his country. See Treason."
"To throw or cast through  over or across; as to traject the sun's light through three or more cross prisms."
"A four-wheeled truck running on rails  and used in a mine as for carrying coal or ore."
"To wash  as tin ore with a shovel in a frame fitted for the purpose."
"A kind of net for catching birds  fishes or other prey."
"To tread upon forcibly and repeatedly; to trample."
"One who tramps; a stroller; a vagrant or vagabond; a tramp."
"To tread under foot; to tread down; to prostrate by treading; as  to trample grass or flowers."
"The act of passing; passage through or over."
"A horizontal crossbar in a window  over a door or between a door and a window above it. Transom is the horizontal as mullion is the vertical bar across an opening. See Illust. of Mullion."
"To traffic in an itinerary manner; to peddle."
"One who trants; a peddler; a carrier."
"To dress with ornaments; to adorn; -- said especially of horses."
"A snare; a stratagem; a trepan. See 3d Trepan."
"To walk or run about in an idle or slatternly manner; to traipse."
"A slattern; an idle  sluttish or untidy woman."
"One who traps animals; one who makes a business of trapping animals for their furs."
"Small or portable articles for dress  furniture or use; goods; luggage; things."
"That which is worthless or useless; rubbish; refuse."
"Like trash; containing much trash; waste; rejected; worthless; useless; as  a trashy novel."

"A white to gray volcanic tufa  formed of decomposed trachytic cinders; -- sometimes used as a cement. Hence a coarse sort of plaster or mortar durable in water and used to line cisterns and other reservoirs of water."
"Labor with pain; severe toil or exertion."
"To take fish  or other marine animals with a trawl."
"As much as a tray will hold; enough to fill a tray."
"The part of a foot lathe  or other machine which is pressed or moved by the foot."
"The offense of attempting to overthrow the government of the state to which the offender owes allegiance  or of betraying the state into the hands of a foreign power; disloyalty; treachery."
"To handle; to manage; to use; to bear one's self toward; as  to treat prisoners cruelly; to treat children kindly."
"One who treats; one who handles  or discourses on a subject; also one who entertains."
"The act of treating for the adjustment of differences  as for forming an agreement; negotiation."
"In a treble manner; with a threefold number or quantity; triply."
"Any perennial woody plant of considerable size (usually over twenty feet high) and growing with a single trunk."
"The quantity or number which fills a tree."
"A species of time; -- so called from its resemblance in form to a trefoil."
"Any plant of the genus Trifolium  which includes the white clover red clover etc.; -- less properly applied also to the nonesuch or black medic. See Clover and Medic."

"An amorphous variety of manna obtained from the nests and cocoons of a Syrian coleopterous insect (Larinus maculatus  L. nidificans etc.) which feeds on the foliage of a variety of thistle. It is used as an article of food and is called also nest sugar."
"A structure or frame of crossbarred work  or latticework used for various purposes as for screens or for supporting plants."
"To shake involuntarily  as with fear cold or weakness; to quake; to quiver; to shiver; to shudder; -- said of a person or an animal."

"A genus of large hymenopterous insects allied to the sawflies. The female lays her eggs in holes which she bores in the trunks of trees with her large and long ovipositor  and the larva bores in the wood. See Illust. of Horntail."
"The rapid reiteration of tones without any apparent cessation  so as to produce a tremulous effect."
"A trembling; a shivering or shaking; a quivering or vibratory motion; as  the tremor of a person who is weak infirm or old."
"To cut; to form or shape by cutting; to make by incision  hewing or the like."
"To have a particular direction; to run; to stretch; to tend; as  the shore of the sea trends to the southwest."
"One whose business is to free wool from its filth."
"A wheel  spindle or the like; a trundle."
"An office and mass for the dead on the thirtieth day after death or burial."
"A crown-saw or cylindrical saw for perforating the skull  turned when used like a bit or gimlet. See Trephine."
"Any one of several species of large holothurians  some of which are dried and extensively used as food in China; -- called also beche de mer sea cucumber and sea slug."
"A braid  knot or curl of hair; a ringlet."

"A movable frame or support for anything  as scaffolding consisting of three or four legs secured to a top piece and forming a sort of stool or horse used by carpenters masons and other workmen; also a kind of framework of strong posts or piles and crossbeams for supporting a bridge the track of a railway or the like."
"3d pers. sing. pres. of Tread  for treadeth."
"A weaver's cutting instrument; for severing the loops of the pile threads of velvet."
"A stool or other thing supported by three legs; a trivet."
"Trowsers; especially  those of the Scotch Highlanders."
"Three  at cards dice or dominoes; a card die or domino of three spots or pips."
"Fit or possible to be tried; liable to be subjected to trial or test."
"Capable of neutralizing three molecules of a monobasic acid or the equivalent; having three hydrogen atoms which may be acid radicals; -- said of certain bases; thus  glycerin is a triacid base."
"A union of three; three objects treated as one; a ternary; a trinity; as  a triad of deities."
"Having the characteristics of a triad; as  boron is triadic."
"The act of trying or testing in any manner."
"The formation situated between the Permian and Lias  and so named by the Germans because consisting of three series of strata which are called in German the Bunter sandstein Muschelkalk and Keuper."
"A term used in the phrase triatic stay. See under Stay."
"Of or pertaining to a tribe or tribes; as  a tribal scepter."
"A frame on which paper is dried."
"A family  race or series of generations descending from the same progenitor and kept distinct as in the case of the twelve tribes of Israel descended from the twelve sons of Jacob."

"An officer or magistrate chosen by the people  to protect them from the oppression of the patricians or nobles and to defend their liberties against any attempts that might be made upon them by the senate and consuls."

"An annual or stated sum of money or other valuable thing  paid by one ruler or nation to another either as an acknowledgment of submission or as the price of peace and protection or by virtue of some treaty; as the Romans made their conquered countries pay tribute."
"An apothecium in certain lichens  having a spherical surface marked with spiral or concentric ridges and furrows."
"To pull; to haul; to drag; to pull away."
"A muscle having three heads; specif.  the great extensor of the forearm arising by three heads and inserted into the olecranon at the elbow."
"An artifice or stratagem; a cunning contrivance; a sly procedure  usually with a dishonest intent; as a trick in trade."
"To flow in a small  gentle stream; to run in drops."
"Given to tricks; practicing deception; trickish; knavish."
"A fabric of woolen  silk or cotton knitted or women to resemble knitted work."
"Short and ready; fleet; as  a tride pace; -- a term used by sportsmen."
"A kind of scepter or spear with three prongs  -- the common attribute of Neptune."
"Lasting three lays; also  happening every third day."
"A Roman copper coin  equal to one third of the as. See 3d As 2."
"One who tries; one who makes experiments; one who examines anything by a test or standard."
"Cleft to the middle  or slightly beyond the middle into three parts; three-cleft."
"A thing of very little value or importance; a paltry  or trivial affair."
"The act of marrying  or the state of being married three times; also the offense of having three husbands or three wives at the same time."
"A catch to hold the wheel of a carriage on a declivity."
"A figure having three angles; a triangle."
"A smooth triangular area on the inner surface of the bladder  limited by the apertures of the ureters and urethra."
"To flow in a small stream  or in drops rapidly succeeding each other; to trickle."

"A series of three dramas which  although each of them is in one sense complete have a close mutual relation and form one historical and poetical picture. Shakespeare's """" Henry VI."""" is an example."
"To make trim; to put in due order for any purpose; to make right  neat or pleasing; to adjust."
"A division of Coleoptera including those which have but three joints in the tarsi."
"One who trims  arranges fits or ornaments."
"Threefold; triple; as  trine dimensions or length breadth and thickness."
"A genus of limicoline birds including many species of sandpipers. See Dunlin  Knot and Sandpiper."
"The union of three persons (the Father  the Son and the Holy Ghost) in one Godhead so that all the three are one God as to substance but three persons as to individuality."
"A three-cornered sail formerly carried on a ship's foremast  probably on a lateen yard."
"To act secretly  or in an underhand way; to tamper."
"Three  considered collectively; three in company or acting together; a set of three; three united."
"The third order of the Linnaean class Polygamia."
"A short poem or stanza of eight lines  in which the first line is repeated as the fourth and again as the seventh line the second being repeated as the eighth."

"A genus of fresh-water or river turtles which have the shell imperfectly developed and covered with a soft leathery skin. They are noted for their agility and rapacity. Called also soft tortoise  soft-shell tortoise and mud turtle."
"To move with light  quick steps; to walk or move lightly; to skip; to move the feet nimbly; -- sometimes followed by it. See It 5."
"The large stomach of ruminating animals  when prepared for food."
"A place where tripe is prepared or sold."
"Consisting of three united; multiplied by three; threefold; as  a triple knot; a triple tie."
"A collection or combination of three of a kind; three united."
"Any utensil or vessel  as a stool table altar caldron etc. supported on three feet."
"Three metrical feet taken together  or included in one measure."
"An earthy substance originally brought from Tripoli  used in polishing stones and metals. It consists almost wholly of the siliceous shells of diatoms."
"One who trips or supplants; also  one who walks or trips nimbly; a dancer."
"A cam  wiper or projecting piece which strikes another piece repeatedly."
"An ancient galley or vessel with tree banks  or tiers of oars."
"To cut or divide into three parts."
"Something having three forks or prongs  as a trident."
"Worn out; common; used until so common as to have lost novelty and interest; hackneyed; stale; as  a trite remark; a trite subject."

"A fabled sea demigod  the son of Neptune and Amphitrite and the trumpeter of Neptune. He is represented by poets and painters as having the upper part of his body like that of a man and the lower part like that of a fish. He often has a trumpet made of a shell."
"A magnificent and imposing ceremonial performed in honor of a general who had gained a decisive victory over a foreign enemy."
"Being three in one; -- an epithet used to express the unity of a trinity of persons in the Godhead."
"A tree-legged stool  table or other support; especially a stand to hold a kettle or similar vessel near the fire; a tripod."
"The three """" liberal"""" arts  grammar logic and rhetoric; -- being a triple way as it were to eloquence."
"To cry  as a buck in rutting time."
"A stylet  usually with a triangular point used for exploring tissues or for inserting drainage tubes as in dropsy."
"A medicinal tablet or lozenge; strictly  one of circular form."
"A foot of two syllables  the first long and the second short as in the Latin word ante or the first accented and the second unaccented as in the English word motion; a choreus."
"Any one of numerous species of marine univalve shells belonging to Trochus and many allied genera of the family Trochidae. Some of the species are called also topshells."
"An old English game; -- called also lawn billiards."
"Any one of numerous species of beautiful tropical birds belonging to the family Trogonidae. They are noted for the brilliant colors and the resplendent luster of their plumage."
"A large  handsome American butterfly (Euph/ades / Papilio troilus). It is black with yellow marginal spots on the front wings and blue spots on the rear wings."
"Of or pertaining to ancient Troy or its inhabitants."
"A supernatural being  often represented as of diminutive size but sometimes as a giant and fabled to inhabit caves hills and like places; a witch."
"A form of truck which can be tilted  for carrying railroad materials or the like."
"A stroller; a loiterer; esp.  an idle untidy woman; a slattern; a slut; a whore."
"A revolving buddle or sieve for separating  or sizing ores."

"A blowing apparatus  in which air drawn into the upper part of a vertical tube through side holes by a stream of water within is carried down with the water into a box or chamber below which it is led to a furnace."

"A native double salt  consisting of a combination of neutral and acid sodium carbonate Na2CO3.2HNaCO3.2H2O occurring as a white crystalline fibrous deposit from certain soda brine springs and lakes; -- called also urao and by the ancients nitrum."
"A toll or duty paid for weighing wool; also  the act of weighing wool."
"A collection of people; a company; a number; a multitude."
"A soldier in a body of cavalry; a cavalryman; also  the horse of a cavalryman."

"The use of a word or expression in a different sense from that which properly belongs to it; the use of a word or expression as changed from the original signification to another  for the sake of giving life or emphasis to an idea; a figure of speech."
"The mouth parts of an insect  collectively including the labrum labium maxillae mandibles and lingua with their appendages."
"Of or connected with nutrition; nitritional; nourishing; as  the so-called trophic nerves which have a direct influence on nutrition."
"A sign or memorial of a victory raised on the field of battle  or in case of a naval victory on the nearest land. Sometimes trophies were erected in the chief city of the conquered people."
"Of  pertaining to or designating an acid obtained from atropine and certain other alkaloids as a white crystalline substance slightly soluble in water."
"A white crystalline alkaloid  C8H15NO produced by decomposing atropine."
"One who deals in tropes; specifically  one who avoids the literal sense of the language of Scripture by explaining it as mere tropes and figures of speech."
"To proceed by a certain gait peculiar to quadrupeds; to ride or drive at a trot. See Trot  n."
"One that trots; especially  a horse trained to be driven in trotting matches."
"To put into confused motion; to disturb; to agitate."

"A long  hollow vessel generally for holding water or other liquid especially one formed by excavating a log longitudinally on one side; a long tray; also a wooden channel for conveying water as to a mill wheel."
"To punish or beat severely; to whip smartly; to flog; to castigate."
"A company or troop  especially the company pf performers in a play or an opera."

"Any one of numerous species of fishes belonging to Salmo  Salvelinus and allied genera of the family Salmonidae. They are highly esteemed as game fishes and for the quality of their flesh. All the species breed in fresh water but after spawning many of them descend to the sea if they have an opportunity."
"The gaining possession of any goods  whether by finding or by other means."
"A boat with an open well amidships. It is used in spearing fish."
"A mason's tool  used in spreading and dressing mortar and breaking bricks to shape them."
"A pledge of truth or peace made on payment of a tax."
"The act of playing truant  or the state of being truant; as addicted to truancy."
"One who stays away from business or any duty; especially  one who stays out of school without leave; an idler; a loiterer; a shirk."
"An East India herring (Clupea toli) which is extensively caught for the sake of its roe and for its flesh."
"A suspension of arms by agreement of the commanders of opposing forces; a temporary cessation of hostilities  for negotiation or other purpose; an armistice."
"A small wheel  as of a vehicle; specifically (Ord.) a small strong wheel as of wood or iron for a gun carriage."
"To walk or march with labor; to jog along; to move wearily."

"Conformable to fact; in accordance with the actual state of things; correct; not false  erroneous inaccurate or the like; as a true relation or narration; a true history; a declaration is true when it states the facts."

"Any one of several kinds of roundish  subterranean fungi usually of a blackish color. The French truffle (Tuber melanosporum) and the English truffle (T. aestivum) are much esteemed as articles of food."
"An undoubted or self-evident truth; a statement which is pliantly true; a proposition needing no proof or argument; -- opposed to falsism."
"A drab; a strumpet; a harlot; a trollop."
"In a true manner; according to truth; in agreement with fact; as  to state things truly; the facts are truly represented."
"A wind instrument of music; a trumpet  or sound of a trumpet; -- used chiefly in Scripture and poetry."

"A wind instrument of great antiquity  much used in war and military exercises and of great value in the orchestra. In consists of a long metallic tube curved (once or twice) into a convenient shape and ending in a bell. Its scale in the lower octaves is limited to the first natural harmonics; but there are modern trumpets capable by means of valves or pistons of producing every tone within their compass although at the expense of the true ringing quality of tone."
"Of or pertaining to the trunk  or body."
"The thorax of an insect. See Trunk  n. 5."
"The stem  or body of a tree apart from its limbs and roots; the main stem without the branches; stock; stalk."
"A bundle; a package; as  a truss of grass."
"Assured resting of the mind on the integrity  veracity justice friendship or other sound principle of another person; confidence; reliance; reliance."

"A person to whom property is legally committed in trust  to be applied either for the benefit of specified individuals or for public uses; one who is intrusted with property for the benefit of another; also a person in whose hands the effects of another are attached in a trustee process."
"Admitting of being safely trusted; justly deserving confidence; fit to be confided in; trustworthy; reliable."
"The quality or being true; as: -- (a) Conformity to fact or reality; exact accordance with that which is  or has been; or shall be."
"To divide or separate  as one sort from another; to winnow; to sift; to pick out; -- frequently followed by out; as to try out the wild corn from the good."
"Any one of several species of large sting rays belonging to Trygon and allied genera."

"A proteolytic ferment  or enzyme present in the pancreatic juice. Unlike the pepsin of the gastric juice it acts in a neutral or alkaline fluid and not only converts the albuminous matter of the food into soluble peptones but also in part into leucin and tyrosin."
"Relating to trypsin or to its action; produced by trypsin; as  trypsin digestion."
"A fore-and-aft sail  bent to a gaff and hoisted on a lower mast or on a small mast called the trysail mast close abaft a lower mast; -- used chiefly as a storm sail. Called also spencer."
"One who makes an appointment  or tryst; one who meets with another."
"The title of the emperor of Russia. See Czar."

"A West African anthropoid ape allied to the gorilla and chimpanzee  and by some considered only a variety of the chimpanzee. It is noted for building large umbrella-shaped nests in trees. Called also tscheigo tschiego nschego nscheigo."

"A venomous two-winged African fly (Glossina morsitans) whose bite is very poisonous  and even fatal to horses and cattle but harmless to men. It renders extensive districts in which it abounds uninhabitable during certain seasons of the year."
"An open wooden vessel formed with staves  bottom and hoops; a kind of short cask half barrel or firkin usually with but one head -- used for various purposes."
"Of or pertaining to a tube; specifically  of or pertaining to one of the Fallopian tubes; as tubal pregnancy."
"Resembling a tub; specifically sounding dull and without resonance  like a tub; wanting elasticity or freedom of sound; as a tubby violin."
"A hollow cylinder  of any material used for the conveyance of fluids and for various other purposes; a pipe."
"A fleshy  rounded stem or root usually containing starchy matter as the potato or arrowroot; a thickened root-stock. See Illust. of Tuberous."
"The sapphirine gurnard (Trigla hirundo). See Illust. under Gurnard."
"As much as a tub will hold; enough to fill a tub."
"One of the two most experienced barristers in the Court of Exchequer. Cf. Postman  2."
"Having the form of a tube  or pipe; consisting of a pipe; fistular; as a tubular snout; a tubular calyx. Also containing or provided with tubes."
"A small pipe or fistular body; a little tube."
"The Mexican pocket gopher (Geomys Mexicanus). It resembles the common pocket gopher of the Western United States  but is larger. Called also tugan and tuza."
"One who  or that which tucks; specifically an instrument with which tuck are made."
"A slight flourish on a trumpet; a fanfare."

"A fine  strong fiber obtained from the young leaves of a Brazilian palm (Astrocaryum vulgare) used for cordage bowstrings etc.; also the plant yielding this fiber. Called also tecum and tecum fiber."
"A Brazilian palm (Astrocaryum Tucuma) which furnishes an edible fruit."
"Of or pertaining to a royal line of England  descended from Owen Tudor of Wales who married the widowed queen of Henry V. The first reigning Tudor was Henry VII.; the last Elizabeth."
"The third day of the week  following Monday and preceding Wednesday."
"A soft or porous stone formed by depositions from water  usually calcareous; -- called also calcareous tufa."
"A collection of small  flexible or soft things in a knot or bunch; a waving or bending and spreading cluster; as a tuft of flowers or feathers."
"To pull or draw with great effort; to draw along with continued exertion; to haul along; to tow; as  to tug a loaded cart; to tug a ship into port."
"In plate armor  a suspended plate in from of the thigh. See Illust. of Tasses."
"Superintending care over a young person; the particular watch and care of a tutor or guardian over his pupil or ward; guardianship."
"A large bulrush (Scirpus lacustris  and S. Tatora) growing abundantly on overflowed land in California and elsewhere."
"Any plant of the liliaceous genus Tulipa. Many varieties are cultivated for their beautiful  often variegated flowers."
"Belonging to  or in the style of Tully (Marcus Tullius Cicero)."
"To roll over  or to and fro; to throw one's self about; as a person on pain tumbles and tosses."
"One who tumbles; one who plays tricks by various motions of the body; an acrobat."
"A cucking stool for the punishment of scolds."
"To swell; to cause to swell  or puff up."
"Swelled  enlarged or distended; as a tumid leg; tumid flesh."
"A morbid swelling  prominence or growth on any part of the body; especially a growth produced by deposition of new tissue; a neoplasm."
"Consisting in a heap; formed or being in a heap or hillock."
"The commotion or agitation of a multitude  usually accompanied with great noise uproar and confusion of voices; hurly-burly; noisy confusion."
"An artificial hillock  especially one raised over a grave particularly over the graves of persons buried in ancient times; a barrow."
"A large cask; an oblong vessel bulging in the middle  like a pipe or puncheon and girt with hoops; a wine cask."
"The Opuntia Tuna. See Prickly pear  under Prickly."
"Capable of being tuned  or made harmonious; hence harmonious; musical; tuneful."
"A rolling  marshy mossy plain of Northern Siberia."
"One who tunes; especially  one whose occupation is to tune musical instruments."
"An under-garment worn by the ancient Romans of both sexes. It was made with or without sleeves  reached to or below the knees and was confined at the waist by a girdle."
"Animal cellulose; a substance present in the mantle  or tunic of the Tunicates which resembles or is identical with the cellulose of the vegetable kingdom."
"A vessel with a broad mouth at one end  a pipe or tube at the other for conveying liquor fluids etc. into casks bottles or other vessels; a funnel."

"Any one of several species of large oceanic fishes belonging to the Mackerel family  especially the common or great tunny (Orcynus / Albacora thynnus) native of the Mediterranean Sea and the Atlantic Ocean. It sometimes weighs a thousand pounds or more and is extensively caught in the Mediterranean. On the American coast it is called horse mackerel. See Illust. of Horse mackerel under Horse."
"Any one of several species of East Indian and Asiatic insectivores of the family Tupaiidae  somewhat resembling squirrels in size and arboreal habits. The nose is long and pointed."

"A North American tree (Nyssa multiflora) of the Dogwood family  having brilliant glossy foliage and acid red berries. The wood is crossgrained and very difficult to split. Called also black gum sour gum and pepperidge."
"A man who breeds  or deals in tups."
"A red or crimson pigment obtained from certain feathers of several species of turacou; whence the name. It contains nearly six per cent of copper."
"Any one of several species of plantain eaters of the genus Turacus  native of Africa. They are remarkable for the peculiar green and red pigments found in their feathers."

"A headdress worn by men in the Levant and by most Mohammedans of the male sex  consisting of a cap and a sash scarf or shawl usually of cotton or linen wound about the cap and sometimes hanging down the neck."
"A right of digging turf on another man's land; also  the ground where turf is dug."
"Having the lees or sediment disturbed; roiled; muddy; thick; not clear; -- used of liquids of any kind; as  turbid water; turbid wine."

"A water wheel  commonly horizontal variously constructed but usually having a series of curved floats or buckets against which the water acts by its impulse or reaction in flowing either outward from a central chamber inward from an external casing or from above downward etc.; -- also called turbine wheel."
"Any one of numerous marine gastropods of the genus Turbo or family Turbinidae  usually having a turbinate shell pearly on the inside and a calcareous operculum."

"A large European flounder (Rhombus maximus) highly esteemed as a food fish. It often weighs from thirty to forty pounds. Its color on the upper side is brownish with small roundish tubercles scattered over the surface. The lower  or blind side is white. Called also bannock fluke."
"A mode of speech peculiar to the Turks; a Turkish idiom or expression; also  in general a Turkish mode or custom."
"A genus of singing birds including the true thrushes."
"A large  deep vessel for holding soup or other liquid food at the table."
"That upper stratum of earth and vegetable mold which is filled with the roots of grass and other small plants  so as to adhere and form a kind of mat; sward; sod."
"A votary of the turf  or race course; hence sometimes a blackleg."
"A turfite; a votary of the turf  or race course."
"Abounding with turf; made of  or covered with turf."
"Rising into a tumor  or a puffy state; swelling; tumid; as turgent humors."

"Distended beyond the natural state by some internal agent or expansive force; swelled; swollen; bloated; inflated; tumid; -- especially applied to an enlarged part of the body; as  a turgid limb; turgid fruit."
"A shoot or sprout from the ground."
"A member of any of numerous Tartar tribes of Central Asia  etc.; esp. one of the dominant race in Turkey."
"An empire in the southeast of Europe and southwest of Asia."
"Of or pertaining to Turkey or the Turks."
"One of a body of native Algerian tirailleurs in the French army  dressed as a Turk."
"Harassing labor; trouble; molestation by tumult; disturbance; worrying confusion."

"To cause to move upon a center  or as if upon a center; to give circular motion to; to cause to revolve; to cause to move round either partially wholly or repeatedly; to make to change position so as to present other sides in given directions; to make to face otherwise; as to turn a wheel or a spindle; to turn the body or the head."
"One who turns; especially  one whose occupation is to form articles with a lathe."
"The art of fashioning solid bodies into cylindrical or other forms by means of a lathe."
"The edible  fleshy roundish or somewhat conical root of a cruciferous plant (Brassica campestris var. Napus); also the plant itself."

"Any one of numerous species of birds belonging to Turnix or Hemipodius and allied genera of the family Turnicidae. These birds resemble quails and partridges in general appearance and in some of their habits  but differ in important anatomical characteristics. The hind toe is usually lacking. They are found in Asia Africa Southern Europe the East Indian Islands and esp. in Australia and adjacent islands where they are called quails (see Quail n. 3.). See Turnicimorphae."
"A person who has charge of the keys of a prison  for opening and fastening the doors; a warder."

"A common  large handsome American swallowtail butterfly now regarded as one of the forms of Papilio / Jasoniades glaucus. The wings are yellow margined and barred with black and with an orange-red spot near the posterior angle of the hind wings. Called also tiger swallowtail. See Illust. under Swallowtail."
"The root of Ipom/a Turpethum  a plant of Ceylon Malabar and Australia formerly used in medicine as a purgative; -- sometimes called vegetable turpeth."
"A little tower  frequently a merely ornamental structure at one of the angles of a larger structure."

"Of or pertaining to Tuscany in Italy; -- specifically designating one of the five orders of architecture recognized and described by the Italian writers of the 16th century  or characteristic of the order. The original of this order was not used by the Greeks but by the Romans under the Empire. See Order and Illust. of Capital."
"An exclamation indicating check  rebuke or contempt; as tush tush! do not speak of it."
"To struggle  as in sport; to scuffle; to struggle with."
"A tuft  as of grass twigs hair or the like; especially a dense tuft or bunch of grass or sedge."
"Be still; hush; -- an exclamation used for checking or rebuking."
"One who guards  protects watches over or has the care of some person or thing."
"A plant of the genus Hypericum (H. Androsoemum)  from which a healing ointment is prepared in Spain; -- called also parkleaves."
"All; -- a direction for all the singers or players to perform together."
"A yellow or brown amorphous substance obtained as a sublimation product in the flues of smelting furnaces of zinc  and consisting of a crude zinc oxide."
"A nozzle  mouthpiece or fixture through which the blast is delivered to the interior of a blast furnace or to the fire of a forge."
"To talk in a weak and silly manner  like one whose faculties are decayed; to prate; to prattle."
"Two; -- nearly obsolete in common discourse  but used in poetry and burlesque."
"A European shad; -- called also twaite shad. See Shad."
"To cause to make a sharp twanging sound; to twang  or twangle."
"To prate; to talk much and idly; to gabble; to chatter; to twaddle; as  a twattling gossip."
"To pinch and pull with a sudden jerk and twist; to twitch; as  to tweak the nose."
"A soft and flexible fabric for men's wear  made wholly of wool except in some inferior kinds the wool being dyed usually in two colors before weaving."
"To handle lightly; -- said with reference to awkward fiddling; hence  to influence as if by fiddling; to coax; to allure."
"Next in order after the eleventh; coming after eleven others; -- the ordinal of twelve."
"One more that eleven; two and ten; twice six; a dozen."
"One more that nineteen; twice; as  twenty men."
"A kind of mattock  or ax; esp. a tool like a pickax but having instead of the points flat terminations one of which is parallel to the handle the other perpendicular to it."
"To touch lightly  or play with; to tweedle; to twirl; as to twiddle one's thumbs; to twiddle a watch key."
"Of or pertaining to a twig or twigs; like a twig or twigs; full of twigs; abounding with shoots."
"To weave  as cloth so as to produce the appearance of diagonal lines or ribs on the surface."

"A machine for cleansing or loosening wool by the action of a revolving cylinder covered with long iron spikes or teeth; a willy or willying machine; -- called also twilly devil  and devil. See Devil n. 6 and Willy."
"Being one of two born at a birth; as  a twin brother or sister."
"Any plant which twines about a support."
"To pull with a twitch; to pinch; to tweak."
"To open and shut the eye rapidly; to blink; to wink."
"One who gives birth to twins; a breeder of twins."
"To move or turn round rapidly; to whirl round; to move and turn rapidly with the fingers."
"To contort; to writhe; to complicate; to crook spirally; to convolve."
"One who twists; specifically  the person whose occupation is to twist or join the threads of one warp to those of another in weaving."
"To vex by bringing to notice  or reminding of a fault defect misfortune or the like; to revile; to reproach; to upbraid; to taunt; as he twitted his friend of falsehood."
"To pull with a sudden jerk; to pluck with a short  quick motion; to snatch; as to twitch one by the sleeve; to twitch a thing out of another's hand; to twitch off clusters of grapes."
"One who twits  or reproaches; an upbraider."
"An abbreviation of Betwixt  used in poetry or in colloquial language."
"Double; duplicate; multiplied by two; as  a twofold nature; a twofold sense; a twofold argument."
"The title by which the shogun  or former commander in chief of the Japanese army was known to foreigners."
"One of the pads on the under surface of the toes of birds."
"An intrusion of one vegetable cell into the cavity of another  sometimes forming there an irregular mass of cells."
"A hollow water-cooled iron casting in the upper part of the archway in which the dam stands."
"A kettledrum; -- chiefly used in the plural to denote the kettledrums of an orchestra. See Kettledrum."
"A flatulent distention of the belly; tympanites."
"Relating to a type or types; belonging to types; serving as a type; typical."
"The mark or impression of something; stamp; impressed sign; emblem."
"Of or pertaining to typhus; resembling typhus; of a low grade like typhus; as  typhoid symptoms."
"According to Hesiod  the son of Typhoeus and father of the winds but later identified with him."
"A violent whirlwind; specifically  a violent whirlwind occurring in the Chinese seas."
"Of or pertaining to typhus; of the nature of typhus."

"A contagious continued fever lasting from two to three weeks  attended with great prostration and cerebral disorder and marked by a copious eruption of red spots upon the body. Also called jail fever famine fever putrid fever spottled fever etc. See Jail fever under Jail."
"Of the nature of a type; representing something by a form  model or resemblance; emblematic; prefigurative."
"To represent by an image  form model or resemblance."

"The government or authority of a tyrant; a country governed by an absolute ruler; hence  arbitrary or despotic exercise of power; exercise of power over subjects and others with a rigor not authorized by law or justice or not requisite for the purposes of government."
"An absolute ruler; a sovereign unrestrained by law or constitution; a usurper of sovereignty."
"Of or pertaining to Tyre or its people."
"A beginner in learning; one who is in the rudiments of any branch of study; a person imperfectly acquainted with a subject; a novice."

"A white crystalline nitrogenous substance present in small amount in the pancreas and spleen  and formed in large quantity from the decomposition of proteid matter by various means -- as by pancreatic digestion by putrefaction as of cheese by the action of boiling acids etc. Chemically it consists of oxyphenol and amidopropionic acid and by decomposition yields oxybenzoic acid or some other benzol derivative."
"The quality or state of being in a place; local relation; position or location; whereness."
"A tribe of North American Indians belonging to the Creek confederation."
"In Shetland and Orkney  a freehold; property held by udal or allodial right."
"In the Shetland and Orkney Islands  one who holds property by udal or allodial right."
"The glandular organ in which milk is secreted and stored; -- popularly called the bag in cows and other quadrupeds. See Mamma."
"An exclamation expressive of disgust  horror or recoil. Its utterance is usually accompanied by a shudder."
"Offensive to the sight; contrary to beauty; being of disagreeable or loathsome aspect; unsightly; repulsive; deformed."
"A Mongolian race  ancestors of the Finns."
"One of a certain description of militia among the Tartars."
"In Russia  a published proclamation or imperial order having the force of law."

"A solution of continuity in any of the soft parts of the body  discharging purulent matter found on a surface especially one of the natural surfaces of the body and originating generally in a constitutional disorder; a sore discharging pus. It is distinguished from an abscess which has its beginning at least in the depth of the tissues."
"A Mexican and Central American tree (Castilloa elastica and C. Markhamiana) related to the breadfruit tree. Its milky juice contains caoutchouc. Called also ule tree."
"A college or corporation in Turkey composed of the hierarchy  namely the imams or ministers of religion the muftis or doctors of law and the cadis or administrators of justice."
"A mineral occurring in white rounded crystalline masses. It is a hydrous borate of lime and soda."
"The amount which a vessel  as a cask of liquor lacks of being full; wantage; deficiency."
"A European owl (Syrnium aluco) of a tawny color; -- called also uluia."
"Pertaining to ulmin; designating an acid obtained from ulmin."
"A brown amorphous substance found in decaying vegetation. Cf. Humin."
"A genus of trees including the elm."
"The postaxial bone of the forearm  or branchium corresponding to the fibula of the hind limb. See Radius."
"Of or pertaining to the ulna  or the elbow; as the ulnar nerve."
"One of the bones or cartilages of the carpus  which articulates with the ulna and corresponds to the cuneiform in man."
"A division of insects nearly equivalent to the true Orthoptera."
"A long  loose overcoat worn by men and women originally made of frieze from Ulster Ireland."
"In the month immediately preceding the present; as  on the 1st ultimo; -- usually abbreviated to ult. Cf. Proximo."
"Going beyond others  or beyond due limit; extreme; fanatical; uncompromising; as an ultra reformer; ultra measures."
"A genus of owls including the great gray owl (Ulula cinerea) of Arctic America  and other similar species. See Illust. of Owl."
"To howl  as a dog or a wolf; to wail; as ululating jackals."
"A genus of thin papery bright green seaweeds including the kinds called sea lettuce."

"A kind of flower cluster in which the flower stalks radiate from a common point  as in the carrot and milkweed. It is simple or compound; in the latter case each peduncle bears another little umbel called umbellet or umbellule."

"A brown or reddish pigment used in both oil and water colors  obtained from certain natural clays variously colored by the oxides of iron and manganese. It is commonly heated or burned before being used and is then called burnt umber; when not heated it is called raw umber. See Burnt umber below."
"Of or pertaining to umber; like umber; as  umbery gold."
"The entrails and coarser parts of a deer; hence  sometimes entrails in general."
"The boss of a shield  at or near the middle and usually projecting sometimes in a sharp spike."

"The conical shadow projected from a planet or satellite  on the side opposite to the sun within which a spectator could see no portion of the sun's disk; -- used in contradistinction from penumbra. See Penumbra."
"Shade; shadow; obscurity; hence  that which affords a shade as a screen of trees or foliage."
"An African two-horned rhinoceros (Atelodus  / Rhinoceros simus); -- called also chukuru and white rhinoceros."
"The euphonic modification of a root vowel sound by the influence of a  u or especially i in the syllable which formerly followed."
"A person to whose sole decision a controversy or question between parties is referred; especially  one chosen to see that the rules of a game as cricket baseball or the like are strictly observed."

"Not able; not having sufficient strength  means knowledge skill or the like; impotent' weak; helpless; incapable; -- now usually followed by an infinitive or an adverbial phrase; as unable for work; unable to bear fatigue."
"An ecclesiastical who holds but one benefice; -- distinguished from pluralist."
"Not armed or armored; having no arms or weapons."
"The two-toed sloth (Cholopus didactylus)  native of South America. It is about two feet long. Its color is a uniform grayish brown sometimes with a reddish tint."
"Not aware; not noticing; giving no heed; thoughtless; inattentive."
"To pour  or take or let go out of a bag or bags."
"To remove a bank from; to open by  or as if by the removal of a bank."
"To remove a bar or bars from; to unbolt; to open; as  to unbar a gate."
"To deprive of the bark; to decorticate; to strip; as  to unbark a tree."
"To free from the restraint of anything that surrounds or incloses; to let loose; to open."
"To cause not to be; to cause to be another."

"To remove a band from; to set free from shackles or fastenings; to unite; to unfasten; to loose; as  unbind your fillets; to unbind a prisoner's arms; to unbind a load."

"To deprive of blessings; to make wretched."

"To free from blindness; to give or restore sight to; to open the eyes of."

"Not born; no yet brought into life; being still to appear; future."
"To disclose freely; to reveal in confidence  as secrets; to confess; -- often used reflexively; as to unbosom one's self."

"To free from tension; to relax; to loose; as  to unbrace a drum; to unbrace the nerves."

"To remove the bung from; as  to unbung a cask."
"To disinter; to exhume; fig.  to disclose."

"To break up the camp of; to dislodge from camp."
"To remove a cap or cover from."

"Not cared for; not heeded; -- with for."

"Of  pertaining to or designating a certain style of letters used in ancient manuscripts esp. in Greek and Latin manuscripts. The letters are somewhat rounded and the upstrokes and downstrokes usually have a slight inclination. These letters were used as early as the 1st century b. c. and were seldom used after the 10th century a. d. being superseded by the cursive style."
"One of the peculiar minute chitinous hooks found in large numbers in the tori of tubicolous annelids belonging to the Uncinata."
"To deprive of the rank or rights of a city."
"To loose the clasp of; to open  as something that is fastened or as with a clasp; as to unclasp a book; to unclasp one's heart."
"The brother of one's father or mother; also applied to an aunt's husband; -- the correlative of aunt in sex  and of nephew and niece in relationship."

"To remove a cloak or cover from; to deprive of a cloak or cover; to unmask; to reveal."

"To open; to separate the parts of; as  to unclose a letter; to unclose one's eyes."
"To free from clouds; to unvail; to clear from obscurity  gloom sorrow or the like."
"Unknown; strange  or foreign; unusual or surprising; distant in manner; reserved."
"To detach or loose from a coach."
"To let down the cock of  as a firearm."
"To deprive of the coif or cap."
"To unwind or open  as a coil of rope."
"To release from cords; to loosen the cord or cords of; to unfasten or unbind; as  to uncord a package."

"To take the cover from; to divest of covering; as  to uncover a box bed house or the like; to uncover one's body."
"To divest or deprive of a cowl."

"The act of anointing  smearing or rubbing with an unguent oil or ointment especially for medical purposes or as a symbol of consecration; as mercurial unction."
"To loose from curls  or ringlets; to straighten out as anything curled or curly."
"To free from a curse or an execration."
"Not cut; not separated or divided by cutting or otherwise; -- said especially of books  periodicals and the like when the leaves have not been separated by trimming in binding."

"Rising and falling in waves toward the margin  as a leaf; waved."

"Below or lower  in place or position with the idea of being covered; lower than; beneath; -- opposed to over; as he stood under a tree; the carriage is under cover; a cellar extends under the whole house."
"To do less than is requisite or proper; -- opposed to overdo."
"To go or move below or under."

"The time between; the time between sunrise and noon; specifically  the third hour of the day or nine o'clock in the morning according to ancient reckoning; hence mealtime because formerly the principal meal was eaten at that hour; also later the afternoon; the time between dinner and supper."
"To free from possession by a devil or evil spirit; to exorcise."
"To put off; to lay aside  as a garment."
"One of a class of fabled female water spirits who might receive a human soul by intermarrying with a mortal."
"To reverse  as what has been done; to annul; to bring to naught."

"One who undoes anything; especially  one who ruins another."

"To strip of drapery; to uncover or unveil."
"To draw aside or open; to draw back."
"Not due; not yet owing; as  an undue debt note or bond."
"To remove the dullness of; to clear."
"Not dying; imperishable; unending; immortal; as  the undying souls of men."
"To drive or draw from the earth; hence  to uncover; to bring out from concealment; to bring to light; to disclose; as to unearth a secret."

"Not equal; not matched; not of the same size  length breadth quantity strength talents acquirements age station or the like; as the fingers are of unequal length; peers and commoners are unequal in rank."

"To make unsuitable or incompetent; to deprive of the strength  skill or proper qualities for anything; to disable; to incapacitate; to disqualify; as sickness unfits a man for labor; sin unfits us for the society of holy beings."
"To loosen from a fastening; to detach from anything that holds; to unsettle; as  to unfix a bayonet; to unfix the mind or affections."
"To deprive of flesh; to reduce a skeleton."
"To open the folds of; to expand; to spread out; as  to unfold a tablecloth."
"To restore from folly  or from being a fool."
"To decompose  or resolve into parts; to destroy the form of; to unmake."
"To take apart  or destroy the frame of."
"To deprive or divest or a frock; specifically  to deprive of priestly character or privilege; as to unfrock a priest."
"To loose from a furled state; to unfold; to expand; to open or spread; as  to unfurl sails; to unfurl a flag."
"To strip of gear; to unharness; to throw out of gear."
"A person so far out of the protection of the law  that if he were murdered no geld or fine should be paid or composition made by him that killed him."
"To cause to be unbegotten or unborn  or as if unbegotten or unborn."
"To loose the girdle or band of; to unbind; to unload."
"To yield; to relax; to give way."
"To strip of glass; to remove the glazing  or glass from as a window."
"To take off the glove or gloves of; as  to unglove the hand."

"Not godly; not having regard for God; disobedient to God; wicked; impious; sinful."

"Of or pertaining to a nail  claw talon or hoof or resembling one."
"To deprive of a guard; to leave unprotected."
"A lubricant or salve for sores  burns or the like; an ointment."

"Hoofed  or bearing hoofs; -- used only when these are of a tincture different from the body."
"To deprive of hair  or of hairs; as to unhair hides for leather."
"To loose from the hand; to let go."
"To divest or strip of hangings; to remove the hangings  as a room."
"Not happy or fortunate; unfortunate; unlucky; as  affairs have taken an unhappy turn."
"To unloose the hasp of; to unclose."
"To take off the hat of; to remove one's hat  especially as a mark of respect."
"To take out the head of; as  to unhead a cask."
"Not heard; not perceived by the ear; as  words unheard by those present."
"To cause to lose heart; to dishearten."
"To deprive of the helm or helmet."
"To bring out from concealment; to discover."
"To take from the hinges; as  to unhinge a door."
"To free from being hitched  or as if from being hitched; to unfasten; to loose; as to unhitch a horse or a trace."
"To drive or remove from a hive."
"To take or steal from a hoard; to pilfer."
"To cease to hold; to unhand; to release."
"Not holy; unhallowed; not consecrated; hence  profane; wicked; impious."
"To remove a hood or disguise from."
"To loose from a hook; to undo or open by loosening or unfastening the hooks of; as  to unhook a fish; to unhook a dress."
"To strip or deprive of hoops; to take away the hoops of."
"To throw from a horse; to cause to dismount; also  to take a horse or horses from; as to unhorse a rider; to unhorse a carriage."
"To drive from a house or habitation; to dislodge; hence  to deprive of shelter."
"A member of the Greek Church  who nevertheless acknowledges the supremacy of the Pope of Rome; one of the United Greeks. Also used adjectively."
"The condition of being united; quality of the unique; unification."
"A fabulous animal with one horn; the monoceros; -- often represented in heraldry as a supporter."
"One who  or that which unifies; as a natural law is a unifier of phenomena."

"Having always the same form  manner or degree; not varying or variable; unchanging; consistent; equable; homogenous; as the dress of the Asiatics has been uniform from early ages; the temperature is uniform; a stratum of uniform clay."
"To cause to be one; to make into a unit; to unite; to view as one."
"Any one of numerous species of fresh-water mussels belonging to Unio and many allied genera."
"The act of uniting or joining two or more things into one  or the state of being united or joined; junction; coalition; combination."
"A woman who has borne one child."
"Being without a like or equal; unmatched; unequaled; unparalleled; single in kind or excellence; sole."
"Of or pertaining to a unit or units; relating to unity; as  the unitary method in arithmetic."

"To put together so as to make one; to join  as two or more constituents to form a whole; to combine; to connect; to join; to cause to adhere; as to unite bricks by mortar; to unite iron bars by welding; to unite two armies."
"The act of uniting  or the state of being united; junction."
"Having the power of uniting; causing  or tending to produce union."
"To reduce to a unit  or one whole; to form into a unit; to unify."
"Acting contrary to the standard of right; not animated or controlled by justice; false; dishonest; as  an unjust man or judge."
"A European aquatic toad (Bombinator igneus). Its back is dark; its belly is marked with crimson. Called also feuerkrote."
"Not combed; disheveled; as  an urchin with unkempt hair."
"To cause to cease to be a king."
"To cancel or annul what was done or sealed by a kiss; to cancel by a kiss."
"To undo or unravel what is knitted together."
"To cease to know; to lose the knowledge of."
"To loose by undoing a lacing; as  to unlace a shoe."
"To take the load from; to take out the cargo of; as  to unlade a ship or a wagon."
"To loose  as that which is lashed or tied down."
"To open or loose by lifting the latch; as  to unlatch a door."
"To deprive of the authority or character of law."
"Not having the claws and balls of the forefeet cut off; -- said of dogs."
"To untwist; as  to unlay a rope."
"To forget  as what has been learned; to lose from memory; also to learn the contrary of."
"To free from a leash  or as from a leash; to let go; to release; as to unleash dogs."

"Upon any less condition than (the fact or thing stated in the sentence or clause which follows); if not; supposing that not; if it be not; were it not that; except; as  we shall fail unless we are industrious."

"To make loose; to loosen; to set free."

"To pick out; to undo by picking."
"To loose from pins; to remove the pins from; to unfasten; as  to unpin a frock; to unpin a frame."

"To remove the plaits of; to smooth."

"To remove a prop or props from; to deprive of support."

"Not read or perused; as  an unread book."
"Not ready or prepared; not prompt; slow; awkward; clumsy."
"To withdraw  or take out as a rope from a block thimble or the like."

"To annul or reverse by an act of the will."
"To wind off; to loose or separate  as what or convolved; to untwist; to untwine; as to unwind thread; to unwind a ball of yarn."
"Not wise; defective in wisdom; injudicious; indiscreet; foolish; as  an unwise man; unwise kings; unwise measures."
"To wish not to be; to destroy by wishing."
"To free from a witch or witches; to fee from witchcraft."
"To deprive of the qualities of a woman; to unsex."
"To undo or destroy  as work previously done."
"To open or undo  as what is wrapped or folded."
"To cancel  as what is written; to erase."
"To loose or free from a yoke."
"Not yet yoked; not having worn the yoke."
"Not zoned; not bound with a girdle; as  an unzoned bosom."

"A tree (Antiaris toxicaria) of the Breadfruit family  common in the forests of Java and the neighboring islands. Its secretions are poisonous and it has been fabulously reported that the atmosphere about it is deleterious. Called also bohun upas."
"To bear up; to raise aloft; to support in an elevated situation; to sustain."
"To charge with something wrong or disgraceful; to reproach; to cast something in the teeth of; -- followed by with or for  and formerly of before the thing imputed."
"To break upwards; to force away or passage to the surface."
"To rear  or bring up; to nurse."
"The act of bursting upwards; a breaking through to the surface; an upbreak or uprush; as  an upburst of molten matter."
"Cast up; thrown upward; as  with upcast eyes."
"To coil up; to make into a coil  or to be made into a coil."
"To end up; to set on end  as a cask."
"Lifted by the hand  or by both hands; as the uphand sledge."
"To hasp or faster up; to close; as  sleep uphasps the eyes."
"To heave or lift up from beneath; to raise."
"A fir pole of from four to seven inches diameter  and twenty to forty feet long sometimes roughly hewn used for scaffoldings and sometimes for slight and common roofs for which use it is split."
"Upwards on  or as on a hillside; as to walk uphill."
"To thrust in up to the hilt; as  to uphilt one's sword into an enemy."
"To hold up; to lift on high; to elevate."

"High land; ground elevated above the meadows and intervals which lie on the banks of rivers  near the sea or between hills; land which is generally dry; -- opposed to lowland meadow marsh swamp interval and the like."
"To lift or raise aloft; to raise; to elevate; as  to uplift the arm; to uplift a rock."
"On; -- used in all the senses of that word  with which it is interchangeable."
"Being further up  literally or figuratively; higher in place position rank dignity or the like; superior; as the upper lip; the upper side of a thing; the upper house of a legislature."
"Proud; arrogant; assuming; putting on airs of superiority."
"In an erect position or posture; perpendicular; vertical  or nearly vertical; pointing upward; as an upright tree."
"To rise; to get up; to appear from below the horizon."
"Great tumult; violent disturbance and noise; noisy confusion; bustle and clamor."
"To root up; to tear up by the roots  or as if by the roots; to remove utterly; to eradicate; to extirpate."
"To rouse up; to rouse from sleep; to awake; to arouse."
"Final issue; conclusion; the sum and substance; the end; the result; the consummation."
"The upper side; the part that is uppermost."
"To grow or shoot up like a spear; as  upspearing grass."
"To stand up; to be erected; to rise."
"To stare or stand upward; hence  to be uplifted or conspicuous."
"The time during which the sun is up  or above the horizon; the time between sunrise and sunset."
"To rise  or cause to rise in a swarm or swarms."
"To sway or swing aloft; as  to upsway a club."
"To take into the hand; to take up; to help."
"To or in the upper part of a town; as  to go uptown."
"To turn up; to direct upward; to throw up; as  to upturn the ground in plowing."
"A genus of birds which includes the common hoopoe."
"In a direction from lower to higher; toward a higher place; in a course toward the source or origin; -- opposed to downward; as  to tend or roll upward."
"To rise upward in a whirl; to raise upward with a whirling motion."
"A cord or band of fibrous tissue extending from the bladder to the umbilicus."
"Accumulation in the blood of the principles of the urine  producing dangerous disease."
"Of or pertaining to uraemia; as  uraemic convulsions."
"Pertaining to  or designating the Urals a mountain range between Europe and Asia."
"Of or relating to the Ural Mountains."
"Amphibole resulting from the alternation of pyroxene by paramorphism. It is not uncommon in massive eruptive rocks."
"One of the nine Muses  daughter of Zeus by Mnemosyne and patron of astronomy."
"Of or pertaining to the planet Uranus; as  the Uranian year."
"Of or pertaining to the heavens; celestial; astronomical."

"An alkaline salt of fluorescein  obtained as a brownish red substance which is used as a dye; -- so called from the peculiar yellowish green fluorescence (resembling that of uranium glass) of its solutions. See Fluorescein."
"A general term for the uranium phosphates  autunite or lime uranite and torbernite or copper uranite."

"An element of the chromium group  found in certain rare minerals as pitchblende uranite etc. and reduced as a heavy hard nickel-white metal which is quite permanent. Its yellow oxide is used to impart to glass a delicate greenish-yellow tint which is accompanied by a strong fluorescence and its black oxide is used as a pigment in porcelain painting. Symbol U. Atomic weight 239."
"Pertaining to  or containing uranium; designating those compounds in which uranium has a lower valence as contrasted with the uranic compounds."
"The son or husband of Gaia (Earth)  and father of Chronos (Time) and the Titans."
"The radical UO2  conveniently regarded as a residue of many uranium compounds."
"A salt of uric acid; as  sodium urate; ammonium urate."
"Of or containing urates; as  uratic calculi."
"Of or belonging to a city or town; as  an urban population."
"A vessel for water for washing the hands; also  one to hold wine or water."
"A very soluble crystalline body which is the chief constituent of the urine in mammals and some other animals. It is also present in small quantity in blood  serous fluids lymph the liver etc."
"Of or pertaining to urea; containing  or consisting of urea; as ureal deposits."

"One of the stages in the life history of certain rusts (Uredinales)  regarded at one time as a distinct genus. It is a summer stage preceding the teleutospore or winter stage. See Uredinales in the Supplement."
"Any one of the many complex derivatives of urea; thus  hydantoin and in an extended dense guanidine caffeine et. are ureides."
"The duct which conveys the urine from the kidney to the bladder or cloaca. There are two ureters  one for each kidney."
"The canal by which the urine is conducted from the bladder and discharged."
"Of or pertaining to the urine; diuretic; urinary; as  uretic medicine."
"To press; to push; to drive; to impel; to force onward."
"The quality or condition of being urgent; insistence; pressure; as  the urgency of a demand or an occasion."
"Urging; pressing; besetting; plying  with importunity; calling for immediate attention; instantly important."
"Of or pertaining to urine; obtained from urine; as  uric acid."

"A part or decoration of the breastplate of the high priest among the ancient Jews  by which Jehovah revealed his will on certain occasions. Its nature has been the subject of conflicting conjectures."
"A vessel for holding urine; especially  a bottle or tube for holding urine for inspection."
"Of or pertaining to the urine; as  the urinary bladder; urinary excretions."
"In mammals  a fluid excretion from the kidneys; in birds and reptiles a solid or semisolid excretion."
"Of or pertaining to urine  or partaking of its qualities; having the character or odor of urine; similar to urine."
"One of the segments of the abdomen or post-abdomen of arthropods."

"A vessel of various forms  usually a vase furnished with a foot or pedestal employed for different purposes as for holding liquids for ornamental uses for preserving the ashes of the dead after cremation and anciently for holding lots to be drawn."
"Of or pertaining to an urn; effected by an urn or urns."
"As much as an urn will hold; enough to fill an urn."
"A morbid swelling of the scrotum due to extravasation of urine into it."
"An order of amphibians having the tail well developed and often long. It comprises the salamanders  tritons and allied animals."
"Of or pertaining to one or more median and posterior elements in the hyoidean arch of fishes."
"Any one of the abdominal segments of an arthropod."

"Any one of the abdominal appendages of a crustacean  especially one of the posterior ones which are often larger than the rest and different in structure and are used chiefly in locomotion. See Illust. of Crustacea and Stomapoda."
"A sort of blue or black clay lying near a vein of coal."
"Either one of the Bears. See the Phrases below."
"The ursine seal. See the Note under 1st Seal."
"Of or pertaining to a bear; resembling a bear."
"A beautiful North American butterfly (Basilarchia  / Limenitis astyanax). Its wings are nearly black with red and blue spots and blotches. Called also red-spotted purple."
"A genus of Carnivora including the common bears."
"A genus of plants including the common nettles. See Nettle  n."
"Resembling nettles; -- said of several natural orders allied to urticaceous plants."
"The black vulture (Catharista atrata). It ranges from the Southern United States to South America. See Vulture."

"A very large  powerful and savage extinct bovine animal (Bos urus / primigenius) anciently abundant in Europe. It appears to have still existed in the time of Julius Caesar. It had very large horns and was hardly capable of domestication. Called also ur ure and tur."
"The crab-eating ichneumon (Herpestes urva)  native of India. The fur is black annulated with white at the tip of each hair and a white streak extends from the mouth to the shoulder."
"The act of using; mode of using or treating; treatment; conduct with respect to a person or a thing; as  good usage; ill usage; hard usage."
"One who has the use of anything in trust for another."
"A Turkish tribe which about the close of the 15th century conquered  and settled in that part of Asia now called Turkestan."

"The act of employing anything  or of applying it to one's service; the state of being so employed or applied; application; employment; conversion to some purpose; as the use of a pen in writing; his machines are in general use."

"Full of use  advantage or profit; producing or having power to produce good; serviceable for any end or object; helpful toward advancing any purpose; beneficial; profitable; advantageous; as vessels and instruments useful in a family; books useful for improvement; useful knowledge; useful arts."
"Having  or being of no use; unserviceable; producing no good end; answering no valuable purpose; not advancing the end proposed; unprofitable; ineffectual; as a useless garment; useless pity."

"An officer or servant who has the care of the door of a court  hall chamber or the like; hence an officer whose business it is to introduce strangers or to walk before a person of rank. Also one who escorts persons to seats in a church theater etc."

"A genus of lichens  most of the species of which have long gray pendulous and finely branched fronds. Usnea barbata is the common bearded lichen which grows on branches of trees in northern forests."
"Pertaining to  or designating a complex acid obtained as a yellow crystalline substance from certain genera of lichens (Usnea Parmelia etc.)."
"The act of burning  or the state of being burned."
"Such as is in common use; such as occurs in ordinary practice  or in the ordinary course of events; customary; ordinary; habitual; common."
"To practice usury; to charge unlawful interest."
"One who lends money and takes interest for it; a money lender."

"To seize  and hold in possession by force or without right; as to usurp a throne; to usurp the prerogatives of the crown; to usurp power; to usurp the right of a patron is to oust or dispossess him."
"One who usurps; especially  one who seizes illegally on sovereign power; as the usurper of a throne of power or of the rights of a patron."
"A premium or increase paid  or stipulated to be paid for a loan as of money; interest."
"The eighth day after any term or feast; the octave; as  the utas of St. Michael."
"That which is used; an instrument; an implement; especially  an instrument or vessel used in a kitchen or in domestic and farming business."
"Of or instrument to the uterus  or womb."
"The organ of a female mammal in which the young are developed previous to birth; the womb."

"An extensive tribe of North American Indians of the Shoshone stock  inhabiting Colorado Utah New Mexico Arizona and adjacent regions. They are subdivided into several subordinate tribes some of which are among the most degraded of North American Indians."
"Any species of large West Indian rodents of the genus Capromys  or Utia. In general appearance and habits they resemble rats but they are as large as rabbits."
"Of  pertaining to or designating a subdivision of the Trenton Period of the Lower Silurian characterized in the State of New York by beds of shale."

"The quality or state of being useful; usefulness; production of good; profitableness to some valuable end; as  the utility of manure upon land; the utility of the sciences; the utility of medicines."
"To make useful; to turn to profitable account or use; to make use of; as  to utilize the whole power of a machine; to utilize one's opportunities."
"Situated at the farthest point or extremity; farthest out; most distant; extreme; as  the utmost limits of the land; the utmost extent of human knowledge."

"An imaginary island  represented by Sir Thomas More in a work called Utopia as enjoying the greatest perfection in politics laws and the like. See Utopia in the Dictionary of Noted Names in Fiction."
"Of or pertaining to Utopia; resembling Utopia; hence  ideal; chimerical; fanciful; founded upon or involving imaginary perfections; as Utopian projects; Utopian happiness."
"A little sac or vesicle  as the air cell of fucus or seaweed."
"- (/). A combining form used in anatomy to indicate connection with  or relation to the uterus; as in utro-ovarian."
"In an utter manner; to the full extent; fully; totally; as  utterly ruined; it is utterly vain."
"A small pulpy or juicy fruit containing several seeds and having a thin skin  as a grape."
"The posterior pigmented layer of the iris; -- sometimes applied to the whole iris together with the choroid coat."

"Pertaining to  or obtained from grapes; specifically designating an organic acid C7H8O3 (also called pyrotritartaric acid) obtained as a white crystalline substance by the decomposition of tartaric and pyrotartaric acids."
"Pertaining to  or designating an acid CH3C6H3(CO2H)2 obtained as a white crystalline substance by the partial oxidation of mesitylene; -- called also mesitic acid."
"The pendent fleshy lobe in the middle of the posterior border of the soft palate."
"Dotingly fond of  or servilely submissive to a wife; uxorious; also becoming a wife; pertaining to a wife."
"The quality or state of being vacant; emptiness; hence  freedom from employment; intermission; leisure; idleness; listlessness."
"Deprived of contents; not filled; empty; as  a vacant room."
"To make vacant; to leave empty; to cease from filling or occupying; as  it was resolved by Parliament that James had vacated the throne of England; the tenant vacated the house."
"A cow house  dairy house or cow pasture."
"Of or pertaining to cows; pertaining to  derived from or caused by vaccinia; as vaccine virus; the vaccine disease."
"A keeper of stock or cattle; a herdsman."
"One who holds the doctrine that the space between the bodies of the universe  or the molecules and atoms of matter. is a vacuum; -- opposed to plenist."
"The quality or state of being vacuous  or not filled; emptiness; vacancy; as vacuity of mind; vacuity of countenance."
"The goddess of rural leisure  to whom the husbandmen sacrificed at the close of the harvest. She was especially honored by the Sabines."
"A small air cell  or globular space in the interior of organic cells either containing air or a pellucid watery liquid or some special chemical secretions of the cell protoplasm."

"A space entirely devoid of matter (called also  by way of distinction absolute vacuum); hence in a more general sense a space as the interior of a closed vessel which has been exhausted to a high or the highest degree by an air pump or other artificial means; as water boils at a reduced temperature in a vacuum."
"Of or pertaining to the vagus  or pneumogastric nerves; pneumogastric."
"A sheath; a theca; as  the vagina of the portal vein."
"Of or pertaining to a vagina; resembling a vagina  or sheath; thecal; as a vaginal synovial membrane; the vaginal process of the temporal bone."
"Moving without certain direction; wandering; erratic; unsettled."
"Wandering; -- applied especially to the pneumogastric nerve."
"An outer  or exterior. wall. See Vauntmure."
"Having no real substance  value or importance; empty; void; worthless; unsatisfying."

"The skin of the squirrel  much used in the fourteenth century as fur for garments and frequently mentioned by writers of that period in describing the costly dresses of kings nobles and prelates. It is represented in heraldry by a series of small shields placed close together and alternately white and blue."
"Charged with vair; variegated with shield-shaped figures. See Vair."
"The third of the four great original castes among the Hindus  now either extinct or partially represented by the mercantile class of Banyas. See the Note under Caste 1."
"A native attorney or agent; also  an ambassador."
"Hanging drapery for a bed  couch window or the like especially that which hangs around a bedstead from the bed to the floor."
"A tract of low ground  or of land between hills; a valley."

"The degree of combining power of an atom (or radical) as shown by the number of atoms of hydrogen (or of other monads  as chlorine sodium etc.) with which it will combine or for which it can be substituted or with which it can be compared; thus an atom of hydrogen is a monad and has a valence of one; the atoms of oxygen nitrogen and carbon are respectively dyads triads and tetrads

"Valerianic; specifically  designating any one of three metameric acids of which the typical one (called also inactive valeric acid) C4H9CO2H is obtained from valerian root and other sources as a corrosive mobile oily liquid having a strong acid taste and an odor of old cheese."
