"A salt of valeric acid with glycerin  occurring in butter dolphin oil. and forming an forming an oily liquid with a slightly unpleasant odor."
"The hypothetical radical C5H9O  regarded as the essential nucleus of certain valeric acid derivatives."
"A male waiting servant; a servant who attends on gentleman's person; a body servant."
"Vigorous in body; strong; powerful; as  a valiant fencer."
"In a valid manner; so as to be valid."
"A tube for drawing liquors from a cask by the bunghole."
"A small sack or case  usually of leather but sometimes of other material for containing the clothes toilet articles etc. of a traveler; a traveling bag; a portmanteau."

"The space inclosed between ranges of hills or mountains; the strip of land at the bottom of the depressions intersecting a country  including usually the bed of a stream with frequently broad alluvial plains on one or both sides of the stream. Also used figuratively."
"A rampart; a wall  as in a fortification."
"The acorn cup of two kinds of oak (Quercus macrolepis  and Q. vallonea) found in Eastern Europe. It contains abundance of tannin and is much used by tanners and dyers."
"The property or aggregate properties of a thing by which it is rendered useful or desirable  or the degree of such property or sum of properties; worth; excellence; utility; importance."
"A genus of small spiral fresh-water gastropods having an operculum."
"Resembling  or serving as a valve; consisting of or opening by a valve or valves; valvular."
"A door; especially  one of a pair of folding doors or one of the leaves of such a door."
"A little valve or fold; a valvelet; a valvule."
"One who vamps; one who pieces an old thing with something new; a cobbler."

"A blood-sucking ghost; a soul of a dead person superstitiously believed to come from the grave and wander about by night sucking the blood of persons asleep  thus causing their death. This superstition is now prevalent in parts of Eastern Europe and was especially current in Hungary about the year 1730."
"The front of an army; the first line or leading column; also  the front line or foremost division of a fleet either in sailing or in battle."

"Pertaining to  or obtained from vanadium; containing vanadium; specifically distinguished those compounds in which vanadium has a relatively higher valence as contrasted with the vanadious compounds; as vanadic oxide."
"The hypothetical radical VO  regarded as a characterized residue of certain vanadium compounds."

"One of a Teutonic race  formerly dwelling on the south shore of the Baltic the most barbarous and fierce of the northern nations that plundered Rome in the 5th century notorious for destroying the monuments of art and literature."
"Of or pertaining to the style of Vandyke the painter; used or represented by Vandyke."

"A contrivance attached to some elevated object for the purpose of showing which way the wind blows; a weathercock. It is usually a plate or strip of metal  or slip of wood often cut into some fanciful form and placed upon a perpendicular axis around which it moves freely."
"Any one of numerous species of handsomely colored butterflies belonging to Vanessa and allied genera. Many of these species have the edges of the wings irregularly scalloped."
"A ditch on the outside of the counterscarp  usually full of water."
"A rope to steady the peak of a gaff."
"Benne (Sesamum orientale); also  its seeds; -- so called in the West Indies."
"A genus of climbing orchidaceous plants  natives of tropical America."
"To pass from a visible to an invisible state; to go out of sight; to disappear; to fade; as  vapor vanishes from the sight by being dissipated; a ship vanishes from the sight of spectators on land."
"The quality or state of being vain; want of substance to satisfy desire; emptiness; unsubstantialness; unrealness; falsity."
"The Australian pied crow shrike (Strepera graculina). It is glossy bluish black  with the under tail coverts and the tips and bases of the tail feathers white."
"A machine for concentrating ore. See Frue vanner."
"A process by which ores are washed on a shovel  or in a vanner."
"An ichneumon (Herpestes galera) native of Southern Africa and Madagascar. It is reddish brown or dark brown  grizzled with white. Called also vondsira and marsh ichneumon."
"superior or more favorable situation or opportunity; gain; profit; advantage."
"Being on  or towards the van or front."
"That which is vapid  insipid or lifeless; especially the lifeless part of liquor or wine."
"Having lost its life and spirit; dead; spiritless; insipid; flat; dull; unanimated; as  vapid beer; a vapid speech; a vapid state of the blood."
"Any substance in the gaseous  or aeriform state the condition of which is ordinarily that of a liquid or solid."
"One who has charge of cattle  horses etc.; a herdsman."
"A Spanish measure of length equal to about one yard. The vara now in use equals 33.385 inches."
"A genus of very large lizards native of Asia and Africa. It includes the monitors. See Monitor  3."
"A wand or staff of authority or justice."
"The calcined ashes of any coarse seaweed used for the manufacture of soda and iodine; also  the seaweed itself; fucus; wrack."
"The ringtailed lemur (Lemur catta) of Madagascar. Its long tail is annulated with black and white."
"Varying in from  character or the like; variable; different; diverse."
"To alter; to make different; to vary."
"Changed; altered; various; diversified; as  a varied experience; varied interests; varied scenery."
"A wanderer; one who strays in search of variety."
"The quality or state of being various; intermixture or succession of different things; diversity; multifariousness."
"To make different; to vary; to variegate."
"Different; diverse; several; manifold; as  men of various names; various occupations; various colors."
"An imperfection on the inside of the hind leg in horses  different from a curb but at the same height and frequently injuring the sale of the animal by growing to an unsightly size."
"A uneven  permanent dilatation of a vein."
"A servant  especially to a knight; an attendant; a valet; a footman."

"A viscid liquid  consisting of a solution of resinous matter in an oil or a volatile liquid laid on work with a brush or otherwise. When applied the varnish soon dries either by evaporation or chemical action and the resinous part forms thus a smooth hard surface with a beautiful gloss capable of resisting to a greater or less degree the influences of air and moisture."

"The god of the waters; the Indian Neptune. He is regarded as regent of the west  and lord of punishment and is represented as riding on a sea monster holding in his hand a snaky cord or noose with which to bind offenders under water."
"In falconry  one of the rings secured to the ends of the jesses."

"To change the aspect of; to alter in form  appearance substance position or the like; to make different by a partial change; to modify; as to vary the properties proportions or nature of a thing; to vary a posture or an attitude; to vary one's dress or opinions."

"A vessel adapted for various domestic purposes  and anciently for sacrificial uses; especially a vessel of antique or elegant pattern used for ornament; as a porcelain vase; a gold vase; a Grecian vase. See Illust. of Portland vase under Portland."
"The grantee of a fief  feud or fee; one who holds land of superior and who vows fidelity and homage to him; a feudatory; a feudal tenant."
"To a vast extent or degree; very greatly; immensely."
"A genus including several species of large marine gastropods having massive pyriform shells  with conspicuous folds on the columella."
"A large vessel  cistern or tub especially one used for holding in an immature state chemical preparations for dyeing or for tanning or for tanning leather or the like."
"As much as a vat will hold; enough to fill a vat."
"Of or pertaining to a prophet; prophetical."
"A magnificent assemblage of buildings at Rome  near the church of St. Peter including the pope's palace a museum a library a famous chapel etc."
"An inhabitant  or the inhabitants of the Swiss canton of Vaud."
"An arched structure of masonry  forming a ceiling or canopy."
"One who vaults; a leaper; a tumbler."
"To boast; to make a vain display of one's own worth  attainments decorations or the like; to talk ostentatiously; to brag."
"The vassal or tenant of a baron; one who held under a baron  and who also had tenants under him; one in dignity next to a baron; a title of dignity next to a baron."
"The thirteenth  or intercalary month of the Jewish ecclesiastical calendar which is added about every third year."
"The flesh of a calf when killed and used for food."
"The ancient sacred literature of the Hindus; also  one of the four collections called Rig-Veda Yajur-Veda Sama-Veda and Atharva-Veda constituting the most ancient portions of that literature."
"A system of philosophy among the Hindus  founded on scattered texts of the Vedas and thence termed the """"Anta " or end or substance."
"A sentinel  usually on horseback stationed on the outpost of an army to watch an enemy and give notice of danger; a vidette."
"A Russian liquid measure  equal to 3.249 gallons of U. S. standard measure or 2.706 imperial gallons."
"To change direction; to turn; to shift; as  wind veers to the west or north."

"An American thrush (Turdus fuscescens) common in the Northern United States and Canada. It is light tawny brown above. The breast is pale buff  thickly spotted with brown. Called also Wilson's thrush."
"A brilliant star of the first magnitude  the brightest of those constituting the constellation Lyra."
"Of or pertaining to vegetables  or the vegetable kingdom; of the nature of a vegetable; vegetable."
"That in or on which any person or thing is  or may be carried as a coach carriage wagon cart car sleigh bicycle etc.; a means of conveyance; specifically a means of conveyance upon land."

"Of  pertaining to or designating certain secret tribunals which flourished in Germany from the end of the 12th century to the middle of the 16th usurping many of the functions of the government which were too weak to maintain law and order and inspiring dread in all who came within their jurisdiction."
"Something hung up  or spread out to intercept the view and hide an object; a cover; a curtain; esp. a screen usually of gauze crape or similar diaphnous material to hide or protect the face."
"One of the vessels which carry blood  either venous or arterial to the heart. See Artery 2."
"Full of veins; veinous; veined; as  veiny marble."
"Of or pertaining to a velum; esp. (Anat.) of or pertaining to the soft palate."
"Any species of oceanic Siphonophora belonging to the genus Velella."
"Any larval gastropod or bivalve mollusk in the state when it is furnished with one or two ciliated membranes for swimming."
"The salted stomach of a calf  used in making cheese; a rennet bag."
"A word occurring in the phrase real vellon. See the Note under Its Real."
"A fine kind of parchment  usually made from calfskin and rendered clear and white -- used as for writing upon and for binding books."
"One of many textile fabrics having a pile like that of velvet."
"Curtain or covering; -- applied to various membranous partitions  especially to the soft palate. See under Palate."
"A silk fabric  having a short close nap of erect threads. Inferior qualities are made with a silk pile on a cotton or linen back."
"Made of velvet  or like velvet; soft; smooth; delicate."
"Of or pertaining to veins; venous; as  venal blood."
"To transfer to another person for a pecuniary equivalent; to make an object of trade; to dispose of by sale; to sell; as  to vend goods; to vend vegetables."
"A European lake whitefish (Coregonus Willughbii  or C. Vandesius) native of certain lakes in Scotland and England. It is regarded as a delicate food fish. Called also vendis."
"The person to whom a thing is vended  or sold; -- the correlative of vendor."
"One who vends; one who transfers the exclusive right of possessing a thing  either his own or that of another as his agent for a price or pecuniary equivalent; a seller; a vendor."
"A vender; a seller; the correlative of vendee."
"A public sale of anything  by outcry to the highest bidder; an auction."
"To overlay or plate with a thin layer of wood or other material for outer finish or decoration; as  to veneer a piece of furniture with mahogany. Used also figuratively."
"A bout  or turn as at fencing; a thrust; a hit; a veney."
"Capable of being forgiven; not heinous; excusable; pardonable; as  a venial fault or transgression."
"The 95th Psalm  which is said or sung regularly in the public worship of many churches. Also a musical composition adapted to this Psalm."

"Matter fatal or injurious to life; poison; particularly  the poisonous the poisonous matter which certain animals such as serpents scorpions bees etc. secrete in a state of health and communicate by thing or stinging."
"Having numerous or conspicuous veins; veiny; as  a venose frond."
"Of or pertaining to a vein or veins; as  the venous circulation of the blood."
"A small hole  as the stop in a flute; a vent."
"That part of a helmet which is intended for the admission of air  -- sometimes in the visor."
"One who vents; one who utters  reports or publishes."
"Toward the ventral side; on the ventral side; ventrally; -- opposed to dorsad."

"Of  pertaining to or situated near the belly or ventral side of an animal or of one of its parts; hemal; abdominal; as the ventral fin of a fish; the ventral root of a spinal nerve; -- opposed to dorsal."
"An undertaking of chance or danger; the risking of something upon an event which can not be foreseen with certainty; a hazard; a risk; a speculation."
"A neighborhood or near place; the place or county in which anything is alleged to have happened; also  the place where an action is laid."
"A small vein; a veinlet; specifically (Zool.)  one of the small branches of the veins of the wings in insects."
"The goddess of beauty and love  that is beauty or love deified."
"An open  roofed gallery or portico adjoining a dwelling house forming an out-of-door sitting room. See Loggia."
"Expressed in words  whether spoken or written but commonly in spoken words; hence spoken; oral; not written; as a verbal contract; verbal testimony."
"A genus of herbaceous plants of which several species are extensively cultivated for the great beauty of their flowers; vervain."
"To make into a verb; to use as a verb; to verbalize."
"Abounding in words; using or containing more words than are necessary; tedious by a multiplicity of words; prolix; wordy; as  a verbose speaker; a verbose argument."
"The privilege of cutting green wood within a forest for fuel."
"Covered with growing plants or grass; green; fresh; flourishing; as  verdant fields; a verdant lawn."

"The answer of a jury given to the court concerning any matter of fact in any cause  civil or criminal committed to their examination and determination; the finding or decision of a jury on the matter legally submitted to them in the course of the trial of a cause."
"A small yellow-headed bird (Auriparus flaviceps) of Lower California  allied to the titmice; -- called also goldtit."
"A commercial name for green aniline dye."
"Charged with leaves  fruits flowers etc.; -- said of a border."
"Green; greenness; freshness of vegetation; as  the verdure of the meadows in June."
"A rod or staff  carried as an emblem of authority; as the verge carried before a dean."
"One who carries a verge  or emblem of office."
"In very truth; beyond doubt or question; in fact; certainly."
"An alkaloid obtained as a yellow amorphous substance by the decomposition of veratrine."
"The quality or state of being true  or real; consonance of a statement proposition or other thing with fact; truth; reality."
"Vermilion; also  the color of vermilion a bright beautiful red."

"An extensive artificial division of the animal kingdom  including the parasitic worms or helminths together with the nemerteans annelids and allied groups. By some writers the branchiopods the bryzoans and the tunicates are also included. The name was used in a still wider sense by Linnaeus and his followers."
"A liqueur made of white wine  absinthe and various aromatic drugs used to excite the appetite."
"A kind of sweet wine from Italy."
"Of or pertaining to the spring; appearing in the spring; as  vernal bloom."

"A short scale made to slide along the divisions of a graduated instrument  as the limb of a sextant or the scale of a barometer for indicating parts of divisions. It is so graduated that a certain convenient number of its divisions are just equal to a certain number either one less or one more of the divisions of the instrument so that parts of a division are determined by observing what line on the vernier coincides with a line on the instrument."
"An alkaloid extracted from the shoots of the vetch  red clover etc. as a white crystalline substance."
"A line consisting of a certain number of metrical feet (see Foot  n. 9) disposed according to metrical rules."
"A change of form  direction or the like; transformation; conversion; turning."
"The reverse  or left-hand page of a book or a folded sheet of paper; -- opposed to recto."
"A Russian measure of length containing 3 500 English feet."
"Against; as  John Doe versus Richard Roe; -- chiefly used in legal language and abbreviated to v. or vs."
"Everything that grows  and bears a green leaf within the forest; as to preserve vert and venison is the duty of the verderer."
"A turning point; the principal or highest point; top; summit; crown; apex."

"Dizziness or swimming of the head; an affection of the head in which objects  though stationary appear to move in various directions and the person affected finds it difficult to maintain an erect posture; giddiness."
"Excitement of imagination such as animates a poet  artist or musician in composing or performing; rapture; enthusiasm; spirit; energy."
"A South African monkey (Cercopithecus pygerythrus  / Lelandii). The upper parts are grayish green finely specked with black. The cheeks and belly are reddish white."
"A rare metallic element of which little is known. It is said by Scacchi to have been extracted from a yellowish incrustation from the cracks of a Vesuvian lava erupted in 1631."
"A bladderlike vessel; a membranous cavity; a cyst; a cell."
"A genus of Hymenoptera including the common wasps and hornets."
"The evening star; Hesper; Venus  when seen after sunset; hence the evening."
"One of the little hours of the Breviary."
"A hollow or concave utensil for holding anything; a hollow receptacle of any kind  as a hogshead a barrel a firkin a bottle a kettle a cup a bowl etc."
"A kind of worsted; also  a worsted cloth."
"An article of clothing covering the person; an outer garment; a vestment; a dress; a vesture; a robe."
"One of the great divinities of the ancient Romans  identical with the Greek Hestia. She was a virgin and the goddess of the hearth; hence also of the fire on it and the family round it."
"Of or pertaining to Vesta  the virgin goddess of the hearth; hence pure; chaste."

"The mark of the foot left on the earth; a track or footstep; a trace; a sign; hence  a faint mark or visible sign left by something which is lost or has perished or is no longer present; remains; as the vestiges of ancient magnificence in Palmyra; vestiges of former population."

"Any one of several species of actinians belonging to the genus Cerianthus. These animals have a long  smooth body tapering to the base and two separate circles of tentacles around the mouth. They form a tough flexible feltlike tube with a smooth internal lining in which they dwell whence the name."

"A room appendant to a church  in which sacerdotal vestments and sacred utensils are sometimes kept and where meetings for worship or parish business are held; a sacristy; -- formerly called revestiary."
"A garment or garments; a robe; clothing; dress; apparel; vestment; covering; envelope."
"Any leguminous plant of the genus Vicia  some species of which are valuable for fodder. The common species is V. sativa."
"Consisting of vetches or of pea straw."
"Long exercised in anything  especially in military life and the duties of a soldier; long practiced or experienced; as a veteran officer or soldier; veteran skill."
"An East Indian grass (Andropogon muricatus); also  its fragrant roots which are much used for making mats and screens. Also called kuskus and khuskhus."
"An authoritative prohibition or negative; a forbidding; an interdiction."
"One who uses  or sustains the use of the veto."
"An Italian four-wheeled carriage  esp. one let for hire; a hackney coach."
"To to/s back and forth; to agitate; to disquiet."
"A gab at the end of an eccentric rod  with long jaws shaped like the letter V."
"Capable of living; born alive and with such form and development of organs as to be capable of living; -- said of a newborn  or a prematurely born infant."

"A structure of considerable magnitude  usually with arches or supported on trestles for carrying a road as a railroad high above the ground or water; a bridge; especially one for crossing a valley or a gorge. Cf. Trestlework."
"A small bottle  usually of glass; a little glass vessel with a narrow aperture intended to be closed with a stopper; as a vial of medicine."
"An article of food; provisions; food; victuals; -- used chiefly in the plural."
"A feeder; an eater; also  one who provides viands or food; a host."
"Of or pertaining to roads; happening on roads."
"Of or pertaining to a journey or traveling."
"More or less extensive patches of subcutaneous extravasation of blood."
"A genus of motile bacteria characterized by short  slightly sinuous filaments and an undulatory motion; also an individual of this genus."
"One deputed or authorized to perform the functions of another; a substitute in office; a deputy."
"A defect; a fault; an error; a blemish; an imperfection; as  the vices of a political constitution; the vices of a horse."
"A smith who works at the vice instead of at the anvil."
"The governor of a country or province who rules in the name of the sovereign with regal authority  as the king's substitute; as the viceroy of India."
"The place or places adjoining or near; neighborhood; vicinity; as  a jury must be of the vicinage."
"Characterized by vice or defects; defective; faulty; imperfect."
"A living being sacrificed to some deity  or in the performance of a religious rite; a creature immolated or made an offering of."
"The winner in a contest; one who gets the better of another in any struggle; esp.  one who defeats an enemy in battle; a vanquisher; a conqueror; -- often followed by art rarely by of."
"The defeat of an enemy in battle  or of an antagonist in any contest; a gaining of the superiority in any struggle or competition; conquest; triumph; -- the opposite of defeat."
"Food; -- now used chiefly in the plural. See Victuals."

"A South American mammal (Auchenia vicunna) native of the elevated plains of the Andes  allied to the llama but smaller. It has a thick coat of very fine reddish brown wool and long pendent white hair on the breast and belly. It is hunted for its wool and flesh."
"One of a class of temporal officers who originally represented the bishops  but later erected their offices into fiefs and became feudal nobles."
"imperative sing. of L. videre  to see; -- used to direct attention to something; as vide supra see above."
"A dry white wine  of a tart flavor produced in Teneriffe; -- called also Teneriffe."
"The state of widows or of widowhood; also  widows collectively."
"Of or pertaining to the state of a widow; widowed."
"To stake a sum upon a hand of cards  as in the old game of gleek. See Revie."
"An old stringed instrument played upon with a wheel; a hurdy-gurdy."
"The act of seeing or beholding; sight; look; survey; examination by the eye; inspection."
"Having peculiar views; fanciful; visionary; unpractical; as  a viewy person."
"In the Orkney and Shetland Islands  beef and mutton hung and dried but not salted."
"Abstinence from sleep  whether at a time when sleep is customary or not; the act of keeping awake or the state of being awake or the state of being awake; sleeplessness; wakefulness; watch."
"Of or pertaining to the vicu/a; characterizing the vicu/a; -- said of the wool of that animal  used in felting hats and for other purposes."
"Active strength or force of body or mind; capacity for exertion  physically intellectually or morally; force; energy."
"One belonging to the pirate crews from among the Northmen  who plundered the coasts of Europe in the eighth ninth and tenth centuries."
"One of the chief administrative divisions or provinces of the Ottoman Empire; -- formerly called eyalet."
"To make vile; to debase; to degrade; to disgrace."
"A small collection of houses; a village."
"A country seat; a country or suburban residence of some pretensions to elegance."
"A small assemblage of houses in the country  less than a town or city."
"One who holds lands by a base  or servile tenure or in villenage; a feudal tenant of the lowest class a bondman or servant."
"Abounding in  or covered with fine hairs or a woolly substance; shaggy with soft hairs; nappy."
"One of the minute papillary processes on certain vascular membranes; a villosity; as  villi cover the lining of the small intestines of many animals and serve to increase the absorbing surface."
"A long  slender flexible shoot or branch."
"Of or pertaining to twigs; consisting of twigs; producing twigs."
"The waste liquor remaining in the process of making beet sugar  -- used in the manufacture of potassium carbonate."
"Any woody climbing plant which bears grapes."
"Of or pertaining to vines; containing vines."
"Having leaves like those of the vine; ornamented with vine leaves."
"A sour liquid used as a condiment  or as a preservative and obtained by the spontaneous (acetous) fermentation or by the artificial oxidation of wine cider beer or the like."
"Of or pertaining to wine; as  vinic alcohol."
"Of or pertaining to wine; having the qualities of wine; as  a vinous taste."
"The produce of the vine for one season  in grapes or in wine; as the vintage is abundant; the vintage of 1840."
"One who deals in wine; a wine seller  or wine merchant."
"Of or pertaining to vines; producing  or abounding in vines."
"The hypothetical radical C2H3  regarded as the characteristic residue of ethylene and that related series of unsaturated hydrocarbons with which the allyl compounds are homologous."
"A stringed musical instrument formerly in use  of the same form as the violin but larger and having six strings to be struck with a bow and the neck furnished with frets for stopping the strings."
"A genus of polypetalous herbaceous plants  including all kinds of violets."
"To treat in a violent manner; to abuse."

"Moving or acting with physical strength; urged or impelled with force; excited by strong feeling or passion; forcible; vehement; impetuous; fierce; furious; severe; as  a violent blow; the violent attack of a disease."

"Any plant or flower of the genus Viola  of many species. The violets are generally low herbaceous plants and the flowers of many of the species are blue while others are white or yellow or of several colors as the pansy (Viola tricolor)."
"A small instrument with four strings  played with a bow; a fiddle."
"A pale yellow amorphous substance of alkaloidal nature and emetic properties  said to have been extracted from the root and foliage of the violet (Viola)."
"The largest instrument of the bass-viol kind  having strings tuned an octave below those of the violoncello; the contrabasso; -- called also double bass."
"Any one of numerous species of Old World venomous makes belonging to Vipera  Clotho Daboia and other genera of the family Viperidae."
"A woman of extraordinary stature  strength and courage; a woman who has the robust body and masculine mind of a man; a female warrior."
"An arrow  having a rotary motion formerly used with the crossbow. Cf. Vireton."
"An ancient French song  or short poem wholly in two rhymes and composed in short lines with a refrain."

"Any one of numerous species of American singing birds belonging to Vireo and allied genera of the family Vireonidae. In many of the species the back is greenish  or olive-colored. Called also greenlet."
"An arrow or bolt for a crossbow having feathers or brass placed at an angle with the shaft to make it spin in flying."
"Having the form of a straight rod; wand-shaped; straight and slender."
"A woman who has had no carnal knowledge of man; a maid."
"A sign of the zodiac which the sun enters about the 21st of August  marked thus [/] in almanacs."
"A certain function relating to a system of forces and their points of application  -- first used by Clausius in the investigation of problems in molecular physics."

"Having the nature  properties or qualities of an adult man; characteristic of developed manhood; hence masterful; forceful; specifically capable of begetting; -- opposed to womanly feminine and puerile; as virile age virile power virile organs."
"A ring surrounding a bugle or hunting horn."
"Furnished with a virole or viroles; -- said of a horn or a bugle when the rings are of different tincture from the rest of the horn."
"A love of the fine arts; a taste for curiosities."
"Having the power of acting or of invisible efficacy without the agency of the material or sensible part; potential; energizing."
"Manly strength or courage; bravery; daring; spirit; valor."
"Contagious or poisonous matter  as of specific ulcers the bite of snakes etc.; -- applied to organic poisons."
"The face  countenance or look of a person or an animal; -- chiefly applied to the human face."
"Sticking or adhering  and having a ropy or glutinous consistency; viscous; glutinous; sticky; tenacious; clammy; as turpentine tar gums etc. are more or less viscid."
"A clear  viscous tasteless substance extracted from the mucilaginous sap of the mistletoe (Viscum album) holly etc. and constituting an essential ingredient of birdlime."
"Adhesive or sticky  and having a ropy or glutinous consistency; viscid; glutinous; clammy; tenacious; as a viscous juice."
"A genus of parasitic shrubs  including the mistletoe of Europe."
"One of the organs  as the brain heart or stomach in the great cavities of the body of an animal; -- especially used in the plural and applied to the organs contained in the abdomen."
"An instrument consisting of two jaws  closing by a screw lever cam or the like for holding work as in filing."
"A divinity of the modern Hindu trimurti  or trinity. He is regarded as the preserver while Brahma is the creator and Siva the destroyer of the creation."
"Perceivable by the eye; capable of being seen; perceptible; in view; as  a visible star; the least spot is visible on white paper."
"The act of seeing external objects; actual sight."
"To go or come to see  as for the purpose of friendship business curiosity etc.; to attend; to call upon; as the physician visits his patient."
"A light cape or short cloak of silk or lace worn by women in summer."
"One who visits; one who comes or goes to see another  as in civility or friendship."
"Of or pertaining to the sight; visual."
"A part of a helmet  arranged so as to lift or open and so show the face. The openings for seeing and breathing are generally in it."
"A view; especially  a view through or between intervening objects as trees; a view or prospect through an avenue or the like; hence the trees or other objects that form the avenue."
"Of or pertaining to sight; used in sight; serving as the instrument of seeing; as  the visual nerve."
"Belonging or relating to life  either animal or vegetable; as vital energies; vital functions; vital actions."
"Organs that are necessary for life; more especially  the heart lungs and brain."

"To make vicious  faulty or imperfect; to render defective; to injure the substance or qualities of; to impair; to contaminate; to spoil; as exaggeration vitiates a style of writing; sewer gas vitiates the air."
"A genus of plants including all true grapevines."
"Having the nature and qualities of glass; glasslike; -- distinguished from ceramic."
"To convert into  or cause to resemble glass or a glassy substance by heat and fusion."
"A genus of terrestrial gastropods  having transparent very thin and delicate shells -- whence the name."
"A sulphate of any one of certain metals  as copper iron zinc cobalt. So called on account of the glassy appearance or luster."
"A kind of glass which is very hard and difficult to fuse  used as an insulator in electrical lamps and other apparatus."
"One of the oil tubes in the fruit of umbelliferous plants."
"Brisk; vivacious; with spirit; -- a direction to perform a passage in a brisk and lively manner."
"Long live  that is success to; as vive le roi long live the king; vive la bagatelle success to trifles or sport."
"Manner of supporting or continuing life or vegetation."
"A genus of carnivores which comprises the civets."
"A disease of brute animals  especially of horses seated in the glands under the ear where a tumor is formed which sometimes ends in suppuration."
"True to the life; exhibiting the appearance of life or freshness; animated; spirited; bright; strong; intense; as  vivid colors."
"To endue with life; to make to be living; to quicken; to animate."
"A councilor of state; a high executive officer in Turkey and other Oriental countries."
"A common gray European moth (Halia vauaria) having a V-shaped spot of dark brown on each of the fore wings."
"A word; a term; a name; specifically  a word considered as composed of certain sounds or letters without regard to its meaning."
"Of or pertaining to the voice or speech; having voice; endowed with utterance; full of voice  or voices."
"Of or pertaining to vowel sounds; consisting of the vowel sounds."
"In a vocal manner; with voice; orally; with audible sound."
"A short or weak utterance; a faint or feeble sound  as that heard on separating the lips in pronouncing p or b."
"An inlet  bay or creek; -- so called in the Orkney and Shetland Islands."
"The way or fashion of people at any particular time; temporary mode  custom or practice; popular reception for the time; -- used now generally in the phrase in vogue."

"Sound uttered by the mouth  especially that uttered by human beings in speech or song; sound thus uttered considered as possessing some special quality or character; as the human voice; a pleasant voice; a low voice."
"Containing nothing; empty; vacant; not occupied; not filled."
"One who  or that which voids /mpties vacates or annuls."
"A flying fish of California (Exoc/tus Californicus): -- called also volator."
"Passing through the air upon wings  or as if upon wings; flying; hence passing from place to place; current."
"A cumbrous two-wheeled pleasure carriage used in Cuba."
"Literally  world's speech; the name of an artificial language invented by Johan Martin Schleyer of Constance Switzerland about 1879."
"Of or pertaining to the palm of the hand or the sole of the foot."
"A mountain or hill  usually more or less conical in form from which lava cinders steam sulphur gases and the like are ejected; -- often popularly called a burning mountain."
"A deal at cards that draws all the tricks."
"The common sort of people; the crowd; the mob."
"A flight of missiles  as arrows bullets or the like; the simultaneous discharge of a number of small arms."
"To baptize; -- used in contempt by the Reformers."
"A circular tread; a gait by which a horse going sideways round a center makes two concentric tracks."

"A turning; a time; -- chiefly used in phrases signifying that the part is to be repeated one  two or more times; as una volta once. Seconda volta second time points to certain modifications in the close of a repeated strain."
"Electric potential or potential difference  expressed in volts."

"Of or pertaining to Alessandro Volta  who first devised apparatus for developing electric currents by chemical action and established this branch of electric science; discovered by Volta; as voltaic electricity."
"Turn  that is turn over the leaf."
"Easily rolling or turning; easily set in motion; apt to roll; rotating; as  voluble particles of matter."
"A roll; a scroll; a written document rolled up for keeping or for use  after the manner of the ancients."
"Having the form of a volume  or roil; as volumed mist."
"Any one of numerous species of large  handsome marine gastropods belonging to Voluta and allied genera."

"A spiral scroll which forms the chief feature of the Ionic capital  and which on a much smaller scale is a feature in the Corinthian and Composite capitals. See Illust. of Capital also Helix and Stale."
"A saclike envelope of certain fungi  which bursts open as the plant develops."

"A genus of minute  pale-green globular organisms about one fiftieth of an inch in diameter found rolling through water the motion being produced by minute colorless cilia. It has been considered as belonging to the flagellate Infusoria but is now referred to the vegetable kingdom and each globule is considered a colony of many individuals. The commonest species is Volvox globator often called globe animalcule."
"A bone  or one of a pair of bones beneath the ethmoid region of the skull forming a part a part of the partition between the nostrils in man and other mammals."
"To eject the contents of the stomach by the mouth; to puke; to spew."
"The yellow fever in its worst form  when it is usually attended with black vomit. See Black vomit."

"A mass of fluid  especially of a liquid having a whirling or circular motion tending to form a cavity or vacuum in the center of the circle and to draw in towards the center bodies subject to its action; the form assumed by a fluid in such motion; a whirlpool; an eddy."
"Consecrated by a vow or promise; consequent on a vow; devoted; promised."
"An ardent wish or desire; a vow; a prayer."
"One who votes; one who has a legal right to vote  or give his suffrage; an elector; a suffragist; as an independent voter."
"Given by vow  or in fulfillment of a vow; consecrated by a vow; devoted; as votive offerings; a votive tablet."
"The person who is vouched  or called into court to support or make good his warranty of title in the process of common recovery."
"One who vouches  or gives witness or full attestation to anything."

"A solemn promise made to God  or to some deity; an act by which one consecrates or devotes himself absolutely or conditionally wholly or in part for a longer or shorter time to some act service or condition; a devotion of one's possessions; as a baptismal vow; a vow of poverty."

"A vocal  or sometimes a whispered sound modified by resonance in the oral passage the peculiar resonance in each case giving to each several vowel its distinctive character or quality as a sound of speech; -- distinguished from a consonant in that the latter whether made with or without vocality derives its character in every case from some kind of obstructive action by the mouth organs. Also a letter or character which represents such a sound. See Guide to Pronunciation // 5 146-149."

"Formerly  a passage either by sea or land; a journey in general; but not chiefly limited to a passing by sea or water from one place port or country to another; especially a passing or journey by water to a distant place or country."
"One who voyages; one who sails or passes by sea or water."
"A cavity in a lode; -- called also vogle."
"The god of fire  who presided over the working of metals; -- answering to the Greek Hephaestus."
"Of or pertaining to the mass  or multitude of people; common; general; ordinary; public; hence in general use; vernacular."
"An ancient Latin version of the Scripture  and the only version which the Roman Church admits to be authentic; -- so called from its common use in the Latin Church."
"A genus of Carnivora including the foxes."
"Pertaining to  derived from or designating an acid obtained from a lichen (Cetraria vulpina) as a yellow or red crystalline substance which on decomposition yields pulvinic acid."
"Of or pertaining to the fox; resembling the fox; foxy; cunning; crafty; artful."
"The brush turkey (Talegallus Lathami) of Australia. See Brush turkey."
"Any one of numerous species of rapacious birds belonging to Vultur  Cathartes Catharista and various other genera of the family Vulturidae."
"The external parts of the female genital organs; sometimes  the opening between the projecting parts of the external organs."
"A kind of clamp with gimlet points for holding a barrel head while the staves are being closed around it."
"The burning bush; -- said to be called after a quack medicine made from it."

"To move staggeringly or unsteadily from one side to the other; to vacillate; to move the manner of a rotating disk when the axis of rotation is inclined to that of the disk; -- said of a turning or whirling body; as  a top wabbles; a buzz saw wabbles."
"A soft  earthy dark-colored rock or clay derived from the alteration of basalt."
"An earthy oxide of manganese  or mixture of different oxides and water with some oxide of iron and often silica alumina lime or baryta; black ocher. There are several varieties."

"To walk with short steps  swaying the body from one side to the other like a duck or very fat person; to move clumsily and totteringly along; to toddle; to stumble; as a child waddles when he begins to walk; a goose waddles."
"A coarse  hairy woolen cloth formerly used for garments by the poor and for various other purposes."
"A ravine through which a brook flows; the channel of a water course  which is dry except in the rainy season."
"A thin cake made of flour and other ingredients."
"A dealer in the cakes called wafers; a confectioner."
"A thin cake baked and then rolled; a wafer."
"To give notice to by waving something; to wave the hand to; to beckon."
"Conveyance on a buoyant medium  as air or water."
"The act of waving; a wavelike motion; a waft."
"To move one way and the other with quick turns; to shake to and fro; to move vibratingly; to cause to vibrate  as a part of the body; as to wag the head."
"A small East Indian wild cat (Felis wagati)  regarded by some as a variety of the leopard cat."
"To pledge; to hazard on the event of a contest; to stake; to bet  to lay; to wager; as to wage a dollar."
"Something deposited  laid or hazarded on the event of a contest or an unsettled question; a bet; a stake; a pledge."
"One who wagers  or lays a bet."
"A compensation given to a hired person for services; price paid for labor; recompense; hire. See Wage  n. 2."
"The young of the great black-backed gull (Larus marinus)  formerly considered a distinct species."
"The manner or action of a wag; mischievous merriment; sportive trick or gayety; good-humored sarcasm; pleasantry; jocularity; as  the waggery of a schoolboy."
"Like a wag; mischievous in sport; roguish in merriment or good humor; frolicsome."
"To reel  sway or move from side to side; to move with a wagging motion; to waddle."
"A wheeled carriage; a vehicle on four wheels  and usually drawn by horses; especially one used for carrying freight or merchandise."
"One who conducts a wagon; one whose business it is to drive a wagon."
"Conveyance by means of a wagon or wagons."

"Any one of many species of Old World singing birds belonging to Motacilla and several allied genera of the family Motacillidae. They have the habit of constantly jerking their long tails up and down  whence the name."

"A follower of Abdel Wahab (b. 1691; d. 1787)  a reformer of Mohammedanism. His doctrines prevail particularly among the Bedouins and the sect though checked in its influence extends to most parts of Arabia and also into India."

"Goods found of which the owner is not known; originally  such goods as a pursued thief threw away to prevent being apprehended which belonged to the king unless the owner made pursuit of the felon took him and brought him to justice."
"A four-wheeled vehicle for the transportation of goods  produce etc.; a wagon."
"A finding of carriages  carts etc. for the transportation of goods produce etc."
"A piece of plank two yard/ long and a foot broad."
"That part of the human body which is immediately below the ribs or thorax; the small part of the body between the thorax and hips."
"A seaman  usually a green hand or a broken-down man stationed in the waist of a vessel of war."
"To watch; to observe; to take notice."
"One who  or that which waits; an attendant; a servant in attendance esp. at table."
"The act of waiving  or not insisting on some right claim or privilege."
"The track left by a vessel in the water; by extension  any track; as the wake of an army."
"Not sleeping; indisposed to sleep; watchful; vigilant."
"To wake; to cease to sleep; to be awakened."
"A forest; -- used as a termination of names. See Weald."
"A streak or mark made on the skin by a rod or whip; a stripe; a wheal. See Wheal."

"To move along on foot; to advance by steps; to go on at a moderate pace; specifically  of two-legged creatures to proceed at a slower or faster rate but without running or lifting one foot entirely before the other touches the ground."
"A kind of knot often used at the end of a rope; a wall knot; a wale."
"A leguminous tree (Eperua falcata) of Demerara  with pinnate leaves and clusters of red flowers. The reddish brown wood is used for palings and shingles."

"Any one of numerous species of kangaroos belonging to the genus Halmaturus  native of Australia and Tasmania especially the smaller species as the brush kangaroo (H. Bennettii) and the pademelon (H. thetidis). The wallabies chiefly inhabit the wooded district and bushy plains."
"A black variety of the jaguar; -- called also tapir tiger."
"A bag or sack for carrying about the person  as a bag for carrying the necessaries for a journey; a knapsack; a beggar's receptacle for charity; a peddler's pack."
"To move quickly  but with great effort; to gallop."
"To roll one's self about  as in mire; to tumble and roll about; to move lazily or heavily in any medium; to flounder; as swine wallow in the mire."
"To roll; to spout; to boil up."
"The fruit or nut of any tree of the genus Juglans; also  the tree and its timber. The seven or eight known species are all natives of the north temperate zone."

"A very large marine mammal (Trichecus rosmarus) of the Seal family  native of the Arctic Ocean. The male has long and powerful tusks descending from the upper jaw. It uses these in procuring food and in fighting. It is hunted for its oil ivory and skin. It feeds largely on mollusks. Called also morse."
"Liable to roll over; crank; as  a walty ship."
"A dance performed by two persons in circular figures with a whirling motion; also  a piece of music composed in triple measure for this kind of dance."
"To heave; to be disturbed by nausea; -- said of the stomach."
"To move irregularly or awkwardly; to wamble  or wabble."
"A tree (Cookia punctata) of the Orange family  growing in China and the East Indies; also its fruit which is about the size of a large grape and has a hard rind and a peculiar flavor."
"Beads made of shells  used by the North American Indians as money and also wrought into belts etc. as an ornament."
"A small stick; a rod; a verge."
"To ramble here and there without any certain course or with no definite object in view; to range about; to stroll; to rove; as  to wander over the fields."
"To be diminished; to decrease; -- contrasted with wax  and especially applied to the illuminated part of the moon."
"A sharp or uneven edge on a board that is cut from a log not perfectly squared  or that is made in the process of squaring. See Wany a."
"A boat for conveying provisions  tools etc.; -- so called by Maine lumbermen."
"A pillow for the cheek; a pillow."
"The Chinese name of one or two species of bamboo  or jointed cane of the genus Phyllostachys. The slender stems are much used for walking sticks."
"Want of hope; despair; also  faint or delusive hope; delusion. [Obs.] Piers Plowman."
"An East Indian plant (Kaempferia Galanga) of the Ginger family. See Galanga."
"A word of uncertain signification  used only in the phrase with a wanion apparently equivalent to with a vengeance with a plague or with misfortune."
"Not to be depended on; weak; unstable."
"The quality or state of being wan; a sallow  dead pale color; paleness; pallor; as the wanness of the cheeks after a fever."

"The state of not having; the condition of being without anything; absence or scarcity of what is needed or desired; deficiency; lack; as  a want of power or knowledge for any purpose; want of food and clothing."
"Untrained; undisciplined; unrestrained; hence  loose; free; luxuriant; roving; sportive."
"One destitute of wit or sense; a blockhead; a fool."
"A surcingle  or strap of leather used for binding a load upon the back of a beast; also a leather tie; a short wagon rope."
"The American hawk owl. See under Hawk."
"The edible tuber of a species of arrowhead (Sagittaria variabilis); -- so called by the Indians of Oregon."
"The American elk (Cervus Canadensis). It is closely related to the European red deer  which it somewhat exceeds in size."
"To cause to shake; to tremble; to move tremulously  as from weakness; to totter."
"A small  hard tumor which is produced on the back of a horse by the heat or pressure of the saddle in traveling."
"One who  or that which warbles; a singer; a songster; -- applied chiefly to birds."
"The act of guarding; watch; guard; guardianship; specifically  a guarding during the day. See the Note under Watch n. 1."
"One who wards or keeps; a keeper; a guard."

"Designating  or pertaining to a kind of glass inclosure for keeping ferns mosses etc. or for transporting growing plants from a distance; as a Wardian case of plants; -- so named from the inventor Nathaniel B. Ward an Englishman."
"Military service; military life; contest carried on by enemies; hostilities; war."
"A South American monkey  one of the sapajous."
"To protect from the effects of; hence  to cure; to heal."
"Fit for war; disposed for war; as  a warlike state; a warlike disposition."
"One often quarreled with; -- / word coined  perhaps to rhyme with darling."
"A male witch; a wizard; a sprite; an imp."
"Having heat in a moderate degree; not cold as  warm milk."
"Abounding in capacity to warm; giving warmth; as  a warmful garment."
"The quality or state of being warm; gentle heat; as  the warmth of the sun; the warmth of the blood; vital warmth."
"To throw; hence  to send forth or throw out as words; to utter."
"The act of warping; also  a charge per ton made on shipping in some harbors."
"The route taken by a party of Indians going on a warlike expedition."
"One who  or that which warps or twists out of shape."

"That which warrants or authorizes; a commission giving authority  or justifying the doing of anything; an act instrument or obligation by which one person authorizes another to do something which he has not otherwise a right to do; an act or instrument investing one with a right or authority and thus securing him from loss or damage; commission; authority."
"A place privileged  by prescription or grant the king for keeping certain animals (as hares conies partridges pheasants etc.) called beasts and fowls of warren."
"An Australian lorikeet (Trichoglossus multicolor) remarkable for the variety and brilliancy of its colors; -- called also blue-bellied lorikeet  and blue-bellied parrot."
"A man engaged or experienced in war  or in the military life; a soldier; a champion."
"The black grouper (Epinephelus nigritus) of the southern coasts of the United States."
"A small  usually hard tumor on the skin formed by enlargement of its vascular papillae and thickening of the epidermis which covers them."
"Having little knobs on the surface; verrucose; as  a warted capsule."
"Having warts; full of warts; overgrow with warts; as  a warty leaf."
"Worn with military service; as  a warworn soldier; a warworn coat."
"Cautious of danger; carefully watching and guarding against deception  artifices and dangers; timorously or suspiciously prudent; circumspect; scrupulous; careful."
"To curse; to curse; to execrate; to condemn; also  to vex."
"A bundle of straw  or other material to relieve the pressure of burdens carried upon the head."

"To cleanse by ablution  or dipping or rubbing in water; to apply water or other liquid to for the purpose of cleansing; to scrub with water etc. or as with water; as to wash the hands or body; to wash garments; to wash sheep or wool; to wash the pavement or floor; to wash the bark of trees."

"The washing out or away of earth  etc. especially of a portion of the bed of a road or railroad by a fall of rain or a freshet; also a place especially in the bed of a road or railroad where the earth has been washed away."
"A pot or vessel in which anything is washed."
"A tub in which clothes are washed."
"A variety of allanite from Sweden supposed to contain wasium."
"A rare element supposed by Bahr to have been extracted from wasite  but now identified with thorium."
"Any one of numerous species of stinging hymenopterous insects  esp. any of the numerous species of the genus Vespa which includes the true or social wasps some of which are called yellow jackets."
"Resembling a wasp in form; having a slender waist  like a wasp."
"An ancient expression of good wishes on a festive occasion  especially in drinking to some one."
"The second person singular of the verb be  in the indicative mood imperfect tense; -- now used only in solemn or poetical style. See Was."
"Loss by use  decay evaporation leakage or the like; waste."
"Desolate; devastated; stripped; bare; hence  dreary; dismal; gloomy; cheerless."
"A kind of white and fine bread or cake; -- called also wastel bread  and wastel cake."
"One who  or that which wastes; one who squanders; one who consumes or expends extravagantly; a spendthrift; a prodigal."

"The act of watching; forbearance of sleep; vigil; wakeful  vigilant or constantly observant attention; close observation; guard; preservative or preventive vigilance; formerly a watching or guarding by night."
"One who watches; one who sits up or continues; a diligent observer; specifically  one who attends upon the sick during the night."
"The leaves of Saracenia flava. See Trumpets."
"The fluid which descends from the clouds in rain  and which forms rivers lakes seas etc."
"The pied wagtail; -- so called because it frequents ponds."
"Of or pertaining to water; consisting of water."
"A unit of power or activity equal to 107 C.G.S. units of power  or to work done at the rate of one joule a second. An English horse power is approximately equal to 746 watts."
"A twig or flexible rod; hence  a hurdle made of such rods."
"To cry as a cat; to squall; to wail."
"To play or move to and fro; to move one way and the other; hence  to totter; to reel; to swing; to flutter."
"One who wavers; one who is unsettled in doctrine  faith opinion or the like."
"Goods which  after shipwreck appear floating on the waves or sea."
"Rising or swelling in waves; full of waves."
"To increase in size; to grow bigger; to become larger or fuller; -- opposed to wane."

"Any one of numerous species of finchlike birds belonging to Estrelda and allied genera  native of Asia Africa and Australia. The bill is large conical and usually red in color resembling sealing wax. Several of the species are often kept as cage birds."

"Any one of several species of small birds of the genus Ampelis  in which some of the secondary quills are usually tipped with small horny ornaments resembling red sealing wax. The Bohemian waxwing (see under Bohemian) and the cedar bird are examples. Called also waxbird."
"Work made of wax; especially  a figure or figures formed or partly of wax in imitation of real beings."
"Resembling wax in appearance or consistency; viscid; adhesive; soft; hence  yielding; pliable; impressible."
"A list of passengers in a public vehicle  or of the baggage or gods transported by a common carrier on a land route. When the goods are transported by water the list is called a bill of lading."
"An Australian insessorial bird (Corcorax melanorhamphus) noted for the curious actions of the male during the breeding season. It is black with a white patch on each wing."
"To journey; to travel; to go to and fro."
"To lie in wait for; to meet or encounter in the way; especially  to watch for the passing of with a view to seize rob or slay; to beset in ambush."
"The side of the way; the edge or border of a road or path."
"Taking one's own way; disobedient; froward; perverse; willful."

"Originally  the title of a military commander in various Slavonic countries; afterwards applied to governors of towns or provinces. It was assumed for a time by the rulers of Moldavia and Wallachia who were afterwards called hospodars and has also been given to some inferior Turkish officers."

"To make weak; to lessen the strength of; to deprive of strength; to debilitate; to enfeeble; to enervate; as  to weaken the body or the mind; to weaken the hands of a magistrate; to weaken the force of an objection or an argument."
"In a weak manner; with little strength or vigor; feebly."
"The mark of a stripe. See Wale."
"A wood or forest; a wooded land or region; also  an open country; -- often used in place names."
"Of or pertaining to the lowest division of the Cretaceous formation in England and on the Continent  which overlies the Oolitic series."
"Having wealth; having large possessions  or larger than most men as lands goods money or securities; opulent; affluent; rich."
"To accustom and reconcile  as a child or other young animal to a want or deprivation of mother's milk; to take from the breast or udder; to cause to cease to depend on the mother nourishment."
"An instrument of offensive of defensive combat; something to fight with; anything used  or designed to be used in destroying defeating or injuring an enemy as a gun a sword etc."
"One who wears or carries as appendant to the body; as  the wearer of a cloak a sword a crown a shackle etc."
"Having the strength exhausted by toil or exertion; worn out in respect to strength  endurance etc.; tired; fatigued."

"Any one of various species of small carnivores belonging to the genus Putorius  as the ermine and ferret. They have a slender elongated body and are noted for the quickness of their movements and for their bloodthirsty habit in destroying poultry rats etc. The ermine and some other species are brown in summer and turn white in winter; others are brown at all seasons."
"The American merganser; -- called also weaser sheldrake."

"The state of the air or atmosphere with respect to heat or cold  wetness or dryness calm or storm clearness or cloudiness or any other meteorological phenomena; meteorological condition of the atmosphere; as warm weather; cold weather; wet weather; dry weather etc."

"To unite  as threads of any kind in such a manner as to form a texture; to entwine or interlace into a fabric; as to weave wool silk etc.; hence to unite by close connection or intermixture; to unite intimately."
"One who weaves  or whose occupation is to weave."
"Thin; sharp; withered; wizened; as  a weazen face."
"One who forms webs; a weaver; a webster."
"Of or pertaining to a web or webs; like a web; filled or covered with webs."
"The standard unit of electrical quantity  and also of current. See Coulomb and Amp/re."
"A foot the toes of which are connected by a membrane."
"Any one of various species of moths whose gregarious larvae eat the leaves of trees  and construct a large web to which they retreat when not feeding."

"A piece of metal  or other hard material thick at one end and tapering to a thin edge at the other used in splitting wood rocks etc. in raising heavy bodies and the like. It is one of the six elementary machines called the mechanical powers. See Illust. of Mechanical powers under Mechanical."
"The ceremony  or the state of marriage; matrimony."
"A little; a bit  as of space time or distance."
"A garment; clothing; especially  an upper or outer garment."
"One who  or that which weeds or frees from anything noxious."
"Weeds  collectively; also a place full of weeds or for growing weeds."
"Of or pertaining to weeds; consisting of weeds."
"A period of seven days  usually that reckoned from one Sabbath or Sunday to the next."
"Of or pertaining to a week  or week days; as weekly labor."
"A kind of trap or snare for fish  made of twigs."
"The lapwing; the wipe; -- so called from its cry."
"One who weeps; esp.  one who sheds tears."

"Any one of several species of edible marine fishes belonging to the genus Trachinus  of the family Trachinidae. They have a broad spinose head with the eyes looking upward. The long dorsal fin is supported by numerous strong sharp spines which cause painful wounds."

"Any one of numerous species of snout beetles  or Rhynchophora in which the head is elongated and usually curved downward. Many of the species are very injurious to cultivated plants. The larvae of some of the species live in nuts fruit and grain by eating out the interior as the plum weevil or curculio the nut weevils and the grain weevil (see under Plum Nut and Grain). The larvae of other species bore under the bark and into the pith of trees and various other plants as the pine weevils (see under Pine). See also Pea weevil
"A corruption of Way  used only in the phrase under weigh."
"One who weighs; specifically  an officer whose duty it is to weigh commodities."

"The quality of being heavy; that property of bodies by which they tend toward the center of the earth; the effect of gravitative force  especially when expressed in certain units or standards as pounds grams etc."
"Having weight; heavy; ponderous; as  a weighty body."
"Fate; destiny; one of the Fates  or Norns; also a prediction."
"A New Zealand rail (Ocydromus australis) which has wings so short as to be incapable of flight."
"A small New Zealand owl (Sceloglaux albifacies). It has short wings and long legs  and lives chiefly on the ground."
"Received with gladness; admitted willingly to the house  entertainment or company; as a welcome visitor."
"One who welds  or unites pieces of iron etc. by welding."
"Well-doing or well-being in any respect; the enjoyment of health and the common blessings of life; exemption from any evil or calamity; prosperity; happiness."
"To wither; to fade; also  to decay; to decline; to wane."
"The visible regions of the air; the vault of heaven; the sky."
"An issue of water from the earth; a spring; a fountain."
"Contraction for we will or we shall."
"Of or pertaining to Wales  or its inhabitants."
"One who cheats at a horse race; one who bets  without a chance of being able to pay; one who receives money to back certain horses and absconds with it."
"That which  being sewed or otherwise fastened to an edge or border serves to guard strengthen or adorn it"
"To roll  as the body of an animal; to tumble about especially in anything foul or defiling; to wallow."
"A young woman; a girl; a maiden."
"Of or pertaining the Wends  or their language."
"A Slavic tribe which once occupied the northern and eastern parts of Germany  of which a small remnant exists."
"Having the nature of a wen; resembling a wen; as  a wennish excrescence."
"A sand snake (Charina plumbea) of Western North America  of the family Erycidae."
"An Australian lorikeet (Ptilosclera versicolor) noted for the variety of its colors; -- called also varied lorikeet."

"The second person singular  indicative and subjunctive moods imperfect tense of the verb be. It is formed from were with the ending -t after the analogy of wast. Now used only in solemn or poetic style."

"The point in the heavens where the sun is seen to set at the equinox; or  the corresponding point on the earth; that one of the four cardinal points of the compass which is in a direction at right angles to that of north and south and on the left hand of a person facing north; the point directly opposite to east."
"Of or pertaining to the west; situated in the west  or in the region nearly in the direction of west; being in that quarter where the sun sets; as the western shore of France; the western ocean."
"The distance  reckoned toward the west between the two meridians passing through the extremities of a course or portion of a ship's path; the departure of a course which lies to the west of north."
"Containing  or consisting of water or other liquid; moist; soaked with a liquid; having water or other liquid upon the surface; as wet land; a wet cloth; a wet table."
"The chaffinch  whose cry is thought to foretell rain."
"The European curlew; -- called also awp  whaup great whaup and stock whaup."
"To strike; to beat; to give a heavy or resounding blow to; to thrash; to make with whacks."
"An American tree  the winged elm. (Ulmus alata)."
"To lash with stripes; to wale; to thrash; to drub."
"Any aquatic mammal of the order Cetacea  especially any one of the large species some of which become nearly one hundred feet long. Whales are hunted chiefly for their oil and baleen or whalebone."
"A vessel or person employed in the whale fishery."
"A light color of the iris in horses; wall-eye."
"Having the iris of light color; -- said of horses."
"To throw one's self quickly  or by an abrupt motion; to turn suddenly; as she whapped down on the floor; the fish whapped over."
"Something uncommonly large of the kind; something astonishing; -- applied especially to a bold lie."

"A structure or platform of timber  masonry iron earth or other material built on the shore of a harbor river canal or the like and usually extending from the shore to deep water so that vessels may lie close alongside to receive and discharge cargo passengers
"A kind of fine sand from the banks of the Trent  used as a polishing powder."
a.  & adv." "As an interrogative pronoun used in asking questions regarding either persons or things; as what is this? what did you say? what poem is this? what child is lost?"
"A kind of stand  or piece of furniture having shelves for books ornaments etc.; an etagere."
"A cereal grass (Triticum vulgare) and its grain  which furnishes a white flour for bread and next to rice is the grain most largely used by the human race."
"To entice by soft words; to cajole; to flatter; to coax."

"A circular frame turning about an axis; a rotating disk  whether solid or a frame composed of an outer rim spokes or radii and a central hub or nave in which is inserted the axle -- used for supporting and conveying vehicles in machinery and for various purposes; as the wheel of a wagon of a locomotive of a mill
"To breathe hard  and with an audible piping or whistling sound as persons affected with asthma."
"Breathing with difficulty and with a wheeze; wheezing. Used also figuratively."

"Any one numerous species of large marine gastropods belonging to Buccinum and allied genera; especially  Buccinum undatum common on the coasts both of Europe and North America and much used as food in Europe."
"Having whelks  ridges or protuberances; hence streaked; striated."
"To cover with water or other fluid; to cover by immersion in something that envelops on all sides; to overwhelm; to ingulf."
"One of the young of a dog or a beast of prey; a puppy; a cub; as  a lion's whelps."
"From what place; hence  from what or which source origin antecedent premise or the like; how; -- used interrogatively."
"At which; upon which; whereupon; -- used relatively."
"In which; in which place  thing time respect or the like; -- used relatively."
"Of which; of whom; formerly  also with which; -- used relatively."
"On which; -- used relatively; as  the earth whereon we live."
"A passenger barge or lighter plying on rivers; also  a kind of light half-decked vessel used in fishing."
"To rub or on with some substance  as a piece of stone for the purpose of sharpening; to sharpen by attrition; as to whet a knife."
"Which (of two); which one (of two); -- used interrogatively and relatively."
"The green woodpecker  or yaffle. See Yaffle."
"One who  or that which whets sharpens or stimulates."
"A sound like a half-formed whistle  expressing astonishment scorn or dislike."
"The serum  or watery part of milk separated from the more thick or coagulable part esp. in the process of making cheese."
"Of the nature of  or containing whey; resembling whey; wheyish."
"Of what sort or kind; what; what a; who."
"A sudden expulsion of air from the mouth; a quick puff or slight gust  as of air or smoke."
"To waver  or shake as if moved by gusts of wind; to shift turn or veer about."
"Acidulated whey  sometimes mixed with buttermilk and sweet herbs used as a cooling beverage."
"Space of time  or continued duration esp. when short; a time; as one while we thought him innocent."
"A little while ago; recently; just now; erewhile."
"Formerly; once; of old; erewhile; at times."
"To cry with a low  whining broken voice; to whine; to complain; as a child whimpers."
"A whim; a freak; a capricious notion  a fanciful or odd conceit."

"To utter a plaintive cry  as some animals; to moan with a childish noise; to complain or to tell of sorrow distress or the like in a plaintive nasal tone; hence to complain or to beg in a mean unmanly way; to moan basely."
"A kind of hanger or sword used as a knife at meals and as a weapon."
"To utter the ordinary call or cry of a horse; to neigh."
"To strike with a lash  a cord a rod or anything slender and lithe; to lash; to beat; as to whip a horse or a carpet."
"One who whips; especially  an officer who inflicts the penalty of legal whipping."
"A saw for dividing timber lengthwise  usually set in a frame and worked by two persons; also a fret saw."
"To whirl round  or revolve with a whizzing noise; to fly or more quickly with a buzzing or whizzing sound; to whiz."
"To turn round rapidly; to cause to rotate with velocity; to make to revolve."
"A perforated steel die through which wires or tubes are drawn to form them."
"One who  or that which whisks or moves with a quick sweeping motion."
"A basket; esp.  a straw provender basket."
"A light carriage built for rapid motion; -- called also tim-whiskey."

"To speak softly  or under the breath so as to be heard only by one near at hand; to utter words without sonant breath; to talk without that vibration in the larynx which gives sonorous or vocal sound. See Whisper n."

"To make a kind of musical sound  or series of sounds by forcing the breath through a small orifice formed by contracting the lips; also to emit a similar sound or series of notes from the mouth or beak as birds."
"The smallest part or particle imaginable; a bit; a jot; an iota; -- generally used in an adverbial phrase in a negative sentence."

"Reflecting to the eye all the rays of the spectrum combined; not tinted with any of the proper colors or their mixtures; having the color of pure snow; snowy; -- the opposite of black or dark; as  white paper; a white skin."
"To grow white; to turn or become white or whiter; as  the hair whitens with age; the sea whitens with foam; the trees in spring whiten with blossoms."
"To what place; -- used interrogatively; as  whither goest thou?"
"Somewhat white; approaching white; white in a moderate degree."

"An inflammation of the fingers or toes  generally of the last phalanx terminating usually in suppuration. The inflammation may occupy any seat between the skin and the bone but is usually applied to a felon or inflammation of the periosteal structures of the bone."
"Of  pertaining to or observed at Whitsuntide; as Whitsun week; Whitsun Tuesday; Whitsun pastorals."
"A grayish  coarse double blanket worn by countrywomen in the west of England over the shoulders like a cloak or shawl."
"To make a humming or hissing sound  like an arrow or ball flying through the air; to fly or move swiftly with a sharp hissing or whistling sound."

"Originally  an interrogative pronoun later a relative pronoun also; -- used always substantively and either as singular or plural. See the Note under What pron. 1. As interrogative pronouns who and whom ask the question: What or which person or persons? Who and whom as relative pronouns (in the sense of that) are properly used of persons (corresponding to which as applied to things) but are sometimes
"Whatever person; any person who; be or she who; any one who; as  he shall be punished whoever he may be."
"Containing the total amount  number etc.; comprising all the parts; free from deficiency; all; total; entire; as the whole earth; the whole solar system; the whole army; the whole nation."
"In a whole or complete manner; entirely; completely; perfectly."
"The objective case of who. See Who."
"A woman who practices unlawful sexual commerce with men  especially one who prostitutes her body for hire; a prostitute; a harlot."
"Resembling a whore in character or conduct; addicted to unlawful pleasures; incontinent; lewd; unchaste."
"A circle of two or more leaves  flowers or other organs about the same part or joint of a stem."
"Furnished with whorls; arranged in the form of a whorl or whorls; verticillate; as  whorled leaves."
"The possessive case of who or which. See Who  and Which."
"To make a rough  humming sound like one who pronounces the letter r with too much force; to whir; to birr."
"For what cause  reason or purpose; on what account; wherefore; -- used interrogatively. See the Note under What pron. 1."
"Having a wick; -- used chiefly in composition; as  a two-wicked lamp."
"A small pliant twig or osier; a rod for making basketwork and the like; a withe."

"A small gate or door  especially one forming part of or placed near a larger door or gate; a narrow opening or entrance cut in or beside a door or gate or the door which is used to close such entrance or aperture. Piers Plowman."
"the material of which wicks are made; esp.  a loosely braided or twisted cord or tape of cotton."
"A rope or halter made of flexible twigs  or withes as of birch."

"Having considerable distance or extent between the sides; spacious across; much extended in a direction at right angles to that of length; not narrow; broad; as  wide cloth; a wide table; a wide highway; a wide bed; a wide hall or entry."
"The angler; -- called also widegab  and widegut."
"In a wide manner; to a wide degree or extent; far; extensively; as  the gospel was widely disseminated by the apostles."
"To make wide or wider; to extend in breadth; to increase the width of; as  to widen a field; to widen a breach; to widen a stocking."

"Any one of several species of fresh-water ducks  especially those belonging to the subgenus Mareca of the genus Anas. The common European widgeon (Anas penelope) and the American widgeon (A. Americana) are the most important species. The latter is called also baldhead baldpate baldface baldcrown smoking duck wheat duck and whitebelly."
"A woman who has lost her husband by death  and has not married again; one living bereaved of a husband."
"A man who has lost his wife by death  and has not married again."
"The quality of being wide; extent from side to side; breadth; wideness; as  the width of cloth; the width of a door."
"Of or pertaining to a widow; vidual."
"To govern; to rule; to keep  or have in charge; also to possess."
"One who wields or employs; a manager; a controller."
"Capable of being wielded; manageable; wieldable; -- opposed to unwieldy."
"A woman; an adult female; -- now used in literature only in certain compounds and phrases  as alewife fishwife goodwife and the like."
"Becoming or life; of or pertaining to a wife."

"A covering for the head  consisting of hair interwoven or united by a kind of network either in imitation of the natural growth or in abundant and flowing curls worn to supply a deficiency of natural hair or for ornament or according to traditional usage as a part of an official or professional dress the latter especially in England by judges and barristers."

"A kind of canvaslike cotton fabric  used to stiffen and protect the lower part of trousers and of the skirts of women's dresses etc.; -- so called from Wigan the name of a town in Lancashire England."

"To move to and fro with a quick  jerking motion; to bend rapidly or with a wavering motion from side to side; to wag; to squirm; to wriggle; as the dog wiggles his tail; the tadpole wiggles in the water."
"The young  either larva or pupa of the mosquito; -- called also wiggletail."
"To signal by means of a flag waved from side to side according to a code adopted for the purpose."
"An Indian cabin or hut  usually of a conical form and made of a framework of poles covered with hides bark or mats; -- called also tepee."
"A temporary mark or boundary  as a bough of a tree set up in marking out or dividing anything as tithes swaths to be mowed in common ground etc.; -- called also wicker."

"Living in a state of nature; inhabiting natural haunts  as the forest or open field; not familiar with or not easily approached by man; not tamed or domesticated; as a wild boar; a wild ox; a wild cat."
"A wild or uncultivated plant; especially  a wild apple tree or crab apple; also the fruit of such a plant."
"In a wild manner; without cultivation; with disorder; rudely; distractedly; extravagantly."
"A trick or stratagem practiced for insnaring or deception; a sly  insidious; artifice; a beguilement; an allurement."

"The power of choosing; the faculty or endowment of the soul by which it is capable of choosing; the faculty or power of the mind by which we decide to do or not to do; the power or faculty of preferring or selecting one of two or more objects."
"A large North American snipe (Symphemia semipalmata); -- called also pill-willet  will-willet semipalmated tattler or snipe duck snipe and stone curlew."
"Of set purpose; self-determined; voluntary; as  willful murder."
"One who works at a willying machine."

"Any tree or shrub of the genus Salix  including many species most of which are characterized often used as an emblem of sorrow desolation or desertion. """"A wreath of willow to show my forsaken plight."""" Sir W. Scott. Hence a lover forsaken by or having lost the person beloved is said to wear the willow."
"Full of wiles  tricks or stratagems; using craft or stratagem to accomplish a purpose; mischievously artful; subtle."
"An instrument for boring holes  turned by a handle."
"A covering of silk  linen or other material for the neck and chin formerly worn by women as an outdoor protection and still retained in the dress of nuns."
"To gain by superiority in competition or contest; to obtain by victory over competitors or rivals; as  to win the prize in a gate; to win money; to win a battle or to win a country."
"To shrink  as from a blow or from pain; to flinch; to start back."
"One who  or that which winces shrinks or kicks."
"To wince; to shrink; to kick with impatience or uneasiness."

"To turn completely  or with repeated turns; especially to turn about something fixed; to cause to form convolutions about anything; to coil; to twine; to twist; to wreathe; as to wind thread on a spool or into a ball."
"The difference between the diameter of the bore of a gun and that of the shot fired from it."
"One who  or that which winds; hence a creeping or winding plant."
"A spindle; a kind of reel; a winch."

"An opening in the wall of a building for the admission of light and air  usually closed by casements or sashes containing some transparent material as glass and capable of being opened and shut at pleasure."
"Having little crossings or openings like the sashes of a window."
"A row or line of hay raked together for the purpose of being rolled into cocks or heaps."
"Consisting of wind; accompanied or characterized by wind; exposed to wind."
