"The expressed juice of grapes  esp. when fermented; a beverage or liquor prepared from grapes by squeezing out their juice and (usually) allowing it to ferment."
"A place where grapes are converted into wine."

"One of the two anterior limbs of a bird  pterodactyl or bat. They correspond to the arms of man and are usually modified for flight but in the case of a few species of birds as the ostrich auk etc. the wings are used only as an assistance in running or swimming."
"One of the casks stowed in the wings of a vessel's hold  being smaller than such as are stowed more amidships."
"A little wing; a very small wing."
"One who wins  or gains by success in competition contest or gaming."
"To separate  and drive off the chaff from by means of wind; to fan; as to winnow grain."
"The season of the year in which the sun shines most obliquely upon any region; the coldest season of the year."
"Suitable to winter; resembling winter  or what belongs to winter; brumal; hyemal; cold; stormy; wintery."
"Having the taste or qualities of wine; vinous; as  grapes of a winy taste."
"A small shaft sunk from one level to another  as for the purpose of ventilation."
"A thread or slender rod of metal; a metallic substance formed to an even thread by being passed between grooved rollers  or drawn through holes in a plate of steel."
"Made of wire; like wire; drawn out like wire."
"The quality of being wise; knowledge  and the capacity to make due use of it; knowledge of the best ends and the best means; discernment and judgment; discretion; sagacity; skill; dexterity."
"Having knowledge; knowing; enlightened; of extensive information; erudite; learned."
"In a wise manner; prudently; judiciously; discreetly; with wisdom."
"To have a desire or yearning; to long; to hanker."
"One who wishes or desires; one who expresses a wish."
"A small bundle  as of straw or other like substance."
"Formed of a wisp  or of wisp; as a wispen broom."
"To show; to teach; to inform; to guide; to direct."
"A small South American monkey; a marmoset."
"A cone of paper which is placed in a vessel of lard or other fat  and used as a taper."
"A flexible  slender twig or branch used as a band; a willow or osier twig; a withy."
"To fade; to lose freshness; to become sapless; to become sapless; to dry or shrivel up."
"The ridge between the shoulder bones of a horse  at the base of the neck. See Illust. of Horse."
"In the inner or interior part of; inside of; not without; as  within doors."
"On or at the outside of; out of; not within; as  without doors."
"To contradict; to gainsay; to deny; to renounce."
"The osier willow (Salix viminalis). See Osier  n. (a)."
"Destitute of wit or understanding; wanting thought; hence  indiscreet; not under the guidance of judgment."
"A person who has little wit or understanding; a pretender to wit or smartness."
"Attestation of a fact or an event; testimony."
"Having (such) a wit or understanding; as  a quick-witted boy."
"In a witty manner; wisely; ingeniously; artfully; with it; with a delicate turn or phrase  or with an ingenious association of ideas."
"Tin ore freed from earthy matter by stamping."
"Possessed of wit; knowing; wise; skillful; judicious; clever; cunning."
"One who  or that which feeds on or destroys wit."
"To marry  as a man; to take a wife."
"A fabulous two-legged  winged creature like a cockatrice but having the head of a dragon and without spurs."
"Dried; shriveled; withered; shrunken; weazen; as  a wizened old man."
"An herbaceous cruciferous plant (Isatis tinctoria). It was formerly cultivated for the blue coloring matter derived from its leaves."
"A deity corresponding to Odin  the supreme deity of the Scandinavians. Wednesday is named for him. See Odin."
"Full of woe; sorrowful; distressed with grief or calamity; afflicted; wretched; unhappy; sad."
"In a woeful manner; sorrowfully; mournfully; miserably; dolefully."

"Any one of several species of wild and savage carnivores belonging to the genus Canis and closely allied to the common dog. The best-known and most destructive species are the European wolf (Canis lupus)  the American gray or timber wolf (C. occidentalis) and the prairie wolf or coyote. Wolves often hunt in packs and may thus attack large animals and even man."
"Like a wolf; having the qualities or form of a wolf; as  a wolfish visage; wolfish designs."
"An adult female person; a grown-up female person  as distinguished from a man or a child; sometimes any female person."
"Becoming a woman; feminine; as  womanly behavior."
"Any one of three species of Australian burrowing marsupials of the genus Phascolomys  especially the common species (P. ursinus). They are nocturnal in their habits and feed mostly on roots."

"That emotion which is excited by novelty  or the presentation to the sight or mind of something new unusual strange great extraordinary or not well understood; surprise; astonishment; admiration; amazement."
"A colloquial contraction of woll not. Will not. See Will."
"Using or doing customarily; accustomed; habituated; used."
"An engraving on wood; also  a print from it. Same as Wood cut under Wood."
"Made or consisting of wood; pertaining to  or resembling wood; as a wooden box; a wooden leg; a wooden wedding."
"In a wood  mad or raving manner; madly; furiously."
"A forest officer appointed to take care of the king's woods; a forester."
"Of or pertaining to the woods or forest."
"Abounding with wood or woods; as  woody land."
"One who wooes; one who courts or solicits in love; a suitor."
"The threads that cross the warp in a woven fabric; the weft; the filling; the thread usually carried by the shuttle in weaving."
"Having a close texture; dense; as  a woofy cloud."

"The soft and curled  or crisped species of hair which grows on sheep and some other animals and which in fineness sometimes approaches to fur; -- chiefly applied to the fleecy coat of the sheep which constitutes a most essential material of clothing in all cold and temperate climates."
"To wind  or wrap; especially to wind a rope round as a mast or yard made of two or more pieces at the place where it has been fished or scarfed in order to strengthen it."
"A stick used to tighten the rope in woolding."
"Made of wool; consisting of wool; as  woolen goods."
"Consisting of wool; as  a woolly covering; a woolly fleece."
"A species of steel imported from the East Indies  valued for making edge tools; Indian steel. It has in combination a minute portion of alumina and silica."

"The spoken sign of a conception or an idea; an articulate or vocal sound  or a combination of articulate and vocal sounds uttered by the human voice and by custom expressing an idea or ideas; a single component part of human speech or language; a constituent part of a sentence; a term; a vocable."
"One of several pivoted pieces forming the throat of an adjustable die used in drawing wire  lead pipe etc."
"Of or pertaining to words; consisting of words; verbal; as  a wordy war."
"Exertion of strength or faculties; physical or intellectual effort directed to an end; industrial activity; toil; employment; sometimes  specifically physically labor."
"A bag for holding implements or materials for work; especially  a reticule or bag for holding needlework and the like."
"A box for holding instruments or materials for work."
"A day on which work is performed  as distinguished from Sunday festivals etc. a working day."
"One who  or that which works; a laborer; a performer; as a worker in brass."
"A man employed in labor  whether in tillage or manufactures; a worker."
"The earth and the surrounding heavens; the creation; the system of created things; existent creation; the universe."
"Relating to the world; human; common; as  worldly maxims; worldly actions."
"A creeping or a crawling animal of any kind or size  as a serpent caterpillar snail or the like."
"Discovered or described by Olanus Wormius  a Danish anatomist."

"Any botfly larva which burrows in or beneath the skin of domestic and wild animals  thus producing sores. They belong to various species of Hypoderma and allied genera. Domestic cattle are often infested by a large species. See Gadfly. Called also warble and worble."
"An Egyptian fork-tongued lizard  about four feet long when full grown."
"To harass by pursuit and barking; to attack repeatedly; also  to tear or mangle with the teeth."
"Bad  ill evil or corrupt in a greater degree; more bad or evil; less good; specifically in poorer health; more sick; -- used both in a physical and moral sense."
"To make worse; to deteriorate; to impair."
"Bad  evil or pernicious in the highest degree whether in a physical or moral sense. See Worse."

"To be; to become; to betide; -- now used only in the phrases  woe worth the day woe worth the man etc. in which the verb is in the imperative and the nouns day man etc. are in the dative. Woe be to the day woe be to the man etc. are equivalent phrases."
"Having worth or excellence; possessing merit; valuable; deserving; estimable; excellent; virtuous."
"2d pers. sing. pres. of Wit  to know."
"2d pers. sing. pres. of Wit  to know."
"3d pers. sing. pres. of Wit  to know."
"An apparition of a person in his exact likeness  seen before death or a little after; hence an apparition; a specter; a vision; an unreal image."
"To snatch up; transport; -- chiefly used in the p. p. wrapt."

"Any one of numerous edible  marine spiny-finned fishes of the genus Labrus of which several species are found in the Mediterranean and on the Atlantic coast of Europe. Many of the species are bright-colored."
"Violent anger; vehement exasperation; indignation; rage; fury; ire."
"To cry  as a cat; to waul."
"Something twisted  intertwined or curled; as a wreath of smoke; a wreath of flowers."
"To cause to revolve or writhe; to twist about; to turn."
"Wreathed; twisted; curled; spiral; also  full of wreaths."
"One who causes a wreck  as by false lights and the like."
"Any one of numerous species of small singing birds belonging to Troglodytes and numerous allied of the family Troglodytidae."
"To turn; to twist; esp.  to twist or extort by violence; to pull of force away by or as if by violent wringing or twisting."
"To contend  by grappling with and striving to trip or throw down an opponent; as they wrestled skillfully."
"To move the body to and fro with short  writhing motions like a worm; to squirm; to twist uneasily or quickly about."

"One who is engaged in a mechanical or manufacturing business; an artificer; a workman; a manufacturer; a mechanic; esp.  a worker in wood; -- now chiefly used in compounds as in millwright wheelwright etc."
"To twist and compress; to turn and strain with violence; to writhe; to squeeze hard; to pinch; as  to wring clothes in washing."
"One who  or that which wrings; hence an extortioner."
"Full of wrinkles; having a tendency to be wrinkled; corrugated; puckered."
"The joint  or the region of the joint between the hand and the arm; the carpus. See Carpus."
"3d pers. sing. pres. of Write  for writeth."
"To set down  as legible characters; to form the conveyance of meaning; to inscribe on any material by a suitable instrument; as to write the characters called letters; to write figures."
"One who writes  or has written; a scribe; a clerk."
"To twist; to turn; now  usually to twist or turn so as to distort; to wring."
"In a wrong manner; unjustly; erroneously; wrong; amiss; as  he judges wrongly of my motives."
"Full of wrath; angry; incensed; much exasperated; wrathful."
"A twisted or distorted neck; a deformity in which the neck is drawn to one side by a rigid contraction of one of the muscles of the neck; torticollis."
"The quality or state of being wry  or distorted."
"A helmeted Australian cockatoo (Calyptorhynchus funereus); -- called also funeral cockatoo."
"A kind of timber truck  or carriage."
"Tending toward a yellow color  or to one of those colors green being excepted in which yellow is a constituent as scarlet orange etc."

"A crystalline nitrogenous body closely related to both uric acid and hypoxanthin  present in muscle tissue and occasionally found in the urine and in some urinary calculi. It is also present in guano. So called from the yellow color of certain of its salts (nitrates)."

"A small three-masted vessel  with projecting bow stern and convex decks used in the Mediterranean for transporting merchandise etc. It carries large square sails or both. Xebecs were formerly armed and used by corsairs."
"A present given to a guest or stranger  or to a foreign ambassador."
"A suborder of soft-rayed fresh-water fishes of which the blackfish of Alaska (Dallia pectoralis) is the type."
"Pertaining to  derived from designating certain amido compounds obtained by reducing certain nitro derivatives of diphenyl."
"A gold coin formerly current in Egypt and Turkey  of the value of about 9s. 6d. or about $2.30; -- also in Morocco a ducat."

"Pertaining to  or designating an acid C8H12O4 related to fumaric acid and obtained from citraconic acid as an oily substance having a bittersweet taste; -- so called from its tendency to form its anhydride."
"A genus of fishes comprising the common swordfish."
"A genus of cetaceans having a long  pointed bony beak usually two tusklike teeth in the lower jaw but no teeth in the upper jaw."
"That portion of a fibrovascular bundle which has developed  or will develop into wood cells; -- distinguished from phloem."

"Any of a group of three metameric hydrocarbons of the aromatic series  found in coal and wood tar and so named because found in crude wood spirit. They are colorless oily inflammable liquids C6H4.(CH3)2 being dimethyl benzenes and are called respectively orthoxylene metaxylene and paraxylene. Called also xylol."
"Any one of six metameric phenol derivatives of xylene  obtained as crystalline substances (CH3)2.C6H3.OH."
"Pertaining to  or designating a complex acid related to mesitylenic acid obtained as a white crystalline substance by the action of sodium and carbon dioxide on crude xylenol."
"Pertaining to  derived from or related to xylene; specifically designating any one of several metameric acids produced by the partial oxidation of mesitylene and pseudo-cumene."
"Pertaining to  or designating either one of two distinct acids which are derived from xylic acid and related compounds and are metameric with uvitic acid."
"A liquid hydrocarbon found in crude wood spirits."
"Nascent wood; wood cells in a forming state."
"Resembling wood; having the nature of wood."
"Any one of three metameric radicals which are characteristic respectively of the three xylenes."
"A genus of endogenous herbs with grassy leaves and small yellow flowers in short  scaly-bracted spikes; yellow-eyed grass. There are about seventeen species in the Atlantic United States."
"A long and open portico  for athletic exercises as wrestling running etc. for use in winter or in stormy weather."

"A South American crocodilian (Jacare sclerops) resembling the alligator in size and habits. The eye orbits are connected together  and surrounded by prominent bony ridges. Called also spectacled alligator and spectacled cayman."
"A West Indian name for two large timber trees (Podocarpus coriaceus  and P. Purdicanus) of the Yew family. The wood which is much used is pale brownish with darker streaks."

"A light and elegantly furnished vessel  used either for private parties of pleasure or as a vessel of state to convey distinguished persons from one place to another; a seagoing vessel used only for pleasure trips racing etc."

"The European green woodpecker (Picus  / Genius viridis). It is noted for its loud laughlike note. Called also eccle hewhole highhoe laughing bird popinjay rain bird yaffil yaffler yaffingale yappingale
"In the German army  one belonging to a body of light infantry armed with rifles resembling the chasseur of the French army."

"A bovine mammal (Poephagus grunnies) native of the high plains of Central Asia. Its neck  the outer side of its legs and its flanks are covered with long flowing fine hair. Its tail is long and bushy often white and is valued as an ornament and for other purposes in India and China. There are several domesticated varieties some of which lack the mane and the long hair on the flanks. Called also chauri gua grunting cow grunting ox sarlac

"A large Asiatic antelope (Budorcas taxicolor) native of the higher parts of the Himalayas and other lofty mountains. Its head and neck resemble those of the ox  and its tail is like that of the goat. Called also budorcas."
"(Ethnol.) A nomadic Mongolian tribe native of Northern Siberia  and supposed to be of Turkish stock. They are mainly pastoral in their habits."
"A kind of demigod attendant on Kuvera  the god of wealth."

"A large  esculent farinaceous tuber of various climbing plants of the genus Dioscorea; also the plants themselves. Mostly natives of warm climates. The plants have netted-veined petioled leaves and pods with three broad wings. The commonest species is D. sativa but several others are cultivated."

"The king of the infernal regions  corresponding to the Greek Pluto and also the judge of departed souls. In later times he is more exclusively considered the dire judge of all and the tormentor of the wicked. He is represented as of a green color with red garments having a crown on his head his eyes inflamed and sitting on a buffalo with a club and noose in his hands."
"An umbelliferous plant (Carum Gairdneri); also  its small fleshy roots which are eaten by the Indians from Idaho to California."
"The cry of the wild goose; a honk."

"A nickname for a native or citizen of New England  especially one descended from old New England stock; by extension an inhabitant of the Northern States as distinguished from a Southerner; also applied sometimes by foreigners to any inhabitant of the United States."
"A fermented drink  or milk beer made by the Turks."

"A South American aquatic opossum (Chironectes variegatus) found in Guiana and Brazil. Its hind feet are webbed  and its fore feet do not have an opposable thumb for climbing. Called also water opossum."
"The power of moving  or being managed at sea; -- said with reference to a ship."
"Either half of a square-rigged vessel's yard  from the center or mast to the end."
"As much as a yard will contain; enough to fill a yard."
"Ready; dexterous; eager; lively; quick to move."
"Spun wool; woolen thread; also  thread of other material as of cotton flax hemp or silk; material spun and prepared for use in weaving knitting manufacturing sewing thread or the like."
"To growl or snarl as a dog."

"An American and European composite plant (Achillea Millefolium) with very finely dissected leaves and small white corymbed flowers. It has a strong  and somewhat aromatic odor and taste and is sometimes used in making beer or is dried for smoking. Called also milfoil and nosebleed."
"The European bar-tailed godwit; -- called also yardkeep  and yarwhelp. See Godwit."
"To cry out like a child; to yelp."

"A shrub (Ilex Cassine) of the Holly family  native from Virginia to Florida. The smooth elliptical leaves are used as a substitute for tea and were formerly used in preparing the black drink of the Indians of North Carolina. Called also South-Sea tea."
"To rise in blisters  breaking in white froth as cane juice in the clarifiers in sugar works."
"A jade; an old horse or mare."
"A small ship's boat  usually rowed by four or six oars."
"To open the mouth involuntarily through drowsiness  dullness or fatigue; to gape; to oscitate."

"A disease  occurring in the Antilles and in Africa characterized by yellowish or reddish tumors of a contagious character which in shape and appearance often resemble currants strawberries or raspberries. There are several varieties of this disease variously known as framboesia pian verrugas
"Yes; ay; a word expressing assent  or an affirmative or an affirmative answer to a question now superseded by yes. See Yes."
"Properly  a variant of the defective imperfect yode but sometimes mistaken for a present. See the Note under Yede."
"To bring forth young  as a goat or a sheep; to ean."

"The time of the apparent revolution of the sun trough the ecliptic; the period occupied by the earth in making its revolution around the sun  called the astronomical year; also a period more or less nearly agreeing with this adopted by various nations as a measure of time and called the civil year; as the common lunar year of 354 days still in use among the Mohammedans; the year of 360 days etc. In common usage the year consists of 365 days and every fourth year (called bissextile or leap year) of 366 days a day being added to February on that year
"The California poison oak (Rhus diversiloba). See under Poison  a."
"Containing years; having existed or continued many years; aged."
"Happening  accruing or coming every year; annual; as a yearly income; a yearly feast."

"The foam  or troth (top yeast) or the sediment (bottom yeast) of beer or other in fermentation which contains the yeast plant or its spores and under certain conditions produces fermentation in saccharine or farinaceous substances; a preparation used for raising dough for bread or cakes and making it light and puffy; barm; ferment."
"The song of a minstrel; hence  any song."
"To cry out  or shriek with a hideous noise; to cry or scream as with agony or horror."
"Being of a bright saffronlike color; of the color of gold or brass; having the hue of that part of the rainbow  or of the solar spectrum which is between the orange and the green."
"A disease of the bile in horses  cattle and sheep causing yellowness of the eyes; jaundice."
"An animal that yelps  or makes a yelping noise."
"A silicate of iron and lime occurring in black prismatic crystals; -- also called ilvaite."
"A common man  or one of the commonly of the first or most respectable class; a freeholder; a man free born."
"To throw or thrust with a sudden  smart movement; to kick or strike suddenly; to jerk."
"Ay; yea; -- a word which expresses affirmation or consent; -- opposed to no."
"Last; last past; next before; of or pertaining to yesterday."
"Of or pertaining to yesterday; relating to the day last past."
"Any one of several species of large marine gastropods belonging to the genus Yetus  or Cymba; a boat shell."
"To give in return for labor expended; to produce  as payment or interest on what is expended or invested; to pay; as money at interest yields six or seven per cent."
"A South American tinamou (Rhynchotus rufescens); -- called also perdiz grande  and rufous tinamou. See Illust. of Tinamou."
"To sing in a manner common among the Swiss and Tyrolese mountaineers  by suddenly changing from the head voice or falsetto to the chest voice and the contrary; to warble."

"A species of asceticism among the Hindoos  which consists in a complete abstraction from all worldly objects by which the votary expects to obtain union with the universal spirit and to acquire superhuman faculties."
"A follower of the yoga philosophy; an ascetic."
"A measure of distance  varying from four to ten miles but usually about five."
"A bar or frame of wood by which two oxen are joined at the heads or necks for working together."
"A small farm; -- so called as requiring but one yoke of oxen to till it."
"The yellow part of an egg; the vitellus."
"At a distance  but within view; yonder."
"The symbol under which Sakti  or the personification of the female power in nature is worshiped. Cf. Lingam."
"In time long past; in old time; long since."
"To pour water on; to soak in  or mix with water."
"The pronoun of the second person  in the nominative dative and objective case indicating the person or persons addressed. See the Note under Ye."
"Not long born; still in the first part of life; not yet arrived at adolescence  maturity or age; not old; juvenile; -- said of animals; as a young child; a young man; a young fawn."
"Like a young person or thing; young; youthful."
"A young person; a stripling; a yonker."
"The form of the possessive case of the personal pronoun you."
"To utter a loud  long and mournful cry as a dog; to howl; to yell."
"The oxide  Y2O3 or earth of yttrium."
"Pertaining to  derived from or containing yttrium."
"A rare metallic element of the boron-aluminium group  found in gadolinite and other rare minerals and extracted as a dark gray powder. Symbol Y. Atomic weight 89."

"The crowned gibbon (Hylobates pileatus)  native of Siam Southern China and the Island of Hainan. It is entirely arboreal in its habits and has very long arms. the males are dark brown or blackish with a caplike mass of long dark hair and usually with a white band around the face. The females are yellowish white with a dark spot on the breast and another on the crown. Called also wooyen and wooyen ape."
"Any one of the four ages  Krita or Satya Treta Dwapara and Kali into which the Hindoos divide the duration or existence of the world."
"A species of Magnolia (M. conspicua) with large white blossoms that open before the leaves. See the Note under Magnolia."
"Christmas or Christmastide; the feast of the Nativity of our Savior."
"A tribe of Indians native of Arizona and the adjacent parts of Mexico and California. They are agricultural  and cultivate corn wheat barley melons etc."
"A genus of birds comprising the wrynecks."
"An oil pressed by the Arabs from the fruit of a small thorny tree (Balanites Aegyptiaca)  and sold to piligrims for a healing ointment."

"A pigment obtained  usually by roasting cobalt glance with sand or quartz as a dark earthy powder. It consists of crude cobalt oxide or of an impure cobalt arseniate. It is used in porcelain painting and in enameling pottery to produce a blue color and is often confounded with smalt from which however it is distinct as it contains no potash. The name is often loosely applied to mixtures of zaffer proper with silica or oxides of iron
"A Turkish chief who supports a mounted militia bearing the same name."
"A district from which a Zaim draws his revenue."
"A horse of a dark color  neither gray nor white and having no spots."

"An immense leguminous tree (Pithecolobium Saman) of Venezuela. Its branches form a hemispherical mass  often one hundred and eighty feet across. The sweet pulpy pods are used commonly for feeding cattle. Also called rain tree."
"The child of a mulatto and a negro; also  the child of an Indian and a negro; colloquially or humorously a negro; a sambo."
"A genus of cycadaceous plants  having the appearance of low palms but with exogenous wood. See Coontie and Illust. of Strobile."
"A fossil cycad of the genus Zamia."

"A West African buffalo (Bubalus brachyceros) having short horns depressed at the base  and large ears fringed internally with three rows of long hairs. It is destitute of a dewlap. Called also short-horned buffalo and bush cow."
"A European pike perch (Stizostedion lucioperca) allied to the wall-eye; -- called also sandari  sander sannat schill and zant."
"A native or inhabitant of Zante  one of the Ionian Islands."
"State or character of a zany; buffoonery."
"An improvised stockade; especially  one made of thorn bushes etc."
"Native sulphide of arsenic  including sandarach or realgar and orpiment."
"A species of macaque (Macacus pileatus) native of India and Ceylon. It has a crown of long erect hair  and tuft of radiating hairs on the back of the head. Called also capped macaque."
"A tool for trimming and puncturing roofing slates."
"A public shed  or portico for travelers worshipers etc."
"A genus of large grasses of which the Indian corn (Zea Mays) is the only species known. Its origin is not yet ascertained. See Maize."
"Passionate ardor in the pursuit of anything; eagerness in favor of a person or cause; ardent and active interest; engagedness; enthusiasm; fervor."
"One who is zealous; a zealot; an enthusiast."

"One who is zealous; one who engages warmly in any cause  and pursues his object with earnestness and ardor; especially one who is overzealous or carried away by his zeal; one absorbed in devotion to anything; an enthusiast; a fanatical partisan."
"Filled with  or characterized by zeal; warmly engaged or ardent in behalf of an object."
"Either one of two species of South African wild horses remarkable for having the body white or yellowish white  and conspicuously marked with dark brown or brackish bands."

"A bovine mammal (Ros Indicus) extensively domesticated in India  China the East Indies and East Africa. It usually has short horns large pendulous ears slender legs a large dewlap and a large prominent hump over the shoulders; but these characters vary in different domestic breeds which range in size from that of the common ox to that of a large mastiff."
"A large noxious fly of Abyssinia  which like the tsetse fly is destructive to cattle."
"The letter Z; -- called also zee  and formerly izzard."
"A medicinal substance obtained in the East Indies  having a fragrant smell and a warm bitter aromatic taste. It is used in medicine as a stimulant."
"An Austrian silver coin equal to ten kreutzers  or about five cents."
"A nitrogenous substance of the nature of gluten  obtained from the seeds of Indian corn (Zea) as a soft yellowish amorphous substance."

"The blind mole rat (Spalax typhlus)  native of Eastern Europe and Asia. Its eyes and ears are rudimentary and its fur is soft and brownish more or less tinged with gray. It constructs extensive burrows."
"The part of a dwelling appropriated to women."

"Properly  the translation and exposition in the Huzv/resh or literary Pehlevi language of the Avesta the Zoroastrian sacred writings; as commonly used the language (an ancient Persian dialect) in which the Avesta is written."
"An atheist or unbeliever; -- name given in the East to those charged with disbelief of any revealed religion  or accused of magical heresies."
"A South African burrowing mammal (Suricata tetradactyla)  allied to the civets. It is grayish brown with yellowish transverse stripes on the back. Called also suricat."
"That point in the visible celestial hemisphere which is vertical to the spectator; the point of the heavens directly overhead; -- opposed to nadir."

"A term now used to designate any one of a family of minerals  hydrous silicates of alumina with lime soda potash or rarely baryta. Here are included natrolite stilbite analcime chabazite thomsonite heulandite and others. These species occur of secondary origin in the cavities of amygdaloid
"The west wind; poetically  any soft gentle breeze."
"A piece of orange or lemon peel  or the aromatic oil which may be squeezed from such peel used to give flavor to liquor etc."
"A Greek letter corresponding to our z."

"A figure by which an adjective or verb  which agrees with a nearer word is by way of supplement referred also to another more remote; as """"hic illius arma hic currus fuit;"""" where fuit which agrees directly with currus is referred also to arma."
"The chief deity of the Greeks  and ruler of the upper world (cf. Hades). He was identified with Jupiter."

"A carnivorous mammal (Viverra zibetha) closely allied to the civet  from which it differs in having the spots on the body less distinct the throat whiter and the black rings on the tail more numerous."
"Curd produced from milk by adding acetic acid  after rennet has ceased to cause coagulation."
"The second month of the Jewish ecclesiastical year  corresponding to our May."
"Something that has short turns or angles."
"A low  thorny suffrutescent crucifeous plant (Zilla myagroides) found in the deserts of Egypt. Its leaves are boiled in water and eaten by the Arabs."
"A district or local division  as of a province."
"A large  venomous two-winged fly native of Abyssinia. It is allied to the tsetse fly and like the latter is destructive to cattle."

"An abundant element of the magnesium-cadmium group  extracted principally from the minerals zinc blende smithsonite calamine and franklinite as an easily fusible bluish white metal which is malleable especially when heated. It is not easily oxidized in moist air and hence is used for sheeting coating galvanized iron etc. It is used in making brass britannia
"Pertaining to  containing or resembling zinc; zincous."
"Native zinc oxide; a brittle  translucent mineral of an orange-red color; -- called also red zinc ore and red oxide of zinc."
"Pertaining to zinc  or having its appearance."
"The positive electrode of an electrolytic cell; anode."
"Pertaining to  or resembling zinc; -- said of the electricity of the zincous plate in connection with a copper plate in a voltaic circle; also designating the positive pole."
"Of  pertaining to or containing zinc; zincic; as zincous salts."
"A small  edible freshwater European perch (Aspro zingel) having a round elongated body and prominent snout."
"Any plant of the composite genus Zinnia  Mexican herbs with opposite leaves and large gay-colored blossoms. Zinnia elegans is the commonest species in cultivation."
"A hill in Jerusalem  which after the capture of that city by the Israelites became the royal residence of David and his successors."

"A mineral occurring in tetragonal crystals  usually of a brown or gray color. It consists of silica and zirconia. A red variety used as a gem is called hyacinth. Colorless pale-yellow or smoky-brown varieties from Ceylon are called jargon."

"An instrument of music used in Austria and Germany. It has from thirty to forty wires strung across a shallow sounding-board  which lies horizontally on a table before the performer who uses both hands in playing on it. [Not to be confounded with the old lute-shaped cittern or cithern.]"
"A genus of grasses including Indian rice. See Indian rice  under Rice."
"A kind of domestic cattle reared in Asia for its flesh and milk. It is supposed to be a hybrid between the zebu and the yak."

"An imaginary belt in the heavens  16? or 18? broad in the middle of which is the ecliptic or sun's path. It comprises the twelve constellations which one constituted and from which were named the twelve signs of the zodiac."
"A peculiar larval stage of certain decapod Crustacea  especially of crabs and certain Anomura."
"A Jewish cabalistic book attributed by tradition to Rabbi Simon ben Yochi  who lived about the end of the 1st century a. d. Modern critics believe it to be a compilation of the 13th century."
"Of or pertaining to animals  or animal life."
"Having the characteristic of Zoilus  a bitter envious unjust critic who lived about 270 years before Christ."
"Resemblance to Zoilus in style or manner; carping criticism; detraction."
"A grayish or whitish mineral occurring in orthorhombic  prismatic crystals also in columnar masses. It is a silicate of alumina and lime and is allied to epidote."
"An Asiatic burrowing rodent (Siphneus aspalax) resembling the mole rat. It is native of the Altai Mountains."
"Of or pertaining to a zone; having the form of a zone or zones."
"A belt or girdle which the Christians and Jews of the Levant were obliged to wear to distinguish them from Mohammedans."
"A division of Mammalia in which the placenta is zonelike."
"Divided by parallel planes; as  zonate tetraspores found in certain red algae."
"Of or pertaining to a zone; zone-shaped."
"Any one of several of South African lizards of the genus Zonura  common in rocky situations."
"A cyst formed by certain Protozoa and unicellular plants which the contents divide into a large number of granules  each of which becomes a germ."
"The doctrine of the formation of living beings."
"Of or pertaining to a zooid; as  a zooidal form."
"That part of biology which relates to the animal kingdom  including the structure embryology evolution classification habits and distribution of all animals both living and extinct."
"An animal which is the sole product of a single egg; -- opposed to zooid."
"Of or pertaining to animals; obtained from animal substances."
"One of the segments of the body of an articulate animal."
"The laws of animal life  or the science which treats of the phenomena of animal life their causes and relations."
"Containing the remains of organized bodies; -- said of rock or soil."
"The dissection or the anatomy of animals; -- distinguished from androtomy."
"Either one of two species of small African carnivores of the genus Ictonyx allied to the weasels and skunks."
"A genus of plants of the Naiadaceae  or Pondweed family. Zostera marina is commonly known as sea wrack and eelgrass."
"One of an active and hardy body of soldiers in the French service  originally Arabs but now composed of Frenchmen who wear the Arab dress."
"An exclamation formerly used as an oath  and an expression of anger or wonder."
"To stew  as flounders eels etc. with just enough or liquid to cover them."
"A little flute or flageolet  especially that which is used to teach birds."

"The most important tribe belonging to the Kaffir race. They inhabit a region on the southeast coast of Africa  but formerly occupied a much more extensive country. They are noted for their warlike disposition courage and military skill."
"A tribe of Pueblo Indians occupying a village in New Mexico  on the Zu/i River."
"A fluosilicate of alumina occurring in tetrahedral crystals at the Zu/i mine in Colorado."
"Any one of numerous species of moths of the family Zygaenidae  most of which are bright colored. The wood nymph and the vine forester are examples. Also used adjectively."
"A soluble ferment  or enzyme. See Enzyme."
"Pertaining to  or produced by fermentation; -- formerly by confusion used to designate lactic acid."
"A mother substance  or antecedent of an enzyme or chemical ferment; -- applied to such substances as not being themselves actual ferments may by internal changes give rise to a ferment."
"A glutinous substance  insoluble in alcohol resembling legumin; -- now called vegetable fibrin vegetable albumin or gluten casein."
"A fermentation; hence  an analogous process by which an infectious disease is believed to be developed."
"Of  pertaining to or caused by fermentation."
"A kind of ancient malt beverage; a liquor made from malt and wheat."
